<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT MUST MULL CARROLL'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Almost to a man the Patriots said the right
thing Sunday. They talked about heart and soul and true grit and
battling back and never saying die and overcoming adversity and
coming back next year with new resolve.
</P>
<P>
   They said Pete Carroll was one of them. It was all for one and
one for all and everybody taking the blame for a defeat that sent
them on vacation far sooner than they ever thought they'd be this
year.
</P>
<P>
   They said it to the media and more importantly they said it
before the media entered the locker room during a moment of what
owner Bob Kraft later called ``bonding.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounded great. It was all baloney.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft was so impressed by this that a minute later he said he
did not know yet if Carroll would be back and he would seek a
recommendation from vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier
on what to do before he made a decision. He said this about a man
who has three years left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of the same players who were so unified behind
Carroll in the wake of a 25-10 AFC wild-card playoff loss to the
Jacksonville Jaguars at Alltel Stadium (would that it were Tell All
Stadium because maybe we'd know more Monday about what tomorrow
holds) were the same ones who have been talking for weeks now about
growing doubts that Carroll can lead them to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, only hours before the game, one of them told a
media member, ``There's not many guys left who have much respect
for Pete and the ones that still do are losing it more and more
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The player in question was not a rabble rouser. He was someone
with eyes in his head and, more importantly, fear in his heart.
Fear of the future. Fear of just what his teammates spoke of Sunday
after they were knocked out of the playoffs with too many backup
players pressed into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was a microcosm of our season,'' said safety Willie
Clay in a quiet voice. ``It was a tough struggle. This is the way
the season has been for us. We put ourselves in adverse situations
and then have to make too many plays to get back. We didn't quite
make it. We battled but we didn't quite make it. It's been a very
tough season. A very long season.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the same Clay who was one minute ranting at Lawyer
Milloy and the next Chris Slade about being out of position in
various defenses, the same Clay who at one point picked up a chalk
board and drew a formation for Slade to show him where he should
have been on an end zone coverage, the same Clay whom secondary
coach Ron Lynn recently called ``a coach on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay has forgotten more about the defenses the Patriots play
than anyone else on the team remembers, but why does he so often
have to call timeout because his teammates are in the wrong
formation?
</P>
<P>
   Why does his team repeatedly waste timeouts early (two in the
first quarter and two more in the third Sunday) because the wrong
players are on the field or not enough of them are or too many of
them are or the ones who are are standing in the wrong formation
for the play that's being called?
</P>
<P>
   Why, after two years and two playoff appearances, did the same
logistical problems surface Sunday that have cropped up time and
time and time again?
</P>
<P>
   Why do they fall behind two touchdowns to a team as injured as
they are?
</P>
<P>
   Why do they open the game with a fumbled kickoff and a penalty
and a series that produces nothing, as has happened time and time
and time again?
</P>
<P>
   Why oh why?
</P>
<P>
   Across the room from Clay, a battered Willie McGinest, his balky
groin again having proved a traitor to him, sat in near exhaustion
and blamed no one and everyone for the whys and wherefores of
Sunday's loss. There were no angry words from him, as there had
been a year ago after a 7-6 playoff defeat in Pittsburgh that so
infuriated him he lambasted Carroll in full view of his teammates
and no one said a word in protest.
</P>
<P>
   This time, McGinest was spent, mentally and physically. Proud to
be a Patriot, proud to have tried to do all he could on one leg,
but sad to see another season end far short of its goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team finds a way to overcome things,'' McGinest said.
``All these decisions as far as coaches and players is not my
decision. I don't know (if Carroll will be back). I think he did a
good job. He led us in the direction we needed to go. We got close
but we didn't finish.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the alarming truth of things. Pete Carroll has led
them close for two years but he also led them into one hole after
another. Whether injured or healthy, the Patriots too often have
had to scramble to survive.
</P>
<P>
   That they are willing to work that hard is clear. That was clear
last season and this season and Sunday. But what is just as clear
is that they cannot reach the goal Kraft has set for them _ the
Super Bowl _ if they continue to dig holes for themselves because
for every time they rise out of one at least as many times they
slip back, as they did Sunday when they had to settle for a field
goal after being first-and-10 at the Jaguar 13.
</P>
<P>
   A touchdown would have given them two straight second-half
scores and the lead and erased a miserably played and
embarrassingly disorganized first half when there were arguments on
the sideline, arguments on the field, and an offense that managed
but one first down to the Jaguars' 12.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't get the touchdown. They fell short as they had
fallen just short last year in Pittsburgh and just short this
season when they barely made the playoffs. Just short. That should
be their epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   So what is Kraft to do?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he'll probably do nothing because that's the easy
choice. He'll probably do nothing because he heard his players say
the right things Sunday and he heard the coach give a stump speech
about how ``what happened in the second half was an explosion on
the sidelines and in the locker room of will and heart and guys
coming through ... ''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounded good. It was all baloney, unless a 15-point loss
can be defined as coming through.
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots did Sunday is what they are paid to do. They
tried hard in a difficult circumstance. That is admirable. It is
also the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   There are no medals for trying in life. There's no jewelry for
it either, and somebody needs to remember that because the Patriots
are a team adrift, a team trying but coming up short.
</P>
<P>
   The tide is not yet high and so the seas are not yet running out
on them, but Kraft need only think back to another time when he and
his family sat in Section 225 instead of the owner's box and
watched a good guy named Ron Erhardt coach the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Erhardt took over a team Chuck Fairbanks had just abandoned the
same way Bill Parcells abandoned this team. They had been
considered one of the most talented teams in the NFL yet had won
nothing much to speak of when Fairbanks left abruptly and Erhardt
replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   Erhardt went 9-7 and just missed the playoffs in 1979, and
doubts began to surface about his leadership. He went 10-6 and just
missed the playoffs in 1980, and the doubts grew. But a decision
was made that you couldn't replace a guy who was 19-13 in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the last of the Erhardt Era, the New England
Patriots went 2-14 with the best offense in football. It was five
years before they made the playoffs again in a non-strike season.
</P>
<P>
   If that 19-13 number sounds familiar, it is the record Pete
Carroll has today. Monday morning, when Bob Kraft thinks about all
the words he heard Sunday, he should think back to what he was
hearing in 1979, when he was just a fan and another coach whose
team kept drifting backwards was 19-13.
</P>
<P>
   He should think about it a lot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
