<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JAGUARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS FINISH ON A DOWN NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Ty Law, the Pro Bowler who was beaten on
the back-breaking touchdown pass to Jimmy Smith in the fourth
quarter, stood up before the team in the locker room afterward and
said, ``This was my fault. I take full responsibility for the
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Armstrong and injured quarterback Drew Bledsoe also gave
speeches to the beaten and stinging Patriots following a 25-10 loss
to the Jacksonville Jaguars in Sunday's AFC wild-card playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The season over after the Patriots couldn't come back all the
way from a horrid first-half performance by the offense, Armstrong
and Bledsoe began looking ahead to next year _ a year in which the
team might have to make another transition depending on whether
coach Pete Carroll is fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said center Dave Wohlabaugh of the speeches.
``I think we needed those guys to do that. I think we can build off
of this and come into next year with a good, positive attitude. I
hope Pete's a part of that, because with everything that happened
and with all of the injuries, he deserves another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the reason the Patriots didn't win Sunday was because
they didn't have a healthy Bledsoe or a healthy Terry Glenn for him
to throw to.
</P>
<P>
   Backup QB Scott Zolak (21 for 44, 190 yards, one interception),
though he led a second-half resurgence, went 5 for 16 for 39 yards
in the first half. At one point he was 3 for 12 (as was
Jacksonville's Mark Brunell) and was missing his targets badly,
once throwing wide of Sedrick Shaw, who was standing right in front
of him.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots left the field at halftime trailing by only
12-0 in a game they could have been out of from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first half wasn't just frustrating, it was ugly,'' said
wide receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``We couldn't do anything right out
there. We came out in the second half and put some things together,
but we couldn't get it done when he had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was referring to a drive that began in the third
quarter and lasted into the fourth, with New England trailing,
12-7. Zolak threw to Tony Simmons for gains of 13 and 16 yards and
to Robert Edwards (28 yards rushing) in the flat for 15. The
Patriots got it as close as the 9, one Zolak pass was off the mark
and another was dropped, and New England settled for Adam
Vinatieri's 27-yard field goal to make it 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   The big play was Lovett Purnell's drop on third and 6. Had he
caught the ball, the Patriots likely would have had a first down,
and it might have even gone for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to give the Jaguars all the incentive they needed
for their resurgence, even with Brunell bothered by an ankle sprain
that has hampered him for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that was the turning point, but if we get
it there, the momentum gets going, it shuts up their crowd, and you
never know what could happen,'' said Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars then drove 70 yards in six plays. Brunell hit on a
22-yard pass play to Pete Mitchell, and three plays later, from the
New England 37, Brunell hit a diving Smith in the end zone, with
Law doing everything humanly possible to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed momentum for us,'' said Brunell. ``It was a simple
hand signal to Jimmy to give him the `go' route. He ran a nice
route and I was able to put the ball out there for him. It was just
a check at the line of scrimmage. That was a big play. They were
moving the ball and putting some points up, and we knew we had to
answer it. Any time we get a press on Jimmy, we feel we have the
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he didn't think the ball was going to go as far as it
did. ``I think the wind took it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Law spoke to his teammates, they soothed him by telling him
it wasn't his fault. And perhaps in the overall scheme of things,
it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, playing without Ted Johnson and Todd Collins,
couldn't contain Fred Taylor, the exciting rookie running back who
wound up with 162 yards on 33 carries. The Jaguars had heard talk
last week that the Patriots thought Jacksonville was more of a
finesse team than a hard-nosed unit. The Jaguars seemed inspired by
that. ``Who's smash-mouth and who's soft?'' said Taylor afterward.
``We put that rumor to sleep,'' added offensive tackle Tony
Boselli. ``We definitely weren't a finesse team today.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Law's miscue, Jacksonville defensive end Joel
Smeenge beat Zefross Moss one-on-one, made a great rush, and hit
Zolak in the chest, causing him to fumble. It was fallen on by end
Tony Brackens, and the Jaguars were back in business at the Patriot
25. From there, Mike Hollis made a 34-yard field goal, basically
drop-kicking it as holder Bryan Barker never really got the ball
down.
</P>
<P>
   The game had started inauspiciously for the Patriots. On the
opening kickoff, Derrick Cullors fumbled when struck hard by former
Boston College linebacker Tom McManus. The Patriots recovered but
had to punt, and Jacksonville drove to a 35-yard field goal to go
ahead, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars got another field goal later in the quarter after
the Patriots stopped Jacksonville at the New England 6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jaguars added their first touchdown in the second
quarter, going 68 yards on nine plays.
</P>
<P>
   The big play was a 21-yard run by Taylor, who seemed to be
stopped in the backfield and then reversed direction, getting it
down to the Patriots' 34. The drive culminated in Taylor's 13-yard
run, making it 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin went for the 2-point conversion, and
Taylor was stuffed in the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Despite adjustments, halftime speeches, and looks in the mirror,
the Patriots simply were outplayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
