<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PACKERS-49ERS-HNS     01-04 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a playoff game for the ages _ in a finish
that will be remembered as one of the most dramatic in NFL history
_ San Francisco quarterback Steve Young found absolution and 49ers
receiver Terrell Owens found redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who never had beaten Green Bay, put an exclamation mark
on a 76-yard desperation drive by throwing a 25-yard touchdown pass
to Owens with three seconds left, giving the 49ers a 30-27 victory
over the Packers in an NFC wild-card game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was double significant because it was in the
playoffs against the team that knocked us out the last three
years,'' said Young, who was 0-8 as a starter against the Packers.
``All we wanted was a chance in the end. We were so grateful for
that last shot.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was more grateful than Owens, who had dropped four
passes, including an easy touchdown, and lost a fumble that set up
a Packers field goal. But on a play that meant survival or death in
the playoffs, it was Owens _ not Jerry Rice _ who caught the most
important pass for the 49ers since Dwight Clark beat Dallas in the
1981 NFC Championship Game to propel San Francisco to its first
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, who thought they won the game on Brett Favre's
15-yard touchdown pass to Antonio Freeman with 1:56 remaining,
played a four-deep zone designed to prevent a touchdown. It was
third-and-three with eight seconds left when Young dropped back,
stumbled and almost fell before regaining his balance.
</P>
<P>
   Owens ran down the middle of the field, and with four Packers
zeroing in on him like heat-seeking missiles, he leaped to catch
the ball and was immediately smashed by safeties Pat Terrell and
Darren Sharper. When he came down just inside the goal line still
clutching the ball, Owens was mobbed by his teammates, and delirium
overcame 66,506 fans at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is going down in history, and I'm just glad to be
part of it,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who ended a five-game losing streak to Green Bay,
advance into the second round at Atlanta. They split the season
series 1-1 with the NFC West-rival Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, who had eliminated San Francisco from the playoffs
the last three years, lost in the first round for the first time
since Mike Holmgren became the coach in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren was beaten by his former team and his former
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful game by Steve,'' Holmgren said. ``He's had
that kind of marvelous season. If someone had to beat us like that,
I'm glad it was Steve. I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   There were six lead changes and seven turnovers in this
confrontation between former Super Bowl winners who could undergo
major changes at the coaching and personnel levels in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who completed 18 of 32 passes for 182 yards and three
touchdowns with two interceptions, and Favre, who was 20-of-35 for
292 yards and two touchdowns with two interceptions, guided their
teams up and down the field against defenses that allowed a total
of 750 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was a physical game that bordered on brutal at times. Running
backs Garrison Hearst (49ers) and Dorsey Levens (Packers) earned
their yards the yard way. Hearst, who didn't practice last week
because of a hamstring injury, rushed for 128 yards. Levens, who
didn't play most of the season because of surgery on his leg,
rushed for 116 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had a lot of ups and downs,'' San Francisco coach
Steve Mariucci said. ``Green Bay's a great team, and they were very
physical, and we rotated players to try to keep them fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys had to suck it up, play hurt and shed a lot of blood,
sweat and tears to win one of the greatest games in the history of
the organization. I think this team showed true character.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers led to most of the scoring. There were five turnovers
in the first half, after which Green Bay led 17-10 on Ryan
Longwell's 23-yard field goal, Favre's two-yard touchdown pass to
Freeman and Levens' two-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers scored on Wade Richey's 34-yard field goal and Young's
one-yard touchdown pass to tight end Greg Clark. Clark caught an
eight-yard touchdown pass from Young to tie the score 17-17 in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Richey and Longwell exchanged field goals to make it 20-20 early
in the fourth quarter. Richey kicked a 40-yarder for a 23-20 Niners
lead midway through the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:19 remaining, Green Bay got the ball at its 11 trailing
by three. Favre took the Packers to the San Francisco 15 and found
Freeman alone in the end zone. Longwell's extra point gave the
Packers a 27-23 lead with 1:56 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers started the winning drive at their 24 with 1:50 left.
Young completed three passes for 29 yards. Then, after an
incompletion, he found Rice near the sideline for a six-yard gain.
Rice appeared to fumble, and the Packers recovered, but the
officials ruled he was down. Replays showed the ball came loose
before Rice's knee hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers didn't waste the second chance. Young completed passes
of nine and seven yards. After an incompletion, there were eight
seconds left. The ball was on the Green Bay 25. One play was all
the Packers needed to make to prevent a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``One shot, one shot was all I wanted,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Young and Owens collaborated on the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faked outside and knifed down the middle,'' Owens said. ``I
had the option of going inside or outside. Steve threw the ball
where it had to be. When I turned, the ball was right there. I was
just happy to catch the ball because I'd had a rough day up to that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens was crying when he came to the bench to be mobbed by his
teammates again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates encouraged me to keep my head up, and I'm so
happy I got a chance to redeem myself,'' he said. ``They were
right. I held my head up. I came up big, didn't I?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
