<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-MINNESOTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA WINS RESPECT FROM BC WITH TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Minnesota wing Mike Anderson called his team's
performance 24 hours earlier against Boston College ``downright
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Doug Woog, said Sunday's rematch was ``all about
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gophers, who were walloped, 8-4, Saturday, gained
some measure of revenge against Boston College when they charged
from behind with two third-period goals to salvage a 3-3 overtime
tie before 3,234 at Kelley Rink.
</P>
<P>
   Rico Pagel scored the tying goal with less than eight minutes to
play when he deflected a blast from the point past the glove of BC
goalie Scott Clemmensen. That came three minutes after Anderson had
pulled the Golden Gophers to within 3-2 with a pretty goal from the
top of the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen, who had 22 saves against Minnesota Saturday, had 33
more Sunday, many of them spectacular. None, though, was more
important than the shot he turned aside off the stick of Bill Kohn,
who blasted the puck from the point through a screen with 1:08 left
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard and good things happen when you work hard,''
said Anderson. ``We came out not wanting a repeat of yesterday. We
played for each other and as a team today rather than as
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Woog was a little more direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about respect and unselfishness rather than pettiness
and selfishness,'' he said. ``When you look at your neighbor in the
locker room and realize what he's doing is just as important as
what you're doing, then you've arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's respect and we needed to make a statement about that
today. I think some people on this team had to drop the I and the
best way to do that is to play with respect for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   BC came out swarming and took a 1-0 lead 3:50 into the game when
Tony Hutchins poked a loose puck past Minnesota goalie Adam Hauser
during a scramble just outside the crease. Late in the period, Jeff
Farkas, who had four goals Saturday, made it 2-0 when he potted a
power-play goal off a rebound to Hauser'sleft.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt Smith bagged his 11th of the season midway through the
second period to trim the deficit to 2-1, but Mike Lephart upped
the margin to a pair again with a wrap-around beauty at 5:49 of the
third period. Then Anderson and Pagel struck to tie the game at
3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota had a golden opportunity to win in overtime when Smith
and Mike Lyons broke in on Clemmensen two on one, but Lyons
mishandled the feed across the crease from Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was the best he's played all year,'' said BC
coach Jerry York of Clemmensen, ``and that's a good sign for us
because we're going to need him at the top of his game as we go
into the Maine (Friday and Saturday at Kelley) series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to sweep the series, that was our objective,'' York
continued. ``Three out of four points isn't bad, but we really
wanted that fourth point.''
</P>
<P>
   BC (11-5-2, 6-3 Hockey East) is idle until its showdown with
Maine this weekend. Minnesota (7-10-3, 5-5-2 WCHA) returns to
league action Saturday at Denver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
