<SLUG> BC-BB-HALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISK WOULD BE NICE CATCH FOR HALL 
</HEADLINE>
 OF FAME VOTE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON FISK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tomorrow, we'll know about Carlton ``Pudge'' Fisk. Will
the one-time Red Sox catcher be elected to the Hall of Fame? And if
he is, which hat will he wear on his plaque?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the results of the month-long balloting of the Baseball
Writers Association of America will be announced. Given the depth
of the competition (George Brett, Robin Yount, Nolan Ryan among
others), there is no guarantee Fisk will be elected to Cooperstown
this time.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk was an All-Star in seven of his 11 seasons in Boston. He
appeared in 1,078 games as a catcher before leaving through free
agency in 1980. He appeared in 1,148 more games as a catcher in 13
seasons in Chicago, to set the record with 2,226 at the position.
The White Sox also used Fisk in left field, at first base, and as a
designated hitter. Late in his career, when he had Bob Boone's
major league record in sight, the White Sox' decision to let
someone else do the catching created some bad blood, the memories
of which remain today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I went out there I tried to play as hard as I
could,'' Fisk said in a recent interview. ``As a catcher, you never
knew how long it was going to last. I had a couple of serious
injuries and operations in Boston but I could have played there
longer. I thought about coming out to Chicago and playing three,
four, or five years. I had full intentions of coming back to New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the years kept going by, I thought I just wanted to prove a
point. A lot of people said I was too old. I was too fragile. Too
brittle. I wouldn't play or wouldn't last very long. I became as
stubborn as I could, I guess. I went out and worked hard every day
to get myself ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he makes it into the Hall or not, Fisk's worthiness
surely will be debated this week. He is a fan favorite in two
cities, but also has his detractors. The mail recently included a
note from a reader, Larry Feehley of Brockton, who said he believes
Fisk shouldn't be on the ballot. Feehley pointed out that Fisk
never won a Most Valuable Player award and batted just .269 over
his 24-year career. Fisk was described as ``an above-average player
who hung on too long to set a secondary record via longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, it was suggested that Fisk was not the dominating
catcher of his time and his career twice ended in much publicized
exits from the teams he represented. Feehley pointed out that
Boston made Fisk a free agent rather than pay a 33-year-old catcher
a premium salary, then just under $700,000. And that Fisk and the
Chicago front office feuded in his closing years all the way to his
major league record number of games as a catcher. Six days after
getting the mark, Fisk was released and asked to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   But after talking with Fisk about this and other subjects, one
becomes more convinced than ever that he belongs in Cooperstown.
You have no heart if you can't reward the man who provided baseball
one of the thrills of a lifetime in the 1975 World Series with his
Game 6 homer. Fisk used to drive people crazy with his frequent
trips to the mound, his slow manner between pitches, and his
countless foul balls to left. But he played sometimes in awful pain
and at the very least was the American League's answer to Johnny
Bench.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of any catcher lasting 24 years in today's game are
exceptionally slim. And catchers are worth their weight in gold.
Fisk was a hell-raiser one day and a gentle giant the next. He was
not always a happy camper when it came to club functions. But they
loved him in Boston. Still do.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do I believe Fisk should be elected to Cooperstown as
soon as possible, he should go in wearing a Red Sox cap. Despite
his exit from Boston in 1980, he still has strong roots in
Charlestown, N.H. Red Sox CEO John Harrington absolutely loves him.
Lately, there have been some good feelings emerging about his early
days in Boston, now that the team's co-owners at that time, Haywood
Sullivan and Buddy LeRoux, have been erased from his memory bank.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk says he is pleased there are people who value what he did
during his career and who won't assess it with just a calculator.
He is reminded that in 1988, former teammate Carl Yastrzemski came
under fire in some quarters at election time. Critics said his 23
years of service and the fact that half of his 3,308 games were
played in the bandbox called Fenway Park detracted from his
accomplishments. Yaz was elected in a first-ballot landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk said he never took the game or the records he set lightly.
The manner in which he prepared for each game was grueling, but it
was something he liked at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I really liked the preparation and the competition,''
he said. ``The older I got, the more single-minded I had to be in
my preparation. Getting into a real regimen of strength and
conditioning allowed me to play as long as I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record motivated me at the end. It suddenly became
approachable and it came in sight. I knew that if I was just given
a chance to compete or participate I could contribute and chase the
record at the same time. I was happy to set the record. But I
wasn't around much after that.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, said Fisk, he won't forget that his days
as a Red Sox are what helped put him in the position he is in now.
He recently became a grandfather. One of his daughters, Courtney,
has returned from college and is living at home. Life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in Boston was the dream of a New England boy come
true,'' said Fisk. ``I think we all know that to play in Fenway
Park was to play in perhaps the best ballpark in all the major
leagues. I'm talking about from what it has to offer in history and
tradition to its dimensions to a close relationship with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the teams that I played on while I was there, if you
had a wish list of people you'd want to have on your team to try to
chase the pennant, just about all of them were on the Red Sox in
those years.''
</P>
<P>
   The years in Boston went quickly after he signed with the Red
Sox, who made him the fourth player taken in the January 1967 free
agent draft. He had chosen the Red Sox and baseball over a possible
career with the Celtics and pro basketball. In hindsight, he did
the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before 1967, there wasn't much going on. But by 1972 I was
able to make it to the majors (he actually debuted in 1969) and we
had a close run. We did it again in 1975. The 1978 season
highlighted the Don Zimmer years for me. It turned out to be a
heartbreaker but a great year, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sticks in my mind is that there were just successful
years against terrific teams like Baltimore and New York, who were
also as good a team as you could put on the field. One of the
reasons the Red Sox-Yankee rivalry was so intense is that we were
equal in talent and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk still has no clue as to why his Red Sox career ended so
abruptly. Sullivan failed to mail him a contract by the Dec. 20
deadline and instead of arbritration, he was given free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys (Sullivan and LeRoux) put me in a position that
it was unacceptable to return,'' he said. ``They made no offer.
They had no intentions of having me come back. I felt for the
longest time that I had been abandoned. Out to sea in a little
rowboat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always had a great time coming back. People treated me
nice and welcomed me with their cheers. That made it fun coming
back. In a way it was a burden, but it was a fun one to shoulder.
To be voted into the Red Sox Hall of Fame is quite an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball Hall of Fame should be next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0036EST &QL; 
