</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-PACKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWENS, 49ERS GRAB VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You could have won a lot of bar bets outside the
Bay Area by posing the following question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Has Steve Young ever won an NFL game with a last-second
touchdown pass?''
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, the answer was no. But that's all in the past
tense now. His 25-yard touchdown pass to Terrell Owens with three
seconds remaining provided the league's resident management orphans
with a 30-27 victory over archrival Green Bay before 66,506
enraptured onlookers at 3Com Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers may not have any front office accountability at
present, but guys in $1,000 suits don't play. Football players do,
and San Francisco's will be heading to Atlanta next Saturday for a
date with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Young and the team exorcised a few ghosts. The
Niners had lost five straight games to the Packers, and they had
been bounced from the playoffs three years in succession. In
addition, Young was 0-8 lifetime against the Packers, a streak that
included some no-hopers in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   This information was known to everyone within a 500-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to get this one,'' said the 37-year old
Young, who has taken some hits in these parts lately for not _
believe it or not _ winning the so-called big ones. ``They had
knocked us out of the playoffs three years running, and if we are
who we say we are, and are supposed to be charging to Super Bowls,
and the same team keeps beating you, that can't be overwritten.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor can anyone overwrite the drama inherent in the final two
drives of this game. For the nine-play, 76-yard winning 49er drive
came in direct response to a crisp nine-play, 89-yard drive
orchestrated by Brett Favre, a drive that had culminated in a
15-yard touchdown pass to Antonio Freeman with 1:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   Young took over with the ball on his 24. There was 1:46 left.
``That's plenty of time,'' he pointed out, ``especially with all
our timeouts. Also, I know I've got big receivers. It's important
to make sure you don't get too greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was 7 for 9 on the final drive, and he had some help.
There was, for example, a spectacular bull-in-the-china-shop 3-yard
catch-and-run by fullback Marc Edwards, who took a short pass and
got the Niners a first down at the Green Bay 47 by refusing to come
down until hit by the 11th Packer. And there was the obligatory Bad
(Non)-Call.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers did indeed catch a huge break when Jerry Rice lost
control of the ball for a clear fumble after making a 6-yard
reception at the Packer 41. But Green Bay did not get the call.
</P>
<P>
   It came down to a third and 3 at the Packer 25 with eight
seconds left. The call, according to coach Steve Mariucci, was for
all four wide receivers to head into the end zone. ``I can't tell
you the name of the play,'' he said. ``Bombs away, and throw it
into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called `All Go,''' said Owens, who found safety Leroy
Butler was giving him the middle. ``I faked outside and knifed back
toward the middle. Steve put the ball right where it had to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Young threw what may have been his best pass of the day, a
bullet that Owens caught to his outside shoulder, and never mind
that he had been dropping passes all day, including one in the end
zone and another on the penultimate possession that would have
given his team a valuable first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' said Young. ``You just
keep playing. I don't even remember. But I'm glad T.O. had a chance
for redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I caught the ball,'' said Owens. ``I had a rough
day, all day.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't anyone to fault. Two great athletes teamed up on a
great play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball goes down the middle like that,'' said Green Bay
coach Mike Holmgren, ``you don't think the ball's going to be
caught, ever. I think it was a marvelous catch. It was the perfect
throw by Young, and Owens made the play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Green Bay examines this game in the sober light of day, the
Packers will feel even worse than they did Sunday. They handed
Young two scores with a fumble and pass interception which led to
touchdown ``drives'' of 19 and 33, yards, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay led by a 17-10 score at the half, but if you had never
glanced at the scoreboard you'd have thought they were up by three
touchdowns, minimum. The Packers had offensive balance (292 yards
passing and 116 Dorsey Levens yards on the ground), and when the
time came to make their own statement they did so via the
aforementioned 89-yard march for what looked like the winning
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't lose a game like this,'' lamented Holmgren, who
very likely was coaching his final game in Green Bay (assuming you
believe half of what you read and hear). ``It's the worst that can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite all that, but in the pro football world, it's bad
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
