<HEADLINE>
ON BALANCE, DOLPHINS CONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Dan Marino didn't have to look at the final statistics
of Miami's 24-17 wild-card victory Saturday over the Buffalo Bills.
He just knew. For the first time in four playoff meetings against
the Bills, the Dolphins finally were able to strike a perfect
balance with their offense.
</P>
<P>
   A 50-50 split between run and pass.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Marino's oft-overtaxed arm was not relied upon to
cover up for an anemic rushing attack, which had gained just 145
yards on 42 attempts in Miami's three previous playoff losses to
the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Marino attempted 34 passes, completing 23 for 235
yards and an 11-yard touchdown to Lamar Thomas. And Miami's rushing
game _ bolstered by the return of running back Karim Abdul-Jabbar
(concussion), left tackle Richmond Webb (triceps), and right guard
Kevin Donnalley (knee) _ netted 117 yards on 34 attempts, with
Abdul-Jabbar doing the bulk of the work by carrying 27 times for 95
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four passing attempts. Thirty-four rushing attempts. One
big playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was a thing we had to do against the Bills defense
because they're so good you really can't drop back and pass every
play like we did in some other games,'' said Miami center Tim
Ruddy.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple formula most NFL coaches strictly follow,
especially during playoff time. Play balanced football. Win, and
move on to the next round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always talked about how we needed to be balanced,'' said
Marino, whose TD pass was the 30th of his playoff career, moving
him into a second-place tie with Terry Bradshaw on the NFL's
all-time list behind Joe Montana (45). ``And I think we were
balanced today. When you can do that and be successful at it, it
really takes a lot of heat off (the passer). You've got guys on
Buffalo who can really rush the passer, and they just can't pin
their ears back and go, so it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped Marino to have the three injured starters back on
offense. That was never more evident than on an impressive 12-play,
52-yard touchdown drive in the third quarter. The Dolphins
demonstrated how committed they were to the rushing game by running
the ball on nine plays, including seven of the first eight.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar highlighted the drive with a 3-yard touchdown burst
up the middle. Then Marino handed off to Stanley Pritchett for the
successful 2-pointer _ Miami's first of the season _ that gave the
Dolphins a 14-7 lead with 2:32 left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Marino completed two of three attempts on the drive, an 8-yard
pass to Thomas and a 6-yarder to Oronde Gadsden for a
first-and-goal at the Buffalo 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our offensive coordinator (Kippy Brown) just
recognized that they might have gotten a little tired and he just
kept calling run after run after run,'' said Webb. ``We just kept
driving it down and pounding it, and we got it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how tired he became on that series, Webb said, ``I got a
little winded, but that was to be expected. I haven't played in
like seven or eight weeks, but I hung in there and made it
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he played at slightly less than 100 percent,
Abdul-Jabbar said the sight of Webb wincing in pain in the huddle
served as all the inspiration he needed to get through the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to ask how he was doing once the whole game,
because I could see it in his face _ I knew he was hurting,'' said
Abdul-Jabbar, who appeared to be hurt himself by the way he
gingerly walked from the trainer's room to his stall in the
Dolphins' locker room at Pro Player Stadium after the game. ``But
he performed great.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on that touchdown drive. Or, rather, that touchdown
stampede.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys up front were doing a great job, but I'm going to
look at the film, because I know I left a few out there,'' said
Abdul-Jabbar, who helped Miami record its first 100-yard rushing
game in postseason since 1994 against Kansas City, which was the
last time the Dolphins won a playoff game before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some times where I just wanted to get the first
down and I think there was a big play outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though when you run the ball, you're going to have a lot
of 1- and 2-yard gains,'' Ruddy said. ``If you stick with it, the
fact is it helps keep the defense honest and it only helps you in
the long run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
