</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FINISHED ON WRONG SIDE OF KEY PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For so long Sunday, the familiar Patriots
were seen in sights so familiar to Patriot fans, sights that so
often this season led to familiar losses to good teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Lovett Purnell being on the field, for some reason, in
key situations and then dropping the key pass. The ball being
handed off to Robert Edwards and the entire Patriot offensive line
still on its feet, no blocks being made by any of them, as Edwards
is pounded to the turf by the Jaguars defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sedrick Shaw blocking no one on a kickoff return, causing
Derrick Cullors to be pounded deep in his own territory. Confusion
in the defense, causing Willie Clay to call a timeout because the
team was in the wrong coverage.
</P>
<P>
   On the key third down of the game, when New England had crawled
back to trail by only 2 points in the fourth quarter, and
Jacksonville was flustered, the Patriots let tight end Pete
Mitchell roam free in the middle, as tight ends have been free all
season, and Mitchell made a 22-yard catch. On and on and on, the
familiar sights of a team that was not championship material.
</P>
<P>
   But one sight unfamiliar to all was this: Ty Law being beaten on
a go pattern down the left sideline by the Jaguars' Jimmy Smith for
the 37-yard touchdown 2 1/2 minutes into the fourth quarter that
absolutely turned the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault,'' Law said time and again in the locker room.
``I take full responsibility,'' he said many times. ``I'm to blame
for the loss'' came from Law's mouth more than once.
</P>
<P>
   No consolation, either, that Mark Brunell's pass was perfect and
Smith's catch was superb. ``It was a great throw and a great catch
by two great players on the other side,'' said Patriots coach Pete
Carroll. ``It took a great play to beat a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he is not the type to let this killer of a play haunt
him during the offseason. But the New England cornerback, in the
first half hour after the play occurred, already had analyzed what
went wrong scores, if not hundreds of times, in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked about Smith's catch, Law began a monologue that
went on and on as he replayed techniques and methods that had
served him so well this Pro Bowl year of his, only to desert him at
the most crucial time of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect thrown ball and catch,'' Law began, ``but I'm
pretty pissed off about that. Being in that situation like that ...
I take everything like that personally. I got to give credit where
credit is due; Mark Brunell threw a great ball and Jimmy Smith made
a great catch. It's just that I didn't make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   January football games are so often decided by this _ great
players making great plays in the fourth quarters of tight games.
Always it divides the winning team from the losing team. And so
Law's monologue went on, analyzing and dissecting every move he
made on the play, but also every thought that went through his head
as Brunell's pass floated high down the left sideline and Law was
step-to-step with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of slowed up there at the end, because I thought it was
an underthrown ball,'' Law went on. ``It seemed like the wind ...
the wind took it or something. Actually, it was such a high arc of
a thrown ball that I was there. And that's why I turned back (to
look at the ball). I might have been looking at the ball too long,
you know what I mean. That might be a bad technique.''
</P>
<P>
   Law's voice was barely audible as he talked on. He had his face
in his locker, but talk Law did, as he always talks after a game,
win or lose, good play or bad play. And so he went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have to look at it again to see if it was bad
technique by me,'' he said. ``I thought I was seeing the ball
coming down ... but it went further than I anticipated. And Jimmy
Smith made a helluva grab. It took every bit of his speed to get
that ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very hard on me. I always take stuff like that to
heart because I'm a competitor and I don't like to give up things
like that, things that I normally don't. But I'm human. But
sometimes, you know, I try to make myself not be human. But this is
very hard, because we were in a situation where we were back in the
game and so I'll take full responsibility for (the loss). I'm
supposed to be a guy who's counted on on this team. It's only one
play, and they say one play doesn't win or lose games, but as far
as I'm concerned that was the turning point of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The play was pure pro football chess at its best. The Patriots'
defense had shown what appeared to be a blitz, but then checked off
into another defense. Brunell had checked off the play he had
called, and given a hand signal to Smith for a ``go'' pattern. And
now it was man-to-man, Jimmy Smith vs. Ty Law, and a season was
riding on who would win the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith likes to have a step or so on me at the start,'' Law
explained, as he voiced his mind's replay, ``but I like to play a
step short on receivers anyway. You play a guy tight and it gives
too much chance to push off and come back on a comeback pass, so I
always play a little shorter, figuring that if the ball is there,
it has to be a perfectly thrown ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Law's words now raced, as his mind did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one time I was not in the vicinity to at least not
make a play on the ball, or make a play on the receiver. That's
because I read the pass wrong. I wasn't there. I mean, as far as
how far the pass was going. You know, the ball was coming down, and
being as I like to play over the shoulder, and not over the top, it
cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Law kept grasping for an answer about why he was not where the
ball came down. He thought he was in perfect position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have been the wind,'' Law said. ``The wind might have
taken it and made it go further than I thought. Maybe that was it
... I don't know ... I thought I was there ... Maybe the wind took
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel's half-hearted attempts on blitzes are familiar,
and so is the sight of Robert Edwards being wide open in the left
flat on that third-down pass from the Jaguars' 6-yard line that
Purnell dropped, when New England was ready to take the lead on the
second play of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was a microcosm of the whole season,'' said Carroll,
and Willie Clay used virtually the same words, saying, ``It was a
microcosm of how the season went the way we dug ourselves into a
hole and tried to climb out.''
</P>
<P>
   But this game was no microcosm of the New England season. That's
because Ty Law got beat deep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
