<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BRUNELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUNELL PRESSES ISSUE WITH AUDIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ When he saw the ``press'' coming, Mark
Brunell decided it was time to take Ty Law to the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't supposed to be the pattern,'' said Brunell of his
37-yard touchdown strike to Jimmy Smith in the fourth quarter that
just about sealed the Jaguars' 25-10 win over the Patriots Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With his team clinging to a 12-10 lead, and the momentum
swinging toward New England, Brunell unloaded the bomb that blew
the Patriots right out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play we had called was an 18-yard comeback,'' said Brunell
of the first-and-10 play. ``But when I saw the corner (Law) started
to move up and press, I gave Jimmy a hand signal that tells him to
change the pattern and go deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith did that, streaking down the left sideline. The Patriots
blitzed, but unlike the success they had attacking the gimpy
Brunell for three periods, this time it backfired. The Jaguars
picked it up, and with no one in front of him, Brunell was able to
step up and throw a perfect strike to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field, both of them were running stride-for-stride,''
said Jaguars tight end Pete Mitchell. ``But at about the 5-yard
line, Jimmy started to pull away from him and the ball was
perfectly thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Touchdown, and a 19-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to have something on that drive,'' said Brunell.
``New England was taking over, had things going for them. We had to
make a statement. We talked about it on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell did not play a good first half. Playing for the first
time in a month and trying to operate on an ankle that had to have
a special tape job and be deadened by medication, he was having
passes sail everywhere except into the arms of open receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated at the end of the half,'' said Brunell, even
though his team led, 12-0. ``We had a terrible series of plays at
the end of the half, and then I hurt my ankle on the last play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Coach) Tom Coughlin and myself talked about whether I could
play the second half, but we really didn't argue. I wanted to keep
on playing. I felt I could play better as the game went along.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell calmed down in the fourth period and reverted to the
accurate passer he usually is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark won the game for us,'' said offensive tackle Tony
Boselli. ``Under the circumstances, he came up with a big game.
When we needed to make a play at the end, he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before the game I thought he would struggle,'' said
Coughlin. ``He practiced this week, but it wasn't like a normal
week of practice. He didn't take all of the snaps because of his
ankle. So we anticipated that it might take a while for him to play
his game, and it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
