<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-McDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS DID GROUNDWORK FOR VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The game was not Mark Brunell vs. Scott
Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   The game was decided by Fred Taylor and Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran the ball and we stopped the run,'' was the first
sentence out of Tom Coughlin's mouth after his Jacksonville Jaguars
had beaten the Patriots, 25-10, Sunday at Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin's assertions are backed up by the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had 162 yards rushing; Edwards had 28 of New England's
total of 35 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was a great complement to a struggling Brunell; Edwards
was no help to a harassed Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we looked at the Patriots on film during the week,'' said
Jaguars tight end Pete Mitchell, ``we saw that the teams that got
very physical with their defense were the teams that had luck
running the ball against them. We just picked up our (run blocking)
game by getting more physical.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars dominated the first half, outgaining the Patriots,
199 yards to 54, while taking a 12-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the game almost turned for New England in a big way when
Brunell injured his ankle on the final play of the half, and
Coughlin had a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really upset because he played the whole half until the
final play without hurting his ankle again,'' said Coughlin. ``Then
he got hit on the final play. We talked about how he felt, and he
wanted to keep on playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, we thought it would take him some playing
time to get back to being sharp. He was definitely off in the first
half. But in the fourth period, he stepped up and made some big
plays that turned the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of dominating the first half, the Jaguars fell asleep
in the third period and the Patriots ran off 10 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   New England grabbed all the momentum in the third, outgaining
Jacksonville by a staggering 130 yards to 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zolak did a better job of getting the ball out (throwing)
faster in the third period,'' said Jaguars defensive coordinator
Dick Jauron. ``They did a good job of spreading us out in that
period. Twice we had our defensive backs go after the ball and
miss, and that hurt us, giving up big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just played sharper in the third than they did in the
first half. They caught on to what we were doing against them and
made some adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   There were three critical plays in the game. The Jaguars made
two of them. The Patriots missed on theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 12-7, Zolak moved the Patriots to the Jacksonville 9
and faced third and 6 early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak threw a pass right into the hands of backup tight end
Lovett Purnell at the 5, and he dropped it. Purnell had a first
down for sure, and most likely a touchdown that would have given
the Patriots a 14-12 lead. Instead they had to settle for a field
goal and still trailed, 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of urgency on our sideline at that point,''
said Jaguars tackle Tony Boselli. ``We knew we had to go out and
score some points. Everything was going New England's way. Luckily
for us, Mark made some big plays and we took the momentum back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots defense had great success attacking Brunell with
blitzes. ``They knew he couldn't run with his ankle,'' said
Jacksonville offensive coordinator Chris Palmer, ``so they came
afer him. They had good pressure. We made some mistakes. He missed
a couple of passes early that could have been touchdowns. But in
that drive he made some big plays. I thought the biggest play of
the game was the completion to Mitchell on third down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, sitting on that 2-point lead, faced third and 10 on
their 30 after the Patriots had kicked their field goal. The
Patriots blitzed again, but this time the Jaguars blocked it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get open in the middle of the field,'' said
Mitchell, who made a 22-yard reception to keep the drive alive.
``Someone jammed me at the line of scrimmage, but once I got away,
I don't know what happened to him. Mark saw what happened and made
a great throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, the Jaguars struck for the decisive score, a
37-yard touchdown pass from Brunell to Jimmy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a great play,'' said Palmer. ``Jimmy had dropped
a pass a few plays earlier when the sun was in his eyes, but Mark
put the ball right on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith beat Ty Law deep and Brunell dropped the ball into his lap
in the end zone to give the Jaguars their first playoff home win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got the lead back, we got the turnovers,'' said
Coughlin. ``They had three; we didn't have any. New England played
hard. They did a great job in the third period, but we were
fortunate to come back in the fourth period to make the plays and
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they ran away with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
