<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO COMPETE 
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-BOS-2   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ After all the talk abut the Bowl Championship
Series, about computer rankings, and polls, the champion of the
1998 college football season finally will be crowned Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be done on the field, between teams who are the best
college football has to offer this season.
</P>
<P>
   In matching No. 1 Tennessee (12-0) vs. No. 2 Florida State
(11-1), the Fiesta Bowl has a game worthy of its hype.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, teams like Ohio State (11-1) can make claims, as they did
after Friday night's 24-14 Sugar Bowl victory over Texas A&AMP;M. There
are Rose Bowl winner Wisconsin and Holiday Bowl winner Arizona,
each with a loss. There's even Tulane, other than Tennessee the
only unbeaten Division 1-A team remaining. All could be considered,
but no one can really quibble with the credentials of either the
Volunteers or Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has earned its shot at its first national championship
since 1951. If the Vols win _ and they are 5 1/2-point underdogs _
they will have beaten eight bowl teams, including three BCS teams _
Syracuse, Florida, and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   They have shown they can win various ways, whether on a
last-second touchdown pass, as quarterback Tee Martin threw in
beating Syracuse in the opener, or with a modicum of luck, as they
had in their last-minute win over Arkansas, aided by a crucial
Razorbacks fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Vols are contending with doubters who believe that
this will be another Tennessee disappointment, another team that
will lose the ultimate game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably a lot of people out there who don't think we
belong in this game,'' said Tennessee wide receiver Peerless Price.
``We've been a team that's been so close for so long. With how hard
we've worked and everything we've overcome, I really can't see
anybody being more deserving to be here than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Price may have a point. The Vols have leaped a steady succession
of hurdles this season.
</P>
<P>
   They switched from four-year starter Peyton Manning to Martin at
quarterback without a hitch; they absorbed the season-ending injury
of their best running back, Jamal Lewis; they adjusted to losing
three starters in their secondary.
</P>
<P>
   This is a much different Tennessee team than the one that lost
to Florida for the fifth straight time last season, than the squad
that was embarrassed and overmatched against Nebraska in the Orange
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there were certain things that had to happen, certain
things that we had to make happen,'' said Tennessee's Phil Fulmer,
who is finally starting to receive recognition as a coach who can
win big games.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols have done it all, mostly with their defense and enough
offensive production by Martin to get them leads.
</P>
<P>
   For Florida State, it has been another year on the edge. The
Seminoles nearly fell off the cliff when they were soundly beaten
by then-unranked North Carolina State, 24-7, Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   But, as much as Top 5 finishes _ of which there have been 12 in
a row _ stumbling at least once a season also has become a Florida
State tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's because of the schedule we play,'' said coach Bobby
Bowden, who never has had an unbeaten season at Florida State. ``We
don't go out and play Tennessee-Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Seminoles win, they will have played nine bowl teams, and
beaten three BCS teams _ Texas A&AMP;M, Florida, and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   They also have overcome adversity, handling a season-ending
injury of quarterback Chris Weinke without much loss of efficiency,
replacing him with untested sophomore Marcus Outzen.
</P>
<P>
   Although Outzen oozes confidence and seems to show no nerves
about the biggest game of his career and his his fourth game as a
starter, count on the Tennessee defense to make him its focal
point.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden already has a national championship, but says he wants
another.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer wants his first.
</P>
<P>
   On paper it looks like a defensive tossup, which could and
probably will be decided by a late-game turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be putting a crown on a great six years, really,''
said Fulmer, who has the highest winning percentage (66-11, 85.7
percent) of any active Division 1-A coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Tennessee can get Win No. 67 Monday night, it truly will have
earned its national championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
