u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ZOLAK-BO     01-04 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ZOLAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK LACKING IN THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Scott Zolak could twist the numbers if he
wanted. It would be easy. Numbers are like that. Sometimes they can
be so flexible that they can make you question what you saw with
your own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people watched Zolak and his Patriots play the
Jaguars on national television Sunday. Another group of 71,139
watched live in Alltel Stadium as the Jaguars ended the Patriots'
season, 25-10, in an AFC wild-card game. Maybe you were one of the
viewers who thought Zolak didn't look good at quarterback. Maybe
you threw things at your television and called the man out of his
name. There's a chance you thought he looked like a veteran
quarterback _ a veteran quarterback who is very experienced at
watching and not playing. Maybe you thought, ``I wish the Patriots
had someone like Mark Brunell,'' the former Pro Bowler who starts
for the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say you didn't watch the playoff game that Zolak was
forced to start because of an injury to Drew Bledsoe's finger.
Let's say you bumped into Zolak at your neighborhood convenience
store and asked him to stack his numbers next to Brunell's. In that
case, the numbers would not reveal the true story. That's because
Zolak could tell you that he completed a higher percentage of his
passes than Brunell. He also could tell you that he threw for more
yards. He could say that he moved his team up and down the field in
the third quarter while Brunell could only direct a couple of
three-downs-and-out series.
</P>
<P>
   If you asked for more, Zolak could recite this quote from
Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin: ``The Patriots played a solid
football game and Zolak made some plays in the third quarter which
got us quite concerned.'' He could accurately tell you that
Patriots coach Pete Carroll never considered taking him out of the
game at halftime but, on the Jaguars sideline, Coughlin and Brunell
could be seen having a lively discussion. Speculation was that
Coughlin was considering removing Brunell before, as Brunell said,
``I just encouraged him, I should say, to keep me in there. It
wasn't a confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   See? Numbers are crazy. All of those words and numbers are true,
yet the Patriots are in Foxborough, Mass., this morning. They are
cleaning out their lockers, having team meetings, and, as Zolak
said, ``picking up two Super Bowl tickets if you want to watch
somebody else play in it. Not me. I'm selling mine.'' He was asked
his selling price for the Super Bowl tickets. ``Oh, face value,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Face value. More than anything, ``face value'' tells
you more about Zolak and the Patriots than numbers. Brunell may
have been wild on some of his throws. He may have looked like a
rookie in the second quarter when he was called for an intentional
grounding penalty that took his team out of field-goal range. But
he did throw for a touchdown, did not have an interception, and did
have a running game.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak can't say that. He got the team into position for a
touchdown in the third quarter, when Robert Edwards scored from the
1. But with his team trailing, 12-7, at the beginning of the fourth
quarter, Zolak needed a touchdown. What his team got was a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say that was the turning point, but if we get it there
it really gets our momentum going and shuts up their crowd,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   You know by now that the opposite happened. After the
Jacksonville lead shrunk to 2, 12-10, Brunell found Jimmy Smith
open against Ty Law. Most of the 34 balls he threw on the afternoon
were wayward, but Brunell threw perfectly toward the end zone on
the ball to Smith. Thirty-seven yards later, Smith had a touchdown.
Shortly after, the locals began to crank up their music and chant,
``We want the Jets.'' Amidst all that was poor Zolak, the guy who
was forced to face the craziness of numbers again.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers can be two-faced. Sometimes they matter and sometimes
they don't. They mattered when the Patriots trailed by 9 in the
fourth quarter. That's because the Jaguars knew that the Patriots
had to pass because they could not run. Edwards finished the day
with 28 yards on 17 carries. Scary numbers. And since Coughlin
knows Bill Parcells's phone number, you can bet that he talked to
the Tuna about the quarterback he coached for five seasons. So
there were no secrets at the end of the game. Not only did the
Jaguars know Zolak would throw, they knew where he was throwing. It
is no surprise, then, that New England was done scoring for the
day.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the best northern Florida afternoon for the Patriots.
It was a day when rookies Edwards and Tony Simmons had more
receptions than Ben Coates. It was a day when the punter, Tom Tupa,
was the most outstanding player. It was a day when the Patriots had
one first down in the first half. It was a day when Zolak walked on
the field, put up slightly better numbers than a Pro Bowler, and
then walked off the field to talk about a loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
