<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN DOWN AFTER GOOD GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ He was their best receiver, their best
return man, and, when it was over Sunday in Alltel Stadium, their
best spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I look at the last couple weeks?'' asked Troy Brown.
``We've gotten our asses kicked the last couple weeks. That's all
you need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Those searching for any shred of positivity from the Patriots'
25-10 wild-card playoff loss to the Jaguars should look toward
Brown. The team had missed his steadiness midway through the season
because of his severe ankle injury. When he is in the lineup, Brown
has a knack for doing good things. Drew Bledsoe has called him ``my
guy.'' Bill Parcells tried to cut him a few times, but the coach
finally realized that Brown made plays.
</P>
<P>
   He did that Sunday, catching four balls for a team-high 46
yards. He returned a punt 17 yards in the third quarter, which led
to New England's final points of the day. He did his job. You
wondered why the ball wasn't thrown his way more often. ``I just do
what they tell me,'' he said. ``I'm not the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown sat next to Bruce Armstrong in the locker room. So he
listened at halftime when Armstrong and a few others tried to
inspire the team for the second half. The Patriots trailed, 12-0,
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armey is a guy who has been around for a long time; he knows
what he's talking about,'' Brown said. ``Some guys listened and
some guys didn't. All I can say is that you have to be ready to
play, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not say the Patriots were not ready to play. He didn't
say they were, either. After a few seconds, he didn't say much at
all. Finally, he shrugged, continued to dress quietly, and said,
``I guess now it's time to go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
