<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAMES ARE TEST FOR BRUINS' RESOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Which way are the Bruins headed? Is the team back to
its winning ways, playing defense first and scoring goals off other
teams' mistakes, just as it did in beating Anaheim, 2-1, Saturday
night? Or was that just one game; did the real Bruins show their
wares in losing three out of four on their recent road trip, when
they were outscored, 17-9?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will take a step in one direction Monday night
against the Calgary Flames. Will it be another game like the
victory over the Mighty Ducks? Or a game like the 6-1 setback in
Dallas Thursday? Which is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a relief if we can back it up,'' said Bruins
veteran defenseman Don Sweeney Sunday after the Bruins' workout at
the FleetCenter. ``It won't be a relief if it's a one-game stint.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the Bruins' difficulties began before the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gotten away from it (playing defensively) for a while
even during our winning streak,'' Sweeney said. ``We were getting
away with little things in areas that we've got to do better in. We
were talking about it, trying to adjust, but when you're winning,
sometimes you overlook those things. When you're losing, that's
what stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   So against Anaheim, featuring the high-scoring trio of Paul
Kariya, Teemu Selanne and Steve Rucchin _ and a team coming off a
7-2 victory against the Buffalo Sabres and Dominik Hasek Friday _
focusing on the little things was an essential part of a winning
formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys did a good job against that top line and, for the most
part, we tried to stay out of the penalty box,'' said Sweeney of
the win over Anaheim. ``Their power play is real good and to stay
focused every shift that you're out and stick to the game plan,
that's what we're trying to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, Ray Bourque talked to the players about how the
Bruins have a pretty good reputation under coach Pat Burns as a
team that other squads don't want to go against. The Bruins make
opponents work for goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to disappoint them (the opponents) in that
area,'' Sweeney said. ``We don't want to do some of the things we
sometimes got away from doing, especially on the last road trip. We
want them to realize that's the way it's going to be to play
against us. We want that reputation of being hard to play against.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a difficult team to play against and when you talk to
other players, that's respect. You have to go out and earn that.
You have to earn that every night. You don't just live on that from
last year. You've got to go out and back that up and give it to
them. You might as well bring them what they expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, who have forged a 17-13-6 record, have no give in
their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspiration comes in the fact how close everything is in
the conference,'' Sweeney said. ``It's going to take a lot of
points to make the playoffs. You've got to realize that. Every
night, those two points you have an opportunity to get are
precious. You've got to realize that from the get-go and go out and
protect them and go out and get them. You want them in the bank now
because it's only going to get harder as the year goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Every team is tough. Any team can beat any other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're gaining ground or losing ground,'' Sweeney said. ``It's
going to be tough all the way across the board. Every night,
there's going to be a challenge, an opportunity to step forward and
take two points. You gain two points and gain ground or push
yourself away from somebody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
