<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' FOCUS TURNS TO CARROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ First, Patriots owner Robert Kraft called
media reports that coach Pete Carroll would be fired after Sunday's
loss ``hogwash.'' He then said that he will let vice president of
player personnel Bobby Grier evaluate Carroll and give the owner a
recommendation on his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby is going to evaluate things on the football field and
(vice president of business operations) Andy Wasynczuk evaluates it
off the field,'' said Kraft. ``That's how our organization works
and that's the process we're going to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Pete Carroll. He's a tremendous guy, a great family
man, and he's done a lot of great things for our organization. He's
a very good coach and we're trying to help him along as much as we
possibly can. I would like nothing more than for Pete Carroll to be
the coach of this team for years and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the stories are ludicrous. Why would anyone in our
family say something like that and hurt our chances right before a
playoff game? Would we be trying to hurt our own chance of winning
the game? Anyone who knows us knows we would never do something
like that. I hated to hear that those stories were out there, and I
can tell you nobody in this organization has anything to do with it
because we haven't discussed it as an organization yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said of the evaluation, ``It's going to be very detailed
and it's probably not going to be right away. I want to evaluate
all aspects of the organization and not just the coach and see the
things we did right and the things we did wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't be a knee-jerk evaluation. And it certainly won't
be based on one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has been meeting with Carroll the past few days. ``I told
Pete that the stories were hogwash,'' he said. ``I told him that he
shouldn't pay any attention to them. He should concentrate on
coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Carroll hurt himself more with Sunday's loss remains to
be seen. What is certain is that Kraft shook Carroll's hand after
the game and thanked him for the season.
</P>
<P>
   He then went across the way and shook hands with Tom Coughlin
and wished him well against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville offensive coordinator Chris Palmer, rumored to be a
candidate to replace Carroll, did not comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
