</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS STAGGER TO FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ They announced plans to move to the state
of Connecticut, ended their season in the state of Florida, and
always seemed to be in a state of confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, take one last look at your 1998-99 New
England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' Season of the Witch ended Sunday with a limp,
25-10 wild-card playoff game loss to the beatable Jaguars by the
swampy shores of the St. John River. The season that started in
promising fashion (the Patriots were considered NFL elite after
their 41-10 dismantling of Kansas City made them 4-1 in October)
ended with Drew Bledsoe on the sideline with a broken finger,
players on the field pointing fingers, and coach Pete Carroll
embroiled in speculation that he may be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming back next year to put together a football team
that can win championships,'' Carroll said after the loss. ``And
I'm going to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Carroll has three years remaining on a five-year
contract, but tanned owner Bob Kraft and his son, Jonathan, failed
to issue any assurance that their coach will return. Both claimed
the decision would be made by player personnel director Bobby Grier
_ which is tantamount to the US Senate claiming the fate of Bill
Clinton lies in the hands of Connecticut State Assembly. Does
George Steinbrenner let Brian Cashman hire or fire Joe Torre? Let's
not be ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Patriots are a team headed in the wrong direction.
In the last two years, since Carroll replaced Bill Parcells, they
have gone from 11-5 to 10-6 to 9-7. They have gone from the Super
Bowl, to the second round of the playoffs, to one-and-out in
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   They were 8 1/2-point underdogs Sunday and played down to the
low expectations. New England fell behind, 12-0, in the first half,
and backup quarterback Scott Zolak made a good case for Bledsoe
($42 million over seven years) to ask for a raise. New England
compiled an embarrassing 54 yards of offense in the first half (one
first down) when Zolak was 5 for 16 for 39 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots showed some heart in the second half, closing
within 12-7 with a 17-play, 85-yard third-quarter drive. Early in
the fourth, they stormed inside the red zone again and it looked
like they might take the lead, but they settled for a field goal
and it was 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   In a season in which the Patriots suffered so many injuries to
key players, it seemed unfair that the final loss would come down
on the head of their best injury-free player. Cornerback Ty Law,
tops in the game at his position, was burned by Jacksonville
wideout Jimmy Smith for a 37-yard touchdown pass that effectively
put the game out of reach. New England's defeat wasn't sealed until
Zolak fumbled on his 25-yard line with 7 1/2 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in New Jersey, the Great White Tuna must have been
smiling when Zolak fumbled. The man who recovered Zolak's fumble
was none other than Tony Brackens _ the lineman Parcells wanted to
draft instead of Terry Glenn three years ago. It was Kraft's
duplicity during the 1996 draft that paved the road for Parcells to
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Brackens's fumble recovery assured that the Patriots would lose
to Jacksonville, which meant another victory for Parcells. This
way, the Tuna gets to play wobbly Jacksonville next week instead of
dangerous Miami. It also means that Kraft continues to look foolish
for playing Strat-o-Matic with the Super Bowl Patriots of 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 Sons of Pete Carroll were certainly unlucky.
Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, and Ted Johnson, three of their best players,
were on the shelf down the stretch, and many fans believed the team
overachieved under adverse conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But Patriot Nation was discouraged by the 31-10 humiliation at
the hands of Parcells's Jets in the final regular-season game and
Sunday's listless loss to a similarly wounded team. And the final
week of the star-crossed season, a pre-playoff time that should
have been joyous, was punctuated by speculation about Carroll's
dismissal floated by an in-house source.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft, the power behind the throne in the family
empire, was enraged that his name was floated (here) as the source
of the rumor and vehemently denied the charge after Sunday's game.
``I've been unjustly accused of something that isn't true,'' he
said before addressing his disgust with ``all the people that have
been putting knives in our backs all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody should be watching their backs in Foxborough this
week. And next. The offseason has only just begun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
