<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     01-04 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASSIC WILD-CARD WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER   
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital)Welcome to today's NFL-heavy edition of The Sporting
Muse:(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's time-honored tradition of equating football with war
is pretty weary, but Sunday's playoff game between the 49ers and
Packers deserves that kind of labeling. This one could be replayed
immediately on ESPN Classic Sports.
</P>
<P>
   This NFC wild card playoff match was about the respect and/or
contempt the two teams have for each other, born of having met in
the playoffs the last four seasons and each taking various turns as
the best team in football. The games' title was no match for these
two teams, who played as if their freedom depended on victory.
</P>
<P>
   The hits were harder and the effort seemed greater. Both teams
lowered their guard as NFL royalty and took wild swings, right down
to Brett Favre hammering a 49er rusher in the facemask before said
lineman had a chance to hit first.
</P>
<P>
   In the years to come, the 49ers' 30-27 win may be viewed as the
last punch of two heavyweights who know their best days are behind
them. We'll likely remember the game longer than the Super Bowl....
</P>
<P>
   It may be the greatest sports mystery of all time: Why do
bright, intelligent coaches pass rush only three men in situations
like Sunday's?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers needed a touchdown to win and were down to their last
few seconds, but that did not deter Packers coach Mike Holmgren
from dropping eight backs into coverage _ and getting beat down the
gut for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The three-man rush is a virtual invitation to disaster,
especially when it comes against a veteran quarterback like Steve
Young.
</P>
<P>
   The book on pass defense may say that an eight-man secondary
ultimately has the edge on five receivers. But what I saw Sunday
was Young finding Terrell Owens in the middle of the field between
five converging Packers.
</P>
<P>
   If the Packers rush four men instead of three, and force Young
to move or at least put a couple of hands in his face, maybe he
doesn't see Owens splitting the seam, or maybe he misfires because
his feet are moving right or left....
</P>
<P>
   The non-call on Jerry Rice's fumble in the final sequence will
undoubtedly feed the machinery to revive Instant Replay. But based
on past applications, that particular play would not have subject
to videotape scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   That's actually the kind of play which sent I.R. to its death.
Once an official whistles a play dead, all action stops. It may
have looked like a fumble or been a fumble, but I.R. can't put a
whistle back into the blower.
</P>
<P>
   The situation depends on the ability of the men on the field to
know when a play has reached its conclusion, a not a nanosecond too
soon or late. I.R. can't fix that problem....
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit difficult to get a handle on the NFC what with all
the newcomers still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing out all results from the 1982 strike season, Arizona is
making its first playoff appearance since 1975 and Atlanta its
third appearance since 1981. Minnesota won its first round game
last year after losing its first postseason outing its previous
five tries....
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a moral to the NFL story at this juncture? When
making quarterback personnel decisions, favor those of vintage.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the eight starting quarterbacks remaining is
33, and its almost 35 if you throw out the kid with the rattle,
Jake Plummer. The Snake turned 24 last month.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the eight are 33 or older. John Elway is 38, Young and
Dan Marino are 37, Randall Cunningham and Vinny Testaverde are 35
and Chris Chandler is 33. Mark Brunell is 28....
</P>
<P>
   Here's some spread numbers, courtesy of The Gold Sheet, for
those who care about such things. Minnesota is 11-4-1, Atlanta
11-4-1, San Francisco 6-9-2 and Arizona 6-10-1; Denver is 9-7, the
Jets 12-4, Jacksonville 10-7 and Miami 10-6-1....
</P>
<P>
   Playoff and bowl perspectives:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona-Minnesota: Has a team that went 9-7 during the regular
season ever made it to the Super Bowl? Yes. Your own Los Angeles
Rams were the only team to do so since the league went to the
16-game schedule. They won the desultory NFC West at 9-7 and then
upset 11-5 Dallas and 10-6 Tampa Bay to earn their only Super Bowl
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals can point to three seasons when a 9-7 team made it
to the AFC title game. It happened in 1983 (Seattle), 1984
(Pittsburgh) and 1995 (Indianapolis). Chances are they'll be
content with beating Dallas and winning a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco-Atlanta: Since 1984, the Falcons' all-time record
against the 49ers is 6-23-1. They split the series this season.
Most of their games have been high-scoring affairs, too. And for
what it's worth, the Falcons are among the league's worst in home
attendance, so who knows whether or not they'll have an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Denver: Between 1983 and 1997, Elway and Marino met once.
Now they meet for the second time in less than a month. Marino won
the latest battle, but the Fish were catching Elway at home and the
week after the Broncos' perfect season had expired. Denver's last
loss at home was to Jacksonville in the 1996 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville-New York Jets: Jags coach Tom Coughlin was on Bill
Parcells' staff with the Giants. The Jags are dangerous, but
Parcells reportedly preferred seeing them than having to play a
third game against an AFC East foe.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee-Florida State: Let me first eliminate any confusion in
the minds of Ohio State fans: The Buckeyes will not win any polls
outside of Columbus regardless of what happens in the Fiesta Bowl
tonight. A 24-14 win against Texas A&AMP;M won't make any difference.
</P>
<P>
   This should be a low-scoring contest. Both teams have great
defenses, with Florida State ranking first or second nationally in
every key defensive area. Both have good but not overpowering
running games. Both quarterbacks are efficient, with Tee Martin
having an experience edge on Marcus Outzen.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State went 7-1 against opponents that bowled this
season, and Tennessee was 7-0. I have nothing good to say about the
BCS, but this matchup is about as close as you'd get to a national
title match without the benefit of a playoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
