<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANOE-CAPSIZES-LADN     01-04 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANOE-CAPSIZES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE KILLED, ONE LOST AS WAVES SINK CANOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY KEVIN F. SHERRY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. -- An outrigger canoe carrying an experienced
six-man paddling team sank in heavy surf Sunday, killing one,
leaving one lost at sea and injuring four others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was totally a freak accident,'' said Michael Davis, 30,
one of the crew members rescued by a fishing boat after several
hours in the 56-degree water. ``We were very trained, skilled at
what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   John Devlin, 50, of Oxnard in Southern California's Ventura
County died in the water, and crew mate Scotty Fullenger remained
missing. One crew member was in critical condition Sunday night and
another in guarded condition. Two others were treated at area
hospitals and released.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 13 years, the six men have gathered four days a
week to paddle their 40-foot Hawaiian-style outrigger canoe and to
rejuvenate their souls, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the team headed out about 8 a.m. in shorts and
T-shirts but no life jackets. The waves were high, but the team had
handled higher, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   About a mile off the breakwater, waves 4 to 6 feet high slapped
water into the canoe, and the crew headed back to the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were already on our way back before we got hit by a couple
of good waves,'' Davis said. ``We took on water, and we sunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Two crewmen swam for shore while four remained with the sinking
boat. Eventually the boat sank, and the four also took their
chances swimming, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hanging close to each other,'' he said. ``It was too
hard. We were just getting worked out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The men did not get very far because of the waves and the cold,
Davis said. They could see the shore and signaled for help, but to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a few boats in the beginning, but they were off to the
distance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis figured his one hope would be to return to the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think anyone was coming by,'' he said. ``I was
thinking about getting all my men to shore.''
</P>
<P>
   After the men spent a few hours in the chilly surf, hypothermia
began to set in. When Devlin died in the water, his three teammates
struggled to keep him afloat, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to hold him,'' Davis said. ``(Captain) Ben
Taitai held him in his arms for about 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, a fishing boat came upon the four men and
helped them aboard. ``Everybody was just at different stages of
hypothermia,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Crewman Justin Heard, 28, of Oxnard was airlifted from the
fishing boat to St. John's Regional Medical Center in Oxnard, where
he was listed in critical condition in the hospital's intensive
care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Taitai, 50, also of Oxnard, were treated for
hypothermia at Ventura County Medical Center and released.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 p.m., a civilian boat that was helping in the search
found crewman Tino Rico, 38. Rico was taken to St. John's Regional
Medical Center, where he was listed in guarded condition.
</P>
<P>
   The search for Fullenger was expected to continue until 1 a.m.
today and start again later this morning, said Dawn Butler, a petty
officer with the Search and Rescue Division of the U.S. Coast
Guard. Helicopters, boats and vehicles from the Harbor Patrol, the
Coast Guard and the state lifeguard station joined in the search on
land, on sea and in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll search until they've exhausted all possibility of the
person being alive,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0103EST &QL; 
