<SLUG> BC-STORM-MIDWEST-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO DIGS OUT, BUT STORM CRIPPLES AIR TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 9th graf to update number of deaths in Illinois and the
Midwest) (lb) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Pummeled by the most ferocious snowstorm in more than
30 years, this high-stepping city, after being slowed to a crawl,
started to come back to life on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 feet of snow blanketed the city, left by a storm so
furious that at times on Saturday street plows sat idle in
futility. By Sunday afternoon, however, after an army of city
workers had scraped and swept with a vengeance, the streets became
passable.
</P>
<P>
   Getting in or out of town by air, however, remained problematic.
O'Hare International Airport, the United States' busiest, and
Midway Airport struggled to get back to normal on Sunday after
virtually shutting down on Saturday. There were still plenty of
canceled flights and long delays for travelers returning from the
holidays. Some 400 people had slept on cots and benches inside the
airport on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, air travel throughout the eastern half of the nation was
disrupted Sunday, as the snow and ice in the Midwest, coupled with
heavy sleet and rain on Sunday morning in the Northeast as the
storm moved eastward, resulted in hundreds of canceled flights and
thousands of disgruntled passengers.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York area, the storm and the ripple effects from the
Midwest stranded or delayed thousands of travelers at Kennedy, La
Guardia and Newark International airports as airlines scratched or
rescheduled flights and threw out their timetables.
</P>
<P>
   With water a foot deep on the JFK Expressway leading to Kennedy
Airport, traffic was halted for more than two hours at
midafternoon, and witnesses told of chaos as riders abandoned
stalled taxis and cars and, with luggage and children in tow,
streamed like refugees for the terminals a mile or two away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely frustrating,'' Adena Muchnik, 26, of New
York said as she and her husband, David, hobbled along the
roadside, struggling with three suitcases and two small children in
strollers, trying to catch a 3:45 flight to Australia. It was
already 3:15, and the dream was dying. ``If we don't make the
flight to Melbourne, we might be out of a vacation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, which barreled up from the Gulf Coast on Friday, also
dumped heavy snow on Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Michigan, Minnesota,
Missouri, Nebraska, Ohio and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was blamed for at least 36 deaths in the Midwest,
including 11 in Illinois. Many were the result of traffic
accidents. A 130-mile stretch of Interstate 65 in Indiana reopened
Sunday after being closed on Saturday, but many counties in the
state still banned unnecessary travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roads were like ice,'' said John Rawlings, who spent the
night with 200 other travelers at a church near Lafayette, Ind.,
after his van slid off I-65. ``The wind just picked it up and put
it in the ditch,'' Rawlings told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast on Sunday, it was rain that turned highways
across the region into running rivers, downed power lines in parts
of Connecticut, caused 200 accidents on the New York Thruway, and
toppled rainfall records in New York's Central Park, where 2.42
inches eclipsed a 1936 mark for the date by more than an inch, and
in Bridgeport, Conn., which had 2.71 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh as it was, the storm might have been much worse if
temperatures, which hovered in the 40s most of the day, had been 10
or 15 degrees lower, and the precipitation had turned to snow,
weather experts said. A meteorological rule of thumb is that every
inch of rain would have been a foot of snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a big snowstorm,'' Todd Miner, a
meteorologist with Pennsylvania State University, said. ``As it
was, all the snow was dumped in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22 inches that was dumped in Chicago was the most in one
storm since 1967. Indeed, for all its reputation for tough winter
weather, the city had not had more than a foot of snow from any one
storm since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   And in a city where where almost everything is viewed through
the prism of politics, the storm prompted plenty of parlor talk
about the infamous snowstorm of 1979, a mess that contributed
mightily to Jane Byrne's upset victory of the incumbent mayor,
Michael Bilandic. Bilandic had been regarded by voters as being
indifferent to the suffering of Chicagoans, in particular
neglecting black neighborhoods on the South Side.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley, running for re-election this year
against Rep. Bobby Rush, made himself highly visible during this
storm, casting himself in news conferences as a general rallying
the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This task will be enormous,'' said Daley. ``Please be
patient.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The storm followed a remarkable stretch of weather in Chicago
during the last months of 1998, mild temperatures, brilliant
sunshine and skies that seemed as blue as Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the blankets of snow have given the city an almost
angelic cast, a look of purity and cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, it's just beautiful,'' said Tom Amenda, 41, a stock
trader.
</P>
<P>
   Amenda and his wife, Mary Shannon, a 38-year-old teacher, had
spent the afternoon shopping, and making snow angels in the yard of
their Wicker Park neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Struck by how quickly the city's streets had been cleaned,
Amenda expressed gratitude for nature's good timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have a blizzard in Chicago,'' said Amenda,
``you want to have it during an election year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
