<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6663 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-STATE-UCL     01-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-STATE-UCLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU LOOKS TO CHANGE LUCK VS. UCLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For eight seasons, Bill Frieder couldn't do it.
Don Newman twice took a shot at it last year and came away empty.
Now it's Rob Evans' turn to try to coach an Arizona State
basketball team to a victory over UCLA tonight when the Sun Devils
visit Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to some good players and a few problems, Evans
inherited a streak of 19 consecutive losses to UCLA, dating to late
in the 1988-89 season. The Sun Devils are 0 for the 90s against the
Bruins. Their last win came under interim coach Bob Schermerhorn,
who replaced the fired Steve Patterson and preceded Frieder.
</P>
<P>
   Frieder's clubs were 0-17 against the Bruins, albeit with some
close calls. The most notable was a 1995 overtime game at Pauley in
which Frieder will swear until his last breath his team was robbed
by an official. Under Newman, the interim coach last season, ASU
lost by five and eight points.
</P>
<P>
   Schermerhorn, meanwhile, is a junior college head coach taking a
leave of absence this season. He watched the Sun Devils on Saturday
when they lost to Southern California, 72-70, at the Sports Arena
in the Pac-10 opener and pronounced them ``very well-coached.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans is responsible for much of that. But he had nothing to do
with the futility against the Bruins and reacted to it
accordingly.``It's no factor now,'' he said. ``Some of the kids
playing now, some were part of the streak, some weren't. I know I
wasn't a part of it. Streaks mean nothing to me. The next ball game
is the only thing that means anything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Evans was at Mississippi, his 1997-98 team won at Kentucky
for the first time in more than 50 years. That was big, but Evans
put it in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Mississippi, every time we did something we broke a
streak,'' he said. ``The situation had been so bleak.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players, especially the veterans, see it a little
differently. Beating UCLA is huge by itself. Being the first ASU
team to do it in almost a decade would be special.
</P>
<P>
   For senior Mike Batiste, who grew up around here, nothing would
be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never beaten UCLA,'' he said. ``It's time to break the
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, ASU will have to avoid the mistakes that cost the
Sun Devils against USC, and do it against a better team. But it is
a younger UCLA team, at least on the surface. With Batiste, senior
forward Bobby Lazor and junior guard Eddie House, the Sun Devils
have three players with more experience than anyone on UCLA's
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could play three-on-three we could probably win,'' Evans
said. ``But they're not gonna allow us to play three-on-three.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores Baron Davis, Earl Watson and Moose Bailey form the
best three-guard rotation ASU has seen, and freshmen Jerome Moiso
and Dan Gadzuric pose big problems inside. And freshman forward
JaRon Rush, the Bruins' third-leading scorer, returns from a
one-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils gave up an 18-point first-half lead to the
Trojans by failing to get back on defense, being careless with the
ball and allowing too many put-backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of got lazy and broke down a little bit,'' Batiste
said. ``We didn't find their shooters. We've got to know who to
guard, who to locate and get to them and get a hand in their
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said ASU might have become worn down in the second half.
Only two reserves, swingman Derrick Davis and forward Chad Prewitt,
played 11 minutes or more. Three USC subs played at least 24
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he would like to go to his bench and give players
like Lohnnie Tape and Jason Patton more time, but it's difficult
when they don't produce in games or practice.
</P>
<P>
   Tape, a 6-foot-7 forward, played one minute against USC before
getting yanked. Patton, a 6-4 swingman, has not yet grasped the
system. He didn't play against the Trojans and hasn't seen
meaningful action in more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have confidence in them,'' Evans said. ``You have
to play them early and in critical situations. When you end up
losing ball games, you end up losing confidence, but you've got to
bite the bullet and play some guys some more minutes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
