<HEADER>
A6664 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-CA     01-04 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIRY TALE SEASON CAPTIVATES NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One journey has ended, and that's the quest for awareness, the
uphill climb through quicksand, the struggle for allegiance in a
fickle desert.
</P>
<P>
   But as you gather around the water cooler, basking in the warm
cocoon of civic pride, reliving the magic and replaying the
triumph, you might not know this:
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are a national entity now.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't just throttle America's Team. They stole its title,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Their quarterback is not only the cornerstone of the franchise,
but the perfect symbol for the NFL. Somewhere in New York,
marketing executives are surely preparing their pitches, clearing
out space in their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Their team is full of characters. From the bravado of Andre
Wadsworth, to the wide eyes of Jamir Miller, to the kaleidoscope
personality of Simeon Rice. From the homogenous coach who has
broken through, to the hermit owner suddenly surfing in the
glorious waves of acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   From the gregarious personnel boss who can't watch (he gets too
nervous at the end of games), yet a man who can't miss (the latest
being Chris Jacke and Carl Simpson). And a staff of assistants
earning their keep.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, NFL rumor monger Fred Edelstein blasted
Marc Trestman during a radio interview. Citing an anonymous source
in San Francisco, he claimed that the offensive coordinator would
show up at the 49ers' training complex on Monday and ask if anyone
had any ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Trestman has been nothing short of brilliant in the second
half of the season. A diverse mind with an aggressive approach. Any
doubts now?
</P>
<P>
   You may not know this, but the Cardinals captivated the country
in a 20-7 pasting of the Cowboys. They are wild, unpredictable, the
best entertainment value in the league. Their infamous futility is
the perfect backdrop in which to frame the story, one that is
currently jumping off the canvass.
</P>
<P>
   And this is not a stretch:
</P>
<P>
   With a decent showing in Minnesota, the Cardinals will be
considered an outside shot to ``win'' the Super Bowl next season.
After all, they do have the eighth pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Nationally televised games. Invitations to Monday
Night Football. No more third-rate broadcasting crews. A new
stadium proposal not unlike Deion Sanders' toe, shot up with
cortizone, upgraded from doubtful to probable in the span of 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, in a hotel bar in Dallas, Plummer's mother
proudly wore her son's jersey. Other Cardinals fans wandered about
in conquest. And in the corners of the room, pockets of Cowboys
fans shriveled in their seats. The iron lungs of arrogance were
reduced to silence.
</P>
<P>
   While they were mute in Texas, the rest of the nation hailed the
conquering heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-eminent voice in Chicago told a half-million readers
that the wrong football team may have left town four decades ago. A
columnist in Dallas said when Troy Aikman shook Jake Plummer's hand
after the game, he may as well have passed a torch. And surely
there are directives from newspaper editors across the land,
messages to their troops in town for the Fiesta Bowl. Requests
that, while you're in town, can you please scoot over and give us
something on the Cardinals?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, something for all you Cowboys fans in the Valley: On
the front page of the ``Dallas Morning New''s' sports section,
these words shined, crafted from the alphabet of treason:
</P>
<P>
   ``Plummer and his Cardinals are the future of the NFC East.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the future is only a proposition, never a guarantee.
When the door finally shuts on this post-season, some weighty
issues need to be addressed. Miller's contract. The demands of Rob
Moore, who is looking for $4 million per season. The happiness of
Bob Ferguson, a man whose accomplishments cannot be understated or
undervalued. The future of Dave McGinnis, the defensive coordinator
about to enter an arena where demand exceeds supply.
</P>
<P>
   But the curtain remains closed on the stage of tomorrow, and it
should be. Because, after 11 years where ambivalence was the flip
side of scorn, after 11 years of empty seats and Broncos fans and
Steelers jerseys, the roots are taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   One journey is over. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
