<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-AZR &LR;      01-04 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINDERELLA CARDS AWAIT NEXT DANCE  
 WILL MIDNIGHT CHIME IN MINNESOTA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone is buying that the Cinderella Cardinals, the NFL's
touchy, feely story of the year, will continue to shock the world
as they march on in the NFC playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are 14{-point underdogs against the Minnesota
Vikings, owners of the NFL's best record at 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' rookie cornerback Corey Chavous said.
``People probably don't think we can stop their offense. We take it
as a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin's team hasn't been a two-touchdown underdog
all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what they've done,'' said Tobin of the Vikings, who
meet the Cardinals next Sunday at the Metrodome in Minneapolis.
``It's pretty impressive. They've got all those weapons and a guy
(Gary Anderson) who hasn't missed a kick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings lead the NFL in scoring (556), passing (270.5 yards
per game) and third-down efficiency (51.4 percent). They are second
in total offense (391.5 yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Randall Cunningham is the NFL's leading passer.
Rookie wide receiver Randy Moss is second in touchdowns with 17.
Anderson is the top scorer, thanks to converting all 35 of his
field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings offensive coordinator Brian Billick acknowledges that he
enjoys using his weapons to give opponents fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a defensive coordinator, when he sits down and goes
back one game, two games, three games, to have the cumulative
effect of `Oh, my God. How do I handle this?' '' Billick told ``Pro
Football Weekly.'' ``I want multiple formations, multiple people. I
want it to look overwhelming to a defense.''
</P>
<P>
   So should the Cardinals, with a 20-7 upset of the NFC
East-champion Dallas Cowboys still on their minds, consider
canceling the trip?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in awe,'' Tobin said. ``We think we're capable of
beating everyone in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Cardinals can say they've beaten a team this season
with a winning record. They played their most complete game of the
season in knocking the Cowboys (10-7) out of the playoffs Saturday
at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now they will try to win a fifth consecutive game for the first
time since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we played an awfully good football game,'' Tobin said.
``It's the first time all year our offense, defense and special
teams played (well) for 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings Coach Dennis Green was impressed. He expected to play
the winner of Sunday's Green Bay-San Francisco wild-card game but
said the Vikings spent as much time last week studying the
Cardinals as they did the Packers and 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had excellent balance,'' Green said of the Cardinals, who
passed for 213 yards and ran for 133. They ran the ball and
controlled the ball well, and their defense was excellent. Any time
you go on the road and win at Dallas in the playoffs, that says
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, no matter who you play, they're going to be
good. Look at how they played Dallas. Clearly, they handled Dallas.
They've got good talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have beaten the Cardinals the past two years,
including a 20-19 victory at Sun Devil Stadium a year ago, a game
in which the Cardinals blew a 10-point lead in the final five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Vikings scored 50 points against AFC
Central-champion Jacksonville. They also routed Green Bay twice
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get into a scoring contest up there,'' Tobin said.
``They have too many weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional edge should go to the Cardinals, who are coming
off the franchise's first playoff win in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first one since emblems were put on helmets, which
happened in 1948, one year after the Chicago Cardinals won the NFL
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all well and good what we've accomplished, but our future
is this week in Minnesota,'' Tobin said. ``Still, I'm proud of
where this franchise is. I'm proud of the way this team now is
thought of around the league. That was a big part of my goals. I
wondered, `Why couldn't the Cardinals be a class organization other
people emulate?' It wasn't thought of that way back then. We've
gone a long way to change that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
