</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSH-FIRE-1stLd-Writethru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUSH FIRE BURNS HUNDREDS OF ACRES IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Adds detail, updates byline, revises number of acres
burned.) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN AND LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A massive brush fire scorched up to 600 acres of
dry hillsides above suburban Porter Ranch on Sunday, as winds up to
50 mph whipped 20-foot flames perilously close to homes.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, which started about 11 a.m. in the city's San Fernando
Valley region about 25 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles,
spread west through the Santa Susana Mountains, creeping within
several yards of homes in the far north portion of Porter Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It burned from the top of the hill to the bottom in about 30
minutes,'' said resident Jerry Colburn, whose back yard abuts the
burn area. ``It kind of jumped around because there were embers
being blown around all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The arid, 78-degree air allowed winds of 35 mph to 50 mph to fan
the flames through brush parched by a season of low rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   While 400 to 600 acres burned, no injuries or structure damage
occurred, and the blaze was fully contained at 5 p.m. just east of
Winnetka, said Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Brian
Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   But residents spent several anxious hours Sunday afternoon
watching thick brown smoke rise off the charred hillside and
debating whether to leave or stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very worried,'' said Alex Henson, 46, whose home was also
on the front line of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here four years and this is the first time we've
had this kind of fire here,'' he said, watching bulldozers clear
dried grass as burning cinders stung his eyes. ``That's why I'm
trying to hang on as long as possible. If worst comes to worst, I
will have to take what I can and run.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 firefighters from the city Fire Department and the
Los Angeles and Ventura county fire departments attacked the blaze
on the ground, while five helicopters dropped water on the flames
or scouted out the fire's path, Los Angeles fire Capt. Tim McDonell
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the fire was reported, the Los Angeles Fire Department's
entire fleet of six helicopters was grounded for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, a department helicopter on a training mission
in the Santa Monica Mountains had a ``hard landing'' because of a
mechanical malfunction, Humphrey said. Under department policy all
helicopters in the fleet are inspected after such incidents,
grounding the fleet on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   One firefighter injured his ankle in the incident Saturday,
Humphrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our airships were out of service at the beginning of the fire.
But within the first half-hour our airships were cleared to fly,''
Humphrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident did not make a difference in terms of firefighting
because the Los Angeles County and Ventura County fire departments
sent a total of three helicopters to the fire at the request of the
city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually three more Los Angeles city helicopters joined in the
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire Department did not order evacuations, but Henson and
other residents stood ready to flee if the flames flared out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a firebreak, and between that and the tile roofs the
fire couldn't get through,'' said Dan Rigney, 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the kind of thing where you get the baby pictures out
and you get things ready to go just in case,'' said his wife,
Jamie, also 45.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in nearby neighborhoods also prepared for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my pictures and clothes in the car,'' said Nenet
Kureghian. ``The deer and rabbits were escaping from the flames and
it became very hot in our house. But there were fire trucks parked
all over in front so I felt pretty safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, fire officials were concerned Sunday afternoon that
the fire was not controlled and still posed a potential threat to
nearby neighborhoods. Because of the steep terrain and high winds,
firefighters could not attack it head on, but fought along its
flanks, trying to reduce and contain it.
</P>
<P>
   As firefighters monitored the fire through the Santa Susana
hillsides, others were stationed in Brown's Canyon and in
neighborhoods below Highway 118 in case the fire took a turn
southward, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get engine companies at least an hour ahead of
the fire, instead of trying to chase it,'' McDonell said.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts were successful, and the department pronounced the
fire contained at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Abkian of Porter Ranch said the flames burned up to her
home, but added that she was confident firefighters would keep them
at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were worried, but those firefighters were right in front of
our house,'' she said. ``They told us that if there was any danger
they would protect us. We trusted them and didn't panic. Now we're
OK. They knew exactly where the fire was heading. Thank God for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
