<SLUG> BC-NICK-NOLTE-IN-THE-THIN-RED-LINE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICK AT NIGHTFALL: NICK NOLTE WALKS THE DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Nick Nolte in a scene from ``The Thin Red
Line.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Nick Nolte takes an interminable drag on a cigarette, squints
his steely blue eyes and squirms, either stalling or at a loss for
words.
 &HT;    The question: What exactly does he do for a living?
 &HT;    ``I'd like to think I'm reflecting some sort of truth,'' he says
finally, exhaling a prodigious plume of smoke that fills a room at
Manhattan's Essex House. ``As an actor you're exposing life's
facades.
 &HT;    ``Acting, it's my marijuana,'' he says. ``It's what scrambles my
brain enough that I get to see past what I'd be so frightened to do
in real life, because real life is full of anxiety, greed and
power.
 &HT;    ``Reflecting all of that is my life.''
 &HT;    A bear of a man with a craggy face and a mad-scientist shock of
salt-and-pepper hair, Nolte has abandoned his usual attire of
pajamas in favor of a gray suit and a tie. He's talking about life,
but he might as well be talking about his latest films, ``The Thin
Red Line'' and ``Affliction,'' two dark dramas now in limited
release.
 &HT;    The former, reclusive director Terrence Malick's first film in
20 years, is based on James Jones' World War II novel, set in the
Pacific theater. Nolte plays Lt. Col. Gordon Tall, a bellowing
battalion commander who, in quest of personal glory, intends to
take a crucial hill on Guadalcanal at any cost, over the objections
of his loyal junior officer (John Cusack) and Capt. Staros (Elias
Koteas).
 &HT;    ``Our favorite phrase for the character was `self-will run
riot,''' Nolte says. ``Terry and I built him as caught between
World War I and World War II. He didn't get time on the firing
line, and most of the men who enlisted at that time were drunks,
homeless people who didn't have anyplace else to go.
 &HT;    ``So this guy's experience was he's a West Point grad training
drunks, going from fort to fort,'' he says. ``There's no war for
him, and he's getting old. And boom! Here's World War II, and now
is his chance.
 &HT;    ``There's the objective, and underneath that is the selfish
reason. Staros is the humanity, the compassion, and the real
question is, does compassion have any place in war?''
 &HT;    ``Thin Red Line'' has gotten tremendous attention as much for
Malick as for the movie itself. And Nolte reports that the director
lived up to his reputation.
 &HT;    ``It's not like he's eccentric or anything, but Terry's mind is
extremely wide,'' Nolte says. ``He can talk about Homer, birds,
history, and you're a little in awe of it.
 &HT;    ``He'd hand me a couple of pages to read,'' the actor recalls,
``and they'd be in Latin. He'd give me poetry and I'd say, `Jesus,
that's wonderful.' He'd say, `That's Homer. Maybe tomorrow you
could look up into the sky and say this.'
 &HT;    ``He'd write long scenes and say, `Edit it down. Find the core
in there.'''
 &HT;    Nolte's other film, ``Affliction,'' is even darker _
understandably, since it's based on a novel by Russell Banks,
author of last year's depressing ``The Sweet Hereafter.''
 &HT;    He plays Wade Whitehouse, a dreamer from a bleak small town who
has family troubles galore: His father (James Coburn) is a brutal
drunk, his brother (Willem Dafoe) long ago fled to the big city and
his daughter (Brigid Tierney) would rather be with his ex-wife
(Mary Beth Hurt). Through in his rapidly unraveling job as a cop,
and even by Banks' standards it's a dark, sad story with precious
few rays of hope.
 &HT;    When director Paul Schrader first approached Nolte several years
ago, the actor turned down the role.
 &HT;    ``I didn't feel mature enough,'' he says. ``I didn't have a
strong enough understanding of my own personal rage and violence in
general to get to the archetype.
 &HT;    ``I could understand alcoholism or being beaten by my father,''
he says. ``Those are easy. I could understand the cultural
standpoint, that we live in a competitive society and that breeds
violence. But I didn't understand the archetype and I didn't
understand the energy of it connected to nature, of why we're
violent and have been for thousands of years.''
 &HT;    There are a lot of violent movies, but few that try to
understand their violence. Three years later, Nolte felt ready to
try.
 &HT;    ``We can reach a certain level of rage that we needed at one
time to survive as a species,'' he says. ``When we socialized, it
became arcane, but that rage is innate and it's still within all of
us ...
 &HT;    ``Once I understood that,'' he concludes, ``I understood that I
am the killer, that I'm capable of killing, that we're all capable
of it. Then I could say to Paul, `I'm ready.'''
 &HT;    Finally released three years after it was shot, ``Affliction''
has garnered positive reviews and talk of Oscar nominations for
Nolte and Coburn.
 &HT;    Nolte couldn't care less about statuettes, he says, but hopes
that the buzz will encourage people to see the hard-to-promote
film.
 &HT;    ``I want audiences to experience it, to experience a catharsis _
not an intellectual catharsis, but an emotional one,'' he says.
``The depth of emotion is part of what's at the bottom of
`Affliction.'
 &HT;    ``Every man and woman has this rage underneath,'' the actor
continues, ``and the denial of that side of us causes us to become
tremendously violent toward one another ... That's how we kill in
the name of righteousness.
 &HT;    ``If you realize that you're the killer, you at least have to
think about what you're doing,'' he concludes. ``That's a
disturbing feeling to get from a movie, and it'll stay with you.''
 &HT;    Incredibly, Nolte will turn 58 in February. He's been a star
since the 1976 television miniseries ``Rich Man, Poor Man,'' and
has established himself as that rarity, a box-office draw who's
also one of his generation's most respected actors.
 &HT;    It didn't come easily, says Nolte, who's gone through several
divorces and fought to kick alcohol and drug abuse.
 &HT;    ``I was 35 when I came out to Hollywood,'' he recalls, ``and I
thought I was mature enough to handle it.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't,'' he says. ``You begin to think you can do no wrong.
Your ego is fed to such a degree that you lose your grounding. It's
very painful and confusing, and you turn to booze and drugs to
escape.
 &HT;    ``You become successful and think you have to repeat it,'' the
actor says. ``It's a frightening, frightening experience.''
 &HT;    Right now, Nolte considers himself a happy guy. He's dating
``NewsRadio's'' Vicki Lewis and has several films on tap, among
them Albert Brooks' ``Muse'' and an adaptation of the Sam Shepard
play ``Simpatico,'' which will co-star Sharon Stone, Jeff Bridges
and Albert Finney. Also in the works are ``Breakfast of
Champions,'' with Bruce Willis, and a number of projects Nolte
intends to produce through his own company, Kingsgate Films.
 &HT;    ``I'm enjoying myself now more than ever,'' Nolte says. ``I've
done the whole journey that can happen to an actor, experienced the
ebbs, spikes, money and adulation.
 &HT;    ``I've dabbled in all that, and I've let it go and returned to a
point I was at when I was doing theater,'' he says. ``I'm only
doing that which I really love, and I'm only going by the
screenplay.
 &HT;    ``I've realized a great director can't overcome a bad script,
that great actors can't overcome a bad script,'' the actor says.
``So I now go strictly by the script.
 &HT;    ``Hollywood still approaches me with big films,'' Nolte adds,
``but the scripts are sh-t. `Thin Red Line' was an exception.
Really, I'd rather make small films that say something, that mean
something, than big films with no heart, that are empty and say
nothing.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
