<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVIN-SPACEY-IN-HURLY     01-04 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVIN-SPACEY-IN-HURLYBURLY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN SPACEY: AN ACTOR'S ACTOR ON THE ACT OF ACTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kevin Spacey in a scene from
``Hurlyburly.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Some actors see Marlon Brando as their greatest inspiration. For
older actors, perhaps Laurence Olivier. For younger ones, maybe Al
Pacino.
 &HT;    But not Kevin Spacey, the Academy Award winner who is this
decade's leading candidate for ``actor's actor.'' His choice is ...
Bugs Bunny?
 &HT;    ``I'm a Saturday-morning-cartoon kid,'' the 39-year-old Spacey
says. ``I'm a Bugs Bunny kind of guy. He gets away with everything.
He tweaks authority. People know they can never really get mad at
him.''
 &HT;    That's different. But then, so is Spacey, who took home the 1995
Best Supporting Actor Oscar for ``The Usual Suspects.'' His flair
for the offbeat, and his remarkable range, are on display in two
offerings on neighborhood screens this holiday season:
``Hurlyburly,'' the hard-hitting adaptation of the David Rabe play,
and the animated crowd-pleaser ``A Bug's Life,'' in which he voices
Hopper, the villainous, marauding grasshopper.
 &HT;    The two parts couldn't be more different, which is exactly what
appeals to Spacey.
 &HT;    ``I'm not one of those actors who aspires to be a movie star in
the sense that I will always show up on screen playing myself,''
Spacey says by telephone from his Los Angeles home.
 &HT;    ``Hey,'' he adds with a laugh, ``I'm not knocking being a movie
star. It's not necessarily a bad job for some people.
 &HT;    ``To me it's not about the money and generating this level of
fame,'' he says. ``It's not about publicity. If it was, my career
would be a lot easier, because then I could just show up in every
movie and do the same thing with my eyes closed. That's exactly
what I don't ever want to do.
 &HT;    ``I never want to hear someone say, `What happened to Kevin
Spacey? Remember that guy? A few years ago he was really
interesting. We expected big things from him.'''
 &HT;    In ``Hurlyburly,'' Spacey plays a sleazy casting agent, complete
with platinum-blonde hair and a side line in cocaine. It's a film
he's long wanted to make, having understudied all the male roles
when Mike Nichols directed the play on Broadway.
 &HT;    ``It's a fantastic actor's piece and very funny,'' he says.
``It's one of those pieces where you sit down and say, `You're
doing this, no matter what.'''
 &HT;    In John Lasseter's ``A Bug's Life,'' his character is just as
creepy, but in another sense. Spacey enjoyed playing the
over-the-top Hopper, he says, because he'd always wanted to do an
animated project.
 &HT;    ``I met John Lasseter at the Student Academy Awards,'' he
recalls. ``We were both presenting, and we got into this great
conversation. I had admired his `Toy Story' (1996) so much.
Finally, John said, `Well, would you ever do an animated film?' I
said, `Why don't you ask me?'''
 &HT;    The director sent Spacey a test animation of Hopper to give him
an idea of the character. The voice was a familiar one.
 &HT;    ``He sent me Lee J. Cobb in `On the Waterfront' (1954), and
animated him doing the lines. It was hysterical,'' Spacey says.
``What cracked me up was that they had this little grasshopper
swearing.''
 &HT;    The actual work of doing voice characterizations is notoriously
dreary, and Spacey reports that recording Hopper took two years of
on-and-off work.
 &HT;    ``You just go into this room and play with your voice,'' he
says. ``They videotape you doing it and send that to the animators.
It helps them use your own gestures and facial tics to infuse the
characters.''
 &HT;    His fans will have a tough time discerning Spacey's features in
the rugged Hopper doll, however. Unlike the recent Dreamworks film
``Antz,'' the animators made no effort to have the characters look
like the actors voicing them.
 &HT;    Not that Spacey minds.
 &HT;    ``Oh, I have an action figure?'' the actor says. ``I must admit
I haven't seen a thing yet.
 &HT;    ``Hey, Christmas gifts for all my friends _ I'm done!''
 &HT;    Actually, Spacey is far from done, though he's a long way from
South Orange, N.J., where he started out. He did his first acting
at Los Angeles Valley College, then moved to New York, where he
studied at the prestigious Juilliard School and began to make a
name for himself in the theater. He won a Best Actor Tony Award for
Neil Simon's ``Lost in Yonkers'' (1991).
 &HT;    By that time he'd already made his small-screen debut in a 1988
multi-episode segment of the series ``Wiseguy'' and his film debut
in ``Heartburn'' (1986), but plum roles proved elusive.
 &HT;    ``I went through a number of tough years, but most people do,''
he says. ``That's what they call paying your dues. Mine are paid in
full.''
 &HT;    His filmography includes roles as a nasty agent in ``Swimming
With Sharks'' (1995), the psycho killer who beheads Gwyneth Paltrow
in ``Seven'' (1996), a gung-ho prosecutor in ``A Time to Kill''
(1996), a gay Southern gentleman in ``Midnight in the Garden of
Good and Evil'' (1997) and a smart cop with a gift for gab in ``The
Negotiator'' (1998).
 &HT;    But it's his ``Usual Suspects'' turn as a petty crook who just
might be the mysterious Keyzer Soze that got Spacey his turn in the
spotlight, not to mention his Oscar.
 &HT;    ``My mother told me later that she had three consecutive dreams
that I was going to win an Oscar,'' Spacey recalls.
 &HT;    It's a good thing she didn't tell him, because he was nervous
enough already. When his name was announced, he says, he almost
passed out.
 &HT;    ``I began to hyperventilate,'' Spacey says, laughing.
``Backstage, I began to realize, `You've just won an Oscar. You've
just spoken to 1 billion people. You don't even know what language
you were speaking in because you were so nervous!'''
 &HT;    Some Oscar winners rush to cash in, grabbing handfuls of the
higher-profile projects that come the winners' way. Spacey, on the
other hand, has been cautious in plotting his next moves.
 &HT;    In other words, don't expect to see him in ``Armageddon II'' or
``Zorro III.''
 &HT;    ``I don't want to do a big studio movie where the audience walks
out going, `What was he doing in this mess?''' Spacey says.
 &HT;    And while an Oscar may draw bigger paychecks, he reports, it
doesn't necessarily attract better scripts.
 &HT;    ``I do think the Oscar has an impact on what you're offered,
money-wise,'' he says. ``It's the nature of the beast, and I'm not
complaining about it. But the scripts are just as bad as before I
won. There's just more of them.''
 &HT;    Spacey will soon return to Broadway in Eugene O'Neill's ``The
Iceman Cometh.'' He will also co-star with Annette Bening in
``American Beauty,'' a film which he describes as being about ``a
married couple going through a difficult phase.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, he recently finished ``Ordinary Decent
Criminals,'' an Irish gangster saga co-starring Linda Fiorentino.
 &HT;    ``It's not shades of `The Godfather,''' Spacey says. ``The
character I play is actually more like Bugs Bunny _ no one can
catch up with him.''
 &HT;    Bugs Bunny as an Irish gangster?
 &HT;    Spacey laughs, but refuses to divulge anything more about the
film.
 &HT;    ``Look, I'm just plodding along, trying to keep my head above
water and do the things that I love to do,'' the actor says. ``My
goal is to be honest to myself, my friends and my family.
 &HT;    ``As far as I'm concerned, I've had a pretty great couple of
years. It just keeps getting better,'' Spacey says. ``I'm really
careful, because the law of averages are that I'm due to get hit by
a bus any day.
 &HT;    ``Just like Hopper, I could be squashed at any moment.''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
