<HEADER>
A6833 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGER-CLINT-BLACK-ST     01-04 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-CLINT-BLACK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC BLACK: CLINT BLACK ON MUSIC, LOVE AND LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Clint Black. 
 By JANET E. WILLIAMS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Who says you can't have it all?
 &HT;    Well, maybe you can't, but Clint Black just might be able to:
best-selling records, a beautiful actress wife, a couple of
shelves' worth of awards ... in only 10 years, since his 1989 debut
album, ``Killin' Time,'' the talented Texan has managed to realize
most of his dreams.
 &HT;    But to sit down in his Nashville office for a conversation with
Black is to realize one more thing, something more impressive than
all the best-selling records combined: Superstar or no, the
singer/songwriter is singularly unchanged by his success. He came
to stardom as a down-to-earth country boy, and to a remarkable
extent that's what he still is.
 &HT;    Black's latest album, ``Nothin' but the Taillights'' (1998),
represents both more of the same and a glance down new paths.
Several of its tracks are co-written with his longtime friend and
writing partner Hayden Nicholas, but a number of the others were
written with fresh collaborators, including such Nashville
mainstays as Marty Stuart, Matraca Berg, Skip Ewing, Steve Wariner
and Kostas.
 &HT;    ``A lot of these guys I'd been wanting to write with all along,
but life gets in the way,'' Black says. ``I'd get so busy that,
whenever I would finally block out two weeks to write, I would go
with the thing that I knew worked, which was Hayden and me. If we
spend a week, I know we can get three to five songs that we love.
 &HT;    ``So it wasn't until I got off the road that I finally started
calling up some of these feelers that I'd put out there years and
years ago,'' he recalls. ``Steve Wariner and I had talked about
writing together like four years ago. Kostas and I had been meaning
to do it for three years. He's in L.A. and I'm not, I'm in
Nashville and he's in Montana, and so we never caught up to each
other.''
 &HT;    Given Black's success, both in critics' eyes and in record
stores nationwide, it would be understandable if he resisted
tampering with his formula. But he insists that ``Nothin' but the
Taillights'' is a natural step in his artistic evolution.
 &HT;    ``I always want to get better,'' he says. ``I've applied myself
to the guitar more now. And I know I'm growing as a musician, as an
engineer ... I have my home studio, and when I'm composing I'm
playing the drums, the bass, the acoustic guitar, the electric
guitar and I sing the lead, and I'll either get my wife or one of
the guys in the band to come over, and we'll do all the background
parts. Just by doing that, I've become more intimate with the song.
I know I'm growing there, and that helps me when I'm writing,
because I see more opportunities on the guitar and melodies open
up.
 &HT;    ``My main intent has always been `Don't write the same song
twice,''' he adds. ``The music that people are making here today,
it influences me ... What's happening on the radio has inspired me
to take chances that I wouldn't have otherwise taken. It's really
all just about trying to write a new song.''
 &HT;    Like most country singers, Black can really dig into a ballad of
loneliness and depression. Offstage, however, he radiates relaxed
contentment.
 &HT;    ``I am generally happy,'' he says. ``One of the things that I
vowed was that I'm going to have a good time, enjoy everything I
can _ even when I make mistakes, I'm going to have fun. I try to
remember that. And I don't always, but for the most part, I'm
blessed, so I'd better look like I'm having a good time even if I'm
not.''
 &HT;    To complain about his own problems, given the degree of his
success, would be downright sinful, the singer adds.
 &HT;    ``With the problems that a lot of people have out there, how
would that look?'' he says. ``How would that make people feel who
are really going through hard times? Just because it's a crazy life
is no reason to be bellyaching. Because everybody has a crazy
life.''
 &HT;    Some of that craziness stems from his seven-year marriage to
actress Lisa Hartman Black, and the complexities of maintaining a
relationship with outposts in Nashville and in Hollywood. But the
singer insists that the two are ``the best of friends,'' and that
their relationship isn't really as unlikely as it seems.
 &HT;    ``If you look at who she is,'' he says, ``she's from Houston,
Texas, she's as country as it gets. She is just the sweetest person
that I know, the most grounded and the best communicator that I
know. That's really what it's all about.
 &HT;    ``We fell in love really quickly, got married very quickly, like
10 months,'' he recalls. ``But we're two people who were old enough
to understand what we were committing to. Never been married
before, either of us, and we really understood what we were
offering and what we were giving.
 &HT;    ``We understood each other well enough to know that whatever
would overcome one of us, the two of us would overcome together.''
 &HT;    With homes in Los Angeles, Houston and Nashville, the two are as
likely to be found relaxing in blue jeans as dressed up in formal
wear for a film premiere.
 &HT;    ``I love Hollywood, I love the movies and all that stuff,''
Black says, ``but she loves her time in Nashville. You see her
running around Nashville, she wears cowboy boots more than I do.
She's about as down-to-earth as it gets. You really couldn't find
anybody more country, in that sense of the word.
 &HT;    ``I can go on about it all day,'' the singer says, laughing.
``She's a solid person. She gives me the strength to relax. There's
no question we're closer today, we understand each other better
today.
 &HT;    ``There's a song Steve and I wrote called `You Know It All' that
goes, `When it comes to me, you know it all,''' Black adds.
 &HT;    ``That's how it works with us, because otherwise the
communication's gone.''
 c.1999 Janet E. Williams  
