A6834 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DORIS-ROBERTS-IN-EVER     01-04 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORIS-ROBERTS-IN-EVERYBODY-LOVES-RAYMOND-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DORIS ROBERTS: THEY ALL REMEMBER MAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Doris Roberts with Ray Romano in a scene
from ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television executives don't seem to be a particularly bright
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, how little they learned from ``The Golden
Girls'' and ``Murder She Wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1984 and 1996, those two shows spent a collective 18
seasons at the top of the Neilsen ratings, proving that veteran
female performers such as Bea Arthur, Betty White and Angela
Lansbury could attract millions of fans _ and, incidentally, earn
millions of dollars for their respective networks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the formulaic world of prime-time programming, where
successful concepts are usually cloned faster than Scottish sheep,
there's still little room for older actresses. Scan the cast lists
of this season's top 20 hits and you'll find only two women who
have celebrated their 50th birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   Both, as one might expect, appear on CBS, a network which has
long been the butt of industry jokes about its penchant for
creating shows that appeal to older viewers. One is ``Touched By An
Angel's'' Della Reese, and the other is ``Everybody Loves
Raymond's'' meddling matriarch, Doris Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of mature actresses was put in perspective for
Roberts recently by her show's producer, Phil Rosenthal, in a
speech at New York's Museum of Television and Radio after
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' received an award from the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the presentation,'' she recalls, ``Phil Rosenthal told
the audience that over 100 women went up for the part of Marie
Ramone. One hundred! And as soon as he said that, I realized that
most of them are my friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``That same week, I was a guest on David Letterman's show,'' the
actress adds, ``and he asked if I'd ever had a hard time. `Hard
time?' There was a 10-year career break when I couldn't get
arrested!
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember once when someone called my agent and said, `I'd
like to book Doris Roberts for a two-day shoot,''' she recalls.
``He said, `Well, I'm sorry, she's not available.' And they said,
`Why not?' My agent explained that I was working, and this person
responded, `Doris Roberts is working!?!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her frustration with Hollywood's unflagging
discrimination against older actors in general and older women in
particular, the 68-year-old Emmy winner has managed to find a home
in one of television's smartest comedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is the writing on `Everybody Loves Raymond' superb,''
Roberts says, ``the whole atmosphere is refreshing. I have to give
the credit to one man, Phil Rosenthal, who has set the tone for
everyone. It's fabulous. It's a joy to come to work in the morning
_ there are no sick personalities to deal with. We come in prepared
to work, and then we go home and have a life. That's very
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more unusual, Roberts says, is the professional support
that is the norm on the ``Raymond'' set.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one on this show is trying to grab the spotlight,'' she
says almost disbelievingly. ``No one's trying to score an
individual touchdown. It's the best ensemble I've ever worked with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do something that I've never heard of on any other
series,'' she adds. ``If the script is difficult for any one of us,
we all get together on Saturday with the dialogue coach to
rehearse. There's no overtime, no extra money _ nobody cares about
that. We simply do it until we get it right and everybody is
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   In shaping the role of Marie Barone, mother of series star
Raymond (Ray Romano), Roberts says that her biggest challenge is to
tread the fine line between funny and obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason `Everybody Loves Raymond' is successful,'' she
says, ``is that it's based on reality. It's not shtick, not forced
laughter. The humor comes from situations that are very
identifiable.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to Marie, it all comes through her innocence,''
she continues. ``She's not a woman who is educated. She was never
taught to do anything but be a mother and a housekeeper and a wife,
and that's what she's done. If she was savvy enough to realize how
intrusive and what a pain in the neck she is, that would make her
quite unpleasant. But everything I do on the set is done through
love.''
</P>
<P>
   That viewers are picking up what she is trying to do was brought
home to Roberts in October, when she won an award from Viewers for
Quality Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do when they present the award,'' she says, ``is
tell you the comments of the people who voted. For me, the most
important thing was that they said, `The sense of humanity that
comes from you is overwhelming.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I thought, `Perfect. They've gotten what I'm after.'''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the show, Roberts' main interest is the Children
Affected by AIDS Foundation, which she has chaired for the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raise money for organizations who feed, house and clothe
children affected by AIDS,'' she says. ``We're the only
organization that does that. It's hard work, but it's worth it
because we've already raised over $900,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, since the 1983 death from leukemia of her husband,
novelist William Goyen, Roberts has worked tirelessly to raise
funds for research into the disease. She's also become an advocate
for her husband's writings, which she considers world-caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in 1987, after her long-running series ``Remington
Steele'' had been canceled, Roberts launched a cross-country tour
to promote her husband's posthumously published collection of short
stories, ``Had I A Hundred Mouths.'' It was more important than her
own work, she told one interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an imitator, an interpretive artist,'' she said then.
``William was a creative one. My show has just been canceled, but
his art will continue. In 100 years no one will know what
`Remington Steele' was, but they'll still be reading his book.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconsidering that remark 15 years later, Roberts has to back
off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at the time I really believed that,'' she says.
``Every time I read my husband's work, I felt such awe and
reverence for him that Doris Roberts the actress was sort of
subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But recently I read from one of his stories at the opening of
the Getty Museum Theatre,'' she recalls. ``We had to add almost
five minutes to the piece because of the audience's laughter and
response. That's when I realized that, of course, I am much more
than just an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finally coming to terms with that,'' she says, laughing,
``which is great. Thank God it happened before I really get too
old!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
