r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-FLIGHT-KAN &LR;      01-04 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-FLIGHT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT ATTENDANTS COULD MAKE SKIES MUCH FRIENDLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A young adult who lives in my house when she's not matriculating
(or whatever) at an institution of higher education had flown to
the East Coast for part of the recent holiday and was due back on a
Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But on the day of her expected arrival she called to say that
the airline, plagued at the time by labor disputes (for which I
even-handedly blame everyone involved plus a few who had nothing to
do with it), had canceled her flight home. She hoped, she said, to
return the next day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She did. But her luggage did not arrive with her. Which is when
I remembered that I was a little out of sorts with the Association
of Flight Attendants, billed as the world's largest flight
attendants' union. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, the flight attendants had nothing to do with any lost
luggage in my family. At least not that I know of. But their union
announced recently that it wants the government to regulate
carry-on luggage. Each year, the union says, some 4,000 passengers
and crew members are injured by bags and objects that fall from
overhead bins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All that may be true. Airline rules vary on this subject. And
enforcement of those rules varies even more. Beyond that, many
airline passengers are nincompoops who place such things as loose
bowling balls in overhead bins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, OK. They flight attendants have a point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if passengers are to lose some of the carry-on privileges
they now enjoy, some compromise must be reached. There are, after
all, things that flight attendants do _ or perhaps must do, to
conform with government regulations _ that are simply beyond what
any passenger should put up with. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as we approach 2000, several decades after auto
makers were required to install seat belts, is there a sane
American above the age of three who does not know how to click a
belt shut or to reopen it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do flight attendants on each flight have to stand in the aisles
before takeoff and demonstrate something even numskulls who can't
set the timer on their VCRs can do blindfolded? And, worse than
that, must they also explain what they are doing over the fuzzy and
annoying public address system? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Something like rocket science may be required to get a passenger
jet airborne, but it isn't needed to operate a seat belt. If
something must be said, wouldn't this suffice: ``Folks, you know
the seat belt rules''? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hold on. I'm not done. If we'll have to limit our carry-on bags
beyond the current rules, let's also forbid flight attendants on
non-meal flights from rolling those stupid beverage carts down the
middle of the aisle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone on board wants a drink. Not everyone wants to be
interviewed by a flight attendant to determine what sort of drink
is desired. Why not just announce that anyone who wants a drink can
turn on the call button? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The amazing result of this sane change would be to let people do
something far more important than taking in liquid. Passengers
could actually get to the bathroom, if needed, or, having made that
trip, return to their seats unimpeded by those cursed beverage
carts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under my scheme, all the flight attendants would have to do is
jot down a few drink orders and go to the kitchen bay (or whatever
it's called) to fill them. Those carts could be melted into
plowshares. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm all for the safety of airline employees. Our carry-on
luggage should not endanger them. But neither should we have to
attend their Seat Belt School for Dummies or be blocked from
responding to nature's call. OK. I'm done. Please return your tray
table to its full upright and locked position and remain seated
until this column has come to a complete stop at the gate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6867 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-MEMORY-KAN &LR;      01-04 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-MEMORY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES BEING FORGETFUL HAS ITS REWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If 1999 turns out anything like 1998 (a clue is they've both
begun with January), there will be lots you'll want to forget a
year from now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Don't stimulate your vagus nerve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, like me until recently, you have no idea you even had a
vagus nerve and, thus, wouldn't know where to find it to protect it
from stimulation, it's time for a short anatomy lesson. (Do you
suppose that's what Bill Clinton said to Monica Lewinsky their
first time together? Let's not go there.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vagus nerve is sometimes called the 10th cranial nerve. It
runs from the brain through the face and thorax all the way down to
your abdomen. Or, looking at it from an abdomen-centric point of
view, it runs from the abdomen to your brain. Which makes it both
long and complex, which this column, despite my best efforts, is
also starting to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the vagus nerve, if you ask me, is that
scientists now think it has something to do with memory and that
(because it's pronounced VAY-gus) it brings to mind the word vague,
which often is a perfect description of my own memory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I can remember a lot of old and useless stuff. For instance,
I can tell you who made the final out of the 1954 Giants-Indians
World Series (the mortal Dale Mitchell on a pop-up to third baseman
Hank Thompson). I can tell you my family's phone number when I was
a child (just plain 893). And I remember that Jan. 3 is the
anniversary of the birth of Grace Anna Goodhue Coolidge, wife of
Silent Calvin Coolidge. (Why would a family name a kid Silent?
Weird.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as I have explained to some of you before, my short-term
memory, were it a car, would be recalled for more than one defect.
In fact, I usually need a grocery list just for bread. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently there is help for people like me. (Even if, in a
technical sense, there are no people like me.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the January issue of the journal ``Nature Neuroscience'' _
which you'll usually find on drug store magazine stands between
``Naughty North Dakotans Weekly'' and ``Vector Analysis Digest'' _
scientists report that memory can be improved by stimulating the
vagus nerve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They had been looking at people involved in a study that was
trying to see whether implanting a vagus-stimulating device (not
unlike a pacemaker for the heart) could suppress epileptic
seizures. Federal regulators, in fact, approved the device for just
that purpose in 1997. (You may know the device by a trade name, the
NeuroCybernetic Prosthesis System. But I'm guessing not.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The memory study showed that people whose vagus nerve was
stimulated improved their score on a memory test by 36 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There may be benefits to remembering 36 percent more stuff than
I do now, but I'm imagining the drawbacks. What good would it do,
for instance, if I could tell you (or anyone who cared) what I had
for lunch a week ago Thursday? Would this be either a small step
for man or a giant leap for mankind? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the light bulb just outside the back door of my house needs
changing again, will it be useful for me to be able to say, ``This
isn't right. I just changed this on Sept. 21''? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What worries me is that with a 36 percent improvement in my
memory, I'd simply follow my current pattern and remember more
useless stuff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, if someone could assure me that stimulating my vagus nerve
would cause me to remember to send a birthday card on time to a
friend in Arizona or to put out the dog and turn off the light at
night (and not, as I sometimes do, vice versa), fine. I'd take the
cure _ if only I could remember my vagus stimulation appointment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
