A6876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     01-04 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Jan. 10.)  
 (DW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLF SOLENT
</P>
<P>
   By John Cowper Powys. (Vintage International, $15.) This British
novel, recently restored to print, follows a sensitive young
Londoner who returns to an insulated village in his native Dorset
and becomes romantically entwined with two vastly different women.
```Wolf Solent' is a modern prose 'Hamlet,''' Percy Hutchison wrote
here in 1929. ``The novel is a momentous piece of work ... of
transcendent interest and great beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   GOD &AMP; THE AMERICAN WRITER
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Kazin. (Vintage, $14.) A renowned critic and
impassioned reader, in his final book before his death last year at
the age of 83, argues that classic American writers from Hawthorne
to Frost to Faulkner were driven by spiritual passion and a
yearning for something like faith, motivations that echo the
author's own emotional approach to his subject. ``He strolls from
writer to writer as if through the rooms of his own house,
occasionally shaking hands, by means of an anecdote, with someone
he has known personally,'' Paul Berman wrote in the Book Review in
1997, adding that when Kazin hits his target squarely, ``the effect
is spectacular and brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   FLYING LEAP: STORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Judy Budnitz. (Picador USA, $12.) These tales twist familiar
middle-class terrain into strange new shapes, creating a world
where a local baker creates babies from dough and high school
cheerleaders get so charged up at a pep rally that they set
themselves on fire. In 1998 our reviewer, J.D. Biersdorfer, called
this ``a consistently impressive debut.''
</P>
<P>
   FATHER, SOLDIER, SON: MEMOIR OF A PLATOON LEADER IN VIETNAM
</P>
<P>
   By Nathaniel Tripp. (Steerforth, $14.) In his unflinching
account of the horrors of war, an ex-infantry lieutenant also
describes his efforts to confront his guilt and achieve manhood
through love and family. ``The writing is cathartic, an expiation
by a middle-aged man haunted by everything that went wrong in war,
in youth, in country,'' David D. Gilmore wrote here in 1997. In
Patches of Fire: A Story of War and Redemption, by Albert French
(Anchor, $12.95), a black novelist tells how his Vietnam War
experiences became a creative wellspring he tapped into after years
of struggle in civilian life. ``It is a classic tale,
life-affirming and updated for the modern age,'' Terrence Maitland
said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   THE GUN SELLER
</P>
<P>
   By Hugh Laurie. (Washington Square, $14.) The hero of this
tongue-in-cheek techno-spy thriller is a dissolute ex-military man
who gets sucked into international intrigue involving money
launderers, terrorists, arms dealers and, of course, beautiful
babes. The result is ``a genuinely witty and sophisticated
entertainment,'' Christopher Buckley wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   UTOPIA PARKWAY: THE LIFE AND WORK OF JOSEPH CORNELL
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Solomon. (Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16.) The
author maintains that the secretive artist known for his boxes
filled with scraps, cutouts and trinkets was primarily an
iconographer and archivist with a basement full of ``source
material,'' including files on movie actresses and 19th-century
ballerinas. In 1997 our reviewer, James R. Mellow, called this a
``thoroughly detailed, highly informative biography.'' Mary
Cassatt: A Life, by Nancy Mowll Mathews (Yale University, $18),
shows how the American-born Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) blended her
love of painting with a desire for financial success. In 1994 in
these pages, Carol Armstrong cited some shortcomings in the
author's straight-ahead approach, but said the book was
``thoroughgoing in its resurrection of the contexts and
conditions'' of the artist's life.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TROUBLE SLEEPS
</P>
<P>
   By Clyde Edgerton. (Ballantine, $12.95.) Much of this novel is
told by a 6-year-old boy who describes what happens when a stranger
in a stolen Buick rolls into sleepy Listre, N.C., in 1950. The book
is ``as much the story of a man who brings random badness into a
good place as it is the story of a boy's search for his own
salvation,'' Mark Childress wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG BALLAD JAMBOREE
</P>
<P>
   Rural North Carolina circa 1950 is also the setting for The Big
Ballad Jamboree, by Donald Davidson (University Press of
Mississippi, $17), which follows the fortunes of a country singer
and his sweetheart, who is collecting folk songs for her a master's
degree thesis. In 1996 in these pages, George Garrett called this
''a lighthearted and (in a musical sense) light-fingered'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   THE REICHMANNS: FAMILY, FAITH, FORTUNE, AND THE EMPIRE OF
OLYMPIA &AMP; YORK
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Bianco. (Times Books/Random House, $20.) This
large-scale chronicle tracks the rise and fall of an Orthodox
Jewish family that at its peak in the 1980's amassed phenomenal
wealth through its international property holdings. In 1997 our
reviewer, Mordecai Richler, called the book ``a nicely balanced
study.''
</P>
<P>
   THE VOICE IMITATOR
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Bernhard. Translated by Kenneth J. Northcott.
(University of Chicago, $10.) The tiny stories in this 1978
collection showcase the Austrian writer's obsessions with
hypocrisy, corruption, murder and lunacy -- and especially his
contempt for his homeland. ``Bernhard's rage against society'' is
``a highly artistic undertaking,'' Peter Filkins wrote here in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
