</P>
<P>
   If the companies simply keep raising premiums, the government or
business or the consumer will eventually object. Cutting back on
services by limiting benefits or refusing to provide certain kinds
of care is proving equally unpalatable.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the optimists from Wall Street, who tend to be true
believers about the power of the free market, say that while the
HMOs have achieved tremendous savings, they have not demonstrated
that they can achieve efficiencies that come from knowing which
drugs or treatments work best.
</P>
<P>
   ``They figured out how to take costs out of the system, but they
need to take care to the next level,'' said Mary Anne Citrino, a
managing director at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. who
specializes in health care.
</P>
<P>
   With profits at many of these companies scarce, investors have
fled the stocks. The number of health-care service companies going
public dwindled last year to the lowest level in a decade,
according to Securities Data Co. in Newark, N.J., and the amount of
capital the new companies raised from the public this year is only
a fourth of the amount raised in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, plenty of people _ the executives running these
companies, for example, and the vast majority of physicians _
continue to make very good livings. UnitedHealth chief executive
William McGuire, for example, made about $10 million, including the
value of his stock options, in 1997, according to Graef Crystal, a
compensation expert. Even Oxford's debacle could prove lucrative to
its founder, Stephen Wiggins, who got a $9-million severance
package when he resigned as chairman early last year. That package
is currently under review by the company.
</P>
<P>
   But many of these businesses appear to be running out of
opportunities. After several profitable years during which premiums
were kept in check, HMOs seem to be no match for the inexorable
rise in medical costs. Oxford, whose rapid growth got the better of
it, has accumulated about $900 million in net losses over the last
12 months because it underestimated the cost of delivering care and
failed to charge enough for its popular plans. The company has
sharply raised its prices at the risk of losing some of its
members.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth, which is considered among the best managed in the
industry, misjudged how expensive it would be to provide care to
the elderly under the government's Medicare program. The company
reported a $565-million net loss in August and rapidly scaled back
its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even an old hand like Kaiser Permanente, a nonprofit pioneer, is
losing hundreds of millions of dollars because demand for care is
increasing and it can do little to check the rising cost of drugs
and medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the managed-care companies were able to
significantly raise their premiums for 1999, they may never be as
profitable as they were five years ago. And the public's
willingness to accept higher prices may be short-lived if people
begin to believe that there is not enough money to go around to
insure that care remains affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold reality began to dawn on people in the system: Saving
money for employers and making money comes at the expense of public
access to doctors, hospitals and services,'' said Dr. Arnold
Relman, a former editor-in-chief of the New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Other attempts to cut costs by being more efficient have also
foundered. When HMOs and other insurers forced doctors to accept
less money for their services, there was little room for the
companies that buy and manage doctors' practices to make money.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many of these companies discovered that their doctors simply
could not deliver care as cheaply as had been expected. FPA Medical
Management of Miami filed for bankruptcy protection in July because
it was losing money on many of its doctors' contracts, and
MedPartners Inc. of Birmingham, Ala., the largest of these
companies, announced last November that it would leave the business
because it could not figure out how to deliver care cheaply enough.
</P>
<P>
   And most HMOs are losing money on Medicare patients, according
to Kenneth Abramowitz, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein. When the
government decided to sharply limit Medicare payments to
managed-care plans beginning in 1999, dozens of HMOs either
abandoned or scaled back their services. Some 400,000 Medicare
patients are being dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the current system say it has never offered an
economic incentive to care for sick people. Because the insurers do
not spread the risk of caring for the sick over the entire
population, and are not paid more when they provide more care, the
companies can only thrive by covering those who are healthiest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a health-care system designed to encourage
health plans to treat the sick, and not compete purely on cost,
there will be no winners,'' said Diane Archer, executive director
of the Medicare Rights Center, a New York consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Half of all the elderly could not get health insurance in 1965,
before Medicare, because private insurers would not cover them or
made their policies unaffordable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the profit-making companies believe it is only a
matter of time before business will find a way to make sense of the
nation's health-care system. But companies will first need to
develop the kind of monitoring systems necessary to know exactly
how care is being delivered and what kind of care is, in fact, most
effective, according to Ms. Citrino. Now, she said, it is like
banking before the development of automatic teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   Others doubt whether the businesses will ever succeed,
especially if they attempt to provide care for everyone, including
those who cannot afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a Wall Street analyst,'' said Relman.``I would have
a no-buy recommendation on them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
