<P>
   Boutros-Ghali, who praised Hun Sen for his policy of ``national
reconciliation,'' said the mass killings by the Khmer Rouge were
the internal affair of a sovereign state, immune from the
``interference'' of outsiders. Cambodians must find their own route
to resolving their human rights issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody sees it this way. The United Nations is
investigating evidence and possible procedures to bring Khmer Rouge
killers to trial if either the Security Council or the Cambodians
agree to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   The process of democratization that the United Nations tried to
initiate in Cambodia at the start of the decade, under
Boutros-Ghali's leadership, has spawned a new cadre of local human
rights workers dedicated to principles of law and justice that
challenge the feudal ways of this politically primitive country.
</P>
<P>
   ``National reconciliation should not be at any cost,'' said Kao
Kim Hourn, head of the Cambodian Institute for Cooperation and
Peace, a local human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   In freeing the leaders of the Khmer Rouge, which has collapsed
over the past two years, Cambodia is bucking a worldwide trend
toward accountability. Tribunals are addressing mass killings in
Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia. Truth commissions have examined
the past in South Africa and Argentina. South Korea has convicted,
then pardoned, two former leaders. Japan has been offering grudging
apologies for its war crimes. Spain is trying to prosecute the
former Chilean dictator, Gen. Augusto Pinochet. Even President
Clinton, visiting Africa, expressed regret over America's
participation in the slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``While much of the rest of the world is moving, fitfully and
problematically, towards ending impunity for crimes of this
magnitude, Cambodia is taking a giant leap backwards,'' said Steve
Heder, a scholar of the Khmer Rouge who is examining records in
Phnom Penh for the War Crimes Research Office of the American
University Law School. ``This cannot be justified in terms of
stabilizing a fragile democracy. This is not an Argentina or a
Chile where a military apparatus left over from a criminal regime
can threaten stability. There is no solid basis on which to base an
assertion that the Cambodians do not want a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The imprisonment of the human rights workers at the time of the
embrace of the Communist leaders suggests that politics rather than
principle is involved _ that Hun Sen finds it in his own interest
to let one party walk free and not the other. It was Khieu Samphan
himself who crystallized what has emerged over recent years as the
Cambodian approach to accountability for political crimes. ``Let
bygones be bygones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights monitors have pointed out for years that no one has
been held to account, or even seriously investigated, for a series
of political killings, including a grenade attack on a political
rally early last year that killed 16 people and injured more than
100.
</P>
<P>
   After their visit to the beach with their families and aides,
the two Khmer Rouge leaders planned a trip to the ancient temples
at Angkor Wat and then a sentimental homecoming to their respective
villages. ``I need to relax a bit,'' Khieu Samphan said, brushing
past reporters who tried to interview him, ``so please forgive
me.'' He seemed a walking advertisement for a problem that human
rights advocates say is dragging Cambodia down: impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People accused of crimes against humanity and mass murder are
allowed to walk free within Cambodia's borders at the same time
that the government is arresting and imprisoning human rights
workers for carrying out their duties,'' said Sidney Jones, Asia
director of the Washington-based group Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights workers, representing Licadho, Cambodia's
leading rights group, were doing what the United Nations intended
and what the Hun Sen government has claimed to support: trying to
assure that public issues were dealt with in a legal way. They had
reportedly advised protesters on how to prepare a petition and
stage a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to trust the justice system, there needs to be some
consistency,'' a Western diplomat said. ``And the arrests of the
Licadho workers are a stark reminder that there isn't this
consistency, that there is a gross disparity between the small and
the big in society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
