<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX     01-04 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bouquets to Larry Flynt
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I go through culture heroes every few years. There was Tom
Paine. Then Miles Davis. Woody Guthrie. Davis again. Jean Shepherd.
Davis. Cesar Chavez. Miles. Right now it's Larry Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, look, is that any worse than Time magazine's tandem folks
of the year _ Bill Clinton and Ken Starr? True, they will go down
in history like two men drowning with their hands around each
other's throat. Together, they disfigured 1998 into one ugly anno.
But couldn't Time have been merciful? Newt would have been a nice
cover boy. He's at least one public nuisance the year rid us of.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is one of the year's other odd good deeds, bestirred from
the obscurity of periodical raunch to rain fire on the political
system with tales of license and lust.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is, of course, being universally deplored for offering a
cool $1 million each for provable stories of sexual misadventure by
big-time political figures. This, it is said, is the politics of
personal destruction, and indeed it is. But Flynt's mischief just
may be a necessary passage, a case of making the already bad so
much worse we finally get over it, like a fever breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt's money already has run off one pol _ the conservative
Republican House speaker in waiting, Bob Livingston, caught in
extramarital affairs (note plural) and abandoned by his
fair-weather friends of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his gynecological journal, Hustler, Flynt is being a bit
of a tease about the rest. He claims he is ready to out another 10
_ two Democrats, eight Republicans _ and says still more are being
investigated. This business could go on awhile, like a centipede
dropping the other shoe.
</P>
<P>
   I've always thought that hypocrisy, like cowardice, is one of
the underrated virtues. If we all told all the truth all the time,
this would be a world of constant abrasion, disillusion and combat.
A little hypocrisy, judiciously applied, is benign grease to the
wheels of life. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with our politics drawn off into a nasty contest in
moral high dudgeon, as the mighty righteous hurl denunciations from
a crenelated redoubt of assumed virtue, bursting a few balloons
might be useful.
</P>
<P>
   The real work of politics is the maintenance of the commonweal _
sustaining Social Security, shoring up the underclass, keeping the
military ready, perfecting the infrastructure. The agenda doesn't
include the moral harassment of the populace. We go to services for
moral instruction, not to political rallies. We elect
representatives, not saviors.
</P>
<P>
   If the politicians who pose as saints come to realize that as a
result they are sure to be searched for sin, then one of two things
will happen. Only real saints will run under that banner or, rather
more likely, the politics of sanctity will suffer a sudden drop in
numbers, easing the air pressure of the whole political biosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Flynt, it must be admitted, is an unlikely hero and an
unappealing one, but if he can panic the political system back to
its proper business, he will have done a welcome job of work.
</P>
<P>
   Come back, Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
