</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Dear Miss Manners
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Jan. 6, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For reasons other than religious, I bid the year-end holidays a
not-so-fond farewell. Frankly, I'm all partied out. I look and feel
bloated, am sleep-deprived and for the past few weeks have felt
improperly dressed.
</P>
<P>
   No manner of spiral-sliced ham, dark-meat turkey, cashew nuts or
frosty mints can soften the fundamental agony attendant to all
those parties: What to wear.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the invitations come with suggestions, but they
are undecipherable. I have spent this just-past holiday season
asking people at parties _ people usually dressed radically
different from me _ just what was meant by the host's suggestion
that we wear ``business casual'' or ``holiday apparel'' or just
plain ``casual.'' There's also ``sophisticated casual'' as well as
``cocktail dress'' and, likely, dozens more, the most intimidating
being ``black tie optional.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what I interpreted those vague recommendations to
mean, I saw few others at parties dressed the same way. Just last
night, I attended a post-holiday party for a retiring friend and
the invitation called for ``casual'' dress. This was fortified by
an afternoon phone call to my host who told me ``casual'' was what
``casual'' should be: ``Hell, just show up in blue jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   So I came in a nice sports shirt and slacks. When I got inside
the house, I was the only one without a jacket _ until I doubled
back to my car to retrieve the one I brought just in case. I saw no
one in blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago, some friends threw a '50s party and told us to
dress as we did in the '50s. Naturally, most women showed up
wearing stiff crinoline under their hoop skirts and the men arrived
in white T-shirts, black pegged pants, white socks and black penny
loafers. My wife was more reflective of her days in the '50s. She
stuffed a pillow under her skirt and came as the pregnant woman she
was in the '50s, and I showed up in an Army uniform, as that was my
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   The more intriguing dress suggestion this past holiday season
called for ``holiday apparel.'' Inasmuch as the party was for Jan.
1, I was not quite certain what holiday it was we were celebrating.
I pondered for a moment the traditional New Year's look of either a
diaper or a long robe with a scythe but concluded that wouldn't
play out well.
</P>
<P>
   And just how timely is it to come to a party on New Year's night
dressed as Santa's elf or the jolly old boy himself?
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, just about every male wore a coat and tie and
the females were dressed, as they say, ``to the gills'' _ an
expression I never have been able to figure out. (That, and ``the
man smokes like a fish.'')
</P>
<P>
   What I did over the protracted party period was to wear pretty
much the same thing, no matter what the invitation said, always
backing myself up with something left in the car; a tie, a jacket,
a dress shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, I am certain, there is a book that explains what the
myriad suggested apparel expressions mean, and if there isn't, then
someone ought to write it. There are millions of persons floating
around this world with invitations in their hands and laden with 16
different kinds of earrings or ties, trying to figure out which and
what might be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're on the party subject, when a lovely buffet table
is presented and you have the salad plate in one hand and the
dinner plate in the other, is it all right to stuff the silverware
in your jacket pocket? Or is the back pocket more acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 0956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
