<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-CITIES-Y2K05-COX     01-04 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-CITIES-Y2K05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad rap: Georgia's Y2K readiness defended
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They say it politely, but some city managers across
the state think Mike Hale got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, Georgia's chief of information technology, last month told
freshman state lawmakers that plenty of municipalities and county
governments are unprepared for the Y2K crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That's the moment _ Jan. 1, 2000 _ when our computer-dependent
society is predicted to lose its electricity, water, sewage
treatment plants, bank statements, defense satellites and
collective wits because computers won't be able to read the new
date ending in ``00.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of exterminating the millennium bug, as some call it,
must be done in the next 12 months. Hale says his remarks were
meant to alert the new class of lawmakers, who take their oaths
this week, to the reality that their districts might need
technological guidance in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as if to underscore Hale's worst fears, Georgia had
the dubious distinction of making The Wall Street Journal's list of
10 least-prepared states for Y2K. Relying on data from the National
Association of State Information Resource Executives, the Journal
said Georgia is only 10 percent ready for the millennium.
(Top-ranked Pennsylvania was listed as 99 percent ready.)
</P>
<P>
   If a snapshot were to be taken of Georgia's Y2K preparedness
right now, it would show vast differences among the 159 counties
and hundreds of cities across the state, admits Bruce Green,
director of the Office of Development, Research and Communications
at the state Department of Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   His staff surveyed more than 400 governments to see what they
are doing, and paying, to get ready.
</P>
<P>
   Some city managers, like LaGrange's Patrick Bowie, say they're
already ahead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we wanted to be unprepared for the millennium, local
businesses are holding our feet to the fire,'' said Bowie. ``We
have several Fortune 500 companies _ Kimberly Clark, Mobil Chemical
and Milliken _ that invited us to meetings at which they put us
under the bright lights and asked us to discuss our Y2K compliance
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Electricity for LaGrange, like that for other Georgia towns and
cities, comes from one of three sources, Bowie said: Georgia Power,
MEAG (the Municipal Electric Authority of Georgia) or one of the
spinoff companies formed when Oglethorpe Power diversified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think those entities are sitting back and waiting
unprepared for Y2K to come upon us, do you? I would say Mr. Hale
had it wrong,'' Bowie said.
</P>
<P>
   Millions for compliance
</P>
<P>
   But what about cities that have no Fortune 500 companies?
</P>
<P>
   A new survey of towns and counties by the Georgia Department of
Community Affairs shows that, with 12 months to go, 498
municipalities and counties are aware that time-sensitive computer
chips could pose problems, and most already have begun attacking
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In reply to the question, ``how much have you budgeted for Y2K
compliance?'' 39 counties said they had budgeted a combined total
of $7,344,100 and 75 cities had budgeted a total of $1,910,700.
Those numbers don't include municipalities, like Marietta or
Lawrenceville, that are part of the greater metro Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Milledgeville's water and sewer director, Barry Jarrett, said
his town's computers already have been refitted at a cost of $6,500
to make sure there are no interruptions in water and sewage
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide water to 40,000 people and have sewage connections
to about 60 percent of homes, and we're doing fine,'' Jarrett said.
``I don't agree with Mr. Hale's remark.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Kennesaw ``is Y2K-ready,'' said Assistant City Clerk
Bonnie Worley.
</P>
<P>
   Not all city planners think a computer breakdown, should one
occur, will mean services come to a screaming halt.
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick's water and sewer director, Bill Powell, said
telemetry (sophisticated measuring) is the only function that
requires computers in the city's water and sewage plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if those processors malfunctioned, nothing major
would happen. After all, we didn't have computers for the past 100
years but we still provided clean water,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrange's Bowie agrees that operating without computers for a
while would not significantly alter the flow of utilities in most
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what we do doesn't depend on the date-stamp function
of a computer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's preparations for Year 2000 have been underway since
1992, when planners first discussed millennium issues. By mid-1998,
the city had budgeted $6 million to replace its mainframe computer
with personal computers, and work was on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Around Atlanta, metro governments were making similar
preparations. Cobb County commissioners expect to spend $3 million
for a courthouse system and millions more to overhaul other county
computers. Cobb's School Board in February earmarked $506,000 for
Y2K changes.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County expects to have spent $14 million by the time
technicians have rewritten 3.3 million lines of code to compensate
for Y2K. Fulton County hired Hitachi Data Systems to complete its
conversion at an estimated price tag of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinnett County expects its mainframe upgrade will cost $9
million, and the state of Georgia, overall, has allocated $152
million to upgrade its systems, with plans to request more funds
from the General Assembly this month.
</P>
<P>
   MARTA, which last year hired the New Hampshire-based technology
consulting firm Renaissance Worldwide, has not yet published a
bottom line for its Y2K upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   But the transit system wants the Legislature to let it spread
the cost of fixing its computers over five years. Current law calls
for the cost to be paid all in one year, which MARTA said could
result in a hike in fares, now $1.50 a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Is it enough?
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate price tag for Y2K changes won't be fully known
until we're well into the Year 2000, said the DCA's Green.
</P>
<P>
   His staff's survey shows a vast range in the amount of money
that governments set aside for Y2K technology, from $500,000 in
Lowndes County to zero in Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current budget was done before we started Y2K planning,
but we'll use money from our contingency fund,'' a Harris official
reported.
</P>
<P>
   In between sit Twiggs ($1,500), Gilmer ($8,000), Butts
($15,000), Baker ($25,000), Telfair ($25,000), Emanuel ($30,000),
Paulding ($50,000 or less for hardware), Floyd ($50-100,000) and
Jeff Davis ($100,000) counties.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam County said it ``will address Y2K in the '99 budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said the survey results concern him. Clint Mueller with
the Association of County Commissions shares his worry.
</P>
<P>
   Both think county and city managers may not be acting quickly
enough, and that the money may not be spent well.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller looks at The Wall Street Journal rating and shakes his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held five workshops over the past year, we had a satellite
teleconference broadcast to 14 sites, we have Web sites that tell
who the state-approved Y2K consultants are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But one problem that city managers have encountered, and one
that even Mueller, Hale and Green may not have anticipated, is a
phenomenon that Toccoa city manager Bill Lewis calls the ``cover
your rear'' syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Even when new equipment is paid for and installed, suppliers and
vendors often are reluctant to guarantee that what they've sold a
city will operate snafu-free.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said his efforts to find out whether embedded chips will
break down on Jan. 1 have met with resounding silence from the
vendors who have sold a range of equipment to Toccoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent letters to all our suppliers, all right, but none of
them wants to make any assurances because they're covering their
own rears in case something does go wrong,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Toccoa has replaced its financial
software, utility billing software and desktop computers at a cost
of about $300,000, but not for Y2K reasons, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were old and it was time to upgrade, but the end result
was that we believe we are now prepared for Y2K,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, who has been dubbed the state's Y2K project director, said
he really became aware in June that ``remote cities and counties
have an increased risk of failed technology.''
</P>
<P>
   That awareness came during a series of six-hour workshops Hale
gave at five locales across Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was during question-and-answer sessions with
municipal managers that he sensed the lack of Y2K preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he says he saw the results of a survey sent by the
Georgia Public Service Commission to 1,200 electric co-ops, towns
and small utilities-providers asking about their Y2K status.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relatively low response rate told me there's a problem out
there,'' Hale said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to The Wall Street Journal figure (10 percent ready),
that's low. I'd say we are closer to 36 percent ready, but I still
believe there are towns out there that are far behind where they
need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The PSC has posted the results of its survey on the Internet at
www.psc.state.ga.us/pscinfo/year%202000/response%20lists.htm
</P>
<P>
   ARE THEY READY?
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Department of Community Affairs surveyed more than
400 city and county governments to determine how ready they are to
deal with the Y2K computer crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the questions and responses:
</P>
<P>
   _ Has anyone in your local government attended any
seminars/courses on this issue?
</P>
<P>
   YES: 43.1 percent
</P>
<P>
   NO: 56.9 percent
</P>
<P>
   _ Does your government have someone designated to coordinate all
Y2K efforts governmentwide?
</P>
<P>
   YES: 62 percent
</P>
<P>
   NO: 38 percent
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you have a budget for Y2K remediation?
</P>
<P>
   YES: 27.2 percent
</P>
<P>
   NO: 72.8 percent
</P>
<P>
   _ Do you have a contingency plan in place for those systems that
may not have been fixed?
</P>
<P>
   YES: 24 percent
</P>
<P>
   NO: 76 percent
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
