<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Set New Year's resolutions that are easy to keep
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Every year it's the same sad story. Many
Americans with the best of intentions make lofty New Year's
resolutions they can't keep.
</P>
<P>
   They tell themselves they're going to run up the stairs every
day at, say, the One American Center until they drop 20 or 30
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later the only thing they've run up is their tab at
the local saloon. Then they get all disappointed with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   You won't catch this kid falling into that stupid trap. This is
because I know that the key to successful New Year's resolutions is
to make resolutions that are easy to keep. Don't ask too much of
yourself. Don't be too demanding. Promise to spend more time
sitting on your butt. Resolve to do stuff you were going to do
anyway. Resolve to sleep in and go to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to New Year's resolutions, you shouldn't raise the
bar. Instead, you should go to one. Instead of setting goals you
can't reach, make a New Year's resolution like this one:
</P>
<P>
   I promise that if I find myself in the One American Center,
forget the stairs. I'm taking the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another good New Year's resolution: I promise to drink
plenty of cold beer. That shouldn't be too darned difficult.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Here's one of my personal New Year's goals for 1999.
I promise not to take any French cooking classes at Central Market.
</P>
<P>
   I also promise that during the New Year I will not rearrange the
furniture in my living room according to the principles of feng
shui.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, I promise to try to stay out of bars that have the
word ``salad'' as part of their names.
</P>
<P>
   See how easy this is? Even someone with absolutely no willpower
can maintain this regimen.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, here are my other New Year's resolutions for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   I promise that when I order a baked potato, I will cover it with
grated cheese, butter, chives, sour cream and bacon bits.
</P>
<P>
   I promise not to stand up in a karaoke joint and do a solo
performance of ``The Wind Beneath My Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of jogging, I promise to mosey.
</P>
<P>
   I promise not to act presidential by messing around with any
22-year-old interns. I promise not to put myself in a position
where I have to tell a grand jury, ``It depends on what the
definition of `old fool' is.''
</P>
<P>
   I promise to go to Dirty's for a cheeseburger.
</P>
<P>
   I promise to continue my long-standing policy of not getting a
stud run through my tongue.
</P>
<P>
   I promise I will not spend a lot of time trying to find a Furby.
</P>
<P>
   I promise that if some of these rubber-britches-wearing,
pedal-pumping, knock-kneed bicyclists hog the road in front of my
car, I will moon them. (OK, so I lied about that one. But I'd like
to.)
</P>
<P>
   I promise that I will not take dulcimer lessons or join a cult.
</P>
<P>
   I promise that I will attend as many University of Texas
football games as possible and hang out at a lot of tailgate
parties.
</P>
<P>
   I promise that if I hear any bad jokes, I will repeat them.
</P>
<P>
   I promise not to join any club where you can't get in without a
tie and a sport coat. I also promise that I will not to go in for a
tuxedo fitting.
</P>
<P>
   I promise that I will not bore people at parties by talking to
them about my aura.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and
Fridays in the Austin American-Statesman. He can be reached at
445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
