<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: An organizer faces the year
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ One of the most intimidating moments of a
year often occurs before it begins. It is when you peel back the
cellophane from a new calendar and look at the days ahead _
unsullied, unblemished, without cross-outs caused by indecision or
arrows and underlines induced by panic.
</P>
<P>
   Tabula rasa, as the philosophers say, a clean slate. Nothing but
possibilities. All blocked off and numbered. Anything that happens
after this point is either a mistake or a complication. It is
downhill from here.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by my organizer, I lead a messy life. It is littered
with phone numbers written in haste, punctuated with triple
underlineage, little arrows and cross-outs. All ineptly corralled
with index tabs. I think back wistfully to the days when my life
used to fit on a wall calendar backed-up by only an address book, a
refrigerator magnet from a pizzeria and disposable things-to-do
lists that lasted little longer than a snooze-alarm dream.
</P>
<P>
   No more. I am cross-indexed. I am marching confidently into the
twilight moments of the 20th century with year-at-a-glance charts,
month-at-a-glance views, and week-at-a-glance blocks. I even have a
little ruler to tell me what week I'm in. A pocket for floppy
disks, a time-zone map and a Fahrenheit-to-Celsius converter in
case you have the urge to tell a Canadian how unseasonably warm
it's been down here.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a to-do list with boxes you can check off to feel
the thrill of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   I have, in fact, already checked the first box.
</P>
<P>
   I find that to-do lists work better with a running start. That's
why I start with something I've already done, then check off the
box as soon as I write down the task. This way the whole to-do list
process is far less daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Is this cheating? Oh, maybe to the purist. But it's not the sort
of thing one would dare take too far. If you overdo it, your to-do
list would turn into a have-done list. Then you'd need to go to the
office-supply store and get specially printed have-done lists with
their own little tab. And to remember to do this errand, you would
need to write yet another chore on the to-do list. This would, of
course, defeat the entire purpose of cheating and make more work.
</P>
<P>
   My organizer also has another tab marked ``ideas.'' Its pages
are blank. I hold out hope.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Get rid of intimidating ``ideas'' tab.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Find organizer sheets with little boxes and the heading,
``Things Successfully Put Off for More Than a Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiving a good, thick, full-service organizer as a Christmas
gift is a wonderful thing, but it does give a mixed message. Did I
get this under the tree because I seem like the kind of person who
could, perhaps, stand more organization in my life? Do I appear out
of control? Did I miss one birthday too many?
</P>
<P>
   To do: Find out if I've been insulted.
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue that this system, however elaborate and
perfect, is out of date. That the true scheduling compulsive would
be computerized and data-linked. Not so. A silicon-and-wire system
can't give you the perspective that dead-tree and ink can.
</P>
<P>
   A computer screen comes up on the right day with no thickness of
pages past and no future pages unflipped. You have accuracy but not
perspective. No stray phone numbers. No underlines. No drink
strains from far away places.
</P>
<P>
   (To do: Take organizer out for a good time.)
</P>
<P>
   Electronics also deprive one of the flip side of clipping clean,
new pages in place _ the pleasures of tossing the old. Maybe
setting those pages on fire for a bad year. Lingering over them in
a good year.
</P>
<P>
   Perspective. It's something computerized scheduled don't give.
In the old pages, you can find the flight numbers of airplanes met.
Tally up the time spent in an orthodontist's office. Shake your
head at pages dark with appointments, meetings and deadlines.
Wonder if you appreciated those clean expanses go on unaccountably
for pages. Cringe at the still-empty boxes on year-old to-do lists.
</P>
<P>
   (To do: Throw out old to-do lists without reading them.)
</P>
<P>
   This is the change of year you can touch. A ritual for sorting
the past and steeling yourself for the future. No delete key can do
it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
