</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For a few bottles of vodka, maybe I'd complain a little less
about being a teacher
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ You think times aren't tough in Russia? Money
is so tight
</P>
<P>
   in the Altai region of southern Siberia that schoolteachers
haven't been paid since February of last year. Local authorities
tried to cut a deal with the unpaid educators - toilet paper and
coffins in lieu of salaries. No takers.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers nixed the idea and it's not too tough to figure out
why. Folks who haven't eaten in a while don't need toilet paper,
and it takes a sick mind to offer hungry people coffins instead of
cabbages.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, an alternative plan was called for and the government
came up with
</P>
<P>
   one: vodka! Fifteen bottles per teacher to kind of tide them
over until the country can scrape up enough rubles to pay its
educators.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, what are the Altai teachers going to do with 15
bottles of vodka apiece? Probably trade most of it for food and
clothing but it wouldn't surprise me if some kept a bottle or two
around the dacha for emergencies, like
</P>
<P>
   snake bite or revolution. I know I would.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolteaching being what it is, I'm thinking a little vodka in
the coffee thermos couldn't hurt. It might even liven up
conversation in the teacher's lounge where we mostly go to gripe.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, like enlisted men, are born bellyachers. It's the
American way. I'm sure that if I didn't grouse about kids and the
thousands of essays I grade each year, I probably would be
considered some kind of deviant and lose my job.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think it's easy; there's an art to being a successful
whiner. Most of it's in the timing. Example: Popular complaint No.
1. ``The cooks in this cafeteria were hired when the Allies closed
down Auschwitz. We made them an offer they couldn't resist.''
Hilarious in the teachers' lounge but falls flat in the food line.
So does, ``In my educated opinion, if vegetables were supposed to
have come all mixed up in a big can, God would have grown them that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Popular complaint No. 2. Do not speak the following words to the
custodian in
</P>
<P>
   January when the boiler has just self-destructed but the blowers
are still running: ``Hey, Benny! The air conditioning's working
great today.'' He will not think this is funny and may try to get
even by tattling to the Director of Support Services that you've
been performing illegal operations on your thermostat with a pair
of scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Little cages and missing control knobs characterize the
thermostats in our building. It's to keep the kids from messing
with them, we're told, but I know better. It's actually a ploy to
keep the teachers in line and remind them of their position in the
pecking order: 1) custodian 2) cooks 3) secretaries 4) bus drivers
5) cheerleading advisor 6)superintendent 7)principal 8) U.P.S.
delivery person 9) teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm not a chronic complainer (although I'm working on it)
but it would be my preference to teach without icicles hanging from
my nose and free of the constant worry that one leg of my long
underwear is suddenly going to drop into
</P>
<P>
   sight.
</P>
<P>
   Each winter the custodian and I play this game of cat and mouse.
I've tried everything from opening the windows and hoping for a
blast of Canadian air
</P>
<P>
   that would cause the system to overcompensate, to the science
teacher's suggestion that I drape a wet paper towel over the
thermostat. Either way, I always get caught. Finally, one of my
students showed me how to stick scissors in the little hole and
turn the control wheel, reminding me of something I learned at
</P>
<P>
   university in Schoolteaching 101: Got a problem? Ask a kid.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what it would be like to teach in Russia where
there are not enough rubles to go around. Somehow I can't picture
doing what I do for toilet paper. My hat is off to those teachers
who keep working for a promise and a few bottles of vodka.
</P>
<P>
   Za vashe zdorovye! (To health!)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to
320 West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
