<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE05-COX     01-04 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprise! Everything you read isn't true
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The World Wide Web has become a valuable source of
information for research, whether you're using it for a project at
work or homework.
</P>
<P>
   But if you plan to use the Web as a research aid, you have to
remember there's nothing particularly magic about information from
the Web. Anyone who wishes can have a Web page and, within really
broad limits of decency and the law, there are no rules or
standards about what is placed on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the really far-out pages that offer proof UFOs exist,
or that the Holocaust did not happen, or that the Earth is flat,
aren't the problem. Common sense helps filter out the obvious
misinformation. It is the well-intentioned and articulate that pose
the most problems. These folks are doing their best to spread the
word, but _ many times _ the word is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing all that won't change your grade from a D to an A, and
it is unlikely your boss will excuse a costly error based on it.
But armed with the knowledge the Web doesn't have any lock on the
truth, there are techniques that let you enjoy the value of the
Web's vast storehouse of information while protecting yourself from
misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   The safest way to approach the Web is to navigate instead of
surf. If you're familiar with how navigating by the stars works,
you know that ships once found their true position by taking
sightings on the stars. Using just one star wasn't enough to
pinpoint your location. It would just give you a general idea of
where you are. You needed three or more star positions to get a
good idea of your location.
</P>
<P>
   When you navigate the Net, the same techniques can help filter
out some of the misinformation. Use three or more sources and
compare the information you find. The likelihood of getting
accurate information increases when you find agreement on the basic
facts from several different sources.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough. Anyone who has ever worked at a newspaper
is aware how misinformation from an old story can be added to a new
story for background. Over the years, the misinformation can be
repeated dozens of times. And with that repetition comes added (and
undeserved) credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happens with information on the Web. The virtues
of the computer at duplicating information by simply copying and
pasting make it more likely that a nifty (true or not) bit of
information will find its way to another Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to take some added star sightings that will help you
ferret out this kind of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Start by evaluating the credibility of the page. If, for
instance, you are reading about cancer treatment on a page
sponsored by the federal government or the American Cancer Society,
then the odds of it being credible go way up. But, just as in real
life, you should be careful when you don't know anything about the
person or group furnishing the information.
</P>
<P>
   There's still an extra step that you can take. Use a recognized
source book in the field that you are researching and see how the
information there jibes with what you are reading on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And many books that have a recent publication date cite Web
resources, giving these sites extra points on the credibility
scale.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is a terrific source of information. Don't be afraid to
use it. Instead, simply avoid the temptation to believe that, just
because you read it on the Internet, it is true.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
