<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE-PAGERS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interactive pagers intelligently handle e-mail, faxing as well
as customary duties
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Your daughter is airborne, flying to Los Angeles,
where her uncle is to pick her up at LAX. You get an urgent call.
The uncle is detained, but a neighbor, a young lady dressed in red,
will pick her up instead. No problem. You get on the computer,
dispatch an e-mail to the daughter, and she receives it on her
interactive pager as she rides the down escalator to baggage claim.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra, your spouse, is making her final business rounds in
Seattle, preparing to fly back to Atlanta on Friday afternoon.
Suddenly, in a stroke of genius, you suggest she pick up some
smoked salmon, a family favorite, to brighten up the weekend. No
problem. You e-mail her on her interactive pager, she sees the
message and instructs the cabby to take the side trip en route to
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Or, your wife is having her second child, and at the hospital
you decide to do it right this time. You use your interactive pager
to e-mail messages to all four grandparents simultaneously, and a
fax to Grandpa Joe, who rarely looks at his e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of the latest in hand-held computing, the
interactive pager. Except for its beep, it has little in common
with its cousin, the ordinary pager. The BellSouth Interactive
Pager, a companion of mine for several weeks, is different because
it sends and receives information. Like an ordinary computer, it
has directories and an electronic address book.
</P>
<P>
   It sends e-mail and faxes more simply than the personal
computer, communicating with other interactive pagers in seconds
across thousands of miles. The communication with computers via the
Internet occurs in four or five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, you cannot reach it automatically by phone as you do
regular pagers. But a toll-free phone call to an operator, on duty
24 hours a day, allows you to send an alert or a dictated text
message.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the interactive pager system is the handy,
sophisticated pager, which is actually a radio that communicates
with a wireless network that is similar to a cell phone network _
but entirely separate.
</P>
<P>
   The low-powered radio contains circuitry that allows you to
write messages and hold them until you want to send them. And it
instructs the network, by way of the nearest communications tower,
to take the message and deliver it directly to another pager, or to
a computer or a fax machine. The network is able to locate the
target, and hold the message for transmission later if the computer
or fax or pager happens to be turned off, or out of range.
</P>
<P>
   This sophisticated technology was first brought together in 1993
to serve mostly businesses, which mostly needed a high level of
communication between offices and field forces. It still does that,
but now since BellSouth bought the business, it is being
transformed into a consumer service as well.
</P>
<P>
   Invented by a company called Ram Mobile Data, which was
purchased in 1998 by BellSouth, the wireless network was used
mostly to serve major corporations with customized programs.
</P>
<P>
   But with the purchase of the company, William Lenahan, president
of BellSouth Wireless Data, said he foresees hundreds of thousands
of individual customers, many eager to join what Chuck Napier of
Convergence Corp. calls ``the mobile digirati.''
</P>
<P>
   As you use the little machine, it does achieve the feel of a
companion. Sitting in a meeting, for instance, you could hear a
speaker talking about the possibility of war between two former
Soviet republics. You could flash a message back to the office to
check company investments there, without leaving the table.
</P>
<P>
   You could, as I did, run across a gift item at Lenox Square
mall, just right for a friend. You could flash a query about the
person's size, and get the answer when she returns from lunch.
</P>
<P>
   You could assign or loan a pager to a teen, and keep track of
his needs, problems or comings and goings during the day, directly
from your office computer.
</P>
<P>
   What is startling is the reach of the system.
</P>
<P>
   And it really works. Recently I loaned my pager to my nephew,
Andre Wallace, who was leaving by plane for a business trip to the
West Coast. His plan was to land in Los Angeles and drive up the
coast to the Bay Area, making several stops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   When he landed at LAX, he flashed me the arrival message as he
took the escalator down to the baggage center. His progress reports
included one from the car as he motored to his hotel, and notices
from various towns and villages as he made his way up through the
central valley. We were in constant touch.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager may sound reminiscent of the ordinary
satellite-based pagers, but it is quite different. Commands are not
broadcast by satellite and picked up by the pager wherever it may
happen to be. Instead, interactive pagers receive messages
addressed only to them.
</P>
<P>
   The little devices are intuitive. If you put a period after a
word, it automatically capitalizes the next letter to begin another
sentence. A single letter ``i'' automatically capitalizes.
</P>
<P>
   The network, sure to serve additional devices, will become the
means to connect hand-held computers, BellSouth announced in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive pager, which costs about $250, connects to the
service for about $25 a month, comparable to cellular phone
service. Some 25,000 ``anytime'' characters can be transmitted
without additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service probably will appeal mostly to business
professionals, and users in field service such as sales,'' said
Janet Boudris, senior vice president for marketing at BellSouth
Wireless Data, based in Woodbridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have found is that many subscribers get them for
business use, but in time they begin to adapt them to personal use,
for instance to stay in touch with children and spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   This all sounds like the pattern when cellular phones were
introduced to the general population in the early 1980s, when the
initial customers were businesses but then spread into the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unanticipated developments, Boudris said, is deaf
people have been attracted to the devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many feel this is the first handy communications device `just
for the deaf,' so practical because it can alert the user by
vibrations,'' she said. ``Then they can communicate in writing.''
</P>
<P>
   One warning, however. The network coverage of the interactive
pager is in its early stages in terms of individual consumer use. I
found a totally dead spot in Stone Mountain, though the signal was
fine just a mile or two away in south DeKalb County and the same
distance westward in East Lake.
</P>
<P>
   As you should with wireless telephones, it would be advisable to
check signal strength in areas where you work or spend the most
time to verify service is satisfactory _ before you sign a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, even if you compose and ``send'' a message
while you are in a dead spot, the message will store and transmit
the moment you enter a service zone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
