<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give yourself a break: Get brakes checked
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brake pedal vibration, or ``pulsation,'' is typically
caused by warped brake rotors or out-of-round (oval-shaped) brake
drums.
</P>
<P>
   The constant heating and cooling of the brake rotor as the
brakes are applied and released eventually causes the flat rotor to
warp (like leaving a vinyl record in the sun). When you step on the
brake pedal, the pads clamp against the high spot on the rotor. As
the low spot rotates around, the pads need to move again to clamp
it.
</P>
<P>
   The pads must move in and out to keep contact with the distorted
rotor. This causes the uneven braking action to be felt through
your foot.
</P>
<P>
   On the rear brakes, the once-round drum becomes oval-shaped, and
the same kind of thing happens. The brake shoes first contact the
high spot, then need to move out to touch the low spot. Again, the
in-and-out action of the shoes is felt at the pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Another contributor to warped rotors and drums is uneven
tightening of the wheel lug nuts. This is sometimes done when the
tires are rotated and the wheels are tightened with an air-driven
impact gun. When you have your tires rotated, insist the wheels be
torqued to specification.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the braking is done with the front brakes, so warped
rotors are much more common than out-of-round drums. If you are
experiencing brake pulsation, have the ``rotor runout'' checked.
This needs to be done by a mechanic with a special gauge that can
measure how much warpage the rotors have. The only thing that will
fix a pulsating pedal caused by rotor warp is to have the rotors
machined flat (turned) or replaced with new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Even though brake drums rarely distort, it can be caused by
driving with the emergency brake left on. The extreme heat caused
by the constant friction of the applied brake can get the drum hot
enough to warp. As with the rotors, the drums will have to be
machined round again or replaced if they've gotten too hot.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget about brake fluid. The reason cars use fluid to
apply the brakes is fluid cannot be compressed. In essence, it
works like a solid rod between your foot and the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   However, air can be compressed. When air gets into the hydraulic
system, it must first be squished before the fluid has a chance to
apply the pistons down at the brakes. Air gets into the hydraulic
system when the fluid in the master cylinder is too low.
</P>
<P>
   Heat also can affect the air in the system. Brake fluid is
designed to boil at very high temperatures (usually between 300 and
400 degrees Fahrenheit). If you've had to apply the brakes for a
long period of time (like descending a steep grade), the brakes can
actually get hot enough to boil the fluid, which will create little
air bubbles. In either case, the brake pedal may feel mushy because
you are having to squish air. You may even have to ``stand on the
brakes'' to bring the car to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   If you are experiencing a mushy brake pedal or you're having to
pump the brakes, the culprit is probably air in the system.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the only way to get the air out is to have the
brakes bled at the wheels. Fluid is pushed through the hydraulic
system and allowed to drain out ``bleeder screws'' until all of the
air has been removed. However, if the brake pedal is going to the
floor and no amount of pumping will stop the car, there may be an
internal fluid leak or external leak. Needless to say, this is a
dangerous situation in need of immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Chevrolet Metro LSi front-drive, two-door
hatchback
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $13,055 (base: $9,790)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 1.3-liter four-cylinder engine, optional three-speed
automatic transmission ($595)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, height-adjustable front
shoulder belts, reinforced roof rails, door pillars and beams,
daytime running lights, optional power anti-lock brakes with front
discs and rear drums ($565)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: package with air conditioner,
carpeted floor mats, $1,375; package with dual mirrors, cargo
cover, $125; AM/FM stereo with CD player and four speakers, $100;
rear wiper/washer, $125
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 30 mpg regular unleaded city; 34 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
