<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hasbro's `Stratego' reborn on CD
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hasbro Interactive has been bringing one age-old board
game after another to computer CD. Its latest offering is
``Stratego,'' a war strategy game. With computer technology, Hasbro
has expanded ``Stratego'' to three levels of difficulty. There also
are five variations of the game, and five board designs to choose
from. Available only for Windows 95 PCs, ``Stratego'' retails for
$29.95.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe but, yes, it's the beginning of a new tax
year. And to celebrate the coming tax season, Intuit has released
MacInTax, the Mac version of its popular tax preparation software.
This version includes several new features that simplify both
preparing taxes and navigating tax forms. For example, MacInTax
lets you import annual financial data from Quicken, if you have the
program. You can also jump among forms and topics with the click of
a mouse from a side-screen directory. MacInTax retails for about
$35.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   There are few things funnier than a bad advertisement. Now you
can look at a whole slew of them at a site called The Gallery of
the Absurd. It features bad advertising from throughout the
industry's history. You'll find, for example, a print ad showing a
laughing family that proclaims in big type ``They're happy because
they eat lard.'' Or how about this one _ Hometown, Ill., resident
Pay Mayo bragging her toilet is the best-smelling one in the
neighborhood. She invites skeptics to come and sniff for
themselves. Find The Gallery of the Absurd at
http://www.absurdgallery.com.
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   It must be the first of the year. The tech magazines are
offering best-of-the-year lists. Yahoo! Internet Life is first out
of the gate. In its January issue, it features a ``Top of the Net''
list for last year. The list includes selections of best Web site,
best Web star, best wacky site and best Net event.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's next generation of laptop computers will include the
ability to play DVD movies. Read about this computer, to be called
the PowerBook G3/300, in the January issue of MacWorld. This
computer will let you watch a movie while traveling cross-country
via airplane, for example. No more settling for the airline's
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, your laptop may not last through the whole flight,
given the state of portable batteries. But Apple Computer is
reportedly working on some improvements here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
