<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trip planner slow at handling its job
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a new player with a very large name in the
trip planning software business.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Trip Planner DeLuxe does no dishonor to its
august name, but on the other hand the players already established
in the field, especially Rand McNally, needn't feel overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   Trip Planner Deluxe is a fairly routine trip planner, rather
clumsy and unintuitive in use.
</P>
<P>
   The maps, as one would hope, are very nice. There is a lot of
detail, and most cities are represented with maps of at least the
major streets; larger cities such as Atlanta have street maps as
detailed as any available for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Trip planning is done either manually, which is not as easy as
most other programs, or through the Trip Wizard, which is easy
enough but still a little cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when you select the Wizard, you get a pointless
introductory screen; next comes a ``Set Origin and Destination''
screen at which you actually select neither. Instead, you click on
either origin or destination, which takes you to yet another screen
in which you type the name of the city or, if you really aren't
sure where you wish to start, scroll down an understandably
interminable list of places to make a choice. Then you go back to
the previous screen and do the same thing for destination.
</P>
<P>
   Five screens, in other words, where one could have done the job.
</P>
<P>
   There is a guidebook where you can choose to get information on
a wide variety of attractions or matters of interest, from
high-rated hostelries and restaurants to historic locations, and
specify how far they can be from a certain point. But you have to
select the point. I can find no way to select an entire route for
this feature. Instead, I had to calculate the route and then click
at random spots along the way to get that kind of information.
</P>
<P>
   Selecting any of the locations produced by the guidebook allows
the user to both locate them on the map and store the information
regarding them to a separate notebook, which can be printed out.
</P>
<P>
   There is a selection of walking tours, which is quite small and
limited to Eastern locations. Short driving tours are much more
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating a trip is the slowest process I've seen in a program
of this type, but it's not slow enough to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   There's a tips and advice section on a number of travel
subjects, useful mainly if you have a computer with you when you
need the advice.
</P>
<P>
   This is a decent travel program, but not even the blank travel
notebook National Geographic includes raises it to the level of
Rand McNally's TripMaker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
