<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft launching new Explorer
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ironically, competition for the best Mac Web browser
has not slackened a bit between Microsoft and Netscape during the
long weeks of the government's antitrust suit against the world's
dominant software provider.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is readying the next version of its Internet Explorer
browser, which will probably be previewed at the MacWorld
convention in San Francisco this week.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of Internet Explorer comes only weeks after
Netscape released the latest version of the Mac version of its
Communicator suite of browser software.
</P>
<P>
   That version has won high praise from reviewers, who gave
Communicator the edge, however fleeting, in its competition with
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Now Communicator may lose that edge if leaks and initial online
chatter about Internet Explorer prove true. This version, dubbed
4.5, promises easier use.
</P>
<P>
   In Internet Explorer 4.5, Microsoft has taken an approach that
differs from its normal software strategy. It has decided to focus
on tweaking Internet Explorer rather than adding tons of new
features.
</P>
<P>
   What a novel idea for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company set out to reduce the number of mouse
clicks and keystrokes users had to make to do common tasks. One way
is through a new feature called autofill, which will be familiar to
users of Microsoft's Word and Excel products.
</P>
<P>
   Like in these programs, autofill will automatically fill in
personal data in a Web site registration after you enter the first
few letters of your name.
</P>
<P>
   There's also new features that improve printing from the Web.
For example, now you can set Internet Explorer to reduce a Web page
to fit a standard 8 1/2x11 sheet of printer paper. This feature
also mimics Microsoft's other products.
</P>
<P>
   Like Word and Excel, Internet Explorer will now automatically
replace a needed file if accidently deleted from its system.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer remains free, and you will be able to download
a copy of the latest version from the Microsoft Web site after its
release.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
