<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A few 1999 resolutions for the road
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is the time of year we typically make resolutions
about things like losing weight, being better organized, being
punctual or trying not to procrastinate. Most of these require more
than a spur-of-the-moment commitment, so we end up breaking most of
them before the holiday decorations find their way back to the
attic.
</P>
<P>
   This year, I decided to focus my resolutions on a subject I can
address one trip at a time. That, hopefully, will not only improve
my outlook, but also those of my fellow drivers. My 1999
resolutions are all directed at being a more aware, courteous and
safer driver:
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not tailgate.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will, when stopped in traffic, leave a minimum of
three-quarters of a car length between myself and the next vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not ride in the left lane.
</P>
<P>
   _ If people are passing me on the right, I will take that as a
directive to move to the right.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will only talk on my hand-held cell phone in the far right
lane (or, better yet, when standing still).
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not ``brake-check'' the car behind me (even if it is so
close I can't see its grille).
</P>
<P>
   _ If I drive an 18-wheeler on a four-lane highway, I will never
attempt to pass another truck while going uphill.
</P>
<P>
   _ When I rent a moving truck, I will limit my travel to the far
right lane.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will do my best to maintain the speed limit and/or keep up
with the flow of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not be a moving roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will never make a left turn from the right lane or a right
turn from the left lane.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will always strap toddlers and babies into their car seats.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will never move a vehicle until all occupants have buckled
their seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will never allow children under the age of 12 to sit in the
front seat of a vehicle equipped with a passenger-side air bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not allow people or dogs to travel in the bed of my
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will not stop in the ``keep moving'' lane.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will stop for red lights, and I won't charge through yellow
lights.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will make sure my vehicle's headlights are properly aligned
so I can see, and so I won't blind other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will never drive in the rain or fog without turning on my
headlights.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will use my turn signals.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will make sure my brake lights and turn signals work.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will try to refrain from giving my spouse more driving
instructions/directions than he really wants.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will work hard to ``chill'' when in Atlanta traffic and try
to be patient with other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   If none of this works, then next year I'm asking Santa for a
tank for the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
