<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMAN-CANNONBALL05-CO     01-04 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-CANNONBALL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The life and times of a human cannonball
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... with a cannon blast lightin' flash
</P>
<P>
   Movin' fast through the tent Mars bent,
</P>
<P>
   he's gonna miss his fall
</P>
<P>
   Oh God save the human cannonball
</P>
<P>
   Wild Billy's Circus Story (1973)
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls.
Three rings of once-in-a-lifetime thrills. Are you ready to be
stunned and amazed, dazzled and dazed by The Lady in the Cube, The
Iron Jaw, The Human Volcano and ... Mark Myers?
</P>
<P>
   That's Mark Myers, The Human Cannonball.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, Vero Beach High Class of '89, is equal to any oddity when
he talks about the finer points of his job. ``Even when I'm
spinning, I can tell which way is up and which way is down.''
</P>
<P>
   Or this: ``You land on your face and you're probably going to
break your neck and you'll probably die. Not a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He says this matter-of-factly: ``If you over-spin or land on
your side, you can break your shoulder, you can break your legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, 28, is starting a second year earning his living.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with female cannonball Vesta Gueschkova, he's a
centerpiece of the 128th edition of the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP;
Bailey Circus.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Pat and Larry, own Treasure Coast Contracting, a
Vero Beach company that builds underground sewers and waterlines.
They saw him perform last winter in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Recounts Myers: ``My dad said, `That's some way to make a
living,' and my mother said, `I almost shut my eyes and couldn't
watch.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, what kind of son becomes a human cannonball?
</P>
<P>
   Myers wasn't supposed to be flying across North American arenas
when he left home right after high school for the 10-week Ringling
Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Clown College in Venice on Florida's west
coast.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't supposed to be blasted into the beyond when he
graduated from Clown College as Marty the Clown and went to work
for Clyde Beatty-Cole Bros. Circus for four years.
</P>
<P>
   But then noted circus daredevil Elvin Bale asked Myers to be a
Human Cannonball for the Ringling circus. Bale recruited Myers
because of his size _ 5-feet-7, 145 pounds _ and athletic ability
honed from high school wrestling and track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it for maybe 20- or 30-hundredths of a
second,'' says Myers. ``The job sounded fun and exciting and not
many people have done it. And it was a chance to travel with The
Greatest Show on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clyde Beatty-Cole Bros. Circus works the East Coast while
Ringling tours all of North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got called up to the big show.''
</P>
<P>
   This Human Cannonball has been launched 440 times in 45 North
American cities so far.
</P>
<P>
   Two Ringling shows, a red and a blue, are always touring. Each
show is created to run for two years. Myers and this blue edition _
it's built on P.T. Barnum human oddities plus tightrope walkers,
elephants, a tiger tamer and other traditional circus acts _ will
end next November.
</P>
<P>
   A Human Cannonball may or may not be included in future shows.
Cannonballs have no lifetime contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Although ticket buyers don't realize it, Myers The Human
Cannonball is also pink-haired Marty the Clown for this Ringling
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clowning is fun because it gives me something else to
do,'' says Myers. ``It gives me a chance to show the audience I can
do something else besides this big act, this dangerous thing being
shot out of a cannon.''
</P>
<P>
   To learn the cannon act, Myers trained with Human Cannonball
Bale for more than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the cannon barrel, Myers fits tight into a capsule that's on
a track. When the cannon is fired, the capsule shoots up the barrel
about 9 feet and stops, ejecting Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a tight, solid object,'' he says. ``If you're
soft, you're going to goosh and get all crumpled up in there and
your knees will bend and it's going to be really painful. If you're
tight and solid, you're ready for the hit.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3-2-1 ... fire, Myers waits a second and is launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capsule slides up and you come out. That's when you click:
You shoot your arms out, your feet come together, your toes point
and you squeeze your legs to get rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger isn't in the flying, it's landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't land right unless you fly right, you can't fly right
unless you're in the capsule correctly and tight. It's hard to play
catch up in the seconds that I'm in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   He has minor injuries such as a jammed finger but nothing that
made him miss a performance.
</P>
<P>
   Myers has been told he flies at 60 mph for the 100 feet from the
cannon to the net.
</P>
<P>
   The cannon shot feels ``like lying down and having a dumptruck
drive into your feet at 50 miles per hour,'' he says. ``When I do
it right and I don't have to think while I'm in the air, don't have
to make adjustments, it's just like flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers doesn't wear protective equipment, and his helmet is mere
canvas, a part of his costume.
</P>
<P>
   Myers has a ritual before each shot that comes from his jujitsu
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I close my eyes and go through this breathing exercise which
helps calm me and I try to clear out the thoughts of what's
happened to me that day because I can't be distracted,'' he
explains. ``I have to be 100 percent every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we're getting ready to go in, I guess you could say I give
my bow of respect to the cannon and then I do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   This six-day-a-week circus job will keep him flying for at least
six more months _ and then, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go to California, get an agent and get into TV or
commercials or movies,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, ``Human Cannonball'' looks great on a resume.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
