<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT05-COX     01-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finally, a site for ig-pay atin-Lay
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bell bottoms, disco and Donnie and Marie have made
comebacks. So did John Travolta and Richard Nixon. About the only
things from the 1970s that haven't returned are TV variety shows
and pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, variety shows will stay gone. The world doesn't
need another weekly hour of Tony Orlando and Dawn. But the Web
could do a lot for pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of sites offer text translators. You type in a line of
text or, in some cases, a Web address, and the application turns it
into pig Latin.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, check http:/www.rinkworks.com/dialect/ or
</P>
<P>
   http://voyager.cns.ohiou.edu/(tilde)jrantane/menu/pig.html. One
site turns the word of God into pig Latin, from Enesis-gay to the
Book of Ob-Jay,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.well.com/user/earl/Ible-bay.html.
</P>
<P>
   The rules behind the language are simple enough: You take the
first consonant of most words, put an -ay behind it and stick it at
the end of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Simple, but time consuming for chunks of text. It would take
minutes to translate the opening words of Lou Gehrig's famous
farewell speech. A Web translator can do it in seconds. ``Odaytay,
Iyay onsidercay yselfmay ethay uckiestlay anmay onyay ethay acefay
ofyay ethay earthyay.''
</P>
<P>
   There are Web translators that change text from one language to
another, like Spanish to English, but those probably have some
practical application. What good is the Web if it also can't be
used for things with no definable purpose?
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance savings available on Internet
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can cost you money: Usually, you have to buy a
computer with a modem and access fees to reach it. But once there,
some things you find actually save you money.
</P>
<P>
   A few new studies by the Telecommunications Research &AMP; Action
Center show how.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC found that in some cases long-distance customers can cut
their monthly bill in half by signing up for service over the
Internet. Internet long-distance service requires you pay your bill
with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC publishes a study called Tele-Tips at its Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.trac.org. This month's study compares rates for
dial-around phone codes. The study found dial-around access offers
some competitive rates, but some have hidden fees that can hit
hard. The report warns that, shockingly, the advertising for the
dial-around codes can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   TRAC is a nonprofit, tax-exempt consumer group that works to
inform long-distance customers
</P>
<P>
   Test your knowledge of 'Sesame Street'
</P>
<P>
   If television is indeed wet nurse to a generation of children,
``Sesame Street'' is the good milk. The children's television
stalwart turns 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the anniversary, the ``Sesame Street'' Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ctw.org/sesame/trivia/0,1736,,00.html, has put
together a trivia game.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know which ``Sesame Street'' characters were inspired by
the movie ``It's a Wonderful Life'' and the year ``Sesame Street''
made its debut? Do you know how big Big Bird really is?
</P>
<P>
   If you knew Bert and Ernie owe their existence to Frank Capra,
the morning show debuted on public television in 1969 and that Big
Bird stands 8 feet, 2 inches tall, there might be no need to play.
</P>
<P>
   The game tallies answers for everyone who plays. If you thought
Fozzy Bear, instead of Bert and Ernie, owed his creation to ``It's
a Wonderful Life,'' you could see how many others were similarly
misinformed.
</P>
<P>
   Take a sneak peek at some famous recipes
</P>
<P>
   If the year between Girl Scout cookie deliveries seems like 10
years, a Web site of copycat recipes might lessen the distance.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.copykat.com is devoted to recipes for well-known
food, like Girl Scout Thin Mint cookies; macaroni and cheese from
Boston Market; and fried chicken from KFC.
</P>
<P>
   There are also recipes for lesser-known delicacies, such as the
Pea Salad from Knott's Berry Farm and the Oyster Bar Trash from
Willie G's.
</P>
<P>
   Most online job help is for nontechies
</P>
<P>
   CareerMosaic, an online job site, released a study showing most
jobs listed on online sites are nontechnical.
</P>
<P>
   The CareerMosaic Index found three of the top 10 most popular
online job searches were related to technical jobs, engineering,
computers and computer programming.
</P>
<P>
   The index found the most popular keywords used in searches were
``manager/management,'' ``engineer,'' and ``sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Online job hunting reflects seasonal trends as well. Teaching
positions ranked 22nd in July, but fell to 28th in August and 30th
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Other job categories among the top 25 were, ``finance,'' ``human
resources,'' ``nurse'' and ``package handler.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by CareerMosaic between July and
September. More than 14 million keyword searches were tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
