 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2510 - January 4, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2510 -- Jan. 4, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SHOCKUMENTARIES : WHEN ANIMALS ATTACK, CARS CRASH
</P>
<P>
   AND STUNTS GO BAD TV 'shockumentaries' such as ``World's
Scariest Police Chases 4'' and ``Surviving the Moment of Impact''
are stealing audiences from high-tech, special-effects,
million-dollar productions The shockumentary is the disaster epic
of the MTV age, edited at light speed. Its goal is to let viewers
quench the morbid desire to witness acts of tragedy and mayhem. By
Tom Vanderbilt. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length
(3,500 words) + edited article available. 2. HOW RUSSIANS LIVE
WITHOUT MONEY Most Russians today live in the precapitalist economy
of the Soviet era - and in some cases, not even that well. By Serge
Schmemann. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (4,600
words) + edited article available. (Schmemann, a reporter for The
New York Times, was its correspondent in Moscow for many years.) 3.
HAVANA : CAPITAL OF DREAMS Fidel Castro took power in Cuba 40 years
ago with the ambitious goals of creating a ``new man'' and
eliminating the profit motive and prostitution. Today, Castro is
like a dinosaur who doesn't know he is extinct. The dollar reigns
in Havana, decay is all around, and prostitutes are plentiful.
Every day, several buildings simply collapse. Despite all this,
ordinary Cubans are finding ways to create their own space, and
make their own luck. And the once-glorious Old Town is finally
being rebuilt. By Eric Follath. From Der Spiegel. (English
translation available.) 1,500 words. 4. FROM MAN AS MEMORY TO THE
CONVEYOR OF HISTORY For decades, no one was interested in hearing
what survivors of the Shoah had to say about their experiences. Now
they are invited to schools and colleges, filmed on video for
archives and asked to speak on radio and TV. A new book by
historian Annette Wieviorka ('The Era of the Witness',) shows how
attitudes towards witnesses of the past have shifted down the
years. By Nicole Lapierre. From Le Monde. (English translation
available.) 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
ATTACK OF THE SUPERBUGS! At least half the human use of antibiotics
in the U.S. is unnecessary or inappropriate, says microbiologist
Stuart Levy. ``Either antibiotics are not indicated at all, or the
wrong antibiotic is prescribed, or it's the wrong dosage or the
wrong duration.'' The upshot of this massive exposure is
disease-causing bugs that resist the drugs that once thwarted them.
They're superbugs and their power is frightening. Superbugs can
withstand not just one, but multitudes of antibiotics. Is it too
late to do anything? By Peter Radetsky. From Discover magazine.
1,100 words + photo
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
INDUSTRIAL GERMANY ONCE AGAIN RIDING HIGH Rolf Breuer, chairman of
Deutsche Bank, sees himself as the new star of Germany's business
firmament. Last November, he announced that his company was taking
over the American bank, Bankers Trust, thus creating the world's
biggest financial services company. Juergen Schrempp, boss of
Daimler-Benz, embodies the new triumphant Germany that is
conquering the United States. And Bertelsmann, the world's
third-largest media company, took over Random House last March,
thus becoming the top US publishing house. By Arnaud Leparmentier.
From Le Monde. (English translation available.) 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
WELCOME TO OUR FAMILY Strangers from abroad seek the American
experience. Busy families are looking for full-time help. Can the
au pair match-up work? By Todd Pitock. From Child magazine. 1,300
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
PORTRAIT OF A BRAVE PUBLISHER ``Being a book publisher in this year
of the Internet and photocopies doesn't seem to be a way of life
anybody with common sense would choose.'' Tomas Eloy Martinez
writes about his unwavering respect for the risks and adventures
implicit in any serious editorial enterprise, and the legendary
publisher Jesus de Polanco. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
CONTROLLING FLIES REDUCES DIARRHEA RATES IN CHILDREN Diarrhea kills
more children than any other disease, taking the lives of more than
3 million children under the age of five each year. Researchers in
Pakistan report that insecticide spraying reduced the incidence of
diarrhea in village children by 23 per cent, indicating this
approach may be a highly effective diarrhea prevention strategy. By
Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
WAR GUILT, AND THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN GERMANY AND JAPAN Ian Buruma
assesses how Germany and Japan have dealt with guilt over their
crimes in World War II. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 11.
FROM NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW : A. SOUTHERN EXPOSURE
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of tragedies involving ice and death (e.g. movies
like 'Titanic,') has led to renewed interest in the heroic age of
exploration. The first explorers of Antarctica could count on
nothing but themselves; sometimes that wasn't enough. Robert R.
Harris reviews books about Scott and Shackleton. B. LOST AND FOUND
Sarah Saffian, an adoptee, had never sought out her biological
parents. Then the phone rang. Andrea Cooper reviews 'Ithaka : A
Daughter's Memoir Of Being Found.'
_______________________________________________________________ 12.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 18h00 GMT
Jan. 6) A. WAKE ME UP BEFORE YOU GO : Some people seem to be able
to decide when they want to wake up before going to sleep - without
recourse to an alarm clock. How does this example of mindpower
work? By Sara Abdulla. 500 words. B. NEW 'SMART' GEL INSTEAD OF
NEEDLES : Daily injections of insulin will soon be a thing of the
past for people who suffer from diabetes. By Philip Ball. 500
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 13.
THE TERRIFYING NEW THREAT IS ANTI-TERRORISM The name of the new
game is ``catastrophic terrorism,'' and it is very frightening not
just because it conceivably could happen, but even more because of
what people who choose to dwell on the possibility, however remote,
want to do about it. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 14.
OVARIAN CANCER'S SUBTLE SIGNS Small symptoms, easily brushed aside
as insignificant, could influence the course of a woman's life. By
Susan McClure. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 15.
EXERCISE WHEN YOU'RE SICK? A strong immune system can rebuff
viruses and bacteria. And exercise, done wisely, seems to give the
immune system a tremendous boost. By Ken McAlpine. 1,000 words.
