<SLUG> BC-BINLADEN-YEMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIN LADEN LINK TO YEMEN EXPLORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following the release of two American tourists
after a deadly hostage standoff in Yemen, FBI investigators have
traveled to the Middle East nation to search for clues in the
attack, a spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators did not confirm reports that Osama Bin Laden, the
Saudi millionaire suspected in the bombing of two US embassies in
Africa this summer, may be linked to the December kidnapping of 16
Westerners. The rescue attempt by Yemeni officials left three
British and one Australian dead. But bin Laden's strong connection
to Yemen, and his anti-Western sentiments, are well-documented, and
might reasonably lead investigators at least to consider his
involvement, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does have ties and contacts there, and there is no doubt
extremist Islamic terrorists have found sanctuary in Yemen,'' said
Stanley Bedlington, a former CIA counterterrorism specialist. On
the other hand, he added, ``He's becoming rather like a mythical
Robin Hood. Any crime that's committed is immediately ascribed to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports of bin Laden's connection to the Yemeni attack
coincided with the release of new interviews with the reclusive
Saudi, including one in which he came close to acknowledging a role
in attacks on Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after the embassy bombings, and the ensuing US
military raid on suspected bin Laden strongholds in Afghanistan and
Sudan, bin Laden summoned two Pakistani reporters to his mountain
compound. There, clutching an AK-47 across his chest, bin Laden
held two interviews on successive days, according to accounts in
this week's issues of Newsweek and Time magazines.
</P>
<P>
   He told each a different story. To the Newsweek reporter, bin
Laden denied all culpability, saying of the bombings on Dec. 22
that he ``did not order them but was very glad for what happened to
the Americans there.''
</P>
<P>
   One day later, he gave a different account to a Time reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the instigation for jihad against the Jews and the
Americans . . . is considered a crime, then let history be a
witness that I am a criminal,'' bin Laden said. ``Our job is to
instigate, and by the grace of God, we did that, and certain people
responded to this instigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve Americans were killed in the Aug. 7 bombings in Tanzania
and Kenya, along with 212 Africans. Bin Laden, who was indicted in
federal court last year, is wanted by the United States. There is a
$5 million reward for his capture.
</P>
<P>
   In the attack in Yemen, a group of assailants, reportedly
members of the fundamentalist Islamic Jihad, captured the 16
tourists on Dec. 29. The incident has sparked controversy between
the host nation and Great Britain, home of three of the murder
victims; it has also brought several FBI agents as well as
detectives from Scotland Yard to Yemen, according to the London
Sunday Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers, who were arrested after the rescue raid, were
allegedly trained by bin Laden, who has also expressed strong
support of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein, the paper said. According
to the Arabic newspaper Al Watan Al Arabi, bin Laden has had
significant business interests in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has been suspected of violence in Yemen in the past,
and is wanted in connection with two separate hotel bombings
targeting Western soldiers in 1992 and 1993, Al Watan Al Arabi
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
