<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A05-COX     01-04 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a way to tell how heavy wrapping paper is before
buying it? I am so tired of cheap paper that tears easily. Surely
there is some guide like there is with sheets. _Carolyn E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Like a 310 thread-count per inch? Some companies have a
reputation for thick paper _ Sample House, Schwartz. You can only
tell by touch or by folding the paper. So that means buying
wrapping paper from a source that allows you to feel the goods.
Paper is measured in mils _ a very confusing measure you never see
on a label. Good wrapping paper is thicker than either fax paper or
newsprint. A simple test: Fold the paper. Folds in thin paper lie
flat; thick paper springs open.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The recipe for Tom and Jerry batter calls for beating
separated eggs and then combining them. I hesitated to use it for
the umpteenth time this year because I could picture my R.N.
daughter asking, ``We're not drinking RAW eggs in this, are we?''
and forcing the rest of the group to make a risk/reward assessment.
Do you know if any food person has ever looked at this and
concluded _ I hope _ that rum, brandy and boiling water clobber any
bugs that may be in those eggs? Am I beating this batter question
to death? Appreciate your time on this less-than-world-shaking
matter. _John N.
</P>
<P>
   A: This cold-weather drink is popular with transplanted
northerners. The bug to worry about in raw eggs is salmonella.
``Alcohol does not destroy salmonella bacteria,'' says Ione Wenzel
of the Texas Department of Health, retail foods division.
Temperatures over 145 degrees (sustained for 15 seconds) kill
salmonella. Maybe the R.N. has a point.Q: This year I could not
find the plain, plastic luminarias _ the ones on a form to place
over Christmas lights. We went to see the lights in Marshall, and
although there are miles of them strung along residential
sidewalks, I did not find them in any stores there. Where do they
get them? All I have found are those miserable things with sand and
a candle. I know it's too late for this year, but maybe for next
year? _Esther McConoghy
</P>
<P>
   A: Farolitos (little lanterns) were used by Spanish colonists in
New Mexico as early as the 1620s. The candles are said to
illuminate the way of the Christ child to holiday homes. Next year
The Famous Christmas Store will have more of these electric
luminarias in stock. To order now and store for Christmas 1999,
call (800) 447-0048, Alsto's Handy Helpers, one of my favorite
catalogs.Q: Where can I buy tire chains for our family cars? I
called around with no luck. I would like to buy them even if I use
them once in three years. Austin definitely needs them after this
horrible ice storm we had. Lives could have been saved.
</P>
<P>
   _Yvonne Heath
</P>
<P>
   A: Order tire chains from any Pep Boys. Chains are ordered in
pairs and range from $50 to $89 a pair. Drive friendly!
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did you sip from the good crystal during the holidays? You may
be interested in a cleaning tip from crystal-master Waterford. Wash
crystal by hand only, using warm water and mild soap. To clean the
interiors of vases and decanters, fill them halfway with warm
water, two tablespoons of white vinegar or ammonia and 1/4 cup
uncooked rice. The rice is a mild abrasive and, when swirled
around, gently removes interior film. Finish with a vinegar and
water solution, which adds sparkle. Dry with a lint-free cloth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Readers shared suggestions for cleaning grimy fireplace glass.
Make sure the glass is cool before cleaning. One reader extolled
the virtues of Easy-Off Oven Cleaner; one, household ammonia and
newspaper; and another, a damp newspaper (not just for getting news
and information anymore!) and wood ashes to cut the black goo.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
