 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Tuesday, January 5, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   PAPERWAR _ The morning Chattanooga Times, started just after the
Civil War, finally surrendered to its afternoon competitor, the
Free Press, and a combined paper starts publication Jan 5. This
signals the end of a decades long war between two paper-publishing
families: the descendents of Adolph Ochs (of NYT fame; the Times is
his first paper), who are liberal, Jewish and old money, and the
McDonalds, who are conservative, fundamentalist Christian and
started the paper in the 40s as a shopper for their own grocery
store. Walter Hussman, owner of the Little Rock paper, bought the
McDonalds' paper, and then the Ochs descendents threw in the towel
and sold to him as well. (Hendrick, Atlkanta Journal-Constitution).
50. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ This week: How to test the
thickness of wrapping paper and other consumer questions. (Greig,
Austin American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ This year, I decided to focus my
resolutions on a subject I can address one trip at a time. That,
hopefully, will not only improve my outlook, but also those of my
fellow drivers. My 1999 resolutions are all directed at being a
more aware, courteous and safer driver. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ What causes brake pedal vibration, or
``pulsation,'' and why. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-CANNONBALL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ladies and gentlemen,
boys and girls. Three rings of once-in-a-lifetime thrills. Are you
ready to be stunned and amazed, dazzled and dazed by The Lady in
the Cube, The Iron Jaw, The Human Volcano and ... Mark Myers?
That's Mark Myers, The Human Cannonball. What it's like to blast
off in the ring. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
ETA: 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-PAGERS _ ATLANTA _ Welcome to the world of the
latest in hand-held computing, the interactive pager. Except for
its beep, it has little in common with its cousin, the ordinary
pager. The BellSouth Interactive Pager, a companion of mine for
several weeks, is different because it sends and receives
information. Like an ordinary computer, it has directories and an
electronic address book. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ ATLANTA _ ``Free'' is the operative word for today.
I'll tell you how to find your own free home in cyberspace, then
we'll talk about some free tools and techniques that can make your
Web site into a good home. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ Software reviews. This week: National
Geographic Trip Planner DeLuxe. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ This column will not move tonight. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ A little care can keep you from being
misled by Web ``information.'' (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. This
week: Hasbro's ``Stratego'' CD. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Ironically, competition for the best Mac
Web browser has not slackened a bit between Microsoft and Netscape
during the long weeks of the government's antitrust suit against
the world's dominant software provider.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is readying the next version of its Internet Explorer
browser, which will probably be previewed at the MacWorld
convention in San Francisco this week. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Bell bottoms, disco and Donnie and Marie
have made comebacks. So did John Travolta and Richard Nixon. About
the only things from the 1970s that haven't returned are TV variety
shows and pig Latin. A slew of sites offer text translators. You
type in a line of text or, in some cases, a Web address, and the
application turns it into pig Latin. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
