<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As the dawn of new century nears, Americans keep their sunny
side up
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are nothing if not perky. As the 20th century winds down,
pollsters, economists and other trend watchers say American
optimism is surging. Instead of turning into a mature country,
weary of its burdens and cynical about its success, we seem to be
getting younger ... and happier.
</P>
<P>
   Cheerfulness is showing up in all sorts of measures. President
Clinton gets impeached by the U.S. House, and his approval rating
surges to more than 70 percent. The global economy turns grim, and
U.S. consumer confidence rises to exuberant levels. The United
States bombs Iraq, and the stock market shoots to record heights.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe our sunniness has something to do with the thrill of
preparing for a new century. Today's optimism in many ways mirrors
what the nation experienced in 1899. ``People were euphoric around
the turn of the (last) century,'' said Claudia Goldin, an economic
historian at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Gay '90s'' of the last century found most Americans
thinking the future was filled with exciting possibilities because
of new technologies and the dramatic growth in immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those same two characters _ the technology wizard and the
naturalized citizen _ may again be fueling our optimism. On Wall
Street, high-tech companies' stock prices soar. Meanwhile,
immigrants stir a sense of hopefulness.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between the late 1890s and the 1990s are
considerable. A century ago, average Americans were just beginning
to see their daily lives become easier because of inventions such
as the light bulb, telephone and bicycle. Parents who used to
huddle around kerosene lamps could relax with the evening newspaper
and watch their children do homework under the bright glow of an
electric lamp.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners, too, were rejoicing. With immigrants streaming
into the country, employers finally could find enough workers to
operate their new steel mills, factories and railroads. And the
immigrants themselves brought optimism.
</P>
<P>
   By moving to a new country, Goldin said, ``they are taking
things into their own hands. So simply in terms of self-selection,
immigrants are optimists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s, Americans are seeing an updated version of
the same trends. Computers are entering our daily lives and leading
us to believe in a better future. When children do school projects
with the help of the Internet, parents feel a sense of pride and
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   And just as in the 1890s, our inventions are giving rise to new
fortunes. Then we admired the builders of railroads, factories and
such; today, we are awed by Bill Gates and other computer tycoons.
And because of the availability of high-tech stocks, many ordinary
workers also are getting richer. ``Americans are saying, `Wow, any
one of us could be a cowboy capitalist too,''' Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, new citizens are renewing our sense of hope.
``Immigrants tend to be people who think the future looks brighter,
especially for their children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even the cheeriest periods have their dark sides. That was
certainly true in the 1890s, when ``there were things that many
people were very scared about: socialism, communism, anarchism,
Catholicism'' and more, Goldin said. ``There was a tremendous fear
that the very rock foundations of the country were going to be
swept away'' by huge businesses, foreigners and political radicals.
</P>
<P>
   Today there is fear, too. Many Americans question whether the
economy can absorb so many newcomers, and parents worry about their
children being exposed to bad influences through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the parallels, the intensity of emotions differs. A
century ago, people were positively ``exuberant'' or abjectly
terrified, Goldin said. In the 1990s, Americans are mellower. For
example, ``people don't seem to be as upset'' about business
monopolies or as inclined to allow fear of immigrants to spark
Klan-type violence, she said.
</P>
<P>
   How long this mellow mood will last is anyone's guess. But look
on the bright side: Optimism is so basic to the American character
that even when it dims for a while, the sun always shines again.
``We are phenomenally optimistic,'' Goldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is an editorial writer for The Atlanta
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
