<SLUG> BC-GRAY-DAVIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S NEW GOVERNOR POSITIONS HIMSELF IN THE MIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Joseph Graham Davis Jr., who was raised in
a Republican family but became the chief aide to former Gov. Jerry
Brown, becomes the first Democratic governor of California in 16
years with a promise to find a center between his father and his
old boss.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Gray'' by his family, Gov.-elect Davis says he'll
take California into an era of political compromise, ending years
of divisiveness between Republican governors and Democratic
legislatures, while steering clear of Jerry Brown's unorthodox
liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the cautious lieutenant governor is borrowing from
President Clinton's centrist playbook: he's tough on crime and
supports the death penalty; he's made education his top priority;
he claims to be a fiscal conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But while those moderate positions may have gotten him elected,
Davis is taking over a California that faces critical problems as
wide-ranging as Indian casinos, clogged freeways and the division
of scarce water resources. And he must try to solve those problems
without a lot of extra cash: The state faces a large budget deficit
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   He also must deal with the pent-up demands of a Democratic state
legislature that has seen many of its initiatives vetoed year after
year by Govs. Pete Wilson and George Deukmejian.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' dilemma is whether to tackle the state's most complicated
and long-ignored problems, such as the shortage of affordable
housing, or push a more limited agenda that he thinks he can
accomplish in time for a re-election bid in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor says he will be able to achieve what neither
Wilson nor Deukmejian nor his old boss Jerry Brown could: broker
solutions amenable to both Democrats and Republicans from his
position in the middle of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Not all observers are as optimistic about the power of a
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy Roosevelt answered that question,'' said state
assemblyman Tom McClintock, a conservative from Ventura who is
often a thorn in the side of Republicans and Democrats. ``He said
(moderate) is the `great gray twilight that knows neither victory
nor defeat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, so far, Davis has built an administration that looks like
what voters would expect from a traditional Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   He has appointed a large number of Hispanics, a few African
Americans, Asians and the ``first Asian-Pacific American to hold a
cabinet position'' _ Lon Hatamiya, the new secretary of trade and
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just going to be an enormous change of tone,'' said
Philip Trounstine, Davis' communications director, who is changing
his party affiliation from decline-to-state to Democrat. ``There is
going to be a change in priorities and emphasis.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis must deal with his first major headache: a projected $2.5
billion to $3 billion deficit. Friday, the new governor will
announce his budget for the coming year. Observers will watch to
see how well he appeases the business community while answering his
own party's call for more money for education, HMO reform and
stricter environmental protections.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, Davis must step into a series of thorny
issues: A battle is brewing with the state's Indian tribes over
regulating casino-style gambling under Proposition 5. The $490
million deal to save some of the Headwaters forest from logging is
falling apart. Trial attorneys, who contributed to Davis' campaign,
want to increase the amount of damages that can be collected in
medical malpractice cases.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his term, he will face some of California's
most controversial and difficult problems. An anti-gay marriage
initiative is headed for the 2000 ballot. The freeways are clogged
beyond anything endured in state history. The Delta is dirty, and
Southern California wants more water from Northern California. The
Asian financial crisis could hammer California.
</P>
<P>
   The first big issue could be the heated struggle over Indian
gambling. Voters approved Proposition 5, the measure to allow
tribes to operate slot machines, but opponents are challenging its
constitutionality in the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who stayed neutral on the issue through the campaign _
though he made conciliatory statements to the tribes _ could make
the issue moot by agreeing to pacts to allow the 44 gambling tribes
to offer slots, which Wilson refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that's on the mind of anyone in Cala
Market, but it's a murky policy area that's going to have to be
resolved,'' said San Francisco assemblywoman Carole Migden.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also will have to deal with a higher education system
that's world-renowned but still reeling from Proposition 209, which
banned affirmative action and led to significant drops in minority
enrollment, including a 47 percent decline among minorities in this
year's freshman class at University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Davis opposed Prop. 209, but has said he would not try to
reverse the successful 1996 ballot measure. During the campaign, he
proposed a new admissions system to require the UC schools to
accept the top 4 percent of graduates from every high school in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone coming in after Pete Wilson has to be better,'' said
Carlos Munoz Jr., professor of history and politics UC-Berkeley and
an outspoken 209 foe. ``(But) I don't see Davis really being that
committed to doing what he can, given his power as governor, to
turn back the 209 tide and change the laws to reflect a pre-209
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who beat Republican opponent Dan Lungren in part by
appearing tough on crime, also will have to manage a prison system
that is growing steadily because of tougher sentencing laws, like
``three strikes,'' which Davis backed. Though crime rates have
dropped in recent years, prison populations continue to swell,
growing 10-fold in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if prison expenses continue to grow, Davis will have less
money available for programs he favors, such as education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
