<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS LURES CLINTON ADVISERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Gov. Gray Davis is drawing
heavily from the Clinton administration for his innermost circle of
advisers, a sign that Democrats banished from the governor's office
for 16 years are returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, Davis has filled five out of a dozen
cabinet positions _ the secretaries of health and human services,
resources, food and agriculture, trade and commerce, and state and
consumer affairs _ with people who have worked or still work for
the embattled president.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 30 top-level people appointed by Davis so far,
eight have worked for Clinton. The migration is a natural one,
especially since Clinton has two years (or less) left in his term,
and Democrats have gubernatorial jobs available for the first time
since Jerry Brown left office in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor-elect made it clear,'' said Davis spokesman
Michael Bustamante, ``that he was going to look for the best and
the brightest California has to offer. I'm certain that was the
same criteria the president used.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Davis appointments, the most politically connected to
Clinton appears to be Davis' new legal affairs secretary, Demetrios
A. Boutris, who worked in the mid-'90s as a special counsel to U.S.
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Boutris was questioned by investigators for
the House of Representative for his role in helping expand the
so-called Bingaman Commission on Pacific trade and investment.
Boutris did the legal work to increase the number of commissioners
from 15 to ``up to 20,'' but, according to a House deposition, not
much more.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was important to the congressional committee
because Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie, a major contributor to Clinton's
legal defense fund, had been appointed to it by President Clinton.
Trie fled the country and now faces charges of funneling illegal
contributions to the Democratic National Committee to gain access
to Clinton and other top officials.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Bustamante said Boutris was ``an extremely
accomplished lawyer who will certainly serve the governor-elect
with distinction.'' He declined to comment on the Trie connection,
saying it was irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Boutris and the agency chiefs, Davis has tapped Los
Angeles firefighter Dallas Jones, a Clinton appointee to a
committee that advises Federal Emergency Management Agency Director
James Lee Witt. Jones will be the new director of the state office
of emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   Grantland Johnson, the new secretary of health and human
services, has served since 1993 as a regional director for the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also appointed former Clinton administration official Mary
Nichols to become secretary of resources, heading the agency that
oversees 14 environment-related boards, commissions and
departments.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists cheered the appointment of Nichols, who also
worked for ex-Gov. Brown and helped form the League of Conservation
Voters. But some conservatives say Davis broke his promise to steer
a middle course in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the campaign, Gray Davis said he'd govern from the
middle,'' said Assemblyman Rico Oller, a Republican from San
Andreas. ``However, this appointment of Nichols signals a return to
the extreme politics of the Jerry Brown administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
