<SLUG> BC-ANNAN-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US, ANNAN AT ODDS OVER IRAQ POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years after the Clinton administration sponsored
Kofi Annan's rise to power as UN secretary general, Washington's
relationship with the Ghanaian diplomat has degenerated to its
worst state ever.
</P>
<P>
   Senior US officials, including national security adviser Samuel
R. Berger and Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, have
accused him in recent months of going soft on Saddam Hussein and
interfering with US plans to bomb Iraq in November, according to UN
sources. Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering recently paid a
visit to the UN chief to quash a series of initiatives under
consideration by his advisers that would have eased sanctions on
Iraq and diluted the UN weapons inspection teams in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As the UN Security Council gets set to debate the future of the
UN's Iraq policy in the coming weeks, US diplomats are seeking to
head off Russian, French, and Chinese attempts to expand the
secretary general's role in managing the UN's relationship with the
Iraqi leader.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute is the feeling that the secretary
general, in his desire to bring peace to the Persian Gulf, has been
too willing to grant concessions to Hussein. But the discord more
broadly reflects the inevitable conflict inherent in the
relationship between the United States and the post of UN secretary
general.
</P>
<P>
   The late U Thant of Burma, secretary general during the 1960s,
riled the Johnson administration by criticizing the US war in
Vietnam and seeking a mediation role. Boutros Boutros-Ghali,
Annan's Egyptian predecessor, was pressured out of office by the
Clinton administration when he did not implement fiscal changes at
the UN urged by Washington and thwarted efforts to launch NATO
strikes against Bosnian Serb forces attacking civilians in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been few moments in the history of the United
Nations when there hasn't been a period of tension between the
secretary general and the United States over the main issue of the
day,'' said James Placke, a veteran US Middle East diplomat who now
works at the Cambridge Energy Research Associates. ``You saw it
during decolonization, apartheid, and throughout the entire Cold
War.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's closest aides say the secretary general's activism in
Iraq has been unavoidable. They note that France, China, and Russia
_ three of the five permanent members of the Security Council _
have been pressing Annan to take a more activist role in Iraq, as
has much of the Arab world. Besides, they say, the secretary
general works for all 185 UN member states and he has a duty to
pursue peaceful settlements, even when that involves sitting across
the table with the world's ``rogue'' leaders, from Hussein to
Moammar Khadafy.
</P>
<P>
   Observers note that the Clinton administration authorized
Annan's diplomatic intervention in Iraq in February when he
traveled to Baghdad to persuade Hussein to grant unfettered access
to UN weapons inspectors seeking to eliminate Iraq's nuclear,
chemical, and biological weapons. They say that Annan is now being
made a scapegoat for an administration that is sensitive to
criticism from Congress that it has appeased Hussein for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a fan of the February deal, but I think its unfair
to say he bore responsibility,'' said Patrick Clawson, an analyst
at the Washington Institute of Near East Policy. ``He offered
himself as a useful interlocutor; he checked very carefully with
the US; and he said if it doesn't work out it's my skin, not yours,
that's on the line. And that's what the Americans wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Clawson said more is at stake for the United Nations than
Annan's personal relationship with Washington. He counseled Annan
to recede into the background on the diplomatic front and work
behind the scenes to forge consensus among the key members of the
sharply divided Security Council. Otherwise, he said, the United
States may decide to ignore the council in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot be an activist in a situation where the permanent
five members of the Security Council don't agree,'' said Clawson.
``Under those circumstances, the best thing to do is go back to
being a secretary and not a general.''
</P>
<P>
   The friction between Washington and the UN has clearly taken a
toll on the secretary general in recent weeks. On the eve of the
US-British air attack on Iraq, Annan reminded Washington that its
policy of toppling Hussein was in no way sanctioned by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has also lashed out at Washington for demanding UN fiscal
reform while failing to pay nearly $1 billion in dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have done enough,'' Annan said during a press
conference in mid-December. ``We should be allowed to focus on our
work and not face constant harassment of reform, reform, reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing to encourage efficiency,'' he said. ``It is
quite another to be subjected to a starvation diet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kofi is a man of peace who tries to avoid conflict wherever he
can,'' said a White House official. ``We respect his integrity and
independence, but at the end of the day we will pursue our own
national interests, and that doesn't always coincide with the
interests of the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody likes and respects him,'' added a former US
official and friend of Annan. ``He is a man of good will. It's just
that a lot of men of good will do bad things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he has created a lot of unhappiness in Washington over
Iraq. Many think he has lost his sense of judgment,'' he added.
``The relationship has gone through a bad spell, which could have a
longer-term impact.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the four-day US-British bombing campaign in
Iraq that ended on Dec. 19, Annan has taken a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say Annan may eventually return to a more active role in
Iraq policy. He has established a task force to generate ideas that
would help unify the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are looking for Annan to come up with ideas,''
said a senior UN aide to Annan. ``The secretary general wants to
wait and allow the temperatures to cool.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
