A7112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-2TA     01-04 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC COLLEGES SEE PERIL IN VATICAN PUSH FOR CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its brochures, Boston College acknowledges that it is a
Catholic school, dedicated by its Jesuit founders to ``a world view
that encounters God in all creation.''
</P>
<P>
   It devotes much more ink to detailing what makes BC a hot school
in national rankings: the academic excellence of its faculty and
graduate schools, selective admissions, its 33 Division I athletic
teams, an $814 million endowment, and the diversity of a student
body that hails from 85 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Catholicism has coexisted with excellence.
</P>
<P>
   But at BC and other Catholic colleges, administrators and
professors say a dispute with the Vatican now jeopardizes the
national prominence they have worked for decades to achieve,
thrusting them into a tug of war that at its most extreme could
force schools to cut their Catholic ties.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on a proposal that would transfer control of
the 236 Catholic colleges and universities in the United States
from their boards of trustees to local bishops, rewriting the
schools' charters to put them under Vatican law.
</P>
<P>
   Schools would be expected to have a majority of trustees and
faculty be ``faithful Catholics,'' and theology professors would be
required to get a mandate from the local bishop. The mandate would
be revoked because of teachings that stray from Catholic doctrine.
Any non-Catholic faculty would have to ``exhibit integrity of
doctrine and good character,'' and would be encouraged to attend
frequent lectures on church teachings.
</P>
<P>
   The document was proposed in November by the US Conference of
Catholic Bishops. But the bishops say they are acting only under
pressure from the Vatican, which, alarmed by recent sales of
Catholic hospitals and declining numbers of nuns and priests to
serve as teachers, wants to make sure that Catholic schools stay
firmly in its fist.
</P>
<P>
   College presidents say that as much as they want to strengthen
Catholic ties, the proposed changes present innumerable legal
perils, and are sure to prompt lawsuits over hiring discrimination
and free speech, prevent schools from getting federal grants and
students from getting federal loans, and hurt the schools' ability
to attract a stellar faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of intrusions into the academic community are just
going to wave red flags in front of a lot of academic bulls,'' said
Thomas J. Reese, editor of America, the Jesuit magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The universities are caught between a rock and a hard place.
Clearly they want to be Catholic, but they also want to be a
credible institution. They are trying to be both, and they think
they are being successful at that. But if the Vatican continues to
pressure them on this, they are going to have to choose between
being Catholic and being academically credible. It's going to force
some of them to be nonsectarian, and force others to give up their
academic respectability.''
</P>
<P>
   For the schools, the conflict is the paradox of prosperity. Like
BC, most were local institutions on the edge of economic stability
in the late 1960s. To stay viable and attract students, they added
lay expertise to once all-clergy boards of trustees and faculties,
putting a premium on academic talent over faith. Encouraged by the
ecumenical spirit that came out of the Second Vatican Council, they
added professors of many faiths.
</P>
<P>
   As they became diverse, national institutions, more conservative
Catholics worried that the schools were putting their religious
identity up for auction. So, over a decade ago, the Vatican and
bishops around the world began discussions about a document to
ensure that Catholic higher education stayed Catholic, both in the
United States and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   With pressure from a delegation of American Catholic academics
that lobbied in Rome, the Vatican agreed that the final document
should respect the culture of different nations _ for the United
States, notions of academic freedom and healthy dissent. In 1990,
it released the document ``Ex Corde Ecclesiae,'' literally ``from
the heart of the church,'' as an overall guideline. The Vatican
left it to bishops in individual countries to localize the document
to their universities.
</P>
<P>
   The US bishops agreed on a version of the document in late 1996
by a vote of 224-6. The Vatican rejected it, sending it back a year
later with a demand for tighter language to guarantee the bishops'
control over the schools _ veto power instead of a consultant's
role. The bishops responded in November with the current proposal,
leaving colleges until May to make comments before a final vote
late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops insist the proposal could change as the debate
unfolds over the year. And how strictly the new rules would be
enforced would depend on state constitutions regarding separation
of church and state, as well as the relationship between colleges
and the local bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston, for instance, has developed a
warm relationship with Boston College's president, the Rev. William
P. Leahy, who is considered to have reinforced the school's
Catholic identity after years when, local clergy complained, the
school had strayed. Law said he will withhold comment on the
document until he sees how the debate plays out over the year.
</P>
<P>
   Some bishops share the concerns about the dwindling Catholic
influence on campus. At the conference in November, Bishop Allen H.
Vigneron, auxiliary bishop of Detroit, welcomed the proposal as ``a
solid mechanism for assuring Catholic identity of institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   College presidents, though, say it presents so many problems, in
practice and in principle, that it would be unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   Under Title VII, federal aid can go to Catholic colleges only if
they are controlled by a lay board. Once control goes to the
bishop, the institutions are classified as church organizations,
and the law throws up a wall barring the school from getting
government money, and students from getting federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
