<SLUG> BC-EXPLOSIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAN CLAIMS EXPLOSIVES STOCKPILE WERE A `HOBBY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A PG&AMP;E serviceman accused of stockpiling large
quantities of explosives materials at his home and workplace simply
had a bad habit of collecting more than what he needed to fuel a
harmless hobby of making little firecrackers, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Joseph Madronich Jr., 44, of San Francisco, has been making
small firecrackers to share with friends for several years with no
intent of creating anything more substantial or dangerous, said
attorney Jerrold Ladar. Friends and family knew of his ``hobby''
for years and even nicknamed him ``the Unabomer'' but felt no need
to turn him over to authorities, Ladar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody felt he was not (a danger) to the community or
himself,'' Ladar said. ``This was just a hobby that he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Madronich, a 19-year PG&AMP;E employee, was arrested Thursday on
three charges of possessing illegal explosives and is being held in
county jail on $1 million bail. Authorities seized five 50-pound
bags of ammonium nitrate, a 33-gallon barrel of calcium nitrate and
bomb-making books from his work locker and his parents' home on
Potrero Hill where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   They also seized ammonium nitrate from a Sonoma home his parents
own _ a substance Ladar said was used to fertilize the garden
there.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the District Attorney's office say they have a
strong case against Madronich but have no evidence indicating that
he was plotting an explosives attack.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Jean Daly said the amount of
explosives found could have ``done significant damage'' to a
building and ``endangered the lives and safety of the general
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Madronich did not intend any harm to come from the
explosives, Daly said, he is still violating the law by possessing
and assembling such devices.
</P>
<P>
   But Ladar said Madronich has been swept up in a zealous
prosecution for having a misguided hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's upset about being arrested,'' Ladar said. ``He has 19
years with PG&AMP;E with no history (of bad behavior). I think he's a
little bewildered. I get the very genuine feeling from him that he
was like, `What did I do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ladar conceded that his client would make a variety of
firecrackers and ``acorn explosives''_ filling acorn shells with an
explosive powder. But he said investigators found no evidence that
Ladar was building anything bigger than a small firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two substances (ammonium nitrate fertilizer and calcium
nitrate) don't pose a danger of exploding unless you mix them
together in some kind of ratio and add a fuel and a fuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that such large quantities of the substance were found
in Madronich's possession were consistent with a habit Madronich
had of collecting more than what he needed, Ladar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tends to oversupply with a lot of stuff,'' Ladar said,
describing his client's penchant for buying in bulk _ be it bottles
of wine or shoes on sale. ``Most of his friends and neighbors say
that this is a guy who's been known to buy more stuff then he
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladar said officials found additional fertilizer at the Sonoma
residence and an unknown white powder that was detonated
underground at the property but no explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client has been very forthcoming with authorities
and hopes prosectors will believe that Madronich did not intend to
harm anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that the search for justice and truth would allow
them to get all their facts before them and they'll see,'' Ladar
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
