<HEADER>
A7118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-04 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT FICTION, COLD MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week prior to publication of his second novel, ``The
Prodigal Spy,'' Joe Kanon opened the front door of his Manhattan
apartment, picked up a copy of The New York Times and read the
following assessment of how he makes his living:
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is colder than a Siberian winter for espionage
tales, many publishing executives and agents say, blaming the end
of the Cold War and shifts in readers' tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Berlin Wall crumbled in 1989 and the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991, writers who established themselves by exploring
the duplicitous world of spycraft have had much more difficulty
climbing the heights of The New York Times best-seller list,
occupying those rarefied levels for fewer weeks if at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of the spy novel is a hard story to read if you've
just finished writing one. ``I was a bit chagrined,'' said Kanon,
``to say the least.'' The Times story will likely hound his
upcoming publicity tour. But it's a safe bet that it won't keep
people from buying his new book.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, his previous work, ``Los Alamos,'' was a runaway
success. Published to critical acclaim, it went on to sell 850,000
copies in hardback and paper. Published in 14 countries, ``Los
Alamos'' received the 1997 Edgar Award for Best First Novel,
occupied the New York Times best-seller list for a number of weeks,
and established Kanon as both a serious and commercially successful
writer.
</P>
<P>
   More important, ``The Prodigal Spy'' is a better book _
emotionally richer and more confidently told. It is the story of a
father and son, disconnected by history and reunited by the loyalty
of love. It begins in 1950, at the height of the McCarthy era, with
a State Department officer who, it turns out, really is a spy for
the Soviet Union. He defects and disappears from his son's life.
Almost two decades later, he makes contact with his son and asks
for his help. He wants to come home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in the consequences,'' says Kanon, an old
friend of this columnist. ``It seemed to me that stories about
defectors always end with their getting on a boat or a plane. But
what happens afterwards? What about the people, the families they
leave behind. So my character, Nick, is a boy whose father defects,
one of those unintended victims for whom history itself becomes a
crime, affecting his whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the book is given over to Nick's investigation of that
crime and its consequences. ``What fascinated me,'' says Kanon,
``is how good people do the right things for supposedly the right
reasons and yet create these appalling, complicated legacies.'' As
the action moves from Washington to London to Prague and finally
back to Washington, those legacies come into ever-sharper relief.
</P>
<P>
   Kanon captures Prague one year after The Prague Spring as few
others have. The sad medley of great beauty, dashed hope, and
intense paranoia is hauntingly rendered. Kanon's portrait of J.
Edgar Hoover in the time of the Nixon presidency seems definitive.
By then, the great crime fighter had become a tyrannical
bureaucrat, clutching his files to hold his job.
</P>
<P>
   As historical events and figures combust with Kanon's imaginary
characters, the pace quickens. Most readers will guess ``whodunit''
early on, but unlike most thrillers, this foreknowledge enriches
the novel's enjoyment. One focuses not on the perpetrator, but on
those perpetrated against. The real story, the story of the father
and son, emerges from the wreckage of ideology, opportunism, and
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtless true that writers like John LeCarre and
Frederick Forsyth have ``repositioned'' themselves in the wake of
their recent commercial disappointments. LeCarre's next novel will
be published in March and takes place in the upper echelons of high
finance. George Smiley and British Intelligence have given way to
hedge-fund managers and arbitrage. Forsyth is writing a sequel to
``The Phantom of the Opera.'' The Jackal has been retired.
</P>
<P>
   But Kanon's spy novel is likely to be every bit as successful as
``Los Alamos.'' This is due, in part, to Internet technologies.
Services like Amazon.com and BarnesandNoble.com use software that
constantly analyze readers' preferences. Those who read and enjoyed
``Los Alamos'' will be informed that its author has a new book out
and that the early reviews are glowing. Those who have an interest
in the McCarthy era will likewise be alerted. The market for
Kanon's kind of fiction will be made aware of his new work in a way
that would have been impossible just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is also due, in larger measure, to Kanon's talent. Great
writers combine expansive powers of observation with keen moral
intelligence. Both are on full display in ``The Prodigal Spy.''
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
