<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REHNQUIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REHNQUIST SEEN AS STERN JUDGE OF IMPEACHMENT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Strom Thurmond made an unusual appearance
before the Supreme Court last October, arriving one Tuesday to see
a friend admitted to the bar. But it was the comportment of the
chief justice that surprised observers the most.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past chief justices, who would have acknowleged the
96-year-old South Carolina senator and former Judiciary Committee
chairman in their midst, William H. Rehnquist hardly blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to Thurmond the same few words he says to anyone
else,'' said Harvard law professor Laurence Tribe, who was in the
courtroom that day. ``He didn't crack a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, as the Senate begins impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton, Rehnquist will assume the role of overseer in
whatever form a trial takes, taking center seat in the well of the
Senate before hundreds of spectators and the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although senators and White House aides have spent the holidays
poring over his books and opinions for clues about how he might
handle the case, associates say it is his manner _ stern,
no-nonsense and businesslike _ that is more likely to make an
impact than any ideology he has outlined during his 27-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, observers have found tantalizing hints among
Rehnquist's academic thoughts about impeachment. His 1992 book,
``Grand Inquests,'' a history of the 19th century impeachments of
Justice Samuel Chase and President Andrew Johnson, vanished from
most bookstores weeks ago. Various reports have resurrected his
opinion in a 1993 case involving the impeachment of Judge Walter L.
Nixon of Mississippi, in which Rehnquist indicated his deference to
decisions of the Senate. And an old C-SPAN interview, in which he
implies impeachment should have a limited purpose, has been
replayed.
</P>
<P>
   His conservative bent has been reexamined, too. Nominated to the
bench in 1971 by President Richard Nixon, then elevated to chief
justice in 1986 by President Reagan after a heatedly partisan
confirmation, Rehnquist ``might be expected to be anti-Clinton,''
Georgetown University law professor Paul F. Rothstein said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to several colleagues and lawyers, Rehnquist would
be too concerned with his constitutional role to advance a
political agenda during a trial.
</P>
<P>
   During a trial, in fact, Rehnquist would not act as a true
judge, but instead as an overseer _ a role the vice president
assumes during all impeachment trials except that of a president.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are his parameters that of a normal trial. Rehnquist will be
constrained by an impeachment provision that lets a majority of 51
senators overrule him at any time _ meaning that serious
constitutional questions, such as whether censure could be
considered, would be in the hands of the Senate regardless of what
Rehnquist thinks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Rehnquist is expected to exert his strongest
influence over logistical matters _ from swearing in witnesses to
keeping order during testimony. And it is here that his
authoritativeness may prevail, according to people familiar with
the Rehnquist court.
</P>
<P>
   No one can predict whether Rehnquist will steer the proceedings
with ease. A trial _ any trial _ is bound to be more unwieldy than
the cases that make it to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Rehnquist has almost no trial experience. He has
sat as a trial judge just once, presiding over a 1984 civil case in
Virginia, in which the decision was reversed on appeal. Faced with
a nasty spat between political parties, that inexperience may put
him ``at a disadvantage,'' Rothstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be better if he had experience,'' Rothstein
said. ``He would be more prepared for what to expect in connection
with the actual nitty gritty of presentation of evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the 16th chief justice has cultivated a stern atmosphere
during his tenure, which is likely to keep him afloat in the Senate
chamber, other lawyers and former clerks said.
</P>
<P>
   In his private world, Rehnquist is regarded as an affable
74-year-old who relishes sports and practical jokes, wanders the
Capitol in near anonymity, and belts out Christmas carols at the
court's holiday parties every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very down-to-earth, approachable, friendly man,'' said
Charles J. Cooper, a Washington lawyer and former Rehnquist clerk.
``If you bump into him as a tourist and ask him for directions, . .
. you'd never know you were just helped by the chief.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bench is a different realm. Litigants who whisper in
court, even when no proceeding is under way, get a talking-to.
Court is in session whatever the weather _ three years ago,
Rehnquist sent federal marshals to the justices' homes to escort
them to work during a blinding snowstorm, according to Ted Cruz, a
lawyer who clerked for Rehnquist in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who speak after the red ``time up'' light are cut off,
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daniel Webster could be arguing before him when the red light
goes on, and I assure you, silence is the only thing that would
take place after that,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to be efficient and not to waste time,'' Cruz said.
``I think he will preside over the trial much in the same way he
presides over the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist apparently did not stray from that path during his
sole trial experience, involving a freedom-of-speech incident in
Colonial Beach, Va. His appearance in the court was unusual;
Supreme Court justices rarely preside over lower courts. But
Rehnquist had been invited by an acquaintance, Judge D. Dortch
Warriner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he understood his role,'' S. Keith Barker,
the plaintiff's attorney, told The Virginian-Pilot newspaper. ``He
didn't flip-flop on his rulings. That's what you want in a judge.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, however, the more convincing evidence that Rehnquist
will conduct a trial by the book is buried in his own writings,
particularly his 1992 book and his written opinion a year later in
the case of Nixon v. United States.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Grand Inquests,'' which is being reissued this month,
Rehnquist plays amateur historian in recounting the impeachment
trials of Chase and Johnson, offering piles of anecdotes from both
cases but few opinions of his own. As a result, scholars are
hesitant to compare past and present. But in broad terms,
associates say, it is fair to assume Rehnquist does not take
impeachment lightly and does not think it should be based on
politics alone.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's standards for impeachment are, apparently, high. He
writes approvingly that when the Senate acquitted Johnson, it
``added another requirement'' to those necessary for impeachment _
that the crime must be serious enough to warrant removal from
office, not just a ``technical violation of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   In a C-SPAN interview after the book was published, Rehnquist
expressed even greater discomfort with the political nature of the
Johnson impeachment, and said that had the Senate voted to remove
the president from office, ``the congressional authority to impeach
would have acted more like a sword of Damocles designed not to
fall, but to hang and threaten the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that gives us a significant clue that Justice
Rehnquist is not in favor of easy removal from office,'' Rothstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nixon opinion may offer insight into Rehnquist's
willingness to let the Senate exercise its will. In denying the
appeal of Walter Nixon, a judge impeached by the Senate for
presenting false testimony to a grand jury, Rehnquist wrote in the
majority opinion that the Supreme Court had no business interfering
in the case because it was ``non-justiciable'' _ it involved a
political question.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had been tried in front of a Senate committee, instead of
the Senate, with testimony presented over four days. Afterward, the
committee presented both sides of the case to the Senate, which
then voted by more than the two-thirds majority to remove the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon fought the impeachment, arguing that the Senate should not
be allowed to relegate the matter to a committee. But Rehnquist
refused to address the case, saying the power to make decisions on
impeachment lay with the Senate itself _ a decision Cruz said
reflected the justice's broader interpretation of when to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his 27 years on the court, a very consistent theme
throughout his opinions has been that it's not the court's role to
be deciding public policy,'' the former clerk said. ``The courts
should simply apply the law, and leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
