<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IDEAS WHOSE TIME NEVER CAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time to look forward, to 1999, but as usual, I'm looking in
the wrong direction. I've been going over a collection of column
ideas that for one reason or another didn't quite make it in 1998.
I hesitate to call it a file because the word ``file'' implies some
kind of order, and this collection is anything but orderly:
</P>
<P>
   --The personal special prosecutor. Everyone should have one of
these, a kind of a cross between Jiminy Cricket and Kenneth Starr.
Actually, many of us already have an internalized personal special
prosecutor. Mine told me to can this idea.
</P>
<P>
   --Staying together for the sake of the cats. I heard about a
married couple who made this decision. For some reason they refused
to let me write a column about them.
</P>
<P>
   --The new breed of superjournalists. Supermodels may be an
endangered species, but superjournalists are everywhere, talking
about themselves, interviewing one another. I'm not a
superjournalist, obviously. For one thing, I don't make more money
for talking about what I write than I do for writing it. Am I
bitter? Maybe. This idea never went anywhere, because I feared it
would be misconstrued by my superjournalist colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   --My secret garden. It's a secret because nobody in their right
mind would ever guess it's a garden. I didn't do this column
because writing about it would have forced me to think about it,
which might have forced me to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   --Everybody's in rehab. It's become a status symbol. People
announce, ``I've been in rehab.'' Then they stare at you, waiting
for you to ask what they've been in rehab for and did they meet
anybody famous there. So often they've been rehabbed for something
really boring, like a broken wrist, instead of some fascinating,
totally depraved addiction. Is there any affliction that isn't
rehabable? Possibly coming up with useless column ideas.
</P>
<P>
   --Pedestrian rage. We don't hear much about it, maybe because,
unlike road rage, pedestrian rage tends to be passive-aggressive.
But it can be dangerous. Pedestrians step right in front of a
moving car to prove they have the right of way, or saunter across
an intersection against the light, glaring defiantly at drivers.
When road rage meets pedestrian rage, things can get ugly, too ugly
for me, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   --The bright side of menopause. I thought and thought about this
one, mostly in the middle of the night, when I couldn't sleep.
That's one good thing about menopause. There are a million ways to
fill the time you used to spend sleeping. That may be the only good
thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   --I feel a pang of sympathy for Camilla Parker Bowles. I waited
too long to do this column. By the time I got around to it,
Camilla's approval ratings had shot up. Maybe she was in image
rehab.
</P>
<P>
   --I launch a campaign to revive popular interest in the work of
Tobias Smollett, the 18th-century social satirist. Smollett's
letter-novel, ``The Expedition of Humphry Clinker'' is ready for
Masterpiece Theater treatment. This may be a column idea whose time
will never come.
</P>
<P>
   --What do you think about when you're exercising? I asked a lot
of people this question and nearly all of them said the same thing:
food. Which is what I think about when I'm exercising. I tried to
do this one, but I kept thinking about food.
</P>
<P>
   --The New Civility. I keep hearing about the renaissance of
civility but I've seen very little of it. I suspect the new
civility is a ragged remnant of the old civility, holding on for
dear life in these uncivil times. Why belabor the obvious any more
than I have to?
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
