<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FATIGUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DISASTER HITS, HOW SHOULD THE MEDIA RESPOND? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
COMPASSION FATIGUE 
How the Media Sell Disease, Famine, War and Death 
By Susan D. Moeller. Routledge. 390 pp. Illustrated. $27.50. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Oct. 23, 1984, NBC News aired what instantly became famous
footage of Ethiopian famine victims in a segment called ``The Faces
of Death in Africa.'' With Americans finally supplied with faces to
humanize the horror of distant starvation, more than 10,000 phone
calls poured into the relief organization Save the Children in the
36 hours just after the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that only the dogged persistence of an overseas NBC
staffer convinced a reluctant network ``bored with the thought of
another African story,'' to air the piece, thus narrowly averting
another textbook case of ``compassion fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, evidence of the media's diminished attention to the
global village is rampant. According to analyst Andrew Tyndall, the
airtime devoted to stories filed by foreign correspondents at the
big three networks decreased from 4,032 minutes in 1989 to 1,991
minutes by 1995. Reporting resources are so thin that former New
York Times editor Max Frankel once surmised that ``America's
picture of the planet is painted'' by no more than a few hundred
correspondents. And a 1995 Pew Research Center study of
international news found that fully one-third of those stories are
``essentially about the United States in the world, rather than
about the world.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is exacerbated by the fact that since the end of the
Cold War _ with its white hat/black hat geopolitical chessboard _
the media have struggled to develop a new global story line.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Compassion Fatigue: How the Media Sell Disease, Famine, War
and Death,'' author Susan D. Moeller indicts the American media for
the public's numbness to tragedy, bloodshed, and pestilence around
the world. The director of Brandeis University's journalism program
argues that compassion fatigue is ``an unavoidable consequence of
the way news is now covered'' _ simplistically, sporadically, and
with conspicuous cultural bias.
</P>
<P>
   (Time for a quick quiz. When was the last time you saw an update
on the havoc wreaked by Hurricane Mitch? Have you already lost
interest in any ``collateral'' damage done by the recent US and
British bombing of Iraq?)
</P>
<P>
   In staying true to her theme of not pandering to ``the public's
short attention span,'' Moeller has written a scholarly book that
is equal parts history lesson and media criticism.b Divided into
coverage of pestilence, famine, assassination, and genocide, it's
not exactly coffee table reading unless you work for the World
Health Organization or the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The author draws important lessons from which stories make the
media cut. The 1995 Ebola epidemic _ which took relatively few
lives _ was a big story, thanks to the horrific course of the
disease and a pop culture confluence. The 1995 Dustin Hoffman movie
``Outbreak'' _ about a lethal plague _ was even used in a
``Nightline'' report as a metaphor for the Ebola outbreak in what
was then called Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the media-unfriendly, unspectacular plague that
flies under journalism's radar screen is the diarrheal disease that
kills more than 3 million children under the age of 5 each year.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Somalia contained many of the crucial dramatic
elements of newsworthiness: A starving populace, heroic relief
workers, and villainous armed thugs. When the cavalry was
dispatched and US troops arrived in December 1992, CBS's Dan
Rather, NBC's Tom Brokaw, and ABC's Ted Koppel went with them to
authenticate an important international story.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Iraq's 1988 campaign of terror against the Kurds, which
included poison gas and may have killed close to 200,000 people _
never got critical mass coverage. One problem was primarily
logistical _ limited ``access and sources.'' But another had to do
with the plot line. The Kurds were caught up in a war between two
nations, Iran and Iraq, that engendered little sympathy in this
country. ``The media like heroes and villains,'' writes Moeller.
</P>
<P>
   When Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq died in a
mysterious 1988 plane crash, even PBS's thoughtful ``MacNeil-Lehrer
NewsHour'' devoted less than 300 words to the story that night. The
Zia assassination didn't become a big story because he was, among
other things, ``a problematic'' figure for the media, one with too
spotty a record to be deemed a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1995 assassination of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, and the assassination, in 1981, of Egyptian leader Anwar
Sadat fit the media's morality play format more comfortably. The
two men, Moeller noted, quickly ``joined the immortal pantheon; the
meaning of their deaths was framed for Americans by journalists
associating them with the iconic martyred leaders of the past,''
such as President Kennedy, Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., and Mahatma
Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion of the Sadat-Rabin killings, Moeller argues that
the slain leaders were sanitized and lionized by a ``partisan''
American media that conveniently overlooked Rabin's initial
repression of the Palestinian Intifada and Sadat's heavy-handed
treatment of internal opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Even those, like me, who believe Moeller gives short shrift to
the two Mideast peacemakers may be hard pressed to dispute her
point that too much coverage is filtered through the prism of
national self-interest. ``The Americanization of events makes the
public feel the world subscribes, and must subscribe, to American
cultural icons _ and if it doesn't or can't it is not worth the
bother, because clearly the natives are unworthy or the issue or
event is,'' she claims.
</P>
<P>
   Moeller's examination of our egocentric view of world events is
provocative. But her implication that the first law of nature
should not drive interest in foreign crises _ that news should not
first respond to threats that may potentially affect us _ is asking
an awful lot of human nature. And it is when ``Compassion Fatigue''
sometimes creeps from shrewd analysis to broad media hectoring that
it is least persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Her insistence that coverage of the African famine became
distorted by celebrity when ``reporters became caught up in the
thrill of watching Mick Jagger and Tina Turner cavort on stage''
during the Live Aid benefit seems gratuitiously niggling. Charging
that ``news shouldn't be marketed as a product . . . Yet news
packaged by the mega-conglomerates tends toward the familiar,'' is
more sloganeering than insightful.
</P>
<P>
   Her ultimate conclusion that ``the solution is for the media
business to get back to the business of reporting all the news, all
the time,'' illustrates media criticism's classic dilemma. It's
easier to diagnose the problem than to cure it.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``Compassion Fatigue'' excels is in its careful dissection
of the institutional, philosophical, and logistical obstacles that
prevent the media from effectively monitoring this planet.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, as Moeller writes, that with the broadcast of the
1984 Ethiopian famine footage, ``years of apathy about starving
Africans were swept away.'' What is also true is that journalism's
crisis mode of storytelling often proves too little too late. By
the time NBC showed the film that elicited such a charitable
outpouring, one relief official noted, ``Most of the people who
were at risk of dying had already died.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz covers journalism and the media for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
