<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SMOKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CALIFORNIA TAX MAY HELP SMOKERS TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCSICO _ Smokers who hope to kick the habit as part of
their New Year's resolutions have added incentive this year:
California's new 50-cents-a-pack cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   The tax, along with a 45-cent price hike tobacco companies are
levying to cover the cost of settling the national tobacco lawsuit,
raises the price of a pack of cigarettes in California to more than
$4 at some grocery stores, the third-highest price in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started smoking, they were just a quarter a
pack,'' said 44-year-old Steve Bower, who was buying cigarettes at
the Cigarettes Cheaper store in Daly City. He began smoking when he
was 11. ``I was going to try quitting and now that extra 50 cents
gives me more incentive,'' he said. ``I'll be saving a lot of
money. Two packs a day is $8, times 30 is $240 a month, multiply by
12, that's a trip to Hawaii every year.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the dozens of smokers streaming into the store on the
final days of 1998 are any indication, addiction could prove more
powerful than price. This week, one committed customer bought
$7,000 _ or 12 cases _ worth of cigarettes. Others said they were
quitting, even as they bought packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' said Karen, holding up a pack of Marlboro
menthols. ``I've already bought the patch and am going to put it on
New Year's Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Proposition 10, which boosted the state's cigarette tax
from 37 cents to 87 cents per pack, was intended to fund child care
programs, advocates are hoping it also will reduce the percentage
of Californians who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Already only 17 percent of Californians smoke _ the
second-lowest rate after Utah _ compared with 23 percent
nationally, according to the national Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention. And certainly a pack-a-day habit is pricier in the
long run than a $29.99 pack of Nicoderm patches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's unclear whether high cost will deter longtime
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Franklin, a health educator for Kaiser Permanente in San
Rafael, said registration for Kaiser's six-week stop-smoking
program is normal for this time of year: ``We're just seeing the
typical New Year's resolution stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   She suspects the tax hike will have its greatest deterrent on
teenagers or other young smokers who don't have a lot of money.
That alone could be a significant accomplishment. Research shows
that people who don't smoke as teens are less likely to smoke in
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanton Glantz, a University of California at San Francisco
professor and one of the nation's leading anti-tobacco crusaders,
said the price hike is certain to prod thousands of Californians to
quit smoking over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very good evidence from all over the world that when
you increase the price of cigarettes 10 percent you get a 4 percent
drop in consumption,'' said Glantz. ``It will take a while to
happen, but you will probably see a 15 percent drop in cigarette
consumption in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Glantz noted that the number of smokers in California declined
after 1988, when voters passed Prop. 99, which boosted the 10-cent
tax on cigarettes to 35 cents, to fund the state's aggressive
anti-tobacco campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people still do it and some people will continue to do
it, but the message in California is very, very clear that smoking
isn't acceptable anymore,'' said Glantz.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco analyst Gary Black also predicts a significant drop in
consumption _ between 10 and 12 percent. But he said the volume of
tobacco sold in the state could drop even more as consumers look to
mail-order houses, the Internet, neighboring states and the black
market to buy cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers innovate. They'll go searching for cheaper
cigarettes,'' said Black, who works with Sanford C. Bernstein and
Co., a New York investment management firm. ``People who live in
(California) border towns will cross over to Nevada.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette discounters in the state have been cashing in on the
tax hike for months.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers began stocking up at Cigarettes Cheaper stores in
November shortly after manufacturers raised prices to pay for the
states' tobacco lawsuit and voters passed Prop. 10 by a narrow,
13,000-vote margin.
</P>
<P>
   The number of smokers patronizing Cigarettes Cheaper stores,
which sell Marlboros for $1.99, or $1.50 less than Safeway, has
jumped 30 percent since late November, according to Ned Roscoe,
vice president of the chain. To meet demand, the company tripled
the inventory in its 220 California stores during the week
preceding New Year's. The company plans to open 50 more stores in
the state this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Parillo, manager of the Cigarettes Cheaper store located in
the Westlake Shopping Center in Daly City, estimates he sold an
average of 1,200 cartons a day in the final days of December, up
from a norm of 300 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite daily deliveries for the final week of the year, the
store, which normally is restocked just twice a week, ran out of
Marlboro hard packs _ the most popular brand _ several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Delfino, who described herself as a social smoker, normally
buys just a pack, but took home a carton of Truex to save $5 in the
New Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to quit but a bargain is a bargain,'' said Delfino.
``Aren't we awful? It's like a run on the store.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few committed smokers are taking the high cost seriously.
Eighty-five-year-old Lina Banideras, who smoked for 35 years, quit
the day after Christmas in anticipation of the new tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cost too much,'' said Banideras, who smoked about a
half-pack a day. ``I was thinking that it would be better for my
health and this just gave me the (extra incentive) I needed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
