<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE MARKETING GIMMICKS A TRIAL FOR MANY CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you sense your annual magazine subscriptions aren't lasting
their full 12 months, you may have good reason.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of one week, we received complaints from two
readers who felt short-changed by industry practices to attract new
subscribers. One has to do with back-dating the starting point of
an annual subscription and the other with the use of the word
``free'' to describe a trial issue of a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   These marketing gimmicks are not new this year, but industry
specialists say they are being practiced more widely as the highly
competitive publishing world vies for new customers.
</P>
<P>
   While questionable magazine marketing tactics often focus on
sweepstakes contests and high-pressure telemarketing pitches, these
recent cases illustrate the need to check the accuracy of your
magazine expiration dates. These dates are posted usually, though
not always, on the magazine's mailing labels.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the case of a reader, who signed up for a
year's worth of Elle, a women's fashion magazine, and expected to
get her first issue sometime in November. What came in November was
not one, but three issues. Within 10 days, she got the issues for
October and November and the newly released December issue.
</P>
<P>
   On the mailing label, her assigned expiration date was September
1999.
</P>
<P>
   When we called the magazine about this problem, Dave Leckey,
vice president of circulation at Hachette Filipacchi Magazine,
publisher of Elle, Women's Day, George, Home and other magazines,
referred to it as ``back-starting.'' He said it is done sometimes
when the company has excess copies of a particular issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back-starting is a way for a magazine to be able to manage its
costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, if a customer isn't happy about receiving the
outdated issues, the company will always accede to such complaints.
In the case of the woman subscriber, he said Elle would be happy to
change the expiration date to November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Industry specialists say a publisher sending old issues is a way
for them to post an earlier renewal date so as to anticipate new
revenue or justify inflated circulation figures from previous
months.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Grossman of Chappaqua, N.Y., the author of Grossman and
Circulation, follows the promotional practices of about 500
magazines. He said sending customers outdated issues is clearly a
problem. ``It's not very good customer relations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another questionable marketing practice, another reader
points out that publishers often depict as ``free'' a trial offer
of a magazine sent to your home. But he found it's only free if you
choose not to subscribe. If you decide to sign up, the first issue
is counted in the year's allotment.
</P>
<P>
   In this common marketing strategy known as a ``soft offer,'' the
publisher sends consumers a postcard in which they are invited to
receive a ``free issue'' to check out the product. By marking yes
and sending the card back, the consumer will get an issue, and soon
thereafter, a bill for a year's subscription.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't want the magazine, they can send the invoice back
marking ``cancel'' and they are not obligated to pay for the first
issue. But if they want to continue receiving the magazine, they
will pay for the so-called ``free'' issue as part of their
year-long subscription.
</P>
<P>
   To secure a genuinely free issue, the reader has this solution:
``I mark cancel on the bill, then subcribe with one of the cards
that are invariably included in the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cargill, vice president of the New England Direct
Marketing Association, described soft-offer tactics as ``fair, but
borderline.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be confusing to say the trial issue is a ``free
issue,'' Cargill said, most ethical magazine publishers make the
terms clear somewhere on the post card. A monthly magazine at $1 an
issue, for example, would state that if the customer likes the
first issue, he or she agrees to pay $12 for 11 more issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Audit Bureau of Circulation, which tracks the publishing
industry, also shed some light on one reason publishers are eager
to count as paid that first free-trial issue. Teresa Baird,
director of periodical field auditing, said a truly free issue
cannot be counted toward that month's circulation.
</P>
<P>
   And paid circulation figures are key numbers that advertisers
want to see when deciding whether to buy space.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say buyers should protect themselves by
reading the language of any magazine promotion and avoiding
third-party dealings when purchasing subscriptions. He also said
buyers should stay alert to the posted expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't pay attention to the expiration dates on
the mailing labels, and they should,'' said Howard Shapiro, a
spokesman for the Federal Trade Commission in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First USA checks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Credit card company First USA recently sent Deirdre Cummings,
consumer program director for the Massachusetts Public Interest
Research Group, a sales pitch that sounded great until she closely
studied the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   First USA offered her checks that she could use to pay off
balances on other credit cards or for anything else she wanted. On
the borrowed money, she would pay a low 3.9 percent annual
percentage rate of interest until March 1. After that, she would
pay her regular credit card rate.
</P>
<P>
   Making the offer more appealing, the bank included a chart
showing her savings if she used the checks to pay off balances on
other credit cards. The savings ranged from $34 on a $1,000
Discover card balance to $164 on a $5,000 MBNA card balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say goodbye to high interest rates right now. Grab a pen,
write a check and cash in on the savings,'' First USA president
Randy Christofferson said in his letter to Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   But a very different picture emerged in the fine print. First,
the savings claims were based on a three-month borrowing period.
Yet Cummings had received her First USA letter on Dec. 21, which
means only a little more than two months were left before the March
1 ending date.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the savings projections did not include a transaction
finance charge of the greater of $5 or 3 percent of the transaction
amount. Adding in that fine-print fee eliminates the savings and in
most cases causes the First USA ``deal'' to actually cost more.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a Discover card with a 17.49 percent APR. First USA
cited savings of $34 on a $1,000 balance carried for three months.
But adding in the transaction charge of 3 percent brings the
savings down to $4. And if the borrowing period is lowered to two
months, the First USA ``deal'' ends up costing $7 more. With a
one-month borrowing period, the extra cost is $19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like a very good deal to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wireless help. If you're shopping for wireless service, you
might find helpful information in a new web site put out by
Wireless Dimension. The company (at www.wirelessdimension.com)
presents itself as a free, impartial and reliable service to help
consumers in the top 10 US cities research wireless products,
identify a local authorized dealer or buy online.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
