<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-SAFRICA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     01-04 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-SAFRICA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAPETOWN, South Africa: ... the past.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some forms of oppression have outlived apartheid. Mark Coetzee,
an artist and owner of the tiny Mark Coetzee Fine Art Cabinet in
Cape Town, says his last three shows have been officially banned _
and they all took place after the new government was installed.
South Africa's equivalent of Mapplethorpe, Coetzee uses openly,
even flamboyantly, gay imagery; some attacks on him have come from
fundamentalist Christians. ``Artists who work outside the
acceptable here are literally starved to death,'' he says. The show
I saw in his gallery was ``Frontier Erotics,'' Clive van den Berg's
miniatures of men loving men, wistful little paintings that deal
with one segment of a society still deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the posh Linda Goodman Gallery in Rosebank, an upscale
Johannesburg suburb that is as close as South Africa comes to
Beverly Hills, that I saw Segogela's work, and that of the
Makhubele family, who have illustrated the history of South Africa
in large cloth hangings studded with beads and safety pins. The
pins have an unexpected, twinkling magic. Goodman is the leading
contemporary dealer in South Africa, in business for 32 years, with
a large European and American clientele. She's shown black artists
all along. During apartheid, blacks weren't allowed to drink
liquor. They were allowed to serve it, though, so if police turned
up at Goodman Gallery openings, black artists being feted instantly
turned into waiters.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman's gallery has its own private parking lot. The crime,
chaos, and corruption of life in South Africa boil down, on a
day-to-day level, to problems like parking. Few whites will venture
to the Market Theatre and Gallery complex in central Johannesburg,
despite the existence of an adjacent parking lot that is floodlit
and free _ except for the 20 cents or so you're expected to tip the
guy loitering next to your car, so he'll guard it instead of
stealing it.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has no museum dedicated to contemporary or modern
art; it publishes no art magazines; it has few committed collectors
of 20th-century work. Since it's largely overlooked, art is a
bargain, relatively speaking. The $83,000 a painting by Irma Stern
recently fetched at auction was not only the record price for
Stern, an expressionist painter who died in 1966 and is little
known outside South Africa. It is also the auction record for a
work by any South African.
</P>
<P>
   But since the fall of apartheid and the elections that swept
Mandela into office, South African art has generated huge interest
_ and a slew of shows _ in Europe and America. Probably the
best-known South African artist on the international scene is
William Kentridge, who was one of the stars of last summer's
``Documenta.'' Kentridge's drawings and films are allegories of
apartheid, of victims and victimizers. He's the subject of a
Boston-area show opening Jan. 15 at MIT's List Center for the
Visual Arts. ``William Kentridge: Weighing . . . and Wanting'' is
centered on Kentridge's fictional protagonist Soho Eckstein, a
white industrialist creep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our art wasn't up to much,'' says Marilyn Martin, ``the
excitement that started with the end of apartheid would have
dissipated by now.'' Martin, who has directed the gallery for nine
years, is a figure of courage and controversy in the small world of
South African art. When she arrived, the gallery's 1930s
neoclassical building was filled with European art. ``We have vast
collections of hunting and sporting pictures,'' she says drily. And
cows. In one room, there's a lineup of mediocre European cow
paintings, an installation that's hard not to read as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has acquired contemporary South African art aggressively
_ even though dealers say she's sometimes unable to pay for it.
She's worked at changing stereotypes. ``Black artists were supposed
to do linocuts,'' she says. ``But we're trying not to have a niche
for `black art.' '' Not a figurative niche, anyway. She's put black
art in literal ones: The niches on the National Gallery's facade,
where you might expect to see marble busts, are instead filled with
vivid Ndebele designs.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're inside the gallery, what you see in the grand hall
that is the most prominent place in the museum is contemporary
South African art, by artists of all races. Among the most
impressive works is the 1979 ``Triptych: Interrogators,'' by Paul
Stopforth, who moved to Boston a decade ago, after Kim Berman, who
had been his student at the University of Witwatersrand in
Johannesburg, helped to arrange an artist-in-residency post for him
at Tufts University. He never went back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's work is some of the finest political art produced
anywhere,'' Martin says. ``It's a pity he left.'' Stopforth
disagrees. He left ``because I thought things would never change,''
he says. ``Living there was a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The interrogators in ``Triptych'' are the jailers of Stephen
Biko, whose death in detention made him one of apartheid's most
famous martyrs. Stopforth slices the interrogators' faces, so you
see only eyes to mouth, the extreme close-up making their snarling
expressions all the more frightening. Floating beside the faces is
an empty chair, a stand-in for Biko. The chill palette of gray and
black suggests both newspapers and fingerprinting. Stopforth
anticipated by 20 years what artists are doing now in response to
the Truth commission _ and he did it at a time when his art earned
him death threats.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone I speak to about Stopforth tells me he was a towering
figure in the anti-apartheid movement; everyone wishes he hadn't
left, or that he'd return. He wishes neither.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists like Kim have sacrificed their own work for a greater
good,'' he says. ``If I'd stayed I might have found myself engaged
more with education than with my art.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, that art has become more personal and less political.
Included in his most recent show was a jaunty little figure called
``Emigre,'' who kicks up one leg, ready to go. For those who know
Stopforth's history, it's impossible not to see this figure as the
artist himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want a blindfolded lady and Roman columns,'' Albie
Sachs says, ``or the idea that the law is handed down from on
high.'' So when it came time to choose a logo for the new
Constitutional Court, the justices settled on a tree, because
``traditionally, that's where African justice took place _ under a
tree,'' Sachs says. This one comforts rather than threatens, its
large canopy spreading hospitably.
</P>
<P>
   The room where the justices deliberate is filled with
contemporary portraits. ``We are being watched by the faces of our
country,'' Sachs says, ``faces of all kinds.'' (Not by all kinds of
artists, though: They're all by women, a coincidence that pleases
Sachs, an outspoken feminist.)
</P>
<P>
   We walk over to the site where the new courthouse will be built,
a site occupied by the Old Fort, which has the distinction of being
the world's only jail where both Nelson Mandela and Mahatma Gandhi
were imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitutional Courthouse, symbol of the country's new
liberty and law, will be built on the site of the symbol of its
past oppression. Parts of the prison complex will remain, with
glass between new building and old, connecting past humiliation
with present hope.
</P>
<P>
   We walk near the ramparts, where twin staircases _ one for
whites, the other for blacks _ offer a cold reminder of the past.
``Even entering jail, people had to be separated by race,'' Sachs
says. He envisions kids climbing on the ramparts, the prison turned
playground. ``I think like a 7 year old,'' says the judge who is an
extremely youthful 63. ``On a mature day. Otherwise, it's 6.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the army still occupies this grim compound. Sachs wants
to take me inside. The gate is padlocked. The fortress once nearly
impossible to escape is now impossible to enter. Sachs asks a
caretaker inside to let us in. He says he can't, not even for a
judge; it's against his orders. ``Some day,'' Sachs says firmly,
``the constitution in this country will be stronger than the
military. But we're not there yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
