<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-2ND     01-04 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-COLLEGES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... federal aid.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting a premium on faithfulness might mean sacrificing
academic quality in hiring, and even if it doesn't, lawyers say
discrimination laws would look unkindly at an institution that
creates the impression that it turns down better-qualified
applicants because they are not faithful Catholics. And the bishops
left open the definition of faithful, which colleges say leaves
them open to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it mean that someone who's divorced is not faithful? That
someone practicing birth control is not faithful? And how will we
know?'' asked Reese. ``And then you get into questions of whether
to hire someone who the bishop doesn't approve. If you do hire
them, you're in trouble with the bishops, if you don't hire them,
you're in trouble with the (faculty unions). With the propensity of
faculty to sue, I would be very concerned if I was a bishop or a
school, because clearly this is going to result in a lot of
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Academics worry that requiring theology professors to get a
mandate from the bishops would create the sense that there was a
holier echelon on campus, relegating non-theology professors and
non-Catholics to second-class citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very subtle, but when you work side by side with someone,
these things matter,'' said the Rev. Ladislas Orsy, a law professor
at Georgetown University and a specialist in church law. ``Rightly
or wrongly, there is extreme sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The church would open itself up to liability for students
injured on school grounds, and to accusations of censorship. And
Orsy adds that schools would lose accreditation, because agencies
that grant it insist on institutional autonomy, and question
non-academic intrusions on key decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Burling, BC university counsel from 1969 to 1994 and now
an education lawyer at Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot, said even past bond
issues and land transfers could become null, because the lay boards
of trustees did not have the authority to make transactions with
what would be ruled church property.
</P>
<P>
   With so many thorns, college presidents say they are not sure
trustees could be persuaded to serve, and without them the schools
would lose the perspective that has helped bring efficiency and
professionalism to many.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``ex corde'' would return the schools to the
margins, many Catholic academics fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great achievements of Catholic higher education is
becoming a key player in the mainstream of American higher
education,'' said Charles L. Currie, head of the American
Association of Jesuit Colleges and Universities. ``They've only
been able to do that by becoming part of the culture of
institutional autonomy, academic freedom, and freedom of
expression. If the church wants to be an institution within that
culture, it has to respect its traditions. You don't go to Russia
to speak Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean,'' he added, ``that every part of the
culture is fine. But you're more effective if you're within the
system than if you're standing outside. One of the great abilities
of the church is its ability to speak to the culture, but if it's
going to be standoffish, it's going to be less effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Their opposition to ``ex corde,'' college officials say, hardly
means they aren't dedicated to the Catholic ideal. In fact, many
Catholic administrators express almost a sense of insult at the
proposal, that the bishops could fail to see how schools have been
working to strengthen their religious identity. Several schools
have commissions on ensuring the Catholic tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that so many schools began as religious institutions
and became secularized should give us pause, because there's
nothing to say that won't happen to Catholic institutions as
well,'' said the Rev. Joseph A. O'Hare, president of Fordham
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think imposing this is the way to go,'' he said.
``It will alienate the faculty and prevent us from hiring the kind
of faculty we want, who will support academic excellence and the
Catholic nature. Imposing any kind of loyalty oath will only deter
people from working here. There are plenty of faithful Catholics
who will say that's no part of an academic institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Heft, chancellor of the University of Dayton and
head of a project on hiring for the Association of Catholic
Colleges and Universities, said most schools don't know what
proportion of the faculty is Catholic, fearing they might violate
laws against discrimination to even ask.
</P>
<P>
   He and others say it's a mistake to assume that only Catholic
professors can support the mission of a Catholic school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen plenty of Catholic professors who don't invest as
much as a Jew or a Protestant,'' said Leahy. ``Faithful Catholics
might be a nice idea, but what you want is someone who identifies
with what you're trying to do with the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidents will meet in various formations next month to
plan how to lobby the Vatican and bishops against the proposal.
Some say they hope to appeal to the Vatican's new secretariat of
education, Joseph Pittau, who is familiar with US higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Some close to the bishops say there is sympathy among them to
the schools' concerns. Given that, they say, the bishops may vote
to reject the proposal, which would at least allow them to report
to the Vatican that they had tried and suggest that it look again
at what they approved so overwhelmingly in 1996. Another option is
to vote to continue studying it, essentially shelving it until
there is a new pope.
</P>
<P>
   But these people add that the schools have to understand the
pressure on the bishops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's naive to see this as a battle between the bishops and the
presidents,'' said Monika Hellwig, a non-voting member of the
bishops committee on ``ex corde'' and executive director of the
Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities. ``The bishops
did what the Vatican asked them to do. Tenure, trustees,
accreditation. All that is irrelevant to the Vatican.''
</P>
</TEXT>
