<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-WATTS-BOS &LR;      01-04 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-WATTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATTS'S POWER TO BE TESTED AS HE STANDS ALONE IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ J.C. Watts Jr. cannot be compared to anyone in the
106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma representative will be the only black Republican in
the House or Senate, and when he is sworn in this week, he will be
the only black in the House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Watts stands alone on the ideological spectrum, as an
African-American who carries the civil rights struggle in one hand
and his own brand of born-again, conservative politics in the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want you to be beholden to them, and they don't want
you to be independent,'' said the former star quarterback. ``Many
in the black community believe you have to think and act a certain
way. But I'm 41 years old, and I can think for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   White liberals, black liberals, and even some black
conservatives distrust Watts's political motives, his benefactors,
and his stellar rise _ fueled by the Gingrich Revolution _ that
arguably has made him in four years one of the most powerful
African-Americans in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For all the buzz on Watts, however, serious questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Will this Baptist minister with a gift for gab use his new bully
pulpit as Republican Conference chairman to remake his party into a
``big tent,'' robbing the Democratic Party of its minority mantle
and its hold on votes that proved so crucial in the last election?
</P>
<P>
   And, if Watts succeeds in bringing more blacks into the
Republican fold, can he solidify his power and go on to a possible
run for higher office? (The second spot on the presidential ticket
is often mentioned.)
</P>
<P>
   Or will his brand of politics prove to be too polarizing? And
will personal baggage haunt his future on a national stage?
</P>
<P>
   Watts grew up in the small town of Eufaula, Okla., poor and on
``the wrong side of the tracks.'' An uncle, Wade, was president of
the NAACP Oklahoma chapter and a legendary figure who, Watts said,
converted a local grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan to Christianity
and who, with Watts's father, pushed the state to integrate.
</P>
<P>
   Watts and his cousin were the first African-Americans in his
elementary school, and it was in those early years he remembered
learning the art of politics _ and the politics of turning the
other cheek.
</P>
<P>
   At a football game in Locust Grove, Watts remembered his family
sitting with a recruiter who had come to watch him as quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The local district attorney walked up to the family and, seeing
the recruiter, proudly pointed to Watts and said, ``That's our
nigger.'' No one said or did anything because the lawyer, despite
his racist language, was sympathetic _ and useful _ to the civil
rights cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.C. always had a gift,'' said Barry Switzer, his football
coach at the University of Oklahoma. ``He was very articulate and
had an air of confidence even as a youngster. He commanded respect
and was an outstanding role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Switzer remembered how Watts, twice named most valuable player
in the Orange Bowl, spoke in church before a game one Sunday. The
Florida State coach, who was present, told his team, ``If that guy
quarterbacks as well as he preaches, we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   An ordained minister and father of five, Watts knows how to
reach his audience. He has an earthy manner when he speaks, and a
charismatic spark. He knows when to roll out his metaphors and when
to repeat a phrase so it sticks. In short, he sounds home-spun,
making a passionate plug for family values without sounding like
the politician preacher he is.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Secretary of State Tom Cole described Watts in the way
people routinely do: as one of the most talented communicators of
his generation. This, in part, explains why Republicans tapped
Watts last year to give the party's response to President Clinton's
State of the Union speech, and why he was elected conference chair
this year, where his job will be crafting and conveying the GOP
message.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches extol such planks of the Republican agenda as lower
taxes, welfare reform, and school vouchers _ all of which are
anathema to mainstream black interests, said Glenn Loury, director
of Boston University's Institute on Race and Social Division.
</P>
<P>
   Watts presents himself as a role model in and out of church, but
this squeaky-clean image does not wash with all of his
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charge, as did Ben Odom, his opponent in the 1998 race,
that Watts is a Bible-thumper who preaches personal responsibility
and family values when his own house is not in order.
</P>
<P>
   Watts piled up a mountain of unpaid debts _ and unpaid taxes _
which resulted in property foreclosures and lawsuits, the result,
he said, of being in the oil business in the late '80s when prices
plunged.
</P>
<P>
   When he was an energy commissioner regulating the oil industry,
Watts was the object of an FBI corruption probe for receiving cash
from the industry he regulated. He was never charged.
</P>
<P>
   He also fathered a baby out of wedlock when he was in high
school. His Uncle Wade raised the child.
</P>
<P>
   Watts admitted to his mistakes, but insisted he always tried to
do right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made dumb choices and I'll make more, but a life can't
always be measured by the dumb choices made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he said, he paid off his creditors rather than
declare bankruptcy, and helped raise the child.
</P>
<P>
   As for the corruption probe, he said, ``There was nothing
illegal, unethical or immoral about taking money from those you
regulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Watts's constituents reelected him with
more than 60 percent of the vote in a majority Democratic district.
</P>
<P>
   Home, Watts said, is where he was taught to be a conservative
before he understood what the word meant. There he learned hard
work and respect for all. There were no victims in his family, he
said, only God guiding people who worked toward their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   That is his answer to critics who cannot fathom how a man who
grew up in the cradle of the civil rights movement could become the
poster child for the Republican Party _ and to those who contend
that Watts is the tool of a right-wing leadership looking for an
African-American to blunt criticism that the party is elitist and
hostile to minority interests.
</P>
<P>
   Watts comes from the Bible Belt and agrees, as do many of his
constituents, with the Christian Coalition agenda. His voting
rating from the group is 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Watts does not always toe the party line. He has voted to
reduce crack cocaine sentencing, and has staked out a position on
affirmative action that makes neither conservative Republicans nor
liberal blacks happy.
</P>
<P>
   Watts's iconoclastic approach may earn him some respect on both
sides of the aisle, but that respect is mixed with suspicion and
even hostility when one considers that he is the only
African-American who has refused to join the Congressional Black
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ``What J.C. has done is taken the language of the civil rights
movement and massaged it into conservatism which, upon closer
analysis, is tainted,'' said Representative Jesse Jackson Jr.,
Democrat of Illinois. ``And it has long-term implications for
undermining progress on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Watts has to do more to reach out to black
Americans than occupy a public post. But he, like others, is trying
to reserve judgment until he sees what, if anything, Watts does for
minority interests once he is in the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well worth watching because he'll be an important
political player well into the 21st century,'' said Cole, the
Oklahoma secretary of state. ``He's got star quality and wants to
play on a bigger stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his future, Watts demurred, saying, ``I can walk
away from this any time. I don't need congressman in front of my
name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-ANALYSIS-B     01-04 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUCIAL TEST OF WELFARE REFORM BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Massachusetts reaches a crucial midpoint in its
welfare reform experiment, the figures and facts suggest two
things.
</P>
<P>
   First, phase one of the law has worked better than many
expected. Second, notwithstanding that success, the hardest part
has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as state Senator Therese Murray, chairwoman of the Human
Services Committee, puts it: ``So far I think the law has worked _
but I have a lot of qualms about what lies ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the good news. Despite widespread predictions of
disaster, the welfare law has made significant strides at reducing
the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't worked perfectly or without some pain and
unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   The recent Suffolk Superior Court ruling that the state acted
unreasonably in cutting cash benefits to as many as 6,000 families
who had applied for disability exemptions from the new law
demonstrates that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, so far, the overall figures tell an unmistakable story.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: In February 1995, when Governor William F. Weld
signed the welfare law, Massachusetts had 102,993 families on the
Aid to Families with Dependent Children rolls. By December of this
year, the caseload for what's now called Transitional Aid to
Families with Dependent Children was 58,961, a decline of about 43
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Claire McIntire, commissioner of the Department of Transitional
Assistance, offers this evidence in support of the new law: Of the
original 41,000 people subject to a benefits cutoff after two years
on the rolls, 36,000 left before the deadline came.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that people are leaving welfare
to go to work in numbers that was not happening prior to welfare
reform,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say policy makers are simply claiming credit for the
work of a booming economy _ and there's little doubt that a rising
tide has lifted many recipients into private sector jobs. A study
by the Pioneer Institute attributes 65 percent of the caseload
decline to the economy, and one-third to welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   But that's still an impressive achievement, says Charles
Chieppo, spokesman for the market-oriented thinktank. ``We have
heard a whole lot of talk about what a disaster the law has been,
but the initial indications are that it is working pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's even more impressive when you consider that even during the
Massachusetts Miracle of the mid-1980s, the AFDC rolls were never
below 83,000 families.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the talk of draconian measures, the truly tough
strictures are only now starting to take effect, as the Department
of Transitional Assistance terminates benefits for those who have
been on the welfare rolls for 24 consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
   That means that those who have left the rolls over the last
several years have, for the most part, received only a slight
nudge, and not a shove. The main change has been the imposition of
a 20-hour-a-week work requirement as a condition of receiving
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Workfare, as that policy is called, was once an oppositional
rallying cry of the welfare rights movement. Indeed, when Governor
Michael S. Dukakis proposed a modest workfare program for welfare
(itals)fathers(unitals) during his first term, it helped antagonize
the Democratic left. The experience helped lead Dukakis to label
welfare ``the Middle East of domestic policy.'' In his second term,
he chose a voluntary welfare policy.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1995, after years of seemingly intractable rolls, the
political mood had changed dramatically. Democratic lawmakers and a
Republican administration agreed the time had come to impose both a
work requirement and a time limit of two years on the rolls in any
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The big question about the work requirement has been whether the
state should allow recipients to let education or training courses
count against it. Advocates say that would help recipients land
better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the state's work-first approach say the most
effective training is imparted on the job, and thus the most
important step toward a career is helping recipients land their
first job.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides can point to studies that support their view. But
either way, that work requirement only applies to about 17 percent
of the caseload _ able-bodied recipients with school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   So far, three snapshot tracking studies DTA has done of those
who have left the rolls before the deadline show encouraging
developments in most cases: 50.3 percent did so because of higher
earnings, while 10.6 percent did so because of unearned income,
generally child support; 4 percent said an absent parent had
returned, and 1 percent reported higher assets. Eleven percent,
meanwhile, had moved out of state, while another 8.3 percent no
longer had eligible children.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the data support the stereotype of a population of
long-term welfare dependents. Only 12.4 percent of the AFDC
caseload, or 5,103 families, have received a welfare check
continuously for two years.
</P>
<P>
   But it's that group that may prove the toughest challenge for
the state's new law. Of that cohort, 2,800 have appealed for a
continuation of benefits; the DTA has sent termination notices to
another 2,233 so far.
</P>
<P>
   It's those people _ and the approximately 1,000 new recipients
who could hit the deadline each month _ whom advocates worry most
about. Some familiar with the caseload say a certain percentage of
recipients may simply be unemployable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that 20 to 25 percent of the people on welfare are
not going to be able to make it in the job market,'' said Phil
Johnston, who has served as both regional administrator of the
federal Department of Health and Human Services and state secretary
of Human Services. ``They are border-line retarded, they have
serious substance abuse problems, they have mental illness, they
are battered women whose emotional stability has been destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say what happens with the time-limited group will tell
the ultimate story about the success or failure of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what will happen to them,'' said Deborah Harris,
staff attorney for the Massachusetts Law Reform Institute.
``Experience tells us that first they exhaust their own network of
family and friends, then they turn to the shelters, and then
perhaps to the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Murray and Commissioner McIntire both say they think the
state has built in enough exemptions, supports, monitoring, and
second chances into the system that that is unlikely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   But both know that despite its initial success, what happens now
that the cutoffs have started will truly test welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned that their children are well and being
taken care of,'' said Murray. ``And that's why we have to stay on
top of this whole thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
