<HEADLINE>
AFTER WARY START, LASER EYE SURGERY BOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For their entire 30 years of married life, Fred and Kristie
Carter have worn glasses _ and hated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get perspiration on them when I work out, they fog up in
the wintertime. I hate having to buy new ones, and the last ones I
got didn't do a good job,'' complains Fred, a designer of Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, the nearsighted couple drove into Boston and
underwent laser vision correction, one after the other, in a
20-minute procedure called LASIK. Each had the surgery in one eye
and both plan to have the other eye treated in a few weeks. Once
both eyes have been treated, they hope to be free from glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Laser vision correction is a form of refractive surgery _
reshaping the cornea, the clear tissue that covers the front of the
eye, so that an image is focused sharply on the back of the eye. An
older technique, radial keratotomy, required making slits deep into
the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   The Carters had LASIK, a relatively new form of laser surgery
that's quickly becoming the standard. Sometimes called ``flap and
zap,'' LASIK calls for a skilled surgeon who makes an incision in
the cornea and folds back a flap of tissue, so that a laser can
sculpt a new shape in the underlying cornea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very psyched about this,'' said Kristie, a software
engineer as she sat waiting her turn at the Massachusetts Eye and
Ear Infirmary's laser center. ``It's something I've wanted for a
very, very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   People like the Carters are fueling the accelerating bandwagon
of laser vision correction, which rolled out with Food and Drug
Administration approval in 1995 of one type of laser surgery called
PRK, but was slow to be widely embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with patient satisfaction spreading by word-of-mouth and
the reassuring results of scientific studies, the number of laser
procedures has been doubling in the United States _ 100,000 in
1996, 230,000 in 1997 and an estimated 400,000 or more in 1998,
according to Irving Arons, director of Spectrum Consulting, which
follows the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of patients are extremely happy,'' says Dr.
Dmitri Azar a corneal surgeon at Mass Eye and Ear who performed
LASIK on the Carters. ``But not everyone gets a perfect outcome,
and if patients have unrealistic expectations'' they shouldn't do
it.
</P>
<P>
   LASIK is so new that is has not been approved by the FDA, and
the long-term effects are not known. Azar says there is more
concern about LASIK in people with very severe myopia, because more
corneal tissue has to be removed, potentially weakening the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   The price _ ranging from about $1,800 to $2,500 per eye,
depending in part on the type of surgery _ remains an obstacle for
many people. The Carters' case was unusual: Her company's insurance
paid for both of them to undergo treatment. Most policies don't
cover it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, eye lasers have become big business. Large chains
of laser centers have opened across the country. Ophthalmologists
are lining up to learn the procedures. Newspapers, radio, and the
the internet carry ads and infomercials. Yet it appears that this
market-driven medical procedure is being carried out ethically and
with few disappointed consumers so far.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says Azar at Mass Eye and Ear, ``if you are having no
problems with contact lenses or glasses and are not dissatisfied
with your present situation,'' it's pointless to take any risk at
all by having laser surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Risks of LASIK and similar procedures include infection,
worsened vision, glare or haloes around lights at night, and even
blindness. But specialists say these risks are very low _ less than
1 percent for infection _ and almost all these problems either go
away or can be cured.
</P>
<P>
   For the Carters, who had researched the procedures thoroughly,
the small risks were acceptable. In interviews the day after their
LASIK procedures, both said they could see distant objects clearly
with the treated eye. ``It's really neat, because without my
glasses I was reading signs all the way home,'' said Kristie
Carter. And neither experienced any pain or sensitivity to light.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, those who seek the surgery are motivated because they
find glasses or contacts uncomfortable, they have recreational
interests or jobs where lenses are a hindrance.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure that was approved in 1995, called PRK, is now
being rapidly pushed aside by LASIK, which involves much less
post-operative pain and yields clear vision sooner after the
surgery than does PRK. In PRK, the laser beam shaves off tissue
from the front of the cornea; because the injured surface is
exposed to the air, healing is more painful. Arons estimates that
LASIK now makes up 80 percent of laser vision procedures. At Mass
Eye and Ear, PRK costs $1,800 per eye and LASIK is $2,200 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   Even high degrees of nearsightedness can now be corrected with
the laser; so can hyperopia, or farsightedness, and moderate
astigmatism.
</P>
<P>
   Another innovation is reversible corneal surgery, in which a
thin plastic ring is placed in an incision in the cornea, leaving
the center part of the cornea untouched. This ``instrastromal''
corneal ring is being used overseas for mild myopia, but is still
experimental in the United States. The chief advantage is that the
ring can be removed and the cornea goes back to its normal shape.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s the field of refractive
surgery was revolutionized by the excimer laser, which uses a
relatively cool beam of energy to remove a thin layer of the
cornea, giving it a flatter shape to alter the way it focuses
light.
</P>
<P>
   PRK was the original excimer laser correction method. PRK, or
photorefractive keratectomy, is still sometimes done for mild
degrees of nearslightedness. In PRK, all the correction is carried
out on the surface of the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   But LASIK has been a major improvement, because the laser
correction actually takes place beneath the corneal surface.
</P>
<P>
   First, the eyelids are clamped open and the eyeball anesthetized
with drops. Next, the surgeon fits a metal ring over the eyeball;
it's held in place by a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Then, using a miniature, automated cutting device called a
microkeratome, the surgeon slices a thin flap of the cornea,
leaving a portion of it attached, much like a hinge. He folds the
flap back, then uses the excimer laser to reshape the corneal
tissue beneath. The flap is then replaced, held there by suction
until it heals in two or three weeks. (Another advantage of LASIK
is this: If after a few weeks, it is found that the correction is
not quite accurate, the surgeon can lift the flap without making a
new incision, re-treat the cornea with the laser, and replace the
flap.)
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after the surgeon is finished with LASIK,
patients can sit up and relax in the waiting room. They will wear a
metal shield over the eye for several nights to prevent
</P>
<P>
   accidental rubbing of the eye.
</P>
<P>
   A LASIK patient can drive the next day and usually can return to
work; with PRK, the recovery is a little slower and the patient may
feel stinging or burning in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Some surgeons will do LASIK on both eyes the same day, while
others prefer to do one and then wait a couple of weeks to make
certain no complications arise.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors caution older patients that once their nearsightedness
has been corrected with PRK or LASIK, they'll likely be unable to
read or see close-up objects clearly without reading glasses.
However, more and more surgeons are offering the option of
correcting one eye for distance vision and the other for reading _
a strategy called monovision _ though not everyone can comfortably
adjust to it.
</P>
<P>
   More so than with PRK, ``LASIK is very dependent on the skill of
the surgeon; that's why patients have to very careful'' in choosing
who will perform it on them, says Dr. Ernest Kornmehl, medical
director of the Center for Laser Vision Correction in Brookline and
a spokesman for the American Academy of Ophthalmology.
</P>
<P>
   He advises potential LASIK patients to seek out a
board-certified ophthalmologist who has had fellowship training in
corneal surgery, been thoroughly trained in LASIK, and has
performed it 50 to 100 times.
</P>
<P>
   What results can you expect? For both PRK and LASIK treatment of
nearsightedness, 95 percent or more of patients end up with 20-40
vision or better. That's the minimum acuity needed for a driver's
license in most states. About half of the patients get 20-20
vision, but sometimes that's after a second ``enhancement''
procedure, done about three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Kornmehl says 83 percent of his patients with mild to moderate
nearsightedness achieved 20-25 vision or better, and after
enhancement, 92 percent had 20-25 vision or better.
</P>
<P>
   For those with more severe nearsightedness, only 58 percent had
20-25 vision after the first LASIK. But with enhancement, that
figure rose to 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, this means that LASIK or PRK may free your
from glasses, but there's also a chance you might need a weak pair
of spectacles for driving at night or other demanding situations.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Azar's LASIK patient who was treated the same day the
Carters were said she won't mind at all if she needs reading
glasses, because the procedure has been so liberating in other
visual ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, it's wonderful,'' said the woman, who is from
Weston but asked that her name not be used. For the first time in
her life _ she's worn glasses since age eight, ``I woke up in the
morning and the world was in focus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
