<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUKON-LETTER-2TAKES-H     01-04 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUKON-LETTER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTER FROM THE YUKON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HUNTER SILIDES  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George and Hunter Silides are spending two years as town priests
in the remote Inuit village of Fort Yukon, Alaska. George, an
Alaska native, is the chaplain at St. Paul's Episcopal School in
Oakland; his wife, Hunter, is a chaplain at Grace Cathedral in San
Francisco. The following is an excerpt from a letter Hunter lately
sent to their friends at St. Paul's.
</P>
<P>
   A man named John Gabriel was born in Fort Yukon in 1924. He
seems to have quarrelled with his father in the late '30s, though,
and shook the dust from his shoes in 1941, leaving Fort Yukon,
never to return. His family all died. I looked it up in the church
records. The troublesome father, the mother, the brothers and their
wives, all of them made their way down to the churchyard and were
buried in their turn, leaving nobody to remember John Gabriel. He
never married. In 1996, it turns out, he was diagnosed with cancer
of the larynx. He died three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   All of those 57 years of life, those two years of illness, all
of it he spent without contacting anybody in Fort Yukon. Probably
he held the same low opinion of the place that most of the
inhabitants do. Probably he thought this was the last place he
would ever find help or succor. But when he died in a Seattle
nursing home, his nearest of kin _ a step-niece in Texas who had
never met him _ sent his remains to Fort Yukon, unaccompanied.
</P>
<P>
   They dressed him in a paper hospital nightgown and put him in a
cardboard box and sent him here. They called ahead to say he'd be
arriving at noon on Monday on a bush plane as freight. Usually
family arrive at the airport with a pickup truck full of somber
nephews. Usually family build the casket and line it with cloth and
dress the body. Usually family dig the grave in the frozen
churchyard and cook for the grave diggers and assemble a potluck
dinner in the Bingo Hall after the funeral. But there was no one to
do these things for John Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   George and I made some phone calls. ``Who? .... Oh, you mean
Paul Gabriel's brother? What ever happened to him? Oh? Well, gee,
he doesn't have any family around here anymore, I guess. All of 'em
dead I guess. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we rounded up a truck and some guys to meet the plane
at noon. He arrived at 9 a.m. The guys with the airport van called
and wanted to know what to do with him. I told them to meet me at
the ``morgue'' (a little cabin next to the church with no heat).
Two men easily lifted the long cardboard box on a plain pine
pallete into the morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't touch!'' One of them scolded me gruffly. Taboo is
hard to manage when the Ginghee (``much talker,'' Inuit for priest)
is also a pregnant woman who mustn't look at or touch death. I
guess they decided that since I was Ginghee, I had to be able to
look at it, but they weren't going to let their grandmothers know
they'd let me touch it. They made a silent compromise in taboo and
went on to deliver the rest of the freight. I stood in the snow in
front of the morgue with a casket to build and a grave to dig.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, George got a friend to start the grave with him:
chop 5 inches of frozen earth with an ax, build a fire, melt some
earth, chop 5 more inches, build a fire. ... I called our radio
station and asked them to announce we needed grave diggers. A girl
from the accounting department of the Native Village office called
up and said she had $210.65 burial assistance money, could we use
it? One of the elders was sitting at my kitchen table drinking
coffee (the diluted Peet's we make and call ``Company coffee'' _
the kind you can see through that people in the village like ...)
when she called. He shrugged, ``We could use it to buy lumber for
the coffin.'' I told her. She hung up. ``Of course, Snooks Herbert
builds a good casket, but I can't ask him to.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
