<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7181 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-SAFRICA-2TAKES-B     01-04 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-SAFRICA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S ART OF TRUTH AND HEALING 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ She must have been kneeling when
they shot her. The single bullet hole is right on the top of her
skull. Because she would not tell them what they wanted to hear,
before they shot her they kept her naked for 10 days, until she
found a blue plastic bag to wrap around her hips.
</P>
<P>
   After they shocked his friend to death with the infamous yellow
generator, before they did the same to him, he asked them if he
could sing.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of Phila Portia Ndwandwe and Harold Sefola are two
of the 37,000 tales of atrocities told to South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission over 2 1/2 years. Once she stopped
weeping after reading these sad stories in the newspaper, South
African painter Judith Mason started making art about them.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she joined Ndwandwe's and Sefola's stories in a
painting she calls ``Homage to the Man Who Sang and the Woman Who
Kept Silent.'' She transformed the blue plastic into a fairytale
gown wafting through the sky. For the murderous generator she
substituted open-mouthed braziers, aglow with light and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's ``Homage'' is destined for South Africa's Constitutional
Courthouse, scheduled to open in Johannesburg in three years. It's
the sort of setting where you'd expect to see stern portraits of
judges in black robes. Instead, there will be unflinching works by
contemporary South African artists, thanks in large part to Albert
Louis ``Albie'' Sachs. A liberal lawyer and erstwhile
anti-apartheid activist, Sachs was, in the 1960s, jailed by the
white South African government without charge or trial, forced into
exile, and, while living in Mozambique in 1988, was blown up by a
bomb planted under his car by agents of apartheid. He lost his
right arm and left eye. Not his spirit, though. You don't think of
Sachs as ``handicapped'' any more than you think the ``Nike of
Samothrace'' is, and the great Hellenistic icon of feminine power
is missing both arms, not to mention her head.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs is a resilient spirit and a jolly one, given to wearing
museum T-shirts, Monet neckties, and Mondrian socks. What he does
not wear is a prosthesis. His refusal to do so seems in the same
spirit that drove the Truth commission _ confronting and
acknowledging the past in order to get on with the future.
</P>
<P>
   Once a victim of an evil government, Sachs now labors to create
a virtuous one. He's a justice of the five-year-old Constitutional
Court, the highest in South Africa. He's an impassioned advocate of
art as well as of law. From his fee for lecturing at Harvard last
year, he saved 5,000 rand _ about $800 _ to pay for the materials
Mason would need to make her ``Homage.'' He already has filled the
walls of the current courthouse with an array of first-rate art by
South Africans, almost all of it donated by the artists, as the 20
or so major works he wants for the new courthouse will have to be.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's political state of emergency has been replaced by
an economic one. The funding that the arts community anticipated at
the dawn of the new democracy hasn't happened. The National Gallery
in Cape Town has had to cancel its art magazine subscriptions, and
its director, Marilyn Martin, says there is no money to pay guards
past March. South African tax law doesn't even allow write-offs for
donations to museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would have expected a larger infusion of money for the
arts,'' Martin laments. ``Artists were used during the struggle for
freedom, and now they're marginalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Penury now isolates South African artists as much as apartheid
once did: The fall of the rand has put international travel out of
reach for many. Judith Mason is one. The 60-year-old artist earns a
pittance from painting. She's anything but a whiner, but others say
that at the point when her career ought to have blossomed
internationally, it withered instead. Her silken, Surrealist style
was at odds with the New York-derived trends that reigned in South
Africa; her work was often overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homage'' will not be. This painting is destined for a place of
honor in the new courthouse. Mason is usually extremely reticent
about showing her work. ``But this time,'' she says, ``I wanted to
shove it down people's throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the South African who is considered an almost
unassailable saint in the West hasn't gone out of his way to
support his country's artists. To Martin, Nelson Mandela hasn't
done nearly enough for the artists who put themselves on the line
during apartheid. On a day when South African newspapers are full
of photos of Mandela hugging Janet Jackson, who was embarking on a
South African tour, Martin says in exasperation, ``There has been
no acknowledgement by our president of the achievement of artists.
Janet Jackson receives flowers and front page coverage with him.
We've invited him to open exhibitions, but with no success.''
</P>
<P>
   Her candor, like Sachs's refusal to wear a prosthesis, seems in
tune with a country determined to get at the truth, no matter how
depressing or undiplomatic. The ``director's message'' section of
museum newsletters is virtually always an upbeat assurance that
things are swell, even if they're not. Martin's messages are
apocalyptic.
</P>
<P>
   In a November swing through South Africa, visiting Cape Town,
Johannesburg, and points between, I saw contemporary art of
exceptional strength and scope. What I didn't see was much abstract
art: South African artists seem to need legible imagery to get
their urgent messages across. It's mostly figurative imagery.
Suffering bodies are to South African contemporary art what
crucifixions are to Early Italian painting.
</P>
<P>
   The figuration varies from Mason's sophisticated metaphors to
the highly spiritual _ and eccentric _ tableaux of Johannes Mashego
Segogela, who might be termed an ``outsider'' or ``folk'' artist in
the West. A fervent believer in heaven and hell, Segogela has
earned an international following for his updates of traditional
wood carving. His little angels tote video cameras, to record what
you're doing on earth and report back to God.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's rich indigenous visual culture means that even
the scarecrows in strawberry fields are crafted with care and
flair. Move them into a gallery and you'd have an ``installation.''
Barbed wire is ubiquitous in the country, coiled atop the walls
guarding the homes of the wealthy. But wire sculpture is a
tradition, too. Black folk artists turn out wry, whimsical wire
works: bicycles, figures, even wire Christmas trees. In a country
in need, there is imaginative recycling of what other countries
would call trash: mats woven from bubble gum wrappers; huge,
elegant metal baskets fashioned from the steel belts on tires.
</P>
<P>
   I saw contemporary art displayed in all manner of settings. In
improvised ``galleries'' made out of metal freight containers in
Soweto, I saw searing photographs of the 1976 Soweto Uprising by
Peter Magubane, who spent 586 days in solitary confinement for this
``crime.''
</P>
<P>
   First-rate commercial galleries are scarce. Johannesburg and
Cape Town are both bigger than Boston, but have fewer good
galleries, maybe three apiece. One of the best is Cape Town's Joao
Ferreira Fine Art. Ferreira's artists range from Jacques Dhont, a
Zaire-born sculptor who lives in seclusion in a South African
forest, weaving rugged, life-sized figures out of wattle bark, to
Sue Williamson, an important figure on the international scene.
Williamson's recent ``Truth Games'' series were, like Mason's
``Homage,'' based on stories that came out during the Truth
commission. Over blown-up newspaper images of victims, victimizers,
and incidents of the most inhuman cruelty, Williamson placed
fragments of text from the TRC, printed on sliding horizontal
plexiglas panels. The panels suggest Venetian blinds, and cast you
as voyeur. Since you're supposed to slide them as well, you also
play a symbolic role in shaping the truth. Everyone, Williamson
says in this work, is complicit; no one can ignore the past.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUKON-LETTER-2NDTAKE-     01-04 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUKON-LETTER-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: ask him too.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Can I?'' With another shrug, he pushes the phone toward me.
Yes, Snooks will build the casket. The girl from the native village
will line it. If only they'd dig the grave. George and a couple of
guys are out there still.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a nickname down here at the Native Village,'' my
contact girl tells me. ``We call him J.G. We went into the files
and found a picture of him. He's a member of our tribe, and we're
going to send him off right. Sarah's making sandwiches and says
she'll pull together a potlatch. We'll probably cry for him, too,''
she announces before hanging up. Snooks finishes the casket the
same day. They take it to the Vocational Educational building to
line it. Colored signs appear all over town, announcing that they
still need grave diggers and the time of the funeral service on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pessimistic elder from the kitchen table conversation has
discreetly leaked word of the inappropriate attire of the deceased
to the right channels. An elder woman appears at the door of the
mission house with a shirt, pants, tie, vest, socks, even
underwear. Every other body in the graveyard is buried in his or
her own clothes. Still, this beats a paper nightgown. The grave is
almost finished. Four more inches. The pessimist asks the grave
diggers (leaking muddy snow from their boots all over my kitchen
floor) if they really need those last 4 inches.
</P>
<P>
   One of the diggers is his profligate son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta do it right,'' the son answers.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's nobody to dress the body, which by this time, in
addition to having been embalmed, is frozen solid. Usually a
grandma does this, or a daughter. But for an unrelated woman to do
it is unheard of, and J.G.'s grandma is already in the churchyard.
I actually know how to dress the dead, because my grandparents were
morticians and Granny told me how. But I cannot look at death.
George and the pessimist head for the morgue with the clothes while
the grave diggers head out to light one last fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds strange, but it felt good to get those socks on his
feet. ...'' George trails off. The profligate bursts in for the
20th time that day. The grave is finished.
</P>
<P>
   We buried John Gabriel at 2 p.m. on Wednesday. The church was
packed. I got to preach the easiest funeral sermon of my life. ``If
we, who did not know John Gabriel, have welcomed his body home so
well, how much more will God, who knew and loved him, welcome his
spirit home? Fort Yukon is a mirror of heaven today.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day was Thanksgiving. This time, I celebrated and
George preached. The church was pretty full for that service, too.
The pessimist was helping to collect the food offerings at the
altar. At the end of the service he stood up straight and addressed
the people gathered there. ``When we first heard that John Gabriel
was being sent here, I was worried. I didn't know how we were going
to manage. But having seen everything that all of you did, I can
say it made my Thanksgiving complete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should have had HIM preach!'' George whispered to me.
</P>
<P>
   Love, Hunter
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7183 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TRAVOLTA-2ND &LR;  &UR;      01-04 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRAVOLTA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LOS ANGELES: ... this character.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travolta is no stranger to Boston. Before appearing here in the
national company of ``Grease,'' he journeyed from his hometown of
Englewood, N.J., to the same Shubert Theatre 12 years earlier to
see an older sister in ``Gypsy.'' After he became a TV star in
``Welcome Back Kotter'' as greaser Vinnie Barbarino, and went on to
play disco king Tony Manero in ``Saturday Night Fever,'' he got
Harvard University's Hasty Pudding pot. Travolta credits his late
mother, Helen, for encouraging him. ``She was a director, a
teacher, an actress. She taught for years. She acted up through the
'50s. She hooked me up early on with a group of actors in New
Jersey that were a spinoff from the Actors Studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sisters Ellen, Ann, and Margaret are still professional
actresses, still making a living. Both my sister Ann and my mother
were in `Saturday Night Fever.' Ellen had a few lines in `Grease'
and Margaret had a little bit in `Michael.' All three girls were
doing quite well long before I was famous. I'm the baby of six
children. In our home, if the arts weren't admired, you were kind
of odd. We were definitely the avant-garde family on our block.''
</P>
<P>
   Englewood was also in La Guardia's flight pattern, which
accounts for Travolta's other love, flying. ``I actually have four
planes,'' Travolta says. He's licensed to fly them all, plus other
planes. ``I probably have logged more time in jets than some
captains on airlines, at least 4,500 hours in jets alone. I've gone
to professional school over the last 18 years at least 30 times.
When you're basically treating it as a profession and not a hobby,
the insurance companies let up, so now I get the normal rate. I
remember as a kid watching a plane come into view and I'd always
imagine who was on the plane and where they were going. I tried to
build a plane in my back yard. I wrote a little book called
`Propeller One Way Night Coach,' about a little boy's impressions
going cross-country when the prop age was moving into the jet
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying subliminally filled Travolta's nerve endings, just as the
original cast album of ``Gypsy'' did all those years ago. If acting
were to dry up tomorrow, Travolta says he'd only have to pass a few
more tests to work for an airline. ``Within a few months I could be
flying for them,'' he says. During weekends on the ``Civil Action''
shoot, Travolta flew himself, his wife, actress Kelly Preston, and
their 6-year-old son, Jett, to their 20-room home near Camden,
Maine, an area he discovered when he was invited there by his
``Look Who's Talking'' co-star and friend, Kirstie Alley, who was
summering there with her then-husband. The Travoltas just spent the
Christmas holidays there.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta's affinity, and his wife's, for Maine govern his wish
to shoot much of the ``The Shipping News'' there when the script of
the E. Annie Proulx novel has evolved to their liking. It will be
the first film in which they'll co-star. Travolta just finished
``The General's Daughter.'' Due next summer, it's a suspense
thriller in which Travolta plays a military police investigator.
Also on the drawing boards is a film of ``Battlefield Earth,'' by
sci-fi author L. Ron Hubbard, who also founded the sometimes
controversial religion, Scientology.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta and Tom Cruise are its two most famous practitioners.
Travolta learned of it in 1975 when he was shooting his first
movie, ``The Devil's Run,'' in Durango, Mexico. The movie, in which
he plays a character denouncing a blasphemer, is forgettable. But a
young actress, Jaan Prather, introduced Travolta to Scientology,
which he says has helped him immeasurably. He credits it for his
virtual singlehanded avoidance of the '70s drug scene in LA and the
help it gave him during periods of grief over the deaths of family
members and others close to him.
</P>
<P>
   These included stars of the past, most notably, Travolta says,
Jimmy Cagney. ``I had the privilege of spending a lot of time with
him,'' Travolta says. ``The old-timers liked me. Barbara Stanwyck,
Fred Astaire, Gene Kelly, Gregory Peck, Marlon Brando. They all had
a special feeling for me, and I always felt more comfortable with
that group than I did with my peers because I didn't know what my
peers felt about me. I didn't know what I was to them. I gained a
lot of strength from Cagney. He taught me that a man can take a
knock and still hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Travolta shares with those earlier stars is their
industry. They used to make films assembly-line fashion. So does
Travolta, ever since his career dwindled, then was reborn when
Quentin Tarantino cast him as a hit man in ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, Travolta turned down ``American Gigolo,''
``Arthur,'' ``Raiders of the Lost Ark,'' ``An Officer and a
Gentleman,'' and ``Splash!'' Then Tarantino cast him as Vinny Vega.
If ``Saturday Night Fever'' was the film that made him, ``Pulp
Fiction'' was the film that remade him. He got paid $100,000. But
having his wife and son on location with him in a more expensive
hotel than the budget allowed left him $30,000 in the red. But his
instincts, and Tarantino's, were right. After ``Get Shorty'' and
``Broken Arrow'' subsequently proved ``Pulp Fiction'' was no fluke,
Travolta joined the $20 million club. He has worked nonstop ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   So the '90s will not be the story of missed opportunities that
marked the '80s? ``Kind of,'' Travolta says. ``I used to say no to
a lot of films. I don't want to say no again to a great
opportunity. And to be honest, these are better opportunities than
the kinds I had when I started in the '70s, so I really wanted to
make up for lost opportunities. I like it better now because
they're better scripts. Anyone's career, the best parts are in
their 40s, 50s and 60s. You have time to rub elbows with other
people. It makes the performances that much richer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
