<HEADLINE>
PAT O'CONNOR PAYS TRIBUTE TO IRELAND, AND MERYL STREEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who's that idiot with the braces on? That guy is a (expletive)
fruitcake. You can't take a man seriously when he's 80 or 90, and
he's wearing braces. Can't he hold up his trousers some other
way?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Braces'' are suspenders, and the ``idiot'' and ``fruitcake''
Pat O'Connor was referring to is better known as CNN talk show host
Larry King. O'Connor was in Boston last fall during the Boston Film
Festival to do the meet-and-greet thing for his latest film,
``Dancing at Lughnasa,'' a project he had wanted to do for years.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to talk about the film, and was eager to chat about
working with its star, Meryl Streep. But nothing could begin until
he let off steam about what he calls ``the Billy Clinton
situation,'' and what's been happening to the man O'Connor says
``has been more important than any other American president to my
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bad it has come to this. It's a terrible waste of
a bright man. I don't care. . . . I think it's a pity,'' he said.
``It's terrible nonsense. He's very bright _ look how many dummies
who've been running this country. If he weren't in office, that
peace treaty wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's native country is Ireland, and his affection for his
homeland is evident in his best films such as ``Cal'' and ``Circle
of Friends,'' the 1995 film that introduced moviegoers to Minnie
Driver. ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' (pronounced ``loo-na-sa'') is also
set in Ireland, this time in a rural parish in the 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Brian Friel's award-winning play, it is the story of
the Mundy sisters, all unmarried, all living under the same roof.
Kate (Streep) is the eldest, and the most severe. She is a teacher,
but is so far removed from the joys of youth, it seems as if she
never enjoyed them. Her sisters, while respectful of Kate, want
something more. They long to love, to dance, to experience the
sweetness that has somehow passed them by. There's Maggie (Kathy
Burke), Rose (Sophie Thompson), Agnes (Brid Brennan), and Christina
(Catherine McCormack), the youngest and prettiest, and also the
mother of a young son, Michael (Darrell Johnston). All of their
lives are altered when their brother Jack (Michael Gambon), a
missionary priest, returns home after 25 years in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was attracted to these women in this quietly desperate
world,'' said a more sedate O'Connor, between sips of merlot at a
Back Bay restaurant. ``But there was also a tremendous spirit, and
self-respect, and respect for each other despite the difficulties
surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in things that are slightly difficult to
define, but are a little bit outside of us,'' he said. ``It's a
triumph of spirit, the struggle against adversity, all of these
things for me are what real drama is. I'm not interested in
testosterone-driven stuff. I'm always interested in the doubts in
people, rather than the certainties.''
</P>
<P>
   The women in ``Lughnasa'' are not unlike those O'Connor knew
when he was growing up in rural Ireland. He left his homeland to
see the world at 18, because ``there was nothing around.'' But he
has never forgotten the honest, decent people who forged his
identity, and the casual kindness they would extend to strangers as
well as friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ordinary. They weren't showy or high-flying or
fashionable,'' he said. ``They were strong women who knew how to
cope with the difficulties around them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the role of Kate, O'Connor always knew he wanted Streep, who
mastered yet another accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so good. She happens to be a star, but first and
foremost, she's a very good actress,'' he said. ``She's extremely
likable, but people tend to think she might be a bit of a diva. But
she's very warm, a giggler, and highly intelligent. She does plenty
of research, but she's not self-indulgent. She knows posturing is
for fools. I adore her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is O'Connor's first film since 1997's
``Inventing the Abbotts,'' which costarred two of his favorite
young actors, Billy Crudup and Joaquin Phoenix. For O'Connor, two
films in two years is downright prolific, considering he's made
only eight films since his directorial debut, ``Cal,'' a movie of a
doomed romance set amid the Troubles in Northern Ireland in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor prefers to take his time between films. He is more
committed to a stable life with his wife, actress Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio, and their two children. They live in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never work when she works, she never works when I work. The
trouble is we can never work together either because of that,''
said O'Connor, who last worked with Mastrantonio in 1990 on ``Fools
of Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been working on anything because I just returned
from Alaska, where she's making a John Sayles film (`Limbo'),'' he
said. ``But we like our life the way it is. I don't need to make
huge bucks all the time, but I do need to have a normal life. I
have a life outside of film, and I intend to keep it that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
