<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC FUTURE HERE IN THE FORM OF MP3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I have listened to the future, and its name is MP3.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat after me: MP3. MP3. MP3.
</P>
<P>
   Got it? Don't forget it. This is going to be huge _ unless big
business kills it.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 stands for MPEG 1 Layer 3. It's technical mumbo-jumbo for a
new audio compression format that can squeeze music files down to
between one-fourth and one-twentieth their normal size _ with
little loss of quality.
</P>
<P>
   A three-minute song, for example, can be compressed into an MP3
file of less than 3 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the programs needed to make and play MP3 files,
not to mention hundreds of thousands of MP3 files themselves, are
available to anyone _ free.
</P>
<P>
   What's all this mean? Computer users the world over can now jump
on the Internet, download as many MP3 files _ songs _ as they want
and play them to their heart's content on their home or office
computer. The quality is phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't stop with your PC or Macintosh. MP3 files can be
transferred via a parallel cable to a device like the Diamond Rio,
a palm-sized player much like a Sony Walkman, that can hold up to
an hour's worth of MP3 music in its 32-megabyte memory.
</P>
<P>
   Just plug in a set of headphones and you're off. Unlike other
portable music devices, the Rio contains no mechanical or moving
parts. So no amount of jostling can make the music skip.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio, which sells for about $200, is available for purchase
online and is expected to be in retail outlets in Phoenix and other
major U.S. cities by the time you read this.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Internet is awash in music. People are trading
songs like never before.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 isn't like previous Internet-related advancements in
technology, such as streaming audio. Remember the first time you
checked that out? Yeah, it was kinda neat, but it still sounded
like a short-wave radio dispatch from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is different. Believe me when I say: It's really cool!
</P>
<P>
   Now, before we go on, we have to address an all-important
question: Is all this MP3 stuff legal?
</P>
<P>
   The quick answer is yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's legal to make MP3 files for your own enjoyment
using CDs you own. It's really no different than recording some of
your favorite CD tunes on a cassette tape that you use for personal
entertainment on a long vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also legal to visit Web sites and download licensed MP3
files _ music the artists have agreed to make available for
distribution in the MP3 format. One good site to find such files is
MP3.com at www.mp3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with MP3 files becomes illegal if you make MP3 files
from commercial CDs and put the MP3 files online or share them with
other people.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with half a brain should know that. I mean, you should
know something is wrong when the latest CD from your favorite group
is on sale at Target for $16.99, but also is available free online
in the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming we all have at least half a brain, then, we'll also
assume that if you run across Web sites full of Top 40 hits in MP3
format that the person behind the site knows full well that he or
she is breaking the law and that you know you'll be breaking the
law if you download any of the files.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this has kept pirates from opening sites all
over cyberspace to trade illegal MP3 files. Some music industry
executives have gone so far as to say they believe the majority of
MP3 files online are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's true, nobody knows. But, as you can imagine, the
record companies and the artists they employ are not very happy
about this MP3 business.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Associa tion of America (www.riaa.com)
views MP3 as little more than a tool for music pirates. The group
has helped close some of the more obviously illegal Web sites and
has even tried to block the sale and distribution of the Rio MP3
player.
</P>
<P>
   Where will all this end? I'm not sure, but I believe record
companies will be forced to climb aboard the MP3 bandwagon _ or
develop something better _ because MP3 works, works very well and
it's free.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, thanks to MP3, high-quality music can be
traded across the Internet quickly and with relative ease. The
implications for electronic commerce are monumental.
</P>
<P>
   While that's being sorted out, I encourage you to give MP3 a
try.
</P>
<P>
   The technology has actually been around for more than a year,
but finally has caught on thanks to the widespread availability of
Pentium-class PCs and similarly powered Macintosh computers that
can decode and play MP3 files on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com offers a wealth of information for the beginner,
including answers to frequently asked questions, links to get the
necessary software, a huge library of MP3-related articles and, of
course, hundreds of legal MP3 files you can download free.
</P>
<P>
   A few well-known artists have made songs available for
distribution via the MP3 format. (Billy Idol had two songs on
MP3.com until his record label forced both to be removed.)
</P>
<P>
   But most of the legal stuff you find online is from unknown
artists who want you to sample their work. The thinking is that
maybe you'll like what you hear and buy one of their complete CDs
somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let this throw you. There's some great music out there.
MP3.com has tunes in many genres, ranging from rock to country,
from New Age to R&AMP;B. There's also folk, swing, classical,
experimental, comedy and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   I dove into the MP3 experience one evening last week. The first
thing I had to do was download and install a program to play MP3
files. I chose a shareware program called WinAmp 2.05. There's a
similar program for the Macintosh called MacAmp. MP3.com offers
links to both.
</P>
<P>
   WinAmp, which costs $10 to register for personal use (do it!),
provides a really cool interface. It looks like a small stereo rack
system, complete with an amplifier, a powerful equalizer and handy
playlist window.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I went to MP3.com's music area and started downloading
titles. By the end of the night, I'd grabbed 11 songs ranging in
size from about 1.3 megabytes to just over 4 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   The music sounded great. I couldn't believe my ears.
</P>
<P>
   Audiophiles, of course, will debate the quality of MP3 files
until they die. After all, they still haven't given up on vinyl!
But I think most people with decent sound cards and speakers on
their computers will find most MP3 files close to CD-quality.
</P>
<P>
   I also liked MP3 right off the bat because it allowed me to work
at the computer and listen to some nice music without tying up my
CD-ROM drive with CDs.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't guessed by now, I'm hooked on MP3. And I think
you might get hooked, too, if you give it a try. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-IRIS-BOS &LR;      01-04 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IRIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN BAYLEY, ON LIFE WITH IRIS MURDOCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ELEGY FOR IRIS 
By John Bayley. 
St. Martin's, 275 pp. $22.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If memory is both the treasure and the drafting table of human
consciousness, then the tragic loss of it manages to annihilate
experience even as it exalts its timeless present. Without the
hindsight to digest and take note of our existence, by which we
turn it into life's narrative, there is nothing left but the
transience of the moment _ the fleeting aroma of the garden, the
feel of a hand upon the cheek, the taste of coffee or sherbert
almost immediately forgotten. This amnesic state is particularly
tragic because we understand its counterpoint: understand that the
world we have built _ art and God and the blessings of love and all
the triumphs of human accomplishment _ has little value without the
power to comprehend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take short views,'' the English literary critic John Bayley
reminds himself, borrowing the phrase from an adage for depression.
``Never further than dinner or tea.'' Alzheimer's disease afflicts
millions of people each year, and, with the violent egalitarianism
of most illnesses, cares not whether its victims are 52 or 84,
poets or madmen. It struck Bayley's wife, the philosopher and
novelist Iris Murdoch, in 1994, when she was 75, and in the few
infinite years since, as she has said to Bayley, she has been
``sailing into the darkness.'' He is with her on the voyage.
Sometimes the seas are stormy and terrifying; more often, they are
known but endless, granting an occasional sense of peace. There is
little else there now but these two devoted people, the one helpful
and the other helpless, clinging to each other and staring at the
far horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elegy for Iris'' is Bayley's restrained and elegant love song
to his wife of 42 years, with whom he first became enchanted when
she rode a bicycle past his window at St. Anthony's College, where
he was teaching in Oxford. She was 34; he, 28, a young man in love
with literature and the promises of the intellectual life. When
they met again, at the home of a colleague, she was sporting brown
cotton stockings and unwashed hair, and she charmed everybody in
the room. She was a philosopher at Oxford, Bayley knew; later, when
they bicycled home together, she confided to him that she was
working on a novel. Thrilled with this privileged information, he
learned soon enough that she had revealed the same secret to easily
a dozen friends. It didn't matter, by then: He was hopelessly in
love, and when he took her to a dance, she appeared wearing garish
lipstick and promptly fell down the stairs. She got up smiling, and
later wrote in her diary: ``St. Anthony's Dance. Fell down the
steps, and seem to have fallen in love with J. We didn't dance
much.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't time for dancing: There were instead novels and
critical studies and works of philosophy, and country houses and
foxes and long swims in the river, and all the braided pleasures
that constitute a shared life. Bayley had to convince this sterling
mind and free soul to marry him; Murdoch seemed far wider and
wilder than that, and only succumbed, he now believes, because she
found a house in the country where he, too, seemed to fit. For the
next several decades, they found together the blissful solitude for
each that Bayley describes, not incongruously, as ``one of the
truest pleasures of marriage.'' And from the beginning, they seemed
to possess a language of intimacy _ a thick communication,
childlike in the best sense _ that superseded the brilliant
critical and creative faculties they each possessed. Today they
rely on that secret language, creating from necessity a kind of
jabberwocky to communicate the feelings between them, if not the
words themselves. ``Now we are together for the first time,''
writes Bayley. ``. . . In a way, like Orids Baveis and Philemon,
whom the gods gave the gift of growing old together as trees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Elegy for Iris'' is beautiful and heartbreaking, though it
isn't really elegiac _ it's more a love poem writ in melancholy, an
ode to the past and the stratosphere of commitment that such a past
ensures. Relayed with the fluid style and even humor of that old
admirable school of British critics, most of whom write as though
they were playing ragtime piano, Bayley's memoir is candid about
the depth and severity of Murdoch's incapacity and yet riven with
dignity. More than anything, it is respectful: This is a woman,
after all, whom he has adored for nearly half a century, and adore
her he still does. In reminiscing through their decades together,
he takes us to Italy and the artwork of Piero della Francesca and
Titian, the writing of Lawrence and Proust, the rivers, beckoning
on a summer day, where he and Murdoch left their clothes to swim.
And in recapturing the past, he has delivered his Iris to us wholly
formed, throughout the cumulative beauty of her life day by day.
When the quite tall novelist Barbara Pym met Murdoch and Bayley,
she later wrote to Philip Larkin about the encounter, saying she
feared she had ``seemed to tower above Iris (though only in height,
of course).''
</P>
<P>
   Exercising restraint about the specific ravages of Alzheimer's,
Bayley is nonetheless never euphemistic; he admits after a
particularly tender passage that ``most days are for her a sort of
despair.'' Like ``Patrimony,'' Philip Roth's brilliantly moving
memoir about his father's death, the tribute and beauty of the
words here are stronger than the pain and mess they describe.
Bayley concedes that he knows nothing of the spiritual life, but it
isn't quite true: The whole lifetime shared in ``Elegy for Iris''
is full of spirit, generous and resilient and partaking of the
bounty, before the darkness began to fall. During the early days of
their love affair, when things between them were difficult or
ill-resolved, Murdoch used to remind Bayley of the myth of Proteus,
who had the power to assume different shapes; when Hercules gripped
him firmly, he returned to his original shape. ``Remember
Proteus,'' she would say to Bayley. ``Just keep tight hold of me
and it will be all right.'' This reassurance, wrenching now,
contains the essence of their life together _ what it was and,
perhaps on the better days, still is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
