<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 
!!! ``Central Station'' Classic humanist art cinema from Brazil.
Fernanda Montenegro is magnificent as a crusty old woman whose
heart is thawed when she accompanies a motherless boy (Vincius de
Oliveira) on a literal and symbolic journey to find his father in
Walter Salles's road film about contemporary Brazil finding its
identity, too. (R) 
 
!!! 1/2 ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' A beautiful film of a beautiful
play (by Brian Friel) about five unmarried sisters in Donegal and
the refusal of their hearts and spirits to be crushed by the
grinding hardship they face and the return, in disgrace, of their
brother, a missionary priest who no longer sees any need to
distinguish between pegan religions and Catholicism. Meryl Streep
is the presiding sister. Michael Gambon is the spiritual pilgrim.
(PG) 
 
!!! ``Down in the Delta'' Richly-textured film directing debut of
poet Maya Angelou. In it, a single mother whose life is falling
apart in Chicago rights herself and her family after she returns to
her relatives and her roots in Mississippi. Alfre Woodard delilvers
a strongly-arched performance as the woman who becomes whole again.
You've never seen Wesley Snipes as he appears here in the role of a
soft-spoken, educated, prosperous Atlanta businessman. (PG-13) 
 
!!! ``Hurlyburly'' David Rabe's houseful of Hollywood loose cannons
make more dramatic sense here than they did on the New York stage.
Sean Penn is intense, yet sympathetic, as Eddie, trying to lose
himself in the fast-lane life, yet also wondering if he shouldn't
be keeping his ear cocked for a wakeup call. Strong support from
Kevin Spacey, and from Chazz Palminteri, Garry Shandling, Robin
Wright Penn, Anna Paquin, and Meg Ryan _ the latter three as women
too strong to be destroyed by the misogynistically destructive men.
(R) 
 
!!! ``Little Voice'' Captivating tale about a reclusive young woman
in a crumbling seaside town in the north of England, squelched into
silence by her mother, except when she uncannily reproduces the
voices of Judy Garland, Marilyn Monroe, Shirley Bassey, and others
she spends her days listening to from her dead father's record
collection. Jane Horrocks is amazing as the girl whose voice is not
little; Michael Caine is wonderful as the sleazy agent who wants to
exploit her talent. (R) 
 
!!! ``Mighty Joe Young'' Solidly-crafted, family-friendly remake of
the 1949 film about a sensitive gorilla who suggests King Kong's
kid brother and is highly unhappy in so-called civilization.
Charlize Theron is the primatologist who turns it into a
beauty-and-the-beast story, and Bill Paxton is another plus in the
role of the guy who wants to save them both. (PG) 
 
!! ``Patch Adams'' This film about a nonconformist doctor who
clowns around with patients in the name of treating them more
humanely and effectively would seem to be made to order for Robin
Williams. But the manipulativeness of the clunky script keeps
getting in the way by stacking the deck. The docs are either rigid
martinets or compassionate shaker-uppers. (PG-13) 
 
!!!! ``Shakespeare in Love'' The best backstage comedy ever made.
It's delightful for other reasons, too. Joseph Fiennes is an
amusingly soulful Shakespeare, Gwyneth Paltrow is luminous as the
high-born woman he was thinking of when he wrote Juliet and the
supporting players are unfailingly zestful, too, from Judi Dench's
high-spirited Elizabeth to Ben Affleck's droll matinee idol to
Geoffrey Rush's desperate theater owner. (R) 
 

