<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-SHAKESPEARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR THE MEANING OF LOVE AND SHAKESPEARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If being a certified genius is a load, Mary Zimmerman _
director of the current production of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
at the Huntington Theatre Company _ bears it lightly. A
Chicago-based director, and a visiting professor at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill., Zimmerman was named a MacArthur
Fellow early last year, a generous financial award that carries the
sobriquet, or ``handle'' as they say out West, of ``the genius
award.'' Her particular specialty is adapting, creating new works
out of non-stage classics, including ``The Odyssey'' and ``The
Arabian Nights.'' At the Huntington in 1996, she directed ``Journey
to the West,'' her adaptation of a novel translated from an ancient
Chinese epic.
</P>
<P>
   This legitimate-stage genius really likes television. Rather
late in an interview (these things happen), the subject of British
actors arose, and Zimmerman slapped it down:
</P>
<P>
   ``I will, to my death,'' she hyperbolized, ``defend the
reputation of American actors. That is a myth, that British actors
are somehow superior. I am perpetually patriotic on the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that somehow the illusion of top-to-bottom
competence, nay, little `g' genius, seemed to characterize even
British television (``Inspector Morse'' or the ineffable Helen
Mirren's vehicle, ``Prime Suspect,'' or the recent ``Nicholas
Nickleby'') wherein even the lowliest of cast members seems ready
to step onto the stage at the Old Vic, Zimmerman heated to her
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is this,'' Zimmerman simplified: ``In America, you
have to make a choice between the legitimate stage _ live theater _
and television and movies. There is no theater in Los Angeles and
there's hardly any television production in New York. Bill Cosby
could get away with it, but that's rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Britain is so small, everything is so close. You can do
television and stage at the same time. Here, it's coast or coast,''
she said, illustrating the vast gap with widespread arms at the
ends of which were, from left to right, a diet soda and a forkful
of salad, an oddity explained by the fact that her only free
moments for interviews are during lunch breaks at the Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are great shows on American television,'' she
emphasized with a stab of a suddenly lettuce-free fork. `` `Law and
Order,' that's a great show with superb acting.'' It is also the
exception that proves her rule _ it's the only prime-time drama
filmed on location in New York City, giving it access to a
metropolis filled with aspiring and successful actors.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's affection for television is really an appreciation
for acting, not for the subject matter of crime and punishment.
``Do you watch `Homicide'?'' she challenged. Disappointed that the
response was negative, Zimmerman offered the opinion that Clark
Johnson (Detective Meldrick Lewis, the dogged, back-to-basics cop
with the dry-as-fingerprint-dust humor) was ``the best actor in
America.'' She explained to the abashed nonviewer that Johnson had
the greatest of acting talents: ``You never catch him acting. I met
him a little while ago, and he's absolutely nothing like the
character on screen. Totally different. That's acting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide'' is filmed entirely on scene in Baltimore, making it
the only other East Coast prime-time drama, and one that can also
draw on actors from New York's on- and off-Broadway talent ocean.
``And there's `3rd Rock from the Sun,' '' Zimmerman said, switching
effortlessly from homicide to humor. ``John Lithgow is fabulous.
You want a British comparison?'' she challenged. ``Lithgow is
America's John Cleese.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the Huntington performance workshop, actors
waited for another grueling afternoon of being funny, the hardest
work in theater. ``I am taking this play for what I really think it
is,'' Zimmerman said, ``a brilliantly conceived comedy, a play you
can't change a line in, or rearrange a scene in, without spoiling
it. And I take it as a play about the meaning of true love. You
could take it cynically, take it darkly, you could make it question
the existence of love. Well, I take it as a serious look at the
question: `Is love real?' That is a fundamental question, even if
the device for asking it includes a magic flower and a healing
herb.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one thing is turning out to be true. Everyone says this is
a play that brings out the best in everyone. In this play, you
really are asking whether the enchanted world is real, or is the
real world the real world? Well, in the theater, and this is always
true when theater succeeds, the fantasy world and the real world
are reconciled.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, artistic associate at the Goodman Theatre in Chicago,
is responsible for casting, directing, and also designing
``Midsummer,'' which, she says, will be done with a minimum of
stage scenery and a maximum of costume. What kind of costumes?
Modern? Elizabethan? ``What I tell everyone is this,'' she said:
``I insist that the official answer to that question is `The
costumes are from the Gorgeous Period.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed as to when in the vast landscape of history one might
stumble upon the Gorgeous Period, Zimmerman allowed it might be
near the Victorian (the ladies will be ladies in long dresses) but
not quite. Perhaps a little on the Pre-Raphaelite edge of
Victorian/Edwardian. But gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been done in modern dress,'' Zimmerman remarked. ``It's
been done in every imaginable way, and it can survive any staging.
I think the only thing that would spoil it would be to direct it
with a dark, cynical view. We won't do that. We will, as I said,
look for the meaning of true love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
