<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S COMPLEXITY WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The human puzzle makes his familiar stiff walk to the
dais. The gleaming Republican faces lay down their salad forks. The
guest draws loud, unsurprising applause. The crowd _ wonks and D.C.
types _ admires his conservatism, his patriotism, his heroism.
</P>
<P>
   You like the human puzzle, apart from -isms, because maybe he is
the most fascinating political game in America today.
</P>
<P>
   Because maybe _ I peg his chances at one in 20 _ he can win
election as America's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Because maybe, mostly, it is impossible to unpuzzle Arizona's
senior senator, John Sidney McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Such fun, though. And suddenly such a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Solving McCain turned urgent last Wednesday, when he formed an
exploratory committee for the 2000 presidential race. McCain called
this a prelude to a decision, a way to stick his toe into the river
of cash needed for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Friday, he headed to the Arizona Biltmore, to a
conservative group-grope billed as ``The Weekend,'' and you could
hear him trying out themes, taking rhetorical baby steps.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller government. Coherent foreign policy. Reformed campaign
finance. An end to the Internal Revenue Service. A return to the
America of Ronald Reagan. A restoration of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even amid today's peace and prosperity, the people know that
something is terribly wrong with the country,'' went one McCain
thrust. ``Ask any American one simple question: `Are you proud?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely the relevant question. It will be asked all this
year and into the next, not only about the country, but about the
quasi-candidate for president, the human puzzle, John Sidney
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Are you proud of him? Always, or merely sometimes?
</P>
<P>
   Or are you confused?
</P>
<P>
   With McCain, the admirable stands have been many, the courage
unquestionable, the contradictions disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   You must applaud him for speaking hard truths to his peers who
crowd the congressional trough, who can't get their fill of pork.
McCain can, and regularly does, cite million-dollar outrage after
million-dollar outrage. He is a conscience on spindly legs. Then
there is his stand against tobacco. You can disagree, but you must
admire his willingness to buck his party and its biggest donors.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can you question McCain's valor. Consider this my allusion
to his Vietnam heroics _ if you need to know more, read every other
article in any other national publication. Or ask McCain himself.
He will get around to telling you, mostly while refusing to tell
you.
</P>
<P>
   If that last sentence sounds like a contradiction, it isn't the
only one.
</P>
<P>
   Since shucking the Keating Five label, the senator has made much
hay over fixing campaign finance, all the while raising much loot _
more than $4 million last election, to beat someone named Ed
Ranger, who barely banked $340,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nary a special interest was missed: 46 grand from US West
donors, 26 large from Bell Atlantic workers, $16,000 more from
Phelps Dodge employees.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the moral high ground is one pricey piece of real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are McCain's contradictions solely political: During the
Senate ethics hearing concerning his Keating involvement, McCain
raged about the personal nature of the attacks on his character.
The same was true in 1994, after his wife's addiction to and theft
of prescription painkillers was revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Given that sensitivity, how do you explain McCain's too-public
joke last June about Chelsea Clinton being ``so ugly''?
</P>
<P>
   You don't, can't. Such is life in the wake of the human puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   He has a temper. He is as human, as authentic, as a politician
gets. At his best, he fights his own party. At his worst, he fights
your best perceptions of him.
</P>
<P>
   Are you proud, he asks? Maybe every American voter will get a
chance to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   They will see John run. They may never solve what makes John
tick. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
