<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
40-YEAR-OLDS WORRY ABOUT RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 42 and my husband is 49. We wish to retire at age 65
with a monthly income of $5,000. Unlike many of your readers, we
started investing for retirement way too late. To date our
investments include $14,430 in my company's 401(k) plan, $8,307 in
Fidelity Growth Company fund, $8,307 in Neuberger and Berman
Guardian fund, and $14,000 in a credit union money market account
earning 3.17 percent interest. In addition to my regular job, my
husband and I have also owned a small business since 1993, and it
has a current capital equipment value of $80,000 to $100,000. As an
owner of the business, a few years ago I also opened a $1,000
SEP-IRA account, but haven't added to it since. Any investment or
monthly savings advice would be greatly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   D.M., Arlington, Texas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You not only need to work out a budget that involves
substantial retirement savings, but you need to adhere to it
religiously.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the goal of a $5,000 monthly income stream in
retirement. What Social Security benefits will the two of you
likely get? You can call Social Security and ask for a form that
allows you to request a statement of your estimated benefits, and I
suggest you do that.
</P>
<P>
   But let's estimate that between the two of you Social Security
probably will bring in $2,000 a month. That means you will need to
produce a $3,000 monthly income stream from your investments.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, as well as to leave a bit of money working so you
will have some protection against inflation, you will need a pool
of about $750,000. If we presume that your husband's business will
have at least the same liquidation value at the time of his
retirement as it does now, we can cut that figure to $650,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's presume that you'll put together a retirement
portfolio that is likely to achieve average annual returns of 10
percent. To get from your current $41,343 savings to $650,000 over
16 years will require monthly additions of $1,019 to your savings _
either through your 401(k) or SEP-IRAs, Roth IRAs, or some other
tax-advantaged savings vehicle such as variable annuity accounts.
</P>
<P>
   And to get the 10 percent average returns upon which that
projection is made, you will have to invest a bit more aggressively
than you've been doing.
</P>
<P>
   The current allocations in your 401(k) account give you a pretty
good idea of the kind of total portfolio you should seek: You have
30 percent in the Merrill Lynch Growth fund, a similar amount in
Merrill Lynch Corporate High-Income fund, and 20 percent each in
Merrill Lynch Basic Value and Merrill Lynch Global Allocation
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The two taxable mutual fund holdings are also fine. But that
$14,000 loafing at the credit union is a terrible investment. Even
if you have mentally put that aside as emergency money, there's no
reason you should tolerate that 3.17 percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   With just a little shopping around the money market funds
offered by mutual fund companies, you can boost that yield to 5
percent or a bit more. And as far as I'm concerned, the tiny level
of additional risk inherent in a mutual fund money market when
compared to a bank or credit union offering is so small as to be
negligible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you can divert any part of that $14,000 from the
money markets into a more growth-oriented investment such as your
mutual fund portfolio, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 44-year-old self-employed artist who needs additional
income. Currently I have $60,600 in Janus High-Yield fund and
$48,000 in Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund. I have several other
funds set aside for retirement, but I need income now. What do you
suggest I could do to produce a better income?
</P>
<P>
   A.H., Escondido, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What you are employing now is frequently called a ``barbell
strategy'' _ balancing a higher-risk investment at one end (the
high-yield, or ``junk'' bond fund) with the very conservative,
low-risk money market fund at the other.
</P>
<P>
   I calculate the effect is a portfolio average of 6.96 percent,
using current yield rates. This comes in a little higher than most
investors who use the barbell strategy, since you've given heavier
weighting to the junk bond fund. (My favorite approach to building
such a portfolio is to put about a quarter of the portfolio in a
money market fund, a similar amount in junk bonds, and the balance
in a good GNMA fund, ending up with a portfolio average yield in
the neighborhood of 6 5/8 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the only way you can increase the yield from such a
portfolio is to move it further toward the higher-risk end of the
spectrum. One way would be to give the portfolio a still-heavier
weighting in junk bonds. Another approach would be to move the
money market funds into a somewhat more venturesome investment. A
small step in that direction might take you to Vanguard's
Short-Term Corporate Bond fund, where you could expect a yield of
about 6.1 percent, which compares to 5.06 percent from the money
market fund..
</P>
<P>
   Or you could increase the risk (and likely return) a bit more by
moving into Vanguard's GNMA fund, where you could expect a yield in
the 6.6 percent area.
</P>
<P>
   But I have a warning if you're contemplating increasing yield by
assuming higher risk _ don't do it unless you're very confident
that you can leave the principal alone for a number of years _ say
five at a minimum, and better yet a decade. The higher the risk
with bond funds, the more the funds will fluctuate when interest
rates change.
</P>
<P>
   With funds such as junk bonds and Ginnie Maes, you can expect
that the sledding will be very tough about two years out of every
ten _ they will keep distributing the yield checks during those
years, but your principal value is likely to fall fairly sharply.
The thing to do when this happens is simply ride out the storm. The
long-term track records show that eventually interest rates change
course again, and the funds then recover. But if you are compelled
to withdraw funds at a bad time you can end up a pretty substantial
loser.
</P>
<P>
   So if your budget is subject to the vagaries of the art market
and you do indeed find yourself drawing upon your principal from
time to time, my suggestion would be to leave the maximum that you
can imagine yourself withdrawing over a five-year period in the
money market fund, only moving the balance into the riskier and
higher-yielding funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I, aged 60 and 62, are selling our primary
residence and anticipate netting approximately $180,000. We will
live in our summer home temporarily until we decide upon another
primary residence more suitable to our early retirement status.
What do you recommend as a safe, easily accessible investment
vehicle with a reasonable return?
</P>
<P>
   R.V., Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since I'm assuming that you're likely to find your new home
within a period no longer than three or four years, I would treat
this money very cautiously. It is short-term money, and if you go
beyond vehicles such as money market funds or CDs, you could find
that the interest rate changes that affect even very conservative
bond funds, such as those holding short-term corporate debt
obligations, can bring declines that more than outweigh the
slightly higher returns that these offer when compared to CDs or
money markets.
</P>
<P>
   So you basically find yourself in the same position as a banker,
who must balance his short-term assets (loans and investments) with
liabilities (borrowings or deposits) of the same duration. Yes,
longer-term investments have a better potential for gain, but
mismatching the duration of an investment and the time frame during
which you will likely need to call upon it can cause agonies that
far outweigh to potential gains. So play it the strait, albeit
boring, way _ through the banks or the money markets.
</P>
<P>
   (But also note what I explained to D.M. above about the
difference between bank and credit union money market accounts and
those offered by mutual fund companies.)
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
