<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRRITABLE-BOWEL-HNS &LR;      01-04 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRRITABLE-BOWEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOWEL ILLNESS CAUSES PAIN AND EMBARRASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On some days, she has constant diarrhea. On
others, it strikes only after eating a piece of chocolate or
something containing milk.
</P>
<P>
   Her symptoms include bloating, gas and abdominal pain, sometimes
so severe that the only relief is staying in bed or close to a
bathroom. A trip to the doctor revealed nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received every test known to man,'' said the 28-year-old
Albany communications specialist. ``When it turned out to be
irritable bowel syndrome, there were no answers.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the biggest frustration for people with this condition.
This young woman didn't want to use her name because she's
embarrassed about an illness so common it strikes an estimated one
of out every five people.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies indicate that irritable bowel syndrome is the
second leading reason why people miss work, behind only the common
cold. Yet IBS is often a difficult illness to pinpoint. Besides
diarrhea, it may cause constipation and excessive flatulence in
some. For others, it's a combination of diarrhea and constipation.
</P>
<P>
   Gastroenterologists often will rule out other potential
problems, like inflammatory bowel disease, Crohn's disease or colon
cancer, before coming up with a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from an inside look at their colon, someone with IBS has
absolutely nothing wrong. There are no pockets, polyps or
inflammation. The problem is functional, not physical.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the colon as a hollow tube that pushes it contents
forward with muscle contractions, a process known as peristalsis.
People with IBS have contractions that are disordered or that move
in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   That's why an attack can sometime strike without warning.
Triggers may include specific foods, stress and hormones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying problem is a malfunction of the smooth
muscle,'' said Dr. David Lyon, a Schenectady gastroenterologist and
chair of the Department of Internal Medicine at Ellis Hospital.
``It's extraordinarily common.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever had diarrhea before a big exam or an important
interview, you can understand better how IBS works.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Quarrier, a gastroenterologist with Kaiser Permanente,
explained that people with IBS are extremely sensitive to normal
events, like hormonal changes in the body or stress. ``People who
have irritable bowel are more sensitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean the problem is in the head? In the past, it was
common for physicians to refer patients with IBS symptoms to a
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, patients were made to feel or told outright
they ought to get a grip on things and other unhelpful
suggestions,'' Lyon said. That doesn't mean relaxation and
visualization techniques can't help someone with IBS manage their
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in your head, it's in your gut,'' said Edward
Blanchard, a psychologist and director of the Center for Stress and
Anxiety Disorders at the University at Albany. ``I think there's a
connection between the head and the gut.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the premise of a study that Blanchard plans to undertake
in January looking at what sort of meditation strategies may be
helpful for people with IBS. For more information, call (518)
442-4025.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Salt II, an Ohio gastroenterologist and author of
the book ``Irritable Bowel Syndrome &AMP; the Mind-Body Brain-Gut
Connection,'' is convinced there's a link between brain and bowels.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for people with IBS and their physicians is coming
up with ways to manage the symptoms. Unfortunately, there is no
cure for IBS. Fiber supplements and some prescription relaxants may
help ease symptoms, but there's no specific remedy.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Salt outlines various strategies for identifying
and treating IBS, like keeping a food diary and trying to identify
the triggers.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the 28-year-old communications specialist is learning
to manage her symptoms. She's cut out caffeine, milk, chocolate and
soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a daily challenge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some days are especially trying. ``It's like having the stomach
flu,'' she said. ``After you go to the bathroom 10 times, you want
to shoot yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood is the Times Union health writer. She can be
reached at swoodtimesunion.com or (518) 454-5445.
</P>
</TEXT>
