</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-Y2K-PC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST ANY PC CAN BE FIXED TO DEAL WITH Y2K BUG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As an exterminator, Alan Friedman kills insects for a
living. But there's one pest that's got him stymied.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Houston Pest Management is now grappling with the
Year 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
   He runs his small, five-person business on four personal
computers, each one from a different manufacturer and purchased in
a different year. He's not sure he wants to shell out to have a
consultant fix his problem, so he's currently trying to fix it
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out whether these machines are
Y2K-compliant, whether the software I have is going to to work,''
Friedman said. ``We are sort of lost at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman is not alone. Like millions of other small business
owners who rely on personal computers, he is just now beginning to
grapple with the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   But both small business owners and home PC users don't have the
resources to hire professionals to help them. The computer industry
is just now coming around to the fact that these folks need
information, and they need it fast.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry experts say that, when it comes to the PC, the
Y2K bug is more of an annoyance than anything else. A personal
computer is not going to become a non-functioning block of metal,
glass and plastic on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it may report dates oddly. Programs that rely heavily
on dates, if they are not Y2K-compliant, may alter important data.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, however, should be rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent or more of PCs are capable of handling 2000 as
a date,'' said Chuck Mills, director of world-wide Y2K integration
efforts at Houston-based Compaq Computer Corp. ``But some cases, it
may be manual instead of automatic. You may have to manually type
the date in, but it will accept 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Y2K bug has been a reality for personal computers
since the creation of the original IBM PC in 1981, the industry
only began working on the problem in 1996. Most computer companies
say that products purchased in 1997 and on should be considered
Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   For Compaq, it's any PC sold since October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in a personal computer begins in the interaction
between two components _ the BIOS and the real-time clock.
</P>
<P>
   The BIOS (which stands for Basic Input Output System) handles
the simplest functions of the computer. It is the BIOS, for
example, that starts the process of starting operating systems such
as Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The real-time clock's function is to keep track of the time and
date. The root of the Y2K problem in a PC lies in the fact that the
year is only expressed as two digits in the real-time clock.
</P>
<P>
   When the computer is turned on, the BIOS gets the time and date
information from the clock. When software programs need to know the
date for some function, they ask the BIOS, which then supplies the
century information.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest PCs, BIOSes didn't ``know'' about the 21st
century, expressed as 20. For these systems, the real-time clock's
turnover to the year 2000 made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   On those machines that can't handle 2000 as a year, users likely
will see Jan. 1, 1980, which is considered ``Year Zero'' for
personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem does not affect Apple Computer's Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers have come up with fixes for the BIOS problems,
and are making use of the Internet and its World Wide Web to
deliver those fixes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tell people to check the Web first,'' said Leslie Schelp,
director of Compaq's Year 2000 program. ``That's the fastest way
they are going to get help.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal computer users such as Friedman need all the help they
can get. His systems range from two machines he bought last year
from a cable TV shopping channel to an older, 80486-based machine.
</P>
<P>
   The experts say that even fairly old systems can be made to
recognize 2000 as a year. David Cunningham, Year 2000 project
manager for Austin-based Dell Computer Corp., said the fixes he's
made available will work on PCs that use the relatively ancient
80286-era processors.
</P>
<P>
   Software and hardware manufacturers say there are a series of
steps PC owners can take to make sure 2000 rolls around smoothly:
</P>
<P>
   _ Begin by determining whether your personal computer itself is
capable of handling 2000 as a valid year.
</P>
<P>
   Check first with the maker of your PC. Many computer makers have
posted on their Web sites Y2K-compliance information about their
products. In some cases, every machine they've ever made is listed.
</P>
<P>
   If you own an off-brand PC, or one that was home-built,
determine who made the motherboard _ the main system board in the
computer _ and contact that vendor. Many clone systems come with a
manual for the motherboard that should provide contact information.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't determine who made the motherboard, you can at
least find out the maker of the BIOS. When your PC is first turned
on, the brand and model number of the BIOS appear briefly.
</P>
<P>
   You can always try to determine on your own if your PC is
Y2K-compliant. The simplest way to is advance the system clock to
11:55 p.m. on Dec. 31, 1999, then shut down the computer. Turn it
back on 15 minutes later. If the date is shown as Jan. 1, 2000,
then the hardware is ready for the new century.
</P>
<P>
   There also are software programs that will test a PC. One of
them is available as a free download from the National Software
Testing Laboratory at www.nstl.com/html/nstly2k.html.
</P>
<P>
   Computers that won't handle 2000 don't necessarily have to be
doorstops. Some BIOSes can be upgraded to make them compliant _
manufacturers make these patches available online or through
technical support services.
</P>
<P>
   For computers that have BIOSes that can't be upgraded, there are
software drivers than be inserted into a system's config.sys file.
For example, both Dell and Compaq have posted these files on their
Web sites. These patches can be used with very old PCs _ in some
cases, they will work with computers that use the Intel 80286
processor, circa 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A generic version of the driver is available from some
commercial software publishers. Symantec's Norton 2000 includes
one, for example.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do the same kind of research on your operating system. All of
Microsoft's operating systems have some problems _ mostly minor _
with 2000 as a year.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes Windows 98, the company's newest.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has released patches for Windows 95, 98 and NT, but
MS-DOS and Windows 3.1 are considered legacy operating systems and
have not been patched. Consider upgrading to one of the newer
versions if you are still using DOS and Windows 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it's important to make sure you have the latest for
your operating system. Several fixes in the latest service pack for
Windows NT 4.0 are required to bring it into Y2K compliance, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Year 2000 Web site is at www.microsoft.com/year2000.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent versions of IBM's OS/2 operating system, Warp 3
and 4, also require available patches to be Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Most versions of Unix either are or can be made Y2K compliant,
including Linux, the increasingly popular Unix-like operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a list of your frequently used software, starting with
the ones that are most important to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a home-PC owner, that might include your personal
finance program, your e-mail software and any productivity titles
you use, such as a word processor or a spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   A small business owner would look at accounting and inventory
packages, spreadsheets and databases, word processors and
communications software.
</P>
<P>
   Most up-to-date software applications are Y2K-compliant. Some
companies have issued software patches to make older versions of
their titles compliant, but others require users to upgrade to the
latest version.
</P>
<P>
   Check the Web site of the software publishers in question, or
contact the companies' phone technical support. As with operating
systems, make sure you have the most recent upgrades to your
current applications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Both types of users should check the documents made with those
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Are you using two digits to indicate the year in your
spreadsheets and word processing documents? Better change those to
four digits. And if you exchanged spreadsheet information with
other businesses, alert them to your changes as well.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's Schelp warns that, with older machines and software,
the simplest and possibly even most cost-effective solution is to
buy your way into Y2K compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do a cost-analysis,'' Schelp said. ``If you can replace that
PC for $1,500, and it will cost you twice that in time and effort,
you're better off just getting a new PC.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
