<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7225 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUG OF THE CENTURY PUTS BITE ON WALLETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History is full of dramatic technology screw-ups, ranging from
building the Tower of Pisa on sodden soil in Italy to the optical
flaw that made the Hubble Space Telescope a myopic wonder.
</P>
<P>
   But few are on as grand a scale as the so-called millennium bug,
in which many computers of all types are unable to understand that
the ``00'' coming after ``99'' in the year field represents the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen to a civilization largely run on computers at
the stroke of midnight Jan. 1, 2000, is anyone's guess _ and
everyone's guessing something different.
</P>
<P>
   Extremists believe we'll be confronted with the end of modern
society as we know it. Voices of reason say there will be some
problems here and there, but nothing widespread and major. Those
with their heads in the sand say it's a big fat hoax cooked up by
greedy, unscrupulous computer consultants.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one thing everyone agrees on. As 1999 begins, the
world's attention will sharply focus on trying to fix the Y2K
problem. So will the world's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Governments, businesses and individuals will spend billions,
maybe trillions, of dollars to fix what is simply a bone-headed,
preventable mistake. That's money that could have gone into
something really useful, other than re-employing the old COBOL
programmers who are being brought in to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   This should not have happened. But it did, and now someone has
to pay for it. That will be you and me.
</P>
<P>
   We'll pay for it in higher taxes, as governments spend cash they
likely don't have to make sure crucial services remain available.
</P>
<P>
   We'll pay for it through increased costs of goods and services
as companies hike prices to make up for Y2K-related expenses.
</P>
<P>
   We know who gets the bill. Who gets the blame?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the programmers trying to scrimp on system resources, or
merely out of laziness, who chose to designate the year with only
two digits?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the managers of those programmers, who didn't foresee that
the software and hardware they were building would be used far
enough into the future to pose a hazard?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the heads of government agencies and captains of industry
who, trying to save a buck, kept ancient computers in place long
after they should have been retired?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that last note doesn't explain why, even as late as
1997, some computers and software were being sold that still could
not handle 2000 as a year.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, sorry. Better make that 1998, because Windows 98 and
Windows NT 4.0 have Y2K problems, too. They've been fixed with
patches, but the notion that any mainstream software introduced 18
months before the dawn of 2000 is not Y2K-compliant is disturbing,
at least. Bill Gates should be ashamed of himself.
</P>
<P>
   I think the blame lies with all involved. Programmers should
have known better. Their managers should have insisted that the
software and hardware be engineered to handle four-digit year
designations.
</P>
<P>
   And bureaucrats and corporate titans should have heeded the
first rule of both evolution and technology: Upgrade or die.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of attention has been paid to those on the fringe who are
panicking over the Y2K bug. The coming of a new millennium has
always attracted the attention of the less rational among us who
believe that a simple change in the calendar means the end of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug has given the fringies more fodder. The worst-case
Y2K scenario has embedded processors failing in airplanes and
causing jetliners to fall out of the skies; banks losing all
electronic evidence of customers' assets; computer-controlled power
plants failing; food and consumer-good distribution systems being
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing this, some people are stocking up on a year's worth of
food; buying property high in the mountains; and brushing up on
their marksmanship so they can pick off marauding hordes of
looters.
</P>
<P>
   There's concern that Y2K hysteria may cause a run on banks late
in 1999, as people become more nervous about having access to their
funds. In fact, the federal mints will be printing more currency to
handle such an occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that the Y2K bug is likely to cause minor
annoyances in this country. Banks are doing very well when it comes
to fixing their Y2K problems. The utility companies are
successfully replacing embedded controllers that may cause
problems. And airplanes that haven't been fixed yet don't have to
take off.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not the end of the world _ literally or
figuratively. The Y2K bug is simply a mistake that we should not
let happen again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
