<HEADLINE>
DOWNLOADING FILES IS RATHER EASY, BUT TAKE NOTE WHERE THEY'RE
SAVED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently bought a new computer. The operating system is
Windows 98. I set it up yesterday and it's just great. I wanted to
download Winamp so I could play MP3 music on my computer. The only
problem is I don't know how to download things. Could you tell me
how to go about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Downloading is simple. There's just one tricky part if you
are a novice computer user, and that's knowing where you saved the
file.
</P>
<P>
   Before you do anything, open up My Computer, open on your C:
drive and create a new folder there called download. (Right-click
in an empty space in the C folder, choose New, then Folder, then
name it Download.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, use your browser to download a file you want. Find the link
on a Web page for the file, click on it, and a Save As box will
appear. (If you use Internet Explorer instead of Netscape
Communicator/Navigator, you may get an extra dialogue box asking if
you want to open or save it to disk _ always choose Save, in this
case.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll get the Save As box and at the top will be the name of
the folder in a little window, with an arrow next to it. Click on
the arrow and you'll be able to scroll through the various parts of
your computer. Find C:, click on it, then find the Download folder,
and double-click on that.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the file should already be in the Save as: field, so
click Save or OK, whatever is there. It will start saving. When
completed, the download window will go away.
</P>
<P>
   Now, go back to the download folder and find the file. If it's
an executable (with an .EXE extension), you'll just launch it like
any other program and it will start its install routine.
</P>
<P>
   It may, however, be a Zip file (.ZIP extension), which is a
compressed collection of the files used by the program. You'll need
to get a copy of an unzipping utility, like Winzip at
www.winzip.com. Of course, you'll have to download it ... but
Winzip comes as an EXE file. Run Winzip, then use it as a program
to open the other file you downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Within my 730-megabyte hard drive, 137 hidden files take up
about 19 MB of space. The main culprit is a file, W95UNDO.DAT, that
uses about 10 MB alone. What role does W95UNDO.DAT play in Windows
95's life? Will Windows 95 live if this file is deleted?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you have W95UNDO.DAT on your hard drive, then you upgraded
that system from Windows 3.1. That file is a compressed archive of
the Windows 3.1 files necessary to restore your system back to its
original, pre-Windows 95 state.
</P>
<P>
   You can delete it, but the safest way to do so is not by simply
nuking the file. Instead, look in the Add/Remove Programs module in
the Control Panel. You should see an item called ``Old Windows 3.x
and MS-DOS system files'' in the list of removable files. Choose it
and click Remove.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to other hidden files on your system _ don't remove
them if you are not absolutely certain what they are. For example,
one very large file in your Windows folder, with an extension of
SWP, is your Windows 95 swap file _ your system's virtual memory.
If you remove it, you'll be in a world of pain.
</P>
<P>
   You might be able to find out more about some files at the
Microsoft Knowledge Base at support.microsoft.com.
</P>
<P>
   I just got a new portable computer. I travel a lot, and am very
nervous about letting security guards run this laptop through the
X-ray machine. I have been told it's safe, but is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it's safe. An airport X-ray machine does not put out a
strong enough magnetic field to damage what's on your notebook
computer's hard disk. If you remain nervous about it, and if your
portable has a removable hard drive, pack that away separately in
luggage that you check.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
