<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-Y2K-SMALLBIZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BUSINESSES MAY BE AMONG MOST VULNERABLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By REBECCA MOWBRAY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The most painful sting of the millennium bug may be
felt at small businesses, where those who own and operate their own
companies rely heavily on computers but can't afford to have
someone fix the problem for them.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Wells Fargo Bank study released in April, 82
percent of small businesses risk Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   About 330,000 of these may be forced to close until a technician
is available to solve the problems, and 370,000 others could be
incapacitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case has not yet been made to a large number of small
business owners that it is worth it to devote resources to find out
if you have a problem,'' said study author William Denny, senior
researcher at the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Denny will release a follow-up analysis in January to see if small
businesses have begun to consider Y2K an urgent problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem is real, and there is no magic patch to fix it.
The insurance industry warns that upgrading computers is a routine
cost of doing business, and policies won't cover Y2K disasters that
strike companies that ignored warnings, said Robert Hartwig, chief
economist at the Insurance Information Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news is companies can do most of their Y2K
inventories themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In hunting for the millennium bug, companies can evaluate their
business operations and make them more productive.
</P>
<P>
   By making Y2K preparations, Christopher Talley, general manager
of the Fleishman-Hillard communications firm in Houston, said that
companies generate a marketing opportunity. A company should
advertise its streamlined, Y2K-ready operation as the one to
deliver the goods on Jan. 1, 2000, when competitors can't.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Administration advises small businesses to
start now. Companies should allow time to assess their situations
so they don't have to make important decisions about operational
equipment under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Most small businesses can fix their Year 2000 problems for less
than $1,000, SBA spokesman D.J. Caulfield said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the clock ticks, repairs may get more expensive because
technicians will be in short supply. If a business is forced to
close because of Y2K failures, when it can reopen may depend on how
soon a technician is available, Denny said.
</P>
<P>
   A company's Y2K investigations shouldn't end with computers.
Machinery and electronic devices such as security systems or cash
registers also may have Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   The level of Y2K risk at a business depends on how heavily the
company relies on computers and automated systems. Older or
custom-designed systems are the most likely to cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   Industry associations are a good source of information about
solving Y2K problems in software or machinery special to the field,
the SBA said, and may be able to recommend technicians who have
already found the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Some fixes may be tax deductible. The Internal Revenue Service
is allowing businesses to deduct the full cost of repairing or
converting existing software with a Y2K problem in a single year.
However, if that fix also makes non-Y2K improvements to the system,
the deduction must be spread across the usual three years.
</P>
<P>
   The SBA recommends a broad assessment of possible candidates for
Y2K problems because electronic components interface with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the major steps of the process it advocates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Awareness: Educate everyone in the company about Y2K issues
and keep them informed about progress.
</P>
<P>
   _ Organization: Create a team of people to lead the company's
Y2K efforts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inventory: Make a list of all hardware, software and anything
else that may have a chip with a date function. Record the vendor,
model and product identification numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Priorities: Label each piece of hardware critical, somewhat
critical, or not critical to the functioning of your business.
Start with the items that are most essential to the core business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assessment: Determine if the most critical items are
date-sensitive and if they will fail when the century changes.
Companies may need to work with the vendor on specialized systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Action: Repair, replace or retire each system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Testing: Test whether each repaired or replaced system works
properly when interfacing with other devices in the work
environment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contingency: In case something goes wrong on Jan. 1, 2000,
companies should make contingency plans for what they will do.
Companies may want to buy a generator or have the extra supplies on
hand that are most critical to their operations. Have some plan of
what to do and what to say to customers if in case the company's
Y2K efforts aren't foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
