<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-DISASTER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY PEOPLE QUIETLY PREPARING FOR POSSIBLE YEAR 2000 DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a cluttered attic corner in his Poestenkill,
N.Y., home, 36-year-old Doug Roseberger is quietly preparing for
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a year since the private school teacher and his wife
Susan first heard about the computer problems that could ensue at
12:01 a.m. Jan. 1, 2000. Since then, he's learned all he could
about Year 2000, or Y2K, threats: power outages, food shortages, a
major recession or, depending on whose web site you read, the
entire collapse of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Roseberger wants to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, he's been attending monthly meetings of the
Year 2000 Interest Group in Albany. Meanwhile, in his attic, he's
cached enough supplies to sustain his family, friends and neighbors
for weeks: cans of soup, cases of toilet paper, pasta, sauces,
peanut butter. Enough to stock a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Roseberger and his wife are hoping for the best. And preparing
for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to put your faith in a system that can crash in
seconds,'' Roseberger said. ``I've chosen to take it seriously.''
In the Capital Region, dozens are taking similar steps. Enough are
worried about Y2K that they have formed a monthly club to help
prepare for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But while some extremists say Y2K will cause The End Of The
World As We Know it, often shortened to EOTWAWKI, most other
experts are taking a much calmer approach. Learn what you can about
how Y2K can affect you, they advise. If you're a business, do what
you need to do to get your computers compliant.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're at it, you might want to get printouts of all
your financial records before the year 2000 and save up two weeks
worth of food. Just in case.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to believe that a calendar flipping from Dec. 31,
1999 to Jan. 1, 2000 could have such devastating effects. On the
other hand, it's even harder to shrug off the impact of this
simple, but extremely expensive, problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 ``bug,'' for those few who haven't heard, is not a
computer virus per se. It is a programming problem that seems to
exist in most of the world's major computer systems. When mainframe
computers were developed decades ago, programmers found they could
save limited memory space by lopping off the first two numbers of a
given year: the date 12.16.1974, for instance became simply
12.26.74.
</P>
<P>
   But when 1999 rolls over to 2000, that space-saving technique
will cause a major problem. Computers will read the ``00'' that
refers to 2000 as ``1900.'' Suddenly, in the mind of the mainframe,
someone who is 34 years old becomes negative 66 years old. And as
companies around the country tested their equipment for Y2K
``compliance,'' they found the change of dates can cause computers
to crash and equipment to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   The problem extends to all computer users, from nuclear power
plants and the Department of Defense to corner banks and your own
PC.
</P>
<P>
   After ignoring the problem for years, businesses are suddenly
sparing no expense to solve it _ which often involves hours and
hours of searching through dense program lines for offending codes.
</P>
<P>
   Programmers from the 1960s (some of whom knew this was going to
happen decades ago) have been lured from retirement with pay as
high as $75 per hour or more, plus bonuses. Others are being hired
from countries like Russia and India.
</P>
<P>
   The costs are mind-boggling. Chevron, the petrolium giant,
expects to pay between $200 million and $300 million to achieve
compliance. International Paper, $135 million. Merrill Lynch, as
much as $400 million. And the federal government? A whopping $4.6
billion, triple the original estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the final cost of solving the Y2K bug around the
world could run from several hundred billion dollars to as much as
$3.6 trillion (according to the book The Year 2000 Problem, by
Capers Jones, a software expert).
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Y2K has been featured in such prominent
places as 60 Minutes, CNN, the front page of the Sunday New York
Times, a feature story in Vanity Fair and the comic Ziggy.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of Y2K has convinced the British government to tell
its citizens to stock up a two-week supply of food. And Canada
recently announced ``Operation Abacus,'' which allows for the
deployment of as many as 32,000 troops to deal with Y2K's
worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   It's the worst-case scenerio that scares people like Roseberger.
It's the realization that so much in the world operates on a
delicate web of interrelated electronics. The thought that
everything, from the stock market to banking, planting crops to
landing airplanes, could be brought to a screeching halt if enough
computers fail.
</P>
<P>
   To some, it's so ironic it's almost funny. After a century of
fantastic technological achievements, the world will host history's
greatest New Year's party _ and then could wake to this planet's
first scheduled disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K Interest Group in Albany meets monthly in a quiet corner
room at the University of Albany Campus Center. The group, which
has been getting together for more than a year, is a well-dressed,
mostly-gray-haired bunch. Many are computer programmers, but the
group also counts a futurist, a teacher and a business manager
among its three dozen members.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Noticably absent are the survivalists who the group's president,
Dick Mills, calls the ``doom and gloom'' types.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really into the inflammatory rhetoric that they want
to hear,'' he said. ``So they don't come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the group watched a presentation by John Gibb of the
New York State Emergency Management Office about emergency planning
(``Why wait?'' the overhead transparencies said. ``Get ready for
next week.'').
</P>
<P>
   Gibb's point was to teach the group that disasters can happen
anytime. He said families should prepare by keeping two weeks worth
of food in the house and have an emergency heating source and other
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope next year we can look back and say, `What a colossal
waste of time that was,''' Gibb said. ``But why wait? Individuals,
communities, businesses need to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy for Gibb to finish his speech. Several people
kept asking questions he couldn't answer, demanding to know, for
instance, what the state was doing to make sure cities and towns
were Y2K compliant (answer: they are providing information and Y2K
audits, but have little authority to demand readiness).
</P>
<P>
   Doug Roseberger, the schoolteacher from Poestenkill, also
attended the meeting. A few nights later, sitting with his wife
near a wood-burning stove in his country home, he recalled how he
first heard of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   It was fall of 1997, and a pastor handed Roseberger a pamphlet
about Y2K. He had a hard time believing what he read. ``It seemed
like a cruel joke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Roseberger a few days of denial, and then some research,
to discover that there were many people who were taking this cruel
joke very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Roseberger keeps a large box filled with Y2K information
from the Internet. ``Power,'' says one folder. ``Military.''
``Power and gas.'' ``Y2K and the Church.'' And, in a slim folder,
``Rosy Scenarios,'' which is filled with diatribes from groups like
the John Birch Society, which believes the Y2K scare is nothing but
hype.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, Roseberger and his wife Susan have been
busy preparing for what, 12 months from now, could be a very rude
New Year.
</P>
<P>
   They already have enough food and other supplies to feed a large
family for a few weeks, but they plan to add much more to the
stock. They also plan to install a hand pump in their backyard well
to ensure access to fresh water and, in case things are really bad,
plans to plant a garden this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Roseberger been warning everyone he knows about
the threat of Y2K. It's an uphill process. Few people even glanced
at the Y2K literature he tried to give away. And his previous boss
told Roseberger he would lose his job if he continued to tell his
co-workers about Y2K (Roseberger later quit).
</P>
<P>
   The more he looked into it, the more worried he became. It was
so easy for San Francisco to suffer a blackout from a simple
breakdown of the electric grid. So easy for nearly all the pagers
in the country to go off-line when a satellite went down. So easy
for computer crashes to have a domino effect, taking down industry
and government pitilessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of fear at first,'' said Susan. ``It's very
overwhelming. We've prayed about it a lot, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are doing more than praying. A look at Albany Medical
Center shows how extensively businesses are attacking Y2K - and how
much it's costing them.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, Albany Med staff have examined 8,000
machines used in the care of patients. They've also looked at
elevators, the heating system, security devices, the high-tech fire
alarms, thousands of desktop PCs, the pneumatic tube system (used
for delivering items to different departments), lighting equipment
and machines used to clean the floors.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Rounds, vice president for plant management, said the
hospital expects all non-compliant computers and machines to be
replaced by the new year, at a cost of several million dollars.
However, as a precaution, more than 100 key employees will be
celebrating New Year's Eve 1999 at the hospital, just in case their
skills are needed.Other organizations are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is no surprises,'' said Gary Schwartz, who is on
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute's Y2K team. ``It's okay for it not
to work, if you know it's not going to work.'' Smaller companies
that need their computers fixed are going to places like the
Compaq/Digital Year 2000 Expertise Center on Washington Avenue
Extension. The quiet office, where computer experts examine systems
and repair or replace any programs that won't work next year, is
one of 19 Compaq operates around the world.
</P>
<P>
   One expert is Mills, the president of the local Y2K group.
Mills, 54, has been a programmer for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very responsible,'' he said. ``I feel absolutely awful
that our profession has let this damned calamity happen to the
world. That's why I'm involved so much - conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills is also the member of the group Computer Professionals for
Social Responsibility - which is currently involved in debunking
Y2K misinformation and stopping the spread of panic.
</P>
<P>
   This group does not believe that the stock market will crash,
governments will collapse and the world will fall into anarchy.
However, they do believe there is the possibility power could go
out for a few days. So Mills is installing a wood stove in his
home, and is following advice to keep two weeks worth of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems are substantial,'' he said. ``We are saying
people want to have 14 days of self-sufficiency. But don't prepare
for the end of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
