<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-MUSEUMS-1000(2T     01-04 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MUSEUMS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STATE TOUR OF NEW AND IMPROVED TEXAS MUSEUMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turn any which way in Texas these days and you bump into another
new art museum. Or plans for another new art museum. Actually,
we're talking about $254 million in projects recently completed,
currently under construction, in development and recently proposed
_ from El Paso to Dallas, Corpus Christi to San Angelo, and a
number of points in between.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the numbers that impress: The architects
involved rank high in an international community that values art
museum commissions above all others. And some of their projects
potentially may compare with Louis Kahn's Kimbell Art Museum in
Fort Worth and Renzo Piano's Menil Collection in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There is Rafael Moneo's new building for the Museum of Fine
Arts, Houston; Tadao Ando's plans for a new Modern Art Museum of
Fort Worth; The Blanton Museum at the University of Texas in
Austin, which will be designed by Herzog &AMP; de Meuron; and Philip
Johnson's new wing for the Amon Carter Museum in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Too, Texas boasts prime examples of adaptive reuse of buildings
for visual art exhibition _ two of which opened last year, one in
El Paso, another in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   So, herewith, a survey of new Texas art museum architecture:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON MUSEUM OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1952
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joan Davidow
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Neil Denari, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Construction cost: $2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Museum officials are conducting a feasibility study
of Denari's plan to renovate and expand the 45-year-old former J.C.
Penney department store that is the museum's home in downtown
Arlington _ with the project anchoring general plans for downtown
revitalization. Blending classical and techo-modern styles, the
plan expands gallery space, from 8,000 to 10,000 square feet. But
more than that, it would transform the quality of space and its
relationship to its environs. A concurrent campaign would raise $2
million in operating endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 275-4600
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN MUSEUM OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1943
</P>
<P>
   Director: Elizabeth Ferrer
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Richard Gluckman, New York
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: Estimated at $35 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Gluckman will complete his design this year for the
new facility _ his first free-standing museum _ with groundbreaking
scheduled for 2000 and dedication hoped for in 2002. Featuring
25,000 square feet of gallery space, the facility will occupy a
full city block in downtown, fulfilling patrons' longtime dream of
a centrally located museum. The museum will maintain its longtime
site at Laguna Gloria, the historic suburban estate that it shares
with the Texas Fine Arts Association.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 495-9224
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACK S. BLANTON MUSEUM OF ART, AUSTIN
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1963
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jesse Otto Hite
</P>
<P>
   Architects: Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, Basel, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $30 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Scheduled to open in late 2002, the building will
serve as a gateway to the University of Texas campus. Historically,
the Blanton (formerly the Huntington Gallery) was divided between
the school's art building and the ground floor of the Ransom
Humanities Research Center. Team spokesman Jacques Herzog envisions
tiled canopies, watercourses and filtered light as responses to the
area's intense heat. He also is pondering a courtyard for
pedestrian flow between campus and Austin proper.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 471-7324
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS FINE ARTS ASSOCIATION, AUSTIN
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1911
</P>
<P>
   Director: Sue Graze
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Gary Cunningham, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $1.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Building: Cunningham adapted a 2-story commercial building in
downtown Austin; built in the 1850s, it may be the oldest brick
building in the city. Planned in two stages, with only stage one
completed, the building (in which Cunningham deconstructs the
present and reveals much of the past) ultimately will feature about
10,000 square feet of exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 453-5312
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ART MUSEUM OF SOUTH TEXAS, CORPUS CHRISTI
</P>
<P>
   Founded: Early 1940s
</P>
<P>
   Director: William G. Otton
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Ricardo Legorreta, Mexico City
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $4 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Legorreta has been commissioned to design a new
education building near Philip Johnson's 1972 museum, which is on
the Corpus Christi ship channel and features 15,000 square feet of
exhibition space. Specific plans have not been presented, but the
new structure needs to address Johnson's sculptural,
poured-in-place concrete building, whose window walls open the
museum to sky and water.
</P>
<P>
   Hours, information: (512) 884-3844
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   MEADOWS MUSEUM, DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1962
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Lunsford
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Hammond Beebe and Babka, Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $22 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Now housed in residential-style rooms in the
Meadows School of the Arts at Southern Methodist University, the
new Meadows will occupy a so-called collegiate Georgian facility
that is a safe bet to blend into SMU's campus. Scheduled to open in
early 2001, the desperately needed new building will feature about
14,000 square feet of exhibition space that will permit exhibition
of the museum's splendid permanent collection of Hispanic art, in
addition to borrowed shows.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (214) 768-2516
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EL PASO MUSEUM OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1930
</P>
<P>
   Director: Becky Duval Reese
</P>
<P>
   Architect: BKM Architects, El Paso
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $8 million
</P>
<P>
   Building: Constructed on the foundations of a downtown bus
terminal, the new home of the El Paso Museum of Art features 30,000
square feet of gallery space. It will allow the museum to exhibit
its surprisingly rich permanent collection of European Old Masters
and contemporary regional works, as well as present temporary
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (915) 532-1707
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MODERN ART MUSEUM OF FORT WORTH
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1892
</P>
<P>
   Director: Marla Price
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Tadao Ando, Osaka, Japan
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $60 million (including $10 million for
site)
</P>
<P>
   Building: Ando's building is scheduled to open in 2002,
replacing the museum's longtime home designed by Herbert Bayer,
with an addition by O'Neil Ford. A 2-story pavilion of poured
concrete encased in glass, it will feature about 50,000 square feet
of gallery space, with special areas for sculpture, oversize
paintings and works on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 738-9215
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMON CARTER MUSEUM, FORT WORTH
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1961
</P>
<P>
   Director: Patrick Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Philip Johnson, New York
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: Estimated $25.5 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Philip Johnson's original memorial to Amon G.
Carter opened in 1961; two later additions will be demolished for
the architect's new wing, scheduled to open in the early 21st
century. Clad in granite and limestone, it will feature about
27,000 square feet of gallery space. Yet another Texas project for
Johnson, it has prompted the architect to say he should have based
himself here rather than in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 738-1933
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS, HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1900
</P>
<P>
   Director: Peter Marzio
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Rafael Moneo, Madrid
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $57 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: The MFAH occupies a number of buildings, spread
over two campuses. Its decorative arts collections and gardens are
in River Oaks, while its fine arts and education operations live in
Houston's Montrose neighborhood _ the site of Moneo's new Beck
wing, with its 85,400 square feet of gallery space. Boxy and
masculine, the Beck will be linked by a James Turrell-designed
tunnel to the museum's main building, which comprises William Ward
Watkins' 1924 beaux-arts structure and Mies van der Rohe's soaring
pavilion, completed in 1974. Then there's the museum's glass-brick
Glassell School, designed by Eugene Aubrey; the children's
education building, designed by Carlos Jimenez; and Isamu Noguchi's
Cullen Sculpture Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (713) 639-7300
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANGELO MUSEUM OF FINE ARTS
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1981
</P>
<P>
   Director: Howard Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Malcolm Holzman of Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer, New York
and Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $6 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Scheduled to open in 1999, Holzman's new $6 million
building features 3,500 square feet of gallery space, as well as a
ceramics studio and kiln yard that serves the museum's focus as a
major center for contemporary ceramics. The building is covered by
a copper saddleback roof and has facades of regional limestone.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (915) 658-4084
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ART CENTER, WACO
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1972
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joe Kagle
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Short list of contenders for the commission is
composed of Philip Johnson and Alan Ritchie of New York; William
McDounough of Charlottesville, N.C.; and Rich Sundberg of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: About $2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Building: The Art Center plans a new 20,000-square-foot
exhibition space to be constructed near its facility in a historic
former residence. (That will be converted to a children's art
museum). The Art Center also has a number of off-site exhibition
spaces, with their policy of openness symbolized by an immense door
sculpture by Waco native Robert Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (254) 752-4371
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact her at vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
