<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7297 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS05-COX     01-04 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOCAL TV NEWS: GOOD OR BAD PAYS OFF IN RATINGS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Local newscasts can win ratings wars by being
either tony or trashy in their coverage but not by being
wishy-washy, a national media study showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report ranked TV newscasts at 61 stations in 20 cities and
discovered a complex correlation between quality news programming
and viewership. The stations with rising ratings either featured
more in-depth, so-called serious reporting or they specialized in
``tabloid'' news and were ranked lowest in ``quality'' by the
study's panel of news professionals and journalism scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The stations least likely to be gaining viewers were those
ranked in the middle in terms of quality.
</P>
<P>
   The survey indicated that ``the important thing is that whatever
you do, go whole hog,'' said Carl Gottlieb, deputy director of the
Project for Excellence in Journalism, the Washington, D.C.,
institute that conducted the study.
</P>
<P>
   The finding ``suggests that audiences are not schizophrenic _
they are segmenting,'' the report concluded. ``There is a group
that embraces news full of revelation, scandal and celebrity. There
is another group that prefers a more serious, information-based
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar observations can be made about newspapers, said
Gottlieb, a 23-year veteran of local TV news including stints at
Fox News and Tribune Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have The New York Times and The New York Post in New York
City'' with vastly different approaches to covering the news and
little overlap in readership, he explained. ``It's not so
surprising that the same thing occurs in TV news.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding that was deemed surprising was the rising ratings
for high quality newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that viewer preference for murder and mayhem in
local news is just another urban myth,'' said Tom Rosenstiel,
director of the project and former media critic for the Los Angeles
Times. ``There's still a market for tabloid news, but quality
sells, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was a debunking of the notion that viewers prefer
shorter stories. The stations with improving ratings produced more
long stories and fewer very short ones (under 20 seconds) than did
the stations with falling ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusions were reached after the panel of experts analyzed
the most popular half-hour news timeslot in 20 cities ranging from
Atlanta to Wichita during a sweeps week and non-sweeps week in
March and April. In all, about 8,500 stories from 600 broadcasts
were studied.
</P>
<P>
   A ``design team'' of news professionals and academics developed
criteria for measuring ``quality'' that included the newscast
closely reflecting the community, covering a wide range of issues,
containing balanced stories, focusing on significant issues and
ideas, citing multiple sources and quoting authoritative people.
The ``quality'' scores of the newscasts were then correlated to
their Neilsen ratings trends over the three-year period from July
1995 to May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the stations with rising ratings tended to
get either an ``A'' or an ``F'' in their grade for quality. Those
least likely to be gaining viewers were in the middle _ often
hybrid newscasts featuring part tabloid, part ``serious''
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, for instance, the study's lowest ``quality'' grade _
an F-plus _ went to the CBS affiliate, WGNX, which was also the
city's only station in the study with rising ratings over the
studied period. In its comments, the study said WGNX had ``the
highest story count in Atlanta'' _ which translates to short
segments _ and ``little investigative reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   The station in Atlanta with the highest ``quality'' grade _ a D
_ was WXIA, which had flat ratings. The report said this NBC
affiliate ``covered institutions and big players in town'' and was
``heavy on unusual events.''
</P>
<P>
   The third Atlanta station studied in the survey was WSB _ with
received a grade of D-minus and had declining ratings. ``Fast-paced
shows. Lots of breaking news. Nearly a third of all stories on
routine crimes,'' was the assessment. WSB is owed by Cox
Broadcasting _ a corporate cousin to Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the dichotomy of the effect on ``quality'' on ratings
are KARE of Minneapolis/St. Paul and WABC in New York City. Both
are gaining viewers. However, KARE was given an A-plus and declared
the ``best among big city stations.'' Meanwhile, WABC received an
F-plus and was critiqued as ``heavy on crime and law stories. Lots
of scandal and sensation. Not very local.''
</P>
<P>
   Stations were studied in Atlanta; Albuquerque; Boston; Buffalo;
Burlington, Vt.; Chicago; Evansville, Ind.; Jacksonville, Fl.;
Lansing, Mi.; Los Angeles; Louisville, Ky.; Minneapolis/St. Paul;
New York; Pittsburgh; Seattle; St. Louis; Tallahassee; Tuscon;
Washington, D.C.; and Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   The stations weren't told about the study ``until after the
fact,'' said Gottlieb. ``We were not looking for cooperation'' from
the newscasts being analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The study was financed by the Pew Charitable Trusts. The Project
for Excellence in Journalism is an affiliate of the Columbia
University Graduate School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Local newscasts feature a lot of ``journalism on the run.''
Almost half (46 percent) of the stories were about commonplace
events such as crimes and crashes. In stories involving
controversy, 43 percent presented only one side.
</P>
<P>
   _ Local news is not the same everywhere. While many stations do
``produce a formulaicconsultant-driven style'' of coverage, the
range of quality is wider than most critics contend.
</P>
<P>
   (end)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
