<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7299 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     01-04 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO DISCARD THIS VENOMOUS POLITICAL BREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our country needs healing, not vengeance; reconciliation, not
revenge. The nation is still in shock from the events of Dec. 19,
when the House voted for only the second time in history to impeach
a president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The public perception of a thoroughly partisan proceeding was
heightened by the predetermined refusal of House leaders to allow a
vote on the motion to substitute censure for impeachment. Several
Republicans have since declared that they'd have supported the
censure option. Apparently it would have passed.
</P>
<P>
   All this has set off widespread lamentation about what has
happened to open-mindedness, bipartisan cooperation, mutual respect
and due process in Congress. Suddenly, commentators everywhere are
decrying the ``slash-and-burn'' politics of ``mutually assured
destruction.'' It's as though the vicious polarization that divides
the parties into hostile camps, each committed to taking no
prisoners, had sprung full blown just this year.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a deadly virus of calculated character assassination
has been gradually infesting our body politic for a decade or more.
A cult of personal disparagement has littered the national
landscape with the wreckage of broken careers and ruined
reputations. Its victims include the guilty and the innocent, their
good names assaulted in campaign ads and deliberate news leaks and
sometimes by overzealous prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The growing list of political assault victims includes former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy and former HUD Secretary Henry
Cisneros, forced to cut short their promising political careers
over charges involving things as petty as having accepted tickets
to a football game and as personal as making a generous settlement
from one's own money with a former paramour.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, although legally exonerated by unanimous jury verdict,
suffered loss of his job, damaging personal publicity and legal
bills reportedly near a million dollars. On being acquitted, Espy
recalled former Labor Secretary Ray Donovan, who in a similar
situation asked: ``Where do I go now to get back my reputation?''
</P>
<P>
   Nor have Republicans been left unscathed. The epidemic of
negativism, once unloosed, finds few mortals immune to injury.
Ironically, two of those who sat in judgment on President Clinton's
peccadilloes _ Reps. Dan Burton and Henry Hyde _ were themselves
subjected to public disclosure of embarrassing events in their
personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Hate begets hate. Vengeance breeds vengefulness. It is of these
that history's most destructive deeds are made.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always thus at the top levels of American political
life. Once the personal honor of a president was precious even to
the leaders of his domestic political opposition, and jealously
protected by them. Other presidents have committed marital
infidelities. Others have obfuscated, fudged, misrepresented facts
_ lied, if you will. Not even their harshest critics clamored for
their impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For most of my 35 years in Congress there was a bond of
fellowship and mutual honor between leaders of rival parties. Sam
Rayburn never would tolerate a disparaging remark about Republican
leader Joe Martin. Everett Dirksen and Lyndon B. Johnson
collaborated.
</P>
<P>
   John Rhodes of Arizona was the House minority leader when I
became majority leader. Occasionally I accompanied him to plead his
case to President Jimmy Carter in matters of importance to Rhodes'
state. When he ran for governor of Arizona, I contributed to his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual respect is the essential oil that lubricates the
machinery of a democratic society. It is what separates us from the
world's tinpot dictatorships in which leaders of the vanquished
party routinely end up in prison. It's what makes a party-line
impeachment alarming.
</P>
<P>
   When I called Speaker-designate Bob Livingston in early December
to congratulate him on his selection by the Republican conference,
Livingston told me that he wanted to try to heal the ugly wounds of
dislike, distrust and accusation that so angrily divide his party
from mine in the House these days.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure he meant it. It's a pity he was denied that chance by
the same slobbering greed for personal scandal that some members of
his party have exploited in their unrelenting drive to destroy
Clinton's presidency. It is a vastly different House than the one I
knew.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago I stood where Speaker-designate Dennis Hastert
stands today, poised to take the oath as speaker. Then, as now, the
nation was numbed by a major scandal. The illegal Iran-contra
scheme had violated at least six laws. Some administration
spokesmen had lied to Congress. Evidence was being hastily shredded
in a feverish cover-up attempt. This was the most alarming
revelation since Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   A volcanic lava of hot anger began boiling inside Congress. Some
Democrats growled that these were ``impeachable'' offenses. Several
committees were clamoring to open hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The public interest, as I saw it, would not be served by
whipping a media frenzy into a constitutional crisis. The last
thing our country needed, I believed, was an impeachment outcry
impugning the president's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan, deeply shaken, insisted that he'd neither
condoned nor known of the illegal covert deeds. Although Reagan and
I disagreed on policy, I wanted to believe him and chose to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, then Senate majority leader, agreed with me
that even to entertain discussion of impeachment would be a grave
national disservice. We appointed one joint high-level
investigating committee composed of committee chairmen, with equal
numbers of Democrats and Republicans; we established a reasonable
time limitation for its proceedings; and we told our appointees
that we wanted no talk of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   May the Senate be mindful of its capacity for good or lasting
harm. And may it recall the ancient prayer of Aristophanes. Walking
among the ruins of the Greek temples destroyed by the fratricidal
Peloponnesian wars, he begged: ``From the murmur and subtlety of
suspicion with which we vex one another, give us rest. Make a new
beginning ... and with some finer essence of forbearance temper our
minds.'' To this, amen.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-MUSEUMS-1000(2T     01-04 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MUSEUMS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STATE TOUR OF NEW AND IMPROVED TEXAS MUSEUMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turn any which way in Texas these days and you bump into another
new art museum. Or plans for another new art museum. Actually,
we're talking about $254 million in projects recently completed,
currently under construction, in development and recently proposed
_ from El Paso to Dallas, Corpus Christi to San Angelo, and a
number of points in between.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the numbers that impress: The architects
involved rank high in an international community that values art
museum commissions above all others. And some of their projects
potentially may compare with Louis Kahn's Kimbell Art Museum in
Fort Worth and Renzo Piano's Menil Collection in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There is Rafael Moneo's new building for the Museum of Fine
Arts, Houston; Tadao Ando's plans for a new Modern Art Museum of
Fort Worth; The Blanton Museum at the University of Texas in
Austin, which will be designed by Herzog &AMP; de Meuron; and Philip
Johnson's new wing for the Amon Carter Museum in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Too, Texas boasts prime examples of adaptive reuse of buildings
for visual art exhibition _ two of which opened last year, one in
El Paso, another in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   So, herewith, a survey of new Texas art museum architecture:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON MUSEUM OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1952
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joan Davidow
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Neil Denari, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Construction cost: $2.5 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Museum officials are conducting a feasibility study
of Denari's plan to renovate and expand the 45-year-old former J.C.
Penney department store that is the museum's home in downtown
Arlington _ with the project anchoring general plans for downtown
revitalization. Blending classical and techo-modern styles, the
plan expands gallery space, from 8,000 to 10,000 square feet. But
more than that, it would transform the quality of space and its
relationship to its environs. A concurrent campaign would raise $2
million in operating endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 275-4600
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN MUSEUM OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1943
</P>
<P>
   Director: Elizabeth Ferrer
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Richard Gluckman, New York
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: Estimated at $35 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Gluckman will complete his design this year for the
new facility _ his first free-standing museum _ with groundbreaking
scheduled for 2000 and dedication hoped for in 2002. Featuring
25,000 square feet of gallery space, the facility will occupy a
full city block in downtown, fulfilling patrons' longtime dream of
a centrally located museum. The museum will maintain its longtime
site at Laguna Gloria, the historic suburban estate that it shares
with the Texas Fine Arts Association.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 495-9224
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JACK S. BLANTON MUSEUM OF ART, AUSTIN
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1963
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jesse Otto Hite
</P>
<P>
   Architects: Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, Basel, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $30 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Scheduled to open in late 2002, the building will
serve as a gateway to the University of Texas campus. Historically,
the Blanton (formerly the Huntington Gallery) was divided between
the school's art building and the ground floor of the Ransom
Humanities Research Center. Team spokesman Jacques Herzog envisions
tiled canopies, watercourses and filtered light as responses to the
area's intense heat. He also is pondering a courtyard for
pedestrian flow between campus and Austin proper.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 471-7324
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS FINE ARTS ASSOCIATION, AUSTIN
</P>
<P>
   Founded: 1911
</P>
<P>
   Director: Sue Graze
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Gary Cunningham, Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $1.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Building: Cunningham adapted a 2-story commercial building in
downtown Austin; built in the 1850s, it may be the oldest brick
building in the city. Planned in two stages, with only stage one
completed, the building (in which Cunningham deconstructs the
present and reveals much of the past) ultimately will feature about
10,000 square feet of exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (512) 453-5312
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ART MUSEUM OF SOUTH TEXAS, CORPUS CHRISTI
</P>
<P>
   Founded: Early 1940s
</P>
<P>
   Director: William G. Otton
</P>
<P>
   Architect: Ricardo Legorreta, Mexico City
</P>
<P>
   Construction budget: $4 million
</P>
<P>
   The project: Legorreta has been commissioned to design a new
education building near Philip Johnson's 1972 museum, which is on
the Corpus Christi ship channel and features 15,000 square feet of
exhibition space. Specific plans have not been presented, but the
new structure needs to address Johnson's sculptural,
poured-in-place concrete building, whose window walls open the
museum to sky and water.
</P>
<P>
   Hours, information: (512) 884-3844
</P>
