</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION WRITERS CHOOSE CLINTON, POPE AS YEAR'S TOP NEWSMAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who was the top religion newsmaker of 1998? We members of the
Religion Newswriters Association couldn't make up our minds.
</P>
<P>
   So President Clinton and Pope John Paul II, for dramatically
different reasons, finished in a tie for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the ritual of welcoming in the new year, the 200
members of our association vote on the top religion newsmakers and
top 10 religion stories.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton finished in a tie with the pope because the debates over
his possible removal from office have forced the nation into an
introspective look at moral behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He forced us to reflect on sin, broken promises and
forgiveness,'' states a news release summing up the association's
decisions. ``He also helped expose national fault lines on
questions of morality and repentance.'' The association is made up
of religion writers for secular newspapers, magazines and
broadcasting outlets.
</P>
<P>
   I cast my vote for the pope, because of the impact of his visit
to Cuba last January. Speaking before 1 million people in one of
the world's last outposts of communism, he called on Cuban leader
Fidel Castro to give more freedom to the people of the island
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Castro did what the pope asked, to a point. While still vowing
to keep communism, Castro released dozens of political prisoners.
Also, he brought joy back to the island by re-establishing
Christmas as a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 religion stories of the year also lean toward Pope
John Paul II and Clinton. Here they are, in order of importance:
</P>
<P>
   1. President Clinton's sexual entanglements with former White
House intern Monica Lewinski provoke a national debate over moral
issues.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pope John Paul II visits Cuba and meets with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   3. A church court fails by one vote to convict the Rev. Jimmy
Creech, former pastor of the First United Methodist Church of
Omaha, of violating church law by performing a same-sex
``marriage'' for a lesbian couple. The action explodes into a
churchwide controversy. Meeting in a hotel in Irving, Texas, the
United Methodist Judicial Council, the highest court of the
denomination, stiffens the penalties against such conduct. They
rule that Methodist statements barring clergy from conducting
same-sex ceremonies have the force of church law.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Southern Baptist Convention, meeting in Salt Lake City,
approves a new church statement on the family that has caused a
furor among defenders of equal rights for women. The most volatile
part of the statement declares that wives should ``submit
graciously to the servant leadership of their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   5. The killing of Matthew Shephard, a gay student at the
University of Wyoming, provokes outrage from many quarters. Also,
debate intensifies over ads by the Family Research Council and
other groups declaring that homosexuals can change their sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   6. A Vatican statement on the Holocaust expresses remorse over
the failure of some Christians to take a stand against the Nazi
regime. But the Vatican's defense of Pope Pius XII, the pontiff
during World War II, brings criticism from some Jewish groups.
Also, Pope John Paul II canonizes Edith Stein, a German Jew who
converted to Catholicism and died in Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   7. Led by a few conservative American bishops and many more from
Africa and other nations, the world's Anglican and Episcopal
bishops approve a statement at the Lambeth Conference in
Canterbury, England, that states that homosexual practice is
incompatible with biblical teachings. The statement is not binding.
</P>
<P>
   8. Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the Michigan physician who believes
euthanasia is merciful, is charged with murder after the television
news show ``60 Minutes'' airs a tape of Kevorkian helping a man
commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   9. The Rev. Henry Lyons, president of the National Baptist
Convention, U.S.A., is indicted on 56 federal charges, including
extortion and fraud. He also admits to an ``improper relationship''
with a female former employee of the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   10. Karla Faye Tucker, who became an eloquent and persuasive
born-again Christian on Texas' Death Row, provokes more debate on
the death penalty. Tucker, who was convicted of a pickax slaying,
publicly pleads for her life, and Pope John Paul II and Christian
Broadcasting Network leader Pat Robertson, among others, join in
asking for clemency. Despite their pleas, Tucker is put to death by
lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
