<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7320 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FOOTBALL-ASTHMA-A     01-04 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FOOTBALL-ASTHMA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH RATES OF ASTHMA ARE FOUND IN ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How common is undiagnosed asthma among athletes? Worried about
the risk the increasingly common lung disease poses, Temple
University researchers have come up with a straightforward method
of finding out: they asked a group of high school football players
to run a mile, and then used a simple breath test to quantify the
huffing and puffing afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The results from one recent survey were disconcerting, but they
could provide a basis for a simple program to help coaches and
trainers detect and treat the condition, the study's author, Dr.
Gilbert D'Alonzo Jr., said in a telephone interview. Of the 214
players tested _ none of whom had received diagnoses of asthma _ 9
percent had exercise-induced bronchospasms, a serious form of
airway obstruction that is typical of asthma. While the finding is
not the same as a definitive diagnosis, which takes observation
over time, it is regarded as a useful stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alonzo, the deputy director of pulmonary medicine at Temple
University in Philadelphia, said he found that percentage
surprisingly high. ``To get to varsity football you need pretty
decent talent,'' he said, ``and you would have thought that most of
the kids with breathing problems would have been filtered out.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that the rate of undiagnosed asthma was
highest _ 13 percent _ among African-American athletes at the
inner-city schools included in the study, which was published last
month in Chest, the journal of the American College of Chest
Physicians. A host of earlier studies have found higher rates of
the disease among minorities, inner-city residents and the poor.
``In the suburban groups, the players knew about their asthma,''
D'Alonzo said. ``The kids in the inner city had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But D'Alonzo found that the affluent suburban and the poor urban
athletes who had been given diagnoses of asthma had one other
worrisome problem in common: None of them were bringing their
medication to the field.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, he said, awareness of asthma's dangers was
raised this fall when a high school cross country runner nearly
died during a training run. The student had left her asthma
medication at home. Fortunately, she was with a friend, who flagged
down a motorist who got her to an emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alonzo said that years of study have convinced him that asthma
attacks are ``by far the greatest threat to the student athletes
today.'' Dr. Jordan Metzl, a sports-medicine pediatrician at the
Hospital for Special Surgery in Manhattan, agreed. ``Asthma is the
most common chronic disease among children,'' Metzl said, ``and an
acute asthma attack is life-threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded by the reluctance of athletes to tell
their coaches about shortness of breath. ``I played college
basketball with asthma,'' D'Alonzo said, ``and I never said
anything: I thought I'd have to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some ``drug-free'' schools include inhaled asthma
medication on their list of banned substances, D'Alonzo recommends
that athletes with asthma be allowed to take two puffs of
albuterol, a widely used prescription medication that clears the
air pathways, before a game and once again during competition if
needed. But if wheezing persists, the player should probably sit
out the rest of the game. He also recommends that all trainers have
an albuterol inhaler in their medicine bag.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Madden, a health educator with the National Center for
Environmental Health in Atlanta, emphasized that having asthma
``doesn't mean you have to give up sports. It's a chronic disease,
but one that can be managed.'' Coaches need to be on the lookout
for players with undiagnosed cases, and to be aware of the
abilities, limitations and warning signs for athletes with asthma
on their teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
