<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7326 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MULTIPLE-BIRTHS-A     01-04 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MULTIPLE-BIRTHS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING MULTIPLE BIRTH FEARS IN FERTILITY CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DOROTHY J. BARNHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fertility drugs provide a mix of hope and fear to those who are
taking them _ hope that the treatment will result in pregnancy and
fear that it will cause high-order multiples, defined as triplets
or more. This fear has been heightened recently with the birth of
the Chukwu octuplets in Houston, whose mother took fertility drugs.
With the spotlight on fertility medication, a long-standing debate
has been reignited: Who is responsible _ the physician or the
patient _ when fertility drugs result in high-order multiple
births?
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, patients desperate for babies insist on
aggressive treatment that is more likely to result in high-order
multiples. In others, primary care physicians write prescriptions
for these drugs without the training or resources needed to fully
manage the patients.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the insurance companies? Some experts in the
field insist that insurers who refuse to cover a full-range of
infertility treatments or timely referrals to specialists carry
some of the burden of responsibility and that covering these costs
would ultimately save money.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Perloe, director of the Atlanta Reproductive Health
Center, said fertility treatment has to be a shared responsibility.
``The physician is responsible for educating the patient regarding
treatment options before initiating therapy,'' he said. ``That way
the correct decisions can be made _ decisions that have profound
economic and moral implications for the couple. The couple can't
make those decisions alone, but as physicians we can't make those
decisions for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Venet Grant, president of the International Council on
Infertility Information Dissemination, places the responsibility
for high-order multiple births squarely on the shoulders of the
physicians and the insurers. While ``it's the physicians'
responsibility to help a couple make responsible choices,'' she
said, ``couples are often driven to do these things out of
desperation because their insurance does not provide them with
adequate medical coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The drugs that carry the greatest risk of high-order multiple
fertilizations are the injectable hormones known as human
menopausal gonadotropins, or hMG, which are probably the drugs Nkem
Chukwu took, although her doctor has not released that information.
Trade names for these drugs include Pergonal, Humegon, Repronex,
Follistim, Fertinex and Gonal-F.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of multiple gestations depends on many factors,
including the dosage and duration of treatment, the woman's age,
and the quality of the sperm, but generally the risk of multiple
births ranges from 10 to 20 percent, the majority of which are
twins, according to Resolve, a nonprofit advocacy group for people
experiencing infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Although large doses of these drugs are used during in-vitro
fertilization, the risk of multiple births is not as high for this
procedure as it is when fertility drugs are used alone, said Dr.
Gary Berger, medical director of the Chapel Hill Fertility Center
in Chapel Hill, N.C., and author of ``The Couple's Guide to
Infertility'' (1995, Doubleday). During in-vitro fertilization, the
eggs are removed from the ovaries and fertilized outside the
woman's body. A known number, usually only two or three, are
returned to the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   That level of control is not possible with drug treatment alone,
Berger explained. However, vaginal ultrasound can provide detailed
pictures of the ovaries and inform physicians how the body is
responding to the hormones. Dr. Perloe said that experienced
physicians look for the number of follicles that are developing in
the ovaries, what size they are and how crowded they appear. The
more follicles there are, the more eggs there may be. In addition,
the estrogen levels in the woman's blood are measured frequently, a
sudden rise indicating that multiple follicles might have
developed.
</P>
<P>
   If an ultrasound reveals many mature follicles, there are
several ways to prevent the release of the eggs and their
fertilization. The physician can cancel the cycle, either by
withholding the final injection of hCG, a hormone that releases the
eggs from the follicles, or by withholding the introduction of
sperm.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to remove some of the follicles before
fertilization, a procedure that is less known but that Dr. Berger
said ``is a better option than selective reduction.'' Most
physicians agree that selective reduction, the removal of
fertilized eggs between 9 and 12 weeks gestation, is the last
resort. This is the procedure that Ms. Chukwu and her husband
reportedly refused due to their religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   But these options are often overshadowed by financial
considerations. Each cycle costs thousands of dollars, making
cancellation an expensive decision. ``People are making choices not
based on quality medical care but on what their insurance will
cover,'' Ms. Grant explained.
</P>
<P>
   She recommended choosing a physician carefully. ``What matters
most is that the physician devotes his or her practice to fertility
issues, she said. ``Find out what their success rate is and how
many high-order multiple births they have come out of their
practice.'' She recommends contacting Resolve for its physician
referral list.
</P>
<P>
   Patients need to take responsibility too, Berger said. ``Medical
care is best when the patient is fully informed and
participating.'' Ms. Grant emphasized that women need to become
involved in their own treatment. ``Don't just lie there and let the
ultrasonographer write things down in the chart,'' she advised.
``Don't go home without knowing what they saw that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Perloe added that patients' responsibilities extend to making
the commitment to the treatment agreed upon. ``You've got to be
willing to devote the time to treatment,'' he said. ``You can't
miss an ultrasound because you had to go to a business meeting. It
has to become your highest priority.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
