<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENTESE: A FULL (NOT FULSOME) COMPLEMENT OF SYNONYMS FOR
REBUKE, SOME MORE PURIFYING THAN OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, January 10.)  
 (EDS: Items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(rl) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Even in survival,'' wrote Jim Hoagland of The Washington Post,
``Clinton will emerge from this experience chastised if not
chastened, humiliated if not humbled.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a serious challenge to synonymists by a serious
foreign-affairs columnist (even though he uses the reader-friendly
``Jim'' in his byline, which would raise the eyebrow of a bygone
era's Walt Lippmann).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chaste  &LR; is from the Latin  &UR; castus,  &LR; ``pure,'' and  &UR; chasten
 &LR; means ``to make pure'' by some mode of discipline, with the
positive connotation of being strengthened by moral correction
(``whom the Lord loveth he  &UR; chasteneth &LR; '').  &UR; Chastise,  &LR; as well as
 &UR; castigate,  &LR; comes from the Latin  &UR; castigare,  &LR; which adds the force
of -igare, or agere, ``to drive'' to the purifying. Although both
verbs mean ``to correct by punishment or reproof,''  &UR; chastise  &LR; adds
coercion or severity to the moral instruction in  &UR; chasten. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the synonymy of censure, then,  &UR; punish  &LR; implies ``to penalize
for disobedience to authority''; the verb  &UR; discipline  &LR; suggests
``to subjugate or bring under control'';  &UR; chasten  &LR; means ``to
strengthen by setting straight'';  &UR; chastise,  &LR; ``to inflict some
coercion in correction'';  &UR; correct,  &LR; ``to straighten for the
purpose of reform''; and  &UR; castigate,  &LR; ``to tongue-lash or rebuke
severely.''
</P>
<P>
   As I parse the subtle Hoagland, his `` &UR; chastised  &LR; if not
 &UR; chastened &LR; '' &UR;  &LR; means ``corrected but not truly purified,'' or
``punished but not made  &UR; chaste. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   What about `` &UR; humiliated  &LR; if not  &UR; humbled &LR; ''? If you're a
gardener, you know what  &UR; humus  &LR; is: that deliciously decomposed
plant or animal manure that, mixed with your back yard's flavorless
dirt, gives an organic boost to the roots of your flowers. It is
also the Latin word for ``earth, ground,'' and is the root of both
 &UR; humble  &LR; and  &UR; humiliate &LR; , &UR;  &LR; words that suggest the bringing of
someone down to the ground, sometimes to the extent of figuratively
grinding his face in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The verb  &UR; to humble &LR;  originally meant ``to make meek,'' as in
Valentine's profession of awed affection in ``The Two Gentlemen of
Verona'': ``O gentle Proteus, Love's a mighty lord,/And hath so
 &UR; humbled  &LR; me, as, I confess,/There is no woe to his correction.''
Now, however, it is part of the lingo of abasement.
</P>
<P>
   Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of Synonyms has an uplifting entry
on  &UR; abasement &LR; . After running through  &UR; demean  &LR; (loss of dignity),
 &UR; debase  &LR; (deterioration in value) and the Pentagon's favorite new
word,  &UR; degrade  &LR; (``conveys a strong implication of the shamefulness
of the condition to which someone or something has been reduced'' _
take that, Saddam), M-W comes to  &UR; humble &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently used in place of  &UR; degrade &LR; ,'' synonymizes the
philological hairsplitter, ``in the sense of  &UR; demote  &LR; when the
ignominy of the reduction in rank is emphasized ... [but) often
suggests a salutary increase of humility or the realization of
one's own littleness or impotence.'' But  &UR; humiliate,  &LR; which used to
be a synonym of  &UR; humble,  &LR; has gained a more forceful meaning of
taking someone down: ``comes closer to  &UR; mortify,  &LR; for it stresses
chagrin and shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, when Hoagland writes that Clinton has been
 &UR; ``humiliated  &LR; if not  &UR; humbled &LR; ,'' I think he's saying that others
have  &UR; demeaned, debased, degraded &LR;  the president, but he remains
neither  &UR; defeated  &LR; nor newly possessed of a sense of meekness and
humility.
</P>
<P>
   Whew! What a spectrum of meaning some columnists can pack in a
single burst of alliteration.
</P>
<P>
   FULSOME APOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   When Sen.-elect Charles Schumer of New York told the House
Judiciary Committee that the president had already made a ``fulsome
apology'' _- intended to mean ``copious, complete, full'' _
usagists like Alistair Cooke winced. Throughout nine decades of
speaking good English, the former BBC commentator knew that the
word meant nothing of the sort. On almost the contrary, he and
other incensed hearings-watchers told me on voice mail,  &UR; fulsome
 &LR; means ``excessive, cloying,'' even ``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Centuries ago, the original meaning of ``full'' in that word had
been influenced by  &UR; foul &LR; . Surely the Clinton defender could not
have intended to leave the impression that the apology reeked. Had
the senator-elect erred?
</P>
<P>
   Two great dictionaries disagree. Webster's New World, now
published by Macmillan, has as its first definition, ``disgusting
or offensive, especially because excessive or insincere  &UR; (fulsome
 &LR; praise).'' But then it reports a second meaning: ``(apparent
revival of the original sense, obsolete since 16th century) full;
ample; abundant: usage objected to by some.''
</P>
<P>
   Now to Merriam-Webster, whose patron saint, Noah himself,
defined it in 1828 as ``gross: disgusting by plainness, grossness
or excess; as  &UR; fullsome  &LR; flattery or praise.'' In the 10th
Collegiate Edition, M-W turns the tables. Its first definition is
``characterized by abundance: copious.'' Only in its second sense
do we get ``esthetically, morally or generally offensive.'' It then
gives other pejorative senses as ``effusive'' and ``overdone''
before swinging back to ``generous in amount.'' A usage note is
added: ``Unless the context is made very clear, the reader or
hearer cannot be sure whether such an expression as  &UR; `fulsome
 &LR; praise' '' means  &UR; copious  &LR; or  &UR; offensive &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This commentator says: If you mean  &UR; full &LR; , &UR;  &LR; say  &UR; full &LR; , &UR;  &LR; or if
you want to put your thumb on the upscale,  &UR; copious &LR; . But if you
mean  &UR; gross &LR; , &UR;  &LR; say  &UR; gross  &LR; or  &UR; yucky &LR; , &UR;  &LR; or try an expletive like
 &UR; feh &LR; ! Never refer to a  &UR; fulsome  &LR; bosom unless you want to get
slugged by an intelligent woman. Indeed, cross  &UR; fulsome  &LR; off your
list entirely. Phooey on ambiguity. Never be of two minds about
ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
