<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7330 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     01-04 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING FOR THE WARNING SIGNS OF AN INVISIBLE KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't see it, hear it, smell it, taste it or feel it. But it
can poison or even kill you without you ever realizing it's around.
It is the deadly gas, carbon monoxide, and winter is the season it
does most of its damage. Despite annual warnings about the many
sources of carbon monoxide and how problems can be prevented and
detected before it's too late, this product of combustion kills an
estimated 2,100 people who did not intend to die and sickens 10,000
others in the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, the flu-like symptoms that are early warning
signs of carbon monoxide poisoning are mistakenly attributed to a
viral infection, and victims are sent home or back to work to
breathe yet more of the deadly gas. Babies and small children
(including unborn children), those with chronic heart or lung
diseases and the elderly are especially sensitive to the harmful
effects of carbon monoxide and are among those who are least likely
to respond appropriately to the first signs of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Although it had long been assumed that those who survive carbon
monoxide poisoning suffer no lasting effects, studies in recent
years have documented permanent problems that may not show up for
weeks or months after an apparent recovery in a large minority of
victims. They can experience long-lasting, even permanent,
neurological and psychological damage that disrupts careers and
families and destroys lives. These findings make all the more
important the need to protect yourself and your family from the
dangers of carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon monoxide forms when hydrocarbons burn incompletely, such
as in wood-burning fireplaces, oil and gas appliances and
fuel-powered vehicles. Once in the air it is readily absorbed
through the lungs. It can also be formed in the liver from
methylene chloride, a common component of paint remover and other
solvents that are easily absorbed as vapor through the skin and
lungs. This is one reason these products warn people to use them
only with adequate ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the blood, carbon monoxide latches tightly onto
hemoglobin, the molecule in red blood cells that carries oxygen to
every cell in the body. The affinity that carbon monoxide has for
hemoglobin exceeds oxygen's attraction by about 240 times. To make
matters even worse, once carboxy-hemoglobin, as the carbon
monoxide-hemoglobin complex is called, forms, the remaining
hemoglobin molecules that carry oxygen are less likely to give up
this vital gas to the tissues that need it.
</P>
<P>
   Most people normally have at most only a few percent of their
hemoglobin as carboxyhemoglobin. Smokers have much more than
nonsmokers, and those who live or work in environments polluted by
tobacco smoke are likely to have even higher levels of
carboxyhemoglobin than smokers themselves. As levels rise to 10
percent or more, symptoms of poisoning start to appear. At first,
they are vague and nonspecific _ headache, dizziness, weakness,
nausea _ and easily mistaken for a touch of the flu. As
carboxyhemoglobin levels rise, victims may experience shortness of
breath, rapid heart beat, difficulty concentrating, confusion,
visual problems, chest or abdominal pain and muscle cramps. The
most severe cases of carbon monoxide poisoning result in loss of
consciousness and death.
</P>
<P>
   The more advanced the poisoning, the more likely
neuropsychiatric damage will result, including such effects as
impaired memory, learning problems, sudden personality changes,
incontinence, Parkinson-like symptoms, dementia and even psychosis.
One-half to three-fourths of those affected recover within a year
from these effects, but for the remainder the damage is permanent.
</P>
<P>
   In your home, it is critically important to be sure that all
fuel-burning appliances are in proper working order. Furnaces
should be inspected and chimneys cleaned annually and kept in good
repair. Gas stoves must be properly adjusted (the flame should be
blue, not yellow), burners kept unclogged and, if possible, fumes
should be vented to the outside or at least circulated through a
hood fan. Gas ranges or ovens should be used only for cooking,
never to heat a room. Newer gas stoves that have low-heat-input gas
pilot lights, and nongas ignition systems are safer than those with
older pilot lights. If you have a gas range, you can have the gas
company turn off the cook-top pilots and instead light the burners
each time with a flicker device that produces a spark.
</P>
<P>
   Charcoal-burning devices, including hibachis, should never be
used indoors for cooking or heating. Last fall, three campers died
in New Jersey because they used a hibachi to heat their zippered
tent.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a gas-fueled or wood-burning fireplace, make sure the
flue is open when fuel is burning and that the doors on wood stoves
fit tightly so that smoke does not escape into the room.
</P>
<P>
   Always sleep with the bedroom window open. Even a few inches can
help prevent carbon monoxide poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   The garage is another common source of trouble. Never idle your
car inside the garage, even if the door is open. Lethal levels of
carbon monoxide can accumulate in just 10 minutes in a closed
garage. Leaving the engine running is especially dangerous to the
entire family if the garage is attached to your house.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the garage, many people succumb unintentionally to carbon
monoxide poisoning when they sit or sleep is a closed car with the
engine running to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, install one or more carbon monoxide detectors in your
home as well as in your car. Safety experts suggest using a audible
alarm installed in a hallway or near the bedrooms. Newer models are
less likely to produce false alarms than ones purchased five or
more years ago.
</P>
<P>
   According to ratings by Consumer Reports, the best detectors
continuously display the level of carbon monoxide present, which
allows you to detect problems before they make anyone ill.
Top-rated models include three that operate on ordinary household
current _ Nighthawk, Lifesaver and S-Tech _ and one that is battery
powered, Safety 1st. There are also inexpensive chemical detectors
available that change color in the presence of increasing amounts
of carbon monoxide, but these cannot help you if you are asleep
when trouble arises.
</P>
<P>
   If your carbon monoxide detector alarm sounds, open windows and
doors, call 911 and ask for the fire department and get out of the
house. If you develop symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, see a
physician without delay, perhaps at a local emergency room, and
make sure your blood is checked for levels of carboxyhemoglobin. Be
especially suspicious of carbon monoxide poisoning if several
members of the household develop similar symptoms at the same time
or if a small pet in the house dies. If relatively advanced
poisoning is diagnosed, the doctor should order a neuropsychiatric
examination _ a battery of tests that takes about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the source of trouble must be detected and
corrected by a licensed professional before anyone re-enters the
house, workplace or vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
