<SLUG> BC-EPIPHANY-JOURNEY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHRISTMAS SEASON ENDS, EPIPHANY SIGNALS OUR SPIRITUAL JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact the syndicate (800) 972-3550 or
(212) 499-3333, or fax (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Four days after Christmas, while coming home from an errand, I
noticed that many of my neighbors had discarded their Christmas
trees. I moaned: Don't they know Christmas is not over?
 &HT;    Evidently not.
 &HT;    Secular Christmas starts the day after Thanksgiving and ends
with the Christmas sales on December 26. Some stalwarts keep their
trees until New Year's. But few preserve the Christian practice of
celebrating the Twelve Days of Christmas from December 25 through
the evening of January 5.
 &HT;    Every year, however, I refuse to dismantle the tree until the
very end. No city-wide recycling program can break my resolve to
maintain the Christian liturgical year.
 &HT;    According to tradition, Christmas' Twelve Days follow the
nativity -- making Christmas a season and not a single day.
Christmas ends when a new church season, Epiphany, begins on
January 6.
 &HT;    Although lost in a haze of post-holiday blues and the return to
school, Epiphany is actually more ancient than Christmas. As early
as the second century, Christians celebrated January 6 as a feast
to mark three events: one, the visit of the Wise Men to the infant
Jesus; two, Jesus's baptism; and three, Jesus's first miracle at
the wedding of Cana.
 &HT;    Epiphany comes from the Greek word, ``epiphania,'' meaning
manifestation or revelation. The day's three-fold commemoration
marks the revelation of Jesus as Messiah, God's long-promised one
as savior of the world.
 &HT;    Given the religious power of Epiphany's message, it is no wonder
why American secular Christmas ignores the day. Sweet baby Jesus is
tangential enough to capitalist Christmas; proclaiming him a
miracle-working Messiah unnerves even some spiritually sensitive
folks. Jesus is safer as a cuddly newborn than one to whom even
kings pay homage.
 &HT;    Yet, there it is. The culmination of Christmas is this odd
collection of stories: of Wise Men following a star and the
church's retelling of the grown Jesus being baptized and performing
his first miracle.
 &HT;    Over the years, Epiphany has puzzled me. Recently, however, I
have become convinced that Epiphany is one of the most spiritually
significant feasts on the Christian calendar. Even those who do not
believe Jesus was the Messiah can draw some spiritual insights from
this celebration. Epiphany is neither obtuse nor irrelevant.
 &HT;    At its heart Epiphany teaches two spiritual realities. First,
God manifests or reveals God's own self to the world. And second,
we need to embark on a journey to discover this God.
 &HT;    As we enter into the last year of the millennium, spiritual
journeys are ``in.'' But even when people speak of their journeys,
it seems clear that many have no idea where they are going.
Epiphany underscores a primary aspect of spiritual pilgrimage: God
went there first. The journey is one where God has travelled and
left traces and tokens of divine presence along the way. God
initiates our journeys by coming into the world.
 &HT;    As in the biblical account of the Magi, spiritual journeys
combine divine and human initiative. God reveals; humankind
responds. This is not a journey for the sake of journey. Rather, it
is a journey following a star -- a sign pointing the way --
directing us to the mystery of God's own manifestation.
 &HT;    Although we follow, that does not mean the way is fixed or
final. When the Wise Men found God's revelation, the baby Jesus was
not exactly the king they had expected. Spiritual pilgrimages are
full of unanticipated turns and surprising discoveries. The journey
itself becomes part of God's revelation in our lives.
 &HT;    Funny thing about those Wise Men -- their journey did not end
when they found Jesus. The gospel says, ``They left for their own
country by another road.'' They went back a different way than from
whence they came. Their journey to God took them home on a course
unlike their previous one. Everything about their journey was
unexpected.
 &HT;    Even Jesus. His journey probably surprised him. Imagine his
baptism as a voice from heaven announced: ``This is my beloved
Son.'' Or that miracle at Cana: ``My time has not yet come.''
 &HT;    These events in his life showed he was both follower and
revelation; a seeker of God and the one sought.
 &HT;    As 1999 dawns and the old millennium draws to a close, Epiphany
fits the spirit of the age. Epiphany celebrates journey. God
journeys to us; we journey to God. And, at the center of the
movement is the mystery of Christian faith: Jesus.
 &HT;    Y2K aside, Jesus is, after all, the one about whom all this
millennial fuss has arisen. Two thousand years after his birth, he
remains both as accessible and enigmatic as ever. Like the Wise
Men, we are still following that star.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
