<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIAMONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBON, NITROGEN, BORON _ AND SHINE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(ms) 
 By JOHN WILSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a little extra boron, these diamonds turned
blue, like the famous Hope Diamond. With nitrogen, they went
yellow. And when radiation somehow hit the crystal structure of the
carbon, these diamonds-in-the-rough shifted to shades of green.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of 260 of these rare flukes in the diamond-making
process, with 12 distinct color varieties, are regularly displayed
at the American Museum of Natural History in Manhattan, where about
a million people a year see them, said Dr. George E. Harlow, the
museum's curator of gems and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   But 1998 was no ordinary time for these stones, formed millions
of years ago as carbon was subjected to great heat and pressure.
Known as the Aurora Collection, these colored diamonds were
prominently featured in a major diamond show at the museum, ``The
Nature of Diamonds,'' which ran through August, and again in a
742-page, 9.8-pound book, ``Collecting and Classifying Colored
Diamonds: An Illustrated Study of the Aurora Collection'' (Ashland
Press, New York, $300). The book is the culmination of a seven-year
effort to examine, photograph and catalog the gems by Stephen C.
Hofer, the author and a gem expert from Stockbridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harlow called the work ``the most comprehensive to date in
the field'' of colored diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Bronstein, a New York gem merchant who assembled the Aurora
Collection, said the book created new systems for measuring and
classifying colored diamonds. ``It pushes the envelope on
diamond-grading science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, owned by Harry Rodman, a 90-year-old New York
gold refiner, has been on loan to the museum and displayed almost
continuously since 1988, with new stones being added periodically.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the New York museum will temporarily lose a little of its
luster. The Aurora Collection and the other diamonds from ``The
Nature of Diamonds'' exhibit will travel to the San Diego Natural
History Museum, where they will be on display from March 27 until
Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
