<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; When Vegetarianism Raises a Red Flag &LR;  There are many legitimate
reasons for eating vegetarian. But according to a recent article
published in the journal The Physician and Sports Medicine, the
practice of vegetarianism may be a red flag for eating disorders in
young athletic women.
</P>
<P>
   The article cited numerous studies that found an association
between meatless diets and eating disorders, including a 1997
Michigan survey of 107 female adolescents who did not eat meat and
214 who did. Those who did not eat meat were found to diet twice as
often, vomit four times as often and use laxatives eight times as
often as those in the meat-eating group. All of these practices are
commonly linked with eating disorders like anorexia nervosa and
bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Davis, vice president of research and program
development at the Renfrew Center, an eating disorder clinic, said
that young female athletes, especially competitive runners and
gymnasts, have a particularly high risk of developing an eating
disorder because of pressures to maintain lower body weight for
their sport. A study at the University of Akron found that more
than one quarter of female adolescent runners were unhappy with
their weight and felt pressure from their parents and coaches to be
thin.
</P>
<P>
   Though young men are much less likely to develop eating
disorders than women, athletically competitive boys may be at
higher risk than their nonathletic peers.
</P>
<P>
   A vegetarian diet by itself is not a cause for concern, Davis
said. ``It is not a problem unless coupled with superstitious
behaviors related to food and eating, which may indicate an
unhealthy, distorted relationship with food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Elizabeth Somer, a registered dietitian, worries that
abstaining from meat without making suitable nutritional
replacements can result in serious problems like protein, iron and
zinc deficiencies, she is quick to point out that not all young
active women who remove meat from their diets do so as a prelude to
an eating disorder.
</P>
<P>
   For young athletes who want to follow a vegetarian regimen,
Nancy Clark, a nutritional counselor at the Sports Medicine Clinic
in Brookline, Mass., recommends eating plenty of soy, beans and
other plant-based protein sources to replace meat protein; an
abundance of dark green leafy vegetables and tofu to meet iron
requirements, and generous amounts of whole grains and cereal
products to reach adequate zinc intake. She also advises taking a
daily multivitamin geared toward those on vegetarian diets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Taking Care of Those Bumps on the Head &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Like that favorite nursery rhyme egg, children commonly suffer
great falls not only off walls, but they also tumble from changing
tables, jungle gyms and down stairs. Older children bump heads on
playing fields or fall off bicycles. Most end up with only a bad
headache, but sometimes complications require emergency treatment
and hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves parents with this often perplexing question: When is
a head injury minor and when should it involve a trip to the
emergency room?
</P>
<P>
   The first thing a parent should do after a fall is find out what
happened, said Dr. Mary Aitken, lead author in a survey of what
physicians do when a head injury involves little or no loss of
consciousness or behavioral changes. This may include minor
concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anything other than the most minor blow, at least call the
doctor and observe the child carefully,'' she said. Nausea,
vomiting, dizziness, headache, loss of consciousness, seizures,
lethargy, irritability, swelling, bruising, bleeding and memory
loss may be signs of a serious problem. Most symptoms, she said,
surface within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the doctors (82 percent) in the survey, published in the
December issue of The Archives of Pediatrics and Adolescent
Medicine, chose observation over more aggressive treatment like
X-rays or tomographic scanning. Of that group, most preferred that
observation take place at home over the hospital. Aitken urges
parents to call their doctor, discuss the child's symptoms, ask
what to do if the child's condition changes and, if it does, how to
reach the doctor. ``Generally, parents know their children best and
should help to assess them and to observe them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Minor head injuries, affecting about 375,000 American children a
year, involve children of all ages but most often active children
and those between 5 and 7, Aitken said. Prevention is even more
important than treatment, she said, pointing to the importance of
proper sports equipment, playgrounds designed for safety and
supervision. ``The main thing is to prevent the head injury in the
first place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Traffic-Ticket Writers as Stress Magnets &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever become livid at the sight of a parking
ticket anchored under the windshield wiper of his or her car will
not be surprised by what scientists have recently quantified: An
average of three times a day, a traffic-enforcement agent has a
hostile confrontation with a member of the public. Taking advantage
of this real-life laboratory, researchers at two New York
universities used parking-ticket writers to understand how heart
rate and blood pressure may change during verbal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   After equipping 115 New York traffic agents with blood pressure
cuffs that took readings every 15 minutes during the work day,
scientists discovered that any communication the agents engaged in
_ conversations with supervisors, the public, or co-workers _ led
to increases in blood pressure and heart rate when compared with
baseline readings taken at the start of the work day. Blood
pressure readings were highest during interactions with members of
the public, and the effects remained after contact ended, according
to the study, which appears this month in the journal
Psychophysiology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic agents unfortunately have a lot of interpersonal
conflicts with motorists who are angry about receiving tickets,''
said Dr. Elizabeth Brondolo of St. John's University in New York
City, who led the study along with researchers from the State
University of New York at Stony Brook. Negative interactions were
described as incidents in which agents were harassed, threatened,
yelled at, spit on, flirted with, insulted, pushed, followed or
hit. ``We wanted to see what their blood pressure was while they
were having these conflicts,'' Brondolo said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
