<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     01-04 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, Jan. 5. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA (Phnom Penh) _ Sihanouk, responding to reminders that
he supported the Khmer Rouge at one time, says he is willing to go
on trial with their leaders. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is
quietly trying to organize an international trial of two senior
Khmer Rouge defectors for their roles in the deaths of more than 1
million Cambodians in the 1970s that would win the approval for a
trial from China and other nations that had supported the Khmer
Rouge in the past. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-REVAMP (Washington) _ After 18 months of battling crises
from Southeast Asia to Russia, the leadership of International
Monetary Fund is proposing a major transformation of the
organization, into a far stronger institution that would
essentially act as global central bank, intervening to bail out
troubled economies at the first signs of trouble instead of after
an economic collapse. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Sen. Trent Lott returned to the Capitol
and prepared a series of meetings with Republicans throughout
Tuesday as senators continued to search for the compromise that
would allow them to end an impeachment trial quickly. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MINN-VENTURA (Minneapolis) _ A profile of Jesse Ventura's wife,
Terry, the new first lady of Minnesota. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA-CANADA (Undated) _ In the first case against the U.S.
government under a little known provision of Nafta, a Canadian
funeral-home company is claiming that the U.S. government should
pay it millions of dollars in damages for what it says was unfair
treatment in American courts. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DAVIS (Sacramento) _ Gray Davis promised to lead
California into a new era of racial harmony and educational
excellence as he was sworn in Monday as the state's 37th governor,
the first Democrat since his old boss, Gov. Jerry Brown, left
office in 1983. By Todd S. Purdum. (Early summary, from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OTTERS (Undated) _ While otters appeared to be flourishing,
scientists recently discovered that the otter population in the
Aleutians had plunged sharply, with no apparent reason. It turned
out that orcas, or killer whales, had started eating the otters
after decades and possibly centuries of peaceful coexistence. With
Graphic and Photo. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEPATITIS (Undated) _ Getting a drug into the marketplace
sometimes can pit manufacturer against patients who volunteer for
the trials. A look at one patient one-third of the way through the
trials for hepatitis C treatment. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOODMORNING-TV-SHAKEUP (Undated) _ In a sign of how vital ``Good
Morning America'' is to the financial health of the ABC network and
its stations, and how dramatically the show's fortunes have fallen,
ABC News on Monday named one of its biggest star journalists, Diane
Sawyer, as a new co-anchor for the morning news show, beginning
Jan. 18. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
