<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICANISMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN WORDS ENRICH THE ENGLISH LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANK ABATE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever since Oxford University Press set up a
U.S.-based office for dictionaries in 1996, its American
lexicographers have been compiling lists and gathering evidence
from newspapers, magazines, broadcast sources, the Internet and
World Wide Web _ even from advertising such as billboards and
grocery coupons.
</P>
<P>
   All are legitimate sources for documenting new-word use. This
American material, along with citations from Oxford's North
American Reading Program (which, from its inception in the
mid-1980s, now has collected nearly a million terms of U.S. origin)
adds richly to the language resources that make up the global scope
of the Oxford Database of World English.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford lexicographers in America are tracking these recent
additions to the language, each of which has some popularity, and
watching developments closely:
</P>
<P>
   _ 24/7 _ hours a day/days a week, as in, ``we are on duty
24/7.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Casual Friday or dress-down Friday _ catching on in more
offices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Duh! _ now widespread as an expression of mocking disbelief
over someone else's folly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laser pointer _ gadget once used only in presentations, now
maliciously.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mouthfeel _ used to describe the texture of a food in the
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Plus size _ of larger clothing sizes, especially in women's
fashions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pop-up video _ a cable channel is devoted to these.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slamming _ illicit switching of one's long-distance telephone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Other words under consideration are not really that new, but do
not appear in current editions of Oxford dictionaries, sometimes
because of their informal status:
</P>
<P>
   _ Class act _ classy person as in ``What a class act she is!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Designated driver _ when a group goes out for drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fat city _ ``Now we're in fat city!'' meaning, ``We've really
made it big.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hissy fit _ ``She had a hissy fit over it''; used by and of
women, disparagingly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nowheresville _ ``This town is nowheresville''; i.e., a real
one-horse town.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parse _ to analyze language, now used of political speech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Piece of work _ ``He's a real piece of work!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Punkin _ as a term of endearment; for ``pumpkin.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Take-no prisoners _ adjective, of a ruthless attitude.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timeout _ a form of discipline for children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Worst nightmare _ usually said as a threat: ``I'm your worst
nightmare!''
</P>
<P>
   Oxford also looks to technical and specialist fields, always
rife with new developments. For example, the field of alternative
medicine has taken off, and many plants, long entered in
dictionaries for their botanical status, now have a medicinal use,
and these entries now need editing (e.g., St. John's wort, saw
palmetto).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the following (from electronics and computers) may be
unfamiliar, but are often just the words someone needs to look up
when reading an article, etc.:
</P>
<P>
   _ Closed-captioned _ as seen on TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cyber- and e- _ as in cyberspace and e-mail; these prefixes
continue to be productive.
</P>
<P>
   _ HDTV _ high-definition television, now available commercially.
</P>
<P>
   _ USB port _ newer type of connection for computer peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   _ XML _ latest generation of computer mark-up language for
multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Examiner contributor Frank Abate is with the U.S. dictionaries
department of Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
