<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MARS-PROBE-ART-2T     01-04 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-PROBE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACECRAFT SPEED TO MARS, HIGH HOPES ON BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh off the launching pad, two new spacecraft are heading for
Mars as part of a 16-year effort to determine once and for all if
life ever arose on the red planet. The two probes make up a second
wave of inquiry, the first having begun in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether Mars harbors life was first asked
centuries ago when astronomers turned increasingly powerful
telescopes on the heavens and found that the reddish planet has
seasons, icy poles and other Earthlike features. Such similarities
have made Mars the main place in the solar system to look for signs
of extraterrestrial life. So far, however, no convincing evidence
has come to light.
</P>
<P>
   The Mars Climate Orbiter was launched from Florida on Dec. 11,
and the Mars Polar Lander followed two days ago, on Jan. 3. Both
were designed by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.
The pair, which cost the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration $357 million to build, launch and run, are to arrive
at the red planet this September and December.
</P>
<P>
   While unlikely to top the Mars Pathfinder rover in terms of
action and spectacle, which riveted millions of computer and
television viewers in July 1997, the pair of spacecraft are meant
to advance the exploratory hunt in important ways. For instance,
the lander spacecraft is to probe deep beneath the Martian surface
in search of water, which is considered the crucial ingredient for
life.
</P>
<P>
   Over at least 16 years, and perhaps longer, the new explorations
of Mars are to involve more than a dozen spacecraft, thousands of
scientists and billions of dollars. No other effort so large and
systematic has marked the recent history of planetary exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Only once before has the United States fixed its powers so
intently on a single planetary body _ the Moon. That series of
spacecraft included the Rangers, Surveyors and Apollos, each one
more ambitious than its predecessor. The effort culminated in
manned landings from 1969 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, exploration of the planets evolved haphazardly over
the decades as American probes flew to Mercury, Venus, Mars,
Jupiter, Saturn and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the victim of the next program we had to sell,''
Daniel S. Goldin, the NASA administrator, said of previous decades
of space exploration. ``Now we have a vision and a strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The piecemeal nature of previous projects caused designers to
make each craft big and costly, and that often inadvertently left
them vulnerable to political whims and uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people involved thought they'd never go again, so they'd
put on every possible instrument,'' said Dr. Bruce C. Murray, a
former director of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory and now a
scientist at the California Institute of Technology. ``Missions got
too complicated, and cost too much, because there was a feeling
there was no tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Mars undertaking involves a series of relatively
low-cost probes compared to earlier spacecraft, which cost about $1
billion each.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the new probes are to build upon one another to
form a scientific foundation for finally answering the life riddle.
</P>
<P>
   Pathfinder studied rocks. Mars Polar Lander will look for water
by digging into icy terrain near the planet's south pole. If the
funding continues, later craft are to collect rocky samples from
promising sites and return them to Earth. Scientists will then
search for signs of microscopic life, either fossil or extant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become the intellectual centerpiece of NASA's space
exploration program,'' said Dr. Bruce Jakosky, a planetary
scientist at the University of Colorado who does research for NASA.
A series of science breakthroughs in the past decade, he added,
have made the discovery of life on Mars ``very plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerted push to solve the life puzzle has prompted Japan,
France and the European Space Agency to add their own spacecraft to
the fleet, at times in partnership with the United States.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Relatively warm and wet in its early days billions of years ago,
the surface of Mars is now an icy red desert etched by old river
beds and flood plains that bespeak torrents of water. Scientists
see the planet as a possible home for microbial life, especially if
the planet's interior is still warm and if water is still flowing
through rocky regions down below, as it does on Earth in aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Polar Lander, the most recent craft to join the hunt, is to
zoom across 470 million miles of space, traveling about 2,000 times
farther than the distance between the Earth and the Moon. It is
remarkably compact, as was evident last month inside a cavernous
building at Cape Canaveral, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing of the squat bundle being readied for launching
suggested that the spacecraft would be able to extend tripod legs,
solar panels, a camera mast and a long arm to form a gangly robot
some 12 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John McNamee, the program manager for the lander and
orbiter, moved around the folded craft in a clean suit, booties,
plastic gloves and a face mask meant to keep his germs from
inadvertently making the trek to Mars and contaminating the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The compact lander, he said, is a good example of NASA's resolve
to do more with less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about half the price, half the mass and able to do much
more science'' than its forerunner, Mars Pathfinder, McNamee said.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless push for lower costs, McNamee added, means the
lander will use regular rockets to slow its descent rather than
innovative air bags, as Pathfinder did when it repeatedly bounced
on the rocky surface before coming to a halt. Air bags weigh more,
and thus cost more to hurl into space.
</P>
<P>
   Bulging outward from the craft were two spheres about the size
of basketballs. These were microprobes, hitchhikers that will be
fired from the lander just before it enters the Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The microprobes will get there faster because they don't have
parachutes or rockets,'' McNamee said. ``They just go right in.''
</P>
<P>
   A first for the exploration of space, the microprobes are to
slam into Mars at about 400 hundred miles per hour, shattering
their protective shells.
</P>
<P>
   The wide upper part of each probe, with antenna, circuits and
batteries, will stop abruptly at the surface. But an inner,
bullet-shaped projectile, linked to the upper part by a cable, will
crash through soil, rock and ice as deep as three or four feet.
</P>
<P>
   The projectile is laden with sensors. An accelerometer will
measure how fast it comes to rest, telling of soil hardness and
revealing any layers of dust, rock and ice. Temperature sensors
will tell how well the Martian soil conducts heat, giving clues to
its composition.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a tiny drill will emerge from the side of the
projectile to sample the soil, heat it and look for water vapor.
That finding would be a first, greatly improving the odds that
microbes might thrive in the alien soil.
</P>
<P>
   About a minute or so after the probes hit, the lander is to
settle down gently some 60 miles away but still near the icy south
pole. A stereo camera atop a five-foot mast will scan the
surrounding landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The lander's flexible arm is more than six feet long and can dig
down as much as two or three feet to retrieve soil samples . In
eight tiny ovens on the lander, soil will be heated and analyzed
for the presence of icy water and carbon dioxide, the main
component of the thin Martian atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Ice at the poles, never before sampled, is thought to be a mix
of water and carbon dioxide in a sort of frozen seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   The lander is to operate for up to 90 days, and the microprobes
for a few hours or days. Their downward probing is expected to
reveal layered terrain that, like tree rings, sheds light on the
seasonal variations of Mars, its climatic past and whether
conditions there were ever favorable for the maintenance of life.
</P>
<P>
   Readings from the microprobes and the lander will be relayed to
Earth by the Mars Climate Orbiter and the Mars Global Surveyor, an
orbiting craft that reached the planet during the first exploratory
wave. Both orbiters are to map the planet and search for good
landing sites.
</P>
<P>
   The surveyor craft has already discovered a region some 300
miles wide that contains large deposits of the mineral hematite, a
rock consisting of tiny crystals of iron oxide that on Earth
typically originate in hot or standing water. Scientists consider
the region a good place to look for evidence of life and are
discussing whether to send a lander there, and possibly one of the
missions meant to return rocky samples to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists say that Mars, despite its deserts and hostile
surface, may ultimately be found to harbor regions aswarm with
alien microbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big believer that there is life elsewhere,'' McNamee
said. ``Out of the billions of places that there are in this entire
universe, I don't believe that this is the one lucky place where it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
