<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-04 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NEWS AND NOTES
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times)  
( ms ) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Order on the Asphalt &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Highway traffic often resembles an amateur Indy 500, with
drivers speeding up, slowing down, changing lanes and passing in an
effort to reach their destinations sooner. But all that competitive
activity, it turns out, can work toward a collective good.
</P>
<P>
   Using computer simulations, scientists from the University of
Stuttgart and the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center in California
have discovered that a disorganized mix of cars and trucks,
traveling at different speeds and maneuvering to get ahead,
transforms itself into a coherent, and safer, block of traffic as
vehicle density reaches a certain point.
</P>
<P>
   In the simulations, which were backed up by real data from Dutch
highways, cars are able to pass without slowing down when there are
relatively few vehicles. As the density increases, with a
corresponding increase in slower-moving trucks and fewer large gaps
that allow for lane-changing, some cars will get stuck behind
trucks and have to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   When the critical density is reached, there are essentially no
large gaps, so all the vehicles are staying in their lanes and
traveling at a relatively slow speed.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers, writing in Nature, noted that once this
density is exceeded, some vehicles have to slow down even more to
maintain safe separation. This creates larger gaps, which allows
once more for lane-changing. Normal highway chaos ensues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Cosmic Panatela &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers studying the center of the Milky Way have found ...
a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   That is, a team of radio astronomers from Taiwan and the United
States has found that a region of hot gas at the center of the
galaxy is cigar-shaped, only one-fourth as wide as it is long.
</P>
<P>
   Most astronomers believe a black hole exists at the heart of the
Milky Way. In this view, the region of hot gas is a result of the
hole's immense gravitational pull. But the shape of the region is
puzzling and does not match theories about black holes. The
American-Taiwanese team suggests that some other mechanism _
perhaps a jet or a wind _ may be at work to explain the odd shape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sudden Shift in the Forest &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ecological change often occurs slowly, over long periods. But a
study of a New Mexico forest shows that nature can sometimes do
fast work.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists studying 50 years of aerial photographs of a
6,000-acre site in Bandelier National Monument have shown that the
boundary zone between two ecosystems _ one dominated by ponderosa
pine, the other by pinon and juniper _ shifted more than a mile in
less than five years during the 1950's. The chief cause, they say,
was a severe drought that killed off many ponderosa pines.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers noted that studies of similar longer-term shifts
had focused on birth and growth of vegetation. Their study draws
attention to the role played by death and could have implications
for other regions as they undergo climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
