<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-CULT-0105-COX     01-04 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CULT-0105-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEIGHBORS NOTICED IDLE AMERICANS BUT COULDN'T SEE SIGNS OF A
CULT
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEVASSERET ZION, Israel _ As Christian Americans, they already
stood out in the Jewish suburbs of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, the 14 men, women and children in custody were at the
center of a mystery about a cult, a police force wary of an influx
of Christians and predictions of world's final days.
</P>
<P>
   Left behind, along with two empty rented homes, were stories
about children who did not attend school and adults with money, but
no jobs, who occasionally hoarded food.
</P>
<P>
   And, apparently discarded by police in a raid the night before,
papers in a folder by the driveway at one house outlined the end of
the world and the prophesies of murderer Charles Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police and secret service raided the two houses Sunday
night, arresting eight adults and six children. Monday, 11 were
ordered deported within three days back to the United States and
three were held for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the group was part of the Denver, Colo.-based
Concerned Christians cult and intended to commit ``violent acts''
late this year that would hasten the return of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that the three men brought before
a court Monday said they were peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not here to hurt anybody,'' a detained John Bayles told
the court.
</P>
<P>
   For the Israeli government, the Americans appeared to be a
preview of what this country of 5 million Jews -- and 1 million
Muslims -- may face during the upcoming anniversary of the
Christian millennium.
</P>
<P>
   As the government prepares for an expected 4 million visitors to
Israel this year -- twice the annual figure -- officials are on
alert about fanatics who connect the year 2000 with Biblical
predictions of the world's end.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Mansfield, director of the Religious Movement Resource
Center, which follows the Concerned Christians, said that these
members of the group may not be violent.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said their leader, Monte Kim Miller has recently
threatened people inside and outside the group. Miller, whose
whereabouts are unknown, tells his several dozen followers that he
will die in Jerusalem late this year and be resurrected. Mansfield
said the arrests would be useful if they cause even these 14
followers to leave Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli political scientist Ehud Sprinzak, who studies religious
extremists, said concern over the millennium fanatics is justified.
But, he said police overreacted to this group. A response
attributed to the Israeli police's lack of experience with
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Police evidence about those arrested Sunday is undisclosed and,
a police source said, much of the impetus for the raid came from
information about the group's beliefs passed on by U.S. law
enforcement officials, rather than crimes committed here. No
charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israeli Police Spokesman Elihu Ben-Onn said the group may
have been planning to attack police in the hopes of starting a
suicidal shoot-out that would send themselves to heaven and bring
them back resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that the group planned violence on Jerusalem's
Temple Mount. The site of the Al-Aqsa Mosque, the third most holy
site in Islam, this high ground in Jerusalem's walled Old City is
coveted also by some Jews who see it as the sacred site of their
ancient temple.
</P>
<P>
   Officials fear an attack on the mosque could provoke a
world-wide bloodletting between Moslems and Jews -- which some say
is the final conflagration before Christ returns.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Ben-Onn said the arrests Sunday might be ``just
the beginning'' of an effort by police preparing for the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Concerned Christians were first on their list. They were
sought in Israel since October, when about 80 members of the group
were known to have sold their homes and are missing.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Begin optional add.)
</P>
<P>
   Police took boxes of files from the house Sunday. A manila
folder found on the ground Monday contained loose-leaf notes and
diagrams, apparently for a presentation, connecting the sayings of
Charles Manson, a 1971 Los Angeles earthquake and Florida's 1992
Hurricane Andrew as signs ``of the impending judgment of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The literature seemed out of place in a neighborhood on the
western outskirts of Jerusalem that seemed peacefully like suburban
America.
</P>
<P>
   At the home in Mevasseret Zion, the children used to play in the
park across the street, with swings, slides and rocking horses on
springs.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors said they were friendly, but one disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were totally unsociable,'' said Rami Hanouni, 60. ``They
would even turn their heads when you looked at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanouni said the group had been there three or four months and
twice had brought in crates of food for dozens of people.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, one bedroom of the house seemed sparse. There was
nothing on the walls and there were a few suitcases in a corner.
The bed was disheveled, possibly having been turned up in the
police search.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor contradicted Hanouni's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't seem weird in any way,'' said a 25-year-old
neighbor who would only identify herself as Hila.
</P>
<P>
   But, she agreed that the children were not in school and they
had vague reasons for coming there. The man introduced himself as
Terry Smith, from Colorado, who had sold his business and come to
Israel for a year because it was ``interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
