<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRUSADE-TV-LADN     01-04 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUSADE-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIFIC `CRUSADE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Somewhere Einstein, Oppenheimer and Feynman are
surely in high-RPM rotation in their graves over what passes these
days for the science in many science-fiction shows on television.
</P>
<P>
   And the late astronomer Carl Sagan even groused that many
space-based shows were further dumbing down an American populace
already veering perilously close to the inhabitants of C.M.
Kornbluth's classic 1951 sci-fi short story, ``The Marching
Morons.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, wherever they are, Albert, Robert, Richard and Carl can
stop twirling in their tombs.
</P>
<P>
   One of Big Science's great bastions, the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena, is helping put the facts back into
science-fiction TV, advising the creators of a show now being shot
in the San Fernando Valley, ``Crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   It inhabits the same future universe as the TNT cable hit
``Babylon 5,'' which ended production last year after its planned
five-year run. But where that show was set in a politically wracked
space station, ``Crusade'' follows the crew of a space ship as it
searches the galaxy for a cure to a virus that threatens to
exterminate humans. Depending on the fate of the NBA playoffs,
which TNT also televises, the show will debut sometime between
April and June.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the storied JPL rocket scientists have
consulted on a television series, said Joan Horvath, the
laboratory's business alliances manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a lot of fun for all the people working on
the project for the exposure between the two cultures,'' Horvath
said.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration started after ``Crusade'' producer-director
John Copeland took a special tour of JPL, where, it turns out, many
``Babylon 5'' fans can be found.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations there turned into a formal technical advisory
role when Copeland and partners J. Michael Straczynski and Doug
Netter began envisioning the new show.
</P>
<P>
   JPL put together a team of scientists _ with many others lined
up wanting to volunteer _ to help the ``Crusade'' creators. Their
first task was to help imagine what the ultimate killer virus would
be like.
</P>
<P>
   Viruses are simple things, mostly a sheath of protein wrapped
around a squiggle of DNA. But that simplicity has allowed nature to
create some devastating plagues on its own, including the AIDS and
Ebola viruses.
</P>
<P>
   So what would happen if an ancient, vengeful alien race wanted
to build a particularly nasty virus that would target humans and
resist cures. If the aliens used nanotechnology techniques now
being explored by researchers, the JPL scientists said, they could
construct the ultimate plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and said, `If we designed a virus (250) years from
now, what would it look like?''' said Straczynski. ``It got pretty
scary. But the JPL people said what they came up with theoretically
could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's underlying premise gives it a tension and an urgency
that many shows lack, said star Gary Cole, who plays ship's Capt.
Matthew Gideon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a strong choice, a simple definition of a mission
so anyone can hop on,'' Cole said, talking in his trailer outside
the cavernous, anonymous industrial building in Sunland that has
been home for both ``Babylon 5'' and ``Crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   With species-wide annihilation looming, Cole said, ``the stakes
can't get any higher than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Straczynski, the main writer of both shows, had always tried to
keep the science straight on ``Babylon 5,'' part of what built the
show's fan base at JPL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a lot better,'' said Straczynski, whose small office
inside the building is crammed with ``Babylon 5'' games, videos,
posters and other products. ``It was part of the sense of wonder:
That's what it would be like in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Envisioning the future has stimulated the JPL scientists'
imaginations as well, Horvath said.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, even in their consulting work, the lab's 5,000
employees focus on solving near-term technical problems, like
getting the Pathfinder to Mars or detecting leaks on the
Trans-Alaska Pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a good thing because it's forced us to think
a bit about what things are going to look like in 250 years,''
Horvath said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same period separates us from (18th-century explorer)
Capt. James Cook as separates us from this (show's) time period,''
Horvath said. ``If you look at the distance in that way, how would
they have thought about us (from the past) and how should we think
about these people (in the future)? What will be easy that was
almost impossible (before)?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, each week's script is delivered to Horvath, who parcels
specific questions out to team members.
</P>
<P>
   They in turn create a fat report outlining such things as the
atmosphere, gravity and geology of the planet being explored in
that week's show, and Netter, Copeland and Straczynski cull details
that can be incorporated into the show.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the acting is done in the sprawling sets in Sunland that
make up the ship's ``interior,'' and house backdrops for some
planet-side scenes each week as well.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles down Lankershim Boulevard at Netter Digital Studios
in North Hollywood, those sets and the JPL suggestions get further
dressed into TV reality at the hands of the same special-effects
artists who helped ``Babylon 5'' win two Hugo science-fiction
awards for best dramatic presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the huge physical sets, the effects artists tweak even
many interior shots, replacing ``blue screen'' backgrounds with
computer-generated scenes of, say, the view through a spaceship's
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can take Joe's imagination and go as far as he wanted to
go,'' Netter said.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the show's creators are counting on pulling in ``Babylon
5's'' rabid fan base, they are reluctant to call it a spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Babylon 5' was sort of like `Bus Stop' in that the stories
came to the station,'' said producer-director John Copeland. ``In
`Crusade,' we go to the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship does sometimes stop at the Babylon 5 space station,
whose characters will make guest appearances, though only Tracy
Scoggins' Capt. Elizabeth Lochley has a substantial presence.
</P>
<P>
   Scoggins, whose character only appeared in the last year of
``Babylon 5,'' said during a break in shooting a scene with Cole
that she was excited to be asked back on the new show because she
so enjoyed playing Lochley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very flattered by that,'' said Scoggins. ``This is a
character I very much wanted. I'm usually very nonchalant about
whether I get a role _ but not this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating the show has been easy in one sense: Virtually the
entire off-screen crew from ``Babylon 5'' has stayed on for
``Crusade,'' creating a familylike stability uncommon in first-year
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Scoggins, who joshes warmly with Copeland and crew members
during shooting breaks and at lunch in the eating area outside the
building, said it makes for a much more welcoming environment in
which to work.
</P>
<P>
   Cole, who previously starred in ``Midnight Caller'' and
``American Gothic,'' called his role the ``trickiest'' he's ever
attempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're very often talking a lot about stuff that's
imaginary,'' Cole said. ``The language, the lingo, the techno-garb
have to seem familiar. It's finding the right tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right tone has sometimes been a challenge for the
JPL collaboration, too, because reality doesn't run all of the
show.
</P>
<P>
   One good example is the use of faster-than-light space travel.
Though it makes a galaxy-wide search for a cure possible, Albert,
Robert and Richard still say you can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland cites recent research on the possibilities of
interstellar travel for scientific cover, but even Horvath says
dramatic license still is required sometimes in even the most
accurate of science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a plot that he wants, you have no choice,'' Horvath
said. ``We wave our hands and say that's alien technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, said Horvath, most of the time, the scientists'
suggestions become part of the dramatists' creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a drama,'' Horvath said. ``But by and large, when
you come up and say, `Wouldn't this be more interesting?' he stands
there and scratches his head and says, `Well, cool'.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1700EST &QL; 
