<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-04 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER DOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Those who think the wrong Dole ran for president
two years ago _ and to judge by the polls that's a lot of people _
got a political break Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When Elizabeth Dole announced that she was leaving her post as
head of the American Red Cross, she did not fully commit herself to
a campaign for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination. But she
said, ``There may be another way for me to serve the country,''
which sounded as though she is preparing to take up where her
husband Bob left off.
</P>
<P>
   The female Dole, 62, will inevitably be suspected of going after
the GOP vice presidential nomination as a more realistic option
than reaching for the top spot. Elbowing her way into the political
dialogue and demonstrating she can compete for votes with the big
boys would be a good way to get a male GOP nominee's attention.
</P>
<P>
   But that may underestimate her. She would come to the
presidential contest with formidable credentials for the White
House, not the least of which are her national name recognition and
her perpetual popularity with both men and women.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll recently ranked her the third most admired female
in America. With a 6 percent rating, she trailed only First Lady
Hillary Clinton at 28 percent and television star Oprah Winfrey at
8 percent. Losing 1996 GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole, by
contrast, was named most admired by only 1 percent of those
surveyed, ranking low alongside Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Elizabeth Dole has never indicated much interest in
seeing her own name on the ballot, preferring instead to serve in
appointive posts and to promote her husband's career. Not that this
was small stuff. Her posts were high ones, including two Cabinet
spots. And Bob Dole's career nearly rose to the pinnacle of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is a practiced speaker and campaigner, she has
avoided becoming directly involved in many of the most contentious
issues that divide the GOP today and would bedevil her as a
candidate. If she has disagreed with any of her husband's
positions, she has been silent about it.
</P>
<P>
   During Bob Dole's losing 1996 campaign against President
Clinton, she was his chief surrogate on the road. But Scott Reed,
Dole's campaign manager, insisted, ``We have never had her out
breaking new ground on policy. She never would.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet times, and opportunities, change. At this moment in history
the country desperately longs for a return to political civility.
It is an elusive quality she has come to symbolize with her
gracious manner and her resistance to personal insults and cheap
partisan shots.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Republican Party suffers from a stubborn gender
gap. (Women have voted Democratic in substantially higher
percentages than they have voted Republican in the past three
presidential elections.)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the quintessential southern belle with the
honeyed tongue and the piquant brains, may be just what the doctor
ordered. She is serious and professional, respected and renowned.
But she has fewer hard edges than Hillary Clinton and is less
threatening to conservatives still uncomfortable with female
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   She speaks North Carolinian fluently. The creamy language of her
native state has a comforting cadence that sells well throughout
the South, where the primaries can be crucial to a GOP candidate.
It may be lost on the North, but every politician needs a foreign
language.
</P>
<P>
   She has more credibility with female voters than her party in
general, which is stuck with positions on family-related issues
that offend many women. These include opposition to affirmative
action, abortion rights, family leave and federal funding for
child-care assistance, prenatal and postnatal care, and more
teachers and better school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Her efforts to identify with women's rights have been erratic,
although she correctly points to her own career as pioneering in
the political world. Regarding abortion, she said during Bob's 1996
campaign that ``I'm where he is _ I'm pro-life.'' That may help to
mollify the religious right, but it will not win her any feminist
points.
</P>
<P>
   If she does not develop an agenda separate from that of her
husband, she is unlikely to get very far. His congressional
prestige allowed him to tower over his party rivals without having
to shape an appealing platform to run on, a lack that voters
noticed. And he found himself trapped in the coils of the
domineering GOP right wing. This undercut his reputation as a
sensible moderate and killed him at the polls in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   How she could overcome the litmus tests of the intolerant right
wing to win the nomination without changing her pleasant image is a
mystery. Perhaps experience taught her husband a trick or two he
could pass along.
</P>
<P>
   But her real problem could be getting past Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the current frontrunner. This is nepotism heaven: a spouse of
a presidential nominee and a son of a president running against
each other. But maybe not against each other very long.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a Bush-Dole ticket, or a Dole-Bush ticket, could be just
the thing to revive Republican fortunes. At a minimum, it would
sound familiar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
