   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ What causes brake pedal vibration, or
``pulsation,'' and why. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-PAGERS _ ATLANTA _ Welcome to the world of the
latest in hand-held computing, the interactive pager. Except for
its beep, it has little in common with its cousin, the ordinary
pager. The BellSouth Interactive Pager, a companion of mine for
several weeks, is different because it sends and receives
information. Like an ordinary computer, it has directories and an
electronic address book. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ ATLANTA _ ``Free'' is the operative word for today.
I'll tell you how to find your own free home in cyberspace, then
we'll talk about some free tools and techniques that can make your
Web site into a good home. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ Software reviews. This week: National
Geographic Trip Planner DeLuxe. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ This column will not move tonight. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ A little care can keep you from being
misled by Web ``information.'' (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVEDTECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are
writing about. This week: Hasbro's ``Stratego'' CD. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Ironically, competition for the best Mac
Web browser has not slackened a bit between Microsoft and Netscape
during the long weeks of the government's antitrust suit against
the world's dominant software provider.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is readying the next version of its Internet Explorer
browser, which will probably be previewed at the MacWorld
convention in San Francisco this week. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Bell bottoms, disco and Donnie and Marie
have made comebacks. So did John Travolta and Richard Nixon. About
the only things from the 1970s that haven't returned are TV variety
shows and pig Latin. A slew of sites offer text translators. You
type in a line of text or, in some cases, a Web address, and the
application turns it into pig Latin. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
