<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND05-COX     01-04 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medical breakthroughs intrigue weeklies
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is little science can do to relieve Bill Clinton's
political headache, but doctors do offer new hope for migraine
sufferers. Newsweek ($2.95) reports on the latest breakthroughs in
treatments for those throbbing headaches, which affect 18 percent
of all women and 6 percent of men. Researchers still haven't
figured out what causes migraines, but triptans, a new group of
synthetic compounds, may be just what the doctor ordered to make
the pain disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95) also pushes the impeachment story inside for a
cover package on the future of medicine. Breakthroughs in genetic
engineering may conquer cancer, grow new blood vessels in the heart
and create new organs. Lifespans will be increased and parents will
be able to choose children's traits. All this is possible, says
Time managing editor Walter Isaacson, but are there ethical
problems?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the federal project to map the human genome is
expected to be completed by 2003, and scientists will be able to
identify genetic error ``as quickly as a supermarket scanner,''
says Time's Frederic Golden. The question is how such information
can be kept secret so it won't be used by potential employers or
insurers. Why should that matter? Well, knowing that you are
susceptible to cancer or diabetes or some other disease would allow
HMOs to keep their costs down by screening out risky candidates.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTBEAT: Even The New Yorker ($3) devotes a chunk of its Jan.
11 issue to medicine. Jerome Groopman takes us into the operating
room at Boston's Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center for an
over-the-shoulder look at a new kind of coronary bypass. Instead of
stopping the heart and hooking the patient to a heart-lung machine,
as is the common practice, surgeon Billy Cohn operates on the
beating heart. Such a procedure, Groopman says, is safer, cheaper
and easier.
</P>
<P>
   On a lighter note, Christopher Buckley writes the headlines we
may _ or may not _ see in 1999. Some examples: ``Poll: Most No
Longer Care Who Is President''; ``In British TV Interview, Lewinsky
Tells of Anger Over Her Secret Service Name, `Humidor'''; ``Clinton
Says He Was `Only Trying to Comfort' Widow After Funeral''; and
``White House Calls Widow a `Scheming Slut.'''
</P>
<P>
   CLASS ACTS: Movies such as ``Scream'' and ``The Faculty'' are
aimed at more sophisticated teens than those of earlier
generations, but the basic elements of youth rebellion and sex
haven't changed since the teensploitation flicks of the 1950s and
'60s. Spin ($2.99) presents a celebration of the tight T-shirts and
out-of-control baby-sitter genre. Not only are the TV networks
airing nine teen-driven programs, but also 11 films about high
school high jinks will open in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROYAL MISTRESS: She's been called ``the Rottweiler'' and
worse, but Camilla Parker Bowles has survived the epithets and the
gossip. Now More ($2.99), the magazine for women older than 40,
shows the other side of Prince Charles' companion. According to
Robert Lacy, the romance is genuine and the couple seem genuinely
suited for each other. And along with the profile is an intriguing
sidebar on ``the other woman'' and what types are attractive to
middle-aged men. Besides the younger ``new trophy,'' there's the
``soul mate,'' who taps into a man's spiritual or artistic
passions, and the ``old friend,'' a woman who has been around for
years.
</P>
<P>
   AND THE NOMINEES MAY BE: If this is January, it must be time to
start thinking about the Academy Awards. Oscar nominations won't be
announced until Feb. 9, but that doesn't stop Entertainment Weekly
($2.99) from jumping the gun with its predictions. EW's choices for
best picture are ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Shakespeare in Love,''
``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``Waking Ned Devine'' and ``The Truman
Show.'' In the best actor and best actress categories, favorites
are Tom Hanks (``Private Ryan),'' Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth'')
and Gwyneth Paltrow (``Shakespeare'').
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
