<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, January 10.) 
 (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Never on Sunday, Says Cayman Islands &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this year, cruise ships will no longer be allowed to
dock at the Cayman Islands on Sundays, Christmas Day and Good
Friday, apparently because of complaints from church officials. The
decision, by the islands' department of tourism, was conveyed to
the cruise lines in a letter last month from L. Angela Martins, the
director of tourism. While Grand Cayman, the islands' capital, is a
familiar stop on cruises to the western Caribbean and through the
Panama Canal, only a few ships call there on Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Royal Caribbean's Splendour of the Seas docks there on its
10- and 11-day Caribbean itineraries, and has six Sunday visits
scheduled for this year, through April 18. Cayman Islands officials
have waived the ban for those six visits, and in return Royal
Caribbean has agreed to move its scheduled Good Friday call on
April 2 to April 1, stopping on Good Friday at Ocho Rios, Jamaica.
At press time Royal Caribbean and Celebrity officials were still
discussing whether Celebrity's Mercury would stop at the Cayman
Islands on Good Friday, as scheduled, or also switch days or skip
that port. Princess and Costa cruise lines are also talking with
Cayman Islands officials, while Norwegian Cruise Line, with only
one Sunday call at Grand Cayman scheduled for this year, says it
will abide by the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Florida Caribbean Cruise Ship Association has
asked Cayman Islands officials to delay the ban, since published
itineraries for 1999 already include Grand Cayman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Silver Collections On View in Virginia &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two galleries displaying fine silver have opened in eastern
Virginia within an hour's drive of each other. One is at the
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in Richmond, the other in Colonial
Williamsburg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The objects in the Richmond gallery, named Discover Silver, are
a gift from Rita Gans, a New Yorker who collected silver with her
husband, Jerome, who died in 1986. The Ganses put together a
notable collection of 17th- and 18th-century British ceremonial
silver. The museum is open every day except Monday from 11 a.m. to
5 p.m. except on Thursday, when it closes at 8 p.m. It suggests an
admission donation of $4. Information: (804) 367-0844. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Williamsburg installation is named the Mary Jewett Gaiser
Silver Gallery, honoring its principal benefactor. Mrs. Gaiser's
first husband, George F. Jewett, with whom she developed the
collection, was chairman of the Potlatch Corporation, a lumber and
paper company in San Francisco.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gallery's first show, called ``Treasure Quest: Great Silver
Collections From Colonial Williamsburg,'' will run through 1999 and
features feature both silver and silver plate in flatware, skewers,
marrow scoops and Scottish silver chalices. One feature is an
epergne, or large table centerpiece, with covered dishes and a
matching platter. Mrs. Gaiser saved the epergne from destruction by
buying it in 1943. Had she not bought it, it would have been taken
back to Britain on a ship that was torpedoed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Gaiser gallery is part of the DeWitt Wallace Gallery. It is
open from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily. Admission is by any of the
various passes sold by Colonial Williamsburg or by a one-day ticket
to all four museums costing $10. Further information: (757)
220-7724.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Last Holdout Joins Airline Smoking Ban &LR;
</P>
<P>
   All flights, both domestic and international, on United States
airlines are now completely smoke-free, according to the Department
of Transportation. In 1989, Congress banned smoking on all domestic
flights. Since then more and more airlines have been instituting
no-smoking policies on their international flights. Last month the
last holdout, Tower Air, eliminated smoking on all its
international flights.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign airlines with flights to the United States have
also banned smoking on all or most of their flights. A list of
foreign carriers and their smoking policies is available on the
Department of Transportation's Web site at ostpxweb.dot.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ski Web Site Lists Resorts, Snow Reports &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Winter-sports enthusiasts can now plan their vacations at
www.ski-resorts.com on the Internet. One feature of the site, begun
in late October, is an online booking directory for more than 400
resorts throughout the world that allows comparison shopping and
room reservations. The site also includes information about
weather, snowfall, lift ticket prices and trail maps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, about 2,000 vacation properties, including hotels,
condominiums and rental homes, can be reviewed and booked directly.
Twice-daily snow reports are provided for some 500 mountains, with
hourly weather updates for more than 1,500 places.. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information about lodging, dining, transportation, child care
and activities is available for featured ski towns _ currently Vail
and Aspen, Colo.; Lake Tahoe and Mammoth, Calif.; Park City, Utah;
Jackson Hole, Wyo.; Sun Valley, Idaho, and Whistler in British
Columbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discounts are offered regularly on the site, and last-minute
travelers can sign up for e-mail alerts of special deals. A related
site, www.mountainzone.com, provides news about skiing and
snowboarding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Letting Your Fingers Reserve a Campsite &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Camping reservations for the most popular National Park areas
can be made on the Internet, using a Visa, Mastercard or Discover
credit card. The secure Internet address is reservations.nps.gov.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The site, which was launched Jan. 5, provides data, including
what is available, for 23 parks and 3 tours. Bookings may be made
five months in advance. The service operates from 10 a.m. to 10
p.m., Eastern time. Reservations can still be made by phone; the
number for most campsites is (800) 365-2267; for Yosemite, it is
(800) 436-7275, and for Carlsbad Caverns, Mammoth Cave and
Frederick Douglass tours, (800) 967-2283.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In New Orleans, Madame John's Legacy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For more than 200 years, the house at 632 Dumaine Street in New
Orleans has survived fire, floods and hurricanes to become a French
Quarter landmark and rare example of the classic Creole cottages
built by families that settled the city in the 18th century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After being closed for more than a decade, the small museum
known in the neighborhood as Madame John's _ its official name is
Madame John's Legacy _ is freshly restored and open to the public,
still a model of adaptation to life in the subtropics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its design resembles the 18th-century architecture found in the
French West Indies. High ceilings mitigate the stifling summer
heat. The living quarters were raised from the ground to escape
dampness and flooding. Tall, carefully placed windows capture
breezes from the Mississippi River, which flows nearby.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The house dates to 1789, when it replaced a similar structure
built in 1730 that had been ruined by a fire that destroyed most of
New Orleans in 1788. In 1794 a fire that leveled much of the
rebuilt city spared Madame John's Legacy. The name was taken from a
book of short stories, ``Old Creole Days,'' by George Washington
Cable, who used the cottage as the setting for a melodramatic tale
about a woman of mixed racial ancestry.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Madame John's Legacy was closed more than 10 years ago by the
Louisiana State Museum system, which owns it, largely because of a
money shortage. It reopened in November with a permanent exhibition
of folk art, 70 paintings, drawings, sculptures and mixed-media
pieces by self-taught Louisiana artists, donated by two New Orleans
collectors, Dr. Kurt Gitter and Alice Rae Yelen, his wife. The
ground floor, enclosed by thick brick walls and once used as a wine
cellar, contains a series of exhibits explaining the history of the
house, using reproductions of old paintings, documents and pottery
found in excavations of the site. The museum, (800) 568-6968, is
open 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday to Sunday; admission is $3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
