<HEADLINE>
TIME IS ON OUR SIDE, YES IT IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   Time dissipates to shimmering ether
the solid angularity of facts. _ Ralph Waldo Emerson
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ According to a commonly used calendar (the
Gregorian), we are now in the ultimate home stretch of the second
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   In the small scheme of things _ our lives _ this is a major
deal. All that remains of the only century most of us have ever
known is a year, one official clump of 365 days in which we can use
``19'' and still signify the present. Even more dramatic, only one
more official clump remains in which we can use ``1'' to signify
our entire millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This time next year _ Lord willing and the Y2K bug don't rise _
our documents, dossiers, diaries and detritus will carry the
utterly new and strange (to us) date of ``2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In the big scheme of things _ the 4.5 billion years in which
Earth has existed _ all of this means nothing. Millennium
schmillennium. What is ``a thousand years'' really? And who got to
start the official countdown clock?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind ``a year,'' time itself is not only relative, it's
fabricated, made up by human beings who want to impose our idea of
``order'' on what we perceive as ``chaos.'' (Tell it to the Milky
Way.)
</P>
<P>
   Worse, human beings, as we know us today (upright in posture if
not always in deed), have been around only about 100,000 years _
give or take a millennium or two. While we likely have spent most
of that 100,000 years trying to ``order'' the universe, we didn't
even get around to formalizing the attempt with an actual calendar
until about 6,200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When I say ``we,'' that is also relative. The ancient Egyptians,
not Hallmark or the Sierra Club, came up with the first recorded
calendar in 4241 B.C. The ancient Jewish calendar crossed the
finish line second in 3760 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   B.C. stands of course for ``Before Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the people who lived during the tens of thousands of
years before Christ thought of themselves as existing ``B.C.'', but
that's where we've stuck them. All of them. The Neanderthals, the
Cro-Magnons, the Egyptians (with and without calendars), the kings
(Tut and Nebuchadnezzar), the warriors (Alexander and Hannibal),
the poets and holy men (Homer and Buddha), the Caesars and the
millions of just-folks.
</P>
<P>
   Christ's birth came to signify the beginning of modern time and
the first millennium, so tough on the folks who didn't make the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   The ironic thing is, even Christ's birthdate is relative. Jerry
Falwell, Pat Robertson and U.S. Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma do
not tend to dwell on the subject, but the best that scientists and
Biblical scholars can do is pin down Jesus' actual birth to
sometime during an 11-year period about 2,000 years ago. He could
have been born four years before we've always said he was born or
as many as seven years after.
</P>
<P>
   Since no one wants to think about re-doing the time lines of
history to reflect this variance, those of us who follow the
Gregorian calendar have basically opted to pretend: Modern time and
the first millennium began the year we say that Jesus was born.
Life, love, commerce and international airline schedules shall
unfold accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   As an old (but not ancient) Italian saying puts it: Se non e
vero e ben trovato _ If it's not true, it's to the point.
</P>
<P>
   Our point now is to fasten our gaze upon an official beginning
of the third millennium and to imbue that beginning with meaning.
Technically, the new millennium will not begin until Jan. 1, 2001,
but _ true to form _ the majority of us is ignoring the
technicality. So, as of this day, we have only 362 remaining clumps
of 24 hours in which to review and assess our place in the universe
and to plan for our individual commemoration of the momentous (to
us) event.
</P>
<P>
   In the big scheme of things, such an exercise is decidedly dumb.
But in the small scheme, where most human beings have always spent
most of their time, it makes perfect sense. Relatively speaking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
