<SLUG> BC-SCI-CASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASES: WHEN RULES FOR BETTER CARE EXACT THEIR OWN COST
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times)  
(ms) 
 By SANDEEP JAUHAR, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  NEW YORK _ I recently spent a week as a ``night float'' at a
major New York City teaching hospital, staying up all night while
other residents slept. My shift began at 5 p.m., when residents
departed for the day, and ended at 7 the next morning, when they
returned. Meanwhile, I was responsible for up to 80 very sick
patients.
</P>
<P>
   One night, shortly after sign-out, a patient with colon cancer
began thrashing about wildly and hallucinating. What might be wrong
with him? I had no clue. What were the results of his blood tests?
I did not know. Could I reassure his family about the results of
his brain scan? I would have to get back to them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical situation for a night float, grappling with a
potentially serious problem with not enough information.
Paradoxically, though, it was the result of changes meant to
improve, not diminish, the care newly-minted doctors give to
patients in New York hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The changes arose from a chain of events that began late one
spring evening in 1984, when a young woman, Libby Zion, entered the
emergency room at the New York Hospital. She was agitated and
running a high fever. Eight hours later, she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Though the exact cause of her death remains a mystery, her case
aroused intense debate over what until then had been little
discussed: the way young doctors are trained in New York State. If
the residents who cared for her had been more rested, many
wondered, would they have been able to save her life?
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a special commission, led by Dr. Bertrand M. Bell,
proposed a number of changes in residency training in New York
State: closer supervision of residents in emergency rooms, more
help with routine tasks like drawing blood and strict work limits
on residents. Residents were prohibited from working more than 24
hours at a stretch or more than 80 hours a week. Eventually, these
changes spread to residency programs throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals that had relied on interns and residents as
medical staff, often working 36 hours at a stretch every two or
three days, were forced to grapple with the problem of
cross-coverage: providing care to patients when their primary
doctor was not on duty. As a result, many hospitals created night
floats _ residents who worked night shifts for specified periods of
time, usually a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the medical profession, including most residents,
applauded the changes. Studies show that, under the old system,
residents after a call night score lower on tests of simple
reasoning, response time, concentration and recall. Many, both
inside and outside medicine, argued that residents could not
provide proper care for patients if they were chronically fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial in The New England Journal of Medicine in 1988,
Dr. Timothy McCall wrote: ``Few would choose to ride in a car
driven by a resident coming off a 36-hour shift. It should come as
no surprise that the public would question the ability of
sleep-deprived residents to make life-and-death decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators also hoped the changes would reduce the toll exacted
on residents in the form of broken marriages, cynicism and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too few residents emerge from training thankful for the
opportunity to practice in a fascinating and intellectually
challenging field,'' Dr. McCall wrote in his editorial. ``Instead,
many believe that the world owes them something for what they've
been through.''
</P>
<P>
   But now it is apparent the changes have brought their own
problems. For one thing, they have left night floats taking care of
large numbers of patients about whom they may know very little.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Bell regulations have argued that there was no
scientific evidence showing that tired residents harm patients,
either by increasing mortality rates or complications. Indeed, a
1993 study in the Journal of the American Medical Association
appeared to indict the very cross-coverage hospitals were relying
on to conform with the new regulations. It showed that increasing
cross-coverage in a large urban hospital caused delays in tests
because of resident oversight and increased preventable
complications like drug reactions and infections.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Norman Levinsky, a residency director at Boston University
Medical Center, wrote in The New England Journal of Medicine in
1988: ``My own experience in staffing our intensive care unit both
in the traditional manner and with a ``night float'' suggests that
errors due to faulty transfer of information are at least as
frequent as those due to fatigue from being on call overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some educators have also argued that work limits were
detrimental to a resident's training, by interrupting learning and
creating a kind of shift-work mentality that is inconsistent with
one of medicine's ideals: that a doctor should assume
round-the-clock responsibility for his patients.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents I know support the changes, as they have
definitely made residency more tolerable. Call nights are no longer
so terrifying when admissions by on-call residents end at 10 p.m.
And post-call days are no longer a fatigue-ridden blur.
</P>
<P>
   But the benefits are sometimes easily forgotten on the night
shift, when inexperience, ignorance and sickness mix in unsettling
ways.
</P>
<P>
   One night during my week as night float, a middle-aged man
hospitalized with colon cancer began to bleed severely from
somewhere in his intestinal tract. At 3 a.m., in his dimly lighted
room, he was asking me questions, but I knew so little of his
complicated case there was not much I could tell him. I felt like a
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The results of his tests, the site of the bleeding, when he
might go for radiation therapy that could save his life _ all that
information was deep in his chart, and in the mind of his sleeping
resident.
</P>
<P>
   At another point that night, I ordered a drug to relieve the
severe hiccups of a patient with esophageal cancer. The drug is
widely used, but as I walked by the nursing station, I casually
checked his chart. There, amid his papers, was a brief note. The
patient had suffered a severe reaction to this particular drug. I
immediately canceled the order, relieved that I had caught this
mistake but alarmed by how easily another could slip through the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents like the night float. You work hard and under
fire most of the night _ residents joke that your beeper goes into
status epilepticus, with constant seizures _ but in the morning
your responsibility is lifted. ``I walk into the hospital
empty-handed, and I leave empty-handed, and I like that,'' one
resident told me.
</P>
<P>
   Most cross-coverage problems stem from inadequate sign-out, as
residents rush to leave the hospital and cross-covering residents
forget to ask important questions. At my hospital, we use a
computerized sign-out program for detailing patients' major medical
problems, hospital course and medications. And a recent small study
showed that standardized sign-out sheets can also help prevent
unnecessary complications.
</P>
<P>
   But more efforts are needed to insure proper information
transfer between residents so that the Bell regulations, intended
to protect patients, do not end up endangering them in new and
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
