<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7530 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DRUG-LABELS-NYT &LR;      01-04 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DRUG-LABELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH FOR CAUSE OF DIET PILL'S RISK YIELDS NEW WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A scientist who helped to develop Redux, one of two weight-loss
drugs taken off the market in 1997 after they were linked to heart
damage, is now suggesting that the problems were not due to Redux
alone, but rather to its being combined with other drugs that had
unrecognized effects.
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, Dr. Richard Wurtman, director of the Clinical
Research Center at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said
his investigation into Redux had led him to believe that
phentermine, a prescription diet drug that was taken with Redux but
is still on the market, might be unsafe if taken together with the
antidepressant Prozac or similar drugs. This risk, he said, might
also exist with some over-the-counter cold medicines and
weight-loss pills.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the current issue of The Lancet, an international
medical journal published in Britain, Wurtman and two other
researchers recommended that the labels on phentermine and the
other medicines be changed to warn consumers of the possible risks
of combining medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Food and Drug Administration did not return
telephone calls seeking comment on Wurtman's suggestion. But other
scientists said his recommendation, based on experiments in just 17
people, needed much more study. It appeared in The Lancet as a
brief ``research letter,'' a category assigned to reports that are
not as comprehensive or scientifically rigorous as full-length
articles. Wurtman's co-authors were Timothy Maher, of the
Massachusetts College of Pharmacy and Allied Health Sciences, and
Ismail Ulus, of the Department of Pharmacology at Uludag University
in Bursa, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's speculative,'' said John Foreyt, an obesity researcher at
the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston. ``But it's
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Phentermine has been on the market in the United States for
decades to treat obesity. Two other drugs were approved later:
fenfluramine, sold as Pondimin, and dexfenfluramine, sold as Redux.
None was a smashing success, but people lost more weight if they
took phentermine with one of the other two, in the combination that
became known as fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in 1997, when doctors began reporting cases of
heart-valve damage in fen-phen users, fenfluramine and
dexfenfluramine were taken off the market. Phentermine was left in
use, because it had been around for a long time without causing
problems, and because none of the reported cases of valve damage
had occurred in people taking phentermine alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although fenfluramine and dexfenfluramine were widely suspected
of causing the heart damage, scientists have yet to determine how
it actually occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reservations, Foreyt said Wurtman's report made an
important point about the risks people take when they mix medicines
in ways that have not been tested or approved by the Food and Drug
Administration. The fen-phen combination, for instance, was never
tested or approved, even though the individual ingredients were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combinations of drugs should not be used unless they've been
approved,'' Foreyt said. ``You don't know the effects of the
mixture. That should be common sense.'' But, he acknowledged, many
people are so desperate to lose weight that they will try almost
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Experts like Foreyt say it is important for people to discuss
all drugs they take with their doctors, even if they are
over-the-counter medications or supplements, because many seemingly
helpful drugs can have dangerous side effects when taken in
combination. ``There is a general belief in this country that if
something is over the counter it's harmless,'' Foreyt said.
``That's not necessarily so.''
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers are wary of The Lancet report, given Wurtman's
connection to Redux. In addition to helping develop it, he is a
director and shareholder of Interneuron Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
Lexington, Mass., one of the companies to which the drug was
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   But Wurtman said there were no plans to try to return Redux to
the market. ``If something that I had a part in inventing as a
scientist turned out maybe to be dangerous to people, then I'd be
obligated to spend a little time trying to figure out what was
going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wurtman and his colleagues decided to study phentermine, and
found that it had an effect that was neither mentioned on its label
nor widely recognized. Phentermine interferes with the body's
ability to break down the hormone serotonin. Fenfluramine and
dexfenfluramine also increase serotonin levels, so that taking
either of them with phentermine effectively blocks all of
serotonin's exits from the bloodstream. It is not known whether
patients taking the drugs have developed excesses of the hormone,
but very high levels, caused by certain illnesses, have been shown
to damage heart valves.
</P>
<P>
   Phentermine inhibits an enzyme, monoamine oxidase, that normally
breaks down serotonin. Other drugs also inhibit the same enzyme,
and they are considered unsafe when combined with other drugs that
raise serotonin, like Prozac and related antidepressants like Paxil
and Zoloft. All the drugs that either inhibit the enzyme or raise
serotonin in some other way carry labels warning that they must not
be used together.
</P>
<P>
   Phentermine, however, is not labeled as an inhibitor of the
enzyme, because that effect was not proved. Wurtman and his
colleagues contend that it has a relatively weak effect on the
enzyme, but might nonetheless cause harmful interactions in some
patients. The research team said it had also found that several
other drugs were weak inhibitors of the enzyme, and urged that they
also be labeled so that doctors prescribing Prozac or related drugs
might warn their patients. The other medications included
pseudoephedrine, the decongestant in cold medicines like Sudafed,
and ephedrine and norephedrine, which are found in over-the counter
diet pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to scare people about this,'' Wurtman said. ``But
doctors who prescribe drugs that block serotonin uptake, like
antidepressants, should have in the back of their minds the
interaction between them and monoamine oxidase inhibitors.''
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern to obesity experts is that some doctors are
prescribing phentermine and Prozac, in a combination known as
phen-pro, to people who want to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never use it,'' said Foreyt, calling it a good example
of a combination that has never been studied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
