<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC ENLISTS SAWYER, GIBSON TO BOOST `GMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diane Sawyer and Charles Gibson have been recruited as a new _
but temporary _ anchor team by ABC in a dramatic shakeup announced
Monday by the network to rejuvenate its sagging ``Good Morning
America.'' Both are taking on the assignments in addition to their
existing duties.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are to be effective Jan. 18. Lisa McRee, one of the
current anchors, is expecting a baby in August and will return to
Los Angeles for special assignments and projects for ABC News. Her
co-anchor Kevin Newman has been named a correspondent for ABC
News's ``Nightline.'' He'll be based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily convened teleconference from Manhattan Monday, ABC
News president David Westin disclosed the choice of Sawyer and
Gibson, who appeared with him and seemed as surprised as anyone by
the turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked if they tested around here for amphetamines,'' Sawyer
joked. ``I have more stamina than you might expect if you saw me
without makeup in the morning. Everyone in the news division has a
stake in `Good Morning America.' I've been getting too much sleep,
anyway. It's not good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning, Gibson, who ended 11 years as ``GMA'' host in
April, admitted he couldn't tell his wife what the advantages were
in returning to the show. ``I'll continue to be tired on Friday
Mornings,'' he said. Gibson said his reaction when Westin first
proposed the teaming was a laughing ``Yeah, wouldn't that be a
hoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Westin said Sawyer told him: ``If the news division needs me to
do it, then I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America'' has sunk well behind NBC's ``Today''
show in the ratings over the past few years. ``Today'' now draws
more than twice as many viewers as its rival. The slide continued
after McRee took over for Joan Lunden in September 1997 and Newman
replaced Gibson last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sawyer and Gibson, who are ``20/20'' anchors, will continue
those duties while taking on their new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Westin said they were recruited because the network felt the
struggling two-hour Morning show was threatening the image of its
news division, of which ``GMA'' is a part.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer, who joined ``20/20'' last September after her
``Primetime Live'' broadcast was folded into it, has been
broadcasting in prime time since hosting ``CBS Morning News'' from
1981 to 1984. Sawyer said she'll ``cut back'' on travel assignments
with ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Westin said the changes include the naming of Shelley Ross as
new executive producer of the show, replacing Shelley Lewis, and of
Phyllis McGrady as ABC News executive in charge. McGrady was ``Good
Morning America'' executive producer from 1984 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, Westin said, had been prompted by the loss of the
show's ``core values'' in the last two years and of its loss of
``soul.'' He said the show needs to ``return to its warmth and its
sense of family values'' after wandering ``too far off.'' He said
he and network management accept responsibility for failure to
respond more quickly to the show's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Westin characterized the moves as the first step in a plan to
shore up the show's sagging status. Although Sawyer said she
expected to be doing the show for ``several months,'' Westin
declined to give a timetable and said he interprets Sawyer's
``several'' as ``more than three.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
