<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN05-COX     01-04 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zell Miller says he was 'dear friend' who gave Clinton poem
 &HT;    (Repeating in political category. Previously moved under
commentary.)
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Zell Miller's poll ratings are at an
all-time high as he leaves office. He could have gone to the U.S.
Senate. But he chose to go back to his North Georgia home instead.
</P>
<P>
   I spent some time this week, asking the governor why.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountains have always jerked me back _ like a dog on a
leash,'' said Miller, packing up his office and trying to explain
his fierce attachment to rural North Georgia: ``There's a
groundedness there _ a certain eternity. It's a place where the
soul never dies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A few times,'' he added with a chuckle,'' I thought the voters
would send me home before I was ready to go. I never needed much
incentive to run again, you know. No outpouring _ just a couple of
nods.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is pretty good at poking fun at himself, but throughout
his 38-year political life, poking fun at his native North Georgia
was off limits. He could go into a rage over negative implications
about the hillbillies in ``them thar hills.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the governor is thin-skinned about criticism of any
kind. No question he appreciates his hard-ball political adviser
James Carville, but he's often more philosopher than politician.
That shows in the 235-page syllabus for the ``Life and Leadership''
course Miller will teach at Young Harris College in his home town
and other places.
</P>
<P>
   The selected readings are full of interesting juxtapositions:
Robert E. Lee's Farewell to his soldiers and Booker T. Wahington's
``Up from Slavery''; Genesis on creation and Rachel Carson on
ecology; the classical philosophy of Plato and Aristotle and
children's classics like ``The Little Steam Engine (that could).''
</P>
<P>
   The romantic poets are his favorites _ John Keats, Percy Bysshe
Shelley. As I skimmed through his selections, I stumbled on four
lines of recent notoriety _ the lines President Clinton read in his
last-ditch effort to fend off impeachment: ``The Moving Finger
writes and having writ/ Moves on; nor all your Piety nor Wit/ Shall
lure it back to cancel half a Line. Nor all your Tears wash out a
Word of it.'' (from ``The Rubayyat'' by Omar Khayam)
</P>
<P>
   The poetry, said the president in his televised speech, was
given to him by a dear friend. ``Yes, I am that friend,'' Miller
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Miller and Clinton seem incongruous friends _
Miller, the homespun teacher, and Clinton, the slick lawyer. But
they became friends when they were both governors of Southern
states, both focused on public education.
</P>
<P>
   Both have greater than 70 percent job approval ratings today.
But Clinton clings desperately to his polls, while Miller ignores
his. Clinton's legacy is uncertain; Miller's is sure. He is the
governor who brought the HOPE scholarships to Georgia, enabling
every youngster who earns a ``B'' high school average to go to
college. He is the governor who initiated the first universal
pre-kindergarten program, distributing free classical music tapes
to every new mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``To govern is to choose,'' Miller says, ``not just battles, but
who you want to help.'' He wanted to help children. He focused on
education to the exclusion of issues critics say he shouldn't have
neglected _ mass transit, and air and water pollution, for example.
He dropped his campaign to remove the confederate battle emblem
from the state flag when political support vanished. He believes
politicans make their greatest mistakes getting caught up in social
issues ``that don't matter at the kitchen table'' _ issues like the
flag, school prayer, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find average Americans on the left or on the
right,'' said Miller. ``You'll find them at K-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 66-year-old Miller returns to his roots, he confirms the
teachings of his greatest mentor, his mother. In his last State of
the State address, he told of sitting on the Miller front porch as
a child, watching car headlights disappear across Brasstown
Mountain. His mother would laugh and say, ``You know what's so
great about this place? You can get anywhere in the world from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Miller named the places, from foreign capitols to
the oval office, that his political journey has taken him. He knows
well it could have taken him to Washington. But, he said,
``Everywhere I've ever been was on my way back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:mezzard(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
