</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My friend Steve Efron was waiting in line at a bar cart by the
tracks at Grand Central Terminal on his way to Hastings-on-Hudson.
A woman rushed up, cut into the line and ordered a gin and tonic.
She then turned and announced to the waiting line, ``I'm sorry but
I have to catch a train.'' Steve didn't miss a beat. ``And I just
come here to drink,'' he said, sotto voce.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost a glove, I rushed off to Bloomingdale's to buy
another pair. I located what I wanted, decided to buy several pairs
and went to a cashier's station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm buying so many because I always seem to be losing my
gloves,'' I said. ``Just like `The Three Little Kittens.''' I got a
blank stare. I thought perhaps I hadn't made myself clear, so I
added, ``You know, like the three little kittens who lost their
mittens.'' Another blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   By now I was beginning to feel a little unnerved. Desperate to
make a connection, I looked around and when I saw no one in the
vicinity, I began singing, ``Three little kittens they lost their
mittens and they began to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the blank stare was replaced with a look of alarm and I
decided a retreat was in order. So I added that I guess they are
teaching different nursery rhymes to the newer generation. But
internally, I was doing my own crying. I understand that the Bible
and Shakespeare no longer form a common ground for universal
discourse _ but can we now no longer even count on a shared
universe of nursery rhymes?
</P>
<P>
   Lori Moskowitz Lepler knew it was time to either re-evaluate her
work situation or learn to cook. The other morning, about 8 a.m.,
her intercom buzzer rang and her 2-year-old son, Jake, immediately
said, ``Mommy, it's dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday morning, my three dogs and I go for an early walk
in Central Park. As I wend my way, I often pass the same man
sitting on the same isolated bench in a remote area, wearing big
earphones over his baseball cap, reading a newspaper, his dog
tucked under his feet. He always restrains his dog, making sure he
doesn't move out from under the bench.
</P>
<P>
   One day as I was getting ready to leave the park, I leashed all
my dogs because we were about to cross the park drive. At that
moment, the man and his dog walked by.
</P>
<P>
   Sloane, my large muscular Rhodesian Ridgeback, by nature very
friendly, broke loose and charged joyfully up to the man's dog to
say hello. As she barked energetically at him to come and play, the
owner started yelling at me, ``Get your dog on a leash, lady,'' as
if that would have made a difference. I responded, ``She's really
very friendly; she just wants to play.'' He responded, ``Well,
how's he supposed to know? He's a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a Saturday afternoon when Lita Karp entered the Grand
Street subway station. As she approached the turnstile, she heard a
male voice singing in Chinese. An audience had gathered to listen,
most of them contributing something.
</P>
<P>
   As she went downstairs to await the train, the song ended and a
new one began. It seemed familiar and Ms. Karp couldn't understand
why she was humming along. Soon the light dawned. The song was a
Chinese translation of ``Old Folks at Home.'' Now she's left with
several unanswered questions _ why and when was it translated, and
did the singer know anything about the Swanee River?
</P>
<P>
   Clara Greenspan was watching a program on innovative school
programming in Texas on Channel 13 one Sunday evening in late
November. As one educator was interviewed, he was identified on the
screen as ``School Superintendant Munoz.'' Write ``Superintendent''
100 times.
</P>
<P>
   Along the same lines, Ian Murphy reports that the writers of the
news zipper at Avenue of the Americas and 48th Street might learn
something from the maxim of the pot and the kettle.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that in early December the ribbon relayed a story
razzing Texas for having to destroy several thousand books because
of poor spelling and grammar. The next story involved Iraq's
importing Viagra even though ``its'' made in the United States, and
the item after that was about the ``vigrous defense'' made by
President Clinton's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Johnson was entertaining friends at a Sunday buffet brunch
at a restaurant that had an impressive display of fish. Along with
the salmon, lobster, oysters and other delicacies was a fish none
of them recognized. It turned out to be sable, but before they
found that out, they queried a waiter about its identity. ``It's a
Jewish fish,'' he said. ``Is it circumcised?'' Mrs. Johnson asked
in jest. ``No, it's smoked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   My friend David Laibman recently called a new French restaurant
in Brooklyn to find out what credit cards they took and what their
reservation policy was. When he also asked if they had a prix fixe
menu, the young woman said, ``No, we change it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Carroll was on a business trip to Dayton, Ohio, recently
with Mark, a business associate. Mark lives in Manhattan but was
born and raised in New Zealand and has a distinct accent. As they
were touring their client's office building, their escort asked
where they lived. Mark spoke first and said ``New York City.'' She
turned to him, somewhat embarrassed, and said, ``I'm sorry, I
should have known from your accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dora Kooby was standing in line waiting to pay for her
merchandise when she heard a woman in another line ask for the 25
percent discount offered on shoes. The cashier replied, ``Ma'am,
these are slippers, not shoes.'' The woman protested, ``Well, I
wear these outside.'' Are slippers shoes when worn outside? Did she
get her discount? We'll never know. The unresolved exchange was
still going on when our correspondent left.
</P>
<P>
