<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA MAY NOT BE THE ROOT OF ALL EVIL AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Very good news arrived just in time to give us
yet another reason to celebrate the coming of the new year along
with a boundless stock market. Violent crime committed by young
people, along with other malefactions, recorded a reduction for the
seventh year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   There is less violent crime among the young today than there has
been for the past 25 years, according to a Justice Department
report.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, must mean that television and the movies have
abandoned their accustomed reliance on violence to make their
products attractive especially to the young. So, too, must have
newspapers done, because experts had assured us that the exposure
of the kids to violence in the media inured them to it and
encouraged them to act out violently.
</P>
<P>
   But one looks and looks at all the media and sees business being
done in the time-honored fashion. Violence is still being peddled,
despite an occasional lapse by some of the media into civic
high-mindedness. Notwithstanding the persistence of the movies and
television to continue to purvey most unwholesome products,
violence among the young _ and not only among them _ dropped to
lows not seen for a quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that the host of experts who sought to treat
deep-seated social pathologies by undermining the First Amendment
to impose restraints on the media likely have been seriously
mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   While the violence portrayed ubiquitously on the large and the
small screen has many faults, being the proximate cause of aberrant
behavior by impressionable youngsters does not appear to be among
them.
</P>
<P>
   So there is good reason to deal with the very real pathologies
in more appropriate ways that are actually effective although they
are more complex than ranting at the media.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department report, along with a host of other
experts, accounted for the sudden rise of juvenile violence in the
mid-1980s and its steady decline since 1991, chiefly citing a drop
in the use of crack cocaine. Crack was sold in small quantities for
relatively little money. It produced an intense high for a short
time, and was fearsomely addictive. Kids became users and runners.
To get money to pay for their habits, they also became robbers. To
protect their crack enterprises, they resorted to guns and used
them freely against rival gangs. The result was the burgeoning
violent crime rate among kids and young people.
</P>
<P>
   With the subsiding of the crack culture, the ancillary robberies
and killings diminished. With the enforcement of stricter gun laws,
the availability of firearms was reduced. With the aging of the
boomers out of their crime-committing years, the number of
potential law breakers shrank. With the steadily improving economy,
more jobs were available to those kids who turned to the drug trade
for lack of alternatives to making a buck.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the intertwined reasons a variety of experts
propounded to explain the welcome crime reduction, in addition to
other efforts more specific to particular communities or
situations. Not one of them, at least so far, said anything about
violence in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Although the media may not be guilty as charged, they are
nevertheless not blameless. If the argument that they spawn
violence among their viewers is not factually supported, their
programming and presentations still are an offense to the
aesthetics of a good life.
</P>
<P>
   Their relentless pursuit of audiences with ever more outrageous
fare numbs minds and dulls sensibilities. Without question, parents
need to exercise their responsibilities and prevent their children
from being overexposed to this tripe. But parental dereliction is
implied by studies that show kids continuing to consume an enormous
amount of television.
</P>
<P>
   Restraining kids from overdosing on the tube may not keep them
from becoming mass killers. On the other hand, it might direct them
to alternatives, such as reading a book or drawing a picture,
building a model ship or collecting bottle caps, that will enrich
their lives, stimulate their interests in ways that apathetically
sitting in front of a TV for endless hours never could hope to.
</P>
<P>
   There are bad books and bad newspapers, just as there are bad
films and television. A major point of life is to develop the
personal discretion to be able to decide which is what.
</P>
<P>
   Parents neglect their duty if they don't help their kids learn
by making choices for them when they are too inexperienced to make
them for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment and news media sensationalize and titillate
for one reason only. They know from gauging behavior of their
audiences that is what constitutes popularity. If viewers'
attention were to be miraculously captured by serializing great
novels, then these communications moguls would just as happily
replace the violence with the likes of Trollope and Thackeray.
</P>
<P>
   They have no vested interest in violence or English masters.
They do have a stake in finding what makes them the most money.
</P>
<P>
   This harsh fact of life gives power to ordinary people, if they
only would chose to exercise it. They could put their power into
play by simply refusing to watch objectionable and exploitative
presentations at home or at the multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been the same, since the ascendancy of mass
culture, that those choices have tended more to the worse than the
better. For which, once again, folks, we can look most profitably
to ourselves for the remedy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
