<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7557 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL-$ADV10-     01-04 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRAZIL-$ADV10-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING BUT STARS AND BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)  
(lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To reach Jericoacoara, you take a highway back through time,
rippling further back with each mile of Brazilian coast. From
Fortaleza, with its sleek beachfront hotels, the road grows
desolate, drought painting the savanna of the northeast dull green
and beige.
</P>
<P>
   Cars give way to horses and mules, buildings shrink to huts, and
spindly goats and cows forage over the brush. As the road goes from
asphalt to dirt to just paths in the sand, you would not be
surprised to find wagon wheels and animal skulls, the detritus of
ancient, failed journeys, strewn by the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Jericoacoara, you take a bus, an impossible, eight-hour
journey from Fortaleza, stopping at every little hiccup of a town
along the highway, or you take a four-hour ride in a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Try to sleep, because it is the middle of the night. You dream
of sand dunes 100 feet tall, massive and immutable as mountains.
You come near, and realize they are always changing shape and
moving with the winds from Africa, and you wonder if this is where
God comes to finger-paint.
</P>
<P>
   To reach Jericoacoara, you close your eyes and say it:
jeh-ree-kwah-KWAH-rah. First it sounds like a fruit, one that grows
in clusters and spills over your mouth. Say it again. It is a bird
squawking, like the roosters whose call bounces over the dunes to
rouse you at dawn. And again: It is a word within a word, like a
seashell held to your ear, calling you to a place that is distant
and familiar, inside you, mysterious and intimate, at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Though people who live here decry the onslaught of tourism, of
buggies roaring over the dunes and houses dotting the shore,
Jericoacoara remains one of the planet's hidden beach treasures. In
Jericoacoara, some 180 miles northwest of Fortaleza on the northern
coast, the trappings of modern life _ cars, buildings, phones and
fax machines _ remain remote.
</P>
<P>
   The town, a smattering of about a dozen streets, is dotted with
single-story shacks, most serving as stores, restaurants or inns.
The streets have grown outward from the Atlantic, and the town is
surrounded by green hills and vast sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Regular electricity arrived only last spring; until then, the
town of 1,400 used generators, and handwritten signs in hotel rooms
still warn of the dreaded hair dryer, which could short-circuit the
whole town for the sake of a do. Only two of the dozen or so places
to stay take credit cards, and public phones shut down at 10 each
night. The streets are all sand: Wherever you are in Jericoacoara,
you never really leave the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Roger, my fiance, and I arrived in Jericoacoara in early July.
It was the feast day of St. Peter, patron saint of fishermen. It
was also the day Brazil's soccer team faced the Netherlands in the
World Cup quarterfinals. Along the road, Catholics were building
towers of wood, some several stories high, to burn fires that night
to honor the saint. Theoretically, there would be fireworks, too _
if any were left after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the saint's humility would be tried, for his was not
the main event that day. All the stores and restaurants shut down
in midafternoon. Brazil was going for its fifth World Cup trophy,
so guests and workers of the Hotel Jericoacoara Praia, where we
were staying, crammed on benches and chairs to watch the game on
the common television.
</P>
<P>
   Picture the comparable scene on the other side of the
hemisphere, where Americans would gather to watch, say, the Super
Bowl. The beer and soda would flow, and the munchies would come in
buckets during frequent commercial breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But here, nobody ate or drank, and there were no commercials.
The concentration was so intense that asking for anything would
have been sacrilege. The only interruptions came when Brazil
scored, raising the trademark ``GOOOOL'' from sportscasters, and
raucous cheers. A busboy crouched in the courtyard, lighting
rockets and cherry bombs.
</P>
<P>
   When stores reopened after Brazil's victory, we bought soap and
shampoo from the drugstore. It was almost night, and we heard,
around the corner, the twang of a berimbau accompanying a chant
that seemed to float off the waves. On an asphalt court behind a
store, teen-agers were facing off in capoeira, a kind of martial
art almost balletic in its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Capoeira arose at the end of the 17th century among slaves, as a
preparation for insurrection or escape, masked as dance to throw
off any whites who happened upon it. While the music plays, the
movement is constant, a collage of pieces from a jigsaw puzzle, or
riddles with open answers. The two rivals cartwheel before each
other or jut in and around each others' bodies, together forming a
whole whose contours change with the next beat.
</P>
<P>
   In capoeira, punches and kicks are thrown but never land, like
the rebellion that never materialized. Freedom came only in 1888 by
royal decree, a year before the Portuguese crown finally left
Brazil and only after slavery ended everywhere else in the
Americas. Through the shifting shapes of the dancers, the view was
clear to dusk's sky, streaked orange and pink over the ocean,
framed by the palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   Starved for the sound of waves, watching for the moon, we found
a place to eat dinner by the shore. The cook sat behind the counter
watching a telenovella, and _ this being the low season _ it seemed
most items on the menu were not to be had. No bread, either. No
juice. No diet soda. It was becoming clear that this is a place
tourists bend into, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she cooked us some fish, rice and beans, and cut up a
salad of cabbage. The waiter found a bottle of beer and one of
water. Since we were the only customers, he stopped by every 30
seconds or so to make sure everything was all right. There was no
coffee and no dessert. We found an ice cream store, but it had
already closed.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, though, the new moon was rising in a sky so clear and
bright that even the moon's hidden side could be made out. The
patch of earth we occupied was dark, far from cities and street
lights, so much so that we felt tiny and mesmerized by the
spectacle overhead. In the sky, billions of stars like small
mirrors flashed glimmers of light across the vast nocturnal
playground. This sky was far richer, more brilliant, than any we
had ever imagined or witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the plenty, it was difficult to recognize the familiar
constellations like Orion's Belt or the Southern Cross. Venus was
lost in an ocean of her sisters. Only the Milky Way was easily
discernible, incredibly so, appearing like a river of stars
spraying white mist.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, briefly dead, come back to talk of rising toward a
white light. I wondered if all these stars were holes in the sky,
through which that brightness becomes visible, flashing us signals
in a heavenly code not yet deciphered.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Sunday, we needed as a day to let the place
sink in before plunging into serious sightseeing. We walked along
the beach, watching the children scavenging for crabs. We sunbathed
and swam in the clear, cool Atlantic. Parasailers glided in smooth
arcs from the shore, powered by winds strong as sure, steady arms.
</P>
<P>
   Past the fishermen's boats waiting for the evening tide, we
trekked to a shoreside dune. From a distance, the dune had seemed
utterly static. A closer look showed the sand cascading down
shelves formed along the dune's face, the desert's answer to a
waterfall. When we returned the next day, the dune seemed utterly
altered, as if somebody had dragged a comb in lazy waves over its
surface.
</P>
<P>
   That night, we had more success with dinner, stopping at a
charming little restaurant, Sabor e Arte (Flavor and Art), that had
opened a couple of months before, run by four young women who had
fled the industrial megalopolis of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs was the only restaurant in town with some notion of
decor, with painted starfish over the bar, tablecloths and a
central pillar open for customers' graffiti. Candlelight flickered
at the tables, while incense rose in curls around the room.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen was a small, open area behind the bar, and as they
grilled our fish, fetched and arranged, the women danced to Phil
Collins. Truth be told, the food was slow in coming but good, and _
a wonderful bonus _ we found somebody there with a dune buggy to
take us sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, at low tide, we headed for Tatajuba,
about 20 miles west of Jericoacoara. The point of Tatajuba is as
much the ride there as the lake that goes by that name. There is no
road per se; we drove along the shore, mile after mile. A makeshift
ferry, really a raft, takes the car across a small inlet, nudged
along by two boatmen digging sticks into the sand.
</P>
<P>
   We drove past a forest of desiccated trees, the roots like
antlers, whitened and dry, vaulting into the sand. Then there is
just ocean, sunlight and dunes tall as multistory buildings, blown
by the wind into dramatic shapes. Some look like bread loaves, and
others swirl into giant beehives. A few end in steep, curving walls
that stretch like bleached, sleek versions of the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The road passes through the old Tatajuba, abandoned when the
dunes advanced and swallowed the houses. Here and there, the corner
of a roof is still visible, peeking out through the sand. The new
fishing village of Tatajuba is a smattering of houses, built around
the town's only television. It sits atop a 10-foot pedestal, in a
weatherbeaten wood cabinet. Each night, the double doors to the
cabinet are opened, and everybody turns out to watch the
telenovellas.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the benches in the square face away from the
television, so that the mayor's name, painted on the inside back of
the bench, can be seen by passers-by. That leaves most of the
residents sitting on the curb, their feet in the sand, to watch
television. There isn't any argument over which station to watch.
Only one, the pervasive Globo network, reaches here.
</P>
<P>
   Coming around the dune to Lake Tatajuba, we stumbled upon a
scene out of Fellini. A toothless old lady sat at a bridge table
along the shore, eager to ply us with home-made candy bars laden
with brown sugar. On an identical white plastic chair next to her
sat a young man in sunglasses and boxer shorts, lost in a book on
etiquette. Specifically lost on the chapter explaining when and how
to kiss a lady's hand.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had a society news spot on a radio station in the
interior, an oddly incongruous way to make a living, because the
Northeast is the poorest part of Brazil. He was headed for
Jericoacoara and asked if we could give him a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Also plying his living at the shore was a boy who persuaded us
to take a sail around the lake on a converted fishing boat for $1.
The candy peddler advanced, her aluminum pot swinging over her arm
like a handbag. Wouldn't we be wanting another sweet when we got
back, she urged; a couple from Sao Paulo had bought eight of them.
Take it or leave it; she'd be going home.
</P>
<P>
   There were no houses around, and I couldn't imagine where home
would be. I half-believed that the crone and the gossipmeister had
somehow just appeared, conjured from the depths of this eerie,
portable desert. The sail lasted but 10 minutes or so, with us
ducking each time the boy swung the sail around to catch a hint of
a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, we were heading back for Jericoacoara, Mr.
Manners in the front seat, deep into the proper silver setting for
formal dinners. We dropped him at the Hippopotamus hotel, where the
management had promised him a couple of free days.
</P>
<P>
   In the late afternoon, we headed out to Thunder Rock, about a
five-minute drive and a scamper down a steep, sandy hill to the
ocean. There we watched the brilliant orange and yellow of the sun
drop down the horizon through an arch in the tall rock. On July 15
each year, residents gather here to watch the sun set perfectly in
the middle of the rock.
</P>
<P>
   We wouldn't be here on the 15th, but as we watched the stars
emerge for another brilliant night, we understood the secret that
made Jericoacoara so hypnotic. Despite the occasional television,
parasail or dune buggy, Jericoacoara remains a place where
technology has not yet dominated nature's rhythms and gifts. There
was television, but it did not carry the main show. There was
electricity, but not enough to erase the starlight.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Remember that you'll need a visa for Brazil. VASP Brazilian
Airlines, (800) 732-8277, and Varig Brazilian Airlines, (800)
673-4561, fly to Fortaleza from Miami. VASP goes on Sunday, Varig
on Tuesday and Thursday; round-trip tickets start at $780.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're on a very tight budget, hire a private car to get
to Jeri, as it is called locally. You can do this through the
tourism desk at the airport or your hotel in Fortaleza. It will run
about $150 each way instead of $12 for a bus, but will save eight
hours and, because of the bus schedules, allow two decent nights'
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest influx of visitors comes from the December holidays
to Carnival. Other peak times are Holy Week and in July.
</P>
<P>
   There are few phones in Jericoacoara. For many places, you will
have to call the town's phone station, (55-88) 621-1144, and ask a
runner to relay your message or to get someone to come to the
phone. The Web site www.jericoacoara.com has some basic information
on the town.
</P>
<P>
   Things to Do
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy the night sky at Jericoacoara, pack an astronomy guide
for the Southern Hemisphere. A small telescope would not be wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Dune-buggy excursions can be arranged at the Casa do Turismo
hotel. Five-hour trips cost $8 to $12.50.
</P>
<P>
   Boat rides can be arranged with local fishermen for a dollar or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Even the best hotels offer rudimentary lodging, and since we
encountered credit-card fraud after our visit, it might wise to pay
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   We reserved a room at the Hippopotamus, Rua do Forro,
Jericoacoara, Brazil 62598-000, but were offered rooms with a
flooded bathroom and wood shavings covered with ants. And it didn't
take credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, the Jericoacoara Praia, 115 Rua fo Forro, accepted
Visa and charged half as much as the Hippo. It has 15 rooms, and
while the flagstones on the walls and floors seemed slapped down,
and a canvas drop ceiling looked as if it had never been shaken out
or vacuumed, the management was eager to please. Doubles cost $25
to $37.50. Reservations: (55-88) 603-1602.
</P>
<P>
   Next trip, I'd try the Pousada Papagaio, which had just opened
and featured 10 lovely, simple rooms with open-air showers and a
beautiful garden of regional trees. Doubles cost $17 or $25
depending on season. No credit cards and no telephone.
</P>
<P>
   A second choice would be the Casa do Turismo, on Rua das Unas,
the largest hotel in town. This oceanfront inn has 20 rooms, rents
water-sports equipment and takes American Express, Visa and
Mastercard. Doubles: $29 to $37.50; (55-88) 621-0211.
</P>
<P>
   Pousada do Paulo, Corrego do Urub, Gijoca de Jericoacoara
(Ceara) 62598-000, is at nearby Paradise Lake. It has five rustic
private bungalows, each sleeping four, with private bath, and with
views of the lake. The restaurant is open 24 hours, serving
Brazilian and Italian dishes. Off-peak rates run $50 a night, cash
only; (55-88) 669-1181;
www.geocities.com/thetropics/1136/Paolo.html.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   There are several restaurants that don't bother with fly traps,
let alone decor or matching plates, but have wonderful food. One is
Sabor da Terra, on Rua do Forro, where we had grilled fish, served
with rice, beans and french fries for about $9. No phone.
</P>
<P>
   A close second was Sabor e Arte, where you'll have a long, if
pleasant, wait. Meals cost $7.50 to $15, there's no phone and so no
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Shop
</P>
<P>
   The state of Ceara is the place to buy anything embroidered or
crocheted. In the bar at the Jericoacoara Praia, you'll find piles
of crocheted beach covers, tablecloths and runners. At the
beachfront stalls in Fortaleza, you can find hammocks for under
$20, embroidered tablecloths for $30 and hand-embroidered linen
place-mat and napkin settings for six at about $10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
