<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIZABETH DOLE LEAVES RED CROSS; PRESIDENTIAL BID NEXT?
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole stepped down Monday as head of the
American Red Cross to decide whether to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, speaking to hundreds of Red Cross employees at the
organization's national headquarters, hinted broadly that she plans
to run for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this important time in our national life, I believe there
may be another way for me to serve our country,'' Dole said from a
flag-bedecked, satellite-wired stage in the organization's ornate
Board of Governors Hall. ``The Red Cross has been a glorious
mission field, but I believe there may be other duties yet to
fulfill.''
</P>
<P>
   After her remarks, as she wound through the crowd past a bank of
television cameras, Dole responded to questions of whether she
would make a White House bid. ``I'm going to give it serious
consideration, along with other options,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's husband, Bob, a former Senate majority leader who lost to
Bill Clinton in the 1996 presidential election, was not present for
the announcement. He has long urged his wife to run for their
party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Elizabeth Dole is one of the most popular
figures in GOP politics and has several important assets at this
stage in the campaign. Among the most important are her famous name
and the fund-raising network that kept her husband in public office
for nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a long record of service with the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina native is a Harvard-trained lawyer who has
served under six presidents beginning with Lyndon Johnson. Her
quarter-century government career includes four years as
transportation secretary in Ronald Reagan's cabinet and three years
as labor secretary under President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole became president of the American Red Cross in 1991, three
years after her husband's loss to Bush in the 1988 GOP presidential
primaries. She took a brief leave of absence from the organization
in 1996 to help her husband campaign against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During her eight years at the Red Cross, the organization
modernized its blood operation and disaster relief services and
redesigned its fund-raising practices. The organization's board
chairman, Norman Augustine, called Dole ``a transformational
figure'' in the Red Cross and, in the event of a disaster, an
``on-site manager'' of relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often said that the weather service tracks Elizabeth,''
he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers believe that Dole may actually be
positioning herself for the 2000 vice presidential nomination, the
office her husband sought in 1976 under Gerald Ford. A woman on the
ticket might help the GOP with women voters, although Geraldine
Ferraro's candidacy in 1984 did not appear to help the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And a pairing with the current GOP front-runner, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, could be an unhappy reminder for Republicans hungry
to regain the White House. The governor is the son of former
President George Bush, who lost to Clinton in 1992,
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dole name does not exactly connote a bridge to the 21st
century,'' said Jack Pitney, a former Republican National Committee
official who now teaches political science at Claremont McKenna
College in California. ``That would be especially true if she
accepted the vice presidential nomination under Governor Bush. A
Bush-Dole ticket would sound like a remake of the GOP's last two
electoral disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
