<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN05-COX     01-04 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Y2K is OK by me
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ It's the first of the New Year, a time
for new beginnings. No time like the present to start preparing for
the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   You can hardly open up the newspaper without seeing a headline
warning of the impending doom of ``Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're like I am, and look no further than the headlines,
you've probably been wondering why all the commotion about a new,
improved, double-strength lubricating jelly.
</P>
<P>
   But read on. ``Y2K'' is abbreviation for the year 2000 and the
likelihood of impending doom when the century turns over and the
computers roll over and play dead.
</P>
<P>
   Apocalypse, if not now, soon.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of our own destruction of our database were sown in the
beginning of the computer age. Youngsters may believe that in the
beginning there was Word Perfect. But this was way before then, in
the 1950s thereabouts, when computers were vast in size and vastly
limited in capacity.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that instead of, say, ``1957,'' computers were
programmed simply to recognize ``57,'' thus saving a couple of
digits. In the process, we may have lost life as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly all utilities and other such niceties of civilization
will fail if computers go kaput come the year 2000, unable to cope
when the century changes. Heaven knows I know how they'll feel.
I've been having trouble coping with change since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even as the doomsday clock ticks down, there are
those among us who believe the Y2K is much ado over next to
nothing, which in turn greatly offends that segment that believes
Y2K-liness is next to godliness.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is much involved. A Baptist church in my little
hometown, for example, is urging members to slowly begin
withdrawing their money from financial institutions during the
coming year, the idea being when the computers fail, the banks will
fail right along with them.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be surival of the best outfitted. True believers of the
worst-case scenario are hard at work stocking up and socking away
foodstuffs, kerosene and water supplies. Some are even digging
their own water wells and connecting their homes to private
generators.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fallout shelter crisis all over again, when some
families in the 1950s installed backyard concrete bunkers in
preparation for nuclear holocaust, also much preached from pulpits
to scare the hell out of us.
</P>
<P>
   What with the untimely implosion of the Soviet Union and the
godless communism therein, Y2K may be helping to fill the void left
for subject matter in sermons of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Y2K lacks the immediacy of A-bomb annihilation.
``Repent now, for tomorrow you may die'' certainly has it over
``Repent now, for 12 months from now your computer may die.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to make light of a subject taken seriously by many among us.
</P>
<P>
   I know an editor who made that mistake. Referred in print to it
as ``Y2Kookiness,'' he did.
</P>
<P>
   An outraged reader called to warn him that he'd be laughing out
of the other side of his face, as it were, come the 2000 revolution
and he finds himself sitting in his own sewage.
</P>
<P>
   I think he missed a good bet. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're right and I'm wrong, indeed, on New Year's Day 2000
I will sit in my own sewage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I'm right and you're wrong, you have to sit in my own
sewage.''
</P>
<P>
   Any takers?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
