<SLUG> BC-SMALL-TOWNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TEXAS TOWN OFFERING INCENTIVES TO NEW RESIDENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Faced with the enviable problem of more jobs
than people, the Panhandle town of Dalhart is offering $1,000 and
help with home loans to those willing to move and work there.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called ``The New Millennium Opportunity,'' began in
the summer when Dalhart employers found that the town's 6,500
population simply could not fill the jobs in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 employers got together with the Dalhart Economic
Development Corp. and put up the money as an incentive to move
here,'' said Warren Slaughter, editor of the Dalhart Texan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 25 skilled positions and about 50 non-skilled
that need to be filled, and we just thought this might be the best
way to do it,'' said Slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those jobs are at a state prison, on a hog farm or on a
potato plantation, the town's largest employers. A number of them,
however, are for accountants, mid-level executives and medical
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The giveaway is not unlike the scheme another Panhandle town
tried two years ago. Lefors, a tiny community of fewer than 600,
offered 14 free residential lots to those who promised to settle
there within six months. Winners were drawn by lottery.
</P>
<P>
   That proved only partially successful. City Secretary Judy
Williams said eight of the lots were eventually taken by people who
now occupy them.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement that owners move to Lefors was removed last
year. Four other lots have since been taken over by out-of-town
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we got a few families here and a number of children
in the school,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalhart plan calls for potential workers to be willing to
move there and work for a minimum of 12 months for one of the
participating employers. As an added incentive to the $1,000 cash,
the development corporation will help the worker obtain up to
$10,000 in home financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't advertise,'' said Slaughter. ``I ran a story on it
and The Associated Press picked it up. We got some calls and about
a half-dozen people moved here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, (last) week, a TV network did a story on it. Since then,
we've gotten about 600 calls in the past couple of days. They're
calling from all over, New York, New Jersey, Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter points out that the attractions to Dalhart may be
limited, but so are the city's drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the cultural experience in Dalhart isn't going to be
anything like a real city,'' he said. ``I mean, we're close to the
mountains in New Mexico and we've got a bowling alley, a community
theater and a movie theater, but there's not a lot of other
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand we have a low tax rate, prices are
reasonable and our crime is below just about everybody's. We've had
five armed robberies in 96 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalhart program is not without its detractors. Slaughter
said a few people felt the offer was degrading to the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they felt that paying people to move here would make
us a laughingstock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, if it works, so what?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
