<SLUG> BC-HARD-BALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE GOVERNMENT: FEAR HAS REPLACED TRUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Assuming Bill Clinton finishes out his term, the
next presidential election promises to be the best _ by that I mean
closest _ since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are contained in a new poll conducted by the Kaiser
Foundation and Harvard University for the Washington Post. It shows
a country caught in an electoral crossfire, between the assault of
religious and cultural conservatives from the right and the
continued fear of tax-and-spend liberals from the left.
</P>
<P>
   How voters react to this dangerous predicament will decide the
presidential election in 2000 and the direction of American
politics in the early 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Clinton supporters in the survey is that more
voters care about ``a candidate's stands on the issues'' _ 37
percent _ than on his or her ``personal morals and ethics'' _ 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also benefit from a growing public tolerance on
matters of personal morality in government officials. While only 24
percent said ``yes'' when asked if the president has ``high
personal moral and ethical standards,'' six out of 10 said
Clinton's behavior is no better or worse than others of his
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Clinton Democrats face trouble is from an equally
pronounced decrease in public respect for government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in 1968, that most explosive of anti-establishment years,
if they ``trust the government in Washington to do the right
thing,'' 61 percent checked ``just about always'' or ``most of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 33 percent checked those responses in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This is a devastating 30-year trend for the Democrats, a
political party that has placed its faith in positive public
solutions to national problems such as poverty, poor health care
and inadequate education.
</P>
<P>
   The antipathy toward Washington shows up in another question put
to voters in the new poll. Asked in 1965 what institution _ ``Big
Government,'' ``Big Labor'' or ``Big Business'' _ they fear poses
the largest threat down the road, 35 percent said ``Big
Government.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the same multiple-choice in 1998, ``Big Business'' scored
somewhat higher as a national pariah, ``Big Labor'' pathetically
lower. ``Big Government'' zoomed to 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What does this tell us about the 2000 presidential campaign?
First, that Democrats will do everything they can to peg
Republicans as the party of the ``religious right,'' a faction
driven to a frenzy by its ideological zeal, its social and sexual
intolerance. Meanwhile, they will seek to de-emphasize their old
reputation for ``Big Government'' solutions to national problems,
including health care.
</P>
<P>
   Second, that Republicans will do everything they can to peg
Democrats as the party of ``Big Government,'' the faction that
tried to create a giant health care bureaucracy. Meanwhile, they
try to lose their label as the party of intolerance with a dramatic
overture to minorities, especially Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties, seeing the same polls, know that the one sure way
to lose the 2000 election is to appear to voters as ``Big
Brother,'' a specter feared as much in the bedroom as in the
pocketbook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
