<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGGIETALES-VIDEO-TEX     01-04 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGGIETALES-VIDEO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VEGGIETALES' FILLS A SPIRITUAL VOID FOR ONE LAPSED PARENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I relate this story with the full knowledge that you, the loyal
reader, will not judge me, lest you be you-know-whated: I take an
unorthodox approach to teaching my child about specific religious
sects. Like, I don't.
</P>
<P>
   I'm all about giving her the 4-1-1 on the things with which she
should be down, such as math and manners and Cartoon Network. But
I'd rather she learn about theology from me, and then decide how
best to apply that knowledge when she makes up her own mind and
decides for herself that she wants to become a Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Kidding. Still, I've found that imparting broad concepts of
religious beliefs to a 4-year-old is a challenge. Before I know it,
the munchkin is confused with talk about sacraments and baptisms
and that many-armed elephant Apu is always breaking out on ``The
Simpsons.'' Unfortunately, you can't count on knowledge of this
sort being received at birth, like a child's understanding of
``happiness'' or ``chocolate.'' I tried that. When she was very
young, I asked my daughter if she knew who ``God'' was. She said,
``Uh ... Mama?''
</P>
<P>
   Close, but no deity. What have proved helpful are Big Idea
Productions' ``VeggieTales,'' the hit videos in which a tomato and
a cucumber discuss God's love for everyone, even Democrats.
Computer-animated vegetables (Bob the Tomato, voiced by Big Idea
president and founder Phil Vischer, Larry the Cucumber, and Junior
Asparagus and his family) hop about, tell Bible stories and sing
ditties. The titles (my daughter particularly liked ``Where's God
When I'm S-scared,'' $12.99) have sold more than 5.5 million copies
to date, and with good reason. They're entertaining for adults,
simple and repetitive enough for small children and they relay
heartfelt, honest Christian values.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes ``VeggieTales,'' at the very least, a good-for-you
alternative to Dexter and his pals at the Cartoon Network. .MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
