<HEADLINE>
CRITICS NAME `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' BEST PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its dominance of year-end critics awards, Steven
Spielberg's World War II drama ``Saving Private Ryan'' was named
Best Picture in the ninth annual Dallas-Forth Worth Film Critics
Association awards.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg was named Best Director, and ``Ryan'' star Tom Hanks
was runner-up for Best Actor. ``Ryan,'' considered the front-runner
for Best Picture at the Academy Awards, also topped the New York
Film Critics Circle and the Los Angeles Film Critics Association
awards, announced late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellan was named Best Actor for his delicately witty
performance as retired movie director James Whale in ``Gods and
Monsters''; ``Gods'' director Bill Condon placed third in the Best
Director race. Cate Blanchett, who gave a dominating, anchoring
performance as Queen Elizabeth I in ``Elizabeth,'' was named Best
Actress. Gwyneth Paltrow, who plays Shakespeare's love interest in
``Shakespeare in Love,'' was runner-up in the Best Actress
category.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting awards went to Billy Bob Thornton, for his role as a
simple Midwesterner who finds all sorts of demons surfacing when
he, his brother and his best friend find a huge cache of money in
``A Simple Plan''; and to Brenda Blethyn, who plays the man-chasing
harridan mother of the lead character in ``Little Voice.''
``Voice's'' Jane Horrocks placed third in the Best Actress
category.
</P>
<P>
   The Metroplex critics association features two unique
categories: Most Underrated Film, and the Russell Smith Award,
named in honor of the late Dallas Morning News critic. ``Love and
Death on Long Island,'' a minor spring release featuring John Hurt
as an aging Brit who falls for a teen heartthrob played by Jason
Priestley, tied with ``Babe: Pig in the City'' for Most Underrated
Film. Hal Hartley's independent epic ``Henry Fool'' won the Russell
Smith Award, which goes to the best offbeat picture.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Benigni's Holocaust comedy-drama ``Life Is Beautiful''
was named Best Foreign Language Film; U.S. director John Sayles'
fable ``Men With Guns,'' with dialogue largely in Mexican and
Indian dialects, was runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-Fort Worth Film Critics Association consists of 49
print and broadcast journalists covering motion pictures in the
Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   The association's Top 10 films: 1. ``Saving Private Ryan''; 2.
``Shakespeare in Love''; 3. ``Gods and Monsters''; 4. ``The Truman
Show''; 5. ``Life Is Beautiful''; 6. ``A Simple Plan''; 7. ``Henry
Fool''; 8. ``Beloved''; 9. ``Pleasantville''; 10. ``Waking Ned
Devine.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Contact him at robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
