<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: THE PHILHARMONIC ON TOUR; PAPER TREASURE TROVE;
ITALIAN MUSEUM TEMPORARILY CLOSED; RUSSIAN ENTERTAINERS AT RADIO
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Nev., Ill., Mass., Italy, Russia)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leopold Damrosch did it in 1882. Gustav Mahler did it
in 1910. Walter Damrosch did it in 1920, Arturo Toscanini in 1930
and Leonard Bernstein, Thomas Schippers and Seymour Lipkin in 1959.
And now it is Kurt Masur's turn.
</P>
<P>
   What they all did was take the New York Philharmonic on tour.
The 1882 journey, the orchestra's first tour, was to the Midwest.
The 1910 tour went to New England; those in 1920 and 1930 went to
Europe, the one in 1959 to the Soviet Union. Masur, the music
director, will be leading the Philharmonic on his first U.S. tour,
beginning Tuesday night in Palm Desert, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The tour then moves to Las Vegas, Costa Mesa, Calif., Los
Angeles, San Francisco, Chicago and Boston, with works by Richard
Strauss, Beethoven, Tchaikovsky and Shostakovich.
</P>
<P>
   Collections
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tapping a collection that has been growing since
1826, the National Academy Museum, on Fifth Avenue at 89th Street,
will hold an exhibition to give significant exposure to its trove
of works on paper. The show, ``Treasures Revealed: 19th- and
20th-Century Works on Paper,'' consisting of approximately 100
drawings, prints and watercolors by American artists, opens on
Saturday and runs through March 7. Among the artists represented
are James Carroll Beckwith, Jasper Johns, Thomas Moran and Elihu
Vedder.
</P>
<P>
   Until Further Notice
</P>
<P>
   The New Sacristy of the Church of San Lorenzo in Florence,
Italy, containing some of the most splendid works of sculpture by
Michelangelo, including the reclining statues of ``Dawn and Dusk''
and ``Night and Day,'' was closed after a large chunk of marble
hurtled to the floor from a column under the roof early on
Saturday. The Italian superintendent for cultural and historical
affairs, Antonio Paolucci, said the sacristy, left incomplete by
Michelangelo in 1534 and holding the tombs of Medici princes, would
remain closed until experts could determine what caused the stone,
weighing several pounds, to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Party On
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Didn't get enough of New Year's celebrations? Life
does offer some second chances. For those who observe the Julian
calendar, used for centuries in Russia before Peter the Great put
his country on the same Gregorian page used by almost everybody
else, the New Year falls on Jan. 13, a festive occasion in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be observed at 7:30 p.m. on Saturday at Radio City
Music Hall here, where Russian pop entertainers will appear in a
three-hour concert called ``Today's Stars: Timeless Songs.''
Featuring Igor Nikolaev, Leonid Agutin and Christina Arbakait, the
event, with scenery, costumes and traditional songs, takes the Old
Russian New Year as its theme.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
