<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the country will be dry and it will not be quite as cold
in the middle of the nation. Jet stream winds from the northwest
will dominate preventing any significant moisture moving northward
from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Frosts and freezes will greet the northern half of Florida with
readings in the northern counties below 20 degrees at daybreak.
High pressure centered over Georgia will circulate chilly air into
southern Florida, but clouds and onshore breezes along with
scattered light showers will keep readings closer to seasonal
levels.
</P>
<P>
   A ridge of high pressure extending northward along the Atlantic
Seaboard will sponsor bright but cold weather into eastern New
England. Over the Appalachians, clouds and flurries are expected in
northern sections with ample sun farther south. Shifting winds over
Lakes Erie and Ontario will cause the snow squalls to move to the
favored regions just north of Syracuse and south of Buffalo, where
up to 12 inches of snow will fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clockwise winds around high pressure over the Southeast will
draw milder air from the southern Plains toward the Mississippi
Valley. Clouds will increase from the eastern Plains to the Great
Lakes. The boundary between retreating Arctic air and a milder
Pacific air mass over the western Plains will be the focus of snow
showers and flurries.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over Nevada will produce dry and mainly mild
conditions in the West. A stream of moisture from the central
Pacific will reach the Northwest with thickening clouds. Fog will
persist in the Central Valley of California.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Perihelion &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, the earth reached perihelion, its closest
approach to the sun during the year. In the current era, perihelion
occurs in the northern hemisphere winter, contributing to a
reduction in annual temperature extremes. Aphelion, the point where
the sun and earth are farthest apart occurs in summer, helping to
moderate the heat of the warm season. However, the earth's orbital
parameters are slowly changing, so that in 11,000 years, perihelion
will occur in summer and aphelion in winter. This will accentuate
seasonal cycles, tending to make summers hotter and winters
colder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
