<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S FUTURE IS UNCERTAIN DESPITE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Before November's election, when George Pataki
seemed likely to sweep over New York City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone like that towering tidal wave in ``Deep Impact'' swept over
Manhattan, I was talking to one of the governor's aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he wins reelection,'' I predicted, ``you guys are going
to be unspeakably arrogant. You're already pushing the envelope
now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, sure,` he told me. ``The minute we win, you guys in the
press will start referring to this as a lame duck administration.
That'll keep us humble enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Pataki won respectably enough, with 54 per
cent of the vote in a 5-3 Democratic state. No tidal wave, though.
No thundering landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Pataki had no coattails. Attorney General Dennis Vacco
went down on election day _ tightly, but down nonetheless. Former
Sen. Al D'Amato lost by a surprisingly hefty margin to Chuck
Schumer. And the Democrats did remarkably well in legislative
elections, especially considering how vigorously the Republicans
had batted them around all year on issues.
</P>
<P>
   Also, this has from the very beginning been an administration
blissfully indifferent to anything the press reports. Its policy
has been to view the press openly as an enemy, to keep the press at
arm's length and to get out the administration's message through an
arsenal of glittering broadcast ads that presents the public not
with news but with spin.
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, they must be right. They won, didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   So, on Friday, George Pataki took office for his second term not
as a lame duck _ New York governors aren't restricted by term
limits _ but as a man longing for national office whose chances for
a place on the presidential ticket seem slimmer than they might
have been before Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, the Democratic Party's strategy for
winning presidential elections has been to cede the south and west
to the Republicans and to concentrate instead on pulling electoral
votes from one or two midwestern industrial states, the Northeast
and from California.
</P>
<P>
   That means that if Texas Gov. George W. Bush ends up as the
Republican Party's presidential nominee in a year and a half, and
he's the current favorite, he's more likely to select a Californian
for regional balance on his ticket than a pro-choice, ethnic,
northeastern moderate whose most recent electoral performance would
seem unlikely to bring the Empire State into the GOP fold next
year.
</P>
<P>
   And if Bush were to look to the Northeast for a running mate, he
would seem far likelier to cast his eye on Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pataki, fellow moderate Ridge has a war record that could
make him palatable to the party's far right out in the hinterlands.
And, unlike Pataki, Ridge probably could actually deliver his state
to the Republicans. Pennsylvania has only two-thirds of New York's
electoral votes, but two-thirds of something is better than
three-thirds of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   There also exists the possibility that whoever ends up as the
GOP presidential candidate in 2000 will go for gender rather than
geography and select Elizabeth Dole as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   So, it seems likely now that George Pataki, whatever his
national ambitions, probably won't be a player in the next
presidential race. Instead, he'll have to content himself with
wrestling with Democratic Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, with an
increasingly independent senate majority leader, Republican Joe
Bruno, and with ducking an Albany press corps that his
administration views with deep, dark suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless he decides to run for Daniel Patrick Moynihan's
U.S. Senate seat next year, which would disrupt the plans of a good
many other people and could provide the electorate with some
fetching entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, it's time for the business of governing in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the blessed silence between elections.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
