<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-$ADV     01-04 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CARIBBEAN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFIT MOTIVE CUTTING JET FLIGHTS IN CARIBBEAN SKIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 10.) 
 (ms) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When American Airlines announced a year ago that it would soon
end jet service between San Juan, P.R., and five Caribbean islands,
routes on which it said it was losing millions of dollars,
officials on those five islands decried the decision as a blow to
their tourist industries. Even American's plan to replace the jets
with much smaller, turboprop planes operated by American Eagle,
American's commuter carrier, did little to mollify them for what
they regarded as an insult.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The islands that lost jet service from San Juan on American are
Antigua, Barbados, Grenada, St. Croix and St. Lucia, while jet
service between San Juan and Aruba was cut to one flight a day from
two. But Antigua, Grenada and St. Lucia were so eager to maintain
jet service that each island agreed to pay American a subsidy, said
to be $1.5 million a year. In exchange, American provides daily
nonstop jet service between Miami and all three islands, and
American Eagle provides three daily turboprop nonstops between San
Juan and Antigua and San Juan and St. Lucia.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in San Juan was restructure,'' said Al Becker, an
American spokesman. ``We basically decided to operate fewer jets
from there to the Caribbean, but we're continuing to operate jets
between the mainland and San Juan.'' On Jan. 31, for example, a
month into the Caribbean's peak tourist season, American will add a
sixth daily nonstop between Kennedy International Airport and San
Juan and a fourth between Chicago and San Juan. Altogether,
American, the dominant carrier to and in the Caribbean, has about
45 daily jet flights to San Juan, all but a few of them from the
mainland.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other airlines are also adding Caribbean flights or have
recently done so, including Trans World Airlines, which is making a
push to pick up some of American's slack and carve out a presence
of its own. It recently began daily service between Kennedy and
Puerto Plata in the Dominican Republic and seasonal daily service
between Kennedy and St. Maarten. On Feb. 3 it will begin daily
service between Boston and San Juan, and on Feb. 11 daily service,
except Wednesday, between Kennedy Airport and Nassau. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines, which has four daily flights between
Newark and San Juan, recently added a daily nonstop between Houston
and San Juan and a weekly nonstop between Cleveland and San Juan.
Kiwi International, which serves San Juan and Aguadilla (in western
Puerto Rico) from Newark, Orlando and Miami, will begin
twice-weekly nonstop flights between Kennedy Airport and Aguadilla
on Jan. 12.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Caribbean airlines are adding flights to the
mainland. Last month Air Aruba, which already flew between Newark
and Aruba, added a four-times-a-week Baltimore-Philadelphia-Aruba
flight. Also last month, Aeromar Airlines began daily service
between Miami and Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic, while
Queen Air began daily nonstops between Kennedy and Santo Domingo.
Both carriers are headquartered in Santo Domingo and fly widebody
airplanes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although a Puerto Rican carrier, Sun Airways, began daily
service from San Juan to Fort Lauderdale and Orlando in
mid-December, within a week it had canceled a number of flights and
was considering cutting back to two flights a week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's 58-year-old British West Indies Airline continues to
fly daily jets between the Caribbean and Miami and New York, while
Air Jamaica flies to those cities as well as to Chicago and Los
Angeles. Meanwhile, several other Caribbean airlines, including
Trinidad-based Air Caribbean and St. Lucia-based Helen Air
Caribbean, have increased their scheduled service throughout the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because American's restructuring means fewer jets to
fewer Caribbean islands, United States travelers to the Caribbean _
especially those traveling beyond San Juan _ can expect fewer
nonstops and smaller planes, and therefore probably less
convenience. For despite additional flights by other United States
carriers, Caribbean air service is not likely to return any time
soon to what it was.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airlines seek to make a profit on every route _ even to the
point of redeploying planes from routes that are only marginally
profitable to those that are more profitable. That is what happened
last year at Las Vegas, where several airlines eliminated flights
or substituted smaller planes for widebodies _ not because Las
Vegas flights were unprofitable but because they provided much less
revenue per mile than did other routes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, while growing numbers of Americans visit the
Caribbean on cruises, the percentage of stopover visitors (those
who eat and sleep there) has plummeted _ to 48.6 percent last year
from 61.8 percent in 1987, according to the Caribbean Tourism
Organization. The reasons, travel authorities say, range from
familiarity with the Caribbean to increased competition for the
tourist dollar to fare sales to many Asian, European and Latin
American destinations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In at least partial compensation, European visits to the
Caribbean have almost doubled since 1987, to 22 percent last year
from 11.2 percent. Much of that increase has been driven by
low-cost package tours and charter flights, mainly to the Dominican
Republic.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than twice as many Europeans _ one million _ visited the
Dominican Republic last year as Americans, and more than four times
the number visited Barbados and Jamaica, the runner-up Caribbean
destinations for Europeans. (The top destinations for Americans are
the Bahamas, Puerto Rico and Jamaica, in that order.) That explains
why British Airways flies to 10 Caribbean destinations, and why
last September, Virgin Atlantic began six flights a week from
London to the Caribbean. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
