<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-ART-MUSEUM-NYT     01-04 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-ART-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: A PARIS SUBURB RECALLS THE '30S, ITS ERA OF GLORY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULOGNE-BILLANCOURT, France _ Even distant European cities feel
intimidated by the elegance, culture and history of Paris.
Consider, then, how difficult it is for an adjacent suburb like
Boulogne-Billancourt to establish its identity. Indeed, were it not
for the circular highway that defines the limits of the French
capital, it would be impossible today to know where Paris ends and
this town begins.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the 1920s and 1930s, Boulogne-Billancourt had its own
distinct personality. Previously known only for its laundries, it
became the center of new automotive and aircraft industries, home
to France's largest movie studio, a retreat for painters and
sculptors and a laboratory for architects and designers inspired by
the new modernist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Boulogne-Billancourt _ the two towns were fused into a
single municipality in 1925 _ has found a way of asserting its
independence from Paris by creating a Museum of the Thirties to
celebrate a time when it was truly different. The new museum,
inaugurated in early December, is part of a graceful modern
cultural center that stands beside the town hall, itself a monument
to 1930s architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Between the wars, long before President Francois Mitterrand
dared tamper with the heart of Paris with his program of Grands
Travaux, Boulogne-Billancourt was the one place where architectural
innovation was encouraged, with Tony Garnier, Auguste Perret, Le
Corbusier, Robert Mallet-Stevens and others free to experiment with
both style and the new material of reinforced concrete. Three Le
Corbusier buildings are among two dozen from that era that survive.
</P>
<P>
   With more space than was cheaply available in Paris,
Boulogne-Billancourt also drew some 30 sculptors, including Paul
Landowski (the cultural center, the Espace Landowski, carries his
name). And when the powerful art dealer Daniel-Henry Kahnweiler
moved here in 1921, writers and artists, from Gertrude Stein to
Picasso, would travel from Paris to spend Sundays at his home. Juan
Gris was among a handful who also settled here.
</P>
<P>
   Pointedly, the new museum does not aspire to present the best of
1930s art. One obvious reason is the impossibility of building a
new collection of works by, say, Picasso, Matisse, Brancusi and
Mondrian, just a few of the great artists living in Paris at the
time. But another good reason is that these artists can hardly be
encased in a single decade and, as such, are less representative of
the '30s than more obscure figures.
</P>
<P>
   While avant-garde artists were moving into abstraction and
Surrealism in the 1930s, neo-classical figurative painting and
sculpture were making a comeback under the umbrella of ``poetic
realism.'' After World War II, when the movement was seen to be
tainted by totalitarian influence, it went out of fashion. But it
nonetheless mirrored an era of both turmoil and nostalgia. And,
crucially, many of its works were within reach of the new museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although a small municipal museum has existed here since 1939,
in 1983 a new curator, Emmanuel Breon, persuaded the town council
to support something altogether more ambitious: a new museum that
would throw a spotlight on Boulogne-Billancourt's heyday in the
1930s. Thanks mainly to donations, but also to some acquisitions,
the museum can now boast a collection comprising some 800
paintings, 1,500 sculptures, 2,000 drawings and 50 pieces of
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's lobby gallery, which looks onto the Espace
Landowski's atrium, has been set aside for sculptures. Many are
romantic statues of nudes, but others evoke the neo-classical
figures that decorated the monumental architecture of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Several sculptures were well known at the time. ``Trinity,'' an
elongated geometrical statue of a father, mother and child by Jan
and Joel Martel, was displayed at the first salon of the Union of
Modern Artists in Paris in 1930. ``Tragedy'' and ``Comedy,'' two
stone figures by the Boulogne-based Portuguese artist Ernesto Canto
da Maya, were shown at the Colonial Exhibition in 1931. The
museum's two other floors are given over to paintings organized
around themes. Although all the art is figurative, one section
emphasizes the return to classicism with paintings like the ``Venus
Anadyomede'' by Georges Sabbagh, inspired by Botticelli, and ``The
Earth,'' a neo-Greek pastoral allegory by Jean Souverbie. Less
typical, although surely more topical when it was painted in 1937,
is Robert Humblot's ``Horrors of War.''
</P>
<P>
   Another section carries the title ``L'Ecole de Paris,'' the name
given to the large number of Central European artists who sought
refuge in Paris between the wars, first from the Soviet Union, then
from Nazi Germany. Prominent here are a series of portraits by
Arbit Blatas, a 90-year-old Lithuanian-born artist who fled to
Paris then and has donated some 50 of his paintings, sculptures and
drawings to the new museum. He now lives in New York and Venice.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has found a way of displaying some works by
Paris-based artists by recalling the ``Sundays in Boulogne'' spent
at Kahnweiler's home. More interesting, perhaps, is the section
dedicated to colonial art _ not folk art, but work done by European
artists visiting French colonies. The museum includes numerous
striking works by Alexandre Iacovleff, a Russian-born artist who
was the official illustrator of major ethnographic expeditions to
Africa in 1924 and to Indochina in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   Until late January, the museum's temporary display area is
dedicated to the Austrian-born painter and architect Leopold
Krakauer, who moved to British-ruled Palestine in 1924 and
subsequently played an influential role in the modernist
architecture of Tel Aviv. The museum has complemented this show by
including designs and models of modernist buildings in
Boulogne-Billancourt that were no less influenced by the
international style of the Bauhaus.
</P>
<P>
   In February, this space will become part of the permanent
exhibition when the museum's collection of 1930s furniture and
decorative arts will be put on display. Temporary shows, starting
with one dedicated to the art and design of the great ocean liners
of the era between the world wars, will then move to another large
gallery in the Espace Landowski.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the museum, which is within easy access of Paris by
Metro, prompts the inevitable observation that the collection
reaches beyond Boulogne-Billancourt to make its point. Yet if its
aim is to recreate the mood of the times, it succeeds. Greater
masterpieces can be found at the Georges Pompidou Center in Paris,
but this museum suggests what the art of the 1930s really felt
like. And, in doing so, it has provided Boulogne-Billancourt with a
past worth visiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
