</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS CONCERNING COINS, VIENNA AND JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10.) 
 (ms) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Small Change That Counts
</P>
<P>
   Q. Whenever I travel abroad, I return with a pocketful of
foreign coins and paper currency. Is there some organization to
which I can contribute this change and know that it will help the
needy? Marilyn F. Rothstein, Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Unicef estimates that about $72 million in foreign coins and
low-denomination bills are wasted each year because they are too
small to be converted, so it has teamed up with 19 airlines in its
Change for the Good program, to collect some of these funds and use
them to help children worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers heading home will usually find a Change for the Good
envelope on their meal tray or seat-back pocket on flights by the
participating airlines. All they have to do is put their
unconvertible foreign currency into these envelopes, and it will be
sent to Unicef. These small sums can do a lot of good: $2 in
change, for example, can buy 25 oral rehydration packets _ a
lifesaving mix of salt and sugar to prevent death by dehydration _
or enough high-dose vitamin A to protect 28 toddlers from blindness
for one year. Since 1991, Unicef says, over $19 million has been
collected through Change for the Good.
</P>
<P>
   The participating airlines are Aer Lingus, Aeromexico, Aero
Peru, Air France, Air Mauritius, Alitalia, ANA, American, Asiana,
Avianca, British Airways, Canadian Airlines International, Cathay
Pacific, Finnair, JAL, Qantas, Royal Air Maroc, Saeta and T.W.A.
</P>
<P>
   You can also drop coins off at Unicef House, 3 United Nations
Plaza, in New York, or mail them to Unicef, 333 East 38th St.,
Sixth Floor, New York, N.Y. 10016.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think all those coins will require too much postage,
you now have a use for all those odd-denomination stamps you've
collected thanks to postal-rate increases over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Vienna Architecture
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to visit Vienna in the fall, and I am interested in
seeing some of the works of Adolf Loos and Otto Wagner, leading
architects at the turn of the century. Do you know of any tours
that would cover their work during this period? Glen Mull,
Hackettstown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Viennese architect Adolf Loos (1870-1933) was one of the
pioneers of the modern European movement. He was an early opponent
of the decorative trend of Art Nouveau, believing that architecture
devoid of ornament represented pure and lucid thought. One example
of this in Vienna is his Steiner House, a three-story residence at
10 St. Veit Gasse consisting of basic flat surfaces and
different-shaped rectangular windows that give variety and movement
to the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Wagner (1841-1918), one of the most influential architects
at the turn of the century, numbers among his students the Art
Nouveau proponent Josef Hoffmann. One of Wagner's buildings in
Vienna is the Majolica House, 40 Wienzeile, whose facade of
colorful Majolica tiles reflects Art Nouveau's use of color in
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   For information on more of these two architects' work, the
Austrian National Tourist Office suggests you send a fax to the
Vienna Guide Service, (43-1) 440 2825. A private tour of about
three and a half hours costs $110 (calculated at 11.70 schillings
to the dollar); a full-day tour $219.
</P>
<P>
   For less expensive options, try Vienna Walks, which conducts a
large menu of tours that vary by month, including architectural
tours focusing on modernism and Art Nouveau. The tours last about
90 minutes and require a minimum of three participants each. They
cost about $11 a person, plus any admission fees, and are conducted
in German and English.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at Vienna's Web site:
info.wien.at. The guide who conducts the Art Nouveau tour, Brigitte
Timmermann, can be contacted directly by telephone and fax at
(43-1) 774 8901. More information: Austrian National Tourist
Office, 500 Fifth Ave., Suite 800, New York, N.Y. 10110; (212)
575-7723, fax (212) 730-4568.
</P>
<P>
   Scholarly Japan
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I want to take an escorted tour of Japan next
spring for about two weeks. We would love one like those run by
Elderhostel, but space is hard to find. Can you suggest similar
alternatives? Elena Stolzer, Kendall Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Elderhostel provides educational trips worldwide for
travelers 55 or older, but if you cannot find space on any of its
trips, some of these tours suggested by the Japan National Tourist
Organization _ all of which include study programs with on-site
study leaders _ might work for you.
</P>
<P>
   The McGill University Alumni Association has a 12-day program in
central Japan March 25 to April 5, accompanied by a study leader
from the University of Toronto. It is intended as an introduction
to Japanese culture. Stops include Tokyo, Mount Fuji, Hiroshima and
the waterside shrine in Miyajima. The price is $3,233 a person,
double occupancy, with air fare from Toronto, calculated at $1.53
Canadian to the U.S. dollar. Contact McGill University, 3605 Rue de
la Montagne, Montreal, Quebec H3G 2M1 Canada; (800) 567-5175.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Barbara Museum of Art's trip April 13 to 25 to central
Japan will be accompanied by Bruce Coats, an expert on Japanese
temple architecture. It is meant to coincide with cherry blossom
season, and much of the trip will be spent in and around Kyoto,
with time in Tokyo, too. The price of $4,990 a person, double
occupancy, includes accommodations and a few meals, but not air
fare. Though the tour is now full, openings may develop. Contact
the museum at 1130 State St., Santa Barbara, Calif. 93101; (805)
963-4364, extension 336.
</P>
<P>
   From March 16 to 25, the Smithsonian Institution will conduct
its Kyoto Interlude. Speakers will include a member of the local
historical preservation society. To better understand traditional
Japanese culture, tour participants will visit a textile factory, a
castle, a tea ceremony and gardens. Rates: $5,575 a person, double,
including air fare from Los Angeles, accommodations and some meals.
Call the Smithsonian at (202) 357-4700.
</P>
<P>
   All the above include upscale accommodations. For tours using
moderate-class accommodations (similar to Elderhostel's), try
Esprit Travel, which has three education-accented itineraries with
a total of six departure dates. They vary in length from 12 to 14
days and in price from $3,000 to $3,250 a person, double. That
includes accommodations, air fare from Los Angeles and most meals.
Expect to do some walking. Contact Esprit Travel, 2101 Wilshire
Blvd., Suite 101, Santa Monica, Calif. 90403; (800) 377-7481, fax
(310) 828-3564.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
