<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The game hasn't changed, but the Falcons have
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charlie Taylor, Falcon spokesman, described it as ``an
ordinary Monday.'' And it was, except that this is January, and the
Falcons don't ordinarily play in January. Except that they're
favored _ favored _ to win only the third playoff game in their
33-year existence. Except that by winning once more they'll advance
to the NFC championship game, where this franchise has never been.
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After a season of extraordinary Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Except that, viewed individually, none of those Sundays were so
extraordinary, either.
</P>
<P>
   Win 14 games and there figures to be a fluke mixed in. The
Falcons had none. Oh, they trailed Indy and Philly early and
Chicago and Detroit fairly late, but not once did this team win a
game where it seemed justice had been flouted. Not once did a
Falcon run a Big Ben and pluck a Hail Mary from the Jaws of Defeat.
There were no finishes on the order Young-to-Owens at 0:03. There
was simply numbing consistency, play upon play, quarter after
quarter, month after month.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent excellence is a blessed thing, but it's hard to
market and harder still to chronicle. Was there one Sunday this
season when everything turned for this franchise? The easy answer
is the second San Fran game _ the Ray Buchanan interception, the
Jessie Tuggle recovery, the Terance Mathis touchdown. But that
ignores the flattening of New England the week before, which was in
its way more impressive. And calling the win in Foxboro the
season's biggest road achievement ignores what happened in
Charlotte before Labor Day, when the tabbed-for-mediocre Falcons
whipped the poised-for-a-rebound Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   So much in life is context. That Carolina game seems
insignificant now, but at the time the Falcons regarded it as a
watershed. That the Falcons would be working in January has been a
given for nearly a month, but it wasn't a given in August. Back
then, the goal was to win nine or 10 times and earn a wild card.
Back then, even that standard-issue assignment seemed ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing story, except that the closer you look the more
mundane it gets. What's exotic about blocking hard and tackling
harder, about running the ball and stopping the run? Where's the
breakthrough in a coach stressing fundamentals? How is this
different from what Lombardi did in Green Bay, what Noll did in
Pittsburgh, what Parcells does wherever he goes? And the answer is,
it's not. At bottom, winning football is always the same.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed is that the Falcons, for so long forlorn, have
come to embody the characteristics of a winner. They don't subsist
on emotion. They didn't beat the Patriots and Niners and then lose
two of the next three. They didn't waver after Dan Reeves was
hospitalized. They kept going, play upon play, quarter after
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Now here they are, spending an ordinary Monday readying to play
the Niners again, unsurprised by being the NFL's surprise team.
Chances are, next Monday will find these Falcons working still,
business as usual, one step from a most extraordinary place, one
step from the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
