<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-     01-04 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STATEOFUNION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE IS RELUCTANT TO DELAY STATE OF THE UNION ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House expressed reluctance Monday to
delay President Clinton's scheduled Jan. 19 State of the Union
address to Congress, despite the urgings of some senators that
Clinton postpone it because of his looming Senate impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton was looking
forward to outlining his proposals to a joint meeting of the House
and Senate as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware of any discussions or requests from the
(congressional) leadership to adjust that date,'' Lockhart said.
``The president is working hard on his speech and plans to deliver
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican and Democratic senators urged Clinton on
Sunday to postpone his nationally-televised address until the
Senate completes action on his impeachment _ either with a Senate
trial or a resolution of censure _ for his cover-up of his sexual
dalliance with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said Sunday that it would be
``unseemly and distracting'' for Clinton to deliver the address
while an impeachment trial was underway. Sen. Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., said that it would be ``inappropriate'' for Clinton to
report to Congress while he was ``under impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, suggested that Clinton merely submit
his State of the Union address to Congress in writing.
</P>
<P>
   A speech delay would be a major blow to Clinton's effort to
portray himself as an undistracted chief executive carrying on
normal business in the face of efforts by the Republican-led
Congress to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, saying that he was choosing his words ``very
carefully,'' told reporters: ``As of now, we're planning to give
that speech on Jan. 19.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and the congressional leadership agreed
last month that Clinton would deliver the address on Jan. 19.
Clinton aides said they wanted a date in the third week of January
in order to accommodate the president's plans to visit St. Louis,
Mo., the following week for the visit of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton wanted to deliver his address as scheduled
to highlight his legislative agenda for the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has important work that he's doing and looks
forward to presenting it to the country,'' Lockhart said. ``The
public has come to expect the president to continue doing his job.
He'll continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers brief Clinton daily on developments with the
threatened Senate trial but Lockhart said the president was not
being diverted from official business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deals on a day-to-day basis with the business at hand here
in Washington, and (the impeachment trial) is clearly on everyone's
plate,'' Lockhart said. ``It's a subject that comes up, but it
certainly doesn't dominate the president's work day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said White House lawyers would be prepared to present
the president's defense against impeachment at a Senate trial if
the proceedings begin Monday. ``We'll be ready to go next week,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued to unveil features of his proposed federal
budget for the fiscal year 2000 that begins next Oct. 1. His State
of the Union address is expected to address those proposals, which
he will submit to Congress by Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We traditionally use this time to try to generate public
support for some of the ideas that the president will have in his
State of the Union and the budget,'' Lockhart said in response to
questions about the administration's timing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
proposed a five-year, $6.2 billion package of assistance for the
long-term care of the disabled, including a $1,000 tax credit for
an estimated 2 million Americans trying to care for disabled
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that there is not a substitute for families
being able to care for their loved ones,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``But
we sometimes forget that caregivers also need care. They, too,
carry enormous burdens.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the $5.5 billion cost of the tax
credit over five years would be offset by closing unspecified tax
loopholes that benefit corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said the
proposal was merely the beginning of an effort with Congress to
address the problem. The message to Congress, Shalala said, is
``Let's sit down and talk together,'' adding: ``I would describe it
as evolving.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton unveiled a proposed $110 billion increase in projected
Pentagon spending over six years in his nationally broadcast radio
address on Saturday. Earlier, he proposed a boost in federal
assistance to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., meets Wednesday with
the Senate's 55 Republicans to search for consensus on how to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal being considered _ put forth by Gorton and Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. _ calls for a two-stage Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under their proposal, House ``managers,'' or prosecutors, would
present the case for impeachment next Monday; Clinton's defense
team would rebut the allegations on Tuesday; senators would
question the two sides on Wednesday; and the Senate would vote
Thursday on whether the House's allegations of presidential perjury
and obstruction of justice, if proven true, would warrant removal
from office.
</P>
<P>
   If proponents of Clinton's removal failed to muster the required
two-thirds majority at that point, the Senate would adjourn the
trial and move to a compromise censure resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
