<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEEDEES-NYT     01-04 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEEDEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A CUBAN SOUND DANCING NORTH &QL; 
 &LR;  There has been a flood of traditional records from Cuba recently,
and the reasons for it are simple. The first is the descent into
irrelevance, perhaps temporary, of the Havana-based Timba dance
music world, which started receiving plenty of attention five years
ago and is now self-destructing. The second is the international
success of the Ry Cooder-produced album, ``Buena Vista Social
Club,'' released last year. Given the easy availability of hundreds
of fine little local Cuban son bands and older singers playing the
same music made by Buena Vista Social Club, it's not surprising
that the market is overflowing. Here are a handful of the best; all
are available from Descarga, (800) 377-2647 or at
www.descarga.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IBRAHIM FERRER: `TIERRA CALIENTE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer was the star vocalist with the Afro-Cuban All-Stars
(another Ry Cooder production), who released an album in 1997 and
toured the United States last year. His own record, with Los
Bocucos, is a marvel of syncopation and oddness. ``Tierra
Caliente'' (Egrem) is sort of son and sort of salsa, and it shows a
side of Cuban music that Americans used to the authenticity of
``Buena Vista Social Club'' haven't seen.
</P>
<P>
   There are electric keyboards and electric guitars, and the
rhythms draw from all over the world. Sometimes the music sounds
Haitian, sometimes Cuban, and it is always joyous, with a sense of
humor that's palpable whether one understands the words or not. And
it has an intensity that only the best dance music achieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOS NARANJOS: `MI SON TIENE PIEL MORENA' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What a rocking little record. With a tres guitar motoring away
at rhythmic figures, the music, hardcore son, never stops. Most of
the songs are older without being overfamiliar, and the chorus
sings away, surrounding the rough tones of the lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   There's a force under the prettiness of the music; suddenly the
music is charging down the highway, swinging with power. ``Mi Son
Tiene Piel Morena'' (Eurotropical) is perfectly made; the band is
obviously a working group, and its precision helps drive the
dance-floor sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   El Son Entero: `Cuba'
</P>
<P>
   Yet another little rock-house of a record. This time it features
the tres playing of Luis Acosta Pino, a virtuoso, and when the
singers call on him to solo, they call him the killer of the tres.
His solos charge the record, zipping around the fretboard, using
more of a jazz sensibility _ he even bends some notes _ than the
traditional Cuban point of view. The music is built around his
solos, and when he starts the band seems to stand back, wondering
what's about to pop out of Acosta's imagination. The group is from
the province of Camageuey, and it uses a few unusual rhythms. If
anybody needed an argument to prove that the son doesn't stand
completely still, this is it. There are occasional imperfections in
the singing in ``Cuba,'' (Playasound) but the feeling and the solos
make up for the problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAITO SUREDA: `AHORA COMIENZO A VIVIR' &QL; 
 &LR;  Sureda is 84 and the title of the record, ``Now I Start to
Live,'' has some truth to it and some wishful thinking, given
Cuba's economy. Sureda sang with Celia Cruz in the Sonora Matancera
and spent much of his life traveling. ``Ahora Comienzo a Vivir''
(Eurotropical) catches him in bolero, son and guaguanco territory,
backed by Su Sonora, a swinging small band with a few trumpets. It
is sophisticated dance music in an older style influenced by jazz,
and Sureda's large, intense voice floats over the classic sound of
the band. The music is nicely balanced and gentle, but with a
rhythmic tug.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LA BANDA MUNICIPALE DE SANTIAGO DE CUBA, `FANFARE CUBAINE' &QL; 
 &LR;  This is an oddity, a record of the community brass band from
Santiago, home of the son, produced by the French ethnomusicologist
Emmanuelle Honorin. The band, started in 1900, is big and full, and
it takes on famous sones, danzones and congas and turns them into
lilting, beautiful orchestral pieces. ``Fanfare Cubaine'' (Buda)
includes the Buena Vista Social Club's ``Chan Chan,'' with tubas
announcing the bass line. The recording is a footnote, but a
gorgeous one that suggests the breadth of imagination and the
conservative essence of Cuban music. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
