<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDSIZED-CITIES-ART-2     01-04 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDSIZED-CITIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPEROUS TIMES FOR AMERICA'S MIDSIZED CITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ky., Mich., Utah, Texas, Colo., Ind., Mo., Calif.,
Fla., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Graphic and photo are being sent to NYT graphic/photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When a recruiter offered her a job as a research
specialist at a rapidly growing medical company, Kimberly Belknap
grabbed it and moved here from Grand Rapids, Mich., to get herself,
as she put it, on a more lucrative career path.
</P>
<P>
   The new job, auditing doctors who test new drugs for
pharmaceutical companies, pays nearly $60,000 a year. Ms. Belknap
earned that much in Grand Rapids, but only by holding two jobs, and
the long hours were getting to her. So was the lack of opportunity.
As a 36-year-old physiologist, she had already risen, in her main
job, to research coordinator at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the feel of this city,'' Ms. Belknap said. ``It is
much larger but very conservative, like Grand Rapids, and the cost
is about the same.'' For $660 a month, she has a two-bedroom
apartment with a fireplace. And there is opportunity in a city with
a big university, teaching hospitals, a young biotechnology
industry and other growing companies like Kendle, the one that
employs Ms. Belknap. ``I have already been approached,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is prospering, drawing professionals like Ms. Belknap
to companies that are expanding or putting new operations here.
Jobs in this Ohio River metropolis are multiplying at a nearly 3
percent annual rate, on the strong side for cities its size _
higher, for example, than the 2.4 percent rate in Salt Lake City,
but lower than the 4 percent for Austin, Texas. The national
average is 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Midsized American cities _ not only Cincinnati, Austin and Salt
Lake, but Denver; Indianapolis; Kansas City, Mo.; Sacramento,
Calif.; Jacksonville, Fla.; Charlotte, N.C., and more than a dozen
others _ reflect the strengths that have sustained the American
economy in the 1990s and, more recently, kept it growing in the
face of economic turmoil abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America has found in these cities a fertile ground for
the service-sector job creation that has played so big a role in
the current expansion. AT&AMP;T, for example, has a huge
telephone-operator center in Jacksonville; Microsoft and Vanguard
chose Charlotte for some of their new service operations; and
Integral Technologies, a new software company with 100 employees,
came to life in Indianapolis, financed by a local venture capital
company, one of many that have sprung up in midsized cities.
</P>
<P>
   Public spending, particularly for downtown redevelopment, like
the two sports stadiums and the riverfront highway under
construction here, also plays a role in these cities' prosperity.
So do tax breaks and other subsidies that the cities use
aggressively to coax companies to locate or expand there. But the
main engine is a plentiful pool of workers who are not too
expensive, even those who are college-educated and highly skilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, everyone was predicting that companies would
move to Montana or some other rural state,'' said Edward Glaeser, a
Harvard economist and urban expert. ``The key now is the
middle-sized city, 750,000 to 2 million people, that can provide
enough amenities, enough of the right sort of labor pool, to
attract companies, encourage expansion and create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater Cincinnati, with 1.9 million people spread over 13
counties in southern Ohio and northern Kentucky, offers such a
pool. Most of the nation's job creation in the 1990s has been
generated by companies in the service and financial sectors, Labor
Department data show. And they have hired mainly among two groups
of workers. One group, near the high end, college-educated like Ms.
Belknap and very skilled, accepts $40,000 to $80,000 as a
satisfactory wage. The other, at the low end, often fairly skilled
but either just starting out or not as well educated, settles for
less than $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller cities, even if they have this mix of workers, lack the
nexus of business services _ accountants, lawyers, advertising
agencies and transportation _ that corporations need, said Mark
Zandi, chief economist of RFA, an economic consulting firm in West
Chester, Pa. And larger cities are saddled with the urban social
problems and the unionized workers that corporate America tries to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The prosperity in Cincinnati could dissipate. Even as new
companies arrive, long-established ones could falter. Auto sales,
now strong, could fall, hurting the numerous parts suppliers here.
China, a big customer of General Electric Aircraft Engines, could
cease to be an enthusiastic buyer of the narrow-bodied airliners
equipped with the jet engines that GE assembles here at a sticker
price of $5 million an engine. Or stock prices, whose rise has
encouraged a flourish of borrowing and spending, could falter,
extinguishing wealth among thousands of shareholders here in such
hometown companies as Procter &AMP; Gamble and Fifth Third Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   But if the booming stock market helps explain the spending and
home construction so evident in this city, Megan McCoy helps
explain why expanding companies like Fidelity Investments choose
cities like Cincinnati to locate new operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCoy, 24, is one of the more skilled people at the low end.
After graduating in May 1997 from Miami University in nearby
Oxford, with a degree in finance, she joined Fidelity, the
Boston-based mutual fund and financial services company that is a
unit of FMR. Years ago, Fidelity had all its workers in Boston, and
the most sophisticated operations are still there. But as Fidelity
grew, it spread across the country, and now 60 percent of its
27,000 workers are in regional centers like the one here, which is
Fidelity's largest, with 3,500 employees _ up from 300 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCoy is a phone operator, taking calls to an 800 number
from Fidelity clients who want to cash in their 401(k) plans. ``I
wanted to get into the securities industry, but I did not want to
be thrown right away into cold calling,'' she said of her decision
to join Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   She commutes from the Hyde Park neighborhood, where many young
singles live, to a quiet, wooded campus of modernistic office
buildings near the city's huge airport, on the Kentucky side of the
Ohio, in one of the two Kentucky counties that are part of Greater
Cincinnati. There, using answers that come up on her computer, she
counsels Fidelity clients who are retiring or leaving a company.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Ms. McCoy earns just under $12 an hour, or nearly
$24,000 a year, although with regular overtime, her total pay in
1998 was roughly $28,000. With many other workers like Ms. McCoy
eager to get started, other companies have also set up telephone
operations here. Citibank, a unit of Citigroup, and GE Information
Technology Solutions are the latest.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Distribution is another growing Cincinnati activity, because of
the giant airport, which is Delta Air Lines' second-largest hub.
From its campus, Fidelity mails the monthly statements to all of
its 12 million clients, as well as the checks they receive and a
variety of other materials. Seven hundred people, earning $18,000
to $23,000 a year, work in mail. An administrative staff for the
entire Fidelity operation, as well as a variety of technical
workers _ more than 500 people in all _ earn between $40,000 and
$75,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work ethic here is extremely strong,'' said Paul Smith,
manager of the Fidelity campus.
</P>
<P>
   The public subsidies are also robust. As a lure, Fidelity got
tax relief equal to about 5 percent of the $100 million
construction cost for its five-year-old campus, a free highway to
its hilly campus, and, starting in January, a telephone center at
Northern Kentucky University, a state school 10 minutes away by
car, where 200 students will do the same work that Ms. McCoy does _
for $2 or $3 an hour less in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no major corporate undertaking seems to happen in the
Cincinnati area anymore without a public subsidy. That is true of
other American cities, although Cincinnati, with strong support
from the Kentucky and Ohio governments, is more aggressive than
most. And the subsidies flow, whether the company is being lured
here, like Fidelity, or is long-established, like Procter &AMP; Gamble,
which gets property tax abatements for new investments.
</P>
<P>
   Anything splashy gets some public money. Duke Realty
Investments, an established developer here, built and recently
opened a gray concrete and tinted glass shopping center on Fountain
Square, the busiest downtown area. Palomino, a trendy, lamp-lit
restaurant, is a tenant. Tiffany's is another, and so are a Brooks
Brothers clothing store and a Lazarus department store. But the
city government, not Duke, purchased the choice site for $80
million and leased it to Duke for monthly payments that cover, in
effect, only $10 million of the city's outlay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not have gotten into this,'' said James Gray, a Duke
vice president, ``if the city had not presented us with that modest
lease.''
</P>
<P>
   A different view of Cincinnati's appeal emerges from the city's
leaders. True, they say, wages are lower than in the Northeast, or
on the West Coast or in Chicago and Detroit. But the cost of living
is also much less. The hub airport, greatly expanded in recent
years, plays a decisive role as a corporate lure, they argue. And
the riverfront construction project, featuring new football and
baseball stadiums for the Bengals and the Reds, each demanded by
the teams, gives the city an indispensable lure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are talking to businesses about locating here,'' said
Robert Wehling, a senior vice president at Procter &AMP; Gamble, the
city's largest employer, ``if you don't have professional sports
teams, you are not going to make their cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The saucer-shaped foundation of the new football stadium is
already in place and bulldozers have cut the wide swath of an
eight-lane highway to replace a road now running through the
riverfront site. Two thousand feet upriver, the Reds' new stadium
will rise almost on top of the team's present stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between these two bookends,'' said Andis Udris, director of
economic development, ``we will have retailers, restaurants,
offices, a museum _ basically items that complement tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   In full swing, the five-year, $800 million construction project,
financed through a half-cent increase in the sales tax, will
generate 2,000 jobs, many at local supplier companies, city
officials estimate. That is roughly 7 percent of the 25,000 jobs
added in Greater Cincinnati in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The riverfront stadiums are marketing,'' said Bob Bedinghaus,
a commissioner of Hamilton County, which includes downtown
Cincinnati. ``They show that this is an exciting place to live and
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are not what encouraged Candace Kendle Bryan and her
husband, Christopher Bergen, to form Kendle, the medical company,
after they moved here from Philadelphia to be near her mother, and
then expand it from 63 employees in 1991 to 350 today in
Cincinnati. Many are nurses, pharmacists and physiologists like Ms.
Belknap. They audit doctors who test drugs on patients before the
Food and Drug Administration rules on licensing the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a big enough health care industry, a critical
mass, so that we have people to draw from,'' Bergen said, ``and
there has to be alternative jobs for our employees who don't work
out or who want other opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the growth, there are caveats. The city's black
population does not share equally in the prosperity. The black
unemployment rate for the area is at least 8 percent, more than
double the 3.4 percent rate for the work force as a whole. And some
of Cincinnati's job gains, like those of other midsized cities, are
someone else's losses. Ashland Oil, for example, is shifting its
headquarters to Cincinnati from smaller Ashland, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zandi, the economist, said, ``There are no hard numbers,
but most of the new jobs in midsized cities seem to represent
expansion rather than transfer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
