<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-DONATE-ART-2TAKE     01-04 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-DONATE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE PATRONS LOST TO MERGERS, ARTS GROUPS FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Va., Texas, Ohio, Ill., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The record number of mergers of large companies
into even larger ones last year has raised concerns at many arts
organizations and other nonprofit groups that a decline in
corporate donations may be an unfortunate byproduct.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the merging companies say they will maintain their
contributions. But ``what usually happens is that the combined
companies do not give as much as each company was giving
individually,'' said Ann Kaplan, research director of Giving USA,
which tracks contributions. ``Companies by their nature are not
philanthropic. They are giving to advance their business
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Recipients of corporate gifts fear that those interests might
change because of shifts in corporate philosophy, overlapping
contributions among newly merged companies or the closing of
headquarters in cities where a merged partner has long had a
presence. Some local arts groups say that even the loss of a modest
grant could be detrimental, because contributions from blue-chip
companies serve as marks of an organization's value to other
potential donors.
</P>
<P>
   The United States experienced more than 12,000 mergers last
year, with a total value of more than $1.5 trillion, although many
of them are awaiting federal approval. Among the companies involved
are major arts patrons like AT&AMP;T, Bell Atlantic, BankAmerica,
Chrysler and Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the anxiety among nonprofit groups is the inability of
some of the merging companies to respond to queries about their
future giving because of a federally mandated ``quiet period''
during which they are not permitted to talk about their plans while
regulators review the deals.
</P>
<P>
   The role of corporate donations in the arts and other
philanthropic activity is huge. According to Giving USA,
corporations gave $8.2 billion to nonprofit institutions in 1997,
which accounted for 5.7 percent of all charitable contributions.
The share rose to 12 percent when contributions to churches and
other religious institutions, which are made largely by
individuals, were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this giving is centered on the communities where
companies are based; and after mergers they are based in fewer
places. Lee Cassidy, executive director of the National Federation
of Nonprofits, said that while mergers tended to hurt nonprofit
institutions in general, he feared they would hit particularly hard
in cases like Chrysler Corp.'s merger with Daimler-Benz AG. Arts
groups and other nonprofits in the Detroit area could feel the
pinch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations that establish themselves through headquarters or
plants or even sales offices in a community tend to support that
community because the people who work for them live in that
community,'' he said. ``I think Chrysler will be less involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Harris, senior vice president for communications for the
newly unified ChryslerDaimler, said that the fears were
understandable but unfounded. The merged company will have dual
headquarters, he said, in Auburn Hills, Mich., a Detroit suburb,
and Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chrysler has been active in the city of Detroit, and we have
no intention of breaking away from that at all,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar concerns have focused on the largest proposed merger of
last year, the $86 billion marriage of Mobil and Exxon, which is
awaiting federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil, more than most companies, has been identified with arts
giving for years, most prominently as one of the first and largest
contributors to public television, including 28 years as sponsor of
``Masterpiece Theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The series is probably safe for now. While a Mobil spokeswoman
declined to comment, because of the ``quiet period'' rules, the
spokeswoman for WGBH in Boston, the producing station, said that in
July Mobil renewed its commitment to the show through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But arts organizations in the Washington area, where Mobil
maintains its headquarters in Fairfax, Va., are concerned. Although
Mobil's marketing and refining headquarters will remain, its top
corporate officers will be leaving, along with other highly paid
executives and, not incidentally, the people who make decisions on
charitable donations. Would the merged Exxon-Mobil in Texas have an
interest is supporting, for example, the Arts Council of Fairfax
County, which received $20,000 from Mobil last year?
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations in the Washington area that have been
supported by Mobil include the principal public television station,
WETA, and the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, which
each received $100,000 in 1997 from Mobil, out of annual budgets of
$55 million and $90 million respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Tukey, executive director of the Fairfax Symphony Orchestra,
said Mobil's donation of $10,000 toward its $1 million annual
budget was vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things, Mobil has been our largest single
corporate underwriter,'' she said. ``They establish a record that
tells other companies that this is a worthwhile venture. When Mobil
leaves, we will have to show the new folks at the merged company
that the partnership that has been in existence is vital to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Arts groups' fears of lost donations are based on experience.
While not caused by a merger, Exxon's move of its headquarters from
New York to Irving, Texas, eight years ago resulted in a big
geographic shift of its support for the arts, which, like Mobil's,
is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were big supporters of the arts in New York City until we
moved here in 1990,'' said Edward Ahnert, president of the Exxon
Education Foundation, from his office in Irving. ``In 1990 we began
a measured program to reduce our support of the community
organizations there.''
</P>
<P>
   The donations instead were largely transferred to the
Dallas-Fort Worth area. ``It is normal for companies to give more
in communities where they have a work force,'' Ahnert said.
</P>
<P>
   According to its report for 1997, Exxon gave more than $2.6
million to arts organizations. Of that, more than $1.3 million went
to groups in Texas in donations of $5,000 or more. In addition,
Exxon gave $832,858 to match employees' cultural donations and
$156,945 in gifts of less than $5,000 each, mostly in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years we have drawn back almost all of our giving in
New York,'' Ahnert said. In 1997 Exxon gave $100,720 to the Houston
Grand Opera and $65,000 to the Dallas Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is not exceptional, said Ms. Kaplan of Giving USA.
When a company's headquarters leave a city, she said, the company
loses its incentive to support organizations in the abandoned city,
and thousands of jobs leave, and with them the donations of the
departed employees.
</P>
<P>
   When Chevron absorbed Gulf in 1984, for example, Gulf's once
ample donations dried up at cultural institutions in its home base,
Pittsburgh. Until the merger, Gulf had sponsored the National
Geographic public television specials, which had been produced by
WQED in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron kept up with Gulf's commitments, and that soothed
community feelings,'' said George Hazimanolis, a spokesman for the
station. ``Chevron supported the arts for a few years and then
moved on to something else.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland faces a similar prospect. A big local employer,
British Petroleum, is acquiring Amoco, but it is moving its
headquarters to Chicago, Amoco's home. The Cleveland Orchestra is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``BP has been very generous in guaranteeing that it will honor
the commitments in Cleveland through the year 2000,'' said Annie
Madonia, the spokeswoman for the orchestra. ``It's hard to tell how
successful we'll be. It's a difficult position to be in.`
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum now gives the Cleveland Orchestra $100,000 a
year. ``We hope the company will continue to be a good corporate
citizen,'' Ms. Madonia said.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations sometimes continue to support programs in the
former home bases of companies they have absorbed. In a $72 billion
merger of telephone companies, SBC Communications, which is based
in San Antonio, is taking over Ameritech, whose headquarters are in
Chicago. SBC has pledged to maintain Ameritech's presence in
Chicago, including its philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Selim Bingol, SBC's spokesman, said that was what happened when
SBC took over Pacific Bell. In 1996, before the merger, Pacific
Bell donated $7.6 million to nonprofit organizations, he said.
During 1997, when the merger took place, the total rose to $9
million. By the end of last year, under full SBC control, Bingol
said, Pacific Bell donated $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   One big merger in New York that probably will not reduce
corporate donations is the $73 billion deal between Citicorp and
Travelers to form Citigroup. The headquarters of both merged
companies are in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Morris, the Citigroup spokesman, said, ``The level of
giving is not going to be affected by the merger per se, but by
business conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new foundation formed by the merged company would
honor multiyear commitments made by the predecessors, although he
warned that new projects might meet some resistance because
financial-services companies have seen their profits squeezed
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for continued charitable commitments is that the
co-chairmen of the merged company, John Reed, who had been chairman
of Citicorp, and Sanford Weill, who had headed Travelers, bring
separate interests to the newly formed corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's main interest is in the social and behavioral sciences.
Weill is a generous supporter of the medical school of Cornell
University and is probably best known in New York for his support
of the arts, especially Carnegie Hall, where he has been board
chairman since 1991. The two men serve on only one board together,
that of Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 another New York merger brought together Chemical Bank
and Chase Manhattan, both of which had been big supporters of the
Museum of Modern Art. ``There has been no impact of the merging
relative to contributions,'' said Liz Addison, the museum's
spokeswoman. In fact, she added, the amount the museum has received
from the merged bank exceeds the amount that the two had given
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Another bank merger raised fears in Philadelphia, where a
carefully worked-out agreement on giving followed the absorption in
1997 of hometown Corestates Financial Corp. by First Union Corp.,
which has its headquarters in Charlotte, N.C. Arts, civil rights
and economic development groups, as well as the city itself,
opposed the merger before government regulators, partly on the
ground that a large corporate donor would be disappearing from the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition was dropped, said Dale Mitchell, executive
director of Delaware Valley Grant Makers, when First Union agreed
to maintain Corestates' previous contributions of $17 million a
year to local groups for five years and to set up a $100 million
foundation whose income provides for future grants.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Mondesire, president of the Philadelphia chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, which
had received support from Corestates, said that the merged bank had
kept up the level of donations but that Philadelphia organizations
would have to be diligent because ``the president here answers to
someone in Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked, however, whether he thought that Philadelphia
institutions would benefit as much from the bank in the future as
they did in the past, he answered warily. ``I think if we're not
careful, they won't,'' he said. ``You lose contact with the local
people who make decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
