<HEADLINE>
PATTERNS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MARYLOU LUTHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A COLOR-FILLED CRYSTAL BALL &QL; 
 &LR;  If President Clinton has to appear before the Senate this month,
Leatrice Eiseman says he should wear navy blue. ``Blue is the color
of credibility, constancy and truth, the color most Americans
associate with dependability and loyalty,'' said Ms. Eiseman, a
color psychology expert.
</P>
<P>
   The president should avoid a red or a red-purple tie, she
warned, as ``these colors speak of sensuality.''
</P>
<P>
   As executive director of the Pantone Color Institute, in
Moonachie, N.J., Ms. Eiseman researches the associations consumers
make with colors and predicts their seasonal selling power. She was
one of the first to say that gray would be the best-selling color
last fall (it was), pegging it as ``the logical, nonthreatening
shift away from black.''
</P>
<P>
   She predicts that pink will be the big hit for spring because it
taps into a national feeling of optimism. ``Pink not only makes you
feel good, it makes you feel better,'' she said. ``Pink soothes.
It's nurturing. It has a softening touch. Our studies show that men
have far less objection to wearing pink and being surrounded by
pink than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first year of the next century, Ms. Eiseman picks blue _
specifically, a sky-blue color she calls (what else?) millennium
blue _ as the winner. ``Blue brings up feelings of the universe,
and it makes the unknown a little less frightening,'' she said.
``The sky, which is a presence in our daily lives, is always there.
That's the dependability factor of blue. The earth can shake under
our feet, but so far the sky has not fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURFING FOR NORMA KAMALI &QL; 
 &LR;  If you were surfing the Internet Monday, you might have read this
exchange on the Norma Kamali Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yumarv: &LR;  ``How long will the fall sale be on? Is it 40 percent
off on  &UR; all &LR;  merchandise?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Norma Kamali: &LR;  ``Thank you for your inquiry regarding our fall
sale. Yes, it is 40 percent off on all fall merchandise. As you
know, sale merchandise is final sale. Please e-mail us your
telephone number so a personal shopper can assist you in making the
best selection for size and fit.'' (By the way, the sale is still
on.)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was Ms. Kamali herself typing in the response. Her
site (www.omo-norma-kamali.com) has been up for more than four
years, but the designer began responding directly to consumers
yesterday. She went on to mention her first sample sale in five
years (Jan. 9 to 16).
</P>
<P>
   Like other retailers going after the estimated $5 billion online
market, Ms. Kamali says holiday sales from her Web site far
exceeded expectations: her 1998 online sales were 50 percent over
1997's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really, really was the first Christmas with so much
activity, so much curiosity,'' she said. Ms. Kamali likens e-mail
and online chat to virtual R&AMP;D. ``It's like an elaborate market
study direct to the designer without all the research,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESIGNS TO HELP BATTLE BREAST CANCER &QL; 
 &LR;  NEW YORK _ Isaac Mizrahi's latest design since closing his
business last October is also his smallest. It's a twin sweater set
with matching scarf, a tweed skirt and jeweled ballet slippers he
created for a 21-inch-high Mme. Alexander Cissy doll.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be among 20 designer-outfitted dolls to be auctioned
in September at a fund-raiser for the Council of Fashion Designers
of America Foundation's Fashion Targets Breast Cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The designers, who dressed the dolls in a joint project with the
Alexander Doll Company, will have their first looks at one
another's creations on Jan. 27, when they meet for a cocktail
reception at the company's factory, in Harlem. Fern Mallis, the
council's executive director, who has already had a look, said she
was also impressed with the designers' deftness with the dolls'
hair and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The Cissy dolls have clothes that range from Diane Von
Furstenberg's signature wrap dress under a long pink mink coat to
James Purcell's ball gown printed with targets that match the
Fashion Targets Breast Cancerlogo pin, which the doll is holding.
All will be offered to buyers at the annual Toy Fair in February,
and the 10 most popular will be manufactured to sell to collectors
for about $450 each. Gale Jarvis, president of the company, said
that all proceeds from the auction of the originals would go to the
breast cancer campaign. She added that at least 10 percent of the
wholesale price would go to the fund when the dolls reach stores in
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
