<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ART-380&AMP;ADD     01-04 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ART-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING FLARES IN SEPARATIST INDONESIAN PROVINCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 BY MARK DODD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ At least nine people were killed, more than
20 injured and scores arrested over the weekend in Indonesia after
a crackdown by government forces in a province that has been a
center of separatist violence.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters and battalion-strength reinforcements have been sent
to Aceh province in northern Sumatra, the scene of the clashes, a
senior military commander said.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said the violence in the area was the most
serious since August, when the military promised local residents
that it would withdraw its forces. That agreement seems
increasingly unlikely to be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A senior army commander based at Lhokseumawe, the industrial
town that is the site of the most recent violence, said by
telephone that police and army reinforcements had secured the town
and restored order, although the situation remained tense.
</P>
<P>
   Lhokseumawe is almost 1,000 miles northwest of this capital, on
the northern tip of Sumatra, Indonesia's largest island.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are nine dead, all civilians,'' the East Aceh military
commander, Col. Johnny Wahab, said.
</P>
<P>
   Wahab said security forces opened fire on Sunday after 3,000
separatist supporters had rioted and looted government buildings.
During the riot, mobs set fire to four police stations, a district
chief's office, an immigration office and a logistics warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   That violence was set off by a military raid on Saturday to try
to capture the leader of the Free Aceh movement, Ahmad Kandang.
Kandang eluded capture. But 132 people were arrested in the
security sweep. Military officials said they had been responding to
two separatist attacks against the military.
</P>
<P>
   Aceh, a staunchly Muslim province, has been a center of
separatist activity since Dutch colonial times. Brutal
counterinsurgency operations mounted by the military in a nine-year
crackdown have inflamed feelings against the army.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has flared in several regions since the resignation in
May of President Suharto, ending 32 years of dictatorial rule.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and residents of Aceh have accused the
military of rape, torture and summary executions. In August, with
the nation under new leadership, the army apologized for abuses and
said that it would withdraw its forces from the province.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most recent crackdown in Aceh began after a separatist
attack on Tuesday in which eight off-duty soldiers were killed
after having been dragged from a bus that the rebels ambushed.
</P>
<P>
   An army spokesman said three recovered bodies bore torture
marks. A search is under way for two marines who are believed to be
alive after having been abducted on Wednesday in an ambush in
northern Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   Wahab said security forces would reassert their authority.
``From where my office is, about one kilometer from the shopping
center, traffic looks normal,'' he said. ``I can't confirm all
shops are open. But it seems life is beginning to get back to
normal. People are still cautious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
