<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT05-COX     01-04 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TO INTUIT: WHERE'S THE BEEF?
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of personal finance software maker Intuit
was depicted by Microsoft's lead attorney Monday as running a
highly successful company without any valid complaints against the
maker of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   As the government's landmark antitrust case against Microsoft
resumed after a two-week holiday recess, Intuit president and chief
executive officer William Harris conceded that his Quicken product
is used in more than 10.5 million U.S. households, with an 80
percent share of retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft's own financial product, called Money, in second
place, Harris voiced fears on the witness stand that the software
giant would use its Windows monopoly to apply undue leverage
against its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But under John Warden's searing cross-examination, Harris proved
unable to show how Microsoft had failed to play by the rules, even
the loosely defined ones in the fast-paced software industry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Quicken's success, Intuit's small
business-oriented product, known as Quickbooks, has 84 percent of
its market, and its tax preparation software has 80 percent of that
market, Warden noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they monopoly products?'' he boomed at the witness.
``Should Quicken be treated as some common carrier?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is that Quicken is not an essential service for
which there is no effective substitute,'' Harris replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you suggesting that the Interstate Commerce Commission be
reconfigured into the National Operating System Commission?''
Warden asked. ``Are you suggesting a National Operating System
Commission should be created?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proposing any such thing,'' Harris responded.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris scored a point when Warden sought to show that
Microsoft, despite the power of Windows, failed to dominate as a
``portal'' on the Internet _ the site users see first when they
enter the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   He testified that he was told by Microsoft's vice president of
personal finance, Lewis Levin, that the company had quickly become
one of the most commonly accessed sites on the Internet ``without
even having tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Levin said that was only the beginning. Harris said
Levin had told him: ``We have a bunch of leveraged assets to get
eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris also said that Compaq, a leading computer maker, came
under pressure from Microsoft to break a deal to display a link to
Quicken on the desktop screen that appears when Compaq machines are
first turned on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq was going to abrogate the contract with us,'' Harris
said. ``We complained to them, and they told us that was simply the
way things were.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, after a top-level talk, Compaq agreed to allow both
Intuit's Quicken and Microsoft's Money program to be provided,
Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit did not sue Compaq, Harris added, ``because we felt that
was about all we could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these stabs, the Microsoft team contended at the end of
the day that Intuit's boss had failed to make a compelling
antitrust case for the Justice Department and the 19 states joining
it as plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to understand why (Intuit) would have come
forward,'' Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said outside the federal
courthouse. ``Our job is the catch the mud that the government is
throwing at Microsoft,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After Harris completes his testimony, the government will call
its last witness, Franklin Fisher. The Massachusetts Institute of
Technology economist has spent the last several months poring over
data taken from Microsoft's Redmond, Wash., databases that detail
the company's contracts with computer makers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
