</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN05-CO     01-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Destiny can defy defeat
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just like that, the Golden Gate Bridge is
sparkling more. The cable cars are climbing higher to the sky.
Really, all you need to know about life here these days is that the
next frown you see when you mention anything involving the 49ers
will be the first.
</P>
<P>
   Still, here is the most striking thing around San Francisco Bay
since the Green Bay Packers were ambushed Sunday at 3Com Park by a
miracle dressed in cardinal and gold: The 49ers don't look so
creaky, so vulnerable, so likely to become an easy stepping stone
for the Falcons to the NFC Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The Redemption Catch lives, just as it will forever through the
magic of NFL Films and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that play is officially a part of us,''
said 49ers strong safety Tim McDonald, referring to Terrell Owens
surviving his horrors at wide receiver for 121 minutes and 57
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as a packed stadium held its breath with three seconds
left, Owens grabbed Steve Young's 25-yard pass for a 30-27 victory
that hid this organization's many woes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, for the moment. McDonald said, ``There's been so much
negative talk around here about this and that, but we have to stay
positive. It's behind us, but it's just below the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance: There are so many vacancies in high places
throughout the 49ers' complex that you'd think somebody had
unleashed a neutron bomb. The ownership situation is absolutely a
mess. So is the head coaching situation, where Steve Mariucci's job
is shaky despite a 29-9 record overall, including 18-1 at home.
Then again, the 49ers haven't won a road game against a team with a
winning record for nearly 25 months.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the 49ers' secondary is a sieve. Green Bay
receivers spent most of Sunday prospering in wide open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   You can expect more of the same Saturday at the Georgia Dome,
where Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler is likely to spend the
afternoon playing catch with his receivers early and often. That
is, when Jamal Anderson isn't chewing through a 49ers' front seven
that has yet to stop the Packers' Dorsey Levens, either on the
ground or through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the 49ers' pass rush is in such disarray that they've
signed ancient and troubled Charles Haley for the playoffs. This is
presumably because Fred Dean or Hacksaw Reynolds wasn't available.
Wide receiver Jerry Rice is aging by the moment. He didn't make a
catch against the Packers until the final seconds. He fumbled it
away, but the officials showed mercy or incompetence by not making
the call.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with everything just said is that logic has nothing
to do with the 49ers these days. Logic always disappears when the
subject is a team hinting of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very important for us if we were going to go
anywhere,'' said 49ers linebacker Ken Norton, still glowing with
others in their suddenly brighter world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were going to continue the dominance of the league the
way the 49ers have, we had to get over Green Bay,'' Norton said.
``It's kinda similar to how we couldn't beat Dallas for the longest
time. Now that we got that off us, the world is out there for us to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but the 49ers' world begins in Atlanta, where another team
hinting of destiny is expecting its own pixie dust.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
