<P>
   IMPEACH-GOP (Washington) -- With their party's public standing
at stake, Senate Republicans schedule a closed-door caucus to
confront deep divisions within their ranks over how to conduct an
impeachment trial of President Clinton. By Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ Though a Senate impeachment trial
threatens to delay his yearly State of the Union message, President
Clinton plunges ahead with a preview, announcing a plan, including
a $1,000 tax credit, to help disabled Americans needing long-term
care and their relatives who provide it. By Ann Scales. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENCY-DOLE (Washington) _ The fast-churning Republican
presidential field takes on new shape as Elizabeth Dole says she is
giving ``serious consideration'' to running for the White House and
Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire files candidacy papers. By
Michael Kranish and Mary Leonard. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MINN-VENTURA (Minneapolis) _ As Gov. Jesse Ventura takes the
helm, those who elected him wonder if the ex-pro wrestler will
change into a more conventional character. Those who didn't wonder
what it will mean for Minnesota. By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-WELFARE (Boston) -- Massachusetts ends cash aid to families
with no income and children to support, halting payments to 740
welfare recipients. By Doris Sue Wong. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
