<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-GALLOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUIS A. GALLOP, 72; HAD OWNED N.H. MAIL-ORDER FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luis A. Gallop, a retired advertising executive who owned and
operated the mail-order company The Booted Sheepherder, died of
myelodysplasia Wednesday in his home in Chapel Hill, N.C. He was
72.
</P>
<P>
   A former resident of Old Greenwich, Conn., and Francestown,
N.H., Mr. Gallop founded the New Hampshire chapter of the Hemlock
Society, a group devoted to legalizing the right of terminally ill
patients to assisted death with dignity. He was also the director
of the World Federation of Right to Die Societies.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Cincinnati, he was an advertising executive in New York
with Reuben Donnelly, Time-Life Inc., Benton &AMP; Bowles, and Venture
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to Francestown in 1971, Mr. Gallop owned and
operated The Booted Sheepherder and became active in town affairs.
He was an active participant at town meetings and was a member of
the town's historical district and water commissions.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Chapel Hill two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He had been married to the late Kathryn N. Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Margie R. Matthews; three daughters, Deborah
Cristman McMullen of London, Dana Cristman Eaton of Sunnyvale,
Calif., and Anne Gallop Pace of Sudbury, Mass.; a son, Charles A.
of Winchester, Mass.; a sister, Fifi A. Bronstein of Los Angeles;
and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-GOP-HNS &LR;      01-04 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE LEAVES RED CROSS; POSSIBLE WHITE HOUSE BID SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole stepped down as president of the
American Red Cross Monday, clearing the way for a possible bid for
the Republican presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional ceremony at the ornate 82-year-old Red Cross
headquarters here, Dole only hinted at what her future plans might
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not made definite plans about what I will do next,'' she
told more than 100 Red Cross employees and well-wishers. But she
did say, ``At this important time in our national life, I believe
there may be another way for me to serve our country.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Soon, I will begin considering new paths, and there
are exciting possibilities. I will choose one and pursue it with
all my might.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, 62, the wife of 1996 GOP contender and former Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole, declined to answer questions from the
stage where she made her announcement. But on her way out, she told
reporters that she would give a presidential bid ``serious
consideration, along with other options.''
</P>
<P>
   A Dole adviser, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the
Associated Press that there are plans to form a presidential
exploratory committee within a month. Some associates said Mrs.
Dole did not want to explore any presidential aspirations while
still affiliated with the nonpartisan Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   After her announcement, she won high praise from Republican
political activists. ``If she ran, she would be instantly viable,''
said GOP pollster Frank Luntz. ``Her style and demeanor are exactly
what Americans want at this point in the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   She also drew praise from a senior Clinton administration
official. Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said
Mrs. Dole had ``provided outstanding leadership to the American Red
Cross'' in her eight years there. ``She brought intelligence, skill
and integrity to the post and she leaves with my highest respect
and affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hanford Dole grew up in comfortable surroundings in
Salisbury, N.C. As an undergraduate at Duke University, she was May
queen, and her strong academic record won her admission to Harvard
University law school, from which she graduated in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   After serving on the Federal Trade Commission from 1973 to 1979,
she held two Cabinet posts. She was transportation secretary under
President Reagan from 1983 to 1987 and labor secretary under
President Bush in 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the still male-dominated world of politics, she has earned a
reputation for keen analytical and policymaking skills tempered by
a sunny disposition and southern drawl.
</P>
<P>
   She has never held elective office. Her marriage to Bob Dole in
1975 brought her new status as half of one of Washington's most
prominent power couples.
</P>
<P>
   She took a leave from the American Red Cross in 1996 to campaign
for her husband, and at the Republican convention that year in San
Diego, she electrified delegates by walking among them,
TV-talk-show style, and offering a lyrical recitation about ``the
man I love.''
</P>
<P>
   With her final departure from the Red Cross Monday, some
political analysts predicted that she may really be a contender for
the vice presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster, dismissed such talk as idle
speculation. ``This isn't about being vice president,'' DiVall
said. ``This is about making a serious bid for the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   DiVall and Luntz said Mrs. Dole would be able to raise up to $25
million, the amount needed to launch a presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz placed her in a league with contenders such as Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., who announced formation of a presidential
exploratory committee last week, and publishing magnate Steve
Forbes, whose vast personal fortune automatically makes him a
credible competitor if he decides to run.
</P>
<P>
   Among potential GOP candidates, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is
widely considered the frontrunner. The field is expected to narrow
somewhat Tuesday as another Republican hopeful, conservative Sen.
John Ashcroft, R-Mo., announces his plans. According to the AP, he
has told at least one backer he is not likely to run.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, whether as a presidential or vice presidential
candidate, would be seen as an asset to Republicans among many
women voters, a majority of whom have preferred Democrats in recent
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, 51 percent of women interviewed in exit polls
reported voting for a Democrat for the House of Representatives
while 46 preferred a Republican. Among men, 52 percent said they
voted for a Republican and 45 percent, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has supported the pro-life position on abortion,
something that Democrats could seek to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Cohen, spokeswoman for Emily's List, a political
action committee that raises money for pro-choice women Democrats,
said she sees a possible Dole candidacy as an attempt by
Republicans to emulate the success of women Democrats such as Sens.
Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer of California and Patty Murray
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic women have been successful in these high-visibility
races; so it makes sense that a prominent Republican woman would
step forward,'' Cohen said. ``Republican women have not made
significant gains in recent elections. So this may be something
helpful to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
