<HEADER>
A7807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURBERRY-FASHION-ART-     01-04 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURBERRY-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURBERRY MODERNIZES AND REINVENTS ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a neat trick, and between Rose Marie Bravo and
Roberto Menichetti, they seem to have pulled it off. They took a
moldering old British clothing company called Burberrys, known
mainly for its plaid umbrellas and raincoat linings, altered the
name to Burberry and gave it a spiffy new look without destroying
its essential character.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bravo, the chief executive, and Menichetti, the design
director, accomplished the feat by looking at the 150-year history
of Burberry and updating the best of its attributes into a
thoroughly modern line of women's clothing and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The trench coats, the plaid, the innovative fabrics _ they're
all there, but reinvented for a new age. The trench coat has been
streamlined, stripped of extraneous epaulets and tabs. The plaid
(which the British call a check, reserving ``plaid'' for tartans)
has come out from under wraps to appear on skirts and dresses. New
ways with materials include coating canvas with voile and
distressing leather with perfume. But there has also been a return
to gabardine, the fabric that Thomas Burberry, who founded the
company in 1847, had specially woven for the durable coats worn by
sportsmen and the military.
</P>
<P>
   The first collection of the new Burberry, for spring of this
year, was quietly introduced last September in the company's London
showroom. Although it wasn't shown on the runway with all the
hoopla that entails, the line took the fashion world by storm. Many
fashion magazines borrowed pieces to photograph, and retailers all
over the world bought the collection.
</P>
<P>
   In stores where once just a smattering of raincoats could be
found, there are now motorcycle jackets and trench coats in buttery
soft leather, jersey T-shirts and hip-slung skirts that bare the
midriff, motocross pants of stretch canvas with insets of leather,
ankle-length kilts without pleats, and plaid dresses of Irish linen
loomed on antique machines. Colors are mainly cool neutrals, with
touches of sky blue, mauve and a yellow inspired by a pair of the
Duke of Windsor's trousers.
</P>
<P>
   The first styles are now arriving in Burberry's stores, in
Bergdorf Goodman in New York, Jeffrey in Atlanta, Louis of Boston,
Joseph and Harrods in London, Colette in Paris, Joyce in Hong Kong
and Taiwan, Trois Pommes in Geneva and Zurich, and Club 21 in
Singapore. Barneys New York started selling the clothes last week
in its Madison Avenue and Beverly Hills stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a big commitment,'' said Judy Collinson, an executive
vice president of Barneys. ``Only 15 percent of the delivery is in
now, and the leather coats are already selling. The line has two
things we always love: beautiful, modern, amazing fabrics and the
old English sports tradition. The marriage of the two things has
been done beautifully. There's a lightheartedness to it, but the
quality is definitely there. We were so excited when we saw it in
London. It was something new and exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Boitano, the executive vice president of Bergdorf
Goodman, called the line ``very sophisticated, in its color palette
and styling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clean sportswear, with a bit of a twist, but still
keeping the Burberry concept,'' he said. ``It's very item-driven,
and that's very much how our customer shops these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The words of praise are music to Ms. Bravo's ears. Since she
left the presidency of Saks Fifth Avenue in October 1997 to
reinvent Burberry, she has hired designers, found new factories in
Italy, eliminated inappropriate licenses and set up a new band of
distributors, dropping those that were channeling goods into
discount stores in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning, just the DNA of the new
Burberry,'' she said last week in the women's department of the
Burberry store at 9 East 57th St. The first shipment of spring
clothes was hanging on racks, and nearby the new handbags and shoes
were on display.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Menichetti, the new Burberry team includes Eugenia
Ulasewicz, as president of retail and wholesale operations in the
United States; Michele Smith, as senior vice president for women's
wear; Robin Marino, as senior vice president for accessories, and
J. Stanley Tucker, as senior vice president for men's wear.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker is working on the men's-wear licenses, changing factories
to upgrade the line of suits and coats and adding more luxurious
fabrics. Meanwhile, Menichetti is designing the signature men's
collection, which will be made in Italy; it will be introduced next
July for the spring 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bravo decided to concentrate on the women's wear first, she
said, because it had no fashion image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burberry had a masculine image,'' she said. ``The women's was
anonymous. We felt we could make a big statement in the women's
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very fortunate in that Burberry has such a reputation
globally,'' she added. ``When you think of all the designers and
brands working so hard to build world recognition, and the Burberry
check is as recognizable as the Coca-Cola bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped the design staff from tinkering with the
classic plaid, making it bigger on certain fabrics and changing the
background color slightly. There are even two tone-on-tone plaids,
in beige and in dark blue, used so far only for handbags. There are
also sleek new leather shoulder bags that are molded to follow the
curve of the hips.
</P>
<P>
   The trench coat has been reinterpreted as a double-layered
dress, and the pleatless kilt is fashioned from two pieces that
wrap around the hips. There are knee-length and ankle-length
skirts, and blazers with a feminine cut.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Menichetti, who worked on Jil Sander's men's wear line for four
years, comes from a family of Italian fabric and clothing
manufacturers. When he went to Burberry last year, he immediately
began to build on its tradition of marrying fashion and function.
He worked closely with Italian mills to develop special fabrics,
because like Thomas Burberry, he believes that everything begins
with the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that he is Italian and Ms. Bravo is American,
they are committed to the Britishness of Burberry. ``When Roberto
and I first talked,'' Ms. Bravo said, ``he instantly understood
that the man of a certain taste, whether in Italy or Japan or
wherever, always had something by Burberry. We felt we could latch
on to that and go into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The path to the new Burberry hasn't been totally smooth. The
company's profits nose-dived 90 percent for the six months ending
last Sept. 30, mostly because of the economic problems in Asia,
which had been Burberry's biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debacle in Asia is complicated, of course,'' Ms. Bravo
said. ``We totally stopped parallel trading, where distributors
sent our products to discount stores. That was a big business, but
over a period of time it was deleterious to the brand. You'd have
products selling at regular price in a store on one side and at a
discounted price on the other side of the street. That detracts
from what we're trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much business was tied up in Asia. That will come back in
time. A lot of London business was from Asian travelers, and the
idea now is not to be so driven by the tourist trade. We want to
gear ourselves to the local audience, wherever our stores are.
Burberry has over 50 stores worldwide. We want to build Burberry
into an international luxury company with a British style and
sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Burberry's parent, Great Universal Stores, is a multifaceted
British company that is also in the mail-order business. Lord
Wolfson of Sunningdale is the chairman of Great Universal, and
Victor Barnett is the chairman of Burberry Ltd. They have both
given their blessings to the changes Ms. Bravo has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor and Roberto and I are working together to clean up and
develop the business,'' she said. ``One of our strategies is to
re-establish ourselves in the United States and London and have a
more balanced portfolio around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Bravo is doing is similar to what other old-line
fashion houses have been doing, starting with Karl Lagerfeld at
Chanel and continuing through Tom Ford at Gucci and, more recently,
John Galliano at Dior, Marc Jacobs at Louis Vuitton and Michael
Kors at Celine.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Burberry is to put the women's collection on
the London catwalks during the fall shows next month. Ms. Bravo
said she wasn't sure Burberry was ready to face the critics last
season. Now she is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
