<SLUG> BC-EURO-TRADING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS GET INTO THE EURO-SWING OF THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Euro-phoria'' struck European financial markets Monday as
investors gave a vote of confidence to a single currency during the
euro's trading debut on stock and currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the arrival of the economic and monetary union of
11 countries, stock markets on the continent rallied as investors
leaped to benefit from gains expected to flow from a stronger, more
competitive Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Spain each rose more than 6 percent. Germany's
blue-chip Xetra DAX rose 5.7 percent, hitting a four-month high.
</P>
<P>
   In currency markets, the euro had a slow but solid first day of
trading, strengthening slightly against the world's dominant
currency, the US dollar, and holding its own against the Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
   European Commission President Jacques Santer expressed
confidence that the euro, representing an economic bloc nearly as
big as the United States, would act as a counterweight on world
currency markets between the dollar and the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of our main goals,'' Santer said. ``The single
currency will be a credible currency accepted by international
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, evidence of the euro's power was suggested by lackluster
action on London's stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The FTSE-100 index was virtually flat Monday, and investors read
it as a message that countries, including the United Kingdom, that
declined to participate in the euro would be left behind. Britain,
one of Europe's biggest economies, has adamantly resisted political
pressures both inside and out to join the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's caution has merit. There is no assurance that early
euphoria surrounding the euro can continue to sustain markets.
Economists predict Europe's growth prospects are expected to slow
in 1999 because of turmoil in Asia and Russia. Certainly, the
long-term impact on 11 different countries of such an unprecedented
conversion of monetary systems is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   But markets bustled Monday with the prospects of integration of
a continent that had been ravaged by two world wars. ``I know the
importance of this currency. I know that it will make Europe move
forward,'' German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   All financial trades and noncash transactions are now being
conducted in euros. The currencies of the 11 unified countries _
Austria, Belgium, Ireland, Italy, Finland, France, Germany,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Spain, and Portugal _ are fixed
against the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors pushed up demand for stocks as they set
about buying shares of companies for index funds that track new
indexes based on companies in the 11 member countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail investors in Europe aren't as accustomed to equity
investments as we are in the US. They tend to prefer index'' funds
over stock-picking funds, said Jonathan Francis, head of global
strategy for Putnam Investments in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The single currency makes it much easier for investors to buy
and sell securities all over Europe without worry about the complex
conversions among the lira, the deutsche mark, the franc, and other
currencies _ and without the currency risks.
</P>
<P>
   The new Dow Jones Euro Stoxx index based on 50 companies in the
participating countries rose 6 percent, nearly double the 3.13
percent return to the Bloomberg Europe 500 index that tracks all of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest showings were in Italy and Spain: Stocks rose 6.44
percent and 6.21 percent, respectively. Germany and France, which
most forcefully pushed for a euro, had increases of 5.7 percent and
5.2 percent, respectively. Austria gained less than 1 percent and
Ireland gained 1.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, ``A very, very good day,'' said David Potts, a European
fund manager for London money manager Guinness Flight.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the significance of 11 industrial nations abolishing
their individual currencies, Potts concluded at the end of a day of
watching euro-market trades that it is ``beneficial for investors
and companies _ I'm convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   While the euro's value is set against European currencies, its
floats against other world currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The euro opened in Asia at a value of 1.17 dollars, peaked
during trading hours in Europe at just over 1.19, and ended Monday
firmly at 1.18 dollars in late-day trading in New York, according
to New York-based Independent Economic Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In trading against the yen, the euro opened at 133.15 yen in
Asia, peaked in Europe at 135.5, and settled back to 132.37 yen in
New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although trading was light, the euro had ``an auspicious
beginning,'' said Pierre Ellis, senior international economist for
the New York office of Primark Decision Economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good, because it was a business-as-usual day despite
the momentous event. The markets had prepared themselves. They saw
it coming and a lot of work that was done paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro may one day rival the US dollar. But US Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin said what was good for Europe was good for
the United States, though he acknowledged the euro would keep
Washington on its toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro just reemphasizes how important it is that we focus
on our own policies and continue to make the United States a place
where people want to invest their capital by having sound policies
here,'' Rubin told reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Experts concede, however, that strong European stock markets
_and economies _ depend most on continued US economic expansion.
``If the US slows down too much, the whole world will slump,'' said
David Lui, manager of the Strong International stock fund in
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions in London and around the world worked
long hours over the weekend to prepare for the euro. Many have set
up dual accounting systems to track transactions in two currencies
until investors get a feel for the value of the new currency and
become familiar with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's trading has largely been dominated by the checking of
systems in an actual trading environment,'' said Timothy Jarrett,
European currency analyst in the London office of Independent
Economic Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
