<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-KOBRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBRICK BIDS ADEIU TO CENDANT NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Money manager Frederick R. Kobrick thought he had a
match made in heaven when he joined with Cendant Corp. a year ago
to start a mutual fund firm. Months later, the unusual marriage
threatened to become a horror show, as Cendant, a marketing and
franchising giant, became a synonym for accounting fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Determined, Kobrick stuck it out, figuring that his partner's
marketing muscle and extensive lists of potential fund customers
far outweighed the image problem of cooked books.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick said Monday that he had axed the Cendant name from his
three mutual funds, formerly known as the Kobrick Cendant Funds.
While he won't say if he plans to dump Cendant as a
behind-the-scenes partner, the name change would appear to presage
a move in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting e-mails from the public about Cendant's role
in the funds,'' said Kobrick, who is chief executive and president
of Kobrick Funds. ``I didn't even see that people were thinking
that Cendant was involved in actually running the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsippany, N.J.-based Cendant owns about 70 percent of
Kobrick's fund firm, although most of the stake is in unexercised
options. Kobrick, a top money manager at State Street Research &AMP;
Management Co. in Boston before striking out on his own, built his
partnership with Cendant out of his close friendship with the
company's chief executive, Henry R. Silverman. The relationship
still stands, mostly because Kobrick thinks other Cendant
executives are to blame for the company's woes. Cendant shocked
Wall Street last April with revelations of accounting problems in
its membership division.
</P>
<P>
   With brands including Avis car rentals, hotel chains Howard
Johnson and Ramada, and real estate franchisee Century 21, Cendant
has reams of customer data and considerable marketing reach that
could prove a gold mine in the cutthroat investment business.
Kobrick's idea in teaming with Cendant was that a Ramada client
might eventually buy a Kobrick-run mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant never played a role in running Kobrick's three small
equity funds, which posted outstanding returns in 1998, their first
year of life, including a 50 percent gain by the $34.3 million
Kobrick Capital fund. The funds never owned any Cendant stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Kobrick-Cendant marriage was highly unusual for the fund
industry, where independent money managers typically form alliances
with traditional financial services companies, such as banks or
insurers. Still, some observers aren't sure that dumping the
Cendant name will translate into a sales fillip at Kobrick. Russell
J. Kinnel, equity funds editor at Morningstar Inc., said most
mutual funds were a tough sell in their first year, since they
lacked a performance record to tout.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick may have dumped his partner's name, but he hasn't
forsaken its stock. His $100 million hedge fund, separate from the
mutual funds, doubled its stake in Cendant to 2 percent of assets
last year when the company nose dived on Wall Street. The
reasoning? ``I expect them to have a big year,'' Kobrick said.
``They've got the wind in their back now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
