</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL, SAYING TEAM HAS COME TOGETHER, LOOKS TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ With plans to attend the Senior Bowl and the
Scouting Combine, Pete Carroll sounded like a man who assumes he is
going to be coach of the New England Patriots next season.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll addressed the team in a fairly long meeting at Foxboro
Stadium Monday, telling his players he wants them to be in top
shape by making a commitment to the offseason conditioning program.
He also spoke in a press conference on a number of issues,
including the progress of younger players, the solid work he
thought his assistants did, and the personnal evaluations that he,
Bobby Grier, and Andy Wasynczuk will make.
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk, the vice president of business operations, said the
process will take about three weeks. Whether a decision on
Carroll's fate takes that long remains to be seen, but for now he
is trying to leave no doubt that he is the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be of great interest to all of you about my job
status,'' said Carroll. ``All I will say is we're going onward.
We're together. The statements Robert (Kraft) made Monday about
those rumors being `hogwash' I think cleared that up. There's been
a lot of talk, rumor about this and that. It was a problem and a
distraction early last week, though we've learned to overcome
those, so we move on. There's no questions to be answered about
that. We're moving into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``To finish after the first round is not what we had in mind.
What came out of the season was a strong sense of what this team is
all about. When you find the connection of being really tight and
being together, not allowing yourself to be split regardless of
where the influences come from, you accomplish some special things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accomplished some things this year, against some odds, that
we can build from, something to move into the future. The ability
to win big games under adversity, duress, and sometimes against
odds, are things we can take with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special plays by players in backup roles were the kinds of
things we take out of this season. Most of the good stories had to
do with courage and overcoming pain because of their commitment to
their teammates. I'm proud that comes from this team. We added to
the foundation of our teams of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew (Bledsoe) emerged this season. It's quite obvious that
the players are committed to him. If you look at the teams who are
in the playoffs, you see those kinds of players leading their
clubs, and our guy has arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the Patriots will head into next season with a
strong nucleus, but added, ``We have to have everybody playing
every week.'' He said there's a ``separation between the quality
players and those who fill in. We have to shrink that gap. We have
to plug in a great player here and there, but we need to stay
together and be healthy. When the chambers are filled, we're as
tough as any team you can go against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are likely to look at free agents this winter,
perhaps at the receiver spot.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll also said the team must deal better with the pressures
of media scrutiny in Boston, calling it a ``force that goes on
outside of your club. You have to stay on track and continue to
stay focused. That comes from maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning his assistants, one or two of whom will likely be
replaced, he said, ``These guys worked their tails off. They were
faced with difficult situations week in and week out with personnel
and also preparing for the tremendous competition we played
against. I thought they did a tremendous job. I'm very proud of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said the Patriots must work on mistakes like too many
men on the field, procedure penalties, and clock management. On the
first play of Sunday's season-ending playoff loss in Jacksonville,
tight end Rod Rutledge was called for an illegal procedure penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was on the charts for several days and one guy got
whacked out and he shouldn't have been on the field,'' said
Carroll. ``The wrong guy left the field because the wrong guy was
out there. If it's recurring, you have to get rid of him. If it's
the same guy, you can fix it; if it's a different guy, you have to
look into why it's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll made it a personal goal to develop younger players, an
area in which he thinks he made progess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a philosophy that we need to develop our younger
talent,'' said Carroll. ``I'd match the playing time of our younger
guys against anyone in the league. We were forced to play them and
we brought them along.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the age of free agency, you have to get something out of
your young players because four or five years down the road, you
might not be able to re-sign them. There are teams in the league
who are trying to win with older players. We need a mixture, a
combination of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the comment today. I thought the group did a very good
job _ Robert (Edwards), Tebucky (Jones), Chris Floyd, Greg Spires,
Rod Rutledge, Tony Simmons started a bunch of games. We got
accustomed to having a rookie starting at wide receiver. Because of
the playing they got this year, it's going to pay off in Year 2 and
3. They're going to make first-time mistakes. They're going to be
on the field at the wrong times, but eventually we'll eliminate
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In evaluating himself, Carroll said, ``I plan to grow and get
better. You get more clearly atuned to what's necessary. It's a
very big job and there are a lot of areas to grow. I'd like to see
my perspective adjusted from one year to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to suggestions that his team is not disciplined,
Carroll said, ``How do you judge discipline? It seems you people
judge by slapping hands with the rulers. Look at George Seifert. I
don't care what label you put on it, he's the winningest coach in
NFL history. But you would never consider him the guy you're
thinking of. He's just the winningest coach who ever lived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
