<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-TEAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL URGES TEAM TO MAINTAIN OFF-SEASON CONDITIONING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Patriots-Carroll)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bob Kraft said Sunday that he wants Pete
Carroll to be more assertive in the manner in which he handles his
team and his players. Kraft didn't come out and say Carroll
definitely will get that chance with the Patriots, but the coach
seemed to begin the process Monday when he addressed the players,
warning them to be in the ``best shape of their lives'' when they
return next season or risk losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the one player who should have been listening
wasn't there. Terry Glenn was back home in Columbus, Ohio, healing
from a broken ankle, when Carroll spoke of each and every player
making a commitment to the offseason conditioning program under
Johnny Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a big statement about the commitment to the
offseason,'' said Carroll. ``It has to be one that brings us back
in the best shape of these players' lives. If they don't do that,
they've sold out themselves and they've sold out on us. So there'll
be a directed commitment to the offseason than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll obviously felt that the conditioning of the team wasn't
top-shelf, particularly with 16 starters succumbing to injuries
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done either by incentives or threats,'' said Carroll.
``You can make sense to them or you can threaten them. We tried to
make sense to these guys. Guys have lives that take them away from
this. In that case, we do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Carroll did get Ben Coates to take part in the
program for the first time, something Bill Parcells never was able
to accomplish. Veterans Bruce Armstrong, Henry Thomas, and Todd
Collins also do not take part, and there was no indication that
will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make them come,'' said Carroll. ``You can't have
mandatory camp at this time in the offseason. We have incentive
programs, we have incentives of maintaining their job position. We
can threaten their jobs and put pressure on them and make them
understand that if they take part in the program under Johnny
Parker, they'll be in great shape and ready for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want more participation than last year, and if we do that,
we'll have as much participation as any team in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's previous team, the San Francisco 49ers, had just
average participation in its offseason program yet has been very
successful year in and year out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were very few veterans, a lot of rookies, and some free
agents who'd show for it,'' recalled Carroll. ``We have veteran
players who took it upon themselves to get ready for the start of
the season. There was a great deal of pride in their individual
conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   No amount of offseason conditioning program can prevent all
injuries, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn reportedly worked out on his own but keeps getting hurt.
Armstrong didn't take part in the Parker program yet made it
through the year healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Wasynczuk, the team's vice president of business
operations, said he has stepped up the workout bonuses in contracts
over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some take advantage of it and some don't,'' said Wasynczuk.
``By doing it, we stress to the player the importance of being in
shape and what our program can mean for them. We understand that
not everyone will take advantage of it, but by inserting a bonus
clause we certainly give them an indication of how serious we are
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk was asked who is responsible for making sure the
players take the workouts seriously. Is it Parker, who has come out
and taken responsibility for the disappointing turnout? Is is
Carroll? Is is Bobby Grier, as the personnel man? Or is it
Wasynczuk, who puts the incentives in the contracts?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's everyone doing their part to stress it,'' said
Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was more participation under Parcells than
Carroll, Wasynczuk said, ``I can't recall the actual numbers. I
don't think it's far off.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, Coates, and William Roberts were among those who
didn't show up under the Parcells regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get everybody on the same page with this,'' said
Chad Eaton. ``I'm coming back in February and I'll be here the rest
of the time working out. I need that. I need it to get better and
to get to the next level of my game. Guys like Bruce, Ben, and
Henry are proven guys. They come to play every year. But there are
guys, like Terry, who need to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
