<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN RE-ELECTION MAY HINGE ON MUNI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, just days into a re-election
year, has already drawn a challenge, if not a challenger:
convincing tens of thousands of regular Municipal Railway
passengers that he's not all talk and no action.
</P>
<P>
   Brown won his office in December 1995 by hammering the incumbent
over San Francisco's dysfunctional transit agency and promising the
city a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, however, Muni's core riders _ about 84,000,
if measured by monthly Fast Pass sales _ still register broad
dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent voters are expressing discontent (with the mayor
in polls), Muni is one of the things they seize on,'' said
Supervisor Michael Yaki, a close Brown ally. ``His election, in
part, is going to be a referendum on how people feel about Muni in
November, rather than how they feel about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   That view _ that Brown is in trouble with a sizable pool of
voters but still has time to improve his standing _ is driving the
mayor's moves at the Municipal Railway.
</P>
<P>
   It explains why Brown is asked the Board of Supervisors on
Tuesday to give final approval to a new round of spending to put an
international management consultant, Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton, in
charge of the Muni Metro system through the fall mayoral election.
</P>
<P>
   It also raises the stakes on his choice of a successor to
departing Muni General Manager Emilio Cruz, who leaves this month
for a private sector job after 2-and-1/2 years at the agency's
helm.
</P>
<P>
   Muni, under Brown's tenure, has been marked by fatter budgets
and increased equipment purchases as well as staggering service
disruptions, safety shortcomings and disciplinary lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, many political observers say Brown's
handling of the agency is unlikely to cost him re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown is not the kind of guy who, because of a job
ratings sag, you start to count him out,'' said Examiner pollster
Brad Coker, citing the mayor's 14-year run as speaker of the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is a consistent frustration among voters with
Muni service. But incumbency is a powerful force in the hands of
someone who knows how to use it to set the agenda,'' said Coker,
president of Maryland-based Mason-Dixon Political Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's political savvy aside, the pollster's survey results are
cause for concern for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In an Examiner poll published a year ago, Brown's rating among
city voters dipped below 50 percent for the first time, with 67
percent expressing dissatisfaction with Muni.
</P>
<P>
   By September, the figure for Muni worsened; 71 percent gave it
an unfavorable rating. And the mayor's grade sank too, with 41
percent saying he is doing a good or excellent job, down from 46
percent nine months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A Chamber of Commerce poll of city voters in May showed how
familiarity with Muni breeds contempt. According to the survey, 63
percent of riders who take Muni once a month or so are satisfied
with it, compared with 52 percent of those who ride weekly and only
35 percent of daily riders.
</P>
<P>
   The low-water mark coincided generally with the so-called Muni
meltdown _ the tumultuous service disruptions the week of Aug. 22
that accompanied the launch of a new metro train-control system.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's response to that cataclysm _ an initiative dubbed the
Muni Recovery Project _ is designed as much to reverse the
political damage as it is to put transit service permanently on
track.
</P>
<P>
   Focused exclusively on the metro _ five subway and streetcar
lines carrying 125,000 weekday passengers, or 18 percent of Muni
riders _ the plan's linchpin is outside management expertise from
Virginia-based consultant Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Under its contract, Booz Allen is supposed to retrain metro
employees to better use the new computer-based Advanced Train
Control System and more quickly address streetcar breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also calls for Booz Allen to increase the number of
streetcars available to Muni each morning by developing better
maintenance at yards housing Muni's new line of Italian-designed
vehicles by Breda Construzione Ferroviarie. A retrofit campaign
aimed at the system's old Boeing-built cars also is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   If Booz Allen meets performance targets by August and keeps to
them through December _ after the city elects a mayor _ the company
qualifies for a 20 percent bonus. It would take the contract's
value from $4.4 million to $5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki, chairman of the supervisors' Transportation Committee,
said the recovery project carries its own political risks for
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one variable in this entire equation is whether Muni can
execute the decisions Booz Allen makes,'' Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The mayor is rolling the dice on this one. A number
of us are going to put our money down on the mayor and the fact
that the way the project is conceived has the best potential for
offering fast improvements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1907EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
