<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROGRAMS-HNS &LR;      01-04 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROGRAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANNOUNCES $6.5 BILLION HEALTH CARE PROPOSAL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the holidays over and an impeachment trial
pending, President Clinton returned to work Monday by announcing a
new legislative proposal to help people in need of long-term health
care.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of many likely announcements this month as the
White House prepares its 1999 agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is keeping with his tradition of using January to offer
glimpses of his legislative priorities contained in his State of
the Union address and in his budget proposal for the 2000 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, meanwhile, remained in a quandary over how to
proceed on a trial for Clinton who was impeached by the House in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this new year gives us all a sense of making a fresh
start, a sense of being able to think anew. It should also give us
a sense of rededication,'' Clinton told invited guests who heard
him unveil a five-year, $6.5 billion plan for $1,000 tax credits to
either patients or caregivers providing long-term health care.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day leading up to the Jan. 19 State of the Union
speech, Clinton will make some announcement. He will release his
budget Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The White House proposals likely will contrast sharply with the
effort by some Republicans to remove Clinton from office with a
trial in the Senate on charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The plan announced by Clinton calls for either the patient or a
family caregiver to receive a $1,000 tax credit based on long-term
health care. It would create a national network for family
caregiver support where the helper can access community resources
and include a national education campaign for Medicare
beneficiaries on their long-term care options. It would make the
federal government the largest employer to offer long-term health
care insurance to its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no single solution to the challenges of care giving,
but together these initiatives represent a powerful first step to
force the kind of challenges we need in our society,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined in the White House's Grand Foyer by first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and several members of Congress. Vice
President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, appeared by satellite to
also trumpet the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why the president is at 70 percent (approval
rating) and the Congress is at 30 percent is that he is the only
one who is not talking about impeachment,'' said Rep. James Moran,
D-Va., who attended the White House announcement on aide for
long-term medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what people care about. This proposal is going to
address that. I think it does have a chance in Congress and I do
think it represents the reason why the president is faring a heck
of a lot better than the Congress is,'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republican Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania complemented
Clinton for keeping his eye on legislative priorities. ``I think
that it's very important that we conduct business as usual. I was
with him, as you know, when he went to Israel, and I think he did a
good job there. And he's moving ahead with the business of the
country,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, who attended the White House announcement, also said he
differed from some of his Republican colleagues who have suggested
Clinton postpone his State of the Union address to a joint session
of Congress. ``I think we ought to keep the business of the country
going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton has every
intention of keeping the date for his speech despite calls from
critics that he wait until after the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has important work that he's doing and he looks
forward to presenting it to the country,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also said the daily announcements were not intended to
detract attention from the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all you have to do is go back to the stories you did
this time last year and the year before, and you'll find that we
traditionally use this time to try to generate public support for
some of the ideas that the president will have in his State of the
Union and the budget,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we could have been smart enough a year ago
December to have worked out a strategy to help deal with the Monica
Lewinsky issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House continued to talk privately to
members of the Senate to see how a trial will proceed. A trial,
only the second for a president in the nation's history, could
begin as early as next week. There is a dispute among Republicans
over whether it should be a short hearing or whether it should be
longer and if the Senate should hear from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton's attorneys would be ready to proceed with
a trial as early as Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
