<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODMORNING-TV-SHAKEU     01-04 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODMORNING-TV-SHAKEUP-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANE SAWYER TO BE CO-ANCHOR OF MORNING SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `e' category) 
(lb) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that underscored how far the fortunes of
``Good Morning America'' have fallen, and how much that hurts the
fortunes of the ABC television network and its stations, ABC News
on Monday plucked one of its biggest stars, Diane Sawyer, from the
firmament of prime-time news and named her co-anchor of the morning
show, where she will be paired with Charles Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was co-anchor of ``Good Morning America'' for 11 years
until last May, when he left the show to Kevin Newman and Lisa
McRee, who had replaced Joan Lunden a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The new anchor pairing will be interim, but indefinite, said
David Westin, the president of ABC News, and will begin Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sawyer, who will retain her twice-weekly role as co-anchor
for the news magazine ``20/20,'' said she envisioned her morning
role as lasting ``a few months, but we're not trying to put a
number on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The move came after a long slide in the program's ratings. Once
the premier show in morning television, it lost its lead to NBC's
``Today Show'' in 1995. Since then it has declined precipitously in
the Nielsen ratings, losing more than a quarter of its audience in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   The morning shows are the most profitable news programs for ABC
and NBC. Year-end figures are not yet available, but estimates
compiled by Nielsen from network and advertising agency figures
show that for the first half of 1998, ``Today'' earned about $117
million for NBC, a unit of General Electric, while ``Good Morning
America'' earned about $77 million for ABC, a unit of Walt Disney
Co.
</P>
<P>
   But these programs are also vital to each network's owned and
affiliated stations. They split advertising time 50-50 with the
network (while the show costs them almost nothing), and the show
helps lead viewers to the rest of a station's morning programming.
</P>
<P>
   Westin acknowledged that ABC's stations had been pressuring the
network to fix whatever was wrong with ``GMA,'' as it is nicknamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make a very dramatic move,'' Westin said.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, the ``Today'' show averaged a 5.3 rating, while ``Good
Morning America'' averaged a 3.0 rating, with each rating point
representing 994,000 homes. ``CBS This Morning,'' the other morning
show, averaged a 2.3 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The move was so dramatic that it stunned the pair's ABC News
colleagues, who regard Ms. Sawyer as one of the stars of prime-time
news, and Gibson as having finally escaped from an early-morning
duty at which he had served long enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one really needs this in their career right now,''
said Westin. ``But Charlie is deeply committed to the `Good Morning
America' franchise, and Diane is being a very loyal colleague and
stepping up to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sawyer co-hosted the morning show for CBS News in the early
1980s, before joining ``60 Minutes'' and then moving to ABC. She
said she would now cut back on assignments requiring travel, but
otherwise planned ``to be fully part of the `20-20' team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll just have to give me a lot of extra makeup for under
my eyes,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until this fall Ms. Sawyer and Sam Donaldson had co-anchored
their own news magazine, ``Prime Time Live,'' on Wednesday nights.
It was renamed ``20/20'' and joined that franchise, with Friday
nights anchored by Barbara Walters and Hugh Downs and Sunday nights
anchored by Ms. Walters and Ms. Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues who insisted on anonymity pointed out that in the
ego-driven world of prime-time news, Ms. Sawyer had been unhappy
about ``Prime Time Live'' being subsumed into ``20/20,'' which was
long identified with Ms. Walters, and that the ``GMA'' role gives
her a fresh and prominent identity, apart from Ms. Walters. It is
also flattering, they said, to be regarded by top management as the
potential savior of a show that is financially vital to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sawyer excused herself early from Monday's telephone news
conference to catch a plane, and had no further comment. Gibson had
just been named co-anchor, with Connie Chung, of the latest edition
of ``20/20,'' on Monday nights, starting Feb. 1. He said Monday he
would do that but would reduce the number of pieces he reported.
</P>
<P>
   Westin and both anchors said that no extra compensation or
contract revisions had been made to induce the pair to take the new
roles.
</P>
<P>
   But two of Ms. Sawyer's favorite producers were chosen to run
``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Ross, who recently produced Ms. Sawyer's exclusive
interview with Ken Starr, the independent counsel prosecuting
President Clinton, was named executive producer of the show,
replacing Shelley Lewis. And Phyllis McGrady, who had been
executive producer of ``Prime Time Live'' for four years until it
was folded into ``20/20,'' will be the ABC News management
executive supervising the show.
</P>
<P>
   Westin said that ABC News management, which has included him for
20 months, was to blame for the swift decline at ``Good Morning
America,'' and that he did not expect recovery ``overnight.'' He
said his two goals were to restore the program's ``core identity,''
which he said means a warmer, more familylike show, and will groom
contributors for the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Today'' show has been successful at gradually acclimating
its viewers to new talent, both anchors and news readers. Matt
Lauer, who replaced Bryant Gumbel as co-anchor with Katie Couric in
1997, filled in as an anchor for almost one-third of the previous
year's shows before taking over.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Newman came from almost total obscurity as an ABC
News correspondent, and Ms. McRee was a Los Angeles local news
anchor when she replaced Ms. Lunden. Westin said Ms. McRee would
become a correspondent based in Los Angeles, in part because she is
expecting her first child next summer and her husband lives there.
</P>
<P>
   Newman will become a correspondent for ABC News' ``Nightline''
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
