<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINN-VENTURA-BOS &LR;      01-04 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-VENTURA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA TAKES OATH; FACES HUGE CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL _ In his Harley Davidson jacket and matching
sweatpants, John Einfeldt figured he'd fit right in Monday at the
improbable inauguration of former pro wrestler Jesse Ventura as
Minnesota's 38th governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Einfeldt had to sneak in a back door of the museum-like
state Capitol building, past the uniformed guards, past the Navy
honor guard, past the men in suits, past the well-coiffed ladies in
demure dresses and polished pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got all the biker votes, but man, I don't see too many of
us here,'' said Einfeldt, peeking out from behind a massive stone
pillar.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Ventura tries to make the leap from a dimple-chinned
curiousity of national proportions to an effective political
leader, Einfeldt's uncomfortable realization underscored the twin
challenges facing a new governor who has traded biker leathers for
sober business attire.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, political analysts and historians say, Ventura must
appeal to the elites who packed the State House Monday, as well as
the majority of Minnesotans who voted for the two major-party
politicians Ventura defeated as a Reform Party candidate. And yet,
if he goes too far to appease them, he risks alienating people like
Einfeldt, hundreds of whom lined up outside the State House to
shake Ventura's beefy hand after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ventura seemed to recognize the challenge ahead.
After taking the oath of office under a soaring marble dome, the
47-year-old governor pledged to his supporters in his
gravel-and-whiskey voice: ``I'm not changing.'' Then he tried to
wrap his huge arms around the rest of the state, including a Senate
controlled by the Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party, and a House run by
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put down the partisan party politics and look at the
bigger picture. We must look at the picture of these young people
who have now come on board,'' he said. ``We cannot fail. We must
not fail. Because if we do, we could lose this generation, and we
dare not let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his most specific message in a brief, rambling,
plain-spoken, extemporaneous address that echoed the stump speech
of his man-of-the-people campaign. Beyond his call for unity,
Ventura made no promise more ambitious than to be honest, work hard
and ``do what's right for the people of Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment at least, that was enough to win him a rousing
ovation from his family, friends, former Navy buddies and pal
Arnold Schwarzenegger, with whom he starred in the films
``Predator'' and ``The Running Man.'' How long the honeymoon will
last, however, was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventura finds himself in a paradox. He ran against the
establishment, and now he is the establishment,'' said Hy Berman,
history professor at the University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to stick to one's guns and be an effective
governor,'' Berman added.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Boyte, director of the Center for Democracy and
Citizenship at the University of Minnesota's Humphrey Institute of
Public Affairs, said Ventura will be judged in large part on how
well he translates his populist appeal into genuine ``citizen
engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a really funny view of politics. They want to be
involved, but they don't have high hopes,'' Boyte said. He compared
voters' feelings toward Ventura to locals' relationship with the
Minnesota Vikings, a team with the best record in football but
uncertain playoff prospects. ``People love how well they're doing,
but they're not quite true believers yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs the Ventura style is winning converts. A
December poll found 69 percent of Minnesotans thought he was doing
a good or excellent job preparing for the office, and 46 percent
said they would support him if another election were held that day.
That was a notable improvement from the 37 percent Ventura received
in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really want him to do well,'' said US Sen. Paul
Wellstone, a Minnesota Democrat who attended the inauguration.
``There's an enormous reservoir of good will and good feeling,
which is a Minnesota political ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Ventura has raised eyebrows in recent  &UR; week &LR; s by
signing a six-figure book deal, accepting corporate sponsorships
for his inaugural and considering plans to license an action figure
based on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even more importantly, he has recently taken a go-slow approach
on a key to his campaign victory: a promise to return to taxpayers
an estimated $3.3 billion state surplus. Such caution drew a muted
protest from the Taxpayers League of Minnesota. Beyond them,
however, it was hard to find anyone Monday who didn't claim to be
among the earliest supporters from mid-1997, when Ventura held
strategy sessions in the barn where his wife Teresa runs a horse
business.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview before the swearing-in, Ventura admitted to
``some butterflies'' then stressed he would not bend too far to
please anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too bullheaded to even try. It's going to be the same
Jesse,  &UR; today &LR;  and always,'' he said. When asked to view the day in
wrestling terms, he said, ``I can't. . .I'm looking to the future,
not the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the five other state officials sworn in Monday, Ventura
did not utter his name as part of the oath. It had been a matter of
some local speculation whether he would use Ventura, his stage
name, or his legal name, James Janos.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura once said he would arrive at his inauguration as
governor by helicopter, then rappel down the capitol's ornate dome.
That plan was nixed when his aides feared Ventura would be swept
like a kite by the winter winds and end up impaled on the arm of a
golden maiden perched just below the dome.
</P>
<P>
   And so, he came by Lincoln Town Car.
</P>
<P>
   The change of heart and transport epitomized his evolution and
political education _ from campaigner to governor, from Jesse ``The
Body'' Ventura of his old wrestling life to Jesse ``The Mind''
Ventura in his new role.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the inauguration was nothing like the predictions of
Garry Trudeau, whose ``Doonesbury'' comic strip spent more than a
 &UR; week &LR;  spoofing Ventura with suggestions that it would be ``total
insanity.'' In one strip, a drug-befuddled character whom Trudeau
imagined organizing the festivities pledged: ``Our citizens will be
running buck wild through the streets!''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen Monday, though there was still time for such
revelry: Inaugural events will continue through Jan. 15, when a
come-as-you-are ``People's Celebration'' will take the place of a
traditional inaugural ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
