<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEW-WASSERMAN-HNS &LR;      01-04 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEW-WASSERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEW WASSERMAN: HOLLYWOOD'S ULTIMATE DEALMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVIN BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis McDougal wasn't particularly surprised by the recent
bloodletting at Universal Studios. What goes around comes around,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal is the author of ``The Last Mogul,'' a long, withering
look at the life and times of Lew Wasserman, former head of the
Music Corporation of America and Universal Studios. At the
beginning of December McDougal read about Edgar Bronfman Jr. firing
Universal Studios chairman Frank Biondi Jr. and head of movie
production Casey Silver _ after having given four other top execs
the boot earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal pointed out that 60 years ago Bronfman's grandfather,
Sam _ future head of the Seagram's empire _ was providing liquor to
the Mayfair Casino in Cleveland, which employed a young publicist
named Lew R. Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bronfman did in three years time, in spite of the
promises he made when he walked in the door, was clean house,''
said McDougal. ``One of the great ironies of the whole Wasserman
story is that a guy who got his start in a Cleveland night club
ultimately loses the studio he worked so hard to get 60 years later
... to the grandson of the Canadian rum-rummer who supplied that
night club with booze.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman, 85, is left with the title of board chairman emeritus
and an estate _ built across a lifetime of cut-throat dealing _
that's valued at more than $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   He would've traded a lot of that money, said McDougal, for more
of a say in what happened to Universal. But the stock deal
Wasserman cut with Mitsushita of Japan in 1992 left him helpless
when Mitsushita turned around and sold Universal to the liquor
giant, Seagram's, in 1995. And there's some irony in that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz, once seen by Wasserman as successor to the
throne, engineered the Seagram's deal without Wasserman's OK. ``The
quiet necromancer in the Seagram-Matsushita deal turned out to be
Lew's own best student,'' McDougal writes in ``The Last Mogul.''
``Just as Lew might have done in an earlier era, Ovitz put a ready
seller and willing buyer together.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other ironies in the Wasserman story, said McDougal,
including the fact that Wasserman's deal-making skills deteriorated
into a series of movie miscalculations.
</P>
<P>
   He thought ``American Graffiti'' and ``Deer Hunter'' would both
be busts, approved box-office clunkers like ``Skullduggery'' while
the studio was $40 million in the red, and on three separate
occasions turned down a $25,000 request to front the making of
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman is credited with bailing Robert Mitchum out of jail
after his marijuana arrest, getting Lana Turner back on the screen
after the murder of Johnny Stampanato, and for movies like
``Operation Petticoat,'' Doris Day's series of bedroom farces,
including ``Pillow Talk'' and ``That Touch of Mink,'' and the
steady growth of game-show, simpleton TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio's saving grace throughout the Wasserman years was
television,'' said McDougal. ``They sucked off millions in
television production funds over the three decades Wasserman ran
Universal.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Most motion pictures Universal produced under the
Wasserman-Sid Sheinberg reign were crap.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another irony, said McDougal _ how the Japanese buyout
of Universal coincided with the end of the both the Wasserman era
and the mob's dwindling infuence in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The former Los Angeles Times reporter and author of ``Fatal
Subtraction: How Hollywood Really Does Business,'' makes no bones
about the ties between organized crime and the movie industry in
the years when Wasserman was rising to power at MCA and Universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the high-water point for mob influence was probably
the mid-'40s, although it persisted well into the 1960s,'' said
McDougal. ``Ironically, it didn't die, I don't believe, until the
Japanese invasion of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were interested in was the bottom line, so payoffs,
bribes, the under-the-table deals and all the other gimmicks that
kept relations cozy between the mob, the Teamsters and the
Hollywood studios were simply unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman had moved from Chicago to Hollywood in 1938 when the
head of MCA, Jules Stein, decided the movie industry was going to
be a fountain of money. Both men, cashing in on the American dream
during prohibition, were weaned on a world spilling over with
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's monopoly control of orchestras during the Big Band era
smacked of mob funding, while Wasserman _ who came to MCA straight
from the Mayfair Casino _ never shook the image that he owed his
Hollywood power to the men with big cigars.
</P>
<P>
   But Wasserman really owed his steady rise to his ability to
wheel and deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lew Wasserman was the genius of the deal,'' he said. ``He
could bring two or more disparate parties together at a conference
table and walk away with a deal everybody was happy with, at least
at the moment. And Lew still got to keep his 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wasserman could in McDougal's words be an ``autocratic
ass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where he screwed up was when he decided to be a filmmaker,
when he started believing his own PR ... that he was, in fact, the
King of Hollywood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman's mantra as an agent was simple, McDougal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep in mind at all times that people are less
important than the deal. Your loyalties first and foremost must
always be to yourself, then to the agency, and only after both
those loyalties have been met, to the client,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wasserman's leadership, the MCA empire grew to be worth
$1.3 billion by 1980.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of money didn't go unnoticed by politicians. Bill
Clinton has visited Wasserman's home more than once and Senator
Dianne Feinstein read a proclamation into the Congressional Record
praising him on his 80th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dennis McDougal covered Hollywood for more than a decade for
the Los Angeles Times. He has written ``Angel of Darkness,''
``Mother's Day,'' ``In the Best of Families,'' and ``Fatal
Subtraction: How Hollywood Really Does Business.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
