<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-WEDDINGS-ART-     01-04 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-WEDDINGS-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KWAMBONAMBI, South Africa: whole generation.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Ms. Mkhwanazi's and Mthembu's first ceremony was pretty
much a standard church wedding with more than 100 guests, the
following day was altogether different. Early in the morning, the
cow was slaughtered in the Mthembu family's cattle pen, where the
men gathered to do the skinning and butchering while the women were
up the hill, cooking over an open fire. Representatives of the
bride's family watched, making sure that they got the right pieces
of meat and singing as the gifts were handed over.
</P>
<P>
   The bride arrived in the afternoon, and after the skirmish over
her attire retired her to change three times behind a blanket her
bridesmaids held up for her. After that her family toured the
Mthembu property with her hope chest, symbolically introducing her
to the ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Then the two families gathered in a wide circle and the men
danced, in Zulu warrior dress. Afterwards, an exchange of presents
began. Many of the groom's family were called forward to accept
presents from the bride _ often blankets and mats that were tried
out on the spot. Those who got gifts sang or danced their thanks.
</P>
<P>
   The last to get gifts was the groom. In a playful skit, designed
to tell him that he could be in trouble if he did not treat the
bride well, he too was given a mat and a blanket. But his blanket
is thrown over his head and the bride's friends quickly descended
on him, beating him with sticks until he could get away.
</P>
<P>
   The bride, 32 and the groom, 33, met when they were still in
high school in 1985 and he decided she would be his wife when they
were both in college, he said. A brother and a close friend began
negotiating a bride price for him in 1994, but the wedding was
delayed because of deaths in the family.
</P>
<P>
   The groom was taken aback at the western custom of proposing to
a woman on bended knee. He said he simply told his future wife he
was going to negotiate for her, and ``she was happy because I had
four or five girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what makes weddings so expensive is the traditional
bride payments, called lobola. This, too, is under attack these
days as some South African women say it encourages the men to feel
they have bought their wives and therefore can abuse them.
</P>
<P>
   But many surveys have found that there is still wide support for
lobola. Ms. Mkhwanazi and Mthembu both said they believe in it. The
groom said he had gained respect for his wife in having to pay to
marry her. The price is always denoted in cows, though these days
it is often paid in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you talk in terms of cows,'' he said. ``Then you say,
`You know we don't have any cows, so let's talk about money now.'
And then you are talking about how many cheap cows and so on.'' A
typical price for a bride is about 11 cows or nearly $3,000, a sum
that could take the average working South African years to save.
Women are worth more if they are the daughters of chiefs or have
education.
</P>
<P>
   Lobola was once an insurance policy in case the marriage broke
up. The cows were held by the bride's family and multiplied as the
years went by. They would help support her and her children if a
divorce occurred. But these days, when it is often cash that is
paid to the bride's parents, it is usually spent long before any
breakup. Ms. Mkhwanazi's family gave her some of the money to buy
her wedding dress and some gifts for the Mthembu family, but often
this does not happen.
</P>
<P>
   The groom is not finished paying when he has paid the lobola.
There are several more ceremonies, including one at which members
of the bride's family get to ask for gifts such as a new suit, a
leather jacket or a washing machine. During this exchange _ which
fills one of the newly married couple's photo albums _ the groom is
given a sheep or a goat to symbolize his acceptance into the
bride's family.
</P>
<P>
   One picture shows a woolly sheep standing in the middle of the
couple's tidy, modern living room.
</P>
</TEXT>
