<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS BEGIN JOCKEYING FOR POSITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the dawning of a new millennium is prompting
some frightened souls to seek cover, it has not scared off the
politicians already lining up to be the first president elected in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   With the presidential primaries more than a year away, a gaggle
of Republicans and a handful of Democrats have already indicated or
are strongly hinting they will seek their party's nomination for
the nation's top political job.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering accelerated Monday with announcements or
near-announcements by several serious candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, a former Cabinet member in two Republican
administrations, announced she was stepping down as head of the
American Red Cross to pursue other options, including a possible
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this important time in our national life, I believe there
may be another way for me to serve our country,'' Dole told
colleagues in a packed hall at Red Cross headquarters, just down
the street from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although she did not make direct mention of any political
aspirations in her 15-minute speech, the wife of 1996 Republican
presidential nominee Bob Dole later told reporters that she would
give ``serious consideration'' to a White House race.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Arizona Sen. John McCain, a former prisoner of war in
Vietnam and maverick lawmaker who championed campaign finance
reform and anti-tobacco legislation, announced he was forming a
committee to explore a presidential bid. McCain is expected to make
his decision in a few weeks, said Howard Opinsky, a San
Antonio-based GOP consultant working for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, a little-known
Republican lawmaker best known for his opposition to abortion, said
he was filing as candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the bell has rung,'' said Republican consultant
Charles Black, who worked on Texas Sen. Phil Gramm's failed
presidential effort in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With no incumbent seeking re-election and no heir apparent on
the Republican side, the 2000 race for the White House is expected
to be highly competitive.
</P>
<P>
   And political experts such as Black say that potential
candidates need to be campaigning early to raise the estimated $20
million necessary to run a credible primary race.
</P>
<P>
   If Dole decides to run, she will likely face an expensive and
tough primary fight with a number of other high-profile
Republicans, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush and the man who
served as vice president to Bush's father, Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidential candidate and wealthy magazine publisher
Steve Forbes, who attracted voters with his flat-tax mantra in
1996, is now actively wooing social conservatives by opposing
abortion and promoting morality.
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran from the 1996 campaign, Lamar Alexander, the
former Tennessee governor and U.S. education secretary, has also
been working Republican primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   And a host of other figures, including conservative activists
Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes, commentator Pat Buchanan, and House
Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich of Ohio, have made noises
about jumping into the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has remained coy about his presidential intentions and has
said he will announce his decision in the spring, toward the end of
the legislative session that begins this month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has been anointed the front-runner by many in the
media, a Dole entry could draw supporters and money from the Texas
governor, particularly among the establishment Republicans to whom
they both appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Bush lavished praise on his potential opponent,
calling Dole a ``really good soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she'd be a great candidate, and I think she's a fine
person,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also declined to give more clues as to his thinking about a
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it just about every day, particularly when I get
asked questions about it. But I've got to give an inauguration
speech. I've spent more time on my inaugural address, which I'm
anxious for you to hear,'' Bush told reporters before traveling to
Florida to watch his younger brother, Jeb, inaugurated as governor
there.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer Democrats have juggled the presidential question as
surveys continue to show Vice President Al Gore with formidable
leads in primary match-ups. Gore has avoided being tarnished by the
White House sex scandal that led to Clinton's impeachment and
dodged a potential land mine when Attorney General Janet Reno opted
not to appoint a special prosecutor to look into alleged
fund-raising abuses during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a number of possible challengers have surfaced,
including former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, House Democratic
leader Richard Gephardt, Massachusetts Sen. John Kerry and
Minnesota Sen. Paul Wellstone.
</P>
<P>
   Although the race has barely begun, a number of possible
candidates are already dropping by the wayside. Last month, Sen.
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska said he would not seek the Democratic
nomination and instead would concentrate on his Senate re-election
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a tough Senate re-election race may have scared
off Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., who for months has been wooing
social conservatives with his emphasis on family values and his
condemnation of President Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has scheduled an announcement Tuesday in his hometown
of Springfield, Mo., but a number of his backers said they believe
he will not run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a Republican consultant and adviser to Ashcroft,
said the lawmaker's key financial supporters in Missouri were not
keen on him running for president because they feared it might make
it harder for him to retain his Senate seat. The state's popular
Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan has indicated he will challenge
Ashcroft in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, the former head of the Christian Coalition, said
Ashcroft's absence from the race could leave social conservatives
with few palatable choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a healthy chunk of the religious conservative
community that is all dressed up for the prom and doesn't have a
date,'' said Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bauer, the head of the Family Research Council, which has
crusaded against abortion and gay rights, may step in to fill the
void.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a real vacuum in the Republican Party. The
mantle of Ronald Reagan has not been picked up,'' said Bauer, who
added that he will make his decision on a presidential bid by the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The early jockeying is taking place in the unusual context this
year of the Senate trial of Clinton, an historic event that is
expected to draw media attention from almost every other political
activity.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial is prolonged some political observers say it could
further hurt the lesser known candidates who need this time to
establish an identity with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a distraction from the presidential contest is
certainly to the benefit of Governor Bush or other front-runners,''
said Steve Grubbs, the outgoing chairman of the Iowa Republican
Party. ``Candidates with lesser name ID will have to rise above the
din of Washington media chatter. That is hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubbs noted that Bush recently called him to congratulate him
on the birth of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that prolonged Senate trial will make it harder for
Bush and others to avoid weighing in on Clinton's troubles. Bush
has so far not said whether he believes Clinton should be convicted
and ousted from office.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Appell, a Republican consultant, said that if Bush does
not speak out more forcefully on Clinton he ``runs a real risk with
conservative and primary voters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
