<SLUG> BC-DELTA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta to announce expansion to overseas destinations
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is expected to announce today what it
calls ``a major expansion'' of international service from
Hartsfield International Airport and New York's Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier handles 80 percent of the traffic at
Hartsifield but faces fierce competition on international routes.
Fred Reid, the company's vice president for marketing who was hired
last summer, is expected to lay out Delta's strategy in the battle
to get a larger share of the overseas travel market.
</P>
<P>
   While the company wouldn't comment on specifics Monday, Samuel
C. Buttrick, an airlines analyst with PaineWebber, said now was an
``inopportune'' time to consider an aggressive international
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``More international capacity is not what the industry needs
right now,'' Buttrick said. ``Margins in all the international
sectors have been under pressure in the past year not only across
the Pacific, where economic pressures have been more publicized,
but in recent quarters revenue trends in Latin America and across
the Atlantic have also deteriorated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Buttrick said, Delta could plug holes in markets that
have bilateral limitations on new service, including the United
Kingdom, Italy, Spain, Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's major strategic challenge at Delta has been beefing up
its international alliance network, considered weak compared with
competing pacts such as United's five-way Star Alliance or
American's planned Oneworld team, which will include British
Airways and others.
</P>
<P>
   While Delta has a solid partnership with Swissair and separate
deals with assorted other carriers, it's been jilted by a few
partners in recent years. An immediate goal is broader ties with
Air France.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Delta unveiled its new premium-service section,
dubbed BusinessElite, to be phased in on international aircraft
over the next eight months. BusinessElite will replace separate
first- and business-class sections on 57 MD-11 and Boeing 767 jets
that fly overseas. It also will be installed in 14 new Boeing 777
widebodies on order.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last month, Delta announced plans to scuttle flights to
Prague, Czech Republic, which it serves from New York via
Stuttgart, Germany. The cut follows last year's elimination of
flights to Berlin, Germany, and Copenhagen, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Delta's weakest theater, the carrier recently finalized
a ``code-share'' deal to market seats on thrice-weekly China
Southern Airlines flights between Los Angeles and Guangzhou, China.
The deal gains Delta its first presence in China.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Delta on Monday closed at $51.93
3/4, down 6 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   reid mug
</P>
