<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HANLON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R. BRENDAN HANLON; ACTOR WHOSE FILMS INCLUDED `A CIVIL ACTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   R. Brendan Hanlon, an actor and accountant who had small roles
in several movies and wrote a book to aid actors and other ``show
biz folk'' with their taxes, died of cardiac arrest Saturday in his
home in Marshfield, Mass. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hanlon was born in Boston. He graduated from Boston Latin
School and earned a bachelor's degree in theater and speech at
Emerson College.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Actors Equity Association and the Screen Actors
Guild, he lived and worked in New York City prior to moving to
Marshfield about 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared as the gynecologist in the 1998 film,``Dirty
Laundry'' starring Jay Thomas, and also appeared in ``Good Will
Hunting,'' ``A Civil Action,'' ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``The Spanish
Prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hanlon maintained a private practice as a tax preparer
specializing in the performing arts and was the author of ``The New
Tax Guide for Performers, Writers, Directors, Designers and Other
Show Biz Folk.''
</P>
<P>
   He also inaugurated and operated the Fine Performance Series at
First Parish Unitarian Universalist Church in Duxbury, Mass., where
he was an active member.
</P>
<P>
   A voracious reader and avid jazz fan, he was remembered by
friends and relatives as a brilliant conversationalist who was apt
to quote sources ranging from the Marx brothers comedy troupe to
poet Seamus Heaney.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Marjorie J. (Lerstrom); a daughter, Nell
Anna O'Dea Hanlon of Marshfield; two sisters, Kathleen Fulton and
Maureen Smith of Sandwich, Mass.; and two brothers, Robert of
Pembroke, Mass. and George of Carver, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
