<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ MOVES TOWARD EVICTION OF U.S., BRITISH RELIEF WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Iraq took its first step Monday toward evicting
American and British relief workers, saying their visas would not
be renewed because their safety could not be guaranteed in the face
of public anger over air strikes last month.
</P>
<P>
   In an unsigned diplomatic note delivered to the U.N. office that
coordinates the Iraq ``oil for food'' program here, the Iraqis
repeated their charges, so far not proved and denied in Washington
and London, that the American and British attacks had targeted
``schools, universities, hospitals, grain depots, means of
communication and factories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of anger that besets 22 million Iraqis may find
expression in unfriendliness,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   But U.N. officials, who say they are studying the note,
delivered by Iraq's representative-designate, Saeed Hassan, also
said the Iraqis have inexplicably not included all Americans in
their ban. Three will apparently be allowed to remain in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Four British experts working on contract to European countries
doing repair and development work for the United Nations may also
remain.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Iraqis seem to have used the decision to expel
British and American citizens in order to move 10 relief officials,
including de-mining experts, out of Kurdish areas in the north,
where standards of living have been improving rapidly. Among the
most successful U.N.-run programs in the Kurdish regions was a
poultry industry, which supplied Baghdad with meat and eggs. It was
run by an American agriculture expert.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ``oil for food'' program, Iraq is permitted to sell up
to $5.2 billion in oil every six months to pay for basic goods like
food and medicine. The program provides Iraqi families with monthly
rations of items like milk, cooking oil and beans. Recently it has
also paid for the purchase of computers and repairs to
energy-producing dams and generators.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, the spokesman, James Rubin, said: ``Any
Iraqi effort to selectively exclude some nationalities from the
staff of the U.N. humanitarian program would contravene the U.N.'s
worldwide policy of nondiscrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin noted that U.N. legal officials were working on a
response. He added that Iraqis had told U.N. officials that the
denial of visas might be ``temporary'' and that the numbers
involved were very small.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad Monday, the government continued its verbal assaults
on Arab leaders who have accused President Saddam Hussein of
provoking the air attacks by refusing to cooperate with weapons
inspectors, who are now all out of the country. Sharp criticisms,
particularly from President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and also from
the Saudi leadership, may have unnerved Hussein, some diplomats
say.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, Amr Moussa, the Egyptian foreign minister, said there
was ``a regrettable campaign in the Iraqi press'' against Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi leadership has appeared slightly off balance in trying
to build public opinion in its favor since the air strikes last
month. Because the missile and bomb attacks were so precisely
targeted, however, there seem to have been few civilian casualties,
relief workers and other foreigners in Baghdad say. This has robbed
the government of the opportunity to play on international opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has focused instead on condemning continued American and
British patrolling of ``no flight'' zones in the Kurdish north and
in the southern part of the country populated by Shiite Muslims,
who have rebelled against Baghdad in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In its diplomatic note to the United Nations Monday, the Iraqi
government said the war ``was still under way by virtue of the
maintenance of the no-flight zones imposed by force of arms and
without the authorization of the Security Council.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
