A7874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS &LR;      01-04 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
740 FIRST TO LOSE WELFARE PAYMENTS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the first time in 60 years, the state is no longer
giving cash aid to families with no apparent income but with
children to support, halting payments this week to 740 welfare
recipients _ the first of thousands of families rubbing up against
the new 24-month deadline for families with children older than
two.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recipients failed to find work or sign up for a job
search, despite having received warnings from the state that their
benefits were about to run out.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, 5,100 families _ each typically consisting of a
single mother with two young children _ became the first to hit the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,800 of those families applied for possible last-minute
extensions, claiming they can't find childcare or have made
good-faith efforts to find jobs. They will continue receiving
benefits until welfare officials decide whether or not to grant
their requests.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 2,300 families have been sent notices they are
about to be taken off the rolls, and as of Monday, 740 of them had
been cut.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the checks have stopped, welfare officials believe,
many parents who dragged their feet will now make serious efforts
to find jobs. Even by taking a minimum-wage job, the officials
said, a parent can easily improve her family's financial situation,
since the monthly welfare grant for a family of three works out to
about $3.26 an hour over a 40-hour week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is able-bodied people should be working,
especially in this economy,'' said Department of Transitional
Assistance spokesman Dick Powers. ``If there were extenuating
circumstances that prevented them from doing so, the extension
process would and will flush them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The cuts represent the triumph of a decades-long battle by
conservative legislators to reverse a ``culture of dependency''
that allowed some families to languish on state aid indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the conviction the welfare system had become so
perverted over the years it was trapping generation after
generation of children in poverty, state policymakers embraced a
welfare overhaul plan in 1995 that prods parents to work by placing
an unprecedented time limit on Aid to Families with Dependent
Children.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely, Powers said, some parents of the families dropped
from the rolls already held under-the-table jobs that they did not
report to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraud exists in the world, and fraud exists in welfare,'' he
said. ``There are people who have been working under the table for
part or all of the 24 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who cannot find jobs right away will inevitably turn to
family networks for help, Powers said, but he eschewed speculation
by homeless advocates that many would eventually end up in shelters
and the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare officials plan to gauge the wellbeing of families who
have been cut under the time limit during monthly meetings the
families still must attend with their caseworkers in order to
remain eligible for food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   If the caseworkers sense a family is in distress, or if a family
fails to show up for the monthly meeting, the state Department of
Public Health, under a $2 million agreement with DTA, will send a
nurse or social worker to the family's home to check on the
children and parents, encourage the parents to apply for an
extension if appropriate, and to make them aware of programs, such
as Medicaid and food stamps, they may still qualify for.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Doolin, director of Catholic Charities of Greater Boston,
believes most parents who have been able to get jobs, have already
done so and have already left the rolls before they hit the time
limit. Therefore, he said, those being cut this week are likely to
fall through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that people who have stayed on up to the 12th
hour of the 24th month are the core that have lifestyle,
psychological or family problems that keep them from working, or
that don't have the skills for the job market,'' Doolin said. ``A
great number also don't have of English language.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolin contends these families, after exhausting any available
family networks, will likely end up in a few months in food
pantries and shelters, which he said have already seen demand jump
since the welfare overhaul plan started three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some families, Doolin acknowledged, have resorted to illegal
activities such as prostitution or drug sales to supplement their
welfare grants. But he shuddered at the possibility that
black-market dealings might become the only means of sustenance for
some whose welfare grants have ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that would not be dramatically accelerated,'' he
said. ``But I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
