<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-HEALTH-COX     01-04 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-HEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes puts emphasis on health issues
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Choosing a doctor like choosing a car mechanic.
Funneling tobacco money into health care. Merging separate
departments into a new health superagency.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by these proposals, Roy Barnes already is emerging as an
activist governor on health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's a clear departure from his predecessor, Zell Miller. So
after years of government cost-cutting, anticipation is running
high among Georgia's health industry officials, as they await the
1999 session of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a governor who is very interested in health issues,
and I think it's exciting,'' says Paul Shanor, executive director
of the Medical Association of Georgia, a powerful physicians'
lobby. ``Frankly, it's an issue that Zell Miller didn't want to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   As in previous years, Georgia legislators are likely to tackle
hundreds of bills with health-care implications. They will consider
large and small changes to a system that can be as confusing as it
is costly. And tinkering with one of health care's many gears can
throw another one out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   Health care problems aren't unique to Georgia. Still, the state
is near the bottom of some glaring health statistics, such as
infant mortality and low birth weight babies. Rural hospitals are
spewing red ink. And 1.3 million Georgians have no health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the cost factor. Businesses are paying higher
prices to cover their employees, who in turn face rising insurance
premiums. The problems persist despite a roaring economy. If the
boom starts to fizzle, fixing the health care system becomes even
more troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco settlement
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's health care system, though, may soon get a new
injection of funds _ thanks to the state's recent $4.8 billion
settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The money would come to Georgia over 25 years, with no strings
attached, after a sufficient number of states give final approval
to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Divvying up the money has already provoked debate. Republicans
have their own ideas: the settlement money belongs to taxpayers and
should lead to tax credits, GOP leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wants the money to go to health. Among his priorities:
Medicaid reimbursement, aid to rural hospitals, medical education,
anti-smoking campaigns and reducing the waiting list for disabled
Medicaid recipients to get services in the home. He's also pushing
early-childhood development programs.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of this debate, of course, depends on when the money
arrives. The first installment could come sometime later this year,
but Barnes thinks substantive tobacco settlement-related
legislation is more likely next session.
</P>
<P>
   Umbrella health agency
</P>
<P>
   Another health-care proposal under consideration is to create a
single department of health. It would merge the following agencies:
the Department of Medical Assistance, which runs Medicaid for 1.2
million low-income residents; the State Health Planning Agency,
which regulates expansions of health-care facilities; the Division
of Public Health; and the State Merit System, which covers state
employees and dependents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've got health scattered among several
departments,'' Barnes says. A unified agency, he says, can provide
a coordinated health plan for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Mentioned as the leading candidate to head a new department is
Russ Toal, a former Medicaid commissioner who's widely respected in
the health-care industry.
</P>
<P>
   The superagency idea also could combine the buying power of
Medicaid and hundreds of thousands of state employees, to lower the
state's total medical bill.
</P>
<P>
   That cost of health care is an annual topic in the General
Assembly. It's the counterpoint to the slew of proposals seeking to
protect patients within managed-care plans, such as HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups and insurers insist that such measures balloon
their health costs. Already, the Georgia Association of HMOs says
that 1999 premium increases are running up to 10 percent. ``The
more you raise costs, the more uninsured Georgians you'll
produce,'' says Earl Rogers of the Georgia Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The medical association argues that managed-care companies have
raised premiums to their proper level, after keeping prices
artificially low in previous years to gain market share. And
alarming cost projections don't account for the ultimate result of
denying needed care _ higher medical bills later, says the medical
association's Shanor.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care revolution, in any event, has been jarring for
many consumers. About half of Georgians now are enrolled in
managed-care plans such as HMOs, up from 33 percent in 1991. Barnes
tapped into consumer angst on HMOs last year when he delivered this
line in his campaign: ``If you can choose who changes the oil in
your car, you ought to be able to choose who delivers your baby.''
</P>
<P>
   How the patient choice issue will play out in legislation,
though, will be tricky. Barnes wants HMO patients to be able to go
to non-network doctors, if the physician agrees to the managed-care
plan's rates. If there's agreement on rates, he argues, how can
costs rise?
</P>
<P>
   Likely opponents _ business groups and insurers _ counter that
the choice argument itself can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a wide range of choice available to Georgians
already,'' says Jack Towsley of Cigna HealthCare, who's president
of the Georgia Association of HMOs. An employee often has a choice
of what type of insurance plan to join, Towsley says. Even in a
strict HMO, consumers have a wide choice of doctors within that
network, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise on choice could arise from expanding the law on
Point of Service plans, where patients can go to non-network
doctors, but must pay more for that right.
</P>
<P>
   Suing your HMO
</P>
<P>
   Another Barnes priority is extending patients' rights to sue an
insurance plan for malpractice. A similar law was passed in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see some responsibility for the health plan
that makes a medical decision that causes an injury,'' says Barnes,
adding that the Texas law hasn't increased health costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Chamber of Commerce would oppose a sweeping
liability measure, says Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO industry, instead, pushes a proposal for an external
review panel for medical decisions, where independent doctors would
rule on the denial of benefits by a managed-care company.
</P>
<P>
   Any legislative remedy, though, generally would not apply to
those Georgians who work for larger, self-insured companies, which
are exempt from state insurance regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has pledged his support to the medical association's push
to make the state Board of Medical Examiners an independent entity.
The board, which regulates and disciplines doctors, is now under
the secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Miller vetoed a similar bill, saying it was
''anti-consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanor, though, argues that the board now doesn't have enough
investigators or lawyers to police the profession. ``To protect
patients, you've got to have an independent body,'' Shanor says.
``There are bad doctors out there. We would like to protect the
reputation of the profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors group is also expected to play defense against
separate bills that would extend prescription-writing power to
psychologists, advanced-practice nurses and optometrists.
</P>
<P>
   Saving rural hospitals
</P>
<P>
   The financial plight of Georgia's rural hospitals again will
draw legislative proposals. Twenty such facilities have lost money
three consecutive years, according to state figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize that all rural hospitals will not
survive,'' Barnes says.
</P>
<P>
   But he also envisions increasing Medicaid reimbursements, along
with some direct aid for these hospitals. Legislators may push for
loosening state certificate-of-need laws, so rural hospitals can
branch into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Other battles may loom over expanding options to nursing homes,
including assisted-living, that Medicaid would reimburse; and over
proposed Medicaid cuts to hospital-based nursing homes. Also on the
table for discussion are two huge health-care contracts: A new $40
million-plus information system for Medicaid, and the selection of
a managed-care network for state employees. Both contracts were set
to be awarded in December, but were delayed by Barnes and Miller
amid questions about the fairness of the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
