<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A TERRIBLE PRECEDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Suppose that in last fall's election Democrats had
gained enough seats to control the House. Suppose that Henry Hyde
and the Republicans had still gone ahead and steamrollered
impeachment through the expiring House.
</P>
<P>
   The illegitimacy of that course would have been obvious. What
actually happened _ pushing a partisan impeachment through before
the new House was sworn in _ has been treated as less dubious. But
the constitutional illegitimacy is the same, and the precedent is
extremely dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   That is the thrust of an analysis by Bruce Ackerman of the Yale
Law School. Professor Ackerman made the point briefly last month in
an Op-Ed piece for The New York Times and in testimony before the
House Judiciary Committee. At the time I thought it was a
distraction from the impeachment debate. Now Ackerman has produced
a full-scale paper. I find it formidably convincing.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the analysis is the original intention of the
20th Amendment, added to the Constitution in 1933. It directed that
Congress meet in January following its election. Before then
Congresses had waited 13 months before convening. The old members,
in lame-duck sessions, often did things that the new members might
not. Outrage grew.
</P>
<P>
   The framers of the 20th Amendment were determined above all not
to let lame-duck members choose the president if no candidate had
an Electoral College majority and the choice was thrown to the
House. The Senate report on the amendment said it would assure that
``the new House of Representatives fresh from the people would ...
select the president.''
</P>
<P>
   It is just as offensive to the intent of the amendment, Ackerman
argues, for the Senate to try a sitting president on impeachment
charges brought by a lame-duck House. The framers would be outraged
at the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, anticipating the argument, have said that
several times in our history judges have been impeached by the
House in one Congress and convicted by the Senate in the next. But
all of those cases except one occurred before the 20th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The one exception proves nothing. It was the case of Judge Alcee
Hastings, impeached before the 1988 election and convicted in 1989.
Judge Hastings made no constitutional objections; indeed, he waived
the point by asking for the delay. So it was not a binding
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   All ordinary legislation dies at the end of a Congress if not
finally enacted. So this impeachment resolution, to be considered
by the new Senate, would effectively have to be given an especially
privileged status. But the framers of the 20th Amendment, Ackerman
argues, would if anything have said that ``a lame-duck impeachment
is entitled to even less respect than an ordinary bill passed by a
lame-duck House.''
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers are wary of raising the lame duck argument
for fear that pro-impeachment forces will denounce it as a
``legalism.'' How, then, may it be raised?
</P>
<P>
   First, Rep. Hyde may ask the new House to reconfirm the
appointment of managers for the Senate trial, as has been done in
the past. Democrats could then move an amendment to force
reconsideration of the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   If the House reappoints the managers without amendment _ or if
Hyde and the Republicans try to proceed without reappointment _
senators could raise the issue at the start of their proceeding.
They could ask Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who will be
presiding, to rule that the lame-duck impeachment resolution is not
properly before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, this is no ``legalism.'' It is a profound historical
and constitutional point, with dangerous implications for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much more is at stake than the fate of William Jefferson
Clinton,'' Ackerman writes. ``If this lame-duck impeachment is
allowed to go forward, a terrible precedent will be created. ... A
time will come when another lame-duck House ... will strike out at
the president of the opposing party. ... Once such an abusive cycle
of impeachments has begun, it will be very difficult to keep under
control the bitter disagreements generated by our often-divided
government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
