<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN04-COX     01-04 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Labeling our lives
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ What would a new year be without catchy new
phrases to describe those of us entering it?
</P>
<P>
   We're all familiar with ``Baby Boomers'' and ``Generation X.'' A
lesser-known appellation for those of us who can't stay awake past
9 p.m. is ``Generation Zzzz.''
</P>
<P>
   The new year also will bring with it some trends in the way we
live. In fact, some of them have been conveniently labeled for us
by Lys Marigold and Faith Popcorn in their book Clicking.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``SOS (Save Our Society): A continuing interest in social
conscience and protecting the planet.'' This has been a trend for
years, it seems, and never quite makes it to the front burner. It
might be better labeled ``RIP,'' especially given the state of our
social conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes ``Being Alive: A growing awareness of health and
quality of life.'' Well, as trends go, it beats ``Being Dead.''
Once again, this one seems a bit like a retread. Sure, sure, we all
want to be more aware of our health and have a good quality of
life. So what's new about that? Somebody pass me the Pringles.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's what the authors call ``Cashing Out: The search for
personal fulfillment outside of high-powered careers.'' Let me go
on the record by stating that many of us never ``cashed in.'' Had
we, though, we might well be ready to go beyond crass materialism
and find meaning in other things like faith, family, friendships or
service to others. Before I completely cash out, though, I'd like
to have a little more cash in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anchoring'' is another trend, described as ``reaching back to
spiritual roots.'' This trend already has a strong foothold, given
the number of current books with the words spiritual, angel and New
Age in their titles. Maybe the problem is too many of us feel
``anchored'' in our spiritual life but would rather be sailing _ as
long as we remember where the port is.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the list is ``Down Aging: A growing indulgence in
childhood nostalgia.'' This used to be known as ``There's no fool
like an old fool.'' Down Aging, I guess, is more politically
correct. Regressing also would work. We know we're experiencing
this when we get weepy over Barbie lunch boxes, hula hoops and
Slinkies. I don't want to down age. It's a little too close to
dotage.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think your personal trends should be for the new
year? Resolutions aside, January is a good time to slow down and
ponder the future. Here are some personal trends I predict for my
life in the coming years:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Downsizing.'' With one son in college and a second closing
in, our household is diminishing _ in bodies if not laundry. We'll
be a smaller group, and that will be a big adjustment. Maybe we'll
have a few years to enjoy it before we ``upsize'' with new
daughters-in-law and grandchildren _ but I look forward to that,
too, as long as they don't all live with us.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Feathering the Nest.'' We have lived in our current house
long enough that major repairs are needed. We either have to make
them or move. New roof, new air conditioning, new refrigerator, new
water heater. I'm lobbying for a nice condo.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Second Aging.'' This period starts around age 45 when we try
to do all the things we didn't do in our 20s and 30s. Like get a
master's degree, take that trip to New England to see the fall
foliage, write a book of poems or refinish antique furniture. The
children had us for years; now we have ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite simple, actually. If I have to live up to a set of
labels, I'm going to choose my own.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
