<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS TAX CREDIT FOR LONG-TERM-CARE FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although a Senate impeachment trial threatens to
delay his State of the Union message, President Clinton plunged
ahead Monday with a preview, announcing a $1,000 tax credit to help
disabled Americans needing long-term care and their relatives who
provide the care.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant health care proposal in his proposed budget
for fiscal 2000 was unveiled at a White House ceremony as the
administration's efforts to publicize the president's policy
priorities in advance of the State of the Union shifts into
high-gear.
</P>
<P>
   As in years past the White House has begun rolling out
proposals, one by one, leading to up the annual address. And this
year, administration officials are proceeding even though the
Senate, as its first order of business, will determine the
procedures for Clinton's impeachment trial, which could wind up
causing a postponement of the Jan. 19 speech.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart said the president
was planning to go ahead with the State of the Union as scheduled,
but he left open the possibility that Clinton could postpone it, as
some Democrats have suggested, if a Senate trial is in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what decisions the Senate will come to as far as
their schedule and their process,'' said Lockhart. ``But as far as
the president goes, he's hard at work on the State of the Union
address. ... He plans to give that speech January 19th.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of this year's new policy ideas are being packaged around
the theme of work and family, as the White House seeks to maintain
Clinton's high approval ratings despite his impeachment by the
House and his impending Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Clinton unveiled the $1,000 tax credit targeted to
2 million elderly and disabled Americans and their families with
long-term-care needs. It is the centerpiece of a five-year, $6.2
billion health care initiative that, if approved by Congress, would
represent the biggest tax credit for families in the
administration's proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing long-term care at home is more and more a common
choice, but . . . it is rarely an easy one,'' Clinton said. ``Since
this kind of care is almost never covered by private insurance or
Medicare, out-of-pocket expenses can be staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, who joined the president for the
announcement, said: ``Every family member has its own story about
how difficult it is to see those we love grow infirm or become
disabled and the challenges we face in giving them the care, the
love, the attention and the medical services they need and
deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the tax credit, Clinton proposed that the federal
government, as the nation's largest employer, begin offering
private, long-term-care insurance to federal workers, retirees and
their families at group rates in the hope that private-sector firms
would follow suit. The government estimates that about 300,000
federal employees would take part in such a program and that it
would cost $15 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton proposed spending $625 million over five
years to create a national family caregiver support program that
would provide counseling, information and other support to about
250,000 families caring for elderly relatives with chronic
illnesses and disabilities. He also proposed spending $10 million
on a national campaign to provide the nation's 39 million Medicare
beneficiaries critical information about long-term care options,
including what Medicare does and does not cover. As part of the
initiative, Vice President Al Gore will conduct a series of forums
nationwide on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term-care initiative was the latest in a series of
proposals Clinton or his aides have announced in advance of the
president's State of the Union message and budget presentation to
Congress Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals have included increasing funding for food safety
by $105 million, or 12 percent, over this year to prevent
potentially deadly food-borne illnesses, and increasing defense
spending by $100 billion over six years to help the armed forces
deal with various world crises and for military pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Clinton said Monday he will resume his push with
Congress to give patients covered by health maintenance
organizations more flexbility to choose their doctors and will
again call for a boost in the minimum wage, now set at $5.15 an
hour, in his State of the Union speech.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, Clinton is scheduled to make announcements on
education, drugs and prisons, as well as deliver a speech Friday in
Detroit on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime the media and everybody else is ready to write off
the president as a lame duck, he shows we are still full of ideas,
and we have a very active agenda,'' said Maria Echaveste, White
House deputy chief of staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
