<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GUNMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI WOMEN INJURED AS GUNMEN ATTACK VAN IN HEBRON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Gunmen opened fire Monday morning on a van
transporting Jewish settlers in the divided city of Hebron,
injuring two Israeli women as they riddled the vehicle with two
dozen bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officials suspect that the gunmen were Palestinian
militants, committing the first successful terrorist attack on
Israelis since early November. They said they believed that the men
fled from the Israeli-controlled part of Hebron, where the attack
occurred, into the Palestinian part of the city, where Israeli
officers are not allowed to pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai ordered the borders of Hebron
closed to Palestinians, preventing them from entering or leaving
the city. He also imposed a curfew on the Palestinians living on
the Israeli side; they were restricted to their homes, although
some slipped out to throw stones at Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting rubber-encased metal bullets, the soldiers injured two
Palestinian youths, striking one 13-year-old boy in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office quickly denounced the
assault on the van as an attack on the peace agreement signed in
Washington in October. David Bar-Illan, a senior adviser to the
prime minister, said the incident made ``a mockery'' of the
Palestinians' commitment to peace under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Citing previous Palestinian violations, the Israelis have
stopped complying with the agreement. They refuse to turn over any
more land in the West Bank, a refusal likely to remain steadfast
until Israelis elect a new government in May.
</P>
<P>
   In Hebron, the gunmen reportedly hid in an alleyway on a winding
road and ambushed the white van as it was leaving the Cave of the
Patriarchs, a holy site to both Jews and Muslims. The women,
kindergarten caretakers, were on their way to work in downtown
Hebron from their homes in the nearby Jewish settlement of Kiryat
Arba.
</P>
<P>
   Flori Hoffi, one of the women shot, was slightly injured; the
other, Fani Elezra, was more seriously injured. Both remained
hospitalized on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said the settlers had been offered an armored
vehicle for such trips, and refused it.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the settlers, Orit Struck, responded: ``They
don't want to give real security to the area. They prefer to put
Jews in bunkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from her hospital bed on Israeli television, Mrs. Hoffi
said, ``I was hit from the first round and ducked, and then I heard
the second round, and I knew my girlfriend was injured from it, and
then she lost consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   After the attacks, the settlers' leaders gathered at the scene,
and young girls swayed in prayer, reading psalms. The leaders said
Netanyahu should go beyond freezing the peace agreement to
invalidating it.
</P>
<P>
   Hebron, where 450 Jewish settlers live amid 150,000
Palestinians, has long been a flashpoint for violent confrontation,
but until this attack, it was experiencing a relatively calm
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officials asked the Palestinians to hunt for the
suspects. ``We approached the Palestinians and asked them to take
action in their territory in order to investigate the matter and
capture the attackers,'' Yitzhak Eitan, the commander for the West
Bank, told the Israeli radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
