<P>
   IMF-REVAMP (Washington) _ The leadership of the International
Monetary Fund, sharply criticized over the past 18 months for how
they handed financial crises from Southeast Asia to Russia, is
proposing a major overhaul of the Fund's operations that could
permit it to intervene directly in the operation of national
economies long before they get into deep trouble. By David E.
Sanger. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOODMORNING-TV-SHAKEUP (New York) _ In a move that underscores
how far the fortunes of ``Good Morning America'' have fallen, ABC
News plucks one of its biggest stars, Diane Sawyer, from the
firmament of prime-time news and names her co-anchor of the morning
show, where she will be paired with Charles Gibson. By Lawrie
Mifflin. (The story has moved in ``f'' and ``e'' news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OTTERS (Undated) _ While otters appeared to be flourishing,
scientists recently discovered that the otter population in the
Aleutians had plunged sharply, with no apparent reason. It turned
out that orcas, or killer whales, had started eating the otters
after decades and possibly centuries of peaceful coexistence.
Exploring the delicate balance of the food chain that was
discovered when researchers set out to learn why. By William K.
Stevens. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) With graphic and
photo.
</P>
