<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BOWL SYSTEM LUCKED OUT ONCE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ ``Once two strangers climbed up Rocky Top,
looking for a moonshine still,'' as the Tennessee fight song puts
it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it was more than two strangers, and they were looking for
a photo opportunity, and instead of Rocky Top it was Mount Kush.
But you get the point.
</P>
<P>
   There would be room for only one team on the symbolic pinnacle
after Florida State and Tennessee finished pummeling each other in
the Fiesta Bowl Monday night. The game would determine the national
college football championship under the new format, pitting the No.
1 team against No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   All the strangers in Volunteer orange and all the strangers in
Seminole garnet were cordial to each other on the pile of rocks
overlooking Sun Devil Stadium. Bowl games, after all, are a rather
bourgeois affair, drawing a bunch of lawyers and accountants who
can afford to travel with their favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   They could probably afford outrageous ticket prices, but were
not forced to pay them. This game was so far from either school
that the demand was down, and scalpers were muttering ``face value,
face value'' as their gloomy mantra as they trudged up and down
Mills Street with the posh tourists practically naming their price.
</P>
<P>
   As a former Appalachian hand, I can testify there were precious
few real hillbillies making their way up the trails of Mount Kush.
The orthodontic smiles and re-sculptured faces told me these were
suburban folks on holiday.
</P>
<P>
   This is the hill up which Frank Kush used to send his football
players, in full battle regalia, in the blazing August heat when he
was the resident sadist at Arizona State. Now tourists do it on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Kush is around here somewhere, and could probably make
a great piece of change hiring himself as a universal football
coach, goading grandfathers and little children up the mountain, to
prove their courage and uphold the American way of life.
</P>
<P>
   There was precious little woofing between the garnet people and
the rather more plentiful orange people, who peered down from Mount
Kush into the empty stadium. Later, of course, the joint would
reverberate with the Tennessee anthem, written in the 60's by
Felice and Boudleaux Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The song _ my favorite rendition is by Buck Owens _ begins,
``Wish that I was on old Rocky Top, up in the Tennessee hills,''
and has absolutely nothing to do with football but rather with the
flinty independence of all mountaineers. Nevertheless, the song has
become a staple at all Tennessee games.
</P>
<P>
   Both schools aspired to lofty heights in Monday night's game.
Each had won a national title _ Tennessee back in 1951 and Florida
State in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was sure to be crowned champion last night because
there was no wiggle room for impassioned whining from a third
school. Tennessee was the only top-level undefeated team (sorry,
Tulane), and once-beaten Florida State had been anointed to
challenge Tennessee in this ultimate game of king-of-the-hill.
</P>
<P>
   The football coaches who vote in the ESPN poll were committed to
crowning the winner while the writers who vote in the Associated
Press poll reserved their right to cast ballots three hours after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   John Cooper tried to make a case after his Ohio State team
escaped Texas A&AMP;M during the long New Year Day glut of bowl games.
Cooper said the writers might consider his team if Florida State
did not rack up many style points in a theoretical victory over
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame John one bit for feeling the way he does,'' said
Bobby Bowden of Florida State on Sunday. ``John might have the best
football team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Bowden quickly added, ``if Tennessee wins this ball
game, they're going to be national champions. And if we win this
ball game, we're going to be national champions.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right about that. Florida State had the good sense of
losing to North Carolina State early, upon which kindly old Grandpa
Bowden informed his older players that they could keep their
scholarships while sitting way down on his bench.
</P>
<P>
   The new system lucked out because there were not three
undefeated contenders trying to squeeze into one Fiesta Bowl. (Come
to think of it, a triangular football game does have its anarchic
appeal.) Ohio State also lost, while UCLA and Kansas State made the
gross mistake of losing in their last regular game, which is bad
timing, since bowl officials penalize teams for recent losses.
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA had not lost to Miami, there would have been a
UCLA-Tennessee game here Monday night, a battle of undefeated
teams. There would have been fewer people on Mount Kush because the
fans would have been down on Mills Street begging for tickets at
$500 or $750 or maybe even $1,000. But we still would have had
countless verses of Rocky Top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers ain't come down from Rocky Top, reckon they never
will,'' is the punch line of the Bryants' classic song. There's not
much pity on Rocky Top _ and no second chances after the Fiesta
Bowl, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
