</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE QUITS RED CROSS, SUGGESTING RUN FOR WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mo., N.H., Ariz.)  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after her husband's unsuccessful effort
to oust President Clinton, Elizabeth Hanford Dole announced Monday
that she was resigning as president of the Red Cross, a move that
several advisers said was intended to clear the path for her own
campaign for the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole had insisted for more than a year that she had no
intention of seeking the Republican nomination, and her
announcement Monday stunned many politicians and strategists in her
party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet given her national prominence and popularity among
Republicans, her appeal to women, her experience as secretary of
labor and secretary of transportation, and her work for the Red
Cross, many strategists say Mrs. Dole could catapult herself to the
top tier of Republican contenders. Polls of Republican primary
voters have shown, consistently, that Mrs. Dole is second only to
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas as the most popular prospective
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, who is 62, did not speak directly of her intentions
in the farewell address she made Monday to Red Cross employees.
``Soon, I will be considering new paths, and there are exciting
possibilities,'' she said. ``I will choose one and pursue it with
all my might.'' Asked by reporters afterward whether she planned to
run, Mrs. Dole said, ``We're going to give it serious
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   But several people close to Mrs. Dole said her advisers had
already assembled a plan for her to raise as much as $22 million
this year, and that they intended to establish an exploratory
committee to begin soliciting donations shortly after she
officially leaves the Red Cross in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In another surprise turn that has roiled the Republican field
even before any candidates have officially announced, several
advisers to Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., said he was expected to
announce on Tuesday that he has decided not to seek the nomination.
He had been aggressively laying the groundwork for a candidacy for
a year and had positioned himself, with some success, as a champion
of religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft had gone as far as to rent space for a campaign office,
and he had planned to be the first candidate to formally announce
at an event on Tuesday in Springfield, Mo. But with his Senate seat
up in 2000, his advisers said, he worried that it was too risky to
try to run for president and win re-election in what could be a
tight Senate contest. Gov. Mel Carnahan announced earlier this
month that he would take on Ashcroft in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, he decided that a Senate seat was too valuable to
the values that he stands for to put in jeopardy,'' said Ralph
Reed, a strategist and former head of the Christian Coalition who
had counseled Ashcroft. ``We've got too many vulnerable seats to
just punt one to the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes, the
publisher, are the two possible candidates who are likely to appeal
to Ashcroft's supporters because they have offered themselves as
religious conservatives with pragmatic campaign experience.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said Ashcroft's decision leaves ``a large chunk of the
religious conservatives' leadership all dressed up for the prom but
without a date.'' The senator had been the choice of Pat Robertson,
founder of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another move Monday that is part of a sudden burst of
activity that underscores how the presidential field for 2000 is
beginning to settle out unusually early, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H.,
announced the establishment of a presidential campaign committee.
While Smith, a hard-edged conservative, is considered a long shot,
he could muddle the nominating process because he is the favorite
son in New Hampshire, traditionally the first primary state.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Vice President Al Gore, the favorite for the
Democratic nomination, and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., announced
that they had formed committees that allow them to begin raising
money.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
