<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NINERS-NYT     01-04 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CHANGING OF THE GUARD WITH 49ERS RECEIVERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No wonder Jerry Rice blew up during the regular
season over his desire to catch more footballs and in bigger
moments. Rice must have seen this coming. He must have realized
long before us that receiver Terrell Owens was the new apple of the
49ers' eyes. Especially of quarterback Steve Young's eyes. That in
the post-season Owens might get more calls. More passes. More
chances to win games. More glory. The Guy. The Star.
</P>
<P>
   It takes one to know one.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a bright, visionary star to peek around the stage just
before the curtain rises and to realize that the props, the music,
the timing, the production is striking a new chord. That an
understudy is being provided with your script. Your show.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has done it all _ won big games in the closing seconds, won
Super Bowls _ and for nearly all of his 14 seasons with the 49ers,
he has been The Guy. The Star. He can discern in practices and in
the game plan and in communication with Young and with his coaches
where the emphasis on placing the football will be. He must have
felt things turning, shifting, as this season unfolded. And in the
49ers' dramatic 30-27 wild-card playoff victory over Green Bay here
on Sunday, it was crystallized. Entrenched. Rice caught one ball
for 6 yards. And even on that one grab, during the game-winning
drive, he apparently fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was Owens who kept getting his number called, who despite
dropping four passes and fumbling once still kept getting his
number called. It was Owens in the end who stole it, won it,
reached for glory, swiped it, and solidified his status as The Guy.
The Star. It was the 25-year-old Owens who was double-covered for
most of the day by the Packers, who chose to single-cover the
36-year-old Rice. Owens made the 25-yard touchdown catch with three
seconds left that created history. New history. A permanent new
49ers order.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Rice said about it:
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was more of a desperation throw, with everybody
trying to go deep and create single coverage. Steve made the right
read and threw a good ball in there. T.O. was able to hang on to
it. We knew we somehow had to get it into the end zone. The guys
kept working and we got it done. This game is going to go down in
history, and I'm glad to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A part of it instead of being squarely in the middle of it? No.
80 in the back seat to No. 81? Instead of J.R., T.O.? Time out!
</P>
<P>
   No. Some things must change. Very little stays the same.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Terrell Owens, T.O., is The Guy, The Star, whom the
Atlanta Falcons must account for most in the 49ers' passing game
when San Francisco (13-4) clashes with Atlanta (14-2) on Saturday
in a second-round playoff game at the Georgia Dome. It would, of
course, be a mistake to ignore Rice. Who says he is completely
done? Certainly he doesn't. Rice can still be a game-breaker and
the Falcons know this only too well. But here is the catch _ now
defenses have Owens first in mind. He commands the attention. The
double-teams. It is his size _ 6 foot 3 inches, 217 pounds _ his
strength, his speed and his huge hands. He is a powerful receiver
who is also graceful. Full of desire. Wonderful combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, a third-round pick in 1996 out of Tennessee-Chattanooga,
grew up immensely in this Packers game.
</P>
<P>
   You think he was not aware of what has happened? What is
happening? During the regular season Rice caught 82 balls and Owens
caught 67. But Owens nearly matched Rice's 1,157 reception yards,
missing by only 60 yards. Owens averaged 2.3 yards a catch more
than Rice. Owens caught 14 touchdown passes; Rice caught 9. Rice's
longest touchdown grab was for 75 yards. Owens earned one of 79
yards.
</P>
<P>
   So, Owens entered the playoff game against the Packers knowing
that the trend in the regular season was going to follow in the
playoffs. Owens would be counted on most in the passing game. The
Guy. The Star.
</P>
<P>
   And he nearly choked.
</P>
<P>
   Think there isn't pressure supplanting Jerry Rice? In the
playoffs, no less?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers cornerback Marquez Pope put it this way: ``When you
are a receiver and you know the ball is coming to you all day, you
can get a little antsy. And then you get the drops T.O. had and you
start to doubt. We kept telling him on the sideline not to doubt
himself. We've seen him all year make plays. We knew he could be
there when it counted.''
</P>
<P>
   And Owens realized he was pressing. ``I woke up a couple of
times last night and I couldn't sleep, so I just laid in bed
staring at the ceiling and I was thinking,'' Owens said on Sunday
after the game. ``I had a vision about making a play and winning
this game. And then once the game rolled around I was pressing.
Near the end of the game, I was already thinking about how I was
going to live with myself knowing I let the team down. I was
thinking, `They have been looking at me all year long. And now
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   This became that. Owens won it. Credit Young for believing in
Owens. You are the quarterback and Owens has dropped the ball all
day and in the final ticks of the clock with everything on the line
you are going to go back to Owens and not to Rice? That takes guts,
and a season's worth of confidence in your receiver. Young clearly
felt that way about Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Some Packers said afterward they had a hard time swallowing the
fact that a player who made as many mistakes as Owens did could
make one play and be a hero. It was Packers cornerback Tyrone
Williams who kept trash-talking Owens in the third quarter over
Owens' drops.
</P>
<P>
   Football players are taught that mistakes kill. That mistakes
cost. That in playoff games mistakes are seldom overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Terrell Owens, T.O, made gaffe after gaffe in his bid to
cement his status as The Guy. The Star. And in one sweeping moment,
he wiped the slate clean and created new playoff history and a new
49ers order.
</P>
<P>
   It looks permanent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
