<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS TO EXAMINE BLEDSOE'S FINGER TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If he had his druthers, Patriots quarterback
Drew Bledsoe would have spent a chunk of time early this week
huddling with the team's medical staff, trying to end his shelf
life and get back on the field against the Denver Broncos this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sunday's loss to the Jacksonville Jaguars left any
mention of his mending digit moot, and Bledsoe plans to take off
Wednesday and ``go hide out for a while and get away from
everything and enjoy being around my family.''
</P>
<P>
   First, though, he will have his right index finger checked out
Tuesday. He expects the pin will be left in it for now and there
will be no problenms with it down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he and his teammates checked out of their Foxboro
Stadium locker room and Bledsoe, standing beside his white sports
utility vehicle in the parking lot, took a couple of minutes to
check in on things Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe started by throwing his support solidly in the corner of
coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, he's taken us to the playoffs two years in a row
and that's nothing to be taken lightly and he's been faced with
some extremely adverse situations,'' Bledsoe said. ``He walked into
a very adverse situation here following Bill and he's done a good
job handling all that pressure. We've had a lot of injuries and
setbacks the last two years, and he's been able to maintain his
poise and maintain his ability to coach the team through all of
that and I think he deserves a lot of credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he appreciates the way Carroll has hung in there in
the coaching pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody could have anticipated how difficult
this situation was going to be to step into,'' Bledsoe said. ``And
I haven't seen him change one bit in the last two years and that's
really to his credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides having Carroll stay around, Bledsoe said it would be
nice to have some continuity in a coaching staff that was
overhauled two years ago when Bill Parcells left, and then added
offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese for this past season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the injuries and all the adversity they've had to deal
with this year, I think they've done a good job,'' said Bledsoe of
Zampese and defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell. ``And plus, we've
been through enough changes here in the past few years. I think it
would be a real bonus if we could keep things in place here. But
we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe liked the way Scott Zolak and the Patriots came back in
the third quarter against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the effort of the team was excellent,'' Bledsoe said.
``I said after the game to the team that it killed me to stand and
watch but I was proud to be a part of this team because the guys on
this team played with a lot of heart and played with a lot of
effort and gave it everything they had.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he had no idea whether he would have been able to
play in the second round of the playoffs, but it would have been
nice to have his status be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a touch-and-go situation and we would have
had to make the call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He echoed Carroll and others on one of the keys to next year:
having good attendance at Johnny Parker's offseason strength and
conditioning programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get guys stronger and faster and in better condition going
into the year, and in a lot of cases that can help you stay away
from some injuries,'' he said. ``It's not going to solve all of
them. Look at a guy like Ted Johnson, I'm not sure you'd find a
better-conditioned athlete in the National Football League.
Sometimes things happen, but you can avoid some things.''
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which some thought he came of age with comeback
wins late in the season before breaking his finger, Bledsoe said
he'll also take the responsibility for some early-season losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't accomplish what we wanted to accomplish this year,
and that's disappointing,'' he said. ``But there are a lot of
reasons for that, and I take a lot of the blame for that. Some of
the games earlier in the year we should have been able to win. It's
something everyone on the team has to address individually about
what we're going to accomplish in the offseason and how we're going
to approach things next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
