<SLUG> BC-EURO-DOLLAR-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE EURO DEBUTS, SOME SAY IT MAY RIVAL THE DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EURO-CHANGEOVER) 
(lb) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The euro _ the new European currency _ had a positive debut
Monday in foreign-exchange dealings. But it is still unclear how
the euro will fare against the dollar this year and what kind of
challenge it will present over time to the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar will stay the world's predominant currency but the
euro will be second,'' said Robert Standing, managing director in
London of the global trading division in Europe for Chase Manhattan
Bank. But, he added, ``the euro will be the first credible
challenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think the euro may be more than a challenger. Fred
Bergsten, director of the Institute for International Economics in
Washington, said the question is not whether the euro will rival
the dollar but how fast that will happen. ``Some people say three
years, some say 10 years; but there is no doubt that it will
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the talk is of the euro challenging the dollar, what
the new currency really represents is another big step toward a
global economy, in which the United States will face more
competition for its share of growth.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the euro is one of the mechanisms that are making
a united Europe far more competitive with the United States. ``Its
a culmination of the globalization trend,'' said Bergsten, adding
that ``what the Europeans have done is show how you can take
maximum advantage of globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   In late trading Monday, the euro cost $1.18060, up from the
$1.17400 value of the old European currency unit on Dec. 31. The
ecu, a basket of European currencies that was the precursor to the
euro, converted into the euro on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The euro rallied from its New York lows as the stock market
reversed course, with the Dow Jones industrial average giving up
most of its gains for the day. The dollar fell much more sharply
against the yen, ending at 112.07 yen from 113.57 Thursday, in
light trading that may have exaggerated the decline, some traders
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new currency, some traders said, was buoyed by European
banks' buying and strong rallies in European stock markets from
Germany to Spain and France to Italy. Traders also said that
trading was orderly, although volume was only moderate. Traders
``were working their way in slowly,'' Standing of Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans used to following the German mark, the Italian
lira and the other currencies from the 11 nations now represented
by the euro, the new currency may be a little confusing. Until now,
the quotes of the value of the dollar against marks or lire have
been in how many of them one dollar can buy. For example, on Monday
the dollar was worth 1,639.34 lire.
</P>
<P>
   But with the euro, its value will be quoted in how many dollars
it can buy. This means that when the euro moves, for example, from
$1.17 to $1.18 dollars, the euro is getting stronger and the dollar
is getting weaker. The British pound is quoted in the same fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Americans will still have to look at the values of
marks and other European currencies, because the euro will only
gradually become available in coins and bills over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   So when travelers go to continental Europe this year, they will
still be spending marks, lire and francs when using cash. But goods
can be bought with euros on credit cards, and visitors can get euro
travelers checks. (Britain and several other European countries are
not adopting the euro.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for the strength of the euro this year, that is open to
debate. There are plenty of currency forecasters who think the euro
will be strong and others who think it will be weak. The
expectation, said Standing of Chase, ``depends on the views of
where the two economies go.''
</P>
<P>
   Many forecasters are expecting growth to be stronger in Europe
than in the United States, which would help the euro. But Paul
Podolsky, a currency strategist at BankBoston, thinks growth in
Europe will be slower. He also feels that the new European Central
Bank will have a more difficult time navigating in its new
environment than others expect.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on Monday, Podolsky said European authorities got
what they wanted: an ``uneventful'' day. He said they did not want
the euro to fall in value nor did they want it to have a volatile
day.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, within the foreign-exchange business the biggest
significance of the euro's trading launch has been its likely
effect on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign-exchange industry has been scaling bank and
adjusting to the arrival of the euro for about a year and
intensively since last May when the launch of the new currency was
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been streamlining and adjusting for all of 1998,''
said Standing. He said that another factor that made life difficult
for many foreign-exchange traders last year was the crash of many
emerging-market currencies. This forced a lot of firms to cut back
or get out of trading those currencies altogether.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
