<HEADER>
A7907 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      01-04 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: raising money.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee is also preparing to
announce an exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Mrs. Dole's move was the biggest surprise as the 2000
presidential race gets under way. ``This is a 95 percent
certainty,'' said John Heubusch, who was a top aide to Mrs. Dole in
the Labor Department and at the Red Cross and has been one of her
closest advisers in discussing a presidential bid. ``The Red Cross
was in pretty bad shape when she got there; it was a really
significant management task to turn that place around. Her ability
to do that has truly gained her some real confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising the money, Heubusch said, ``wouldn't be easy but would
be doable _ when given a task she can complete it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fabrizio, the pollster for Bob Dole's presidential campaign
in 1996 who has worked closely with the Doles, said, ``Leaving the
Red Cross is a serious indication that she is serious.'' (She took
a leave when she helped Dole's presidential campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole is a very disciplined politician who is known for
carefully stage-managing her every public appearance. But she has
never held elective office and many strategists questioned whether
she could endure the demands of a presidential campaign. While Mrs.
Dole could compete for Christian voters, she was described by
several people as a ``Billy Graham Christian'' because she is not
known as a a conservative ideologue.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole's departure at the Red Cross headquarters two blocks
from the White House was also a masterful political event. It was
packed with more than 500 cheering employees, and she was praised
repeatedly for her leadership over the last eight years. As she
entered the room an announcer boomed over the loudspeaker, ``Our
beloved president of the American Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a touch that surely did not please the White House, Mrs.
Dole's aides distributed a statement from Donna Shalala, the
secretary of heath and human services who is president Clinton's
designee on the board of the Red Cross. ``She brought intelligence,
skill and integrity to the post,'' Ms. Shalala said, ``and she
leaves with my highest respect and affection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
