<SLUG> BC-DDN-NELLOMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former track star faces jury in rape charge
 &HT;    By Rob Modic
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A 12-year-old girl will testify today about how
former Olympic track hopeful Christopher Raulins Nelloms raped her
eight times when she was between 8 and 11 years old, an assistant
Montgomery County prosecutor told a jury Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nelloms, 26, of Trotwood, Ohio, faces a mandatory life sentence
if a Montgomery County Common Pleas jury of nine women and three
men convicts him on even one of the rape charges.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Kevin Lennen contended that the girl is a
``pathological liar'' who was sent to Nelloms for better discipline
after having trouble at her single mother's home.
</P>
<P>
   Nelloms was living with his fiance, Tina Smith, at the time the
girl first disclosed the allegations, last April 9. Lennen proposed
that the girl concocted the accounts of the rapes, an attempted
rape and a felonious penetration with a finger to avert being
returned to her natural mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lennen said the girl's testimony is also suspect because, during
the investigation, she changed some of her accounts of the rapes
and other sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant county prosecutor Angela Frydman said the girl first
disclosed the rapes to Tina Smith after watching a television
program about child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Frydman said Nelloms first assaulted the girl when she was 8,
shortly after he broke up with his wife, Mary, in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After several rapes while in Nelloms' care, the girl was
returned to her mother but did not reveal the assaults, Frydman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl visited Nelloms again when she was 10 and was subjected
to several more assaults, Frydman said. The girl will also testify
that Nelloms claimed after one assault that he would be
electrocuted if she told anyone about the sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Frydman said the head of the child abuse unit at Children's
Medical Center will testify that an examination of the girl found
evidence consistent with the girl's accounts. Lennen, however,
claimed there would be no physical evidence or any other witness to
support the girl's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Modic writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
