<HEADER>
A7909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER05-COX     01-04 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio Valley trying to dig out despite hard freeze
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The main roads are clear but local side streets
will likely remain rutted ice rinks for several days after this
weekend's snow, rain and hard freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Deep freeze temperatures Monday kept road salt from doing much
good against the packed snow and ice that coated many local roads,
local streets maintenance directors said.
</P>
<P>
   Those temperatures dipped to 3 degrees by 6 p.m. and the wind
chill was as low as -17 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Today the high is expected to reach 15 with a low near 10. By
Wednesday, temperatures are expected to be relatively warmer with
the high near 30, a low near 20 and a chance of snow. Thursday and
Friday's forecasts call for highs in the upper 30s and lower 40s
and lows in the mid 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The cold and icy weather may have contributed to a second death
in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Icy road conditions contributed to a fatal crash near the
Auglaize-Shelby County line late Sunday. Pramilaben Patel, 48, was
killed when the 1991 Ford Aerostar van in which she rode spun out
of control, landing on its right side in the median between the
north and southbound lanes of Interstate 75 six miles south of
Wapakoneta.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Ramarnlal Patel, 57, and another passenger, Adam
Patel, 18, received minor injuries in the accident, which happened
at 10:18 p.m. The survivors were treated and released at Wilson
Memorial Hospital. All were from Detroit, Michigan. Meanwhile,
Dayton police continued to investigate Monday's death of a man
found face down in the snow Sunday at 334 Norwood Ave. Herbert L.
Simon, 46, of 1231 S. Broadway St., was discovered about 8 a.m. and
was dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Police don't suspect foul play, said Sgt. Gary White. The cause
of death has been deferred pending the return of toxicology and
other tests, according to the Montgomery County Coroner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Ice became the biggest problem Monday as hospital emergency
rooms reported a rash of fall-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Roads stayed coated with ice after Saturday morning's fluffy
snowfall was packed down by cars, then matted with freezing rain.
By the time plows reached many side roads Sunday, they could only
scrape off the snow blown on top, leaving an inch or more of ice
below.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency rooms across the area have seen 250 to 300 people
treated for injuries related to the ice. Falls have outranked
injuries from traffic accidents 10 to 1, according to Dr. James
Augustine, an emergency physician at Miami Valley Hospital and
medical director for the Washington Twp. Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami Valley Hospital, which sees a third of the emergency
department volume in Montgomery County, 44 people were treated for
ice-related injuries on Sunday, Augustine said. Of those, 30 were
for falls, 10 for sledding injuries, three for traffic accidents
and one for a snow shoveling injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really very hazardous,'' Augustine said. ``The EMS people
are just going nuts with falls.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect icy sidewalks and driveways for the next few days, he
said. Some of the ice will melt gradually, only to rapidly
re-freeze as the sun goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine advised people to wear shoes with tread, to walk in
the snow instead of on ice, and to avoid carrying things when
walking outdoors. One person was treated for an impaled hand after
falling while carrying a sharp instrument, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kettering, ice patches formed on roads that were plowed
first, according to Wayne Springer, assistant streets maintenance
director.
</P>
<P>
   Plowed snow blocked drainage and Saturday night's rains backed
up and froze into sheets, Springer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streets we worked very, very hard to get to bare pavement
then became thick ice,'' Springer said.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Dayton streets were cleared to the pavement after crews
from three departments hauled the snow away in trucks and dumped it
in parking lots at city parks.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton crews had trouble on side streets because of the rain and
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The residential streets, some are in decent shape, some are
much less so, a lot of them much less than we would like,'' said
Dennis Goodrich, manager of street maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Some Dayton-area residents seemed pleased Monday with how
quickly street crews had responded to the snow and ice, if not with
the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can see where all the snow gets blown,'' said Danny
Glascoe, 30, pointing in frustration to the ridge of plowed ice
blocking his and other parked cars along Dayton's Illinois Avenue.
``But I guess they're doing the best they can in this weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Winglewich, a 64-year-old resident of Marilyn Street in
Kettering, said he was impressed that city crews had already
cleared smaller side streets like his.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I can remember them coming out here this
quickly,'' he said. ``My only problem is, my car has to negotiate
that little bump'' at the end of the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Road crews have no choice, though, street maintenance officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were bombarded with calls from people whose driveways were
(blocked by mounds of plowed snow),'' Robert Hoag, operations
engineer for the Montgomery County engineer's office. ``I feel for
them because my driveway was plowed in. We know of no other way to
get the roads open other than the way we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Xenia, plows and ice trucks may head back out tomorrow if
temperatures rise into the high 20s as expected. The city expected
the delivery of an additional 500 tons of road salt today.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The storm) shouldn't hurt us too bad but if we get another
storm, it could put a dent in the salt supply,'' said Charles
Leonard, Xenia's assistant public service director.
</P>
<P>
   The ice and nasty weather did not cancel classes at the
University of Dayton or Wright State University on Monday, though
UD officials said a handful of classes were cancelled because
professors were stranded at airports around the country, unable to
make connecting flights to Dayton in time for the start of classes.
</P>
<P>
   UD will not penalize students for missing class Monday if they
could not return to campus because of weather, said UD spokeswoman
Pam Huber.
</P>
<P>
   WSU's Lake Campus canceled classes Monday, but the main campus
did not. It is up to the professors' discretion whether to penalize
Monday absences, a WSU spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service was trying to make deliveries in the
Dayton area Monday, but spokesman Lee Withers said carriers were
being slowed down by unshoveled sidewalks and driveways, and ``we
may run out of daylight'' before all deliveries were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 concern is for the safety of our carriers and our
drivers,'' Withers said. ``I can say in the 454 (ZIP Code) area,
we're making an attempt to deliver. We ask that our customers be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm had little impact on the area's air freight companies.
</P>
<P>
   Emery Worldwide wasn't operating Friday through Sunday because
of the New Year's holiday, said Jim LaScala, human resources
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working feverishly today to clear the ramp,'' he said.
``It's almost clear as we speak. We expect to be pretty close to on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Airborne Express in Wilmington had crews salting the runway
before the storm began Friday night, ``and they've just been
working ever since,'' said spokeswoman Rita Carey. She said
Airborne had some delays Saturday because snow and ice on the ramp
slowed down loading and unloading of planes, but that problem has
been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky it happened on a holiday weekend, because we
didn't have a whole lot (of deliveries),'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   Piqua Police Lt. Tom Higgins said anyone venturing out in this
weather should have winter protection kits in their vehicles,
including blankets, extra clothes, a cell phone or CB radio, shovel
and road salt or sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the best thing is to stay home,'' Higgins said. ``If you
don't have to be out there, don't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
Reporters Tom Beyerlein, Jim DeBrosse, Mark Fisher, Lou Grieco,
Lisa Perry and Brandon Peterson contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
