<HEADLINE>
LAST FLINGS OF THE 20TH AND 200TH CENTURIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the sophisticated design magazine Metropolis asked 50
famous designers what innovations the next 12 months will bring,
most answers were grand ( &UR; Esther Dyson &LR;  suggested mapping the
Internet) or baffling (``white paint,'' said architect &UR; Frank &LR; 
 &UR; Gehry &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Clothing designer  &UR; Betsey Johnson  &LR; was practical: ``Why does
every laptop, every computer, every cell phone have to be black or
cream?'' Johnson suggests hot pink or chartreuse, to bring ``an
aesthetic element to technology.'' But if she's not colorblind,
she's behind the times: Nokia already makes colored cell phones,
and the iMac is turquoise and white.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Checking out the Web site of his hometown of Millbrae,
Calif.,  &UR; Steve Finacom  &LR; was disappointed _ and impatient _ when he
read that construction on the 8.7-mile BART extension from Colma to
Millbrae, begun in August 1997, is aimed for ``completion in the
year 20001.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ U-Decide, a set of cards designed to serve as an
``inspirational decision-making tool'' for women, ``empowering its
users to make confident choices,'' includes quotations from
 &UR; Pliny the &LR;   &UR; Elder &LR; ,  &UR; Benjamin Franklin &LR; , &UR; Helen Keller  &LR; and
 &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Diana &LR; , who said, ``Everyone needs to be valued.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 'Twas the season:  &UR; Barbara Lewis &LR;  received a Christmas
greeting/letter from her dentist that celebrated the year's
achievements, including ``saliva tests and antibody treatment for
dental decay-causing bacteria.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Angela Weber  &LR; was fascinated to read in Virgin Airline's
in-flight magazine, Hot Air: ``During depressurized flight, the
volume of intestinal gas inside the gut of test pilots and
astronauts expands with altitude. At 35,000 feet, the volume is 5.4
times what it would have been at sea level.'' Readers turning up
their noses at what they perceive as low humor should consider the
real peril, noted in Hot Air, of asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jury members watching TV during breaks in proceedings of the
Los Angeles Superior Court last year got into a fight while
watching ``The Jerry Springer Show,'' says the Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gloria Gomez &LR; , manager of juror services, confirmed ``problems
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest issue of Art and Antiques notes that novelist
 &UR; Danielle Steel  &LR; owns a full-scale carving of a camel, bought in
Paris, of course.
</P>
<P>
   _ A worker's compensation claim for $77,000, filed by a
Milwaukee court reporter who said she had suffered ``vicarious
trauma'' as a result of working on the court trial of  &UR; Jeffrey &LR; 
 &UR; Dahmer &LR; , has been denied, reports the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIRTH OF THE BLUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Comedian  &UR; Jon Stewart &LR; , who emceed a recent fund-raising dinner
in New York for a Jewish educational foundation, said Jews and
blacks had taken different approaches to being persecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks wrote blues and Jews complained,'' Stewart said. ``We
just never thought about putting it to music.'' He said his
grandmother had written a blues song called `` `Gee, It's Drafty in
Here.' And Side B is `Now It's Too Hot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN MANNERS FAIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   British-born editor  &UR; Harold Evans &LR;  revealed at a luncheon in New
York recently that he was re-educated when he came to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   He learned on his first trip, in the '50s, ``that the elaborate
English way of speaking did not play,'' he said, in remarks quoted
in the New York Observer. Visiting Chicago, ``I bought a ticket at
the el. `Thank you, thank you, thank you very much,' I said. The
guy behind the ticket window lunged, `Did you say something,
(unisex body aperture deemed unmentionable)?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GUESS WHO'S COMING TO DINNER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lennart Ohlsson  &LR; reports from Stockholm, where the Nobel Prizes
were handed out in December, that American winners are bringing
such large posses with them these days that there's no room at the
official celebration banquet for the Swedes.
</P>
<P>
   Stockholm TV reported that Swedish political leaders usually
invited to the banquet were relegated to a restaurant meal when one
American brought 40 guests to the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   This ``may be a sign of the increasing affluence of the U.S.
population in general,'' says economist Ohlsson, ``or of top class
scientists in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Women usually like taking side trips to crafts markets, but
men would never do that. Men hate crafts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Women's travel club founder Phyllis Stoller, quoted in the
Wall Street Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-POLITICS-BOS &LR;      01-04 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL FORCES BUILD OVER EURO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Even by Monday morning standards, when grumpiness on
the Underground is de rigueur, Paul Johnson looked especially
sullen Monday as he stood in a crowded aisle of a Northern Line
train bound for his job in the City, London's financial center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm exhausted,'' the 40-year-old financial analyst confessed.
``I worked right through the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the sleepless sacrifice of Johnson and an estimated
30,000 City bankers, stockbrokers and computer technicians that
propelled the euro off to a smooth start Monday, even though
Britain is one of four of the European Union's 15 members that are
not participating in the new single currency effort.
</P>
<P>
   If Monday marked the practical start of the euro, which was
launched New Year's Day but not traded until Monday, it also
signaled the opening salvo of what promises to be a spirited,
divisive political battle here in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And while most of the modern political battles here have cleaved
along opposing positions staked out by the Conservative Party and
the more liberal Labor Party, it became clear Monday that the
debate over whether Britain should join Euroland will be less
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, the Labor leader, said he
wants to join the single currency, but will leave it to the British
people in a referendum that won't be held for at least three or
four more years. But David Owen, who was a foreign minister for a
Labor government in the late 1970s and since 1992 has served in the
House of Lords, the upper house of Parliament, emerged Monday as a
key convert to the ``No'' campaign. Owen, long considered a
``europhile'' in favor of closer cooperation in Europe, said he
drew the line at a single currency, saying it was too much a
surrender of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The former Conservative leader and prime minister, Edward Heath,
simultaneously emerged as an unlikely champion of the euro. Heath
said Britain had wasted 22 years dithering on whether to join the
European Union, and now he worries that the country will do the
same on the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The British were not the only ones bickering about the euro.
French and Germans stepped up their war of words over how long Wim
Duisenberg, the Dutch banker who last year was elected to an 8-year
term as president of the new European Central Bank, should serve.
While the French claim there was a deal that Duisenberg would step
down after four years, the Germans want Duisenberg to serve out his
full term to provide stability for the new currency.
</P>
<P>
   While the political battles raged, the markets purred. Traders
like Jeramy Batstone of NatWest Stockbrokers, a British brokerage
house, said that while the volume of euro trading was low and it
had not yet been ``stress-tested,'' the first day of trading went
smoothly nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The new currency had what analysts consider a glitch-free launch
across the continent, gaining slightly on the US dollar and British
pound. Computer systems throughout Europe were ready to begin
trading in the euro Monday morning after an army of workers, like
Johnson in London, recalibrated them to recognize the new currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro has been greeted well,'' concluded Jean-Claude
Trichet, governor of the Bank of France, breathing a sigh of relief
that echoed across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   The debut was marred only in Amsterdam, where anarchists smashed
a custard pie into the face of Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm
when he arrived at the Dutch stock exchange for the start of
trading. The anarchists claimed the euro is ``authoritarian.''
</P>
<P>
   London traders were considerably more hospitable to the new
currency, despite the fact that Britain is avoiding the euro, at
least for now. Few of them believe the doomsayers who predict the
end of the City as Europe's financial capital. As one trader at
Merrill Lynch observed, the multinational makeup of the City
ensures that many deals involving euros will still be made in
London.
</P>
<P>
   About six times as many foreign exchange deals currently are
made in London as Frankfurt, Europe's other major financial capital
and now home to the new European Central Bank that sets monetary
policy for the 11 nations that have joined ``Euroland,'' the new
name for the bloc using the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Because it handles about a third of the world's foreign exchange
deals and is home to some 500 international banks _ the most in the
world _ the euro will be traded in the City despite Britain's
reticence to join the currency.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, it will not be circulated as hard cash
but rather as another currency that can be used in electronic
transactions, credit card purchases and travelers checks. In
January 2002, euro coins and bills will begin to circulate, and six
months later the national currencies of the 11 countries will be
withdrawn from circulation.
</P>
<P>
   While traders and bankers shrugged at the smooth start, the
amount of retooling necessary beforehand was staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a news agency, Reuters also supplies financial
information to more than half the stockbrokers in the City. About
300 of the 700 workers used by the company worldwide during the
weekend conversion were here in London. Geoffrey Sanderson, who
leads Reuters' euro program, said 1 billion pieces of data had to
be converted, including prices for 47,000 futures, 20,000 European
share issues, and 6,000 government and corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Financial institutions enticed workers to take part in the
round-the-clock operation by promising bonuses and perks, and by
providing free food, rooms and, in some instances, vintage
champagne when it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Capital, a money management firm, booked 80 rooms at
the Britannia Hotel in the Docklands section so its conversion
specialists could sleep without going home.
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer, Britain's biggest department store chain, said
it would accept payments in euros. But by mid-afternoon, cashiers
at the Oxford Street store, in London's busiest shopping district,
said they were still awaiting their first euro transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't hold my breath,'' a cashier sighed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
