<SLUG> BC-CLOONEY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old movies bring fame to a former journalist
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nick Clooney has spent a lifetime in what he calls ``this
general communications racket,'' the interlocking industry of show
biz and news and talking about both. These days, the former
anchorman _ father of George, brother of Rosemary _ is better known
than he's ever been, talking about old movies on the cable network
American Movie Classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All films are history,'' he says. ``They tell us what we
laughed at, what we drank, what we smoked, how we felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when those old movies seem, from today's vantage, racist or
sexist. AMC shows old Charlie Chan movies, Tarzan movies with
horrific stereotypes of Africans, and Westerns that were
``demeaning, degrading or patronizing,'' in Clooney's words, in
their presentation of Native Americans. Watch a great old musical
like ``Holiday Inn'' on AMC, and there, smack in the middle, is a
minstrel number, with white actors in blackface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some black family is watching that, that's gonna jolt the hell
out of 'em,'' Clooney acknowledges. ``That's why I try to describe
it in advance. I understand the criticisms (of showing such old
movies). But we're not gonna cut that out, not gonna P.C. it. This
is how we were; that's the truth of how we felt at that instant.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his son George of ``ER'' and movie fame, Nick Clooney is a
talker, holding forth over lunch at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in
Buckhead about meeting Orson Welles, gossip about Richard Widmark,
how Henry Fonda was discovered, the state of journalism today. He's
in Atlanta this week as guest co-host of WXIA's ``Peachtree
Morning,'' the 9 a.m. talk show, along with his wife, Nina, and
their foundling dog, Spags.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, 62, almost got into movies himself, following his
sister Rosemary (``White Christmas'') to Hollywood, where he read
for Cecil B. DeMille. The producer liked his looks and his voice,
but told him, ``You look 18 and sound 40. Come back when the
qualities merge.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clooney went into the Army, got into the communications
racket, substituted for Dick Clark on ``American Bandstand,''
hosted a talk show in Cincinnati (near his home in Maysville, Ky.)
and was a TV news anchor and news director as high up as KNBC in
Los Angeles. For the past four years, he's been AMC's main
ambassador and started his own research library (600 books and
growing) to help him write his movie introductions.
</P>
<P>
   The movie that's on his mind at the moment is ``Out of Sight,''
which just beat ``Saving Private Ryan'' for best film in a surprise
vote by the National Society of Film Critics. Although the movie
was not a hit, some critics considered it George Clooney's best
work yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that great?'' he beams, then recounts the critical
reception of ``Out of Sight'' and the European box office tallies
(No. 1 in Britain for two weeks, ``No. 2 or 3 in Italy'').
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't yet talked about the win to George, who's filming his
final ``ER'' episode this week in Los Angeles (airing in late
February). But he has thought about how his life turned out,
keeping him connected to the movies, but never in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things work out the way they're supposed to work,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
