<HEADER>
A7924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAPERWAR05-COX     01-04 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERWAR05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With today's merger of the morning Times and the afternoon Free
Press, a city mourns the passing of a journalism legacy
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA _ This time the Yankees are going, not coming. And a
lot of Chattanoogans are sad to see them leave.
</P>
<P>
   The 130-year-old Chattanooga Times _ an institution built by
Adolph Ochs, an Ohio-born rabbi's son famous for his role in making
The New York Times great _ has surrendered to its archrival, the
home-grown Chattanooga Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, the morning Times (circulation 42,000) and the
afternoon Free Press (circulation 40,000) are one morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' capitulation comes after decades of strident
squabbling between the two papers, both of which were family-owned.
Ochs' descendents _ liberal, Jewish, old-money _ ran the Times. The
McDonald family _ conservative, Christian, newer money _ owned the
Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a strange mix of philosophies,'' says Peter
Pringle, a journalism professor at the University of
Tennessee-Chattanooga. ``There's so much bad blood between them.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while _ nobody will say how long _ the new paper will
carry both names. Still, partisan readers of both papers are leery
about the merger and new, out-of-town ownership of the combined
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're damn tootin', it's very upsetting,'' says Frances
Alexander, an executive of Chattanooga's Tennessee American Water
Co. ``The Times is as much a part of our history as the Battle of
Lookout Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Bonds, a bartender at the Big River Grill, is just as
worried about what might happen to the old afternoon paper, once it
absorbs the Times. ``I've always read the Free Press,'' she says.
``It's got more of that hometown feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Ochs bought the struggling Times in 1878, the paper has
seen itself as a bastion of big-city-style journalism, trumpeting
civic progress and championing such causes as civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Press, on the other hand, was started in 1933 by a
grocer, the late Roy McDonald, who gave it away to advertise
products sold in his stores. It has always reflected a conservative
Christian viewpoint in its news columns, as well as on its
editorial page. Into the 1990s, it still referred to the Chinese as
``Reds.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Times has been known for pushing education and
national and world news on its front page, the Free Press' claim to
fame has been local coverage, fires, crime and ribbon-cuttings,
wrapped around ``grip and grin'' photographs sent in by readers.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day, for example, while the Times ran photos of the
Clinton impeachment hearings on its front, the Free Press displayed
a huge picture of a local restaurant that had burned, along with a
murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two couldn't be more different,'' says Kittrell Rushing, a
journalism professor at UT-Chattanooga. ``This merger is a real
blow to the city. The professional community and the educated folks
are very much concerned they won't even recognize the new paper.
And that's a real shame, because thanks to Adolph Ochs, this is
where modern, objective journalism was born.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's led to the takeover of the Times:
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War, the Times replaced the old Chattanooga
Rebel, which had fled the city just ahead of Union Gen. William T.
Sherman's invading army. (Its staff was captured and its presses
destroyed near Valdosta, Ga.) The 19-year-old Ochs, whose family
had moved from Cincinnati to Knoxville just after the war, borrowed
$2,000 to buy the Times in 1878, vowing to ``give the news without
fear or favor.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper prospered. When The New York Times, then considered an
industry rag, went on the block in 1896, Ochs bought it and moved
to the Big Apple. But he retained his Chattanooga ties and became
the leading force for preserving historic battlefields at
Chickamauga, Lookout Mountain and Missionary Ridge. He kept control
over the Times until his death in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   His only child, a daughter, inherited the paper, and she left it
to her four children. They in turn passed it to their 13 children,
who owned it in absentia until the recent sale. The family, which
continues to pump philanthropic dollars into the community, ran the
Times as an independent company, separate from The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Times owners' tried to buy the Free Press. But
its publisher, Lee Anderson, a former reporter who married into the
McDonald family, vowed never to sell to the ``Philistines.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their rivalry, the families tried to work together at
times. The Times and Free Press agreed as early as 1942 to save
costs by sharing the same building, presses and advertising and
clerical staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The families split the papers' operations in 1966, even though
that meant extra expenses. The Free Press moved to an 1880s hosiery
mill, lugged in old presses from storage and started publishing a
Sunday paper in competition with the Times. The Times fired back by
starting its own short-lived afternoon paper, the Post.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the papers entered another agreement. It required the
Times to kill its Sunday paper, leaving that lucrative market to
the Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   The competition might have continued, with the Times owning an
edge in daily circulation and the Free Press publishing the big
Sunday edition. But the Free Press' Anderson is 73, and Frank
McDonald, son of the Free Press' founder, is 69 and seriously ill.
Neither had children who wanted to take an active ownership role.
</P>
<P>
   So in March, the family sold the Free Press to Walter E. Hussman
Jr., 51, a mild-mannered but tough-minded businessman who heads
WEHCO Media of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Hussman, at 27, had taken over the Arkansas Democrat and led it
in a 17-year war with the older and larger Arkansas Gazette. He
won, defeating the powerful Gannett chain, and since 1991, Little
Rock has been a one-newspaper town.
</P>
<P>
   When Hussman bought the Free Press, the Times chose not to
compete with his empire and put itself on the block as well.
Hussman's Free Press bought it and announced the two papers would
be combined.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Holmberg, 76, Ochs' granddaughter and Times publisher for
28 years until 1992, admits that the merger is a ``very sad
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Times readers will see things and say, 'Ah, I don't
want to read this.''' Holmberg says. ``A lot of people are very
emotional about the Times. I run into people on the street who say,
'Oh, I just can't talk about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   She shares the readers' dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was an icon in this city. I feel like I've lost
the first of my children.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her children, however, who sealed the paper's fate.
Holmberg says the next generation of her family, who all live
elsewhere, didn't think it would be worth sinking $50 million into
the Times to save it.
</P>
<P>
   But she bravely maintains that the merger won't kill her
grandfather's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Times has not died,'' declares Holmberg. ``It's going to
be reborn.'' She's optimistic that with a bigger editorial staff,
the merged paper will be better than either the old Times or Free
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Times managing editor Ron Smith, whose job ended Monday, talks
hopefully about his old paper's future as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the afternoon paper that's disappearing,'' he insists.
``The afternoon newspaper did not win the war here.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone knows it did.
</P>
<P>
   The Times published for the last time Monday, and surviving
staff members trooped from 11th Street to 10th, from their offices
in a clean, modern structure to the Free Press' dusty old structure
with exposed water pipes and heat ducts and boxes of supplies
stacked everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Times staff took the biggest hit, with 19 of 56 staffers
given pink slips. At the Free Press, 19 of 89 lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who keeps a big, black Bible on his huge desk and who
has written Free Press editorials for decades, doesn't quite
foresee a born-again Times. Anderson, who will serve as an
associate publisher of the new paper, vows it will be based ``on
the Constitution and the Bible, like we've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson stresses that ``it'll be run from here'' because
``Walter wants a Chattanooga newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Local service is our strong point,'' he says. ``We ran 11,000
pictures last year.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, at least, the new paper will have facing editorial
pages, one on the left reflecting the Ochs tradition of liberal
views and on the right, conservative opinions of the McDonalds.
It's not clear whether this will last; Hussman's Arkansas paper has
only one editorial voice _ conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be six weeks, six months, six years or forever,''
says Paul Neely, former publisher of the Times and now an associate
publisher of the hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hussman says the combined paper should satisfy
customers of both papers. He foresees a slight drop in weekday
circulation, but growth on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's being lost is afternoon delivery,'' he grins.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chattanoogans, though, don't see it that way. They openly
mourn the loss of their tie to Ochs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to point out, when people visit, not only Missionary
Ridge and Lookout Mountain, but to tell them that in a sense, The
New York Times started here. It's a very nice thing to be able to
say,'' says Jeff Messinger, owner of the upscale Mount Vernon
Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga native Franklin Seymour calls the merger ``a sad
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've driven up the Ochs Highway to my job for 23 years,'' he
says. ``We're losing a legacy, and we're going to feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chattanooga Times covers its demise as an independent paper:
http://www.chattimes.com/.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Hendrick is a staff writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
