<HEADLINE>
SECRET-LOAN SCANDAL CLAIMS THIRD BLAIR OFFICIAL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A scandal that has already cost Prime Minister Tony
Blair his closest political confidant and a principal connection to
big business claimed a third government official on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Charlie Whelan, said he was leaving as press
secretary to Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, the second
most powerful man in the government. He said the ``absurd'' level
of public attention to his possible role in the departure of two
officials 12 days ago made it too difficult for him to carry on
with his job.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, Peter Mandelson, 45, the trade and industry minister
who was Blair's chief aide and architect of the Labor Party's 1997
election victory, and Geoffrey Robinson, 60, a millionaire
industrialist who served as paymaster general, quit their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Behind all three departures was a secret $625,000 home loan from
Robinson to Mandelson in 1996, which Mandelson failed to reveal
even when Robinson's outside financial affairs became the subject
of an investigation by the department Mandelson came to head.
</P>
<P>
   The episode has become the first major disruption in the smooth
operation of the 20-month-old Blair government. Blair has obtained
the highest approval ratings of any prime minister in modern
British history, but when he returns from a visit to South Africa
this week he will face challenges to his government's reputation
for discipline and control.
</P>
<P>
   Blair vigorously campaigned for office on claims that his
government would put an end to the kinds of scandals that forced
out 12 of Prime Minister John Major's ministers. And the current
incident exposes tensions between his office and Brown's that date
to the keen competition between the two men for the leadership of
the party after the death in 1994 of its former head, John Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Whelan, 44, a Brown loyalist long seen as a stoker of a
simmering feud between his boss and Mandelson, was suspected of
being the person who disclosed the secret loan arrangement between
Mandelson and Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Monday saying he would be quitting ``as soon
as an appropriate opportunity becomes available,'' Whelan denied
that he was the one who turned Mandelson in, but said he was
leaving government anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it absolutely clear that I was not responsible
for disclosing any information about Peter Mandelson's mortgage and
I refute any suggestion that I was,'' he said. ``I do, however,
take the view that the job of press secretary becomes extremely
difficult if the press secretary, and not the department he serves,
becomes the story and the subject of excessive attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Press secretaries and information management have become stories
more often in this government than in past British ones because of
the importance the Blair people attach to presentation, or
``spin.'' Alastair Campbell, a former correspondent for The Daily
Mirror who is Blair's spokesman, has insisted on a level of
coordination in the issuance of government information that has
been unseen until now in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has often been reported to be put out with Whelan's
independence and resistance to direction from 10 Downing Street. On
Monday, he bade him a blunt farewell, saying, ``I have got no doubt
whatever that he will find work that he will probably enjoy more
and which will use his talents well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whelan and Mandelson shared the same press honorific, ``spin
doctor,'' but little else. Whelan, a Communist in his youth and a
former union press officer, is affable, gruff, profane, someone who
The Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said ``never
called a spade a spade when he could call it a bloody shovel.''
Mandelson is silky and urbane, an Oxford graduate with cosmopolitan
tastes in friends and clothes who embraced the world of business
and taught the once-socialist Labor Party to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson accepted the loan from his millionaire colleague on
the Labor back benches when he decided to move from a modest
apartment to a house costing $790,000 in the fashionable Notting
Hill area of West London. He said he expected that a family
inheritance would enable him to pay it back promptly.
</P>
<P>
   Whelan fell under suspicion in the last 10 days of intense media
speculation because he is a friend of Paul Routledge, a journalist
who last year composed an admiring biography of Brown and has now
written a damning one of Mandelson, which began serialization in
The Mirror on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The information about the secret mortgage was in the first
chapter of Routledge's book, but The Guardian published it first on
Dec. 22, leading Mandelson and Robinson to resign the next day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
