<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7931 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES05-COX     01-04 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late talks fail to rescue Hayes
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell and Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hayes Corp. on Monday laid off all but a handful of
employees, after running out of cash when bankers slammed the door
on financing for anything but a liquidation of the once-proud
company.
</P>
<P>
   Once the leading maker of analog modems, Hayes sent about 250
employees home without severance packages, apparently giving up the
ghost after months of struggle through sagging sales, feuding
executives and a stock price crashing toward zero.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the end loomed, officials were still negotiating
with potential ``white knights'' who might have purchased Hayes,
said Ron Howard, Hayes' chief executive officer. ``As late as this
weekend, we had significant interest in the sale of the company as
a going concern, but the bank wouldn't fund that.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks ended Monday, and the company moved to close down.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, which filed for bankruptcy protection Oct. 9, once
dominated the modem market. Although the company slipped into
bankruptcy in 1994, Hayes fought off takeover attempts and emerged
in 1996, an independent company with projections of $300 million in
revenue. The company reported several strong quarters and then
began to battle falling sales and disappearing profit margins. The
company had hoped to hang on while it nurtured new technologies for
high-speed connections to the Internet. But the bridge to that
future depended on either a rebound in sales or in reshaping itself
to slash costs.
</P>
<P>
   Howard on Monday declined to name potential suitors. But Hayes
had been in talks with Kaifa Technology of Taiwan and another
unnamed company that would have put the Hayes name on modems it
manufactured. Even as its debts grew steeper, Hayes officials had
hoped such a deal to outsource production would offer a way to keep
the company alive.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations produced no deal.
</P>
<P>
   NationsCredit, which had funded the limping company after its
fall into bankruptcy protection Oct. 9, put officials on notice two
weeks ago that it would not fund efforts to find a suitor or to
keep the company in business. When Hayes failed to find alternate
sources of revenue _ a buyer or a big contract _ it had no choice
but to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done what the bank demanded, and this is an incredibly
sad day,'' said Howard, who came to the company with high hopes a
year ago in a merger with Access Beyond. ``I am sort of at the
emotional end. This has been a tear-filled day, crying with a great
group of employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Through years of turmoil, the Hayes work force had been shaved
from more than 1,200 to fewer than 500 in November, when the
company shut down its manufacturing unit. Those who stayed until
the end now must get into queue with other creditors, hoping a
liquidation will leave them a few scraps of severance.
</P>
<P>
   Workers were told Monday to attend a 3 p.m. meeting at the
company's one-story headquarters in Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   P.K. Chan, company president and manufacturing chief, passed out
a one-page letter from Howard to employees written on stationery
that proclaimed the company's 20th anniversary last year. The
letter offered little hope to employees but, then, after all the
bumps in the road, few were shocked at the turn that took them to a
dead end.
</P>
<P>
   Workers interviewed after the meeting declined to give their
names. An engineer who spent 15 years with the company said he went
to the meeting expecting bad news, but hoping the business would
continue, at least limited operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably made some bad decisions toward the end,'' he
said. But even as late as last summer, the company seemed to be
showing promise, he said. ``We had a lot of orders coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Another worker, a nine-year employee, blamed the decision made
late last year to go public, arguing that it was premature. Going
public, ``you had a higher authority to answer to.''
</P>
<P>
   Many employees who left months ago were given generous severance
checks. Not so Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody expected it (the closing), but at least we thought
we would get some severance,'' said a worker. Yet despite the lack
of an extra paycheck, ``everybody seemed to take it pretty good,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loading her minivan, one office worker said she joined the
company two and half years ago shortly after it had emerged from
its first sojourn in bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally came here thinking I could be on the dream team
with Mr. (founder Dennis) Hayes bringing the company back, and I
honestly thought we were going to be able to turn it around. I hate
it for Mr. Hayes,'' she said. ``He built something really good
here, and to see it go down and him get kicked out ...''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hayes has been alternately cursed and hailed for his role
in founding the company and steering it from upstart to dominance _
and then into trouble. Yet in bankruptcy court, Hayes had made an
impassioned plea that he be permitted to reject takeover bids that
ranged up to $140 million. As the prime shareholder, he would have
been the prime recipient of those offers, but he wanted the company
to remain independent and in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   To convince the judge, Hayes accepted investment that diluted
his control, hired a chief executive officer and gave up day-to-day
control of operations. But the CEO stayed less than two years.
After the merger with Access Beyond, Howard became CEO _ and the
two men did not get along.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Hayes agreed to resign as chairman of the board.
Monday, he declined to comment on the company's fate or on his own
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes Corp. owes creditors about $42 million. The company has
several hundred creditors, although the bulk of the debt is owed to
NationsCredit and a few large suppliers like Lucent Technologies,
which says it is owed $4.8 million, and another chip maker,
Rockwell Semiconductor Systems, which alleges a debt of $2.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Campbell, attorney for the committee representing
creditors, said the company is not formally being liquidated. ``In
order to have a liquidation you'd have to sell all the assets,
employ an auctioneer and so on, and that would require a court
order.''
</P>
<P>
   The next court session is set for Jan. 19, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said that while formal sale of assets has not begun, the
company is no longer in business. ``The company is being
liquidated. The company is no longer being operated as a going
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he will remain chairman of the board but is no
longer an employee.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Hayes would mark the fall of one of Atlanta's
brightest and earliest technology stars. But while Hayes dimmed and
declined, the company was also eclipsed by newer technologies aimed
at the Internet, electronic commerce or biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes was surely no meteor, its fall taking years. And as the
light from Hayes fades, remaining employees can at least emerge
into a vibrant economy, a bustling market for high-tech talent.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Reiser, a software engineer, joined the company three
years ago. Like many colleagues, he started sending out resumes in
recent months after growing difficulties grew ever more grim. He
does not expect to be without comparable work for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some good prospects,'' Reiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell and Matt Kempner write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
