<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-SHOW-BOS &LR;      01-04 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SHOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE DEVOTEES GATHER WITH NEW CONFIDENCE ABOUT COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly two years after Apple Computer Inc.
advertisements began imploring computer users to ``think
different,'' the company has given the entire industry plenty to
think about.
</P>
<P>
   After a long period of massive losses and plummeting sales for
its Macintosh computers, Apple has mounted a comeback that has
astonished the industry. Its new iMac personal computer has become
the best-selling desktop machine in America, boosting Apple's share
of the market for the first time in years. Better yet, the company
is making money again _ $309 million in fiscal year 1998, which
ended in September.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means that this week's MacWorld, a gathering in San
Francisco of Apple computer users, is the most upbeat in a long
time. A crowd of about 600 responded Monday with lusty cheers to
the greeting from computer-industry journalist David Pogue:
``Welcome to the first MacWorld conference that nobody thinks will
be the last MacWorld conference.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the dramatic revival of Apple's fortunes, severe
challenges lie ahead. Apple is stable and profitable once again,
but it's an open question whether the company can do what it must
to secure its long-term survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the phase where they cut and tightened up and got
into shape,'' said Bruce Stephen, industry analyst with
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. Although Apple has
gained some market share, he added, ``we think they're going to be
a niche player.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, a close look at Apple's 1998 results shows that most
of the company's profit came from cost cutting, including the
elimination of 4,200 jobs and a reduction in spending on research
and development. Lower spending on research is a risky move for a
high-tech company whose future depends on a steady stream of new
products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, unit sales of Macintosh computers actually declined
last fiscal year, to 2.763 million, from 2.874 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, Apple introduced iMac, and the elegant desktop
machine has led to a burst of new Macintosh sales. The market
research firm PC Data Inc. reported last week that Apple's iMac was
the best-selling personal computer in America in November. The iMac
represented 9.1 percent of all PCs sold, by dollar volume, in
November, up from 6 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, priced at $1,300, was the company's attempt to regain
a foothold in the home computer market. But anecdotal evidence
suggests that the iMac is also finding a place in many businesses,
as an inexpensive computer that connects easily to corporate data
networks. Keith Geck, Apple's vice president for business sales,
cited a recent sale of 300 iMacs to Genentech Inc. of San
Francisco, a major biopharmaceutical firm. ``We're beginning to see
good acceptance of iMac inside organizations,'' Geck said.
</P>
<P>
   But barriers to greater acceptance of Macintosh computers remain
formidable. Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies, a
computer-industry research firm, sobered the crowd by declaring
that Macs will never make up more than 10 percent of all desktop
machines. ``Whether we like it or not,'' he warned, ``the desktop
war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner, of course, was rival Microsoft Corp., whose Windows
software is on well over 90 percent of the world's desktop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Apple can't hope to prevail over the long run by simply selling
to its base of loyal customers, Bajarin said. ``They need new users
if Apple is to be around five years from now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bajarin hopes the company can find these new users in millions
of households which still lack cheap, easy-to-use computing
devices. Apple, he argued, is well-placed to serve that market.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry-watchers had expected Apple to address the home
computing market this week by showing off a new portable _ a sort
of entry-level laptop . Apple is known to be working on such
devices, but last week company officials flatly denied that these
machines would be on display at MacWorld.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rumors abound that during his keynote speech on Tuesday,
Apple's interim chief executive officer Steve Jobs will make some
dramatic announcements. He's expected to provide details about a
new series of high-end Macs codenamed Yosemite, and intended for
heavy-duty users in publishing, graphic arts and the sciences. He
may also announce dramatic price cuts
</P>
<P>
   on the iMac that could bring the price of a basic unit below
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because Apple makes hardware as well as software, the company
has no choice but to lower prices, in Bajarin's view. ``The whole
concept of premium pricing is dead,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   But it's unclear whether Apple can maintain its recent level of
profits while selling cheaper machines. The company's gross margin
on sales was a healthy 25 percent in the last quarter of fiscal
1998, but even Apple officials predict that this will come down
because of the need to slash prices.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important topic on the MacWorld agenda will be
the latest news about Mac OS X, the company's long-delayed new
operating system which is supposed to debut this year. OS X, built
around a core based on the advanced Unix operating system, could
finally make the Mac competitive with Microsoft Windows NT among
high-end operating systems for running corporate computer networks.
And the new version of Windows NT, renamed Windows 2000, has
suffered delays, giving Mac OS X an opportunity to win new
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Macintosh loyalists gathered here are expecting mainly good
news from Jobs. But nobody is ready to declare victory yet. ``These
guys are realistic,'' said Bajarin. ``They can get into a rah-rah,
but at the end of the day, these people know as well as anyone that
this company is still fighting for its life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
