<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLAT-AIRTOUCH-BOS &LR;      01-04 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLAT-AIRTOUCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC WOULD GAIN NATIONAL REACH WITH AIRTOUCH DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Corp.'s proposed acquisition of AirTouch
Communications Inc. would become a second linchpin of the New
York-based telephone carrier's plans to become a nationwide player
in telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which has lost some wireless telephone customers
since AT&AMP;T Corp. launched its national single-rate calling program
last year, would be better able to compete against AT&AMP;T with a
one-rate service coast-to-coast.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of having a national wireless footprint akin to
AT&AMP;T's _ is the most immediate reason why Bell Atlantic wants to
spend around $45 billion to acquire AirTouch Communications of San
Francisco in a stock swap. AirTouch would provide Bell Atlantic
with a dominant West Coast presence in wireless.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier strategic move to expand coast to coast, Bell
Atlantic agreed to buy GTE Corp. for $52.9 billion, a deal expected
to close later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, a spokesman for Bell Atlantic Mobile stressed that
the complex negotiations are continuing and that no definitive
agreement has been completed. Over the weekend, both companies
confirmed they are in merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are already partners in a company, called PrimeCo
Personal Communications, which offers wireless digital services in
communities between the two coasts that are not served by either
AirTouch or Bell Atlantic .
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch is the leading mobile telephone carrier in California
and other West Coast markets and, like Bell Atlantic, lacks a
national calling program like AT&AMP;T's Digital One-Rate, which
provides customers with a single rate for a fixed number of
minutes, eliminating ``roaming,'' long distance and other fees.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T owns most of its nationwide wireless network, enabling it
to hold down costs. By contrast, Bell Atlantic, whose mobile
telephone service is largely limited to 13 East Coast states, must
rely on other regional carriers to complete calls. Because Bell
Atlantic must access fees to the other carriers, its single-rate
plan is more costly.
</P>
<P>
   With the expected acquisition of GTE Corp., which serves parts
of California, Texas, Tennessee and several other states states
plus scattered markets nationwide, Bell Atlantic would still lack a
cohesive wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   The AirTouch combination, along with PrimeCo, would catapult
Bell Atlantic into the top four national wireless telephone
carriers along with AT&AMP;T, Sprint PCS and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T changed the wireless market with its One-Rate program and
Bell Atlantic knows that to compete nationwide it must go
nationwide and spread out its reach plus lower its overall costs,''
said Judy Reed Smith, president of Atlantic ACM, a Boston
telecommunicaitons consulting and research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's wireless expansion quest is also a hedge against
expected declines in local and long distance calls over today's
telephone wires.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile telephone traffic is growing by leaps and may soon
eclipse local phone service as more and more people turn to cel
phones instead of traditional phones for everyday calling,
according to several market analysts. To make sure Bell Atlantic
does not lose its current customers to AT&AMP;T, Sprint or other
nationwide cellular telephone carriers, Bell Atlantic wants to
become a national wireless carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will start to see this year a lot of price reductions to
where wireless service is going to be the dominant voice
communications technology in about five years,'' predicted Andrew
Cole, senior manager of the wireless practice at Renaissance
Worldwide, Inc., a Stamford, Conn. consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All wireless carriers need to reduce their costs and rates,
which are now 9 cents to 17 cents (a minute), to around 3 cents in
the near future. And if Bell Atlantic wants to be a major
telecommunications player it must expand its wireless operations to
be cost competitive with AT&AMP;T, Sprint and other carriers.'' said
Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains uncertain whether Bell Atlantic and AirTouch
could strike a deal soon as Bell Atlantic reportedly wants to avoid
paying a big premium in its bid for the largest wireless phone
company.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, AirTouch shares closed at 68 1/4, down 4 3/16 while Bell
Atlantic dipped 2 1/16 to 51 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell Atlantic and AirTouch reach stalemate in their
negotiations, several other potential buyers could emerge,
including MCI Worldcom Inc., which unlike AT&AMP;T and Sprint, doesn't
own a wireless service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie Ebbers (MCI Worldcom chairman) has said in the past
year that he understands the strategic importance of owning a
wireless asset, '' said Scott Wright, telecommunications analyst
for Fahnestock &AMP; Co. ``And while there does not appear to be anyone
else in the wings, the rumored terms from Bell Atlantic may be
disappointing.'' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
