<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES05-COX     01-04 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunday's loss may send Holmgren packing
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after the season ended for Green Bay coach
Mike Holmgren, his stint with the Packers likely ended as well. The
team's gut-wrenching Sunday defeat at San Francisco meant other NFL
clubs could seek permission to discuss job vacancies with Holmgren.
Three teams _ Baltimore, Philadelphia and Seattle _ all phoned
Green Bay president Bob Harlan and general manager Ron Wolf on
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   According to his contract, which runs through the 1999 campaign,
Holmgren can leave the Packers for a job that provides him the dual
roles of coach and general manager. A team would have to send Green
Bay its second-round draft choice as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of speculation that he would replace Steve Mariucci
in San Francisco, it now appears Holmgren's likely landing spot is
Seattle. Owner Paul Allen, who tried to hire both Holmgren and Wolf
at various times last season, certainly has the financial
wherewithal to propose a blockbuster deal.
</P>
<P>
   League insiders and Green Bay officials told the
Journal-Constitution on Monday that a contract with Seattle could
be worked out within 48 hours. Through club president Bob Whitsitt,
the Seahawks are offering a five-year deal worth $4.2 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows what all the stipulations are in (Holmgren's)
contract with us,'' Wolf said. ''I'm under the assumption I still
have a coach for now. Mike has a window where he can look at other
things, but our goal remains keeping him here.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikely. In August, the Pack offered Holmgren a
contract extension worth close to $3 million annually and he
rejected it. Wolf has told confidants in the last 24 hours that he
feels Holmgren is off to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren could not be reached for comment but his agent, Bob
Lamonte, acknowledged he had a ''hectic day'' on Monday dealing
with his coveted client's options. In his seven seasons in Green
Bay, Holmgren has a record of 84-42.
</P>
<P>
   So who might coach the Packers next season? Wolf almost
certainly will not promote
</P>
<P>
   offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis or quarterbacks coach Andy
Reid, but those close to him feel he has had someone in mind for a
few weeks. It's believed Wolf talked to New York Jets assistant
head coach Bill Belichick. But the more likely successor to
Holmgren is former Philadelphia head coach Ray Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys codgers
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys looked old and used-up in Saturday's loss to Arizona
and no one more so than 13-year veteran guard Nate Newton. The
Cardinals' brilliant defensive game plan exploited the ''A'' gap
between center Mike Kiselak and Newton for several big plays by
linebackers Mark Maddox and Jamir Miller. But Newton, 37, wasn't
the only player who showed his age. Michael Irvin couldn't shake
the coverage of corner Aeneas Williams. Quarterback Troy Aikman
never demonstrated a sense of urgency. Tackle Erik Williams looked
confounded at times. ''This is not a young team and it's not
getting any younger,'' Deion Sanders warned afterwards. Despite the
denials of owner Jerry Jones, a major overhaul is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Chomping for Champ
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Bengals own the third overall selection in the
'99 draft and, while it's early, seem to be leaning toward choosing
a cornerback. Toward that end, the Bengals very quietly dispatched
defensive coordinator Dick LeBeau to the Georgia Dome last week to
watch Champ Bailey in the Peach Bowl. Because his paperwork for
entering the draft had not been finalized, scouts cannot yet
comment on Bailey. The Bengals feel they will lose corner Ashley
Ambrose in free agency and their other starter in '98 was rookie
Artrell Hawkins, a second-round choice.
</P>
<P>
   Art-ful dodger
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable element about Art Shell's denial he would be
interviewed by Cleveland Browns president Carmen Policy is that
league officials desperately wanted to get the word out on the
Falcons offensive line coach. In fact, NFL operatives were leaking
news of the interview to selected media on Saturday. Yet when Shell
was contacted by the Journal-Constitution, he claimed the reports
were wrong. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue knows he has a public
relations nightmare. Counting George Seifert in Carolina, there
have been 17 head coaching changes since Tony Dungy was hired in
Tampa Bay and none of the jobs went to minority candidates. League
officials have been phoning owners and requesting they be sensitive
to the race issue, and some have been. Former Philadelphia
defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas interviewed Monday for the head
coaching job in Baltimore. Current Kansas City offensive
coordinator Jimmy Raye will interview for the vacancy in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news Bears
</P>
<P>
   In addition to getting permission to talk with Raye, the Bears
also plan to meet with Chiefs defensive coordinator Gunther
Cuningham, Pittsburgh defensive coordinator Jim Haslett and former
UCLA coach Terry Donahue. There is a possibility Chicago will talk
with Lewis and Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching carousel
</P>
<P>
   Haslett, who will interview today in Seattle, may have
overplayed his hand in Philly, where he is viewed as the
front-runner. He reportedly told operations director Tom Modrak he
wants a seven-year contract and a $2.9 million budget for
assistants. After his interview in Seattle, Haslett will head to
Baltimore. . . . The Bears will have not made contact with Hall of
Fame linebacker Mike Singletary, who is lobbying for a shot at the
job. . . . San Diego GM Bobby Beathard is very interested in Oregon
State coach Mike Riley. . . . Although Falcons defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks said he has not been contacted about the
opening at the University of Washington, some people on the West
Coast are pushing hard for him there. . . . Rams owner Georgia
Frontiere will meet with her football braintrust in (of all places)
the new-age Mecca of Sedona, Ariz., today. It is believed she'll
agree with team president John Shaw that Dick Vermeil be retained
for another year. . . . Mike White could replace Jerry Rhome as
Rams offensive boss. . . . New England personnel director Bobby
Grier interviewed each player individually on Monday and asked each
about coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   The zebras
</P>
<P>
   In the press box at San Francisco on Sunday, director of
officiating Jerry Seeman told anyone who would listen that game
officials ruled correctly the day before on the play when it
appeared Buffalo wide receiver Andre Reed had scored against Miami.
Seeman was conspicuously quiet, though, when officials blew a call
on a Jerry Rice fumble that would have ended the 49ers comeback.
Second-year field judge Kevin Mack, who was closest to the fumble,
seemed to freeze on the play. Veteran line judge Jeff Bergman
instead came across to incorrectly rule that Rice's knee was down
before the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
