<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GOVERNOR PROCLAIMS ERA OF `HIGHER EXPECTATIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Declaring ``a time to do great things again,'' Gray
Davis took office Monday as the 37th governor of California,
pledging to overhaul the troubled public schools of the nation's
most populous state as the centerpiece of his efforts to shepherd
its growth and preserve its prosperity in a new century.
</P>
<P>
   In his inaugural address, Davis, the first Democrat to hold the
state's top job in 16 years, sounded forceful notes of contrast
with his Republican predecessor, Pete Wilson, and to a lesser
degree with his onetime boss, former Gov. Edmund G. Brown Jr.,
whose '70s-era skepticism led him to proclaim a time of lower
expectations for the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we begin a new chapter in the history of California: The
era of higher expectations,'' said Davis, who began his political
career as Brown's chief of staff, but Monday sounded like a more
optimistic Democratic forbear, Brown's father, Pat, who presided
over the state's explosive growth in the 1950s and '60s. ``We will
embark in a new direction guided by our lasting values.''
</P>
<P>
   After thanking Wilson for cooperating in the transition to a new
administration, Davis several times implicitly rebuked his
predecessor's highly publicized campaigns against affirmative
action and illegal immigration, telling a cheering audience at the
Memorial Auditorium here that ``you can finally ring down the
curtain on the politics of division.'' Those words left Wilson and
his wife, Gayle, the only people seated on the stage amid a
thunderous standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis, 56, a cautious, career politician who has spent most
of his adult life aiming for the job he assumed Monday, made it
clear that he plans no radical change, though Democrats control all
three branches of state government for the first time since Jerry
Brown's day. Instead, Davis repeated the moderate mantra that
helped him win a 20-point victory over his conservative Republican
opponent, former State Attorney General Dan Lungren, last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will govern neither from the right nor the left, but from
the center, propelled not by ideology, but by common sense that
seeks better results,'' Davis told a crowd that included Vice
President Al Gore and former Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is to begin work in earnest this week, when he presents
his first budget on Friday and, keeping a campaign promise, calls a
special session of the State Legislature to focus on improving
school accountability, increasing teacher preparation and assuring
that every child learns to read by the end of the third grade. None
of those tasks will be easy for Davis, who won office with strong
support from the state teachers union, which feuded bitterly with
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis fired a not-so-subtle warning shot across the
teachers' bow Monday, acknowledging: ``Yes, there are some
deficient teachers and principals out there,'' and adding: ``Under
my administration, they will either get better _ or they will be
encouraged to find another line of work.'' And he vowed: ``The time
has come to restore California's public schools to greatness. The
voters demand it, our future depends on it, and I am determined to
make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican minority leader of the State Assembly, Rod
Pacheco of Riverside, said he agreed with ``a lot of what I
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican themes,'' Pacheco said. ``That's good. We'll do
what we can to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much Davis can do about education in the short term
remains to be seen. In the last two years of Wilson's
administration, the legislature and voters approved several
changes, from smaller class sizes for early elementary grades to
mandatory testing of students to an end to most bilingual
education, that are still being phased in. And despite a booming
economy, state and local government budgets remain relatively
tight, in part because of restrictions on taxation like Proposition
13, the 1978 ballot measure that capped local property tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But while Davis has made it clear that he will not try to reopen
past policy debates, like the ballot measure that overturned
affirmative action programs, he has already sent some signals of
change, like appointing the state's first black and Asian cabinet
members. And with a 23-year career in politics, Davis, who
campaigned against a field of richer, flashier Democratic rivals
with the slogan, ``Experience Money Can't Buy,'' has a good idea of
what he may be in for.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his career, as a state assemblyman, controller and,
for the last four years, lieutenant governor, Davis was mocked as a
tireless fund-raiser, who rode his staff hard and was as bland as
his first name. But he is having the last laugh now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, sometimes a person meets his moment,'' Davis said in
an interview published Monday in The Sacramento Bee. ``I have
always been a pragmatist and moderate by nature. I have always been
more interested in solving people's problems than in espousing a
rigid ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read all these commentaries about me, and they're always
saying how dull and stodgy and predictable, but that's just the way
I am,'' he added. ``Happily, the people were in the mood for the
kind of person that I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
