<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SWEETENS BID FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shoring up potential holes in Boston's bid for the 2000
Democratic National Convention, the city added another $1 million
in cash and services to its $32.4 million proposal in the home
stretch of the siting contest.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they were hopeful that throwing in a
cutting-edge web site, another $750,000 for the media pavillion,
and free airport shuttle service might clinch a Hub victory over
the other finalists, Denver and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's smoke coming out of the smokestack and it's white
smoke,'' quipped Mayor Thomas M. Menino, in reference to the signal
used by the College of Cardinals after they successfully choose a
new pope.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is believed to be the first of the final three to fatten
its offer, but details of each bid are being jealousy guarded, said
Howard Leibowitz, Menino's point person on the convention proposal.
</P>
<P>
   US Senator Edward M. Kennedy lauded the sweetening of Boston's
bid as further proof the city ``has the resources and facilities to
be the best site for the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials are especially proud of the high-tech plan,
dubbed ``America's web of democracy,'' which proposes the first
Internet-friendly political convention.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the software and technical know-how contributed by local
computer gurus, 3Comm has offered to donate palm-size computers for
floor delegates, according to bid documents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, spearheaded by local software pioneer John J.
Cullinane, focuses heavily on direct contact between voters and
party officials, as well as a separate educational site for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Besides offering two-way communication between delegates,
constituents, and the DNC, the system would also hawk Boston
examples of pet programs of the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates could also send a ``letter from Boston'' to their
hometown paper each day and the media could hold ``virtual press
conferences'' via the website, according to bid plans.
</P>
<P>
   While Denver has also hawked its high-tech capabilities in its
bid, Leibowitz said the DNC site committee specifically invited
Boston to flesh out a technology proposal because of the city's
Internet industry reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newsweek had us as one of the top Internet cities _ they
didn't have either of the other two,'' said Leibowitz.
</P>
<P>
   At this nail-biting stage, all the conventional wisdom is mere
speculation, however.
</P>
<P>
   The spirits of Denver and Boston officials were buoyed after Los
Angeles, the frontrunner, scored low marks in the DNC's follow-up
site visit last month. LA reportedly did not have detailed plans on
convention logistics and, with a Republican mayor, had no elected
official to sign off on commitments for police and other government
services.
</P>
<P>
   After reported success of the DNC visit to Denver, Boston
officials decided to firm up areas that had left questions
unanswered when DNC site panel members were here last month.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the DNC visit, city Transportation Director
Andrea D'Amato had simply reassured the committee that Boston could
devise a shuttle service for delegates, given its success at
transporting runners and officials for the 100th Boston Marathon
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But when Denver's shuttle service won kudos from the DNC, Boston
officials dropped their nonchalance, and created plans and obtained
Massport sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Boston has enhanced its $1.5 million plans to upgrade
the FleetCenter parking structure for media work space by $750,000.
DNC panelists asked a lot of questions about the media
accommodations when they were here.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't use the money for the media, Leibowitz said,
``They can spend it on whatever they want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
