<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASDAQ AT NEW PEAK; INVESTORS WAITING FOR DELUGE OF IPOs  
(rl) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks spurted, then retreated and finally closed
mixed Monday, as traders and investors began to focus on upcoming
quarterly earnings reports and a fairly hefty calendar of expected
initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Following the market's steep selloff last summer, the flow of
new stock offerings slowed significantly, effectively capping the
pool of securities investors could choose from. A rise in new
supply would alter the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market enjoyed four months of no new supply, a strong
merger and acquisitions market and strong inflows of funds,'' said
Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new issue calendar is as big as I have seen, which means
things will not be so favorable as they have been. That will leave
the spotlight squarely on earnings, and I don't think they will be
so great.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, for instance, Goldman, Sachs sold 50 million shares
in the MBNA Corp. Goldman had purchased the block of new shares
from the company. The transaction raised $1.2 billion for the
credit-card company. Shares of MBNA closed at 24, down 13/16 on the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations of good fourth-quarter earnings reports from
technology companies helped to push the Nasdaq composite index to a
new record. The Nasdaq index rose 15.36, or seven-tenths of a
percent, to 2,208.05. Early in the session the index traded as high
as 2,233.57. The Nasdaq rose 39.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which gained 16.1 percent last
year, began 1999 with a gain of 2.84, to 9,184.27. Before a number
of computer-generated sell programs hit the blue-chip index, the
Dow was up as much as 168 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index posted a loss of 1.13, to
1,228.10. During morning trading, the index traded as high as
1,248.81. It rose 26.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   More than eight stocks rose for every seven that fell on the New
York Stock Exchange. Volume on the Big Board was active, at more
than 892.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions were very orderly,'' said one block trader, who
asked not to be identified. ``We were so busy that we weren't
paying attention to what the market was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts attributed the market's strong early advance to a
surge in European stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices on the Continent rose on optimism that the arrival
of the euro will help to increase economic efficiency and growth,
which would be beneficial for the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices on the French, German and Italian exchanges were up
more than 5 percent Monday. Of major European markets, only
Britain, which is not adopting the new currency, registered a
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks retained their popularity Monday, particularly
the biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 2 5/16, to 141. Intel gained 2\, to 120 13/16.
Cisco Systems gained 2 1/2, to 95 5/16. And Internet companies like
Amazon.com and Yahoo also posted big gains. Amazon shot up 33
11/16, to 354 15/16. And Yahoo rose 11 1/16, to 248. But America
Online, trading for the first time as a component of the S&AMP;P 500,
fell 6 5/16, to 148 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Spyglass declined 7, to 15, after the maker of software that
hooks devices up to the Internet said it expects to report a loss
of 14 cents to 16 cents a share. Analysts had been expecting the
company to eke out a profit of about a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Dow stocks, AT&AMP;T gained 2 1/8, to 77 7/8, after the
company said it had dropped a plan to separate its consumer and
corporate businesses. DuPont rose 2 3/16, to 55 1/4, on the
expectation it would seek a more attractive acquisition candidate
after the company ended its $750 million purchase of the white
pigment business from Imperial Chemicals Industries PLC.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper fell 2 11/16, to 42[. And IBM, whose stock
was one of the most impressive performers last quarter, fell 1 3/8,
to 183. General Electric also slumped, losing 1 7/16, to 100 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   The day's big gainers also included E-Trade, the online
securities broker. The company's shares jumped 8 21/32, to 55 7/16,
after it said it will split its common stock 2 for 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
