<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MAYOR PREPARES TO SHAKE THINGS UP IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first hint that things might be different was
Mayor Anthony Williams' arrival time Monday, 1:59 p.m., one minute
early for his first news conference as the District of Columbia's
mayor. His predecessor for 16 of the last 20 years, Marion Barry
Jr., usually appeared about 20 minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was sworn in on Saturday, also wore a bow tie, an
unlikely accessory for Barry.
</P>
<P>
   But they were not the only changes apparent on Williams' first
full day of business. Making good on a campaign promise to improve
the delivery of city services, he said he challenged his cabinet
heads, most of them Barry holdovers, to develop action plans within
a week, or face the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of asking a series of hard-hitting
questions,'' he said to a room packed with reporters and members of
his administration. ``They have a lot of work to do in the next
days. How they respond will tell us a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 48, the district's former chief financial officer, was
elected in November largely on promises of fixing a city that was
broken for years and holding city employees accountable for their
job performance. He vowed to have garbage collected on time, fix
the potholes and have city workers respond to callers by saying,
``I'll find out,'' rather than ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the parade of new staff members he introduced, heads
could roll. Few served under Barry, who chose not to seek a fifth
term, and most had unusually impressive academic or employment
credentials. But Williams stressed that he wanted to give the
holdovers a chance to prove themselves before seeking replacements.
</P>
<P>
   For all the need for improvement, the city Williams inherited
from Barry is vastly different from the one Barry took over when he
returned in 1994 after his disappearance from politics while he was
in prison for drug possession. Then, the district had a deficit in
excess of $700 million, and few departments operated as they were
intended to.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Congress, controlled by Republicans, shifted the
power of running the city from Barry to a financial control board
that was created in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years, the board and Williams, who was hired
by Barry, were so successful in cutting spending and reorganizing
agencies that Williams could have as much as a $400 million surplus
for the current fiscal year. In addition, crime rates have fallen,
as they have in most big cities, and city services are improving.
The control board has returned the operational powers to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams insisted that he would not be ``a totally happy
camper'' until he felt that the changes residents clamored for were
under way. And responsibility for that, he said, starts with
department heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hold line workers accountable if you don't hold
managers accountable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' challenge to the cabinet heads, which he made in a
morning meeting, was included in a 46-page booklet he distributed
to them in which he also outlined his expectations for six months
and beyond. It was the kind of written guideline Barry used to
circulate to managers. But with the new mayor's tenuous allegiance
to officials from a previous administration, the latest
recommendations seemed to carry more weight.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Williams' newly won power was evident in his
demeanor as he spoke and answered questions for nearly an hour. He
seemed to have shed the self-deprecating image of the nerd, which
he embraced as chief financial officer and as a campaigner. He
spoke in a strong voice that reflected confidence in his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of his highest political priorities would be to
press Congress for the restoration of full home rule, which the
city lost to the control board. By law, the district must balance
its books four consecutive years before the board can be shut down.
It has two to go, but as the ultimate authority over the nation's
capital, Congress can do anything it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said his harmonious working relationship with the
board's new leader, Alice Rivlin, the vice chairman of the Federal
Reserve, as well as with the District Council, could help win an
assurance that federal lawmakers would not renege on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a bad hand, and now we have to make it into something
good,'' Williams said. ``Over the next couple of years, we'll spell
out the criteria that ought to be applied for the full resumption
of home rule and the elimination of the control board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
