<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-EXPORTS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS INSIST ON STRICT SATELLITE EXPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss.)  (js) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders have warned President Clinton
not to weaken a new law that makes foreign policy and national
security the only basis for approving exports of U.S. satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has delayed telling Congress how it
will put the new law into effect. It tightens control over
satellite exports by shifting regulation back to the State
Department from the Commerce Department, which places trade as a
top priority.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the military budget bill signed last October, the
Clinton administration was required to tell Congress by Jan. 1 how
the State Department will replace the Commerce Department as the
licensing authority for most commercial satellite exports. Even
though Clinton originally opposed the measure, administration
officials said he will comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, nine Republican senators, including the majority
leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, warned Clinton in a letter not
to ``undermine the clear intent'' of the law by finding a way to
give the Commerce Department a role.
</P>
<P>
   That warning came as a select House panel issued a bipartisan
report saying that the national security of the United States had
been harmed by satellite technology transfers to China. The
700-page secret congressional report will be delivered to the
administration this week.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will work with Congress to declassify some of
the report and respond to its 38 recommendations, some of which
involve strengthening the export licensing process.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the report covers a 1995 decision by the Commerce
Department approving aid provided by Hughes Electronics, a
satellite manufacturer, to Chinese rocket scientists. The Commerce
Department failed to insure that Pentagon monitors were present
when Hughes gave the Chinese lessons in commercial rocket launches
that also had broad applications to ballistic missiles. The House
select committee has suggested ways to broaden the role of the
Defense Department in the licensing process, officials also said.
</P>
<P>
   A required report on complying with the new satellite export law
will be sent to Congress shortly and it will not give the Commerce
Department any formal role in the licensing process, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes that the national security of the
United States was adequately addressed and protected under the
previous systems but we will of course implement the new
regulations consistent with the law,'' said David C. Leavy, a White
House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, when President Clinton signed the National Defense
Authorization Act for 1999, he said he ``strongly opposed'' the
provision shifting satellite licensing back to the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This change is not necessary to ensure effective control of
U.S. exports of satellites and could hamper the U.S. satellite
industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the State Department can take only foreign policy and
national security factors into account when deciding an export
license.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Clinton reversed a decision by his secretary of state
and transferred authority for most satellite exports to the more
business-friendly Commerce Department. China buys U.S. satellites
and it also sells services as a low cost launcher of satellites.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Commerce Department documents turned over to the select House
committee show that Commerce officials tried to address concerns by
Hughes officials about the role of Pentagon monitors at satellite
launches. And they show that the Commerce official who allowed
Hughes to help the Chinese solve the failure of one of its rockets
in 1995 knew his approval could be seen as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The licensing official, Gene Christiansen, wrote in a 1996
e-mail message turned over to the select committee that ``some
would say to release that data to the Chinese would violate the''
licensing conditions, making it more likely ``that our decision
will be challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Pentagon and the State Department did just that,
finding that Hughes had significantly improved China's ability to
launch satellites and ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon report showed ``the Commerce Department's record of
putting commercial interests ahead of American national security,''
the letter from Lott to Clinton said. Its signatories included the
chairmen of four key committees.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes officials have defended their 1995 help to the Chinese by
citing the Commerce Department's approval.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter last week to Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, the company's chairman said Hughes ``will adopt new
policies and procedures for the export of technology and
equipment,'' including a ``new internal export compliance
program.''
</P>
<P>
   William A. Reinsch, the undersecretary of commerce for export
administration, told Congress last summer that Hughes' help to
China was ``appropriate and without risk to national security,''
but he said his department should have referred the matter to the
State Department for review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
