<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BROWN-ART-620&AMP;A     01-04 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BROWN-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND EMBRACES MAYOR JERRY BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CALIF-DAVIS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ People here expect Jerry Brown to be a
different sort of mayor. On his first day, he did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   From his morning meditation at his downtown loft, to his earnest
pronouncements of what ``we can do together'' before throngs of
well-wishers outside City Hall on a windy, chilly afternoon, to his
tieless suit _ the shirt, as usual, had a banded, priestly collar _
the three-time candidate for president and two-time governor of
California became mayor of the state's seventh-largest city in his
classic, inimitable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the 60-year-old native San Franciscan, who moved across
the Bay to Oakland five years ago to form a research organization,
We the People, and start a radio talk show, marched six blocks from
the swearing-in ceremonies at the Paramount Theater to the rally at
City Hall. He was escorted by a jazz band and what seemed like the
entire city.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a few pickets from a group that says the new mayor's
promise to reduce crime amounts to an order for police to round up
blacks, Edmund Brown Jr.'s inauguration was greeted with the wild
enthusiasm that politicians' dreams are made of. He gave just a
three-minute speech at his swearing-in _ after a tedious ceremony
in which Board of Education members and City Council members took
their oaths. But his words, judging from the audience's response,
were inspirational. When he said: ``Everything will be made
right,'' the cheers had an almost religious zeal.
</P>
<P>
   At his rally, Brown, his voice slightly hoarse, announced four
goals: to reduce crime, to attract 10,000 people to live downtown,
to help parents and teachers create public charter schools, and to
encourage celebrations, festivals and artistic performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much that we can do together,'' Brown said, as the
crowd shouted its approval.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland has high hopes and expectations for its new mayor. Brown
won the nonpartisan primary with more than 58 percent of the vote,
avoiding a runoff with 10 opponents. His ballot proposition to
change the balance of power, giving the mayor more power than the
city manager, was supported by 75 percent of voters. And his
inaugural festivities, ``Celebrating Oakland,'' which offered
citizens a jam-packed schedule with scores of local acts _
musicians, visual artists, dancers and poets _ were touted Monday
as a sure-fire sign that the new mayor is planning to showcase the
best Oakland has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a breath of fresh air in the American political
syndrome,'' said Tom Siporin, a poet and yogi who hobbled on a
crutch to attend the rally in the City Hall plaza. ``He's a great
attempt to show there's hope in the inner city. He's a visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, with close to 400,000 residents, suffers from a serious
inferiority complex. The city has been called homely and
crime-ridden, a poor cousin to San Francisco, for so long that
these have become its defining characteristics. Meanwhile, the
city's assets _ its thriving port, its handsome neighborhoods high
on the Oakland hills, its growing community of artists and
musicians, many of them refugees from San Francisco's sky-high
rents _ have been largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Residents clearly believe that the new mayor, with his high
political profile and pull as a media magnet, could give their city
the respect and attention it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland is a beautiful city and with a strong mayor we will
have an even better Oakland,'' said Clement Sinclair, an automotive
shop teacher and Democratic party worker originally from Jamaica.
``People who have run away from Oakland in the past will now be
glad to come back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Henrietta Hamilton, who has lived in Watts and Harlem and now
lives in Venice, Calif., flew up to Oakland to attend the
inauguration. ``I would like to change the world and I can't
imagine a better person than Jerry Brown to do it here for
Oakland,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's plans are already being criticized as too vague by some
local political pundits. Skeptics doubt whether a would-be
philosopher king, the former ``Gov. Moonbeam,'' with all his new
age-ish rhetoric, could also be a pragmatic nuts-and-bolts
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry just doesn't have the mind for these everyday matters of
city government,'' said Robert Warwick, a member of a local
Democratic club that backed one of Brown's primary opponents. ``I
know Jerry well,'' he said. ``He used to be involved with Zen
Buddhism and so was I. But he was a terrible governor. That stupid
tax reform proposition he pushed ruined the state for 25 years and
now he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Brown accomplishes, Warwick said, given the
expectations it will not be enough. ``The idea that one charismatic
guy could come here and turn things around is ridiculous,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But his was a minority opinion, one that Brown surely did not
hear above the roars of approval Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know politics is not doing too well in this country
lately,'' he told the city. ``But in Oakland, we're putting it all
together. It's real in this town. We're going to break the mold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
