</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-PROCESS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas clemency process debate continues
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Unlike the Democrat he's replacing, Republican
Attorney General John Cornyn isn't pushing for changes to the
state's clemency process for condemned killers, an aide said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Death-row inmates today are seeking temporary changes to the
process by which they can ask the state to commute their death
sentences to life in prison. Under the current system, the
18-member Board of Pardons and Paroles votes on their fate by phone
or fax. They do not meet publicly or speak to each other about each
petition.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates challenging the process say it violates the state's Open
Meetings Act.
</P>
<P>
   Two state judges already have ruled that the process is
unconstitutional, but appeals courts have later reversed their
rulings. District Judge Scott McCown today could set temporary
rules for the clemency process while a trial is held to determine
whether it is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, former Attorney General Dan Morales said the process
should be changed to include an open meeting. U.S. District Judge
Sam Sparks, though highly critical of the process, said it
nonetheless meets the minimal standards for due process under
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Cornyn spokesman Ted Delisi said Cornyn supports the
current process.
</P>
<P>
   ``As confirmed by a recent federal court decision, the state's
clemency statute affords each death row inmate sufficient due
process,'' Delisi said. ``As the state's top lawyer, Judge Cornyn
will defend the clemency process to assure the swift administration
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn is a former judge on the Texas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the Pardons and Paroles Board, has
said that he believes the process is fair and legal. He added,
though, that he is open to changes.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush said he, too, is willing to listen to
recommended changes but supports the current process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no doubt in my mind that any person we have put
to death in the state of Texas has had full due process and has
been guilty of the crime charged,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
