<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRONG 49ER-PACKER RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers' stunning 30-27 victory over the Green
Bay Packers on the Fox network Sunday produced a 24.2 overnight
Nielsen rating _ the highest for a National Football League
wild-card playoff game since 1991. The rating represented a 27
percent jump from the comparable game last year, the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers against the Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   The game demonstrated the potent drawing power of two of the
league's most successful and storied teams, even in a wild-card
matchup. The game was carried in the coveted 4 p.m., Eastern, time
slot, when more people are watching television, on a day when much
of the country was beset by torrents of rain or snowstorms.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of the game sustained increasingly higher ratings.
The game opened with a 19.8 rating from 4:15 to 4:30, jumped to a
25.9 from 6:30 p.m. to 7 p.m. and finished with a 28.5 from 7 p.m.
to 7:30 p.m., Eastern, when Terrell Owens caught the winning pass
from Steve Young with three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Each overnight rating point represents 624,000 TV households.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, the market closest to Green Bay, the game produced
a 53.7 rating and a 76 share, meaning 76 percent of the homes
watching TV in the market were tuned to the game. In San Francisco,
the rating was a 42.0/73. The New York market posted a 22.3/36. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Jacksonville's 25-10 victory over New England, the CBS
overnight rating was an 18.7, up 1 percent from last year's
comparable game, New England against Miami, which was carried by
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   All four wild-card games, including the two played last Saturday
on ABC, posted higher ratings. The 17.9 rating for the
Buffalo-Miami game was a 15 percent improvement on the comparable
game last year, and the 21.0 for the Arizona-Dallas game
represented a 24 percent increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
