<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-2TAKES-NY     01-04 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS STILL SEARCHING FOR WAY TO HANDLE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators searched on Monday for the formula that
would produce bipartisan support for a curtailed impeachment trial
of President Clinton as a few more Republicans expressed opposition
to the compromise plan under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   With the 106th Congress set to convene on Wednesday, Sen. Trent
Lott, the majority leader, returned to the Capitol to prepare for
Republican and Democratic conferences on Wednesday that could
determine whether the Senate can find a way around a full trial
with extensive testimony from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   A day after some senators called on Clinton to postpone his
State of the Union Message if an impeachment trial was under way,
White House officials said Clinton still planned to deliver the
annual policy address on Jan. 19. However, they did not close the
door to a delay. Democrats close to the White House said the
president would put off his speech for a week or so if the Senate
seemed able to wrap up impeachment proceedings quickly this month.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate still appeared far from agreement on a proposal
by Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn.,
that would condense a trial into a matter of days and then require
test votes on whether each of the two articles of impeachment sent
by the House warranted Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, neither article drew the 67 senators that would
ultimately be needed to convict Clinton, then the Senate would vote
to adjourn the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say Lott will move ahead with the proposal only if a
majority of the Senate's 55 Republicans back it, but opposition to
the plan only seemed to be growing among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious mistake,'' said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H. ``It's
not constitutional. It creates a bad precedent and I don't think
this president would take it seriously.'' And Sen. Orrin G. Hatch,
R-Utah, expressed opposition in an op-ed article in The Washington
Post, saying he feared the procedure could create a long-term
precedent and be seen ``as a repudiation of the House's decision to
impeach President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
