<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PHILLIPS-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR NHL TO CONSIDER NO-TOUCH RULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the aftermath of the knee injury to Glen Murray
on Saturday night, much of the talk in the Kings' dressing room was
about the need for the National Hockey League to consider adopting
the international no-touch rule for icing.
</P>
<P>
   This was after Murray, in a breakneck race to beat Colorado
defenseman Aaron Miller to the puck to wash out an icing call,
landed awkwardly, tearing the medial collateral ligament in his
right knee, an injury that will deprive the Kings of their best
all-around forward for at least two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives a reason for no-touch icing,'' Kings defenseman Rob
Blake said later, referring to the rule under which the whistle
blows for icing the moment the puck crosses the goal line. ``If
there's no-touch icing, there's no injury on that play. I think it
definitely should be in the game. I've seen a lot of injuries like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   One that springs to mind is the broken leg suffered by
then-Dallas defenseman Mark Tinordi several years back along the
same Forum end boards where Murray was injured. On that play,
former King John Druce was chasing Tinordi for the puck, and at the
speed they were traveling, it didn't take much body contact by
Druce to send Tinordi crashing into the boards, another clean hit
resulting in a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   And for what?
</P>
<P>
   Under the current icing rules, about 95 percent of the time fans
are treated to the thrilling sight of a defenseman leisurely
skating into his own end to tap the puck with his stick so the
referee will whistle icing.
</P>
<P>
   Less often you get a foot race, such as the one in which Murray
was hurt. Less often than that, the offensive player wins the race
and captures the puck to wash out the icing, and his effort results
in a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting no-touch icing is one rule change the NHL could make
that would arouse little controversy, wouldn't alter the fabric of
the game, and would reduce the risk of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Blown call: Clearly, NHL vice president Colin Campbell should
have given Phoenix's Dallas Drake more than a four-game suspension
for his boarding penalty on the Kings' Doug Bodger last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings placed Bodger on injured reserve Monday because of his
cervical and shoulder strains, meaning the Kings' defenseman
probably will miss at least as many games as Drake. Somehow, this
doesn't seem fair.
</P>
<P>
   Drake was apologetic about the hit.
</P>
<P>
   `After my hearing over the phone (with Campbell), I thought four
games was a little harsh,'' he said. `But I did hit him from
behind. He spun around and I should have stopped, but I didn't. The
league's trying to cut down on things like that, and I just put
myself and him in a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have been much worse. Bodger was lucky to avoid a
severe neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall improving: St. Louis' Geoff Courtnall _ brother of the
Kings' Russ Courtnall and Kings fans' No.1 enemy during last
season's playoffs _ has been sidelined more than a month because of
a concussion resulting from a hit by Washington's Joe Reekie.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is Courtnall is feeling better and has started
light workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually the daily routine was to wake up with a headache, and
by mid-afternoon, I felt really sick to my stomach _ and tired,
like I needed to lay down,'' he said. ``I'd get back up and still
have a headache. It'd go like that every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting depressed last week, thinking that I might not
ever play again. It was scary for two or three weeks. When you have
headaches 12 hours out of the day and feel lousy every morning when
you wake up, it's pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough talk: Chicago fans better hope the NBA lockout is settled
and Michael Jordan returns to the Bulls. The Blackhawks certainly
aren't filling the void.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bob Murray recently ripped several of his
younger players: Eric Daze, Chad Kilger and Ethan Moreau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear we're putting too much pressure on the kids and that
they don't have confidence. That's horse(bleep),'' Murray said.
``It's having a passion for the game. You've been playing hockey
since you were 4 or 5 years old, and either you want to win or you
don't. Just go out and do what you have to do to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like losing bothers some of these guys. The
sense of urgency and desperation, I'm just not seeing it. It has to
be an attitude within the team that says losing is not OK. You've
got to hate to lose. I just wonder sometimes how many of our guys
hate to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockeytown South? When Detroit lost at Nashville recently, the
arena was loaded with red-and-white clad Red Wings fans, many of
them Michigan transplants working at the Saturn automobile plant in
nearby Spring Hill, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot more Red Wings fans than I thought I would,''
Predators left wing Denny Lambert said. ``I came out in warmups and
I thought, `We're in Detroit.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
