<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONUTS-MOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNKIN' DONUTS SUES FRANCHISEE OVER A MOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was 15 minutes of fame Dunkin' Donuts did not
want.
</P>
<P>
   It began last week with a photograph in The New York Post of a
mouse munching on a doughnut in the window of a shop in midtown
Manhattan. Soon everyone was cracking jokes about what Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani called a ``disgusting, horrible story.'' David
Letterman placed the news on his ``Top Ten List'' of things
overheard in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number nine,'' he declared. ``It's so cold the rat on my
doughnut just froze.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dunkin' Donuts struck back, filing a lawsuit in
Federal district court in Manhattan that accused the Riese
Organization, the company that runs the franchise outlet at 46th
Street and Fifth Avenue, of breaching its contract by not meeting
the donut chain's health and sanitation standards. The suit seeks a
court order forcing Riese to close the shop and remove the familiar
Dunkin' Donuts sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime someone laughs at your trademark and what's going on
in your shops, you've been damaged,'' said Jack Laudermilk, a
lawyer for the Dunkin' Donuts chain, which is based in Randolph,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been made the butt of a joke in New York _ on
television, in the newspapers,'' he said. ``We take it not as funny
but as something very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin' Donuts has about 3,700 stores nationwide, including
about 200 in New York City, of which about 30 are run by Riese,
said Jennifer Rosenberg, a spokeswoman for the chain.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Dunkin' Donuts has sent workers to inspect all of
the stores run by Riese, as well as others in New York, ``to make
sure that all of the locations are up to our standards for
sanitation and food and safety and quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The shop in question, she said, will remain open until the suit
is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin' Donuts said it notified Riese last Thursday, the day
after the Post article appeared, that it was terminating its
franchise contract for that location. It is not clear from the
lawsuit whether Riese is contesting the action, or what explanation
Riese may have. Dunkin' Donuts said that it was not seeking to end
its contract with the other Riese locations.
</P>
<P>
   A Riese spokeswoman would not comment Monday night, saying that
the company had not yet reviewed the suit. Riese is a major
operator of fast food restaurants in Manhattan, including such
outlets as Nathan's, Roy Rogers and TGI Friday's.
</P>
<P>
   Dunkin' Donuts said in the suit that the shop shared common
storage, refrigeration, and seating areas with other Riese
franchises at the location, which had been ``cited numerous times''
by the New York City Department of Health for sanitation-related
violations, including the existence of vermin.
</P>
<P>
   Moving quickly and forthrightly can be an important means of
restoring a company's reputation when a crisis occurs, marketing
experts have said.
</P>
<P>
   One, Stephen Greyser, a professor of marketing at Harvard
Business School, said the lawsuit is a correct step but may not be
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the problem will be broad one, as customers who
consider eating at Dunkin' Donuts shops around the country ponder
what they may find there.
</P>
<P>
   The suit ``certainly sends a signal to other franchisees,''
Greyser said. ``That's very important. The point is, these kinds of
things, if you pardon the pun, have a long tail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
