<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHATTANOOGA-NEWSPAPER     01-04 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHATTANOOGA-NEWSPAPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHATTANOOGA TIMES FOLDS AFTER LONG NEWSPAPER WAR
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chattanooga Times, the newspaper that Adolph S. Ochs took
over 120 years ago with borrowed money and the same stubborn
confidence that later led him to buy The New York Times, published
its final edition Monday as control passed from Ochs' 13
great-grandchildren to the owner of its evening rival, The
Chattanooga Free Press.
</P>
<P>
   The two newspapers fought pitched battles against each other in
the 1970s. Although the hostility was muted after a joint operating
agreement took effect in 1980, they retained distinct
personalities. The Times featured a liberal editorial page and
in-depth, analytical coverage; The Free Press fought back with
scrappy, locally oriented coverage and a deeply conservative
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the two newspapers become one, carrying the nameplates
of both. But while Chattanooga becomes a one-newspaper town, it
will keep two editorial voices. The 70,000 or more subscribers to
the merged newspaper will have the chance to read two editorial
pages, _ The Times' opinions on the left-hand side, The Free Press'
on the right.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative to the sale _ an expensive battle between two
newspapers with daily circulations of just over 40,000 and profit
margins in the single-digit range _ was favored by neither the Ochs
descendants nor Walter E. Hussman Jr., who bought The Free Press 10
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the chief executive of Wehco Media Inc., the 52-year-old
Hussman controls lucrative cable and broadcast properties in
Arkansas and Louisiana and had emerged victorious from a fierce
newspaper war in Little Rock eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In national terms, the loss of The Times further cuts the ranks
of towns with more than one newspaper. Among large cities, New
York, Chicago, Denver, Boston and Seattle stand almost alone as
cities with more than one newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 great-grandchildren of Ochs, who owned The Chattanooga
Times, were among the unsuccessful bidders for The Free Press when
its owners, the McDonald family, put it up for sale about a year
ago, Hussman said. The Chattanooga Times and a small printing
operation are held separately from The New York Times Co., whose
controlling shares are also owned by Adolph Ochs' descendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make economic good sense to have two newspapers in
this city, especially two that were in full-fledged battle,'' said
Ruth S. Holmberg, the chairman of The Chattanooga Times, who is one
of Ochs' four grandchildren. ``We had made a bid for The Free
Press, and this is what we would have done. It just makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said, ``yesterday was a very hard day.'' Monday
final edition of The Times included a cartoon of Adolph Ochs with a
tear sliding down his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Hussman of Wehco had for two decades been friendly with the
publishers of The Free Press, beginning in the late 1970's, when
Hussman, then the publisher of the financially shaky Arkansas
Democrat, turned to Roy McDonald for advice on how to make an
evening newspaper successful. McDonald obliged. With his counsel,
Hussman ended the Little Rock wars when Wehco bought its rival and
merged the two as The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Golden, a son of Mrs. Holmberg who was one of the 13
owners of The Chattanooga Times, said of the sale: ``It was a very
emotional decision. This is where our roots came from. This is
where Adolph Ochs developed his instincts and his feelings about
journalism that blossomed so well here and in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   But, added Golden, who is also vice chairman of The New York
Times Co., it became clear that a ``full-blown newspaper war''
would cost somewhere between $60 million and $80 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hussman and Golden said that averting a costly war would
free more resources for ambitious journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But John Siegenthaler, the former publisher of The Nashville
Tennessean, was not sanguine. ``I think that the absence of
meaningful competition in most communities in America right now
results in the cynicism many people feel for the press,'' he said.
``There's no second voice, no second check, no real monitor. While
it's true that in some cities a single newspaper has done
extraordinary things, it's by no means an automatic result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
