<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FALCONS REPORT: Reeves gets clearance for bigger workload
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves got a doctor's OK Monday to
increase his workload in preparation for Saturday's NFC playoff
game at the Georgia Dome against the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   But as he continues to recuperate from quadruple heart bypass
surgery Dec. 14, that doesn't guarantee he will be on the sideline
this weekend, or even at practice today. Barring complications,
Reeves will be at the game, but the risk injury on the sideline
could necessitate a move to the press box, high above the playing
field. That decision will come later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Falcons had mandatory weightlifting and running.
Reeves arrived mid-afternoon at team headquarters and sat in on
early offensive meetings, as the game plan was being constructed.
He said he would not stay late into the night, as he usually does,
and he was hopeful Dome officials can clean up after Monday night's
professional wrestling event so the Falcons can practice there this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That would take the team out of the cold, and increase chances
of Reeves being involved. He stayed in his office during two
cold-weather practices last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need as much concentration as we can get,'' he said,
explaining that cold weather distracts players and coaches alike.
``My checkup went well, and I'm cleared to do as much as I can
until I get tired.Shell game
</P>
<P>
   Falcons offensive line coach Art Shell has had preliminary phone
conversations with Cleveland Browns president Carmen Policy about
the coaching job for the expansion franchise, but has not had an
official interview.
</P>
<P>
   Shell, 52, had a 54-38 record coaching the Oakland Raiders in
1989-94. He did not return phone calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who on New Year's Day gave Policy permission to talk
with Shell, said he believes Shell and Policy agreed on a formal
interview date dependent on when the Falcons' season ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shell) has talked to Carmen . . . to set something up,''
Reeves said. ``Art has not been up there (to Cleveland).''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   The only two players held out of practice last week, cornerback
Ronnie Bradford and linebacker Craig Sauer, are likely to practice
today. Bradford (slight shoulder separation) said, ``You can't keep
me out of pads.'' Sauer's strained hamstring has improved. . . .
Fullback Bob Christian, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament in
his left knee Dec. 13, will have surgery today.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen Falcons were at ``Monday Nitro,'' the WCW
event at the Dome. Some were teammates of pro wrestling star
Goldberg when he was a reserve defensive tackle for Atlanta in
1992-94 under the name Bill Goldberg. The former Georgia star had
16 tackles and four quarterback pressures for the Falcons. . . .
Defensive end Chuck Smith has 48 1/2 sacks in his seven-year
career, and his seven of the 49ers' Steve Young are more than any
other player.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
