A7967 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS &LR;      01-04 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP TO CAUCUS OVER IMPEACHMENT TRAIL PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With their party's public standing at stake, Senate
Republicans Monday hastily scheduled a closed-door caucus for
Tuesday to confront deep divisions within their ranks over how to
conduct an impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The private meeting, on the eve of the swearing-in of the 106th
Congress, could determine the course of the potentially explosive
proceedings, which one Republican senator Monday declared of more
consequence than ``the trial of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid polls that show the Republican Party suffering a serious
backlash from the presidential impeachment crisis, the 55 GOP
senators had planned to huddle Wednesday or Thursday to wrangle
over starkly divergent plans to conduct the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, pushed up the caucus
to Tuesday to try to unify his GOP colleagues and prevent
additional damage to the Republican cause in the prelude to the
high-stakes impeachment showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This speculation about the trial of the century _ I think it's
the trial of all time,'' said Senator Arlen Specter, a Pennsylvania
Republican. ``I don't think there has ever been a trial in the
history of Anglo-Saxon jurisprudence which is as important as this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate anxiously braces for the first presidential
impeachment trial in 130 years, the House will revisit the issue
Wednesday, just hours after the swearing-in of the new Congress and
less than three weeks after the lame-duck House impeached Clinton
on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice stemming from his
sexual affair with a former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional rules require the newly inducted House to
reauthorize the 13 managers _ all members of the House Judiciary
Committee, including the chairman, Henry J. Hyde _ who will present
the impeachment case against Clinton in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democrats, who gained five seats in the last election,
plan to use the occasion to press anew for a vote to place the
House on record in favor of censuring Clinton rather than removing
him from office.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders blocked such a vote last month on the
final day of the 105th Congress and are expected to do so again
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly like to see Henry Hyde be able to present
the testimony and what he needs to do to put his case forward,''
said the House speaker-designate, J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the Republican majority is split over a
bipartisan proposal to abbreviate the impeachment process with a
vote to determine if the charges meet the constitutional standard
of high crimes and misdemeanors required to remove a president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   At least two-thirds of the Senate's 100 members would need to
decide that the charges constitute impeachable offenses for a full
trial to proceed. If less than two-thirds votes to proceed, a
simple majority of 51 senators could vote to adjourn the trial and
set up a possible censure vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who is keenly aware that the impeachment saga indirectly
led to the fall of House Speaker Newt Gingrich and his would-be
successor, Robert L. Livingston, has expressed partial support for
the plan, which all 45 Senate Democrats appear poised to back.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a dozen conservative Republicans, including
Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire, have blasted the plan as a
dereliction of the Senate's constitutional duty to fully examine
the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a number of moderate GOP lawmakers, such as Specter
and Senator Mike DeWine of Ohio, have attacked the plan, imperiling
efforts by Lott to rally a Republican consensus for the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the 13 managers from the House would present
the impeachment case to the full Senate next Monday. Clinton's
lawyers would present their rebuttal Tuesday, and senators would
use the following day to ask questions of both sides. A vote would
follow, on Thursday, Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the process would prevent senators from
cross-examining witnesses whose previous testimony has conflicted
with Clinton's, including his personal secretary, Betty Currie, and
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard to have a trial without witnesses,'' Specter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the pre-trial plan said it was crucial to avoid
proceedings that could drag on for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to have a short trial,'' said Senator John
Breaux, a Louisiana Democrat. ``I just think it's impossible, if
you're going to have a trial with witnesses, to make it quick and
short.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Lott and the Senate minority leader, Thomas A. Daschle,
have said they want to avoid the possible spectacle of a full trial
on the sex-related charges. And both continued to reach out to
lawmakers Monday despite the GOP's intraparty differences. Yet the
outcome remained highly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Lott will propose the plan, I believe, only if a
majority of Republicans favor it,'' said Senator Slade Gorton, a
Washington Republican, who developed the proposal with Senator
Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton said he could not estimate how many Republicans will
back the plan. And other Republicans said Lott would be reluctant
to pursue the strategy without a solid GOP majority behind it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
