<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      01-04 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BELL ATLANTIC, AIRTOUCH WRESTLE WITH MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time the stock market had opened Monday, Bell
Atlantic Corp. and Airtouch Communications Inc. had publicly
confirmed their merger discussions. But investors remained
uncertain that a deal would materialize _ and on favorable terms _
and sent down the value of both companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, the No. 1 local phone company, is negotiating to
acquire Airtouch, one of the world's biggest wireless telephone
carriers, for around $45 billion in stock, roughly 10 percent more
than Airtouch was worth before the talks became public last week.
But some Wall Street analysts think that some Airtouch investors
would have a hard time going along with what they might perceive as
an ungenerous offer. (Relative to Airtouch's share price a month
ago, however, the premium would be closer to 25 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the negotiations have said, however, that
Bell Atlantic could offer as much as $50 billion for Airtouch, not
including the value of Airtouch's debt, and it appeared that
wrangling over valuation could be delaying a deal's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as important, it was not certain Monday that Bell
Atlantic would be able to use a favorable method of accounting
called pooling of interests in the event of an acquisition. It is
unlikely that Bell Atlantic would proceed with a deal if it were
not sure that federal regulators would approve of pooling.
</P>
<P>
   Once investors are convinced that a takeover is imminent, shares
of the acquiring company usually decline, mostly because investors
believe that the company's earnings will suffer from the costs of
the merger. Shares of the presumed target usually rise, mostly
because investors believe they will get a premium over market value
once the deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than a sense of conviction, a sense of confusion
continued to hover over Bell Atlantic and Airtouch's shares Monday,
sending both down. Bell Atlantic's shares lost $2.0625, or 3.8
percent, closing at $51.9375 on the New York Stock Exchange.
Airtouch's lost $4.1875 or 5.8 percent, closing at $68.25. While it
seemed unlikely that federal regulators would altogether prevent
Bell Atlantic from using pooling, the complicating factors in a bid
for Airtouch have seemed serious enough that the two companies
continued Monday to speak privately with regulators at the
Securities and Exchange Commission about the deal's accounting,
executives close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The big benefit of pooling is that it allows acquiring companies
to avoid taking charges against their future earnings to cover the
difference between what they pay for another company (in this case,
say, $45 billion) and the value of the target company's tangible
assets (in the case of Airtouch around $8 billion). When a company
uses purchase, rather than pooling, accounting, those charges must
be taken in order to balance its books.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the many catches, however, are that the target company
cannot have undergone any major changes in capital structure within
the two years before a pooling (at least not any major changes made
in contemplation of a future pooling), while the combined company
cannot divest any major assets for two years after a pooling.
</P>
<P>
   These catches create at least two potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are good reasons for Bell Atlantic to want to spin
off its wireless operations, after acquiring Airtouch, by issuing a
separate tracking stock, which is meant to represent one aspect of
a company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether Bell Atlantic issued $45 billion or $55
billion worth of stock for Airtouch, such a deal would seriously
dilute Bell Atlantic's future earnings, perhaps by more than 20
percent. By issuing a tracking stock (much as the Sprint Corp. did
recently for its interest in the Sprint PCS wireless venture), Bell
Atlantic would allow more conservative investors to continue to buy
a stock tied to its core operations, while allowing others to
invest in the fast-growing, though less-profitable, wireless
operation. (And it would pick up separate sets of Wall Street
analysts to pitch those two stocks.)
</P>
<P>
   The SEC might prohibit such a move for two years after a
pooling, or conversely, prohibit pooling in the first place if Bell
Atlantic planned to subsequently issue a tracking stock. (AT&AMP;T
Corp. plans to issue at least one tracking stock after acquiring
Tele-Communications Inc., the cable television giant, but is not
using the pool method of accounting in that acquisition.)
Privately, executives close to the negotiations say Bell Atlantic
does not plan to offer a tracking stock after a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The second potential problem lies in a deal that Airtouch made
with Mediaone Group Inc. (formerly U S West Media Group) last
spring. In that, Airtouch received Mediaone's domestic wireless
businesses in exchange for $4.5 billion of Airtouch's stock. It is
possible that by issuing so much stock, Airtouch may have tainted
itself for the purposes of pooling.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell Atlantic and Airtouch could have some good arguments
for why the Mediaone deal should not matter for the purposes of
pooling. They could argue that Airtouch was not thinking about
merging with Bell Atlantic when it issued all of those shares for
Mediaone, thereby letting Airtouch off the hook (though most people
who follow the communications industry have been expecting an
Airtouch-Bell Atlantic merger for at least a year).
</P>
<P>
   They could also argue that the amount of stock issued for
Mediaone was minuscule relative to Airtouch's overall size.
Moreover, of the $4.5 billion in stock that Mediaone received, $1.6
billion was in preferred stock that Airtouch had the option of
converting into cash, rather than into common shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
