<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-ART-NYT     01-04 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: CONN.) 
CONNECTICUT CELEBRATES ITS TWO NUMBER-ONE BASKETBALL TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Tip-off was three hours away and the temperature
was 14 degrees, but it was party time outside the University of
Connecticut basketball arena. Three early birds started the line at
daybreak by pitching a tent on the top steps, and other students
staked their claims with a barbecue, sleeping bags, a sofa, a Ford
Escort for blasting tunes and a pillow for playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   And these were students who already had tickets. They just
wanted front-row seats, the better to howl for the Husky men and
heckle their victims, who on Saturday night happened to be the
Georgetown Hoyas, who were eventually packed away 87-64. Here among
the wind-swept farms of eastern Connecticut, the Huskies are
redefining the term ``basketball powerhouse'': Both the men's and
women's teams are ranked No. 1 in the nation, a feat that has been
accomplished only once before. By Connecticut, back in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just for a week. This time, the two teams have led
the nation six weeks running. They continued the rout on Saturday
when, in a rare eclipse, both played home games seven hours apart,
leaving both teams 11-0 and UConn's fans baying with an amazed
euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to say, `Yukon? Is that in Canada?''' said John
Dipollina, 19, a sophomore majoring in sports management.
</P>
<P>
   UConn basketball frenzy is by no means confined to this
supercharged season, or to this university's 14,000 undergraduates.
It has been a consuming pastime for years in this state, which has
no major league team in any sport (jai alai doesn't count) and a
heavy concentration of UConn alumni (two-thirds of the 140,000
living alumni are still in Connecticut).
</P>
<P>
   People here still talk about the riot of '53, when the state
police had to restore order after 100 ticketless Husky fans rushed
the gates of a game with Holy Cross. A documentary last year on
Connecticut Public Television went so far as to call the
university's men's basketball ``the single unifying force in the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Emery, 42, who did not attend Connecticut but has missed
only eight men's home games in 20 years, is known in the stands as
``Big Red'' and is famous for trying to rally the team by using his
hefty frame to spell out U-C-O-N-N as if it were Y-M-C-A, with the
fans around him chanting along.
</P>
<P>
   At shops on campus and in downtown Hartford, Husky fans have a
choice of UConn dog dishes, UConn milk-chocolate dog biscuits
(marked ``Not for animal consumption'') and UConn yard signs that
warn, ``Beware of the Dog.'' (Though the official explanation is
that the mascot was picked by students in 1934 in tribute to the
frigid hills around Storrs, the choice is more widely thought to be
a play on ``Yukon.'')
</P>
<P>
   And now, Husky fans feel they have license to be cocky. ``You
talk about Notre Dame football, you talk about UConn basketball,''
said Wayne Davidovich, 40, a carpenter from Madison, Conn., who is
not an alumnus but has owned season tickets for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive his reach. Not only are the teams undefeated, they have,
at times, overwhelmed their opponents. The men's record this year
includes scores of 102-67 and 102-60; the women have won 117-20 and
107-56. After Villanova (an impressive 10-2 record going into the
game) went down 100-76 on Wednesday, one player, Howard Brown,
mashed his face and body despondently against a pillar as he waited
his turn in the post-game interview room. ``You can't really get
used to the kind of pace and pressure they put on you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that was the doormat of its conference, the Big
East, throughout the 1980's, closing seasons with humiliating
records in the conference like 3-13 (twice), 4-12 and 5-11 (also
twice). In a sign of how much things have changed in the '90s, the
men are faulted for never winning a national championship, despite
making it to the ``Sweet 16'' of the NCAA tournament six times.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent victory at the Hartford Civic Center, where the
Huskies play half their home games because it holds larger crowds
than Gampel Pavilion on campus, a hospitality suite on the 17th
floor of the Hartford Hilton buzzed with tales of the time when the
team played on a retractable floor over the clay of the ROTC drill
shed, tickets could be had the day of the game and even the best
seats were unassigned.
</P>
<P>
   Now, fans seeking scalpers no longer simply hang out in the
Civic Center's food court. The high demand forces them to work the
frosty streets of downtown Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   For the women, who won the national championship in 1995, the
change is perhaps even more dramatic. Just 10 years ago, at game's
end, fans surged onto the court to hug the players and give them
homemade cookies. These days, if they wait long enough, they might
get an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   The stands at the women's games are peppered with parents who
have taken their daughters along, hoping that the players will
serve as role models. ``Are you going to be a Husky?'' Vince
Peterson, an insurance-company manager, asked his 4-year-old,
Courtney, during a hot-dog break on Saturday. She was wearing a
team jersey, socks and a T-shirt. ``Shea Ralph!'' she replied,
naming her favorite player, a junior guard.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Gervino, a Hartford lawyer holding a teddy bear for her
4-year-old daughter, Kayla, said the men's games are too stressful.
``Their fans yell at the coaches, yell at the players, yell at the
officials,'' she said. ``I guess the stakes are too high. This is a
lovefest: We love the players, we love the coaches, we love
UConn.''
</P>
<P>
   The team encourages the emotional attachment. In the official
guides, the men's biographies stick to birth date and major, while
the women's includes hobbies (''running, shopping and watching
`Jeopardy!'''), favorite food (``frozen yogurt with chocolate
sprinkles'') and pregame routine (''curl my hair'').
</P>
<P>
   The oncourt dominance by both teams dovetails with a 10-year, $1
billion makeover that the university calls ``UConn 2000.''
Bulldozers chug around campus, some sod is so fresh it looks like a
jigsaw puzzle, 150 new faculty members have arrived in 18 months,
out-of-state enrollment is up and donations have soared from $8.2
million in 1995 to a projected $25 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The university chancellor, Mark A. Emmert, said the timing of
the basketball dominance is perfect for his plans for an overall
renaissance. ``In a university community, there's few things that
generate more excitement than construction and winning athletics,
and we have a double dose of both,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All this has critics on campus fretting that the university may
be becoming famous for the wrong reason. Even comments from the
teams' supporters tend to bolster that view. ``We bring in these
key speakers _ Nobel Prizes and all that _ and they go in the small
halls,'' said Phil Barry, a longtime Connecticut athletic official
who retired in 1987. ``But if somebody throws a basketball up in
the air around here, you know you're going to have 5 to 10,000
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Alumni still bring their children to see the farm animals and
slurp ice cream (14 percent butterfat) at the dairy bar just down
the hill from the cow barns, but few can imagine the days when the
university was Connecticut Agricultural College and the basketball
team was the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   As if to mark the new era for Connecticut sports, the team on
Saturday introduced a second mascot _ a 10-foot inflatable husky,
complete with huge, floppy sneakers _ that is to join the beloved
Jonathan the Husky Dog, who's just a guy in a furry white suit. The
fans booed the newcomer, happy to dance with the Husky that brought
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
