A7985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUBWAY-KILLING-NYT     01-04 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DAY AFTER KILLING, RIDERS ARE CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: With related stories, NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM, NY-SUBWAY-SUSPECT) 
(rl) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some people looked over their shoulders. Others
stayed away from the edge of the platform. On Monday, many people
were being just a little more cautious after hearing what happened
to 32-year-old Kendra Webdale, who was pushed in front of the
uptown-bound train on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm shocked, and I'm looking over my shoulder,''
said Daniela Lopez, 18, a student from Flatbush, Brooklyn, as she
waited for the same train at the same station _ East 23d Street _
only a few feet from the spot where Ms. Webdale had been pushed to
her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always told me to stay behind the orange line,''
Miss Lopez said, keeping a sizable distance from the two colored
strips _ one yellow, one orange _ that are designed to keep riders
at least 30 inches from the edge of the tracks. ``Today, I'm really
standing back.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the subway system struggled to keep a sense of
proportion. So bizarre and infrequent, attacks like the one on Ms.
Webdale might best be compared, they said, to lightning bolts, or
bricks falling with fatal precision onto pedestrians from Manhattan
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what a varied and heavily visited city we live in,
you have to wonder why this sort of thing doesn't happen more
often,'' said Nancy Shupack, 47, a native New Yorker who teaches
cosmetology at West Side High School in Manhattan. She said she has
used the subways all her life, without being threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be focused, and be aware of the signs that
someone may act aggressively,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Police and transit officials said they could not find exact data
on how frequently incidents like the one involving Ms. Webdale have
occurred or been attempted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a 20-year-old woman was killed when pushed from between
cars of a moving train by a teen-ager who was trying to mug her.
And in a highly publicized incident in 1979, a 17-year-old high
school student, Renee Katz, was pushed in front of a train at the
West 50th Street subway station. She survived, but lost her right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Al O'Leary, chief of public information for New York City
Transit, said some people seem not to guard against the dangers. He
described a scene of cavalier indifference on the platform at 86th
Street in Brooklyn Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were reading their newspaper stories about this young
woman's death as they stood right at the edge of the platform,'' he
said. ``The point is that subways are heavy machinery, they do not
stop quickly, and please don't stand near the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though such horrific attacks have been rare, the death of
Ms. Webdale provided a stark reminder, particularly for passengers
at the 23d Street station, of what can happen on narrow subway
platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``On most days, I would say that the subway system is safe,''
said John Laracuente, 35, a native of Chelsea who said he has used
the 23d Street station frequently for most of his life and has
never been accosted. ``Today, after what happened here yesterday,
I'd have to say the subways are going down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
