<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRADING BEGINS SMOOTHLY AS EURO ENTERS MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   The euro had a nearly flawless debut in world markets as
European financial institutions opened for business without a hitch
and Europe's new single currency climbed in value against other
major currencies.
</P>
<P>
   In its first full day of trading, the euro opened at $1.17 and
climbed to nearly $1.186 before falling back to about $1.18. Far
from being unsettled by the uncertainty or technical glitches, the
stock markets in Frankfurt, Paris, Milan and Madrid all jumped by 5
percent or more. But the reaction was much more subdued in the
consumer marketplace, where there was little evidence of change.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the euro will fare against the dollar and what
kind of challenge it will make against the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   IMF CHIEFS CONSIDER CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the International Monetary Fund are proposing a major
overhaul of the fund's operations that could permit it to intervene
directly in the operation of national economies before they get
into deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   CBS IN DEAL WITH AMERICA ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   CBS News will announce a deal with America Online this week to
become the exclusive broadcast news provider for the online
service, executives involved in the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   A REQUEST TO LIMIT MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   The head of Intuit, which makes the Quicken personal-finance
software, urged the judge in the antitrust trial against Microsoft
to limit that company's use of its market-dominating Windows
operating system to promote its other products.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORK SOLUTIONS TO SPLIT STOCK
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions, which has a temporary monopoly on the
distribution of Internet addresses, announced plans for a stock
split and a secondary offering of 4.58 million shares. The proposed
offering would reduce the ownership of the parent company, Science
Applications International, to 45 percent from the 72 percent it
owns now. Shares of Network Solutions rose $24.125, to $155.
</P>
<P>
   RUMORS ABOUT AUTO MERGERS
</P>
<P>
   The talk at the North American International Auto Show this year
is about which automakers will be the next to merge. Jacques
Nasser, who became Ford's chief executive on Friday, declined to
comment on rumors that Ford was talking with Volvo or BMW.
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS MAY REDUCE DONATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Many of the United States' arts organizations and nonprofit
groups are concerned that the record number of corporate mergers
last year may lead to a decline in donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
