<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF GAMES REKINDLE THE INSTANT-REPLAY DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a rash of high-profile controversial officiating calls
marred several games during the National Football League regular
season, there was a move afoot to reinstate instant replay for the
league's post-season play. Criticized as both an overreaction and
as hastily conceived, the instant replay playoff proposal was
retracted.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt some league officials approached last weekend's
wild-card playoff games with fingers crossed. Their wishes were not
granted.
</P>
<P>
   What some may have feared came to pass _ and fumble _ at the
conclusion of dynamic games in San Francisco and Miami this weekend
as officials' calls once again became a source of debate and
discord.
</P>
<P>
   Television replays appeared to show that San Francisco 49ers
wide receiver Jerry Rice fumbled the football before he was down
with about 30 seconds remaining in the 49ers game with Green Bay.
The fumble was recovered by Green Bay's Bernardo Harris.
</P>
<P>
   But the game officials ruled that Rice was down, and that a
whistle had blown before the football came loose. Four plays later,
San Francisco's Terrell Owens scored the dramatic, game-winning
touchdown in the 49ers' 30-27 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Green Bay's general manager, Ron Wolf, fumed in his
team's locker room, arguing strenuously that the league must
institute instant replay next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody in their right mind knows that was a fumble,'' Wolf
told reporters. ``Maybe you didn't watch any football this year;
we've had a lot of bad calls. The league has to address it and
correct these errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, can it be done? I'm not sure. Replay has failed so many
times. But I would think after what happened to Buffalo these last
couple of weeks we've got Buffalo's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I would assume we'd get some more votes and get this thing
passed. It needs to be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, George Young, the NFL's senior vice president of
football operations, said of the 49ers-Packers game, ``I thought it
was a great game and a great ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Young confirmed that under the instant-replay system used by the
league from 1986 to 1991, Rice's fumble would not have been a
reversible call because the whistle had blown indicating Rice was
down. All play after the whistle in that situation is irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning minutes of the Miami-Buffalo game Saturday,
Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie passed to Andre Reed, who was
tackled at the goal line. When a touchdown was not called, Reed
jumped up, bumping an official as he argued the call.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was ejected from the game and issued an unsportsmanlike
conduct penalty. Instead of having the ball within inches of the
goal line, the Bills, who trailed by 10 points at the time, were 15
yards away and eventually settled for a 33-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo regained possession and drove to the Miami 5-yard line
in the final seconds before a Flutie sack and fumble cut short its
rally. Miami advanced with a 24-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
