<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLON-AD-COLUMN-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  
 ADVERTISING: FALLON McELLIGOTT STRENGTHENS ITS NEW YORK BRANCH  
(lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After some stops and starts that made a ride on the
subway seem smooth by comparison, Fallon McElligott is hoping that
a reconfigured management team will get its operations in New York
back, well, on track.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott, the creatively focused shop based in
Minneapolis, is known for sassy campaigns for brands like BMW cars,
Lee jeans and Miller Lite beer. The agency's top executives have
been seeking to gain a better foothold in the competitive New York
market as part of ambitious growth plans that include opening an
office in London.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Fallon McElligott hired Jamie Barrett as creative
director for the New York office, known as Fallon McElligott New
York City. Barrett, who had most recently been a leading creative
executive on the Nike Inc. account at Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland,
Ore., completes a four-person team of managers that also includes
Alison Burns, who was hired in July as president for the office
after working at agencies such as Bartle Bogle Hegarty.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight years at Wieden, I was mentally and emotionally
ready to try something new,'' Barrett, 37, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you do 100-plus commercials for Nike, you feel maybe you
have something else to prove,'' he added. ``Having been given the
opportunity to work on a creatively glamorous account like Nike, I
relish the opportunity to work on accounts not as seemingly
glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott New York City ``was a perfect opportunity,''
Barrett said, ``because it felt like a place ready to explode; all
it needed was to get all the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott has been trying for several years to piece
together a New York presence. After opening a small service office,
the agency decided to expand through a majority-owned joint venture
with Andy Berlin, who has held executive posts at agencies
including Goodby, Berlin &AMP; Silverstein in San Francisco (now the
Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners unit of Omnicom Group).
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture agency, named Fallon McElligott Berlin, opened
in 1995 and handled a roster of blue-chip clients that included BMW
motorcycles sold by a unit of BMW AG, Coca-Cola Co. and the NBC
unit of General Electric Co. But in November 1997, after the
collapse of negotiations for Berlin to buy the majority interest in
Fallon McElligott Berlin, the agency was dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   As Berlin and other executives left to form Berlin Cameron &AMP;
Partners, Fallon McElligott combined remnants of the joint venture
with its small office to open a full-service New York outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an entrepreneurial opportunity wrapped up in a brand
name,'' Barrett said of Fallon McElligott New York City, which has
about 65 employees handling accounts with billings estimated at $75
million out of an agency total estimated at $500 million. There are
about 525 employees in Minneapolis and 10 more in London.
</P>
<P>
   Among the New York clients for Fallon McElligott _ for
advertising, interactive marketing, public relations and graphic
design _ are Time and Fortune magazines, published by the Time Inc.
unit of Time Warner Inc.; Conseco Inc., the insurance conglomerate,
and Nikon Inc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most recent significant gain came in early December, when
Georgia-Pacific Corp. named Fallon McElligott New York City to
handle consumer paper products like Angel Soft, Coronet, MD and
Sparkle; spending for those brands has run about $13.5 million a
year but could be increased for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely see the opportunity in New York as being to
compete on a larger scale than simply against the creative
boutiques,'' said Ms. Burns, 35, who joined Barrett for the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Burns said one goal was ``defining New York accounts'' like
local retailers, which she said would ``provide opportunities to
make a creative mark in this city and help separate us from
Minneapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   She described the other target as ``the soft underbelly of large
agencies that are not delivering'' outstanding campaigns ``for
clients with large budgets'' because, she said, they are too
focused on ``service and relationships rather than the creative
product.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Barrett's second stint at Fallon McElligott, as he
worked for the agency from 1984 to 1990. He left to join the New
York office of Chiat/Day, now the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of Omnicom,
and then moved to Portland in 1991 to work for Wieden &AMP; Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always maintained good ties with Pat,'' Barrett said,
referring to Pat Fallon, the chairman at Fallon McElligott, who
spends two or three days a week at Fallon McElligott New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why I'm back,'' he added. ``If you make a
decision to return to an agency 10 years later, you had a good
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Both executives said they were aware of the daunting pitfalls
that confront agencies staking claims to the New York market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest danger is to believe that if you build it, they
will come,'' Ms. Burns said. ``We take New York seriously. It's a
tough environment. You need to have a strong sense of purpose, a
strong team and an indefatigable will to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who see significance in odd coincidences, Barrett and
Ms. Burns both described stints in sports journalism before they
started their careers in advertising. Barrett once wrote for Squash
News, while Ms. Burns once edited articles about women's rugby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
