<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM-ART-     01-04 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG WOMAN'S DREAMS OF NEW YORK END TRAGICALLY IN SUBWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 10 p.m. ET; with
NY-SUBWAY-SUSPECT, NY-SUBWAY-KILLING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She came to New York from Buffalo in the spring of
1995, like so many young, ambitious people, in search of adventure
and the writer's life. But unlike the dreamers who envision fame
and fortune in the towers of Manhattan and find only misery and
loneliness in its slums, Kendra Webdale seemed ready for the city.
</P>
<P>
   She was 29, had a degree in communications from the State
University of New York at Buffalo and had had various jobs,
including one in local journalism that whet her appetite. She was,
by all accounts, self-reliant, well-read and flexible: trusting,
even with strangers, but wary and tough when she had to be.
</P>
<P>
   She found a roommate and a walk-up apartment in Manhattan's
Flatiron District, took a receptionist's job at a recording company
and found her way into the stream of life in the city: running
every morning before dawn, going to the library to research ideas
for her screenplay, finding inspiration in the hills of Central
Park and the canyons of midtown. She often took pictures like a
tourist.
</P>
<P>
   She was slender and blonde and had dates and boyfriends, though
there was no one serious in her life, acquaintances said.
Thoughtful, vivacious, she made friends easily _ at work, in her
building and in the bars of the East Village. Above all, her family
and friends said, she loved New York: for its crowds, for its whirl
of daring and diversity, for its daily sense of possibility.
</P>
<P>
   There was, in all of this, no way to foresee the sudden end on a
rainwashed Sunday afternoon _ the man in the beige coat approaching
on the subway platform at 23rd Street, his mumbled incoherent words
and, as she turned away, the hands on her back, hurling her onto
the tracks into the path of the onrushing train.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webdale, 32, was killed instantly. And on Monday, as the
29-year-old man who had been grabbed on the platform by witnesses _
a man with a long history of mental illness _ was arraigned on a
murder charge, New Yorkers who had come to think of their city as a
safer, gentler place were abruptly confronted with images of their
own worst nightmare _ the crazy subway pusher _ and the reality
that all the plunging crime statistics can mean nothing in a moment
of madness.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the victim's grieving relatives, friends and co-workers
tried to make sense of an essentially senseless act, however, there
were some voices of reason, if not of understanding or forgiveness,
and they came from her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a random incident,'' the victim's father, Ralph T.
Webdale, said from his home in Fredonia, 35 miles southwest of
Buffalo. ``Kendra always liked New York, and she was very
comfortable in the city when we visited there. She just absolutely
fell in love with the city. She'd been there three years. She felt
safe there. I think it was a random, ridiculous thing. It could
have been anyone, and any place.''
</P>
<P>
   Webdale, 57, vice president for finance and the chief financial
officer for Brooks Memorial Hospital in nearby Dunkirk, and his
wife, Patricia, 57, a payroll worker, raised five daughters and one
son, recalled the slain woman on Monday as considerate,
compassionate and loving, a gentle person who cared deeply about
others and about her adopted city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendra had always wanted to go to New York,'' Mrs. Webdale
said. ``We're proud of her, that she organized herself and got a
job and enjoyed her life. He dream was to write a screenplay. She
was seriously researching the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred miles away, Ralph T. Webdale Jr. and Kim Webdale,
the victim's brother and sister, spent three hours sorting through
his sister's possessions on Monday in her fourth-floor walkup at
158 East 23d Street. Afterward, they spoke briefly to a reporter,
and echoed their parents comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the kind of person who would have helped the kind of
person who did this,'' the brother said. He showed some of the
photographs they had found in her room _ Kendra, blonde and
blue-eyed, on the sidewalk, smiling, and in a bar with four
friends, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the most beautiful girl _ not only outside, but inside
as well,'' Kim Webdale said. ``We will miss her very much. She was
not afraid of the subway. She rode it all the time. Kendra loved
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears welled up, and she could not go on.
</P>
<P>
   The third of six children, Kendra Webdale was born in Buffalo in
1966, but the family moved to Fredonia, when she was eight and she
graduated from Fredonia High School in 1984. Her siblings Besides
Kendra, Kim and Ralph, the siblings are Kelly, Suzanne and Krista.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Kendra attended the State University of New
York at Cortland for two years, then transferred to the
university's branch at Buffalo, where she graduated in 1988 with
what her mother called good grades and a degree in communications.
</P>
<P>
   She later worked in a variety of jobs, among other things as a
switchboard operator at the hospital in Dunkirk where her father is
a corporate officer. From July 1995 to March 1996, she was the
editor of two weekly publications in Buffalo _ The West Side Times
and The Buffalo Rocket _ which are distributed free and have a
combined circulation of 26,000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
