<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     01-04 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAREHOUSE MANAGER'S THUGGERY NEEDS ARRESTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(
 &HT;    Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by e-mail to lloydonjob(at)aol.com, or they
can be mailed to P.O. Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names will be
withheld upon request.) 
BY Ken LLoyd, Ph.D.  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Our manager, who owns this warehouse, has punched holes in
his office wall and recently used profanity over the loudspeaker
that was directed toward every employee. The 30 of us never know
what will set him off or what could go flying next. Not only do we
have to deal with his bad behavior, the warehouse supervisor often
makes racial comments and uses profanity. Other than finding
another job, what actions can we take? T.B.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since your manager does not know how to manage himself, it
should come as no surprise that he does not know how to manage
others either. One way to deal with him and the equally clueless
supervisor is to act collectively and assertively.
</P>
<P>
   Tell your manager that you and your associates need to meet with
him at his earliest convenience. During such a meeting,
specifically describe the behaviors that are creating problems and
then present suggestions to correct them.
</P>
<P>
   Let him see the present and potential costs associated with
fear, harassment, hostility, intimidation and safety issues in your
company. Tell him that you hope he will make the necessary changes
soon, as you would prefer to resolve matters within the
organization rather than seeking outside remedies.
</P>
<P>
   You and your associates have many rights as employees, and you
should seriously consider asserting them. Rather than letting your
manager step all over you, the time has come for all of you to take
some steps of your own.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You can't imagine our shock and dismay when we were told that
the new manager of our department is going to be the owner's son.
He is a spoiled brat who lacks the training and experience to be in
management, and several of us who have been here for years are
ready to quit. Should we tell the owner he is making a big mistake?
M.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. When a new manager is brought in from the outside, it is not
uncommon to find a combination of employee resentment and
resistance. And this negative reaction is intensified if the new
arrival has previously established himself as a spoiled brat whose
skills and experience appear to be rather thin.
</P>
<P>
   Although much depends on your working relationship with the
owner, if you approach him now, there is virtually no chance that
he will say, Gosh, you're right. My son isn't qualified for this
job. What was I thinking?
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that the owner's son is going to be your new
manager, and it makes sense to approach him with an open mind.
After all, there have been plenty of cases where people move into
leadership positions for which they are seemingly unqualified, but
rise to the occasion and perform at outstanding levels.
</P>
<P>
   However, if his performance turns out to be more outrageous than
outstanding, inform the owner of the specific gaps in his son's
performance, and tell him that he is not being fair to his son by
placing him in this position. Then present some alternative
positions, as well as educational options, that may better suit his
son.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the bigger picture, many companies today find real
advantages by promoting from within, and you may be appropriately
concerned that the owner of your company opted instead to promote
from within his own family.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We put in a new sick-leave policy and one of our employees
analyzed it and e-mailed just about everybody here and said the
policy is a ``step in the wrong direction.'' My instant reaction
was to terminate him, but now I'm not so sure. What do you suggest?
T.T.
</P>
<P>
   A. If this employee were standing at the proverbial water cooler
and trouncing the new sick-leave policy, you would be ill-advised
to terminate him, and you would be equally ill-advised to do so
now. For many employees today, e-mail is an electronic water
cooler.
</P>
<P>
   However, companies can have policies regarding inappropriate use
of the company's e-mail system. If you have such a policy and the
employee in question knew about it and violated it, then there may
be a basis for some action.
</P>
<P>
   While part of your decision must rest on whether this employee
is highly productive or rarely productive, it may help to step back
and look at the incident from a slightly broader perspective. For
example, if you are a company that values the employees as
resources, and truly encourages their inputs and suggestions, this
employee's behavior may be a normal and even positive outcome. It
points to a need for communication, rather than condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   Although this employee advised everyone that the new policy is a
step in the wrong direction, taking action against him may be an
even bigger step in the wrong direction. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
