<SLUG> BC-BBO-ORIOLES-CUBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES-CUBA SERIES RAISES SECURITY CONCERNS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Security concerns may undermine the Baltimore Orioles' latest
effort to arrange a two-game home-and-home exhibition series with
the Cuban national baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   An Orioles delegation is scheduled to travel to Cuba later this
week to negotiate the series, which the club began trying to put
together three years ago, but its trip may be aborted by Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball official said Monday that no final decision had been
made, but he acknowledged that many concerns have been raised,
including those involving security. The official said such hatred
of Fidel Castro existed among Cuban expatriates in this country
that allowing a major league team to play in Cuba could put major
league players at risk in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a lawyer on the players' side said Cuban players in
the majors and other Latin players had such strong feelings about
the treatment players received in Cuba that they would likely
oppose the idea of a major league team playing there. Other
players, the lawyer said, would most likely support the position of
their fellow major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official disclosed Monday that the Orioles
had received permission to send a delegation to Cuba to discuss the
possibility of a game in Havana and a game in Baltimore in March.
Officials interested in creating better relations with Cuba
apparently believe sports is one way to begin to thaw the hostile
relations between the countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years or so, various initiatives have been
undertaken to send a single team or an all-star team to Cuba. But
United States and Major League Baseball policy never allowed the
initiatives to get far.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles began their attempt about three years ago, but their
initial plans were halted when Cuba shot down two planes flown by
expatriates in 1996. The club periodically revived its efforts,
becoming most active recently.
</P>
<P>
   By gaining special licenses from various government agencies to
travel to Cuba, the Orioles went beyond any point they had reached
previously.
</P>
<P>
   Club officials have discussed the matter with baseball officials
and were never told to end their efforts. But baseball officials,
having taken a closer look, apparently see greater risks.
</P>
<P>
   A initiative on the Cuban front came to light Monday. The lawyer
on the players' side said that while major league players were on
strike in 1994, an intermediary representing the Cuban government
approached the players association about the possibility of playing
games in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The union, the lawyer said, checked with government agencies and
determined that it would violate United States law if it made any
kind of arrangement with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   About two months ago, Cuba's sports minister, Humberto
Rodriguez, raised the possibility that Cuba might allow its players
to play in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are receptive to any proposal by the major leagues as long
as it respects the principles of Cuban socialist sports,''
Rodriguez was quoted as saying in an interview in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Castro told United States newspaper editors in
Havana that he was not opposed to Cuban teams competing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Cuba has been embarrassed and angered by
the defection of a series of players, including Orlando Hernandez
of the Yankees and his half-brother, Livan Hernandez of the Florida
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   For a Cuban player to play for a United States team without
defecting, the Cuban government and Major League Baseball would
have to reach an agreement on pay. The Cuban government would want
the players' salaries, but the union, if not baseball officials,
would find that a major problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
