u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-NEONATAL1ST     01-04 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-NEONATAL1STLEDE-WRITET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTUPLETS-NEONATAL-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: New to correct baby's weight and year Texas Children's
Hospital Neonatal Intensive Care Unit was established 
 
TEXAS NEONATAL ICU WORKING WITH RECORD NUMBERS 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In a low-lit room he shares with his bigger brother,
baby Ikem, the smallest of the seven surviving octuplets, lies
nearly motionless, wrapped in bunting on a warming bed.
</P>
<P>
   The beeping of a monitor is his lullaby. A Beanie Baby dog and
bear, only slightly smaller than he, sit near his head. Tubes and
lines run from his hands, feet and face.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Ikem moves a tiny right hand near his ear, fingers
clutched in a fist. He opens his eyes for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   For an outsider getting a first glimpse of the baby who weighed
only 17.6 ounces at birth, the focus inevitably shifts from Ikem's
innate charm and baby-appeal, to the ventilator and IV keeping him
alive. It's a jarring contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this sight is commonplace at the Texas Children's Hospital
Neonatal Intensive Care Unit, which every year cares for 900 of the
sickest babies in Arkansas, Louisiana, Oklahoma and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Children's Neonatal ICU (or ``nee-cue,'' as staffers refer
to it) served as a backdrop while attention was focused on the
world's first surviving set of octuplets born to Nkem Chukwu and
her husband, Iyke Louis Udobi, on Dec. 8 and Dec. 20.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital is a record-breaker in its own right, and is
playing an increasingly important role as the number of infants
born prematurely with low birth weights continues to climb.
</P>
<P>
   With 120 beds, and plans to add 40 more in the next two years,
it is the largest unit of its kind in the United States. The NICU
can handle 60 babies who are ``level three'' patients, requiring
some sort of breathing assistance, either through mechanical
ventilation or other positive-pressure devices.
</P>
<P>
   The Chukwu babies, one of them born at 25 weeks and the rest
born at 27 weeks (full term is 37 or more weeks), are all level
three patients. They remained in critical but stable condition
Monday. Six of the seven surviving babies _ girls Chidi, Chima,
Ebuka and Echerem, and boys Jioke and Ikem _ are breathing on their
own; the other, baby girl Gorom, is receiving assistance from a
ventilator. Baby Odera died Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Because of intense media interest, and the parents' request for
privacy, the hospital has taken additional security measures,
putting the newborns in isolation rooms along the rear wall of the
unit. A uniformed Houston police officer sits in front of the
rooms. Two hospital security officers patrol the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   A staff of more than 350 doctors, nurses, respiratory
therapists, nutritionists and other experts provide
around-the-clock care. An on-site breast-milk bank serves 100,000
meals a year.
</P>
<P>
   The babies rest in ``pods,'' or groupings of four to six, with
nurses perusing thick binders of medical charts at an island in the
middle. Preemies frequently have heart, lung and intestinal
problems, and several hundred surgeries a year are performed right
there, with doctors bringing a mini-operating room to the pod.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of volunteers sew quilted covers for the incubators and
hold the older babies, providing skin-to-skin contact. A six- or
nine-month stay is not uncommon (one child recently went home after
a yearlong stay), and the volunteers fill in as comfort-givers
while parents are at work or tending to needs at home. Doctors say
the Chukwu babies are likely to remain in the unit until March. The
five surviving sextuplets born to Chris and Christopher Collins of
nearby Kingwood in November will be there at least until February.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at Texas Children's,
said the last two months of 1998 have been the unit's busiest since
it was established in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In the period between the births of the Collins sextuplets and
the Chukwu octuplets, the hospital, which rarely turns patients
away, reached its level three capacity and sent three babies to
neonatal units at Hermann Hospital and Ben Taub.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, the unit had 119 babies, 56 of them in level
three. Thirty-five of the babies were the result of multiple
births, according to a hospital spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Fertility drugs, which help countless couples have children,
also contribute to the growing number of multiple births. These
often produce underweight and premature babies.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said the annual number of twins born has increased by 50
percent over the last 18 years. In 1996, there were more than 6,000
births of triplets or more, nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a significant part of this increase in very
low birthweights,'' Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   The murmurs of nurses and doctors and the low-key setting belie
the stress of the place. To keep the unit staffed with six Baylor
College of Medicine faculty members, three ``fellows'' (doctors
learning the neonatology specialty) and eight Baylor medical
residents, Weisman has to hire more than three times that many.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the doctors provide hands-on patient care for an
average of only four months at a stretch. The rest of the year they
spend on research, teaching or administration; Weisman explains
they need time away from the NICU _ the job carries a high burnout
rate. Every detail matters, and there are hundreds of details to be
kept track of daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty high pressure cooker. These patients don't have
little problems, they have big problems,'' said Weisman, who spends
only three months out of the year seeing NICU patients. ``The
margin for error is very, very small. You don't have leeway for
making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
