<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFOMERCIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMERCIALS GET FAT IN '98 ON DIET DESIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Couch potatoes across the world saw 1998 as a time
to slim down, making televised pitches for exercise- and
diet-related products among the top grossing infomercials of the
year, an industry tracker has reported.
</P>
<P>
   Americans' determination to get in shape helped L.A.-based
National Media Corp.'s Quantum Television unit place four of its
shows in the top 10, according to the Infomercial Marketing Report
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The list is based on confidential sales figures from all the
companies in what has grown into an $800 million industry, said
Steve Dworman, who publishes the report.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has long been considered the epicenter of the
infomercial universe. Two of the industry's pioneers _ eternally
peppy Mike Levy and his ``Amazing Discoveries'' series, and Ron
Popeil of Ronco fame _ are Angelenos, and a host of post-production
facilities and other companies have sprung up across the L.A. area
to service the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For '98, the infomercial for Bioslim, a dietary supplement, was
the top grosser with about $80 million in sales. Quantum's show
about T-Fal cookware pulled in about $30 million for 10th place,
Dworman said.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise, cosmetic or dietary products held six of the top 10
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weight loss has always been a popular category,'' Dworman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales volume industrywide, though, was down slightly from 1997
when Total Gym grossed about $95 million sales to lead the year.
Total Gym finished third in '98.
</P>
<P>
   The drop is due to a combination of factors, industry experts
said, including the higher cost of television time and less of it
being available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago on Lifetime (cable channel) they used
to air infomercials until 7 a.m. not until 5:30 a.m. or 6 a.m.,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kirby, president of National Media and chairman and chief
executive officer of Quantum Television, said variety is the key to
his company's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a product-driven business,'' he said. ``Product is and
always has been king. The most innovative marketers are the ones
who garner sales.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is not surprised that exercise equipment and dieting
programs are popular with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 25 percent of all Americans are overweight so that's
a pretty big potential universe of customers to reach. We believe
there will always be a market for three to four innovative fitness
products a year in this industry,'' Kirby said.
</P>
<P>
   Dworman noted that viewers don't mind making a significant
financial commitment in their pursuit of a more healthy lifestyle
because many of the products cost more than $100; Quantum's
Timeworks exercise machine tops the scales at $599.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by John Pitre, who also invented a $10,400 home
exercise gym that claims to give a total body workout in four
minutes. The Rom, as it is known, is made in Van Nuys, a Los
Angeles suburb. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
