<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8025 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM-ART-     01-04 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of 26,000.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis M. Gallagher, general manager of Rocket Communications,
which owns the publications, recalled that Ms. Webdale supervised a
small staff of writers and editors, met deadlines and had what he
called a charming personality, happy without being bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   By the spring of 1996, however, the taste of local journalism
was no longer sufficient. Ms. Webdale's longstanding plan to move
to New York finally became a reality, her parents said. While her
sister, Kim, had lived in New York City for nearly a decade, Kendra
did not move in with her or even unduly rely upon her. She had her
own plans and hopes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Through newspaper advertisements, her mother said, she found a
roommate _ the name, Lindsey, was all the family could remember on
Monday _ and the small walkup flat on East 23d Street. She
occasionally took trips home to Fredonia, but never thought of
moving back, her parents said.
</P>
<P>
   She eventually found a job as a receptionist at the Masterdisk
Corp., in midtown Manhattan, which has 15 employees and produces
master recordings of pop music. She was remembered by employees and
managers there on Monday as so likable that workers from other
companies in the building often stopped by her fifth floor desk in
the mornings to chat or say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a beautiful, beautiful girl,'' the building's security
guard, who asked to remain unnamed, said. He said Ms. Webdale
opened her office each morning and at lunchtime would come
downstairs to smoke a cigarette on the sidewalk. ``If I had a bad
day, or a problem with my wife and I didn't feel like talking, as
soon as I saw Kendra everything would be fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Levine, the company's president, issued a statement
calling Ms. Webdale ``an exemplary employee and individual,'' and
adding: ``What we will most of all remember is her bright smile and
sweet demeanor. We will forever miss her. It is a tremendous and
painful loss to all who knew her.''
</P>
<P>
   In off hours or on days off, Ms. Webdale loved to lounge on the
hills of Central Park, friends said. She also spent hours at the
New York Public Library researching ideas for a screenplay she
hoped to write, her friends and parents said. She had always been
trim and something of an athlete _ her father taught her to
waterski in Lake Erie when she was a teen-ager _ and she kept in
shape in New York, rising before dawn for a 5:30 daily run through
her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Enrico Cordero, who lives down the hall from Ms. Webdale,
recalled how they had met, just passing on the steps and greeting
one another with a smile and a hello, and how they later became
friends and confidants, sitting together often at the head of the
stairs to smoke cigarettes and talk. The ash tray they used was on
the landing there on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of television programs they liked, of new wave and
rock music, of dating problems and jobs. She was thinking of
changing jobs, but had apparently not confided this to anyone but
him, Cordero said. ``She loved hanging out,'' he said, remembering
making the rounds of East Village bars with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember one time I was kind of depressed and I wanted
to go out,'' Cordero said. ``She saw I was depressed and she came
out here, sat out here and we talked for an hour and a half. I can
honestly tell you she did not complain about anything once.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webdale and her sisters and mother all met in New York last
September and participated in the Run for the Cure, a Central Park
event to raise funds for breast cancer research. They gathered
again for Christmas in Fredonia, and it was their last time
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty, perky, gentle, kind, fun, mischievous,'' her
devastated mother said.
</P>
</TEXT>
