<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-EMISSIONS-COX     01-04 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-EMISSIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researchers release results of emissions study
 &HT;    (ATTN: FLORIDA EDITORS)
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ About 1.4 million Florida car and truck
owners shouldn't be required to test their vehicles' emissions,
according to the recommendations of an independent consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But those who must get their car or truck inspected should pay
more than double the current fee for each test, concludes a study
of Florida's emissions testing program by Sierra Research of
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the state legislature released Monday,
researchers recommended exempting cars less than four years old
from inspections. The exemption would affect about 220,000 cars in
Palm Beach County. The report also recommended switching the annual
tests to every other year, and changing to a newer, more powerful
method of detecting auto pollution. About 500,000 cars in the
county still would be tested.
</P>
<P>
   And it suggested increasing the fee from $10 to $22.50 per
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're suggesting changes that would focus the program on the
dirty vehicles without worrying too much about those vehicles you
know are running clean,'' said Richard Joy, the study's primary
author.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the latest voice among a growing number of critics
who want to alter or abolish the emissions testing program, which
cost motorists in six counties $48 million in 1998. But it is not
the outright denunciation that some suspected would be issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the (legislators) who demanded this report
were hoping it would say you don't need to do (tests) at all,''
said Randy Lewis, a spokesman for the companies that conduct the
emissions tests. ``It looks a lot different than what they
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that testing companies make a hefty profit from
a program that cannot demonstrate any substantial results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about air quality _ those companies could care less
about air quality,'' said state Rep. Jim Fuller, R-Jacksonville, an
outspoken critic of the program. ``This is about money, and how
much they can make from our state's car owners in a program that's
totally unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who chairs the House Transportation Committee, said he
plans to file a bill this year to abolish the testing program
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Emissions testing began in 1991 in an attempt to diminish air
pollution in auto-clogged regions of the state. The reasoning is
simple: Well-maintained cars spew out less pollution. The annual
tests, conducted in Palm Beach and five other counties, are
designed to weed out ``gross polluters,'' which are about 5 percent
of the vehicles on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 4.8 million cars were inspected, according to the
Florida Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The private companies that hold the lucrative emissions testing
contracts pumped hundreds of thousands of dollars into politicians'
coffers, and hired high-powered lobbyists, to ensure the survival
of the testing program, state records show.
</P>
<P>
   Through their political action committee, called AirPac,
emissions testing companies donated $274,300 to candidates and
political parties during the 1998 elections. That's almost double
the $144,250 AirPac gave during the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The group funneled $115,000 directly to the Republican Party of
Florida and $66,500 to the Democratic Party. The rest went to
various candidates in $500 donations, including Fuller and most of
the legislators on the House and Senate transportation and
environmental protection committees, which must pass any bills that
affect the testing program.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant's study, which cost $125,000, was commissioned by
the legislature last year after a Palm Beach Post investigation
found no evidence that tests have done anything to improve
Florida's air. Tougher regulation of car and truck manufacturers
has been the primary reason for cleaner air across the nation, the
Post found, not emissions tests.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant's recommendations included:
</P>
<P>
   Exempting vehicles less than four years old from the tests. The
state tested about 1.44 million cars that age in 1998; almost all
of them passed. ``Since they fail so rarely, it really doesn't make
sense to test them,'' Joy said.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting the test every other year instead of annually.
Researchers found that such a change would only slightly increase
the amount of air pollution, and would be extremely popular with
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing a more powerful emissions test that would do a
better job of detecting pollution. The new type of test would rev
the car's engine to simulate driving up a hill, while the current
test examines the engine while it is idling.
</P>
<P>
   Those recommendations are similar to changes that will
automatically go into effect if the legislature fails to act on the
testing issue when the current contracts expire this April.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one crucial difference: Current law caps the fee at
$10, while the report recommends increasing it to $22.50.
</P>
<P>
   Testing companies argue they cannot be profitable without a fee
hike, because the changes would reduce the number of cars being
tested by 65 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just cannot support the program without raising the
fees,'' said Curt Kiser, a former Republican state senator who is
now a lobbyist for Envirotest Technologies, which tests cars in
Palm Beach and Miami-Dade counties.
</P>
<P>
   Testing opponents argue that a fee hike is not necessary,
because testing companies already make a tremendous profit.
</P>
<P>
   Trebor Banstetter writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
