</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORK-SOLUTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK SPLIT, NEW OFFERING FOR INTERNET REGISTRAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Network Solutions Inc., which has a temporary
monopoly on the distribution of Internet addresses, announced plans
Monday for both a stock split and a secondary offering of 4.58
million shares. The moves will reduce its parent company's holdings
below 50 percent and give Network Solutions greater flexibility to
make acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification is key since it is expected that Network
Solutions will this year lose its exclusive government contract for
registering the popular Internet addresses that end in .com, .net
and .org. That lucrative monopoly accounts for nearly all the
company's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The stock split announced Monday, to take effect at the close of
business on Feb. 26, will increase the number of shares outstanding
from approximately 16.4 million to 32.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed secondary offering would reduce the ownership of
the parent company, the Science Applications International Corp.,
to 45 percent from the 72 percent it owns now. Analysts said the
new offering, combined with the increased shares, would enable the
company to diversify beyond the domain name registration business.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Preissler, an analyst at Paine Webber in New York, said the
moves would ``further help the company become a little more
independent and choose its own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the stock at some point becomes poolable,
which would enable Network Solutions to make acquisitions without a
heavy accounting charge.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions shares rose $24.125 Monday to close at $155.
</P>
<P>
   Preissler said he did not anticipate a substantial drop in
Network Solution's stock price as a result of the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that this is a company that has consistently
exceeded expectations by quite a bit,'' he said. ``As long as they
continue to deliver the profits they have in the past, I am less
concerned about valuation than I might be on something that has no
profit anytime in the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions has enjoyed phenomenal growth as the exclusive
global registrar for the basic Internet addresses known as domain
names, registering some three million such addresses at $70 each.
Its income for the first nine months of 1998 grew threefold, to
$7.5 million, or 45 cents a share, compared with $2.5 million, or
20 cents a share, for the first nine months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Christmas, the company's stock prices tripled,
jumping to an all-time high of $172.25 after announcing several key
alliances with the Netscape Communications Corp. and Yahoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
