<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAPED-CALLS-SPI &LR;      01-04 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAPED-CALLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT, MEDIA TAKE SIDES IN CONGRESSIONAL TAPE FLAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What started out as a spat between Reps. Jim
McDermott and John Boehner over an illegally taped phone call has
turned into a broad legal battle pitting the newspaper industry
against the Justice Department, with each side claiming the case
has enormous implications.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post Co., The New York Times Co. and several
other media outlets and organizations say they will enter the fray
on McDermott's side. They say the First Amendment to the
Constitution protects the Seattle Democrat's right to leak to
newspapers an illegal recording of a telephone call among a group
of Republican leaders, including Boehner, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott has declined to say whether he provided the tape to
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are exceedingly important because a ruling that
held the First Amendment didn't protect disclosure could greatly
curtail news reports about issues that are very important to the
public,'' said Theodore Boutrous Jr., a lawyer representing the
Post and the Times, as well Dow Jones &AMP; Co. Inc., the A.H. Belo
Corp. and the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press. ``Many
of the most important news stories in our history have come in
cases where the source may have obtained information in a manner
that is subsequently challenged in court.''
</P>
<P>
   But siding with Boehner, the Justice Department argues that
another important principle is at stake: the privacy of cellular
telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of legal protection, cellular telephone
communications are highly vulnerable to surreptitious electronic
surveillance,'' the Justice Department argued in a brief filed last
week with the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
``The large and rapidly growing percentage of the nation's
telephone traffic carried by cellular networks would be exposed to
unauthorized interception, disclosure, and other uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The entry of the Justice Department and the news media comes as
Boehner is attempting to persuade a panel of appellate judges to
reinstate his lawsuit against McDermott, which was dismissed in
July by U.S. District Judge Thomas Hogan. The judge ruled that the
Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986, which restricts the
taping of cell phone conversations, violates the First Amendment
when it is applied to the disclosure of illegally intercepted
telephone conversations by someone who did not participate in the
interception.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from an incident in December 1996, when Boehner,
sitting in the parking lot of a Florida waffle house, used his
wife's cellular telephone to participate in a conversation among
Republican leaders, including Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation, in which the Republicans were discussing how
to handle ethics charges against Gingrich, was intercepted on a
police scanner by John and Alice Martin, a Florida couple active in
Democratic politics. The couple _ who later pleaded guilty and paid
a fine _ illegally recorded the conversation and delivered the tape
to McDermott, then the ranking Democrat on the House ethics
committee investigating Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, the contents of the tape recording were
published by The New York Times, the Atlanta Journal/Constitution,
and the capital newspaper, Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department launched an investigation, but to date
has taken no action against McDermott. Boehner dipped into his
campaign treasury to sue McDermott, and it is that suit that was
dismissed last summer and is now under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district court ... concluded, contrary to explicit Supreme
Court precedent and to basic common sense, that the First Amendment
gives a blanket immunity to all who encounter stolen, confidential
information to disseminate it across the world,'' Boehner's lawyers
argued in their brief last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman McDermott, quite simply, can not hide behind the
First Amendment to avoid being held responsible for his knowing and
deliberate criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the Boehner vs. McDermott case are now comparing
it to the 1971 Pentagon Papers case, New York Times Co. vs. United
States, in which the Supreme Court refused to bar The New York
Times from publishing a top-secret history of U.S. involvement in
Indochina that had been provided to the Times by antiwar activist
Daniel Ellsberg. Ellsberg had stolen the material from the
Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner argues that in the Pentagon Papers case, the court
merely refused to restrain newspapers from publishing the
documents, but did not rule out later punishing the papers for
doing so. (The government attempted to prosecute Ellsberg, but the
case was thrown out because evidence against him had been illegally
obtained.)
</P>
<P>
   But the news media, which will file its brief on McDermott's
behalf next month, argues that the Pentagon Papers is a similar
case showing the potential importance of allowing newspapers to
publish illegally obtained information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
