<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT HAD LONG HISTORY OF MENTAL ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: With NY-SUBWAY-VICTIM, NY-SUBWAY-KILLING) 
(rl) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He graduated from the prestigious Bronx High School
of Science. His roommates described him as gentle and not prone to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also a loner, spending his time walking by himself or
sequestered in his rented room listening to music. And for the
better part of a decade, officials said, Andrew Goldstein, 29, the
man accused of pushing a young woman in front of an oncoming train
on Sunday night, bounced back and forth among city and state mental
hospitals, private hospitals, halfway houses and outpatient
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein often told his roommates that the pills he took each
day were for a memory problem. When he was arrested on Sunday, he
told detectives that he was paranoid. After he was arraigned on a
second-degree murder charge yesterday, his lawyer, Kevin Canfield,
said ``he has a history of schizophrenia.''
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in December 1997 on a misdemeanor assault charge
for injuring a woman in a Barnes and Noble bookstore in Queens, and
was placed in a city psychiatric ward for two weeks. But his
roommates and law enforcement officials said they had no other
indication that he might turn to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt someone would hurt him before he would go out and hurt
somebody,'' said one of Goldstein's roommates, John Olson, 20.
``I'd never think that this guy could do something like this. He
was a pussycat.''
</P>
<P>
   While there were many signs that he was troubled, officials said
there were apparently no grounds to place him in an institution.
Under state law, people must be judged both mentally ill and a
danger to themselves or others to justify an involuntary
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Until he was arrested on Sunday night and accused of killing
Kendra Webdale, 32, by pushing her in front of a subway train at
the 23d Street and Broadway station, Goldstein lived in a rented
room in a basement apartment in Howard Beach, Queens. Roommates
said he spent his time taking solitary walks, listening to Pink
Floyd songs, watching television and sometimes just sitting and
staring into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed very lonely,'' said Mario Ocampo, 20, whose mother
rented Goldstein the room. ``He was always alone. He was always
asking me to come down to watch TV or asking if he could come up
here to watch TV. Once I caught him in his room just staring at his
legs. And the cleaning lady saw him staring dead-on at the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   He once showed great promise. In 1987, Goldstein graduated from
the Bronx High School of Science, the elite public high school,
school officials said. But two years later he was committed to a
state mental institution. Most recently, law enforcement officials
said, Goldstein was an outpatient at the Bleuler Psychotherapy
Center on Queens Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest in a long string of facilities to try to
treat his mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Goldstein was committed to the Creedmoor Psychiatric
Center, a state-run center in Queens. He was in and out of
Creedmoor three times until he was finally discharged in August
1993.
</P>
<P>
   After he left Creedmoor, he spent more than a year in the Leben
Home for Adults, a 361-facility in Elmhurst, Queens, that provides
room and board for mentally ill adults. At the time, he received
treatment at the New York Psychotherapy and Counseling Center. Then
came his treatment at Bleuler. Officials there did not return calls
seeking comment about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's only prior contact with the law, police officials
said, came on Dec. 14, 1997, when he was arrested at a Barnes and
Noble bookstore in Forest Hills, Queens. A law enforcement official
said Goldstein had been harassed by several youths in the store
and, as he rushed toward the door while trying to leave, knocked a
woman into a bookcase, injuring her eye and face.
</P>
<P>
   The record of that case was sealed, the official said, because
the woman did not want to proceed with the case. But the police
brought Goldstein to Elmhurst Hospital Center for evaluation, and
he was kept for two weeks, said a hospital official.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, law enforcement officials said, he went to Bellevue
Hospital for treatment. In August he went to Hillside Hospital in
Glen Oaks, Queens, to ask for help. He was evaluated and given a
prescription for 10 days worth of medication, said Carol Hauptman,
a hospital spokeswoman. But when hospital officials called him back
to see if he was taking his medicine, she said, they found he had
given them the wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Goldstein was arraigned on second-degree murder
charges in Manhattan Criminal Court. An assistant District
Attorney, William Greenbaum, said: ``He admits pushing her onto the
track. The evidence is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's court-appointed lawyer, Kevin Canfield, requested
that his client be placed on a suicide watch. The judge ordered
Goldstein to undergo a psychiatric evaluation. He is scheduled to
appear in court again on Feb. 2. ``He's very disturbed, I can say
that,'' Canfield said. ``He has a history of schizophrenia.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who was dressed in green chinos and a black jacket,
seemed unsteady on his feet. Short, clean-shaven and slightly
pudgy, with dark curly hair, he stared ahead and blinked repeatedly
as prosecutors read the murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives and prosecutors were trying Monday to retrace
Goldstein's steps on the day of the murder. Detective Lt. John
Shields said Goldstein came into Manhattan at around 10 in the
morning, ate fast food, wandered the streets and listened to CDs at
the free listening stations in a Virgin Megastore.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 p.m., Shields said, Goldstein walked up to Ms.
Webdale on the south end of the northbound platform of the N and R
station at 23d Street and Broadway. ``He just spoke to her
briefly,'' he said. ``He asked her the time. And shortly thereafter
he pushed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Three cars of an oncoming train ran over Ms. Webdale before the
train stopped, the police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2149EST &QL; 
