<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON &LR;      01-04 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Big Macworld Opens Its Gates in S.F.  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista and Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Macintosh revival rolls into town this morning, and there's
plenty for the faithful to whoop about. For now.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 68,000 Macophiles are expected to stream into the
Moscone Center at this year's Macworld Expo to trade Mac tips, kick
the tires on new products and revel in Apple Computer's remarkable
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company is set to show off new top-of-the-line
Power Mac G3 desktop machines based on the iMac's curvy,
translucent design, along with a new operating system for corporate
users of high-end computer servers and workstations, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The personal computer pioneer is back in the black after two
years of knee-buckling losses; interim Apple CEO Steve Jobs is
expected to announce a fifth-straight profitable quarter in a
keynote speech today; a flabby, unwieldy product line has been
whipped into shape; sales of the iMac are shooting off the charts;
powerful new Macs are on the horizon; and Apple's market share has
climbed to about 5 percent, according to ZD Market Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there were questions about Apple's survival the last few
years, the issues now seem to revolve around innovation, new
products and excitement,'' said Macworld Expo show director Rob
Scheschareg. ``We expect a big walk-up crowd because of interest in
the iMac.''
</P>
<P>
   With Moscone Center as the temporary epicenter of the Mac
universe, city transportation officials anticipate a traffic crush
and advise the use of public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hype and hoopla surrounding the weeklong computer
show, though, long-term concerns about Apple linger.
</P>
<P>
   Apple must overcome a historic problem _ inspiring software
companies to write programs for the Mac _ if it is to complete its
self-proclaimed five-step rehabilitation, industry observers said.
It's a chicken-and-egg conundrum: Having more applications spurs
Mac sales, but software-makers are reluctant to invest in writing
new programs until sales increase.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing with Wall Street analysts in October, Apple CFO
Fred Anderson outlined a ``hierarchy of survival'' based on Abraham
Maslow's ranking of societal needs. He said the PC-maker has
accomplished the first two steps and is working on stages three
through five of that comeback plan: (1) survival, (2)
stability/profitability, (3) setting a product strategy, (4)
regaining application support for Apple platforms and (5) driving
growth.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said there are no signs of an immediate return to
Apple's glory days, when software developers made cutting-edge
products for the Macintosh platform before Windows. The cold
reality is it's still a Windows world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if Apple has any realistic shot at getting its
old leading-edge position back. I think it's too late for that,''
said Jeff Tarter, publisher of Soft-letter in Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were hard-pressed to think of any new Mac-only programs
besides those made for graphic artists and publishers, who have
remained Apple's most loyal customers. Most consumer and business
Mac programs are also available for Windows, although the reverse
is not always true.
</P>
<P>
   Even longtime stalwart Mac developers like Adobe Systems and
Macromedia have shifted more of their resources to writing software
for the lucrative PC market.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Macromedia, which made its mark as a Mac
developer, said PC sales now account for 57 percent of its
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The story is in the numbers. Despite the iMac's sales, there are
37.2 million Windows-based computers in U.S. households and only
about 5 million Macs, according to Media Metrix, a New York company
that is considered the A.C. Nielsen Co. of home computer usage.
</P>
<P>
   And while Mac sales were basically flat for three years, the
number of home PCs grew by 50 percent during the same time , said
Bruce Ryon, general manager of Media Metrix technology division.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no incentive for any developer to try Mac first,''
said Ryon, who once worked for Apple's consumer division as a
business development manager.
</P>
<P>
   Popular desktop games, for example, used to be released in Mac
versions first before Windows. But now, many games are developed
for Windows only because the smaller Mac market doesn't yield
enough sales, Ryon said. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Analysts said Apple's best chance for growth is in the
consumer market, and the company has made important strides by
successfully marketing the iMac as a quick and easy way to connect
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, that sales strategy may not boost Macintosh software
sales because consumers don't see the iMac as a device to play
games or run programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the focus of this machine is to download
Web pages rather than running software off a disk,'' Tarter said.
</P>
<P>
   According to numbers released last month by PC Data Inc., a
Reston, Va., market researcher, the iMac accounted for 8.2 percent
of retail and mail-order computer sales in November, making it the
top-selling model. Some analysts expect the company to report sales
as high as 535,000 units in the quarter ended December 25.
</P>
<P>
   But iMac shipments have not translated into more Macintosh
software development, said Chris Shipley, editor of Demo Letter, an
industry newsletter in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't seen any startup software-makers target the Mac
market for the past year, Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheschareg said the expo has the same number of exhibitors
(450) and projected attendance (68,000) as a year ago. He noted,
however, the addition of gaming and consumer areas, technical
conferences and first-time vendors such as Real Networks and VR
Toolbox.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry observers expect the iMac to spur development and
sales of new peripheral devices _ including technology based on
Universal Serial Bus, which makes it easier to plug in joysticks or
digital cameras, and ultra-fast FireWire connections.
</P>
<P>
   Apple, which is in a self-imposed quiet period before it
announces its fiscal first-quarter results on January 13, declined
to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
