<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-AMERICA-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE MAY LINK TO CBS NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS News will announce a deal with America Online Inc. later
this week to become the exclusive broadcast news provider for the
online service, executives involved in the agreement said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal lacks only some final details, the executives said.
When completed, it will mean that CBS will replace ABC News as the
provider of news in text, video and audio on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   For CBS, the move to American Online has the potential to
jump-start what has been a lackluster presence on the Web. By wide
consensus, CBS News has lagged far behind the other news networks
in terms of what it has offered to users of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For America Online, a deal is likely to mean a more favorable
financial arrangement than the service had with ABC, one executive
said.
</P>
<P>
   The exact terms of the deal were not available Monday, but one
executive involved in the negotiations said that it would be along
the lines of ``promotion for promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was reported in the Hollywood Reporter on Monday.
Executives from CBS, America Online and ABC, declined to comment on
the record. An America Online spokeswoman, Wendy Goldberg, labeled
it ``a rumor, and we don't comment on rumors.'' Gil Schwartz, the
chief spokesman for CBS, said, ``We don't have anything to
announce.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Bergmann, a spokeswoman for the ABC News online
service, said, ``It's our standing policy not to comment on
contractual arrangements.'' The America Online contract is known to
be near an end.
</P>
<P>
   An executive involved in the CBS deal said it would include
America Online's affiliated services, AOL.com and Compuserve. That
will give CBS access to America Online's 15 million subscribers, by
far the biggest number on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet services of the other network news organizations
have been far ahead of CBS. CNN's Web site and MSNBC.com, which NBC
operates with Microsoft Corp., are among the most heavily
trafficked sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, CBS had been in talks with CNN about a merger of
news-gathering resources. That arrangement might have required CBS
to pay for access to CNN's news material. The CBS chairman, Mel
Karmazin, said in December that he was looking instead for a way to
generate revenue from CBS' news product.
</P>
<P>
   CBS does have a promotion-for-pay arrangement with the online
services that use its Sportsline and Market Watch products. And CBS
had already established a relationship with America Online last
fall in a promotion campaign for its new fall prime-time
entertainment lineup. That promotion was regarded as highly
successful by CBS executives.
</P>
<P>
   An executive involved in the America Online-CBS negotiations
said that American Online was also concerned with competitive
Internet moves being made by Walt Disney Co., the parent of ABC,
which recently started an Internet portal, the Go Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
