<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEBTS-SFCHRON &LR;      01-04 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Debtors Faced With House of Cards  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Home equity lenders these days are advertising tantalizing offers
for startlingly high levels of credit _ offers likely to be
particularly enticing to people suffering from a post-holiday
financial hangover.
</P>
<P>
   Some solicitations offer hundreds of thousands of dollars. Some
tout loan amounts higher than the value of the properties securing
them. And some direct mailers catch the attention of those in debt
with faux checks made out in their names.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of marketing the loans to pay for home improvements _
their traditional purpose, and one that is likely to generate a
good return _ the mail, TV and radio solicitations encourage people
to take a dream vacation, buy a new car or consolidate credit card
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are biting at the offers, but consumer advocates
warn of dire consequences in the event of job loss or other
financial misfortune. Unlike credit cards, home equity loans are
secured by the borrower's property, which could be lost in a
default.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so problematic to put your house on the line for
anything as insubstantial as credit card debt,'' said Linda Sherry
of Consumer Action in San Francisco. ``Most of the things you paid
for probably aren't even around anymore, and you're putting your
home on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of people who took out a home equity loan in
1997 identified debt consolidation as the main reason, up markedly
from 36 percent the prior year. Home improvement was a distant
second (23 percent in the 1997 survey) followed by education and
automobile purchases, according to the Consumer Bankers
Association's latest poll.
</P>
<P>
   Although delinquency rates on home equity loans remain low
(between 1 and 2 percent), that could change in a recession, said
Monica Steinisch of the Consumer Credit Counseling Service of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest danger lies in ``high loan-to-value'' (LTV) loans
worth 125 percent or even 150 percent of a home's value. In a
default, borrowers could lose not only their homes, but additional
assets as well.
</P>
<P>
   High LTV loans are based on the estimated earning potential of
the borrower, not just the value of his or her home, said Sung Won
Sohn, chief economist with Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``nobody knows what's going to happen two years down the
road _ you could be out of work,'' Steinisch said.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional second mortgages tend to be capped at 80 percent of
the homeowner's equity in a house. So someone with a $350,000 house
who has a $250,000 first mortgage and $100,000 of equity could
receive an $80,000 home equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   A high LTV mortgage, on the other hand, could be valued at up to
$187,000 _ 100 percent of the homeowner's equity ($100,000) plus 25
percent of the appraised value of the house ($87,500), said Earl
Lui, senior attorney with Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Big-name financial institutions generally don't offer the risky,
high LTV loans. And the companies that do promote them only award
them to the best credit risks, Sherry said. ``It's a
bait-and-switch to get people into a new loan,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lui said the popularity of home equity loans is just one more
manifestation of Americans' love affair with credit. ``This is part
of a growing phenomenon in our society where people are living
beyond their means and taking on more debt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their risks, home equity loans aren't always a bad
thing, even when used for things other than home improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Average interest rates currently are running between 8 and 9
percent, half the level of some credit cards. (High LTV rates run a
bit higher.) And interest payments on home equity loans are
generally tax-deductible, just like the interest on primary
mortgages. So borrowers may be able to save a good deal by
consolidating credit card debts into a home loan.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many people can't resist the temptation to start
using plastic after transferring their debt to a home equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   That's why debt counselors advise people with a lot of credit
card debt to avoid home loans. Instead, they suggest reducing
interest payments by regularly transferring balances to new cards
with low introductory rates and paying off as much of the balance
as possible each month.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is discouraged by lenders, of course, who make
money from high balances. Both credit card companies and home
equity lenders have reduced their required minimum monthly payments
to discourage customers from paying off their loans, Sohn said.
</P>
<P>
   The current deluge of home equity loan offers is no accident.
Lenders are pushing such loans aggressively these days because they
have been burned by credit cardholder bankruptcies in recent years.
With home equity loans, that credit is secured by physical assets.
</P>
<P>
   Also, banks have plenty of room for additional home loans in
their portfolios because many were paid off during the rash of
mortgage refinancings this decade, said Fritz Elmendorf of the
Consumer Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   A number of resources are available for debt holders who are
considering a home equity loan.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Credit Counseling Services, which has offices around
the Bay Area, offers worksheets and other resources on its Web site
to help people deal with all types of debt or other financial
problems. The nonprofit group also offers counseling over the
telephone or in person for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   People who have decided to take out a home loan must decide
whether they want a standard loan or a line of credit. Standard
loans must be taken out in a lump sum and repaid in monthly
installments, just like primary mortgages. Interest rates, which
are generally fixed, are now about 8.9 percent, according to Bank
Rate Monitor's daily survey.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of credit, which are becoming more popular, can be drawn
upon at the borrower's discretion, just like a checking account.
Interest is paid only on the outstanding balance. Lines of credit
generally have a floating interest rate, now about 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As with any kind of financing, shop around for the best deal on
a home equity loan. Don't just accept the first offer you receive,
even if the phony $50,000 check with your name on it makes your
mouth water. (The check is just a marketing gimmick _ you still
have to apply for the loan, and it's not guaranteed you'll get it.)
Borrowers should read the fine print and tally up startup fees and
annual fees when deciding which loan to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Ads and solicitations by lenders are required to identify their
regulator, usually the California Department of Corporations or the
California Department of Real Estate. Consumers can check out
potential lenders with those two agencies.
</P>
<P>
   You also can check the following resources for help:
</P>
<P>
   _Bank Rate Monitor,  &LR; www.bankrate.com  &LR; (loan rates and other
information).
</P>
<P>
   _Consumer Bankers Association,  &LR; www.cbanet.org  &LR; (loan rates and
other information).
</P>
<P>
   _Cardweb Inc.,  &LR; cardtrak.com  &LR; (credit card rates and fees).
</P>
<P>
   _Consumer Credit Counseling Service,  &LR; www.cccsmoneymatters.org
 &LR; or (800) 777-7526 (financial planning advice and worksheets).
</P>
<P>
   _California Department of Corporations,  &LR; www.corp.ca.gov  &LR; or
(213) 736-2751 (licensing and disciplinary histories of mortgage
bankers).
</P>
<P>
   _California Department of Real Estate,  &LR; www.dre.cahwnet.gov &LR;  or
(510) 622-2552 (licensing and disciplinary histories of mortgage
brokers).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
