<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BankAmerica Says 80% of Old BofA Execs to Stay  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The new BankAmerica said yesterday a large majority of managers
from the old BofA have decided to stay put, a development analysts
said is surprising given the upheaval since North Carolina's
NationsBank took control three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 percent of the old BofA's 1,134 executives and managers
are remaining, while the rest are taking advantage of severance
packages triggered when NationsBank bought San Francisco's BofA and
took its name, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank insisted that it's keeping almost all the people it
wants. The bank offered jobs to 918 of the BofA executives and
managers, and 98 percent signed agreements to stay, spokeswoman
Melba Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the numbers are right, it's encouraging,'' said Joseph
Morford, an analyst at Van Kasper &AMP; Co. ``It could be the first
step in putting some of these social issues to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Current and former BofA employees say many managers found
NationsBank job offers irresistible because they still would let
the employees collect golden parachutes down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Practically all of the managers who agreed to stay signed
agreements that provide them their entire severance benefit plus a
10 percent premium in two years if they aren't happy at the new
bank. The payouts would be made in stock, with minimum sums
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They provided a very lucrative package,'' said a former BofA
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some bank watchers suggested that NationsBank was
hiding defections at top executive levels by releasing statistics
that included hundreds of middle managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at key positions, key roles, it's much
different,'' said Tony Price, an executive recruiter with Russell
Reynolds Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The bank declined to release separate data on the 45 top
executives who composed the old BofA's Senior Management Council,
arguing that the information could be misinterpreted. At least 15
of that group, including seven of 10 women, have resigned or been
forced out, said current and former bank employees.
</P>
<P>
   Since The Chronicle reported the departures of six senior female
executives last month, Executive Vice President Mary Wikstrom quit,
the bank confirmed. Wikstrom ran the old BofA's telephone banking
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those 45 people had the most lucrative contracts, and money
may have been a factor,'' NationsBank's Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of managers from the old BofA who leave is an
extremely sensitive issue, given the turmoil that's rocked the bank
since NationsBank snared BofA.
</P>
<P>
   After NationsBank chief executive Hugh McColl ousted David
Coulter, his counterpart at the old BofA, analysts warned that the
bank could be vulnerable to an exodus of senior staff members as
NationsBank consolidated control.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and managers of the old BofA were covered by
so-called change-of-control agreements, contracts awarding them big
payouts if the bank were sold.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on their rank, they were eligible to collect benefits
that ranged from less than a year's to three year's worth of salary
and bonuses. The deadline for exercising the golden parachutes
passed late last month.
</P>
<P>
   Women represented 27 percent of those covered by golden
parachute agreements, and they constituted the same percentage of
those who opted to stay, the bank said. ``There's no gain nor loss
for women,'' Spencer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
