<SLUG> BC-AIRTOUCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AirTouch Merger Hopes Kept Alive  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bell Atlantic Corp. and AirTouch Communications are in closed-door
meetings trying to resolve thorny issues surrounding their possible
merger, sources close to the negotiations said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which is rumored to be offering about $45 billion
for San Francisco's AirTouch, is trying to avoid being socked with
a bill for ``goodwill'' _ the value of a company's reputation and
its customer and business relationships _ that could dilute the
phone company's earnings for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are also reportedly hammering out what assets will
be divested if a merger goes through. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is in the process of acquiring GTE Corp., which
operates wireless service in some of the same cities as AirTouch,
including San Francisco and San Diego. Federal rules prohibit
companies from owning two major cellular licenses in a single
market, so a deal with AirTouch would force Bell Atlantic to dump
some of either GTE's or AirTouch's cellular licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and AirTouch have confirmed they are in
negotiations but have not given details of any deal. In a prepared
statement, AirTouch said ``significant issues still remain'' and
``there can be no assurance that any transaction will result from
these discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is courting AirTouch to help it get a ``national
footprint,'' which would give it access to more customers and the
opportunity to offer a single rate for service across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Customers have become extremely picky when it comes to wireless
service and now favor providers that can offer national service for
a low price.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, which has 5.7 million cellular customers on the
East Coast, has been losing customers to companies like AT&AMP;T,
Sprint PCS and Nextel, which offer nationwide wireless service.
</P>
<P>
   That's because carriers that don't have a national network must
sign expensive roaming agreements with providers where they don't
have a presence. They pass along costly ``roaming fees'' that can
amount to 60 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   As wireless prices drop, analysts said, the only choice for
carriers that want to survive is to build a national network and
drop the roaming charges. The latest industry statistics predict
costs for wireless service will fall to 3 cents per minute over the
next two years. Companies with roaming charges will find it hard to
compete in a market with such low rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roaming (charges) will rapidly be going away,'' said Kevin
Roe, an analyst with ABN AMRO in New York. ``It's arcane. There's
no reason why you should be paying more if you leave the home
network. They don't have it in Europe and it only existed here
because we didn't have competition in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining with AirTouch would give Bell Atlantic customers in
almost every state and catapult the company to the No. 1 wireless
carrier in the world with more than 14 million wireless customers
in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch has 7.6 million U.S. customers, Bell Atlantic has 5.7
million and GTE Wireless has about 5 million. However, some of
those customers could be lost to divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets Bell Atlantic closer to being a nationwide
provider,'' said Jane Zweig, an analyst with Shosteck Associates in
Wheaton, Md. ``Bell Atlantic has a very strong presence on the East
Coast, GTE has the Southern states and AirTouch gives them the
West.''
</P>
<P>
   While a merger would mean one fewer competitor, industry
watchers said the deal would be good for consumers because it would
enable Bell Atlantic to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be very good for customers who will be able to buy a
phone and use it nationally and internationally,'' said Cole of
Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 percent of Americans subscribe to a cellular service,
and that number is expected to hit 30 percent by the end of 1999,
according to the Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect the deal to go through, although some think
Bell Atlantic will wind up paying much more for AirTouch than the
rumored price, which is a 10 to 15 percent premium over AirTouch's
stock value.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance it will be higher than $45 billion,''
said Andrew Cole, senior manager at Renaissance Worldwide, a
telecommunications research firm in Boston. ``I can't imagine
(AirTouch chief executive) Sam Ginn is going to sit back and take
10 to 15 percent. It's an extremely strong possibility that there
will be other suitors for AirTouch, and Bell Atlantic needs
AirTouch to have a national footprint.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the prolonged negotiations took its toll on both
AirTouch and Bell Atlantic stock yesterday. AirTouch, which soared
after the rumors first surfaced on New Year's Eve, fell $4.19 to
$68.25. Bell Atlantic dropped $2.06 to $51.94.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
