<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SangStat Gets OK on Drug to Stop Rejection  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A Menlo Park biotech firm said yesterday it has received Food and
Drug Administration approval for a new drug to prevent kidney
transplant rejection.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat Medical Corp. said the FDA had OKd its petition to
begin U.S. sales of Thymoglobulin. The remedy, which was developed
in Europe, is already being prescribed in 51 other countries to
help reverse acute organ rejection, a condition that occurs when a
recipient's immune system fights a kidney transplant as if it were
an invading disease.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analyst David Buck with Sands Brothers in New York
said Thymoglobulin will compete with an existing drug called Atgam
that costs $8,500 for the post-surgery treatment. Based on his
assumption that SangStat will price Thymoglobulin at $6,000 to gain
a price advantage, Buck estimated that the new drug will earn $10
million for the company this year _ and make the startup profitable
in 2000. SangStat, which went public in 1993, lost $21 million in
1997 on sales of $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's FDA approval of Thymoglobulin was SangStat's second
recent coup. In November, the company received the green light to
start selling SangCya, a drug that kidney, heart and liver
transplant patients must take daily for the rest of their lives to
prevent organ rejection.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat has allied itself with European biotech firms, notably
Rhone Poulenc Rorer Inc., to cooperate in developing, testing and
selling transplant drugs.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat coupled yesterday's Thymoglobulin news with an
announcement that former Rhone Poulenc executive Jean-Jacques
Bienaime would become its new chief executive officer. Bienaime,
who joined SangStat in June as president, will replace Philippe
Pouletty, who will remain as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Buck said the management change was expected, as Pouletty had
earlier signaled that he was grooming Bienaime for the CEO spot.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat shares gained $1.50 yesterday to close at $22.75 before
the drug approval and management change were announced. The company
hit a recent high of $40.63 in December 1997 but sank as low as
$15.13 in the fall stock slump that affected many small biotech
firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
