<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Qualifying For the Roth IRAs  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  We are a retired couple with a combined adjusted gross
income of slightly more than $100,000. We are interested in opening
Roth Individual Retirement Accounts. At first we heard that you can
qualify for a Roth if you have income of less than $160,000. But
then someone told us that our income would have to be less than
$100,000. Which is correct?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Actually, both.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to roll funds over to a Roth IRA from a traditional
IRA, a 401(k) or other retirement plan, you and your wife must have
a combined income no greater than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to start a new Roth, you can do it if your
income does not exceed $160,000. For single individuals, the limit
is $110,000.
</P>
<P>
   So you and your wife won't be able to do a rollover, but you can
start new Roths, with maximum contributions of $2,000 each per
year.
</P>
<P>
   You really should. I can't emphasize strongly enough what a
great deal Roth IRAs are.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional IRAs, your investment gains are taxed as
ordinary income when you withdraw your money. With a Roth, all your
investment gains accumulate tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional IRAs, you are forced to withdraw funds after
you reach age 701/2. With a Roth, there is no requirement to remove
your funds, regardless of your age. In fact, you can go on
contributing to a Roth after age 701/2.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Performance
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been working at my current company for a couple of years
and have been contributing to the 401(k) plan all this time.
Believe it or not, I have yet to see a statement of my balance. I
know how much I have deposited, but I just don't know how my money
is performing. I'm beginning to wonder whether my money is even
making it into the 401(k) account. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Most 401(k) providers send their participants a report
every quarter detailing the plan's investment performance. But no
provider is legally required to send any statements unless the
participant asks. Your provider's behavior is dubious from a
customer-relations standpoint, but it's legal.
</P>
<P>
   The law does require the provider to send a statement once a
year if you ask for it. If the provider wants to play hardball, you
will have to keep asking every year. But perhaps you can get them
to put you on a regular mailing list _ and if you plead enough you
might even get quarterly reports. Give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Giltenan, a spokesman for T. Rowe Price, one of the leading
401(k) providers, says there is legislation before Congress that
would require providers to send out more than one statement per
year if a participant desires. T. Rowe Price itself sends
statements out quarterly without being asked. ``Any provider worth
its salt does that,'' Giltenan contends.
</P>
<P>
   Paying for College
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to take money from my Individual Retirement
Account to pay my son's college expenses. I am less than 591/2
years old. What is the maximum annual amount I can withdraw without
paying the 10 percent penalty tax? Also, can I use IRA money to pay
for college expenses incurred before 1998?
</P>
<P>
   A: Let's take the last question first.
</P>
<P>
   Congress liberalized the rules for education-related IRA
withdrawals, effective Jan. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If you take money out of your IRA to pay college expenses
incurred before that date, you will get hit with the 10 percent
penalty because you are less than 591/2 years old. In addition, you
will have to pay regular income taxes on your withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   If you withdraw money to pay expenses incurred on Jan. 1, 1998,
and later, again you must pay regular income taxes. But there will
be no penalty no matter what your age. And you can withdraw as much
money as you need to meet legitimate educational expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The money you withdraw must be used only for certain narrowly
defined purposes such as tuition, fees, books, supplies and
equipment necessary to get your son through his course of study.
But you can't use it for room and board, travel expenses and other
so-called incidentals.
</P>
<P>
   In figuring how much you can withdraw penalty-free, you must
take into account any tax-free scholarships, grants or other
education-related payments your son may have received. Included in
that total would be any withdrawals from an Education IRA, if you
have one.
</P>
<P>
   If your son's education expenses amount to $20,000, say, and he
got $5,000 in nontaxable reimbursements, you can withdraw no more
than $15,000 from your IRA if you want to avoid the 10 percent
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
