<SLUG> BC-FBC-UTEXAS-RECRUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas hauls in big ones
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas football team continued to put
together what likely will be one of the country's top recruiting
classes, by picking up commitments from the top offensive lineman
in the state and one of the best defensive ends in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   UT picked up pledges from Houston Yates offensive lineman Alfio
Randall and Cole Pittman, a defensive end from Shreveport, La. The
two commitments give UT 26, although two, including Pittman, will
enroll in school this month and their scholarships will count
toward last year's class.
</P>
<P>
   Randall is ranked No. 4 on the Austin American-Statesman's
Fabulous 55, a list of the state's top recruits. He is the 15th UT
commitment from the list. Texas A&AMP;M has the second highest number
of commitments with four, with Tennessee in third with three.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman is the best defensive player in Louisiana and before the
season was ranked as the top rush end in the country by SuperPrep
and Blue Chip Illustrated. The National Recruiting Advisor ranks
Pittman as the 89th best player in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman brought Texas Coach Mack Brown, recruiting coordinator
Hardee McCrary and wide receiver coach Darryl Drake to Sunday
morning church services, where he announced his commitment to the
congregation. He already has graduated from Evangel High School,
will enroll at Texas this month and go through spring drills in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman also took official visits to Nebraska, Florida and LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Texas was the best place for me,'' said Pittman, who
registered 125 tackles and 21 sacks this fall. ``I'm glad I found
the college that I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall, who also considered Georgia, Michigan, Tennessee and
Nebraska, is UT's fifth commitment from the Fab 55's top 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns also have commitments from No. 6 Derrick Dockery,
an offensive lineman from Garland Lakeview Centennial; No. 7 Kenny
Hayter, a running back from Cypress Falls; No. 9 Artie Ellis, a
wide receiver from Spring Westfield and No. 11 O.J. McClintock, a
wide receiver from Westwood High School.
</P>
<P>
   National signing day is Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Randall had committed to Texas this summer, but withdrew it in
the fall to make sure he made a passing test score on his college
entrance exams. Both his aunt and uncle, whom he lives with, said
Randall has reaffirmed his commitment to the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Halliburton writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
