A8053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-NEIGHBORS-COX     01-04 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-NEIGHBORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neighbors lend helping hand during bad weather
 &HT;    By Lawrence Budd and Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ After four days spent snowed in at her Bellbrook
home, Vera Sorah was ecstatic at the prospect of being liberated by
Anthony Bizzarro's labors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been out since Thursday. I'm getting cabin fever,''
said Sorah, 80, Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   All over the Miami Valley, people strived to return their lives
to normal after the weekend snowstorm. Some returned to work, while
others, like Bizzarro, took time to help their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting Bizzarro's arrival Monday, Sorah and her husband,
Elmer, 86, stayed busy taking down the Christmas tree and packing
up holiday decorations. The couple had enough supplies to carry
them through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of food. I just want to get out of this
house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Sorah wasn't so anxious. On Sunday, he had taken a spill
while trying to negotiate drifts up to a foot deep that had piled
up against the garage door. ``I don't want to go out in this
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Bizzarro was hacking his way through the final patches
of frozen snow filling the Sorah's driveway. After two hours of
work, Bizzarro seemed to have prevailed. The cost to the Sorahs: a
cup of hot chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally a cup of hot cocoa will do the trick. I've already
had my first glass,'' said Bizzarro, a volunteer firefighter clad
in an insulated union suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the neighbors know me. They know to call me if they
need help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A young trio of Good Samaritans in Huber Heights _ Jasmin
Carter, 12; Lauria Bonds, 11; and Adriana Meade, 11 _ spent part of
their day off from school Monday afternoon helping friends and
neighbors dig out their driveways near Troy Pike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really look at it as hard work,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel better helping people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we just hope that people don't die (in the snow and cold),
like that one man in Dayton we heard about,'' Meade said.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, when they're finished for the day, Carter said,
``We're all going over to (Meade's) house for macaroni and cheese
and hot chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Meyer, a letter carrier whose Dayton route is near Woodbine
and Woodman avenues, said many of his customers are too elderly to
shovel their walks, but some still found a way to make his life
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made paths from one driveway to the next, and that's
nice,'' he said. ``I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   The minute Danny Glascoe, 30, of Illinois Avenue in Dayton tried
to get his car unstuck Sunday, ``about three or four people were
helping me,'' he said. ``One guy saw me and came out of his car
about halfway down the street, and a neighbor I know ran down the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Winglewich, 64, of Kettering said his Marilyn Street
neighbor Phil Hart lent him a younger man's muscle ``when he saw I
was digging out from my steps to get to my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Spoonamore of North Dayton was cleaning off her own van
Monday afternoon so she could give a stranded neighbor a ride to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just always check on everybody around here _ if anybody
needs a shovel or a ride,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Hurd, 33, of Dayton was on his way across town to offer
his girlfriend a ride to work Monday morning when his Caprice
Classic stopped cold and couldn't be revived at the intersection of
Forest Avenue and Grand Street.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd knew just who to call _ his uncle, Larry Banks, who drove
all the way down from Clayton to try to restart his engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure what's wrong yet, but he's here to help me
out,'' Hurd said, watching his uncle trying to do his magic with
starting fluid and jumper cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was asleep when he called me this morning about
eight,'' Banks complained good-naturedly. ``And I shoveled him out
twice last night, too. I still got my stuff in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurd smiled. ``Yeah, he's the one I call.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Budd and Jim DeBrosse write for the Dayton Daily News,
Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
