<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY TRADES CALICHMAN TO NEW ENGLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- The Galaxy traded all-star defender and team captain
Dan Calichman to New England Monday for for a second-round college
pick (13th overall) and the Revolution's first-round supplemental
choice in the upcoming 1999 drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman, 30, was sidelined most of last season sidelined with
a broken leg. The fiery, red-head who gave his heart and soul to
the Galaxy made a spirited comeback and rejoined the team for its
regular-season finale, but wasn't fit enough for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The New York native was instrumental in leading the Galaxy to
the MLS Cup in 1996 and was the only Galaxy player to start in all
32 regular-season games in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman was one of the team's most vocal players and also one
of the most adored by fans. But he said he believes his trade
stemmed from his disagreements with coach Octavio Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been torn between trying to rip (Zambrano) apart and just
saying my piece and moving on,'' Calichman said. ``This trade made
me very upset and it was very personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously excited that New England wanted me. I have a
background in New England and certainly if there's another team to
go to, that would have been the one, but I didn't want to leave the
Galaxy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, who left for Ecuador Friday for a family visit, won't
return until the middle of this month. Before he left, however, he
explained his reasons for the trade, which was agreed to in
principle last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very grateful to Dan and all that he has done,''
Zambrano said. ``We will miss his leadership but I believe it is
time for the Galaxy to make a movement toward youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Jolley (23 years old) played an instrumental role for us
last season and now we need to give him time to develop into one of
the finest defenders in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman said he didn't believe that for a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he says he did this to bring up the future of young
players, I'm not buying that,'' Calichman said. ``What kind of
future does (Zambrano) have? He has a one-year contract left. He
doesn't even know his future with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this was a personal decision. You can't tell me he
would give up his captain after all I did to come back for this
organization for any other reason than a personal one. He had his
reasons, but all his talk about the future and going in another
direction is for the reporters to believe, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Galaxy was sold to Kings co-owner Philip F.
Anschutz for $26 million. Zambrano's future with the team was in
question at that time and a few of the players, including
Calichman, voiced their displeasure with Zambrano to new team
president Tim Leiweke.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy wound up retaining Zambrano as coach. Calichman
believes his trade had something to do with his comments to
Leiweke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly haven't denied I was one of the players who spoke
to Tim, but the players didn't set up that meeting,'' Calichman
said. ``The players were asked to come in and be honest and I don't
feel bad about what I said. I have no guilt, I answered questions
to what was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, this was just a personal decision because I didn't
have nice things to say and Octavio has an idea of who went (to the
meeting) and what was said and that played a big part in this
trade, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano won't get a chance to respond to Calichman's comments
until a conference call this morning, but assistant coach Ralph
Perez came to Zambrano's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was bad blood between Octavio and Dan, I can honestly
say I didn't see it,'' Perez said. ``Sure, there were some comments
that were made that took Octavio by surprise because he never
expected or anticipated some players were unhappy, but that had no
bearing on this trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only carry so many defenders and central backs,''
Perez continued. ``We have a number of players in the over-30 age
group. We had to take a hard look and make a decision, and that was
to go with younger players at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman also was upset that neither Zambrano nor Perez
informed him that a trade was brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes, both of them handled this with tremendous
disrespect to me after all I have done since the beginning,''
Calichman said. ``Last year was a tough year and after all my
effort to come back this is what I get for it, not even a phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought at least I earned the respect for the coaches to
call me and tell me what was going on and that never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said that wasn't possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad Dan feels we didn't communicate with him,'' Perez
said. ``I don't think it's a good idea to tell players you're
thinking about trading them. What happens if it doesn't work? You
have an unhappy player then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team itself is respectful of Dan. The players admired his
ability to come back in such a quick manner and so did Octavio and
myself. But this all boiled down to a business decision and nothing
else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
