<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-DELIVERIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING EXCEEDS GOAL IN AIRPLANE DELIVERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ By dramatically reducing its inventory of planes sent
to the desert for storage, The Boeing Co. was able to deliver a
record 559 airplanes last year _ nine more than its goal.
</P>
<P>
   When Boeing announced at the end of the third quarter it had 36
planes in desert storage that it had not been able to deliver to
customers because of the Asian economic crisis, most industry
analysts doubted the company would be able to reduce that inventory
enough to meet its goal of delivering 550 planes by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Monday, in publicly releasing its total commercial
and military airplane deliveries for 1998, that it had only four
remaining planes in desert storage at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very positive,'' said Peter Arment, aerospace analysts
with JSA Research. ``It's a positive that should be well received
on Wall Street about how the compay is dealing with the excess
capacity out there in the world's airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's final 1998 delivery figures were released after the
stock market closed. Boeing's stock closed Monday at 32 15/16, up
5/16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Undelivered planes are flown to airfields in the deserts of
California and Arizona for storage because the weather is ideal and
they will not deteriorate. Many of the 36 aircraft in desert
storage on Sept. 30, the end of the third quarter, were meant for
Asian customers who could no longer afford them. Boeing had to find
new buyers for those planes to meet its year-end delivery goal.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mulally, head of Boeing Commercial Airplanes, told
reporters last week, that ``all the financing came together'' to
allow airlines to buy or lease the Boeing planes stored in the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally replaced Ron Woodard, who was fired as head of the
commercial business at the end of August. Despite one of the
industry's biggest boom cycles ever, Boeing lost money for the
first time in a half-century in 1997 and its production lines were
a mess as it tried to crank up production to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   To reach its goal of delivering 550 planes this year, Boeing had
to push a record 182 out its factory doors in the fourth quarter.
It ended up delivering 191 planes in the fourth quarter, for a
year-end total of 559.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered 375 planes in 1997. Included in that figure
were planes built by McDonnell Douglas, which was acquired by
Boeing in mid 1997
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's previous commercial delivery record before the merger
was 446 planes in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing plans to deliver 620 planes in 1999, an 11 percent
increase over this year's total.
</P>
<P>
   But the company enters the new year with the airplane industry
in an economic downturn. The company plans to slash its work force
by 48,000 over the next two years. Many of those job losses will
come from its commercial business in the Puget Sound area.
</P>
<P>
   Production will begin to decline after this year. Boeing plans
to cut its production from from 47 jets per month at the end of the
fourth quarter to 43 by the end of 1999. Production will come down
even more in 2000, to about 35 planes per month.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is ending production of the MD-11, MD-80 and MD-90 models
that are built at the former McDonnell Douglas plant in Long Beach,
Calif. It also plans to cut production of its flagship 747 jumbo
jet in Everett from the current 5 per month to two per month by the
end of 1999, and possibly as few as one per month. Asian airlines
are the biggest customer for the 747, but the economic crisis in
that part of the world has forced carriers to reduce their fleets
and postpone new orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
