<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WORK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION REVIEW: THE FACE OF HATE MADE PLAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (Production notes at end of the review)  
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First prize in Wednesday night's contest for crudeness and
cruelty to homosexuals must go to middle managers of a West Coast
branch of Cantor Fitzgerald, a big securities trading company. The
disgusting adolescent pranks of these million-dollar-a-year traders
drove Mark Anderson out of what he thought was a bright new career.
</P>
<P>
   But blue-collar workers, too, showed they can compete, sometimes
physically, by picking on Ron Woods, a Chrysler electrician.
Fearing for his safety, he left the company.
</P>
<P>
   And lest the working class get all the credit for
anti-homosexual enthusiasm, Cheryl Summerville was dismissed by
Cracker Barrel, a Southern restaurant chain, on the ground that her
``sexual preference failed to demonstrate normal heterosexual
values.''
</P>
<P>
   The three case histories that make up HBO's ``Out at Work''
attest that animus against homosexuals is still alive if not
exactly well around the nation. As the program, narrated by Grethe
Cammermeyer, an Army colonel who was discharged for revealing that
she is a lesbian, reminds us, in 40 states it is still legal to get
rid of people because they are not heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an upbeat note here, it is the resistance shown by
the subjects of the abuse. Ms. Summerville especially was
championed by picketing, sit-ins and other well publicized
demonstrations, which resulted in Cracker Barrel's protesting that
it did not discriminate, not that Ms. Summerville or the others who
had been discharged got their jobs back.
</P>
<P>
   Woods won election as a union delegate and went on to campaign
for a ``sexual orientation'' clause in the anti-discrimination
provisions of the new Chrysler contract. He didn't succeed
entirely, but changes have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking in these accounts is the mockery, the revulsion,
the downright hate evidenced by some of those who are caught on
camera. No sympathy for Ms. Summerville is detectable among
worshipers at the local Baptist church. Elsewhere a man quotes the
Bible as his authority that homosexuals ought to be killed. The
milder punishment, defended by Cracker Barrel patrons who say their
``family values'' are offended by the presence of a lesbian
waitress, is to take away her livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Work'' is a close-up of how deeply feelings against
homosexuals can still reach and how vicious they can be.
</P>
<P>
   PRPODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA UNDERCOVER
</P>
<P>
   Out at Work
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Wednesday night at 10:30, Eastern
</P>
<P>
   For Anderson Gold Films: produced and directed by Tami Gold and
Kelly Anderson; Lillian Benson and Ms. Anderson, editors; original
music by Don Dinicola; Grethe Cammermeyer, narrator. For HBO:
Sheila Nevins, executive producer; John Hoffman, supervising
producer; Geof Bartz, supervising editor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
