<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-SEASON-COX     01-04 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA seeks cancellation of season
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBA leadership announced Monday night a recommendation to cancel
this season and begin preparations for 1999-2000 with ``replacement
players.''
</P>
<P>
   In what was tantamount to a direct plea to the players union to
vote for the owners' last proposal, presented Dec. 29, commissioner
David Stern and deputy Russ Granik said in a teleconference call
that the union's final offer was unacceptable. Granik called it
``in many respects a step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer was presented Monday afternoon by union executive
director Billy Hunter and players association president Patrick
Ewing and then forwarded to the nine-member labor committee, which
voted unanimously to recommend killing the season, Granik said. The
full 29-member board of governors will consider that Thursday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting to see what they're going to do,'' Hunter said
Monday night, before announcing he is going to bring all 430
players to New York for a vote Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll educate them to make an informed decision,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern made an appeal to middle- and lower-echelon players by
painting a picture of a new, small league for elite players that
would leave them out in the cold next winter. ``Our players have
been sold a bill of goods about a new league,'' he charged.
</P>
<P>
   The clear reference was to agents David Falk and Arn Tellem when
Stern said agents will take 100 players and abandon the rest. They
would then be there for a reconstructed NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cancel season we've been directed by committee to make
plans for the '99-2000 season. It's not necessarily a pretty sight
early on,'' Stern said. ``If we have to rebuild, we will rebuild.
We have draft choices (among a pool of players). If we can't make a
deal with this issue we have to deal with the issue of replacement
players. A new league would skim off a view players and that would
be it. a sad thing to contemplate and I'm sorry our own players
can't deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it is clear that the union will face decertification
because it could not make a deal the only union members next season
presumably would be those who compete in the new league that has
been proposed only in the most general terms. ``Decertification is
of no interest to us one way or the other,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the enormity of the task of reconstructing TV
contracts and ticket prices for a downscale NBA, Stern said, ``We
are aware of what that entails'' and even suggested the he
preferred that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be commissioner of a league that doesn't have tiers
of competitiveness and doesn't lose money,'' Stern said. He spoke
of a modeling the NBA as a hybrid of other sports leagues and said
that meant dealing with competitive issues. ``I want to have 29
teams that fans think can compete and have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the NBA could simply declare an impasse on Thursday and
open its doors to anyone wishing to play, he said, Nothing prevents
us (from doing that) but the committee has agreed not to do that.
Having come this far, with the uneasiness and lack of definition,
the season's lost. We're not going to play this year.''
</P>
<P>
   If the season is canceled Thursday the decision will be
irrevocable, Granik said. ``if we cancel the season that means the
season is canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there was simply no progress, that the league and the
union were still far apart on such issues as maximum salaries,
percentage of income in years four through six of the proposals and
the numbers for rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
