<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSES-CENSURED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSES IN CHEMOTHERAPY OVERDOSE FACE CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts licensure officials decided Monday to
take action against 18 nurses involved in two 1994 chemotherapy
overdoses at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute for their role in the
widely reported medication errors, which resulted in the death of
one patient and serious cardiac injury to another.
</P>
<P>
   Two nurses have signed consent agreements with the state nursing
board accepting a year's probation and rigorous retraining in
cancer chemotherapy administration. For the other 16, there will be
a disciplinary hearing and possible sanctions ranging from license
revocation to a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The state's action reopens a not-quite-healed wound at the
renowned Boston cancer center, which is still implementing reforms
in response to the overdoses. It also guarantees a national debate
within the profession about the accountability of nurses for
medication errors, according to those in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will cause a lot of controversy and debate among nurses,''
said Bridget Culhane of the Pittsburgh-based Oncology Nursing
Society. ``Some people feel nurses should walk on water and never
make a mistake, and others feel we should acknowledge that nurses
are human.''
</P>
<P>
   In her nine years with the Oncology Nursing Society, which
represents 27,000 nurses who specialize in cancer care, Culhane
said she knew of no other case in which oncology nurses have been
disciplined by licensure boards for chemotherapy overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy overdoses may be on the rise, due in part to the
proliferation of high-dose treatments. A recent survey by Judith
Shindul-Rothschild of Boston College found that nearly half of
oncology nurses believe medication errors are increasing, a higher
proportion than among any other nurse specialties.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is growing tension between the
traditional school of thought, which insists on strict individual
accountability of medical practitioners for negligence, and a newer
view that decries the ``blame game'' and calls for systemic reforms
and greater openness about errors.
</P>
<P>
   Shindul-Rothschild said the board's decision to take action
against the nurses is ``a bitter, bitter lesson'' for all nurses,
but added: ``I don't think the board of nursing has a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call ourselves licensed professionals for a reason,'' the
Boston College nursing professor added. ``We are each and every one
of us accountable for our patients. Once you take on that mantle,
you take every responsibility that goes with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others sharply disagreed with the board's decision.
Dana-Farber's president, Dr. David G. Nathan, and its nursing
chief, Susan Grant, called it ``inappropriate and unwarranted,''
and noted that the institute, the state health department, and
national accreditation officials found no fault with individual
nurses involved in the overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   The Dana-Farber chemotherapy overdoses brought international
attention to the problem of medication errors. The episode resulted
in the death of 39-year-old Betsy A. Lehman, a Globe health
columnist, and heart damage in Maureen Bateman, a 53-year-old North
Andover schoolteacher who later died of recurrent cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Some nursing authorities commented in 1995, when the overdoses
first became known, on the conspicuous absence of nurses among
those held accountable for the errors by the Dana- Farber's
internal investigations and disciplinary processes. The hospital
did cite doctors and pharmacists as contributors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the institute explained that it was not policy to
require nurses to double-check doctors' medication orders and
verify their accuracy with experimental protocols or treatment
plans. Such a requirement has since been implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts nursing board officials said in interviews Monday
that nurses should be held accountable for not verifying doses
regardless of hospitals' policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board did discuss that issue,'' said Theresa Bonanno, a
nurse who is executive director of the Massachusetts Board of
Registration in Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law states that the nurse is fully accountable for the
safety of the care that he or she delivers,'' Bonanno said. ``So
despite the fact that there may have been an institutional policy
that said the nurses didn't have to check, it's a basic standard of
care that the nurse knows the drug or the treatment being
administered by him or her as an individual is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Culhane said the Oncology Nursing Society's voluntary guidelines
say that nurses should check doctors' orders against chemotherapy
protocols or treatment plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before treating, our guidelines say you must compare the
written orders to the formal drug protocol and identify the therapy
prescription and administration route,'' Culhane said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Reardon, a Boston attorney who represents all 18 nurses
involved in the case, said he will challenge the board's claim that
the standard of care requires nurses to delve into lengthy and
highly technical chemotherapy protocols before treating each
patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nurses were acting off not a handwritten order sheet but a
typewritten order sheet that had the protocol listed at the top,
and the doctor had filled in for individual patients what he
considered to be the appropriate dosages,'' Reardon said. ``My
contention is that satisfied the nurses' requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney said his clients ``feel terrible about what
happened, just terrible. They feel a strong commitment to the
patients and the patients' families. But it arose out of an order
that was incorrectly entered.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor who wrote the incorrect order, James Foran, was in
training as a cancer specialist at the time. Now doing cancer
research in London, Foran signed a consent agreement in November
acknowledging to the Massachusetts Board of Registration in
Medicine that he was guilty of negligence, misconduct, and
malpractice. The board suspended Foran's right to renew his
Massachusetts license for three years, retroactive to October 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The state pharmacy board in 1997 formally reprimanded three
Dana-Farber pharmacists for their role in the overdoses.
</P>
<P>
   The board cited two nurses for ``signing off'' on the mistaken
medication order, seven for administering the incorrect dosage for
four days to the two patients, and 16 for failing to verify the
dose during their monitoring of the drug infusions.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing board issued ``orders to show cause'' to the 16
nurses, which requires them to show the board why their licenses
should not be revoked or suspended or they should not receive other
discipline, such as remedial training or reprimand. Formal
disciplinary hearings will be scheduled sometime this year, board
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 are Nancy M. Hopkins, Christin O'Brien, Rolf W. Ludwig,
Robyn V. Woodward, Mary Edson Cowell, Leslie Rae Spencer, Karen
Anne Poreda, Heidi L. Dipietro, Shelly H. Ferman, Maura A. Murray,
Maria Minks Wadsworth, Donna Joseph, Kelly McNeill, Ilene A.
Galinsky, Susan Aikey, and Sheila B. Rozanski.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Lucca and Judith Esther Prisby signed consent agreements,
acknowledging the board's allegations as factually correct and
agreeing to obtain advanced certification in oncology nursing or to
complete 45 hours of additional training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
