<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN BE A VIRTUAL TOM OSBORNE AT THIS SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Jan. 2, 1984. The Orange Bowl. One second remaining on the
scoreboard. Nebraska 30, Miami 31. The Cornhuskers have scored and
it's decision time _ go for the tie or the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   And you're Tom Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   That is the role the Nebraska Education Association is putting
visitors in at Coach Osborne: More Than Winning
(www.net.unl.edu/osborne), an interactive site that commemorates
the former Nebraska coach's book while mirroring the recent PBS
special on his storied career.
</P>
<P>
   If Osborne fans missed the Jan. 1 PBS special, they can catch up
at the show's companion site, which was produced by the Nebraska
Education Association's multimedia department at the University of
Nebraska in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers' season is over, of course, but Nebraska fans
who endured the four-loss campaign are certainly aching for
nostalgia, and the Osborne site fits the bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's a chance to be Tom Osborne for a few plays.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the site's best feature is the Be The Coach
section where visitors can match their play-calling skills with
Osborne (Frank Solich might want to try it, but you didn't hear
that here).
</P>
<P>
   The site, also accessible through PBS Online
(www.pbs.org/coachosborne) includes an in-depth Osborne biography,
stories from his coaches and recruits, a discussion section and
history on Nebraska football since 1890.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska-Miami scenario in Be The Coach is among five plays
_ four offensive and one defensive _ that can be viewed on the
site. Each scenario offers three possible plays, which are actual
plays that Osborne called in real-game situations. Make the right
call and up pops a video clip of the play with Osborne explaining
his reason for calling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get the great plays that are near and dear to
Nebraska fans' hearts,'' said Joel Geyer, producer of the site and
PBS special.
</P>
<P>
   In developing the site, Osborne was asked to select pivotal
plays from the top games of his career, Geyer said. Geyer soon
discovered that Nebraska football produced more pivotal plays than
a Web site could handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a CD-rom game if someone wanted to be a little
ambitious,'' Geyer said. ``But (the education association was)
looking for a site friendly for folks with a 28.8 (bits per second)
modem and a 4-year-old computer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a limitation Tom Osborne-wannabes will simply have to
endure.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S A SUPER SITE: The NFL and Lycos Inc. have joined forces for
this year's edition of Superbowl.com (www.superbowl.com) the
official site for Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   So what does that partnership between the NFL and the 'Net's
second-most visited hub site mean for the average Super Bowl fan?
</P>
<P>
   For one, it certainly means a killer search function on
Superbowl.com.
</P>
<P>
   But it also means increased interactivity and content.
Superbowl.com has always been a five-star site when it comes to
functionality, but Lycos' presence should mean improved technology.
</P>
<P>
   Superbowl.com will include dozens of live chats with players,
coaches and analysts; interactive fan sections; multimedia features
of current matchups and previous Super Bowl highlights; a free
user-friendly homepage builder; searchable image galleries; and
lots of official merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   NEW E-ZINES: Two speciality publications now have companion
online versions.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Training Yearbook Online (www.springtrainingmagazine.com)
fills a void when it comes to baseball spring training on the 'Net.
Before this site came along, spring-training information was
limited to individual baseball sites. The Chapel Hill, N.C.-based
magazine culls data it compiles on spring training _ ticket
information, schedules, maps, top 100 minor-league prospects, etc.
_ and posts it online.
</P>
<P>
   Goalies World Magazine (www.goaliesworld.com), produced by
Gilles Moffet of Loretteville, Quebec, mirrors its print edition
with computer rankings of 700 goalies in 17 professional, junior
and college leagues, commentary and back issues.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
