<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS' DOWNGRADING YIELDS DIP IN MINIMED SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a run-up that saw the company's share price
nearly double in two months, medical devices manufacturer MiniMed
Inc.'s stock dropped as much as 14 percent Monday after the company
was downgraded by two analysts.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed, based in the L.A.-area suburb of Sylmar, shares closed
the day off $7.375, or 7 percent, at $97.375, after a late rally
muted the sell-off. At one point, the issue had been down more than
$15.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of insulin infusion pumps for diabetics was downgraded
Monday by analysts at Salomon Smith Barney and ING Baring Furman
Selz, which changed their recommendations from ``buy'' to
``outperform'' and from ``strong buy'' to ``buy,'' respectively.
The changes came after an extended rally that saw MiniMed's share
price climb from $55.50 at the end of October to a 52-week high of
$110.375 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock was starting to look very pricey relative to the
existing set of (earnings) expectations out there,'' said Volpe
Brown Whelan &AMP; Co. analyst Phillip Nalbone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nalbone said he is maintaining a ``buy'' recommendation
on the company because of its future earnings potential. MiniMed
announced last month that the Food and Drug Administration will
soon begin consideration of approval for its blood glucose sensor,
also aimed at diabetics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
