</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SEASON IN DOUBT AS UNION OFFER IS REJECTED
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Calling the players' latest labor proposal
inadequate, the National Basketball Association's negotiating
committee voted unanimously on Monday to reject it, reaffirming
that it would recommend the cancellation of the season to the
league's board of governors when it meets in New York on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern made his strongest comments yet
regarding the potential loss of the season, saying that the union's
latest offer not only fell short of the league's desires but
represented a step backward. After meeting for an hour with Billy
Hunter, the union's executive director, and Patrick Ewing, the
union's president, Stern said a settlement appeared unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the union said it would put the league's latest
offer _ one that Stern has said is final _ to a vote of the full
membership at a meeting of players in New York on Wednesday. Stern
has been pressing the union's bargaining committee to do just that,
but until Monday night it had refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said all along the players should have an opportunity
to be heard,'' Jeffrey Mishkin, chief legal counsel for the league,
said when told of the union's intention to hold a vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday night, Hunter said the union was
changing its stance on putting the offer to a vote ``to assure that
the owners understand the level of player resolve and the degree of
opposition to the NBA's onerous demands.'' Hunter said the union
would continue to recommend against accepting the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, league officials were concerned about the format of
the vote, which Hunter did not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing the 9-0 vote by the league's labor committee
Monday, Stern said: ``The NBA owners are going to act on the
recommendation. We're going to lose a season and probably the
careers of 20 percent of our players. It's a terrible thing.'' No
professional sports league has ever lost a full season because of a
labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner also spoke openly about the future of the
league in the event of a canceled season, adding that he could
envision using replacement players.
</P>
<P>
   Stern had already said that he would recommend the season be
scrapped if the players did not accept the league's offer by
Thursday. So his dire comments and the committee's vote may be part
of a 11th-hour negotiating strategy intended to put pressure on the
union.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it worked, at least as far as persuading the players'
association to call for a general vote. More than 400 players have
been invited to New York to take part on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player members of the NBPA negotiating committee
previously rejected the NBA's final proposal unanimously,'' Hunter
said in a prepared statement. ``The committee stands by that
determination and will continue to recommend against acceptance of
that proposal. To assure that the owners understand the level of
player resolve and the degree of opposition to the NBA's owners
demands, the negotiating committee will convene an all-players
meeting in New York on Wednesday, Jan. 6, at which time the general
membership will be asked to approve the negotiating committee's
recommendation to reject the NBA's final proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the union's members were convinced that Stern and
Russ Granik, the deputy commissioner, would recommend canceling the
season before negotiating with the union. Buck Williams, the former
union president, saw the management's action as a negotiating ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still Monday,'' he said. ``I would caution that no one be
alarmed until the 7th at least. I'm sure Stern wants to apply as
much pressure as possible. David Stern is on banking on a player's
vote. My whole issue is that we shouldn't vote now.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, were
concerned about putting the owners' offer to a vote of the general
membership. The feeling was that the players would not be voting
for the deal but instead voting to salvage what's left of the
season and might therefore take any offer on the table.
</P>
<P>
   But with several players recently publicly requesting a vote of
the general body, Hunter and the negotiating committee decided to
gamble. If the players do not accept the deal, it sets the stage
for either a whirlwind last round of talks between the two sides or
it ensures that the NBA will become the first major sports league
to lose an entire season to labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate making a deal,'' Stern said. Reflecting on
the possibility of using replacement players in the 1999-2000
season, he said: ``It's not necessarily a pretty sight early on,
but obviously if we have to rebuild the league, we'll rebuild the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of bringing more than 400 players into New York
for Wednesday's meeting seemed daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to educate them about the pros and cons of the deal
and we will ask that they support the negotiating committee's
decision to reject the proposal,'' Ewing said. ``We'll see how the
guys vote and then take it to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Monday night came after Ewing and Hunter had an
almost fruitless meeting with Granik and Stern. The union was
hoping its most recent concessions, including agreeing to an
absolute maximum salary limit for players with at least 10 years'
experience, would prompt the league to further negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The main stumbling block could be how much revenue will be paid
to the players during the six-year deal. The sides also have
differences on the length and terms of a new rookie salary scale
and a number of other economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   In its proposal, the union asked that 55 percent of revenue
devoted to salaries in the fourth year, while the owners have
offered 53 percent. In the fifth year, players want 56 percent
while owners are offering 53.5. And in the final year, players want
57 percent _ the amount they received last season _ while the
league is offering 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to see a proposal that reached for ours,'' Stern
said. ``Instead I saw one that went backwards.'' Stern said, adding
that another full bargaining session ``doesn't seem likely at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is the deadline Stern set for reaching a new labor
agreement, and chances appeared small that a deal could be reached
in time to save even a 45- to 50-game season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always hope, but right now we don't have any meetings
scheduled,'' Granik said. ``Based upon how far apart we are,
there's a lot more needed to be done than simply tweaking the
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   More than three months of the season has been lost after the
owners locked the players out and about $500 million in player
salaries. Ewing alone has lost more than $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned and see on Thursday how close we are,'' Stern said.
``In order to see who's more accurate in his depiction of where we
are, we're going to have to lose a season.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said: ``I don't think it's the interests of the owners to
blow the season up. I still believe we're going to have a season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
