u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-LOCKOUT-BOS &LR;      01-04 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-LOCKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA PLAYERS WILL VOTE ON OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA Monday had all but put an RIP banner on the 1998-99
season, rejecting the players' final proposal to end the lockout,
with the Thursday deadline looming. Shortly thereafter, however,
the Players Association announced plans for a full-scale,
rank-and-file vote Wednesday in New York on a proposal from the
owners that the union considers unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise announcement of the vote came from union head Billy
Hunter on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' He said those players who do
show up _ all 400-plus were invited, but he could not guarantee
their appearance _ will be given a full presentation of both
``final'' proposals and then be allowed to vote. When asked if the
players would back the union, Hunter said, ``I believe that's going
to occur,'' but he also said that if the players vote to accept the
owners' proposal _ which some players already have said is fair _
then he would go along with that decision as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I serve at their pleasure,'' Hunter said, adding that he would
not resign if the vote went against his recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter had repeatedly rejected calls for a rank-and-file vote,
saying that the players had authorized the 19-man executive
committee to decide whether an offer was worthy of acceptance. The
committee voted unanimously last week to reject the owners' final
offer.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say on ``Larry King Live'' why he had changed his
mind regarding a vote, but there is believed to be a substantial
number of players and agents who feel that the owners' terms are
not objectionable enough to sacrifice a season for. However, Hunter
said as many as 80-85 percent of the players support the union's
stance, a figure he based on a series of conference calls over the
past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hunter's appearance on CNN, he and Players' Association
president Patrick Ewing presented the union's final offer to
commissioner David Stern and deputy committee Russ Granik. They, in
turn, presented it to the league's nine-member Labor Relations
Committee, which, as expected, unanimously rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it would make a similar recommendation
Thursday to the 29 owners, at which time they would be expected to
kill the season. Stern said the deadline was firm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recommending that the players' offer be rejected,
Stern also said the owners will be given some thoughts about the
1999-2000 season, one which could be played with non-union players
if the union logjam is not broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pretty sight,'' the commissioner said. ``If we have
to rebuild the league, we have to rebuild the league and share the
spirit of partnership that got us to where we are. At some point,
you have to give it your best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft class of 1998 has not yet signed on with the union and
there are more than 200 free agents as well. Stern said that the
1999 draft class would be considered in that group of players who
would hopefully form the new NBA. The commissioner said there would
be no use of replacement players to finish this season, however.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Granik also reiterated that the owners felt that
cancelling the season was preferable to playing under the
conditions spelled out in the union's last offer.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said talk of union decertification was ``of no
concern to us'' and that he had no plans to declare an impasse and
dictate terms of conditions. He also said players should be wary of
talk of a new league, which he said would skim 100 players, many
clients of the top agents, and then leave the other 315 looking for
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so sad to me, it's almost unspeakable,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the sides are still wide and many, the
two men said. They are apart on what percentage should go to the
players, on how much the top players should be paid, on mechanisms
to get players even more money via salary cap exceptions, and on a
rookie wage scale. The union Monday offered to cap top earners at
salaries starting at $15 million, but also reportedly wanted
increases in that amount tied to revenue growth and raises in
excess of 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
