<SLUG> BC-R-MINN-VENTURA-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MINNESOTA, A RELUCTANT FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct hed)  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. _ There is, of course, the matter of the
silverware.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, frets the wife of the new governor of
Minnesota, ``if there is some queen and king of Sweden who come
here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you address these people? What fork or knife do I pick
up first?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a potential society page scandal, a first lady faux pas of
the first degree, and Terry Ventura knows it.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been part of the baggage as her husband, Jesse ``the
Body'' Ventura, the former professional wrestler, has become the
country's most unlikely political star. Ventura was sworn in as
Minnesota's 37th governor on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Ventura's inauguration, his wife was
busy trying to calm her butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I have just been treading water to make sure I
don't drown for the last two months,'' she said a few days before
the inauguration. To one television interviewer, she said: ``I'll
be the one tripping down the stairs in her formal gown.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that she does not appreciate the fact that her
husband, a man whose early career involved wearing a pink feather
boa and butting heads with Hulk Hogan, managed to upend the
stalwart Republican and Democratic candidates with his raucous
third-party insurgency. It is just that this extraordinary chapter
in her husband's celebrity forces her to become a celebrity, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, our victory turned into this giant Frankenstein
monster rampaging through the village,'' Ms. Ventura said from her
husband's transition office in the basement of the state Capitol.
``My phone is ringing off the hook. They have all these
expectations. They want me to give speeches. Well, the last time I
gave a speech I was at my sister's wedding. I was the maid of honor
and I said: `Congratulations. Have a great life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the down-to-earth Ms. Ventura, 43, who raises horses and
teaches riding on the couple's 32-acre ranch northwest of
Minneapolis, did not want her husband to run for governor at all.
She supported his decision, but largely stayed in the background
during his campaign. Her first reaction on election night was to
crawl into her mother's lap and cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid, a lot, of this loss of personal anonymity _ did
I say that word correctly?'' she said. ``I was afraid of the rabid
press thing, of where if you do make a mistake, my gosh, it's not
your mistake, it's the whole state's mistake. I was so enjoying our
little private life. Now the guys at the feed store want
inauguration party tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but those catty celebrity-watchers have started
to weigh in, even in mild-mannered Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone wrote into a gossip column and said why doesn't she
change her hair and she has too much hair,'' said Ms. Ventura, who
has decided to keep her dark tresses long and natural. ``My mom
said, `Well, do you like your hair?' and I said, `Yes, it keeps me
warm in the wintertime.'''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a farm family from Vernon Center, in the
southern part of the state, Terry Ventura has acknowledged that she
is not without social refinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not stupid,'' she told a Minnesota newspaper. ``I went to
Wendy Ward Charm School at Ward's when I was 13, excuse me. I know
how to walk, how to get in and out of a car without showing the
world everything.''
</P>
<P>
   With a good-natured laugh, she said in the interview from the
transition office that she briefly considered hiring first lady
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I thought to myself, that's not really why people
elected Jesse,'' she said. ``The first thing they always say is
that `You're always so real.' I'm afraid that if I did that my
husband and I might lose that appeal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Terry Larson was a 19-year-old receptionist when she went to
ladies' night at a bar called the Rusty Nail and fell for the
bouncer, 23-year-old James George Janos. (He hadn't yet changed his
name by picking Ventura off a California map.)
</P>
<P>
   They married a year later and she went on the road with him
during his stint as wrestling's bad boy, a role that sometimes
riled up fans to the point where they would taunt Ms. Ventura and
pelt her with sno-cones. But most of the time, she said, ``I could
fade back into the shadows. That is no longer an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Ms. Ventura has had to put aside many of her
responsibilities on her Jester's Falling Tree Ranch as she prepares
for a role of throwing parties and charity fund-raisers. She will
also supervise a staff of eight at the governor's residence, even
though the first family plans to live there only part time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is being run on my dining room table,'' she said.
``I had to put an extra leaf in the table so that I could have a
typewriter and a phone and files. Every time I walk through that
room, the stress level goes right through my hairline.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ventura also plans to get involved in two policy issues:
farming, because of her background raising horses, and special
education, in part because the Venturas' 15-year-old daughter,
Jade, has a learning disability. The couple's 19-year-old son,
Tyrel, works at a hat store and has hopes of a career directing
films.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura suggested in a recent television interview that the
first lady earn a salary for her work, say $25,000. But Ms. Ventura
said that was his idea, not hers. She doesn't want to overplay the
importance of her role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not here to whisper in my husband's ear every night,''
she said. ``I'm certainly not going to be stomping up and down the
aisles of the Legislature saying you have to change this or that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
