<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STERN PLAYS HIS UGLY ENDGAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coming next season to an arena near you: 29
variations of the Vancouver Grizzlies. Choice club seats and luxury
suites on sale soon.
</P>
<P>
   That was the latest threat David Stern made to his nervous
players Monday night, and to nauseous fans. Professional basketball
with replacement players, the Charlie Ward Association. Or maybe he
just meant a union-less league whose replacement players are the
real players, just no longer under the leadership of Billy Hunter
and David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Stern insisted, would junk the National Basketball
Association season Thursday and the value of their $150 million
investments unless the players came crawling back, on the
commissioner's non-negotiable terms.
</P>
<P>
   Vote, Stern again demanded, or starve.
</P>
<P>
   So the desperate players will vote on the owners' last proposal,
and a betting person would wager that they'll play. But there was a
better way to do this, a more compassionate way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players wanted to settle, that's clear, but Stern could
have let them do it with dignity,'' one person with ties to the
negotiations said Monday on condition of anonymity. ``How could a
man who is supposed to be so smart sit there and say, `no more
meetings,' and ever expect these players to feel anything but
contempt for him in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Worse than bad business, this has become repulsive theater,
insensitive on many fronts, including one that is, at least
symbolically, racial. Stern moved this week from his pure-as-snow
vacation mountain to his Manhattan ivory tower but not off his
refusal to barter, even to the bitter end. In the endgame of the
most trying time of his 15-year run, he looked less like the cool
negotiator and more like a zealot fueled by thinly veiled rage,
what many of his opponents have claimed he is privately like.
</P>
<P>
   I have said all along that the union's threat to let the season
die rather than swallow a regressive deal was outrageous, but the
players did move significantly off their original positions, agreed
to what one former player agent called ``concessions that were once
unthinkable.'' Under the union givebacks, no longer would
21-year-olds or even 25-year-olds hold teams hostage. Stern argued
that he must have more, including stricter caps on salaries for
those in the league 10 years. Anyone who can't figure out what a
10-year veteran is worth is just plain dumb.
</P>
<P>
   From Stern's side, this became so bitter, so personal, payback
for the shadowy games of Falk and his imitators, for extracting
unrealistic sums for his clients without regard for their effect on
the league over all. But if Stern and the owners underestimated the
players' resolve, the union became too imbued with Falk's brazen
attitude that, in the end, he always wins. He always won the
individual contract wars, with Michael Jordan, with Patrick Ewing,
even with blanks in his gun like Kenny Anderson. But this
negotiation was different. It was collective, and carefully planned
by Stern, who took one look at the union negotiating team and was
blinded by the imagined face of Falk.
</P>
<P>
   Though it may run counter to the idea of Hunter, the union's
executive director, as some independent pilot championing a great
social cause, the reality is something closer to what Stern
believed. And it is laughable when those who may soon need a few
Knick quotes try to separate Ewing from Falk, as if the former is
earnest and the latter is evil. The inescapable truth is that Ewing
and others have been doing Falk's bidding for years.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for instance, back in 1990 a raucous union meeting
over a popular pension plan proposed by the president at the time,
Isiah Thomas. On the grounds that it meant less money for stars,
Falk opposed it. He stormed out of the meeting, Jordan and Ewing
right behind.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the very selection process for the job that
Hunter eventually got, at the 1996 All-Star Game in San Antonio
when Len Elmore, not Falk's candidate, began his 45-minute
interview with a short, prepared speech. When he finished and began
fielding questions, Ewing and Dikembe Mutombo, another Falk client,
walked out.
</P>
<P>
   The Falkanized union has sorely cost the players. Behind the
rhetoric, Hunter realized that he was left with no winning cards.
He already surrendered on issues that Falk told his clients they
would not have to. But now, half the season gone, Hunter
encountered a commissioner who wanted more than a score. He wanted
to slam dunk, and hang from the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than allow this to play out the right way, in marathon
talks, Stern wielded his leverage like a club, browbeating the
players with apocalyptic visions of the absurd. Chances are, he
won't be taken up on his bluff, which is what he deserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
