<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKER-DESIGNATE SAYS HE WILL WORK TO RESTORE FAITH IN THE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dennis Hastert, the speaker-designate, said
Monday that after a scandal-wracked year punctuated by the
impeachment of President Clinton his top priority is ``restoring
America's faith in this U.S. House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is clear,'' Hastert told reporters at the Capitol
before his first meeting with a new House Republican leadership
team. ``The American people want us to go to work. They want us to
produce good policy.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, a six-term Illinois Republican, was the consensus
choice of House Republicans to succeed Rep. Robert L. Livingston of
Louisiana, who abruptly stepped aside the day the House impeached
Clinton, after revelations about Livingston's own past marital
infidelities. Livingston was also the speaker-designate when he
removed himself from consideration and announced his intention to
resign from the House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans will meet on Tuesday to formally nominate
Hastert, a former high-school government teacher and wrestling
coach. The full House is to elect him on Wednesday, when the 106th
Congress meets for the first time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With political rancor seething in the Capitol, Hastert's
reputation as a conciliator will be sorely tested, especially since
the Republican majority has shrunk in the new House.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hastert expressed confidence that he could court
Democrats on important issues from Social Security reform to
national security. ``A smaller majority makes the dynamics change,
obviously,'' Hastert said. ``But I've always been a person who
believes that we need to work across the aisle.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the bruisingly partisan impeachment hearings and vote on
the House floor, however, Democrats appear to be in no mood to
accept any olive branches from Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with the Senate moving ahead this week with Clinton's
impeachment trial, House Republican leaders are pushing ahead and
at least going through the motions of preparing a budget and other
legislative haggling that begins this time every year, as if
nothing were amiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see what's happening in the Senate as interfering with
what we're doing, setting up committees and all,'' said Rep. Tillie
Fowler of Florida, the fifth-ranking Republican in the House
hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore what he says is the urgency to get on with
ordinary business, Hastert has also tried to distance himself from
the confrontational, slash-and-burn tactics of Speaker Newt
Gingrich, whom he is to replace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Congress has to go to work,'' Hastert said. ``We have to
start to produce good things that the American people want: the
policies that address the needs of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   To help bridge the rift between moderates and conservatives
among his own rank-and-file, Hastert said he would grant wider
authority to Republican committee chairmen. Gingrich had
centralized power, leaving many chairmen grumbling about
micromanagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I have to do, I will be me, and I'm not going to try
to emulate Newt or anybody else,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before their three-hour meeting, which lawmakers said afterward
was largely devoted to ironing out details about the opening of
Congress and reviewing the rules that will govern the House,
Republican leaders touched on some of the legislative themes they
want to address in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list was working with the White House and
congressional Democrats to shore up the Social Security system, but
not at any expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any tax increase in trying to strengthen Social
Security,'' said Rep.J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the incoming chairman
of the Republican conference.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also signaled their intention to make national
security an issue, especially at a time when rogue nations from
Iraq to North Korea are suspected of possessing, or seeking to
acquire, nuclear, biological and chemical weapons and the
long-range missiles to fire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have the Cold War threat of nuclear-tipped missiles
aimed at us,'' said Rep. Floyd D. Spence of South Carolina, the
chairman of the House National Security Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Spence added that a new danger facing the United States was ``a
proliferation of missiles throughout the world. Many countries have
them that didn't have them before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
