<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI HEADED FOR ITALY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Olowokandi's Bologna has a first name...
it's V-i-t-r-u-s.
</P>
<P>
   His Bologna's second name is K-i-n-d-e-r.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Vitrus Kinder of Bologna, Italy _ the defending
champion of European League basketball _ has a contract with
Olowokandi's name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, NBA lockout notwithstanding, Olowokandi will have a lot of
bread in Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great about this opportunity,'' said Olowokandi, a
7-foot Nigerian who demonstrated enough promise while playing for
the University of the Pacific to be selected by the Clippers with
the first pick in the last NBA draft. ``With the uncertainty of the
NBA season, I have to entertain all options.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the option he selected: earn a reported $1 million for
playing for Vitrus Kinder until Feb. 15; if the NBA season is
rescued, Olowokandi can return to the United States and play for
the Clippers. If the NBA season is flushed, Olowokandi will finish
the season in Italy and earn another $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to those familiar with basketball overseas, this is a
sweet deal, the most lucrative rookie gig in the history of Euro
hoops and the richest contract in Europe this season. Being
un-American makes Olowokandi more valuable than an American player
of equal ability; foreign leagues typically have limits on how many
Americans each team can sign. In Olowokandi, Vitrus Bologna picks
up an American-caliber player without having to sacrifice another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the playing opportunity and the compensation are
fantastic for me at this point,'' Olowokandi said at a news
conference in Washington, D.C. ``I expect this to be an excellent
experience for me in preparation for my NBA career.''
</P>
<P>
   But how excellent do the Clippers consider his adventure to be?
</P>
<P>
   If an NBA season is salvaged, the Clippers will have a rookie
center who at the very least is in game shape. Of course,
Olowokandi won't be around for any Cliff Notes version of an NBA
training camp. It would require additional time for their top pick
who has played basketball for a whopping four years to reach the
same page as his coach and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But in reaction to Olowokandi's new deal, the Clippers deferred
to the NBA's legal department. The team was unwilling to break the
league-imposed, $1 million cone of lockout silence, and the league
office prescribed the following response:
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0497 </DOCNO>
