<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT     01-04 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUGH DECEMBER MAY BENEFIT JETS IN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, when Mo Lewis was a rookie, he was in a
playoff game wearing a New York Jets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what was happening,'' says the Pro Bowl-bound
linebacker. ``I thought you're supposed to be in this every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, seven years later, he is back, and the only current Jet who
can make that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the players on the roster, the linebacker is the only
homegrown Jet with playoff experience. Over all, 19 players have
seen post-season action, but for 18 of them it was someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that the Jets, who go back to work Tuesday
for their first playoff game since 1991, are hardly a collection of
wide-eyed innocents when it comes to post-season action. On the
other hand, of the four American Conference teams still alive in
the post-season, the Jets are last in playoff-hardened players.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars, the Jets' opponents in a second-round
game Sunday at Giants Stadium, have 33 players who have been in the
post-season, 26 of them with Jacksonville. Miami has 36 post-season
players, 31 of them with the Dolphins, and Denver, the defending
Super Bowl champion, has 44, and all of them have been in the
playoffs with the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those other teams had as tough a December as the
Jets did. In fact, rarely does a team wind up its season as upbeat
and as tested. It wasn't merely the Jets' six-game winning streak,
or the fact they captured 10 of their last 11 games. Of equal
importance, was the fact that the Jets swept their three key
division opponents the last three weeks, including victories on the
road in Miami and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last four weeks were as close as you could get to the
playoffs, at home and away,'' said punter John Kidd, who went to a
AFC championship game with Buffalo back in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the coaching staff is so experienced and that carries
over to players,'' the 37-year-old Kidd added. ``Coaches have their
set ways of approaching the bye week and the playoffs. The young
guys here who haven't been in a playoff game have experienced
pressure the last few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   And the current Jets who have been in the playoffs with other
teams _ including half of the starters on offense and defense _
constitute an important core of veterans. Those with playoff
experience are team leaders, including quarterback Vinny
Testaverde, running back Curtis Martin and linebackers Bryan Cox
and Pepper Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have enough guys who have been in the tournament,''
said Jets Coach Bill Parcells. ``I've got 19 players _ that's about
35 percent of your team _ that kind of have an idea of what's going
on. And I don't have to tell a Keyshawn Johnson or Wayne Chrebet
too much about what's going on. The Buffalo and Miami games are
about as close as you're going to get to a playoff atmosphere. It's
been pretty rowdy in the last month, both home and away.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Parcells was increasingly upbeat about and impressed
with his team's performances as the season drew to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought opponents were going to have to play well,'' he
said. ``I'm more positive now that teams are going to have to play
well to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The only defeat the Jets suffered over the last two-thirds of
the season was a last-second loss in Indianapolis to a weak Colts
team, and that surprising setback was probably instructional,
according to Parcells. `
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, the lesson was learned,'' he says of that game.
``Finally. You can learn those lessons long enough so they send you
home. I'm not worried about that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Parcells thinks his team will be ready to cope with
anything thanks to the challenge that December presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose the game,'' Parcells said, ``everyone will say,
`Well, they don't have playoff experience.' Well, that's a crock. I
know I'm going to feel good about our preparation for this game
because we'll have time. Winning those last four games makes a
believer out of me that we're going to try hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville went all the way to the AFC championship game two
years ago and should not have any difficulty dealing with playoff
pressure on Sunday. But what the Jaguars have not had to do lately
_ indeed, what they haven't had to do all season _ is play in a
bad-weather game. They have not even played up north since late
November.
</P>
<P>
   But Coach Tom Coughlin does have them accustomed to the road. In
their brief history, the Jaguars have played five playoff games,
four of them away from home. And they have managed to split those
four, winning and losing in Denver, winning in Buffalo, and losing
in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin and Parcells both have an obvious toughness about them,
and the players who have prospered under them are for the most part
hardened performers. Nervousness is unlikely to play a part in this
game. Certainly not for the Jets, who, after all, were feeling
calculated pressure from Parcells from the moment they put on
T-shirts and shorts in training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
