A8108 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HALL-LADN     01-04 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SUSPENSE FOR BRETT, RYAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For most of the 28 former major leaguers on the
1999 Hall of Fame ballot, this morning's press conference in New
York will bring suspense and anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   For two of them, however, the announcement of this year's
inductees has been a foregone conclusion since they retired after
the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan and George Brett are among 11 players on the ballot
for the first time. The only question involving the two --
particularly Ryan -- is whether or not they will be voted in on
every ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The highest percentage of votes ever recorded on a first-time
ballot went to Tom Seaver, who received 98.8 percent (425 of 430)
of the votes from the members of the Baseball Writers' Association
of America in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the ballot for the first time include Robin Yount,
Carlton Fisk, Dale Murphy, George Bell, Mike Boddicker, John
Candelaria, Charlie Leibrandt, Frank Tanana and Mike Witt.
</P>
<P>
   While Yount and possibly Fisk stand a chance to be inducted on
their first try, it traditionally has been more difficult to be
voted in the first time around. Throughout the years, Joe DiMaggio,
Roy Campanella and Harmon Killebrew are among the candidates who
did not get elected on the first try.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's credentials during a 27-year career with the Mets,
Angels, Astros and Rangers are incredible and are comparable to
Seaver's.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who had a lifetime record of 324-292, holds 53 major
league records, including most seasons played and most seasons
pitched (27); most no-hitters (seven); most games having allowed
one hit or fewer (19); most strikeouts (5,714); most seasons of 300
or more strikeouts (six); most games with 15 or more strikeouts
(26); most strikeouts in a single season (383); and most
consecutive starts (595). The list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for any professional athlete, if they are fortunate
enough to (go into the Hall of Fame), it pretty much wraps up their
career, sums up their career,'' Ryan told the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed (with the Mets), I had no idea whether I had the
talent or the ability to make the big leagues. Then, I made it my
goal to qualify for the pension. I felt that (playing four years)
was hopefully a realistic goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who is a member of the Rangers' front office, spends most
of his time operating his Texas ranches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at my career is I was very fortunate, and I was
happy with it,'' he said. ``I don't think you have regrets. I would
have liked to have gotten into more postseason play, but a lot of
times you don't have control of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ryan is known for his strikeouts, he said he is most
proud of his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really reflect (on my career), but I think I pretty
much get the most satisfaction out of being able to pitch as long
as I did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brett's credentials are impressive too.
</P>
<P>
   The El Segundo High graduate was a 13-time All Star, won batting
titles in three decades (1976, '80 and '90), led the AL in hits
three times (1975, '76 and '79), hit safely in 30 straight games
(1980), is fifth all-time in doubles, 13th in hits, at-bats and
total bases and is tied for 22nd in RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only player in major league history with 3,000 hits,
300 homers, 600 doubles, 100 triples and 200 steals.
</P>
<P>
   There are two players on the ballot for the 15th year, the
maximum number of years allowed on the ballot. It is the last
chance for election by the BBWAA for Mickey Lolich and Minnie
Minoso.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining players on the ballot include several who will be
close to getting the required 75 percent of the votes. Many expect
Yount to be elected in his first year of eligibility. Fisk and
Murphy also will receive strong consideration in this, their first
year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Others who could be close are Dwight Evans, Steve Garvey, Tony
Perez, Bruce Sutter, Tommy John and Jim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining players on the ballot include Bert Blyleven, Bob
Boone, Gary Carter, Dave Concepcion, Ron Guidry, Keith Hernandez,
Jim Kaat, Dave Parker and Luis Tiant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
