A8110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-PENSION-NYT &LR;      01-04 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-PENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LATE PENSION? BUREAUCRACY JUST YAWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is a good-news story in the sense that
everything turns out all right. But it takes a while to get there,
way too long as far as Gail Bernstein is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bernstein is a former public school teacher in New York
City. She put in for retirement late last June, 38 years after
first stepping inside an elementary school classroom in Brooklyn.
Altogether, she was on the job about 30 years, not counting time
when she worked outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   Like many thousands of teachers before her, she figured it would
take the usual two or three months before the first pension check
landed in the mailbox. Even that seemed like a long time to Ms.
Bernstein, especially since she understood that teachers in the New
York state retirement system routinely received pensions after only
a month. But what are you going to do? Fight City Hall? These days,
you can hardly get into City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   So she waited at home in Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   When September passed without a dime in sight, she called the
city's Teachers' Retirement System. Not to worry, she was told. The
check will be in the mail by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Ms. Bernstein was badly feeling the pinch. No money
had come in for months. Her husband had died 10 years ago without
leaving any insurance. She had her regular expenses, plus she was
helping her daughter through graduate school. Her checking account
was drying up fast. ``I was at the point where I had to cash in my
two mutual funds,'' she said, ``and my credit cards were almost at
the max.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, she was told. The check would be in hand by Nov.
30.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Ms. Bernstein was on the phone to her union, the United
Federation of Teachers. Were people there helpful? ``Their reply
was: `Take out a loan. What are you worried about? When you get
your check, you'll be a rich lady.'''
</P>
<P>
   Back she went to the retirement system, which advised her to
forget about November. Now, she was ``targeted'' for Dec. 30,
though she was warned that not even that date was definite, but
then what in life is?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bernstein, going broke, dared ask where in the bureaucratic
mill her paperwork lay. At the city's Office of the Actuary, said a
woman on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked for the phone number of the actuary, she said I
was forbidden to have it and I could not call them to check on the
progress of my check,'' Ms. Bernstein recalled. ``She remarked that
even she was not allowed to have this number. I was so upset I
asked to speak to a supervisor, who of course was too busy to speak
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the supervisor did call the next day, to say there was
nothing he could do. He, too, suggested she borrow money somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It's very frustrating,'' Ms. Bernstein said just before
Christmas. ``No matter where I call, they say, `Take out a loan.'
But will they pay the interest on that loan?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all polite,'' she said. ``But no one seemed to
really care. They didn't even say `Sorry,' just: `That's the way it
is. The money will come whenever it comes.' But this is my money
we're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Her long wait brought to mind the excruciating delays of three
and four years ago when thousands of public school teachers took
advantage of an incentive plan to retire early. They then twiddled
their thumbs for many months _ up to a year, in some cases _ until
pension checks arrived. ``We got beaten up big time,'' said
Jonathan Kimmel, counsel to the retirement system's board.
</P>
<P>
   The system is considerably more efficient these days, Kimmel
said. Still, ``isolated incidents'' like Ms. Bernstein's do occur,
he acknowledged. ``I won't say that it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong in this case was not clear. ``I think my papers
fell through the cracks,'' Ms. Bernstein said. ``However, there are
a lot of people whose paperwork falls through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider this, then, a cautionary tale of what can happen when,
for whatever reason, the bureaucracy gods frown upon you. Not that
you ever had any doubts on that score.
</P>
<P>
   As for the promised good news, Ms. Bernstein's check finally
arrived on the last day of 1998: a six-month total worth
$21,415.51, plus $47.59 in interest. Pension payments should now
arrive problem-free for the rest of her life, although ``at this
rate,'' she said, ``they've shortened it a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
