<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCES: FARRIS WILL CHOOSE NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA junior offensive tackle Kris Farris has
called a news conference for Wednesday morning and will announce
he's applying for the NFL draft, according to sources within the
football program.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, the Outland Trophy winner, is expected to be a late
first- or early second-round draft pick. He spoke with Bruins coach
Bob Toledo on Monday, but Toledo declined to comment on Farris'
decision.
</P>
<P>
   His departure leaves the Bruins with a major hole at left
tackle. One sophomore, Josh Webb, and three freshmen, Dave Wilford,
Blake Worley and Mike Saffer, are expected to contend for the
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Yox all, folks: Strength and conditioning coach Kevin Yoxall, a
major component to UCLA's resurgence, has accepted a similar
position at Auburn and will depart this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yoxall said UCLA offered a better package, but the small-town
lifestyle appealed to his wife, Nancy, a native of Tyler, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo acknowledged Yoxall's impact but said the Bruins are
better equipped to handle his departure than they were a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built the program up, and I think it'll be easier to
maintain it,'' Toledo said. ``To get to this point was pretty
tough, and it's been a big part of our success. But we're a lot
better off now than when (Yoxall) took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges update: Offensive coordinator Al Borges is not a
candidate for the coaching vacancy at Washington, according to
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Toledo spoke to Huskies athletic director
Barbara Hedges, who was an administrator at USC in the mid-'70s
when Toledo was an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   After she gauged Toledo's interest in the job _ he has none _
they spoke about possible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think... she's probably looking for a guy with head coaching
experience,'' Toledo said. ``That's not to say down the road that
Al wouldn't have a chance. But she called more to talk about
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't ask (permission) to talk to (Borges). He's not a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The defensive shuffle: Toledo met with his assistant coaches
Monday and revamped the defensive assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will play a 4-3 defense next year (four linemen,
three linebackers) instead of the 3-4 they used this season. To
compensate, outside linebackers coach Bob Field will now coach the
defensive ends, and defensive line coach Terry Tumey will
concentrate on the tackles. Marc Dove will handle the linebackers,
and defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti will oversee the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the day: From Toledo, responding to criticism of the
Rose Bowl loss: ``It's not like we were embarrassed by a 6-5 team
or anything like that. We got beat by an excellent team from the
Big Ten that was a top-10 team.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster update: Linebacker Michael Wiley will have career-ending
back surgery and be placed on a medical scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins now have 21 scholarships available for recruiting.
They had 15 seniors this season and were one under the NCAA's
85-scholarship limit. Three scholarships became available when
Damian Allen (track), Zak Haselmo (transfer) and Jeff Wright
(transfer) departed. Add Wiley and Farris, and that makes 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
