NYT-01-04-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-WHITFIELD     01-04 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-WHITFIELD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' Whitfield is all business
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bob Whitfield kicked back the other day and put his
feet up while sitting in his Atlanta recording studio. As he waxed
philosophical on his dual careers as the Falcons' left tackle and
as an executive in the music business, it is clear that the two
jobs don't match.
</P>
<P>
   But little about the 6-foot-5, 318-pounder seems to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   The former All-American from Stanford has marched to a different
tune since before Atlanta made him the No. 8 choice of the first
round of the 1992 draft.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Whitfield was voted as a first alternate to the Pro
Bowl and has played a big role in helping running back Jamal
Anderson rush for a franchise-record 1,846 yards on an NFL-record
410 carries.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitfield, 27, never has been voted to the Pro Bowl, despite
talent widely considered sufficient enough to make it on a
consistent basis.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Whitfield, an intelligent man with a quick if peculiar
wit, has an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be totally in tune, or I can be lackadaisical and out of
it,'' he said. ``I can shut down the best, or get beat by the
worst. Some (game) days, you just wake up sharper. You hear things,
and see things _ driving to the stadium, everything is just
sharper.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can wake up some days, and it's just like, 'I do not
want to do this. I'm ready to retire.' I'll be at the stadium, and
I feel like, 'I do not want to play this game; I hope that dude
across from me does not play hard.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Lester Archambeau was a senior at Stanford when
Whitfield arrived as a big and raw prospect out of Carson, Calif.
He doesn't understand his teammate any better now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What parts of Bob are normal?'' Archambeau wondered. ``He's a
big and talented guy . . . with a different sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield's role at his Patchwerk Recordings studio near the
Georgia Tech campus is more consistent and well defined.
</P>
<P>
   After starting the business five years ago, in part to help a
childhood friend who wanted to start making albums, he poured his
heart into the business, as much or more than he did football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive downtown after practice every day . . . stay
there 'til midnight and drive home and go to practice the next
day,'' he said. ``That was too much stress, too much anxiety. It's
like (defensive end) Chuck Smith said _ it wasn't paying my bills
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   So Whitfield stopped going in '96, except for Tuesdays, the
Falcons' off day.
</P>
<P>
   Business has improved, not so much because he's not around but
because the 3,500-square-foot studio with 48-track recording
capabilities has become a little better known. Some steady clients
over the last few years have been ``Usher,'' ``TLC,'' ``OutKast''
and ``ATLiens,'' all of whom have made recordings that have sold at
least 500,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Plaques on the purple walls stand as proof.
</P>
<P>
   His childhood friend, Curtis Daniel, runs the studio, and Norman
Kerr, a friend from Stanford, runs the music end of the business.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that 1998 will end up being the first year the
studio makes a profit, but even if it doesn't, Whitfield loves his
hobby.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, he got involved in some production work, but that
required patience. Bob Whitfield doesn't always have a lot of
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to be the producer. Hey, I played piano, drums and
trumpet,'' he said. ``It was more fatigue, more stress. I used to
sleep on the couch some nights. It was losing money, but I didn't
count it as a loss. I counted it as an experience. If it's
something you want to do . . . you can take setbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting the studio so his friend, rap artist Ras Kazz,
could get a jump start on his profession, Whitfield took it
seriously for a while. Upon realizing his skills were better suited
for football, he stepped back.
</P>
<P>
   The place still has his unique flair, however.
</P>
<P>
   The decor is generally purple and black. There is a red
billiards table. A soda machine offers the usual, plus Bud Light. A
candy and chips machine offers the usual, plus Phillie Blunt
cigars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a little something for everybody,'' he said, a big
grin creasing his face. ``It's fun to be here, but it's not my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Football is much of Whitfield's life, although the single father
spends a lot of time with daughter LaNiece, 8, and sons Kodi, 4,
and Kairo, 2.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield, who has played the game with more purpose than usual
this year, said part of the reason is because the team's success is
a motivating factor.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start playing football until ninth grade. I was too
big to play Pop Warner,'' he said. ``Sports were never big for me.
I was always a straight-A student.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started playing, I was weak as hell. I was a . . .
nerd. I'd just go to school, do my homework, run the streets a
little bit. I wasn't the athletic type. I was never honed to be a
football player. I would be bored if I was.''
</P>
<P>
   After a bad game, don't even think of asking Whitfield what went
wrong. He's likely to start rambling, saying that he forgets
things. Even teammates have a hard time talking seriously about
Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bob has always had the talent, but he's just getting
more recognition this year because of the offensive numbers we're
putting up,'' said Anderson, referring to an offense that scored a
franchise-record 442 points and finished No. 7 overall in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``His timing is incredible. He knows when to break the tension
with a joke or something. He's not a real talkative guy in the
huddle, but then again, when you just look at his face, you laugh.
He's the ugliest guy on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield is by no means alone in helping pave the way for
Anderson's big season, as a young offensive line that drew a lot of
criticism early in the year has matured faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
   But he's the anchor of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   Now the questions are whether he can keep it going and for how
long.
</P>
<P>
   He has two years left on a four-year, $18.5 million contract
that included a $6.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play 10 more years if I can get it worked out where I
don't have to do no doubles (two-a-day practices) in training
camp,'' he said. ``They (stink), man. I don't need that (stuff).''
</P>
<P>
   There he goes again, marching to a different tune.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
