<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK-SCRATCHING MAYOR LINGERS IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York extended his weekend
political trip to Phoenix, staying until late Monday night to
burnish a mutually advantageous relationship with Sen. John McCain
of Arizona. The mayor is considering a run for the Senate, while
the senator is considering a run for the presidency _ and each man
could use the other's support.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani left New York Friday to speak at an annual gathering of
conservative Republicans in Arizona, but his aides said that he
decided to linger a little longer in the sunny, 68-degree weather
at the invitation of McCain. The senator confirmed that Giuliani
had been to his home for a reception over the weekend, along with
other prominent Republicans, and that he was bringing the mayor to
the Fiesta Bowl on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republicans have grown closer in recent months. The
mayor also helped the senator raise money at two events last year,
one in Arizona and one in New York City. But they did not spend
their time talking about how Giuliani might fare in the Senate,
McCain said. ``I find him an intriguing man and I enjoy his
company. I just think he's a helluva guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the sometimes volatile Giuliani would be suited
for the strained politeness of the Senate, McCain laughed. ``You're
probably asking the wrong guy,'' he said. ``I'm not known for my
mild-mannered, Clark Kent temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   That Giuliani and McCain are friendly _ and even went to a
football game together _ may amount to little more than
post-election political blather. McCain said it was ``premature''
to say whether there might be a place for Giuliani in a McCain
administration, and a high-ranking aide to Giuliani made clear that
their friendship did not constitute an implicit endorsement of the
senator for the presidency. The aide covered other bases by
emphasizing the good relationship that Giuliani also has with Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, another possible contender for the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But the interest of a prominent Republican in the mayor does
reflect Giuliani's national appeal. After attending the
inauguration of Gov. George E. Pataki in Albany on Friday, he and
several aides flew to the Phoenix assembly of conservatives and
other Republicans. The gathering was previously known as the Dark
Ages in mockery of President Clinton's annual Renaissance Weekend
in South Carolina, but organizers decided that ``Dark Ages'' might
not convey the proper political message. It is now called, simply,
the Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Giuliani impressed the crowd with his explanation
of how he had reduced crime and the welfare rolls in New York City.
Although he did not trumpet his socially moderate stands on
abortion and gay rights in front of his largely conservative
audience, he did venture the risky opinion that President Clinton
should not be ousted from office because of the Lewinsky affair. He
then spent his time hobnobbing with other stars in the Republican
firmament.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani continues to refine plans for his political future. On
Tuesday he is scheduled to announce that his chief of staff, Bruce
Teitelbaum, is leaving the administration to oversee his
fund-raising machine, which grinds away despite mayoral term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   According to several aides, Teitelbaum will be responsible for
Solutions America, Guiliani's federal political action committee.
Solutions America is supposed to be the vehicle by which the mayor
promotes himself and his policies on a statewide and national
scale, and would be central to any plan that he might have for
running for the Senate. John Gross, a friend of the mayor's and a
former federal prosecutor, will continue to serve as treasurer for
Solutions America and for two other campaign committees, Friends of
Giuliani and Giuliani for New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
