<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLAIBORNE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT AGAINST UNION IS GIVEN CLASS-ACTION STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge has granted class-action status to a
lawsuit filed by a group of Brooklyn garment workers who accuse
their union of failing to fairly represent them in a dispute with
Liz Claiborne several years ago. But the ruling, released last
Wednesday, still leaves the workers facing an uphill fight.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in October 1997 against the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, known as Unite, by
union workers employed at Mademoiselle Knitwear, which manufactured
sweaters under the Claiborne label until Claiborne successfully
sued it for trademark infringement in a case decided early last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The workers have accused the union of selling them out in
earlier arbitration disputes with Liz Claiborne. Specifically, the
workers say the union agreed in the spring of 1997 to nullify an
earlier arbitration victory and drop a pending claim against
Claiborne in exchange for Claiborne's agreement to pay up to $20.5
million to the union.
</P>
<P>
   The union contends that the payment represented damages owed by
Claiborne under its union contract for use of nonunion
manufacturers over several years, and was unrelated to the
settlement of the arbitration disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mademoiselle factory in Brooklyn, once a union showcase
before it was caught in a web of angry litigation, sought
bankruptcy-court protection after Claiborne filed its
trademark-infringement case. It closed late last year, after the
death of its owner, Shraga Newhouse, last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rhine, who represents the workers, said that as many as
500 former Mademoiselle employees could be affected by the
class-action case against Unite, scheduled for trial in September
before U.S. District Judge Harold Baer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But such cases are difficult to win, legal scholars say, and
this case has already sustained several legal setbacks. In August,
Baer dismissed all the workers' original complaints against Liz
Claiborne and all but two of their complaints against Unite,
saying, ``Obviously it will be difficult for the workers to
ultimately prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, an investigation of the union's actions, initiated
by the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan in response to the
workers' complaints, was closed without any finding of unlawful
activity, according to documents filed with the U.S. bankruptcy
court. Similar complaints by Mademoiselle, filed with the National
Labor Relations Board, have also been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, JoAnne Mort, Unite's director of communications,
called Baer's decision last week ``a purely routine, procedural
ruling, which has no bearing on the merits of the case.'' She
added, ``In fact, the case has no merit, as indicated by the many
prior rulings in favor of Unite from Judge Baer, the National Labor
Relations Board and other impartial authorities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
