<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTS IN MILLIONAIRE'S DISAPPEARANCE PROCLAIM INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Appearing confident and describing the case against
them as weak, Sante and Kenneth Kimes pleaded innocent at their
arraignment Monday on charges of murder, conspiracy and fraud in
the disappearance of Irene Silverman, a Manhattan millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and son, in their first court appearance since they
were indicted on murder charges last month, proclaimed their
innocence and demanded fair treatment in a hearing marked by the
theatrical atmosphere that has surrounded them since their arrest
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accuse the Kimeses of carrying out an elaborate
scheme to murder Ms. Silverman and steal the title to her East 65th
Street mansion last summer. Investigators have been unable to find
the missing woman's body, so, six months after her disappearance,
the case against the Kimeses is based entirely on circumstantial
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   At the arraignment in Manhattan, Mel Sachs, their attorney,
demanded access to Ms. Silverman's mansion, asked that the Kimeses
be released on bail and said outside court that the charges should
be dismissed. Judge Herbert Altman asked for written arguments from
Sachs by Jan. 28 and ordered the Kimeses held until then.
</P>
<P>
   During the court proceedings, the Kimeses' actions sometimes
drew as much attention as the legal arguments. The two were
whispering to each other and holding hands so often that Altman
ordered them to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses' show of unity may be strategic. Their lawyer has
complained that law enforcement officials have frequently planted
informers in the Kimeses' jail cells. If one were to cooperate with
officials or turn against the other, it could vastly increase
prosecutors' chances of winning a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Monday, mother and son appeared confident and in
accord. When asked what her plea was, Mrs. Kimes, 64, began a long
statement: ``Yes, your honor, I plead not guilty and I pray to be
treated as equally as any other. . . .'' But Altman cut her off
abruptly and snapped, ``That will be enough!''
</P>
<P>
   Kimes also maintained a determined stance. When asked by the
judge whether he and his mother wished to have separate lawyers, he
responded, ``We would like to stay with Sachs, given the weakness
of the charges.''
</P>
<P>
   As they left the courtroom, Kimes, 23, smiled at a half-dozen
reporters and four sketch artists covering the hearing and said,
``Good morning, take care.'' Mrs. Kimes smiled and said, ``Good
morning, thank you, we're innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, a dozen television photographers and
other reporters swarmed around Sachs. A British television crew is
making a documentary and at least two writers said they were
working on books. Sachs was repeatedly asked why they had been
holding hands in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with it,'' he said. ``Perhaps it's
being forgotten that is a mother and child. It was nothing more
than a sign of the deep and abiding love that they have for one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses are also suspects in homicides in California and the
Bahamas. On the day Ms. Silverman disappeared, the Kimeses were
arrested in Manhattan on charges of using a bad check to buy a car
in Utah, but prosecutors have produced no witnesses or forensic
evidence linking them to her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says the Kimeses kept records outlining their
plan to steal the title to Ms. Silverman's mansion. If prosecutors
can present a convincing account of malfeasance by the Kimeses
leading to Ms. Silverman's disappearance, they may be able to win a
murder conviction, legal experts say. A murder conviction under
such circumstances is difficult, the experts warn, and the
prosecution could have to settle for a conviction on the lesser
fraud charges, they add.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
