<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAB 5': WOMEN ASSUME ARIZONA GOVERNORSHIP, OTHER TOP POSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A group picture of the five women was splashed across
the pages of ``People'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Their faces were superimposed on the bodies of the Spice Girls
in ``George'' magazine. And they have been featured in national
newspapers and on network television.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't entertainers. On Monday, they became the five
most powerful women in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull, Secretary of State Betsey Bayless, Attorney
General Janet Napolitano, Treasurer Carol Springer and
Superintendent of Public Instruction Lisa Graham Keegan _ dubbed
the ``Fab Five'' by the media _ officially took office during an
inaugural ceremony on the Arizona Capitol Mall in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They were sworn in by a sixth Arizonan, U.S. Supreme Court
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who praised the ``independent and wise
voters'' who elected the women, earning the state another spot in
the history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have varying responsibilities, we have different styles,
and we even may have some philosophical differences,'' Hull said
after she was administered the oath of office by O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we share a commitment to working together for the
betterment of the state of Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated crowd of more than 1,000 packed the mall for the
ceremony, and about 600 of them lined up afterward to shake hands
with the officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong ceremony marked the first time that any of the 50
states has exclusively installed women in its top five elected
posts. And there were several other firsts associated with the
ceremony:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hull is the first woman to be elected governor of Arizona. As
a legislator in the late 1980s, she also was the first woman
speaker of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ O'Connor is the first woman U.S. Supreme Court justice. She
also was the first woman to serve as majority leader in the Arizona
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Napolitano is Arizona's first woman attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   _ Springer is the first woman state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano, the only Democrat in the group, said the female
leaders have the same concerns as male politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot was said in the last few weeks about the Fab Five . . .
and the underlying message was that somehow we were different than
our male counterparts,'' she said. ``But on the issues that concern
me and concern us, I think we are united.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull also sought to downplay the significance of the all-woman
leadership team, saying the national media were making too big a
deal about it. The women have been interviewed by several national
media outlets since the November election, including an appearance
Monday on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all ran good campaigns, we're all qualified, we've
all got experience,'' Hull said. ``It just happened to be that we
had five very well qualified women running. We don't think it's as
different as people seem to think all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged that the national attention is good for
Arizona, which has suffered through periods of bad publicity, most
recently following the 1997 bank fraud conviction of former Gov.
Fife Symington. Hull, who was secretary of state at the time,
automatically became governor upon Symington's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you are talking about Arizona, nothing is too much
attention,'' Hull said. ``Our national image is important.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2241EST &QL; 
