<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTERAIR-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX AREA SCORES WIN OVER AIR POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX One pollutant down, two to go.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in metropolitan Phoenix are celebrating two straight
years of meeting federal clean-air standards for carbon monoxide,
the invisible but noxious compound that helped give the region a
national reputation for bad air.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishment means the Phoenix area has a good chance of
avoiding federal fines or severe restrictions on cars, trucks and
businesses due to carbon monoxide pollution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``While we certainly can't become complacent in our ongoing
fight for cleaner air, this is a tremendous achievement,'' Tempe
Mayor Neil Giuliano said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   But the news isn't as good when it comes to ozone, a summertime
pollutant, or particulates, the tiny bits of soot, grime and
exhaust that lodge in people's lungs and give the region's brown
cloud its distinctive coloring.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a landfill fire, particulates reached unhealthful
levels in southwest Phoenix last week, where they exceeded federal
clean-air standards. Throughout the Phoenix area, motor vehicles
are the main source of particulates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``We have had substantial, substantial success with our
invisible pollutants,'' observed Dave Feuerherd, program director
for the American Lung Association in Arizona. ``We've done
virtually nothing with our visible pollutants.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Phoenix area residents say their lungs continue to suffer
because of the lack of action. Christy Krejci of Scottsdale blamed
bad air last week when she began to have trouble breathing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I just felt atrocious,'' she said. ``When I went to bed the
night before, I felt like I was suffocating.''
</P>
<P>
   So she packed her two young children in the car and drove north
to New River to fill her lungs with clean air. The Lung Association
told her that particulate pollution, not carbon monoxide, probably
caused her breathing problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area also faces potential problems with ozone.
Although the pollutant remained below federal pollution standards
for the last two summers, authorities worry that the levels could
rise again if the Phoenix area experiences stagnant air and
especially high summertime temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerherd and other authorities say the state needs to do much
more to reduce particulate pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel trucks should be required to use a cleaner-burning fuel,
something that California has done for some time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other steps, ranging from street cleaners that
vacuum, rather than sweep, debris, to boosting requirements for
alternatively fueled vehicles, Feuerherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't likely to be dealt with in the legislative session,
which begins next week. Instead, lawmakers are expected to focus on
ways to improve the state's vehicle-emissions program, said state
Sen. Marc Spitzer, R-north Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer credited technology for helping the Phoenix area reach
its clean-air milestone with carbon monoxide, and it may work for
the other two pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question technology is a great ally,'' Spitzer
said. Such advances as the catalytic converter, cleaner-burning
fuels, and vapor-recovery hoses at gas stations have helped to
reduce carbon-monoxide levels.
</P>
<P>
   The automotive industry, responding to federal mandates, has
been building ever-cleaner cars. And the state's vehicle-emissions
program has pinpointed the bigger polluters.
</P>
<P>
   By going two calendar years without a carbon-monoxide violation,
Phoenix area officials have strengthened their case to have the
federal Enviromental Protection Agency classify the area as meeting
clean-air standards. Currently, its air quality is rated
``serious.'' The last violation was recorded in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The reclassification would mean that the EPA no longer could
threaten sanctions, including withholding federal freeway dollars,
for failing to meet clean-air goals.
</P>
<P>
   But the effect on daily life would be almost undetectable. The
emissions test would remain, as would the myriad of other measures
passed in the last decade to curb carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Those measures would be needed to keep air quality at acceptable
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Krejci thinks reclassification would be a bad move. A resident
of north Scottsdale, she said economic penalties may be the only
way to slow galloping growth.
</P>
<P>
   Growth will continue to be a challenge, air-quality officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Maricopa County environmental officials were warning residents
to watch for carbon monoxide buildups this week. They looked
nervously to the traffic from the commuters going back to work
after the holidays, with Fiesta Bowl traffic layered on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, county officials are thinking of creating
public-health advisories for particulate pollution, similar to the
advisories issued for carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Al Brown, director of the Maricopa County Environmental Services
Department, said the advisories would be helpful in April and
during the summer monsoon, when high winds stir up particulates.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he believes the advisories make people think twice
about how their activities contribute to air pollution. A recent
survey found that 90 percent of those polled were aware of
advisories, and that 60 percent said they did something to curb
polluting emissions. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or via e-mail at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
