<SLUG> BC-CHEMICAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPERIAL CHEMICAL'S SALE OF UNIT COLLAPSES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Imperial Chemical Industries acknowledged Monday that a
$1 billion deal to sell its white pigment business to the DuPont
Co. and NL Industries had collapsed, renewing analysts' concerns
about the British company's ability to reduce a mountain of debt.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont and NL Industries pulled out of the deal because of
undisclosed conditions set by the American Federal Trade
Commission. Under the deal, DuPont, of Wilmington, Del., would have
acquired the operations of Imperial's Tioxide unit outside North
America while NL, based in Houston, would have taken those in North
America. Tioxide makes titanium dioxide, a powdery white pigment
used in paints and plastics.
</P>
<P>
   The sales were part of a drive by Imperial, the third-largest
chemicals producer in Europe, to move away from bulk chemicals. Sir
Ronald Hempel, the company's chairman, said the ``transition
strategy remains unchanged, although we are disappointed that we
have not been able to complete these transactions.'' The end of the
deal was first reported in The Wall Street Journal on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts viewed the sales as crucial to reducing debt, estimated
late last year at 4.4 billion pounds, or $7.3 billion. Much of the
debt is related to Imperial's $8 billion takeover of Unilever's
specialty-chemicals division in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the collapse of the deal, Imperial also announced
plans Monday to take a charge of 120 million pounds, or $199
million, and eliminate 1,000 jobs in its decorative paints,
industrial specialty and other specialty chemicals businesses _
measures intended to save $115 million annually within two years.
But the moves left the stock markets unimpressed, confirming
Imperial's status as Britain's poorest-performing blue-chip company
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Imperial dropped as much as 9 percent, falling to
(PS)4.72, before recovering to 4.94 pounds, compared with a high of
12.44 pounds last May. In New York, shares of DuPont rose $2.1875,
to $55.25. NL closed up 25 cents, at $14.4375.
</P>
<P>
   The deal's collapse was ``quite a major blow,'' said Jeremy
Chantry, an analyst with Credit Lyonnais Securities, reiterating
that analysts had been expecting a sharp reduction in debt from the
sale of assets.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in three months that regulators dealt a
setback to Imperial's plans. In October, a $455 million deal for
the sale of its Crosfield division to W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. also fell
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, the British chemicals concern said in a
statement that it expected its profit before tax and charges for
1998 to exceed (PS)315 million _ now $522.9 _ and that its net debt
had fallen by an unspecified amount since late last year. The
profit forecast, well down from the 1997 figure of (PS)385 million,
or $632 million, was roughly in line with analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Alan Spall, Imperial's chief executive, told reporters
that the collapse of the deal would not hurt profit because the
Tioxide business _ one of the world's biggest producers of titanium
dioxide _ was making money. He said one possibility was to spin off
the business as a separate company, but he did not rule out other
offers. Some industry analysts said, however, that the depressed
state of the world chemical market could make it difficult to find
other buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early days as we take stock of the situation,''
Spall said. ``The industry will continue to consolidate, and we
have a lead position in Europe, which is very valuable. We have no
doubt that our phones will be ringing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
