<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      01-04 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICKS RULE! (BUT DON'T DARE SAY IT) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Five capable, intelligent women were sworn in as
Arizona's top office holders Monday, ruining the day, and possibly
the next four years, for me and every other newspaper guy between
the Grand Canyon and the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   It's not polite to say, but it's true. I only bring it up it
because, sometimes, ``a man's gotta do what a man's gotta do.''
</P>
<P>
   And, under the newly installed Gov. Jane Hull, Secretary of
State Betsey Bayless, Attorney General Janet Napolitano, Treasurer
Carol Springer and Superintendent of Public Instruction Lisa Graham
Keegan, what a man's gotta do is throw out his favorite cliches.
</P>
<P>
   They no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   As Gov. Hull made her acceptance remarks in the Capitol,
speaking of her love for the state and her desire to put an end to
negative campaigning, it occurred to me that no matter what this
governor or her female cohorts say, you'll never see it described
as emanating ``from mouths of babes.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmless catch phrases are now slaps in the face.
</P>
<P>
   New guidelines are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for us guys, no one has stepped forward to ``take
the bull by the horns.'' And for good reason. There are no bulls
left in office. And the word used for female members of the cattle
family is construed as insulting.
</P>
<P>
   Cliche-wise, we're ``on the horns of a dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ``back to the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, for the foreseeable future, I suggest ``it's better
to be safe than sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, when referring to any of Arizona top five office
holders, the phrase ``woman of the house'' may be acceptable when
speaking of the State House. But saying ``a woman's work is never
done'' is off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, an enterprising guy could whip up a batch of a bumper
stickers saying, ``Arizona _ where chicks rule!'' But he better not
say it out loud.
</P>
<P>
   And if ``chicks'' is unacceptable, what about birds?
</P>
<P>
   Do these five ``birds of a feather flock together?'' And could
they ever ``count their eggs before they're hatched?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   In the proper context, a writer still could say that ``sauce for
the goose is sauce for the gander.'' But the governor, secretary fo
state, attorney general, treasure or school superintendent could
never, (begin ital) ever (end ital) be called ``the goose that laid
the golden egg?''
</P>
<P>
   I know. It's confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Are there no more ``girl Fridays'' in Arizona? Or are there
(begin ital) only (end ital) ``girl Fridays?''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the fact it's no longer possible for Arizona bigwigs
to forge a ``gentleman's agreement'' should improve state politics.
</P>
<P>
   And, it's nice to live in the one state in America where it's
extremely unlikely our top elected officials ever will be ``caught
with their pants down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even at her own inauguration party, it would be
disrespectful to call Gov. Hull the ``belle of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as, no matter who firm she governs, it would be rude to say
she ``rules the roost.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Brother is no longer watching, fellas. He and his buddies
got swept in November.
</P>
<P>
   There is no ``old boy network'' anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor, who's bounced from one political job to
another, is a (begin ital) Jane (end ital) of all trades. And there
are four others lined up behind her.
</P>
<P>
   This has never happened before. Not in Arizona. Not anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to say ``it'll all come out in the wash,'' but that's
like saying we got women doing the state's dirty laundry. (Which is
true but impolitic.)Besides, no one knows if these five females
will get along. (Again, I wouldn't say it's because ``too many
cooks spoil the broth.'')
</P>
<P>
   These are trying times for those of us who carry the politically
incorrect a Y chromosome. I'm not sure how it will end up, with
five women in high political office. I do know, however, that
``it's not over 'til. . .'' No. Don't even go there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
