<SLUG> BC-MONEY-RESOLUTIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 RESOLUTIONS  FOR 1999 THAT  WILL MAKE YOU  HAPPY IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If everybody followed through on New Year's
resolutions, we'd all be trim, rich and constantly pushing the
envelope of self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many Americans are growing paunchier and say their
lives are dull, while bankruptcy filings indicate that a growing
number of consumers are facing serious money difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the problem with resolutions is that we try to achieve too
many things at once, then become discouraged when success isn't
immediate. With that in mind, here are 12 financial resolutions
that can be spread over the year _ sort of like a book-of-the-month
club centered on saving, spending and investing rather than
reading.
</P>
<P>
   The following tips won't shrink your waistline or make you a
more interesting person, but they can help you gain control of your
finances:
</P>
<P>
   January: Get your credit-card debt under control.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday spending frenzy is over, so it's time to reign in
expenditures and cut borrowing costs. Pay off high-interest
balances first, put your credit cards out of sight and switch your
debts to credit cards with lower interest rates. The average rate
is 18.75 percent, but you can do better.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Credit Counseling Services Southwest of Phoenix
suggests that you create a realistic budget and that you write down
your goals and post them in a prominent place. Also, tell friends
and co-workers about your goals, because a public declaration may
make you more committed.
</P>
<P>
   The number of personal bankruptcies in Arizona soared 25 percent
to nearly 24,700 in 1997, and another big increase is anticipated
for 1998. Simple overspending rather than, say, a medical emergency
was the reason cited by 58 percent of people who sought help from
the counseling service.
</P>
<P>
   February: Organize your financial records.
</P>
<P>
   This will not only help you prepare your tax return but may be
essential if illness requires that you turn your financial affairs
over to someone else. Make a list of important documents _ account
statements, insurance policies, paycheck stubs, loan contracts and
more _ and specify where these records can be found. Put your most
critical documents in a safe-deposit box or home safe, and make
copies for everyday reference.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank is among the many financial firms that offer tips on
keeping records. Call 800-669-2635 for its free booklet ``Getting
Financially Organized _ Money Minder Worksheets.'' The booklet also
makes it easy to track prescriptions and medical records.
</P>
<P>
   March: Quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just a good health tip but a sound financial
management tool. That's because non-smokers pay much less in
life-insurance premiums than do nicotine-addicted people.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 40-year-old, non-smoking man can buy a 30-year
term-life policy with a $500,000 death benefit for $700 in yearly
premiums, reports Chicago-based MasterQuote of America
(800-337-LIFE), an insurance-shopping service. A male smoker of the
same age would face annual premiums of $2,130 for the same
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   April: Open a Roth individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   These IRAs celebrated their first birthday Friday, and they're
still one of the hottest things around in retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   Although you can't deduct the money you place in a Roth, as with
traditional IRAs, you get better tax treatment when you withdraw
the cash. Assuming you keep the money in place for at least five
years and past age 59{, you don't face any taxes on investment
interest or earnings. Withdrawals from traditional deductible IRAs
trigger ordinary income taxes. Plus, principal pulled from a Roth
can be tapped at any time, tax free.
</P>
<P>
   Roth investors are limited to a $2,000 yearly contribution, but
you still have until April 15 to invest for 1998 taxes. You can put
aside a full $2,000 each year if your income is below $95,000
(singles) or $150,000 (married couples).
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Young, a vice president at WestAmerica Investment Group in
Scottsdale, can't figure out why every eligible person didn't open
a Roth in 1998. ``Most serious investors have $2,000 lying around,
and the Roth's a great deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   May: Establish automatic deposit and bill-paying procedures _
before you go on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   You can save gasoline and time by not running to the bank each
time you receive a paycheck. You can save postage and time by
electing to pay routine monthly bills automatically. Usually, all
you need to do is fill out a one-page form.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 97 percent of people who use direct deposit said they
are extremely satisfied with it, according to a May survey by the
Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis that had a margin of error of
plus or minus 5 percentage points. Yet only about one-third of
employers offer direct deposit, reports the Direct Deposit
Coalition in St. Louis. If your company lacks this convenient and
safe means of transferring paychecks, ask for it.
</P>
<P>
   June: Join an investment club.
</P>
<P>
   These groups can be a great way to learn about the stock market
and meet new friends. Club members meet once a month to discuss
stocks for purchase and review holdings. Many also recruit guest
speakers such as executives of Arizona-based companies. Most clubs
require investment commitments of just $25 to $35 a month, so as
not to break your budget.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Investors Corp. is the main umbrella
group for investment clubs.
</P>
<P>
   July: Rebalance your investment holdings.
</P>
<P>
   It's counterproductive to tamper with your portfolio too often,
especially if you incur transaction costs or trigger taxes in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   But rebalancing your mix every half-year or so can provide a
good way to skim some profits from hot investments while adding to
laggards. ``It forces you to sell high and buy low,'' said Donna
Brotherton, a financial adviser at the Advisors Group in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Rebalancing makes more sense if you're using mutual funds rather
than individual stocks or bonds because it's easier to buy and sell
small-dollar amounts, including fractional shares. Almost all fund
families allow free switching over the phone or Internet.
</P>
<P>
   August: Resolve to earn at least 4 percent on your cash
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   There's usually no good reason to routinely tie up thousands of
dollars in a checking or savings account paying perhaps 2 percent
interest or less. You can double your return by transferring most
of the cash into a bank certificate of deposit or money-market
mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   The latter are yielding more than 4.5 percent on average these
days, about one-third of a percentage point more than six-month
CDs, reports IBC Financial Data in Ashland, Mass. Money-market
funds come with check-writing privileges that give you instant
access to your cash. While not guaranteed by federal deposit
insurance, these mutual funds are extremely secure.
</P>
<P>
   September: Teach your kids about money and investing.
</P>
<P>
   A recent University of Michigan study found a pretty strong link
on intergenerational investment behavior _ young adults were more
likely to own stocks and have bank savings accounts if their
parents did.
</P>
<P>
   Consider giving your kids investing experience by setting up a
gift account in their names and filling it with stocks or mutual
funds. One suggestion: the Stein Roe Young Investor Fund
(800-338-2550).
</P>
<P>
   Young also suggests tax-sheltered education IRAs. But because
investments here are limited to $500 a year, he thinks these
accounts are best for preschool kids. ``Even if you can put away
only $500 a year, you'll have some serious money for a child after
maybe 15 or more years to invest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   October: Put more money into the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good tip for any month of the year, reflecting the
market's tendency to rise over time _ by about 11 percent a year on
average. But September and October traditionally are the two
weakest months of the year, which may make them a good time for
bargain hunting.
</P>
<P>
   November: Check your estate plan.
</P>
<P>
   If you recently got married, divorced, lost a family member, had
a baby, moved to another state or purchased real estate, it may be
time to make sure your will or living trust still reflects your
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Also, make sure you have correctly titled accounts such as IRAs
that fall outside your will or trust. For real estate and non-IRA
investment accounts, consider ``community property with right of
survivorship,'' a titling that offers married couples tax benefits
while keeping property out of probate.
</P>
<P>
   December: Plan your taxes.
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, this is the last month for taking action
that can shave your 1999 taxes. Strategies range from deferring
income into next year (if you have that option) to accelerating
deductible expenses by incurring these costs in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As for investments, consider selling laggard stocks or mutual
funds to lock in losses that offset up to $3,000 in yearly income,
and beware of buying mutual funds before they make a year-ending
distribution of capital gains. ``Buying the distribution'' in this
manner would subject you to taxes on profits realized earlier in
the year, even though you didn't share in the gains. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
