<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-U.S.-ART-1STLEDE     01-04 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-U.S.-ART-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-670(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. READY TO EASE SOME KEY ASPECTS OF POLICY ON CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout to clarify policy proposals and tighten story;
Adds reference to Jose Mas Canosa in 7th graf.)  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(js) 
 BY TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is ready to let more people and
more money flow to Cuba, senior U.S. officials said Monday, while
rejecting a fundamental review of U.S. policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The moves would let Cuban citizens receive millions more dollars
from American friends and family members, allow them to buy more
U.S. food and medicine, permit more direct flights between the two
countries, renew direct mail service from the United States and let
the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban national baseball team play
ball in March, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright formally recommended
the steps to President Clinton Monday, and the White House is
expected to announce them on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official, speaking in Ms. Albright's
seventh-floor State Department offices, said that the measures
``are intended to strengthen support for the Cuban people,'' to
allow them ``some elbow room'' and ``some modicum of
independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said the moves are intended to increase
educational, religious and humanitarian contacts with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms in U.S. policy toward Cuba were reviewed three years
ago, but were halted when Cuba shot down Cuban-U.S. pilots for an
anti-Castro group. The proposals moved forward after Pope John Paul
II visited Cuba a year ago. ``The pope's visit created a wedge''
through which political light and air can stream into Cuba, a
senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was the death last year of Jorge Mas Canosa,
leader of the Cuban American National Foundation and the most vocal
and influential anti-Castro Cuban-American political figure in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The nature and the timing of the announcement also arose in part
from a report just completed by the Council on Foreign Relations,
published under the signature of two former senior State Department
officials. The report proposed essentially similar steps, and some
bolder ones, like granting some U.S. businesses licenses to operate
in Cuba and promoting Cuban-U.S. military ties.
</P>
<P>
   The council's report said it was intended to ``break the current
logjam'' in American policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the U.S. embargo against Cuba, imposed 37
years ago, would remain in effect. So would additional restrictions
added after the pilots were shot down.
</P>
<P>
   But individually, some of the changes would be incremental
expansions of existing policies on private relief aid to Cuban
citizens. But taken together they represent a consensus among top
officials that, since the 40-year-old reign of Fidel Castro is
likely to end soon, the United States must ``promote a peaceful
democratic transition'' by injecting U.S. money, culture and ideas
into the isolated island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing what we can to expand the space'' in which Cuban
citizens can breathe more freely, the administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The measures endorsed by Ms. Albright can be undertaken by
presidential order, without congressional approval. But Sen. John
Warner, a R-Va., said he was ``concerned that these efforts fall
way short'' of what could have been accomplished by a national
commission that he had proposed to review and revise U.S. policy
toward Cuba. Ms. Albright recommended that no such commission be
formed, saying it could never resolve the question of the economic
embargo imposed by the United States against Cuba in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lost opportunity for America to review a policy of
basic isolationism,'' Warner said Monday night. ``We allow food and
medicine to get into North Korea. We allow food and medicine to get
into Iraq. And we still deny this tiny country basic things.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the news in Miami, the Cuban American National
Foundation, a conservative exile group, issued a statement on
Monday saying that most of the measures to be announced are
consistent with current policy and praised the administration for
refusing to re-evaluate U.S. policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The most important proposal is to increase the flow of U.S.
dollars to Cuba, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such remittances are currently limited to $1,200 a year from a
Cuban-American family to relatives in Cuba. The amount could
increase sharply under the plan proposed by Ms. Albright: any U.S.
citizen could send $1,200 a year to anyone in Cuba except to senior
Communist officials. Religious groups, human rights groups and
other organizations may be able to send larger sums to sister
organizations under proposals still in the works, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The most politically appealing of the proposals was for holding
two exhibition games between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban
national team. Baseball is immensely popular in Cuba, a wellspring
of baseball talent despite its poverty.
</P>
<P>
   However, a baseball official said Monday night that fears of
angering anti-Castro Cuban-Americans could delay or scuttle this
week's planned trip to Havana by members of the Orioles
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles have been privately discussing such an exhibition
with U.S. officials since 1995. Their owner, Peter Angelos, is a
major financial contributor to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But in February 1996, the Cuban Air Force shot down two unarmed
civilian aircraft flown by Cuban exiles testing Castro's will.
Clinton almost immediately signed legislation to tighten the U.S.
embargo and strengthen trade restrictions against Cuba. The moves,
which pleased anti-Castro Cuban voters in Florida and New Jersey,
froze attempts aimed at thawing American-Cuban relations, including
the idea of a baseball game being played by a U.S. team in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles organization received Washington's permission for a
trip to Havana later this week to discuss how to schedule a game.
If games could be set up so that the Cuban government receives
little financial benefit from them, and that profits go to
authorized charities benefiting Cuban citizens, government
officials would grant the team the license to play ball _ once in
Havana, once in Baltimore, during the exhibition season in March.
</P>
<P>
   At least one staunchly anti-Castro senator, Robert Torricelli,
D-N.J., said on Monday that he found the new steps unobjectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing here morally offends me,'' he said. ``Our ultimate
weapon against Fidel Castro is the flood of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the administration's idea of sending U.S. food
to independent restaurants and independent farmers in Cuba was
naive, since few such institutions exist and those that survive are
tiny.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, a Yankees fan, jokingly warned that ``having the
Orioles going to Havana may be good foreign policy, but it's bad
baseball strategy.'' Baltimore finished fourth in the American
League's east division with a 79-83 record last year.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the forthcoming report from the
Council on Foreign Relations helped to shape their new proposals,
in part because it has received support in conservative circles,
leading them to believe that the steps put forth by Ms. Albright to
the president on Monday would be seen as politically bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, one of the two principal authors of the Report,
Bernard W. Aronson, a former assistant secretary of state, said:
``American policy has succeeded in containing the spread of Cuban
Communism. That battle is over. We can move to a new stage in our
policy. We should, because within the shell of Communist society in
Cuba there is a fragile civil society clawing its way to the
surface.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
