<HEADLINE>
NEW ATTORNEY GENERAL RESTORES JOB PROTECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Reversing his predecessor's policy, Eliot
Spitzer, New York's new attorney general, announced Monday that he
would restore job protections for homosexuals at the state Law
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means that homosexuals will once again be included
on the list of groups in the attorney general's office that are
explicitly protected against discrimination in employment, hiring
and access to services. The office employs 1,800 people.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's action marks a break with his Republican predecessor,
Dennis Vacco, who rescinded the 15-year-old anti-discrimination
policy in 1995, just a few weeks after taking office. At the time,
Vacco said he was not motivated by any hostility toward homosexuals
or a desire to exclude them from employment opportunities. Rather,
he said, the action was intended simply to bring the department's
workplace policy in line with the state's human rights law, which
covers age, color, creed, disability, marital status, national
origin, race and sex, but not sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's decision stirred deep anger among gay political leaders
and their supporters. They said it sent a message that his office
did not view anti-gay bias as a serious problem, even though one of
its main responsibilities is to enforce civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's motives were also sharply questioned by gay and lesbian
leaders because he had refused to condemn his political supporters
during the 1994 election for attacking his Democratic opponent,
Karen Burstein, as ill suited for office because she is a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco, whose victory in 1994 made him New York's first
Republican attorney general in nearly two decades, was defeated in
November by Spitzer, a Democrat, in one of the most tightly
contested races of the political season.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's decision to restore the job discrimination ban was
greeted with expressions of gratitude and relief from gay and
lesbian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was clear hostility toward lesbian and gay people under
the Vacco administration,'' said Matt Foreman, executive director
of Empire State Pride Agenda, a lobbying group. ``We hope that
Spitzer's decision will reverse what happened under Vacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuals in the Law Department first won job protection in
March 1980 under an executive order signed by Robert Abrams, who
was then the attorney general. His successor, G. Oliver Koppell,
renewed the order in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's action was one of two executive orders that Spitzer
issued Monday, his first official day in office. In the other
order, he banned employees from making financial contributions to
any campaign committee he establishes.
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Spitzer repeatedly criticized Vacco's
hiring practices, saying he had fired scores of experienced lawyers
and replaced them with younger, inexperienced lawyers who had ties
to powerful members of the Republican and Conservative parties.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's first day in office was not all serious business. Not
long after his aides began sending out faxes to the media Monday
morning, they learned that they were arriving at the other end with
the tag line: ``$8 Million Man.'' Spitzer's aides suspected it was
a prank by someone in the previous administration, a reference to
the total amount of money that Spitzer, a wealthy Manhattan lawyer,
spent in an unsuccessful race in 1994 and in his recent successful
campaign for attorney general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
