<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-GUNLAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta plans to sue gun makers
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The city of Atlanta will sue gun makers this year, in
an attempt to hold them accountable for the havoc and expense
created by shooting injuries and deaths, Mayor Bill Campbell said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If the city moves forward with such a lawsuit, it would join a
growing nationwide trend akin to the lawsuits against the tobacco
industries that reaped millions in court settlements for state
governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's the same issue,'' Campbell said. ``Just as the
tobacco companies were held responsible for the carnage and
health-related issues, so it is that those who provide the guns for
those that pull the triggers must be held accountable as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The cities of Chicago and New Orleans filed similar lawsuits
last year, seeking millions of dollars in damages for public
expenses related to shooting deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell did not specify which gun manufacturers the city will
target, nor did he say whether the city will join a class-action
lawsuit with other cities, or initiate a lawsuit of its own.
</P>
<P>
   He would only say that the city is interviewing lawyers to
present its case, and that the lawsuit would be filed ``definitely
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell made the announcement during his annual
``state-of-the-city'' address before the Atlanta City Council, an
upbeat speech in which he bragged on his administration's
accomplishments _ from negotiating a new downtown arena for the
Atlanta Hawks basketball team to improvements in the city's public
housing _ since he took office in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we're not a perfect city . . . but we are a great
city,'' Campell said. ``And undeniably better than what we had
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell pledged to make public safety a priority, highlighting
a plan to provide raises for police. He claimed that crime is at
its lowest point in 30 years, ``in every single category'' and used
murder statistics to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell carefully chose numbers to paint a positive picture of
crime in the city. Campbell said that the 149 homicides in 1998,
noting that Ivan Allen was mayor, were less than the 183 in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't say is that more people were murdered in 1998 in
the city than in 1977, 1978, 1983, 1984 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Jabari Simama, the mayor's director of marketing and
communications, acknowleged that the statement is unclear, and said
he plans to check the statistics before the mayor delivers a
similar speech today to the business community.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the mayor intended to communicate is that overall crime
is down to 30-year lows and that the homicide rate is lower in 1998
than it was in 1968,'' Simama said. ``The mayor did not
intentionally mean to ignore any years in between when the homicide
rates may be lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor outlined other goals for 1999, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ An effort to provide computer access to every Atlanta public
school student. ``In the early years of the next milennium,
economic analysts are saying that if you do not have computer
skills, you won't be able to find many jobs,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell did not provide details on the idea, but said he would
soon announce a proposal involving ``a partnership with the private
sector, Atlanta public schools, and 100 Black Men of America so
that we can work hard to make technology available to all of our
students at the very outset of their education.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Formation of a city committee to ensure every city resident is
counted during the 2000 census. Campbell said the city loses
$400,000 of federal funding for every 20 resident that are not
counted. The mayor said the city was under-counted by 13,000 people
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Campos writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
