<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANFRAN-NEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One practice enough for instinctive Haley
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Santa Clara, Calif. _ He did not dominate as he did in his glory
days, but out-of-retirement lineman Charles Haley impressed his
team so much during a 31-play stint Sunday against Green Bay that
the 49ers expect him to be even more effective Saturday against the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Haley gets four days of preparation _ he had just one
before playing against the Packers _ and the Georgia Dome turf
should benefit the speed rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been a little rusty,'' coach Steve Mariucci said,
``but he ran around and gave us some juice, some fresh legs. He had
an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Haley had two tackles and a pressure on Brett Favre that
resulted in a fourth-quarter interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence forces you to think about him,'' safety Tim
McDonald said Monday. ``You can't expect to block him with one guy.
...His instincts carried him. It was good for him to get a game
under his belt and to feel the talent around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst seems OK
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who had Monday off, came out of the game with the
Packers in good shape in terms of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern was running back Garrison Hearst, who played
despite a slightly pulled hamstring. He left the game late in the
fourth quarter but had only suffered cramps in his calf and
hamstring, which should not keep him out of Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was sore,'' Mariucci said, ``but he should be able
to go. The hamstring is in better shape this week than it was last.
It's just a matter of getting the soreness out.''
</P>
<P>
   Trick question
</P>
<P>
   McDonald was taken aback when a radio reporter asked whether his
team had received a favor from the Arizona Cardinals, who knocked
off Dallas, leaving San Francisco to play Atlanta instead of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to answer that,'' McDonald said after a few
seconds. ``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   Before answering another query, however, McDonald said: ``It's a
tough road no matter what order it comes. Play Minnesota now, then
you've got Atlanta next. Play Atlanta now, you've got Minnesota
next. There's no getting around it. You've got to play them to get
where you want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   No road warriors
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers lost four games on the road this season and won all
their games at 3Com Park. The reason?
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost four games to playoff teams on the road,'' Mariucci
said. ``Our opponents have been very good teams. But games like
(Sunday's) are tremendous experience for our young guys. I think we
grew up a lot. Maybe now we're more ready for a playoff game on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice has achy knee
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Rice, who had just one catch for 6 yards Sunday, has a
sore knee that probably will limit his practice time this week. ...
The 49ers will practice today and Wednesday and head to Atlanta on
Thursday night after a workout. ``It's a short week, but it's good
that we're playing a team that we're familiar with,'' Mariucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
