<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8270 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-WRI     01-04 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: President Clinton.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, who is generally more
moderate than Gregg and Hatch, underscored once again his
determination to see a full trial. ``As a precedent it has to be
done right,'' he said of an impeachment trial after attending a
health-care event at the White House. ``I think it's the trial of
all time. I don't think there has ever been a trial in the history
of Anglo-Saxon jurisprudence which is as important as this one.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the House, Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who is expected
to be elected speaker this week, said he would like to see a House
prosecution team led by Rep. Henry J. Hyde make the full case that
led the House to approve the articles of impeachment charging
Clinton with perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly like to see Henry Hyde be able to present
the testimony and what he needs to do to put his case forward,''
Hastert said, ``but that decision is in the Senate and we'll see
how that works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, an author of the compromise plan, said he still believed
a Republican majority would coalesce around his proposal once
lawmakers returned to the Capitol this week and studied its
details. ``I have hopes that it will because I think it's logical,
but I have still to persuade 28 members,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he wanted to see the Senate operate in a bipartisan
way to avoid a ``residue of partisan bitterness'' that could hurt
its ability to reach compromises on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican aide close to the negotiations under way in the
Senate said the chances that Gorton's plan ``as proposed to the
letter'' would be approved were ``almost nil.'' But he added that
``a close facsimile or a cousin of the plan is probably something
that still has momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican whips were to meet on Tuesday morning to
assess the sentiment of their caucus, and officials said that a
number of changes were under discussion in the Gorton-Lieberman
plan in an effort to attract more Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They ranged from giving slightly more time for the House and the
White House to present their cases to the Senate to taking actual
votes on the articles of impeachment instead of test votes. Another
possibility would be to dispense with the test votes and simply
take a vote to adjourn the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us are open to some modifications,'' said Lieberman,
the other author of the plan. But he said he still wanted to avoid
numerous witnesses and to stop a trial from dragging on even if
there were no hopes of gaining the votes to convict the president
and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key turning point in all these discussions is whether
witnesses are called or not,'' Lieberman said. ``Then it gets into
a very different kind of procedure that I'm afraid will become not
only more sordid but will become more partisan and inevitably
become a long trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators have only a few days to iron out these details. Senate
Republicans and Democrats both plan to caucus on impeachment on
Wednesday, the first day of the new Congress. Clinton on Monday
staged a White House event on aid for the chronically ill _ one of
a series of public appearances intended to help him dominate the
public policy agenda. His spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said that the
president intended his State of the Union speech to showcase the
agenda that he will pursue this year regardless of the progress of
the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president believes,'' Lockhart said, ``and those
who have watched him believe, that one of the main reasons that he
continues to enjoy support from the American public is he puts
their interests first, he puts their business first, and that's
what he's going to continue doing,''
</P>
</TEXT>
