<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C., N.Y.)  
 DR. RUTH IS SILENT: TEEN-AGE CROONER; EUROS FOR SALE; BOOK
BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVING? LET LIVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The septuagenarian sex therapist DR. RUTH WESTHEIMER listened to
the talk about Social Security and health care. But like the agenda
planners and policy makers at Renaissance Weekend, the annual
Democratic battery-charging session held in Hilton Head, S.C., she
continued her silence about the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an entire year, I have absolutely not talked about the
issue,'' she said Monday. ``I have a proposal for a book in the
works based on the phrase that Henry Kissinger used, `Power is an
aphrodisiac,' but I will never talk about people who are alive.
David and Bathsheba, yes, and Queen Victoria, and I might go as far
as the Windsors.''
</P>
<P>
   OLD AT HEART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is a 17-year-old singer like TIM DRAXL doing in
a Greenwich Village piano bar called Eighty-Eight's?
</P>
<P>
   Not ordering drinks, that is for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like alcohol at all,'' he said. ``Can't stand it.''
And even if he wanted a martini or a Manhattan, the waiters and
waitresses have been told he is not to be served.
</P>
<P>
   But he is to sing. He opened Monday night and is scheduled to
appear again Tuesday and next Monday and Tuesday, performing
standards by Gershwin and Cole Porter, among other songwriters. The
club's owners say he is one of the youngest performers to appear in
a New York cabaret, and one of the youngest to arrive with a
five-album record contract from a major label, Sony/Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tells me I'm so young,'' he said Monday. Grown-ups
also wonder why he likes the music of the 1930s better than, say,
the music of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not normal,'' he said. ``I listen to pop, but I have a
stronger passion for this music. It's more, I think, music for the
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE CHECK FITS ALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We've had a few people ask, but no one's bought,''
LORENZO CESARE said shortly before 2 p.m. Monday from behind his
teller's window in the Thomas Cook currency exchange at 1590
Broadway, near 48th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The unbought item he was talking about was the euro, the single
currency that 11 European nations began using on Friday.
Specifically, he was talking about euro traveler's checks; hard,
cold cash euros will not be issued until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Then EDWARD MAHER, a baker from Lake Ronkonkoma, N.Y., walked
in. He asked for traveler's checks; some in pounds, some in francs.
</P>
<P>
   Cesare told him that Thomas Cook had stopped selling traveler's
checks in francs because France had made the switch to the euro. So
he bought two 50-euro traveler's checks at $61.50 apiece, along
with several hundred dollars' worth of pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm curious how easily this is going to be accepted,'' said
Maher, who is scheduled to leave Wednesday for a trip to London and
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``The articles I've read all equate the way Europe used to be
until last week with going to New Jersey and having to use
different currency,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   BARGAIN GIFTS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lot of gift givers on the Upper West Side must have
given music-loving friends or relatives copies of ``The Good
Life,'' the autobiography that TONY BENNETT wrote with help from
the jazz scholar WILL FRIEDWALD. The week before Christmas, a tall
stack of ``The Good Life,'' which was published at $25 last year by
Pocket Books, dominated the 50-percent-off table at the Barnes &AMP;
Noble near Lincoln Center; a sign, perhaps, that book buyers had
not snatched it up as fast as better sellers in the store, on 66th
Street between Broadway and Columbus Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, bargain hunters noticed that the pile of ``The Good
Life'' was much shorter than before Christmas. Towering over it
were two new titles: ``At Home in the World,'' by JOYCE MAYNARD
(Picador, originally $25) and ``Journey to Beloved,'' by OPRAH
WINFREY and KEN REGAN (Hyperion, originally $20).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
