<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Peru: New premier named in shuffle
</P>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ With his support declining in the polls, President
Alberto Fujimori announced he would shuffle his Cabinet, but not
change the government's economic policies. Victor Joy Way Rojas,
leader of Congress and a longtime ally of Fujimori, will replace
Alberto Pandolfi Arbulu as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: New top justice picked
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The 11 justices on Mexico's Supreme Court elected
a new president to a four-year term. Genaro David Gongora Pimentel,
61, favors refocusing the court's attention on constitutional
matters and away from workaday cases that currently crowd its
agenda. He also reportedly favors expanding the court's power to
interpret laws, a prerogative limited under Mexico's system.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: Back from the brink
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement, 59, returned
to work, four months after surviving a nearly fatal reaction to
anesthesia for a kidney stone operation at a military hospital. ``I
have dallied with the beyond,'' said Chevenement, who spent eight
days in a coma, ``and I've returned both the same and different.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Philippines: Reprieved from death
</P>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ The Supreme Court gave a six-month
reprieve to a poor house painter three hours before he was to have
been executed for raping his 10-year-old stepdaughter. In a case
that aroused furious debate over the death penalty, the painter,
Leo Echegaray, would have been the first person executed in the
Philippines in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Link in Bomb Blast Seen
</P>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ Police said a pipe bomb that wounded
five people in a parking lot here on Friday was similar to one that
blew up the Planet Hollywood restaurant last August, and to bombs
used to attack police stations and homes of drug-dealing gangsters.
The Planet Hollywood bombing has not been solved, but an anonymous
caller said a group called Muslims Against Global Oppression did it
to avenge U.S. cruise missile attacks on Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Russian Jews Get Second Party
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A second political party for Russian immigrants has
been created by Avigdor Lieberman, a former chief of staff to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Lieberman's new party is seen as a
Russian offshoot of the Likud, Netanyahu's party, and presents the
first real rival for the party of Natan Sharanksky, the trade
minister and former Soviet dissident.
</P>
</TEXT>
