<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MISSING-COUPLE-NYT     01-04 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-COUPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDLORD OF MISSING COUPLE IS HELD ON FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a year after a Manhattan couple argued with
their landlord and then disappeared, the landlord, Robert
Rodriguez, was arrested Monday, and investigators searched his
Orange County home, as well as the apartment building where the
couple lived.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who had refused to allow the police to search his
property, was not charged in connection with the mysterious
disappearance of his tenants, but with a variety of ``white-collar
crimes,'' including tax fraud and grand larceny, according to
law-enforcement officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, the New York Police Department
acknowledged only that Rodriguez was in custody, that two search
warrants had been executed, and that ``Mr. Rodriguez owns the
building at 76 Pearl St. where Michael Sullivan and Camden Sylvia
resided prior to their disappearance on November 7, 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple were last seen in a video store after arguing with
Rodriguez over the lack of heat in their apartment on Pearl Street,
in the financial district. Rodriguez himself disappeared for two
weeks shortly after friends discovered the couple were missing. He
then reappeared without explaining his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Rodriguez has declined to cooperate with police
seeking to find Ms. Sylvia, 36, an artist and real estate agent,
and her companion, Sullivan, 54, an actor and art-gallery worker.
In particular, he has refused to let the police search his
property. Frustrated investigators have even flown over the
seven-acre Orange County home in helicopters and sent dogs sniffing
for anything that might provide the basis for a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said the search warrants were executed
shortly after Rodriguez's arrest Monday _ one for Rodriguez's home
in Slate Hill and the other for the Pearl Street apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of searching for evidence of the white-collar
crimes, investigators could presumably look for clues concerning
the whereabouts of Ms. Sylvia and Rodriguez. But since search
warrants are narrowly drawn, investigators might be confined to
Rodriguez's house, or even parts of his house, rather than the
entire property of the Slate Hill estate and the Pearl Street
building.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Marro, Rodriguez's lawyer, declined to comment
immediately on the arrest, saying he had not heard from Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Goldfeder, the lawyer for the families of Ms. Sylvia and
Sullivan, said: ``This is the first real break in 14 months in this
case. It's the first opportunity for the authorities to find
something that may resolve the disappearance.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, six investigators were in Rodriguez's locksmith
shop on the ground floor of the apartment building, taking out milk
crates full of items from the shop. Kim Magistro, a neighbor of the
missing couple, said the investigators were also questioning Gina
DeLarosa, a friend of Rodriguez who lives in a second-floor
apartment. Ms. Delarosa has an unlisted number and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the building, on three different floors, six yellow
ribbons in memory of the missing couple had been tied to the fire
escapes by their friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
