<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUL TROUBLE HAUNTS USC IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC had a rare weekday matinee at the Sports
Arena, which is just as well, because the Trojans demonstrated
against eighth-ranked Arizona on Monday that they still aren't
quite ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   At least when their top player gets in foul trouble. Or they
play a top-10 team.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans wilted in the second half of an 87-78 loss to the
Wildcats before 4,116, but USC coach Henry Bibby seemed more
enraged by the officiating than the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Center Brian Scalabrine, USC's leading scorer, played most of
the contest in foul trouble after picking up his third foul just 14
seconds into the second half. Scalabrine joined point guard Brandon
Granville, who already had three fouls in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Two other starters _ Jeff Trepagnier and Sam Clancy _ picked up
their third fouls less than three minutes into the second half. Add
to that the fact Bibby received a technical foul in the first half
from referee Dave Libbey, and it wasn't too hard to translate his
post-game comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was in Tucson, Ariz., instead of Los Angeles, for
whatever reasons,'' Bibby said. ``The officials should never be
able to set the tone and I'm not saying they did or didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in foul trouble. We lost a lot of momentum with the
fouls being called. That deflates you. It takes its toll on what
you're trying to do on the floor. It took Brian Scalabrine out of
the game. ''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier was a little calmer in his analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to the refs now. We get bad calls every game,''
Trepagnier said. ``We just play through that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans may have been upset with the officiating, but their
offense also disappeared in the second half. After building a 44-35
halftime advantage, led by several alley-oop dunks to Trepagnier,
the Trojans lost their rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   USC shot 27 percent in the final 20 minutes and was outscored by
18 points. Unlike Saturday's dramatic comeback victory over Arizona
State, USC received little help from its shooting guards. Seniors
Adam Spanich and Elias Ayuso were 4 for 18 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure, but I think we were settling for bad shots,
forcing too many shots,'' Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of USC's offensive woes were due to the disappearance of
Scalabrine, who scored a season-low eight points. After getting
into foul trouble, the 6-foot-9 center abandoned going inside and
stayed on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do what I wanted to do. Why I started pulling up
outside was a mistake,'' Scalabrine said. ``That was a big mistake
on my part, not being aggressive. I had to change the way I played.
With the fouls, I wasn't as aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Trojans were depleted by foul problems, they
still led 66-61 when Ayuso hit a 3-pointer with 7:36 left.
</P>
<P>
   Then Arizona star Jason Terry decided to join the game. Terry,
who scored just two points in the first half, drove the lane for a
basket. He then added a 3-pointer and followed with a steal and
layup. By the time Terry finished, the Wildcats had outscored the
Trojans 11-1 and taken a 72-67 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans never recovered from that spurt, failing to get
closer than three points the remainder of the game. Terry finished
with 16 points and made 6 of 8 shots in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't contain him on penetration,'' Bibby said. ``He got
by our people and penetrated. You've got to respect him.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's bid to gain respect this season has only been slowed
against premier teams. The Trojans (9-2, 1-1) have lost to
then-No.10-ranked Kansas and to the No.8 Wildcats (9-1, 1-1), who
were undefeated before losing to UCLA last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For USC, the toughest part was losing at home. After squeaking
past Arizona State on Saturday, the Trojans were hoping to sweep
the homestand before this week's tough trip to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't lose any home games in the Pac-10,'' Scalabrine
said. ``One of our goals was to go undefeated in the Pac-10 and
they took it away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only highlight for USC was the play of Clancy. He
didn't see a minute of action against Arizona State, then started
against Arizona and finished with 16 points and 10 rebounds before
fouling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been looking for a player to fill that slot. He did
exactly what we wanted him to do,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The loss snapped USC's nine-game winning streak at the
Sports Arena.... This is Arizona's first victory at the Sports
Arena since 1996.... USC shot a season-low 36.6 percent, the first
time the Trojans shot below 40 percent.... The Trojans are just
3-15 against ranked teams since December, 1996.... USC has scored
78 points in both losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
