<HEADLINE>
MERGER RUMORS ABOUND AT BIG AUTO SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (js) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ When top auto executives gather here each winter for
the North American International Auto Show, the talk in the halls
is usually about the latest car or, more recently, the latest sport
utility vehicle or pickup truck. But at this year's show, there is
also another theme: merger rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Daimler-Benz A.G. and Chrysler Corp. announced their
merger last May, and particularly since the two companies completed
the deal last November, the industry has been full of speculation
on who might link up next. But top industry officials here said
Monday that while many auto makers were cautiously and tentatively
holding discussions, that did not necessarily mean another deal was
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The company most often mentioned as a potential acquirer is Ford
MotorCo., which has accumulated $22 billion in cash, a hoard equal
to nearly a third of its market value. Just before Christmas,
rumors started that Ford was in talks to acquire Volvo of Sweden or
BMW of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, who became Ford's chief executive on Friday with
the retirement of Alex Trotman, expressed amusement Monday at the
rumors. ``I was lying back on a beach over the Christmas period
reading about all these wonderful strategic meetings being held
that I clearly wasn't involved in,'' Nasser said in an interview at
Ford's huge, two-level display here, which is almost as long as a
football field.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser declined to discuss either Volvo or BMW but did say,
``Everyone's talking to everyone else.'' Yet Ford views the
prospect of an acquisition as a potential opportunity rather than a
necessity, and therefore is in no hurry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haste, in these circumstances, I wouldn't put a premium on,''
Nasser added.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has insisted that it wants to stay independent and that the
controlling Quandt family has no intention of even discussing a
sale. ``BMW will remain independent and, contrary to all the
speculation and rumors in the industry, there have not been any
discussions,'' said Helmut Panke, a member of BMW's management
board.
</P>
<P>
   Panke was particularly emphatic that BMW had not been
negotiating any deals with Ford. ``I can really confirm that there
haven't been, are none and will be no discussions'' with Ford, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bodil Eriksson, a senior vice president of Volvo, said Monday
that while the company was willing to talk to other auto makers
about cooperating on production and other ventures, it was not
interested in being acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo is small by industry standards. In terms of sales, it is
twice the size of Microsoft Corp. but only one-seventh the size of
Ford. Smaller auto makers that lack broad ranges of models and
international operations are increasingly seen as the most likely
to engage in mergers.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp., already the world's largest auto maker,
has shown little interest in growing through acquisitions. G.
Richard Wagoner Jr., GM's president, said Monday that there had
long been speculation that the auto industry would undergo
considerable consolidation, but the DaimlerChrysler deal might yet
turn out to be an exception rather than a new rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking about this business getting down to `X'
major players _ 5 or 10, pick a number _ for a decade,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Neumann, a member of Volkswagen AG's management board, took
a similar position, saying that informal talks did not
automatically mean that more big transactions were on the way.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler officials started the current merger speculation
by insisting that their transaction was necessary to achieve
greater economies of scale. But even DaimlerChrysler has had
trouble moving quickly on further deals.
</P>
<P>
   Jurgen E. Schrempp, the company's co-chairman, said in
mid-November that he expected a decision by the end of 1998 on
whether to buy Nissan Motor Corp.'s stake in Nissan Diesel. But no
decision has been reached, and Thomas Stallkamp, DaimlerChrysler's
president for North American operations, said Monday that the
company was concerned the Japanese economy might not have hit
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has also been rumored to be interested in Nissan, but Ford
executives have become leery of any deal because of concerns that
Nissan's balance sheet may not reflect the true extent of its
debts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
