<SLUG> BC-NJ-DROUGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT RAIN OF LITTLE HELP TO N.J. AND N.Y. RESERVOIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday's rain _ bountiful in some areas, sparse in others _ did
little more for the reservoirs serving New York City and
northeastern New Jersey than stop the steady decline in levels that
began last fall, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All the reservoirs remain well below normal, despite the storm,
according to officials in New York and New Jersey. While they
welcomed the rain, they cautioned that significantly more was
needed and warned that residents must continue using water
judiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it didn't amount to very much and it's not
going to change our situation dramatically,'' Cathy DelliCarpini, a
spokeswoman for New York City's Department of Environmental
Protection, said of the storm. ``What we need is some consistent
rainfall. One storm is not going to make up for several months of
below-normal rainfall.''
</P>
<P>
   On average, New York City's three major reservoir systems
received only nine-tenths of an inch of rain on Sunday, which
provides little more than the 1.3 billion gallons of water that the
city uses each day, Ms. DelliCarpini said. By Monday afternoon,
runoff from the rain had pushed water levels in all the reservoirs
from 51 to 51.3 percent of capacity, she said. Normally, at this
time of year, they should be 78 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the city's daily supply comes from three big
reservoirs in the headwaters of the Delaware River in the
southwestern Catskills. They rose only a tenth of one percentage
point _ from 36.2 to 36.3 percent of capacity _ because the storm
that hit near them produced sleet and frozen rain that has not
melted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any appreciable runoff and that's what we need,''
said Christopher Roberts, a spokesman for the Delaware River Basin
Commission, a four-state agency that regulates water use in the
Delaware's watershed. ``So, we're still in pretty bad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless major storms hit by mid-January, Ms. DelliCarpini said,
New York City's water managers plan to declare a ``drought watch''
sometime between the middle and the end of the month. Under a
``watch,'' officials would intensify appeals for voluntary
conservation of water, including running public announcements
encouraging water savings. Officials began to call for conservation
on Dec. 14, although this was a low-key appeal.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, New Jersey declared a ``drought warning'' for
about 2 million people served by 13 reservoirs in the state's
densely populated northeastern corner. As in New York City, the
warning was primarily an appeal to conserve by running washing
machines and dishwashers only with full loads, taking shorter
showers, repairing all leaks and using water intermittently while
brushing teeth or shaving.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's 13 reservoirs received an average of 2.2 inches of
rain. Water storage in them rose Monday to 45.1 percent of
capacity, up from 42.9 last Thursday. But normally at this time of
year, the 13 would be nearly 79 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to continue to conserve,'' said Shing-Fu Hsueh,
water supply administrator in New Jersey's Environmental Protection
Department. He said the storm cut the rainfall shortage in the
state's northeastern corner since July from 13 to 11 inches. And,
he added, without heavy storms soon, the state is likely to declare
a water emergency and to impose mandatory cutbacks in water use in
40 days. Before the storm, officials had planned to mandate the
restrictions in 30 days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us another week or so on an emergency,'' he said of
the rain. ``If we get lucky, we won't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's situation is not as ominous. About 2.2 million of
its 3.2 million residents rely on reservoir water. Most of the
reservoirs there are at or above normal, primarily because they are
big, have large watersheds to collect runoff and are not as
vulnerable to rainfall shortages as the rest of the region is.
</P>
<P>
   The only problems now are reservoirs that serve about 150,000
residents in and near Greenwich, Norwalk and Ridgefield, said James
Okrongly, head of public water supply planning in Connecticut's
Public Health Department. All are less than half-full, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping a wary eye on them,'' Okrongly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
