<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIP-CLUB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIP CLUB USES LEGAL LOOPHOLE TO STAY OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURGH, N.Y. _ When Robert Hopkins opened a strip club along
the tattered main street here earlier this month, he expected to
wrangle with city officials, who had warned him he was not
permitted to offer adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   So one of the first things he did was hang a sign near the
entrance of his club, Lips, announcing that it would admit minors.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Hopkins was following a route mapped out by a state
Supreme Court justice in Manhattan, who declared that a New York
City strip club could not be subject to laws regulating adult
entertainment if minors were allowed inside.
</P>
<P>
   In that decision, Justice Stephen Crane said that Ten's World
Class Cabaret, an East Side topless club, could remain open despite
the city's strict zoning codes because the city's law defined an
adult establishment, in part, as one that does not admit minors.
</P>
<P>
   Ten's World got around the issue by saying it would allow young
people inside if they were accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   City lawyers appealed the decision (and the City Council quickly
went to work to change the definition of adult establishment), and
arguments are scheduled for Jan. 5 in the Appellate Division in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Newburgh's adult entertainment law, and the laws of other cities
across the state and country, include a loophole similar to New
York City's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the zoning law used all across the country,''
said Mark Alonso, the lawyer who represented Ten's World. ``It was
passed down from one town to another. Once they came up with the
concept of using zoning laws to fight topless clubs, it became very
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hopkins, 51, a real estate developer who lives in Goshen and
is new to the strip club business, the judge's ruling came along at
the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an easy way we found of not arguing with the town over
the adult establishment law,'' he said. ``If we didn't have an
argument with the town, we could just make it a normal above-18
admission. This is a technicality.''
</P>
<P>
   Newburgh city officials say Hopkins was told long before he
opened his business that a strip club would not be allowed because
the site is too close to a residence and across the street from an
adult bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as Lips opened on Dec. 11, Hopkins was charged
with violating the city's zoning ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   James Morrill, Newburgh's building inspector, declared Lips an
adult club, subject to adult entertainment rules, even if it
sometimes admits minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a minor shows up without a parent, the minor would be
turned away,'' said James Morrill, the building inspector.
``Therefore it does exclude minors.''
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with Ten's, for a minor to be allowed into Lips,
a parent or legal guardian must accompany him or her, tour the
facility first and sign a waiver accepting responsibility, Hopkins
said. The minor must sign a waiver, too.
</P>
<P>
   Only one boy has tried to get into the club since it opened, and
he was turned away because the man accompanying him could not prove
he was the boy's guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said he did not relish allowing youngsters into strip
clubs, but said Newburgh's laws are unconstitutional because they
go beyond restricting where strip clubs can operate by effectively
banning them.
</P>
<P>
   Newburgh's zoning law, adopted in 1996, does not allow adult
businesses within 1,000 feet of a home, house of worship, school or
other adult business; Hopkins said no place in the city meets that
definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the designated district,'' he said. ``We are in the
Industrial-2 zone, where you could almost produce nuclear warheads,
and still there are residences allowed here. We're not being
cavalier about letting minors in. We want to follow the letter of
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, some advocates of adult entertainment are
critical of using the admission of minors as a legal strategy for
keeping clubs open.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the January issue of Stripper magazine, a national
trade journal for the strip-club industry, warns against using
minors to circumvent zoning laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risky to allow under-age kids into clubs,'' the
magazine's publisher said. ``You could open yourself up to a lot of
other charges, like child endangerment. You don't want to do that
in some small town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
