u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      01-04 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNSETTLING THE CITY'S CAMPAIGN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Jan. 5:
</P>
<P>
   Pity the candidate who ventures now into New York City politics.
The ground rules for local elections have suddenly become vastly
more chaotic as lawyers for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani squabble with
the city's Campaign Finance Board about the formula for matching
public subsidies with private political contributions. This
internecine argument threatens to unsettle candidates in special
elections for City Council this year and could undermine one of the
best and fairest campaign finance reform systems in the country.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this issue so disheartening is that it all goes back
to a puerile political contest last year between the mayor and
Council Speaker Peter Vallone. Vallone wanted a referendum on
Yankee Stadium. To block any such vote, Giuliani had his cronies
cobble together a slapdash charter reform item that, like all
charter referendums, automatically bumps a normal referendum from
the ballot. The language of Giuliani's charter reform sounded
enlightened _ it banned corporate donations _ and the voters
adopted it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the mayor's lawyers are arguing that their charter
item not only bans corporate donations but also wipes out
improvements in the campaign finance law that were enacted last
year by Vallone and the City Council. The council had adopted a
two-tiered approach to the voluntary campaign reform law. If a
candidate took contributions from corporations, whether IBM or the
local pizza parlor, the city would match all donations dollar for
dollar up to $1,000. If the candidate refused corporate money, the
match went to $4 for every dollar donated, for contributions of up
to $250.
</P>
<P>
   The charter vote knocked the corporate contributions out of the
city's system, but the mayor and the Campaign Finance Board are at
odds about what is left. The Finance Board has notified the city
that, with all participating candidates now shunning corporate
money (albeit by fiat), all should get the 4-to-1 match, which
would help entice people into the system. However, Robert Harding,
the mayor's budget director, argues that, with no corporate
contributions available to be refused, the entire system reverts to
a 1-to-1 match.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone and the council need to tidy up this mess, by making it
clearer that all candidates who choose the city's finance plan will
now have the 4-to-1 match. Without such an effort, the next sorry
steps will inevitably lead to the courthouse, where a legal fight
between the mayor and the campaign board will merely extend the
confusion and convince many candidates that even a model campaign
finance system is not worth the trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
