<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8308 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     01-04 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SEASON DOWN TO LAST SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The lockout game clock is down to its final
precious seconds, and now NBA players will get the chance every
athlete craves: to decide the outcome with everything on the line.
And this time, literally (begin ital)everything(end ital) is on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA rejected the players association's final offer Monday,
and owners will vote Thursday on a recommendation to kill the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a last-gasp shot by the players. The union announced
it will conduct a vote Wednesday of its 400-plus members on the
league's final offer. A majority no vote probably means no season.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA labor relations committee, which includes Lakers owner
Jerry Buss, voted unanimously to recommend cancellation after
reviewing the union's final proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have had to see a proposal that reached for ours.
Instead it in many ways went backwards,'' commissioner David Stern
said. ``We don't anticipate making a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, the only pro league never to have lost a game to labor
conflict prior to this season is perilously close to becoming the
first in history to lose an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations having failed, the players now hold their own fate
in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of players _ including New Jersey Nets stars Jayson
Williams and Keith Van Horn _ had pressed for a membership vote in
recent weeks. Union leaders resisted, saying the membership had
given final authority to the 19-player negotiating committee.
</P>
<P>
   They begrudgingly changed course Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee... will continue to recommend against acceptance
of the (owners' final) proposal,'' union director Billy Hunter
said. ``To assure that the owners understand the level of player
resolve and the degree of opposition to the NBA's onerous demands,
the negotiating committee will convene an all-players meeting in
New York... at which time the general membership will be asked to
approve the negotiating committee's recommendation to reject the
NBA's final proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Free agent Malik Rose, a member of the negotiating committee,
predicted 70 percent of the players would vote against the NBA's
offer. Privately, league officials are convinced a vast majority of
players will take their deal rather than lose the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they elect to go against the (union's) recommendation,''
Hunter said, ``then we'll have to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   And if everything goes wrong this week, everyone involved will
have to live with some heavy consequences, Stern warned.
</P>
<P>
   If owners vote to cancel the season, they will then proceed with
plans for a 1999-2000 season _ probably without the union's 400
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may or may not be dealing with those players if we cancel
the season,'' Stern said. ``I think the parties will start on their
separate courses and we may or may not be dealing with those
players anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern is assuming superagent David Falk will try to launch a
rival league, using his clients, Michael Jordan, Patrick Ewing and
Alonzo Mourning among them, and other superstars as the main draw.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern said the rest of the union's members will be left out
in the cold. The NBA, he said, will start anew with college
draftees and other available, nonunion players _ presumably from
European leagues and the Continental Basketball Association, though
he didn't offer such specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily a pretty sight early on, but obviously if
we have to rebuild the league, we will in fact rebuild the
league,'' Stern said. ``We're looking for people who share the same
idea of partnership that got us where we've gotten to.... We're not
talking about members of the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting between league and union leaders ended after
barely an hour. Hunter presented the players' last offer, which
included absolute maximum salaries for all players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the (union's) final proposal moved towards the NBA in
nearly every significant area, the commissioner and deputy
commissioner (Russ Granik) felt that anything short of total
capitulation to their position is unacceptable,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Though union leaders agreed to cap individual salaries, they
still insisted that players receive 57 percent of league revenues
in the final year of the agreement. Owners, who imposed the lockout
when the players' take hit 57 percent last season, are offering no
more than 54.5 percent, with each point representing approximately
$20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't in any way significantly different, at least in my
judgment, from where the union has been on prior offers,'' Granik
said. ``We're far apart on every issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stern: ``The proposal which was delivered would have been a
good one to start from six months ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
