<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAIN-FUNCTION-SFCHRO     01-04 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-FUNCTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STRUCTURES IN MOTION SEEN AT SYNAPSES  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a picture familiar to generations of high school biology
students: the human brain and its intricate circuitry, fine nerve
networks that resemble the branches of a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after peering closer than ever before at the elaborate
branches of individual nerve cells, scientists have discovered that
the twigs, known as dendrites, are decorated with tiny ornaments,
called dendritic spines _ and that the ornaments can move.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it appears that these critical parts of the brain can
change and even multiply, a notion that revolutionizes previous
views of the structures as passive receptacles.
</P>
<P>
   Exquisitely small, dendritic spines typically serve as the
receiving end of the synapses, which are neuronal connecting sites
where nerve cells transmit signals to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Synaptic connections allow the brain to detect sensations.
Synapses also are the principal means by which the brain records
memory and coordinates movement.
</P>
<P>
   Using the latest in laser and video imaging technology, brain
experts have seen and recorded dendritic spines sprouting and
changing form within fractions of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why this happens is an enigma. But early clues, laid out
during recent scientific meetings in San Francisco and Los Angeles,
suggest some intriguing possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The brain, it seems, may have the power to create new synaptic
circuits when necessary _ like an unlit room that sprouts its own
power outlets to accommodate new lamps.
</P>
<P>
   This may help explain the brain's phenomenal ability to rake in
huge amounts of information and rapidly store it for long-term use,
researchers say. Unraveling how the brain works, scientists add,
may help open new doors to treating common neurological disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding how synapses form is very important to
understanding brain function,'' said Stephen Smith, a professor in
the Department of Molecular and Cellular Physiology at Stanford
University School of Medicine. ``Somehow, trillions of circuits get
wired up in the brain, and that's what allows the brain to do what
it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in Smith's lab at Stanford, Cold Spring Harbor
Laboratories in New York and the Friedrich Miescher Institute in
Basel, Switzerland, have all produced stunning time-delayed images
showing the submicroscopic dendrites in action. A sample of such
video can be seen at San Francisco's Exploratorium museum, part of
a current exhibit on memory.
</P>
<P>
   This was no easy feat considering the dimensions involved _ some
dendritic spines measure less than a micron, or a millionth of a
meter, in width.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss researchers used a green fluorescent material derived
from jellyfish to tag a protein called actin, which helps muscles
contract. Results showed actin also concentrates in dendritic
spines, helping them to move and change shape.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting pictures make the knobby spines look like glowing,
pulsating Christmas tree bulbs clinging to the spidery outer
branches of the nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   Each ``pulse'' corresponds to a physical change in the anatomy
of the nerve cell. This happens ``faster than almost anyone
imagined,'' in the space of a half-second or less, said Andrew
Matus, one of the Swiss researchers.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``almost anyone'' because noted molecular biologist
Francis Crick, co-discoverer of the DNA double helix, suspected
long ago that dendritic spines might ``twitch'' for reasons then
unknown. Now, Matus said, there is photographic evidence suggesting
that ``Crick's general idea turns out to be absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers have been making headway in identifying the
even smaller structures found within the dendritic spines.
</P>
<P>
   Neurologist Kristen Harris of Children's Hospital and Harvard
Medical School in Boston reported on the latest such work during a
recent Society for Neuroscience meeting in Los Angeles. She
suggested that dendrites and their mysterious ornaments come in
different species, with varied shapes and internal features,
possibly because they all have different functions.
</P>
<P>
   In one set of experiments, drugs were applied to thin brain
slices from laboratory animals in order to block synaptic activity.
Results showed a sudden bloom of dendritic spines, as if nerve
cells had sent out search parties for the missing signals.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been shown that after excessive brain activity, such
as in epileptic seizures, large numbers of dendritic spines
disappear. One explanation could be that the brain tries to
maintain a certain optimal level of activity by regulating the
number of connecting sites, sending out or retracting dendritic
spines as needed. An absence of dendritic spines has also been
found in brain autopsies of schizophrenics.
</P>
<P>
   Just what happens to make them appear or disappear is still
being investigated. But it is all part of a new view of the central
nervous system as an astonishingly malleable thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of dynamics in the architecture,'' Smith said.
``The more we look, the more it seems there are dynamic processes
going on at many levels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
