<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVSREAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, ANSTEY HAPPY ABOUT VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mavericks guard Hubert Davis joined teammate Chris
Anstey yesterday in blasting the NBA union and saying the players
should accept the league's latest proposal before the season winds
up unceremoniously being canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make any sense why we're not playing,'' Davis
said. ``I've talked to a lot of NBA guys, and a lot of guys said
they'll take \Rcommissioner David Stern's final offer\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully everyone will wake up and see how lucky we are and
get back on the court. The good part about it is we'll figure out
what's going to happen this week.''
</P>
<P>
   After refusing to let the players vote throughout the heated
negotiations with the NBA owners, union leader Billy Hunter has
relented and will let members vote on commissioner Stern's offer
tomorrow in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Anstey said they can live comfortably with the outcome
of tomorrow's vote, which can possibly save the season. They're
just glad the outcome is finally in the hands of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes that we don't accept \RStern's offer\S,'' Davis
said, ``then I can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey was one of the first group of NBA players who, early last
month, said the players should vote on whether to accept any of the
NBA offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now we'll know what every single player in the league
is thinking,'' Anstey said. ``I guess then hopefully we'll get a
season underway by means of a vote. If not, that means the majority
of the players don't want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said if the players vote to not accept his offer, he will
begin working on a league with replacement players. That will
consist of rookies, and players from the Continental Basketball
League and foreign leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds a bit extreme, and it's a bit of a shock coming
out of left field,'' Anstey said. ``You have to take commissioner
Stern serious that there may not be a season. I think he's gone
past trying to use bluff tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and several other players have taken exception to Hunter
and those players on the 19-member executive committee who have
steadfastly referred to Stern's proposal as a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work six months playing basketball, so I don't know what a
bad deal is,'' Davis said. ``The minimum salary is right around
$300,000 \R$272,500\S. I think that's probably a top salary for a
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was scheduled to make $645,000 this season, said he
never voted for those 19 players on the executive committee to
represent him in the negotiations. Most of the players on the
committee, including Patrick Ewing, Dikembe Mutombo, Juwan Howard
and Alonzo Mourning, are represented by powerful agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how they got picked,'' Davis said. ``I want
to play, and I can't see how we can't be thankful for where we are.
You've really got to understand how blessed we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0538 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAVOTE-TEX     01-04 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAVOTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE OF UNION MEMBERS IS LATEST PROPOSAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Minutes after the NBA owners' Labor
Relations Committee unanimously rejected the players' supposed
``final'' offer last night, players union executive director Billy
Hunter decided to allow a vote of all 450 players on the owners'
latest proposal delivered 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, scheduled tomorrow in New York, could decide the fate
of the 1998-99 NBA season and the general direction of the league.
If the majority votes to accept the owners' proposal, a 45-to-50
game schedule could begin as early as Feb. 1. If players reject the
offer, owners are prepared to vote to cancel the entire season at
their Board of Governors meeting Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be close, real close,'' said a Western
Conference All-Star, who asked to remain anonymous. ``I know there
are some players coming out and calling for this vote or what not.
But a lot of us have been behind the union from the start back in
Las Vegas. It'd be a shame to back down now after coming this far.
But at least now there'll be no mystery. It's all up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern and players like Kevin Willis, Keith
Van Horn and the Mavericks' Hubert Davis have been calling for a
union vote in recent weeks. But until last night, Hunter rested his
strategy with a 19-player negotiating committee of mostly
``high-end'' salary players who continually turned down ownership
offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player members of the NBPA negotiating committee
previously rejected the NBA's final proposal unanimously,'' Hunter
said last night. ``To assure that the owners understand the level
of player resolve and the degree of opposition to the NBA's onerous
demands, the negotiating committee will convene an all-players'
meeting in New York \Rtomorrow\S, at which time the general
membership will be asked to approve the negotiating committee's
recommendation to reject the NBA's final proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the decision to hold the vote, the season seemed in
desperate peril. With the Thursday deadline Stern set to recommend
canceling the season approaching, owners voted to reject a union
offer and even begin preparations for a 1999-2000 season featuring
replacement players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very, very far apart,'' said NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik. ``We went over their proposal and there's
not any significant differences to make us optimistic. With the
clock ticking like it is, it felt like a step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stern, ``This is a terrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, just months ago the only U.S. professional sports
league to never miss a game because of labor problems, is now a
vote away of becoming the first to cancel an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, over how to divide the league's annual $2 billion
revenue, has already wiped out two months of the season. Granik
said the sides remain at odds over a cap on high-end salaries, the
percentage of revenues paid in player salaries during the last
three years of a six-year deal, a rookie pay scale and salary-cap
exceptions. The key issue remains the percentage of revenue paid to
players, with the sides apart by 7.5 percent over the six years, or
around $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the players vote to reject the proposal and this season is
canceled, Stern promised to swiftly begin preparations for a league
of replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not necessarily be a pretty sight early on,'' he
said, ``but if we have to rebuild the league we will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-04-99 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990104.0539 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAVOTE-TEX     01-04 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAVOTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE OF UNION MEMBERS IS LATEST PROPOSAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
