<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVSREAX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, ANSTEY HAPPY ABOUT VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mavericks guard Hubert Davis joined teammate Chris
Anstey yesterday in blasting the NBA union and saying the players
should accept the league's latest proposal before the season winds
up unceremoniously being canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't make any sense why we're not playing,'' Davis
said. ``I've talked to a lot of NBA guys, and a lot of guys said
they'll take \Rcommissioner David Stern's final offer\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully everyone will wake up and see how lucky we are and
get back on the court. The good part about it is we'll figure out
what's going to happen this week.''
</P>
<P>
   After refusing to let the players vote throughout the heated
negotiations with the NBA owners, union leader Billy Hunter has
relented and will let members vote on commissioner Stern's offer
tomorrow in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Anstey said they can live comfortably with the outcome
of tomorrow's vote, which can possibly save the season. They're
just glad the outcome is finally in the hands of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes that we don't accept \RStern's offer\S,'' Davis
said, ``then I can accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey was one of the first group of NBA players who, early last
month, said the players should vote on whether to accept any of the
NBA offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now we'll know what every single player in the league
is thinking,'' Anstey said. ``I guess then hopefully we'll get a
season underway by means of a vote. If not, that means the majority
of the players don't want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said if the players vote to not accept his offer, he will
begin working on a league with replacement players. That will
consist of rookies, and players from the Continental Basketball
League and foreign leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds a bit extreme, and it's a bit of a shock coming
out of left field,'' Anstey said. ``You have to take commissioner
Stern serious that there may not be a season. I think he's gone
past trying to use bluff tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and several other players have taken exception to Hunter
and those players on the 19-member executive committee who have
steadfastly referred to Stern's proposal as a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work six months playing basketball, so I don't know what a
bad deal is,'' Davis said. ``The minimum salary is right around
$300,000 \R$272,500\S. I think that's probably a top salary for a
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was scheduled to make $645,000 this season, said he
never voted for those 19 players on the executive committee to
represent him in the negotiations. Most of the players on the
committee, including Patrick Ewing, Dikembe Mutombo, Juwan Howard
and Alonzo Mourning, are represented by powerful agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how they got picked,'' Davis said. ``I want
to play, and I can't see how we can't be thankful for where we are.
You've really got to understand how blessed we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
