<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKFARMERS-SUIT-1ST     01-04 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKFARMERS-SUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGREES TO SETTLE DISCRIMINATION CASE WITH BLACK FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for brief inserts in 2nd and 7th grafs.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture has agreed to pay hundreds of
millions of dollars to settle a lawsuit brought by thousands of
black farmers who say the department discriminated against them by
denying loans and other subsidies, representatives of the
department and the farmers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Gray, the department's civil rights director, said the
department will not admit to having discriminated against the
farmers, but will agree that its procedures in handling bias claims
have been flawed. Under the terms of the consent decree, which
could be formally announced as early as Tuesday, the department may
have to pay as much as $300 million and possibly more for claims
dating back 16 years, depending on how many farmers come forward
with claims, Ms. Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers who have an active discrimination case or who file
an affidavit of discrimination that names specific individuals in
the department who denied them loans will be eligible for $50,000
tax-free, and will have all their debts to the Agriculture
Department forgiven, said John Boyd Jr., president of the National
Black Farmers Association, which filed the 1997 lawsuit that led to
the settlement. The average debt for most black farmers is between
$75,000 and $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers who have better documentation of bias can forgo the
$50,000 award and negotiate higher awards with an outside
arbitrator, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 farmers around the country are part of the
class-action lawsuit, Boyd said, and another 1,000 to 2,000 farmers
are likely to file claims once the settlement is announced. The
majority are likely to claim the $50,000 award, he said, as they
lack the explicit proof of discrimination necessary to get a larger
arbitrator's award.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous victory for black farmers across the
nation,'' said Boyd, whose group represents about 60,000 farmers
and their family and other supporters. ``We met with the president.
We tied a mule to the White House gate. We lobbied Congress. And
finally farmers are getting some relief for the way they were
treated in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, when the Reagan administration abolished the
Agriculture Department's Office of Civil Rights, many of the
nation's 18,000 black farmers _about 80 percent of whom are in the
South _ have complained that they have been denied loans and
subsidies simply because they are black. While they have watched
white farmers in their counties receive thousands of dollars of
loans, the farmers say, they were told by local officials of the
department that the programs have run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried for nine years to get a farm operating loan,'' said
Boyd, himself a tobacco farmer from the remote fields of southern
Virginia, near Baskerville. ``Back in 1992, the county supervisor
for the department threw my application in the trash. He said they
didn't have any more money. When the investigator asked him why he
had made only two black farm loans, he said black farmers were
lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the farmers, who originally sought $3 billion, were
able to document that loans to black farmers took far longer to
process than loans to white farmers, and that far more of their
applications were denied. By 1996, when the civil rights office was
restored by the Clinton administration, the department had admitted
that some discrimination had taken place, and that the backlog of
discrimination cases was enormous and in disarray. The department
did not try to justify the higher rate of denials.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers began to hold large and visible protests in
Washington, at one point tying a mule to the White House fence.
President Clinton met with Boyd and several other leaders in
December 1997 and promised to seek a resolution of the case, and
Congress eventually passed a bill that extended the statute of
limitations in the case beyond the usual two years.
</P>
<P>
   By last October, the path toward a settlement seemed clear,
although the details were still to be worked out. The department's
inspector general issued a report saying the civil rights office
was in disarray, and recommending that an outside body administer
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, when a federal judge ruled that the black
farmers constituted a legitimate class for purposes of the lawsuit
_ a major victory for the farmers _ a spokesman for Dan Glickman,
the agriculture secretary, said the department wanted to resolve
the issue quickly and compensate those who had claims. The case was
scheduled to go to trial next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this goes a long, long way, maybe all the way, toward
resolving the outstanding complaints against the department,'' Ms.
Gray said Monday, ``They were concerned about having their
complaints processed within the department, so the settlement will
allow them to have their concerns processed outside of the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cash awards, Boyd said his group remains concerned
that many of the department officials who presided over the
original discrimination still have their jobs and will not be
punished under the settlement. Ms. Gray acknowledged that the
settlement does not have a procedure for disciplinary action
against department officials, but said the department would change
its internal procedures for investigating bias claims in a way that
could lead to greater discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already drafted and cleared through the department new
regulations which will allow us, we think, to process complaints in
a more timely fashion,'' she said. ``We certainly have changed some
of our procedures as it relates to our responsibility to follow up
with disciplinary action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
